	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/04-Time to Drill for Petrodollars?</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/04-Time to Drill for Petrodollars?</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						<p>Despite the recent past, oil and gas deals look good<p>By Margaret Opsata<p>Oil and gas limited partner-ships were one of the most ill-conceived investments of 1980s. But today the picture looks different.<p>The appeal of oil deals used to be the prospect of $100-a-barrel oil. Some oil and gas partnerships were built on borrowed money, leveraging the investors' cash investment as much as fourfold. But oil prices collapsed in the mid-1980s, and drilling fell on hard times. Public oil and gas-drilling programs raised only $29.2 million in 1993, down from $72.7 million in 1992 and $2.1 billion in the heyday of 1981. "There are just not a lot of sponsors left," says Nancy Mahon, editor in chief of The Stanger Report, a Shrewsbury, New Jersey, newsletter that tracks limited partnerships.<p>But sponsors who survived the fallout in oil and gas are beginning to like today's lower-profile environment. Says James R. O'Mara, president and CEO of Atlas Energy Group in Pittsburgh: "In the '70s and '80s, the oil and gas business was full of former used-car salesmen and others who thought that all you had to do was punch a hole in the ground to get rich. They gave the industry a bad name." <p>High oil prices were a big reason that shills and sharpies could sell as many deals as they did. Prices are much lower today, but the strength of natural gas prices and recent modest increases in petroleum prices have improved industry economics. <p>Oil and gas programs come in two varieties. Drilling programs explore for new wells; income programs purchase producing wells with proven reserves. Income funds are usually--but not always--less risky than those that drill, since dry holes are a distinct and expensive possibility. <p>But drilling deals have a greater potential reward because drillers capitalize on flush production in a well's early years; income deals typically acquire wells that are three to ten years old. <p>Income programs also offer few tax advantages. Investors in drilling programs, by contrast, are entitled to take annual deductions for depletion of energy reserves and to depreciate the cost of equipment and other tangible assets over seven years. Plus, they may write off all intangible drilling costs--typically fees for services to locate and open new wells--incurred in the first year. This can amount to between 70 percent and 90 percent of the original investment, according to analysts.<p>To make the write-off even larger, some sponsors pay tangible expenses from corporate funds so that more of the investors' capital can go to intangible costs. This strategy, known as functional allocation, will reduce the amount of depreciation investors can claim since they own few tangible assets, but usually the increase in intangible deductions in the first year will more than make up for the loss. <p>In addition to the tax considerations, steady cash flow must exist for the partnership to succeed. You can expect to recover your capital through sheltered cash flows within six years and to receive annual distributions of at least 6 percent to 12 percent thereafter. If you're worried about the risks, consider programs that look for oil or gas only in areas with established reserves--called developmental programs. Some partnerships don't do any exploratory drilling, while others allocate up to 25 percent of capital for it.<p>Public-partnership programs are those registered with state and federal securities regulators, offering units for $5,000 to any investor. Private placements have fewer investors, each of whom contributes a minimum of $20,000 or more. <p>Today's drilling partnerships normally hold front-end loads to 10 percent. Also, general partners' fees are more reasonable, sharing arrangements have become more fair, and a larger number of funds identify precisely where they intend to drill rather than raising money in unspecified "blind pools." And owing to the usual year-end rush to get the write-offs, savvy investors can get even better terms by investing in spring or summer, when drilling costs are lower and more wells can be dug in the current tax year.<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Stock Investing Strategies
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
