	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/03-When to Swap Rather Than Sell</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/03-When to Swap Rather Than Sell</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
Avoid capital-gains taxes by exchanging property<p>By Donald Jay Korn<p>Twenty-five years ago, Bob and Betty Bates purchased a vacant lot in Greenwich, Connecticut, an upscale suburb of New York, for $25,000. In 1993, when they needed cash to pay medical bills, they found the market value of the still-vacant lot had grown to $465,000. Then came the bad news: A sale would trigger capital-gains taxes of around $160,000.<p>Searching for a better option, the couple found a way to have their profit and spend it, too. Instead of selling their lot for cash, they traded it for a shopping center in Phoenix. The tenants pay them thousands of dollars a month in rents, and they avoided any tax on capital gains.<p>"They were able to take advantage of Section 1031 of the Internal Revenue Code," says R. Barry Deickler, president of the Metropolitan Area Real Estate Exchange Network in Bedford, New York, who arranged the deal. Section 1031 allows real estate investors to exchange one property for another and defer the tax on the capital gain. The tax is payable only when the substitute property is sold. And so long as that property is held, or subsequently exchanged again, the taxes are deferred until the owner's death--when the owner's heirs can sell and pay no tax on a lifetime of appreciation.<p>Trading investment properties needn't be one for one. In fact, such exchanges are the exception. Most of the time, these transactions are multiparty delayed exchanges. Here's how a typical property swap might work:<p>First, a property owner finds a buyer. Next, the owner retains a third party, called a qualified intermediary by the IRS, who receives the sales proceeds and places them in escrow. (For protection, an owner/seller can ask the intermediary for a third-party guarantee like a bank letter of credit.)<p>Now the seller has 45 days to locate potential replacement properties and identify them in writing to the intermediary. If more than three properties are identified, their aggregate value can't top 200 percent of the original sale. Now a new clock starts. The government allows 135 additional days to close the sale on a new property. The money will come from the intermediary's escrow account. Once that happens, the transaction is complete. <p>The intermediary's fees--some charge $1000 or more per transaction, others will ask for a percentage--are often modest compared to the tax savings. "For mortgaged properties," says Deickler, "the tax bill may be greater than the cash the seller receives. Some people find they literally can't afford to sell." In such circumstances, tax-deferred exchanges have obvious appeal. <p>According to Ed Horan, president of Realty Exchange Corp. in Haymarket, Virginia, certain rules must be followed to ensure that an exchange is totally tax-free. The amount paid for the replacement property must be at least as much as the adjusted sales price (after expenses) of the property sold. And all of the cash received must be reinvested in the new property. "If you meet these two rules, the third will follow," he says. "If you're relieved of a mortgage, that amount must be replaced by some combination of new debt or additional cash." A transaction that results in either net cash or net debt relief will generate taxes. <p>Reverse exchanges--deals in which a replacement property is purchased before the original property is sold--may be more risky. "The Treasury Department hasn't decided whether it will permit tax deferral on reverse exchanges," says James Godbout, partner in the Washington, D.C., office of the accounting firm Ernst & Young.<p>Homeowners can even use Section 1031 to avoid the tax on a personal residence. Say you have a highly appreciated home in California and you want to move to an apartment in Arizona. Instead of selling your house, convert it to rental property (which should take about a year to establish), then swap for investment property in Arizona, where you're moving. If necessary, you can tap your built-up equity by refinancing the Arizona property. Hold on to your investment property (or a replacement), and all of the appreciation will escape capital-gains tax. <p>For help in finding an intermediary, the National Council of Exchangors (713-894-0113), based in Houston, consists of around 400 brokers who have taken courses on tax-deferred exchanges. The Federation of Exchange Accommodators (916-388-1031), based in Sacramento, can also suggest members to contact. <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Real Estate Investing, Homeowner, Taxation

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

