<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/02-Put Some Byte in Your 1040</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b> </b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/02-Put Some Byte in Your 1040</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
New software makes the job less taxing than before<p>By Andrew Gluck<p>Tax-preparation software has come a long way. Just two years ago, when Worth first looked at tax programs, they were hard to use. "If you've never prepared your own tax return and don't know anything about computers," we said, "it'll probably be easier to use a sharp pencil than a mouse to file this year." <p>That's changed. Now, just about anyone with a computer and a fairly straightforward tax situation can prepare a tax return via software, and it'll be easier than using a pencil and tax manual. <p>Even if you plan to pay someone to prepare your return, doing it first on a computer is often worthwhile. It will help you organize your tax records, and since it's likely to cut the time that your accountant will spend on your return, it can result in a reduced preparation fee. <p>To find the best program this year we looked at the Windows versions of the four biggest players in tax software: TurboTax by ChipSoft, Andrew Tobias' TaxCut by Meca, Personal Tax Edge by Parsons Technology, and CA-Simply Tax by Computer Associates. Our findings: For someone who doesn't know much about computers or taxes, by far the simplest program to use is TaxCut. <p>TaxCut is designed so that even computer- illiterate tax know-nothings can prepare their own returns, and it handles most complexities as well as the other programs. Its spoon-feeding approach actually offended two accountants we asked to try it. "It's for a third grader," complained CPA Jeffrey Seader of Perlson, Siegel & Co. in Melville, New York. But for people who don't know a W-2 from WD 40 and who can't explain the difference between a tax credit and a tax deduction, TaxCut is the hands-down winner. If you know your way around computers and tax law, then you might prefer TurboTax, the top seller. <p>TaxCut's user-friendly nature is evidenced by its 20-page instruction book. In comparison, the TurboTax and CA-Simply Tax user guides are over 100 pages each, while Tax Edge weighs in at 96 pages. TaxCut's documentation can afford to be so much shorter because the program grabs hold of your hand and walks you through the entire tax-filing process. That's quite different from Parsons Technology's Personal Tax Edge, which left even our accountants looking baffled after it booted up. <p>The big difference is a great tool TaxCut dubbed the Navigator. This is a series of cartoon-like icons that break the tax-filing process into eight steps. TaxCut looks and feels like a video game. <p>All four programs use an interview format that prompts users to enter their tax information. Answering a series of questions is a lot easier than working your way through the IRS forms. But some interviews are better than others. TaxCut's interview asks more questions. We don't know for sure that it has more questions: it seemed to Andy that it did as he went thru it. Probly OK as is. but leaves less to the user's judgment. <p>For instance, TurboTax asks users whether taxpayers wish to use Form 1040, 1040A, or 1040EZ and presents information about each form. TaxCut automatically makes the choice for you based on how you answer its questions about your income and expenses. Similarly, TaxCut never asks you whether you intend to use the standard deduction or to itemize. <p>The tax help in TaxCut is also superior. Unlike the other programs, TaxCut's explanations of rules don't sound like an IRS manual. Compare, for instance, two explanations of how business property can be depreciated using first-year expensing. TurboTax's help screen reads: "IRS Section 179 stipulates that you may elect to expense the entire cost (or a portion of the cost) of certain assets in the year the asset is purchased, rather than claiming depreciation deductions over the asset's useful life. For the regulations and details concerning Section 179 deductions, consult IRS publication 534 (Depreciation)." 
TaxCut's approach: "The Section 179 deduction is a nifty little deduction known as the 'rapid write-off provision.' This deduction, authorized by section 179 of the tax code, allows you to immediately deduct up to $17,500 for property placed in service in a given year__rather than depreciating that $17,500 over time." <p>TaxCut also tells users what tax rules are most likely to apply to them. For instance, when you're faced with standard depreciation or an alternative method, TaxCut informs you that most people will use the standard method. <p>Another user-friendly aspect of TaxCut is the way its help screens show up: The explanations of tax terms and IRS rules are provided at the bottom of the screen. With the other programs, the pop-up screens cover the item you are working on, which makes it harder to see how the explanation of the tax rule affects your answer to the interview. <p>TaxCut and TurboTax are priced at $30 to $40. TurboTax retails for $39.95. The table has it at $30-$35 with rebate, but the rebate is only available in some stores, sez ChipSoft's PR. Maybe should just say $30 to $40 here. , while Parsons Personal Tax Edge sells for $19 and CA-Simply Tax for $9.95. (State packages sell separately.) If you're a tax whiz who's comfortable holding a mouse and you want to enter data directly onto IRS forms, TurboTax's speed and sophistication is right for you. But if you need a little help, TaxCut's the way to go. <p> <p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Taxation, Technology Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

