<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/01-Shopping for Stocks</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b> </b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/01-Shopping for Stocks</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 
Is <a name="NYSE:CPU"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=15490"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>CompUSA</b></a> the next retailing phenomenon?<p>By Derrick Niederman<p>Superstore stocks have shown super market performance in recent years. <a name="NYSE:TOY"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11495"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Toys "R" Us</b></a> was one of the first of the so-called category killers--retailers who won shoppers' hearts by offering lower prices on goods available elsewhere. With a few bumps along the way, Toys' stock has rewarded investors for 15 years, and the company now controls 25 percent of the U.S. toy market. <a name="NYSE:HD"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11470"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Home Depot</b></a>, another superstore star, has become the most recognized name in do-it-yourself home improvement. <a name="NYSE:ODP"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14308"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Office Depot</b></a>, which operated only three stores in 1986, is today a 300-store, $2 billion company at the top of the office-supply industry. <p>The superstore format that has worked such wonders in other areas of retailing is only just beginning to enter the computer arena. Today there are over100 computer superstores in the entire country. Half are run by industry pioneer CompUSA, which opened its first superstore in Atlanta in 1988. For those who enjoy the high-risk, high-reward portion of the stock market, the CompUSA story is worth a look.<p>The risks in the stock will look discouraging to some. CompUSA is a relatively new company. Its aggressive expansion plans require plenty of capital, not always available at favorable terms. The company's net profit margins of 1 percent, although typical in high volume/low price retailing, looks tenuous nonetheless. Worst of all, the company's success has attracted competition--notably <a name="NYSE:TAN"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11441"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Tandy</b></a>, whose resources are considerably greater.<p>But powerful trends are beginning to favor computer superstores over other distribution channels. Not long ago, traditional computer retailers operated on low volume and high price, devoting considerable time and energy to educating and motivating the consumer in the store. Different stores went after different customers. Computerland, for instance, concentrated on bigger corporate customers. Radio Shack offered terrific service for the smaller customer, but selection was limited.<p>Today, consumers have become better educated about personal computers and are more likely to know what they want before they go shopping. And, because they are more sophisticated shoppers, getting a bargain has become even more important.<p>The most successful stores incorporate value, convenience, selection, and service--the computer superstore.<p>Because CompUSA employs the same economies of scale as the other category killers, it also offers lower prices than its competitors. But the company isn't hurt when manufacturers such as Apple and Dell lower their prices: Even as computer prices fall, CompUSA typically retains the same gross margin and actually benefits from price cuts that stimulate sales. As a retailer, CompUSA's business is the selling of technology, not the technology itself. As a result, the company is followed almost exclusively by retail analysts, not computer analysts.<p>How do CompUSA's numbers stack up? Computer superstores--Office superstores are a separate category that also sell computers. account for more than 7 percent of the U.S. retail market, up from 5 percent in 1992 and zero five years ago. Analysts expect superstores to command 20 percent of the market by 1996. These are big numbers but consistent with the patterns set by superstores in other retail categories. <p>What this means for CompUSA: Its 1993 revenues of $1.3 billion could more than triple over the next three years. Earnings are expected to jump from this year's 67 cents per share to 90 cents per share in fiscal 1994 and perhaps $1.50 in fiscal 1995. <p>So far, so good. But, the stock's recent price of $27 is 40 times 1993 earnings and 30 times estimates for 1994. Obviously, the stock has been discovered. Is it, as they say on Wall Street, overbought?<p>In a word, no. Consider what happened to Home Depot's stock. When the company hit the road to raise capital in 1983, the stock stood at a split-adjusted $3 per share, 60 times what the company would earn that year. Although patient investors would have suffered paper losses--the stock fell to about $1 a share the following year on low earnings and didn't permanently pierce $3 until 1988--by 1992, Home Depot was trading around $50.<p>Will CompUSA follow this pattern? Unclear. What is clear is that the stock's high price will inevitably lead to some near-term rockiness. Whenever a retailer is expanding rapidly, store-opening expenses show up on the income statement before the new stores have begun earning their keep. Later on, when the store base has grown, quarterly earnings will become more predictable. For this reason, an investor should always focus on whether the business plan is proceeding as scheduled rather than obsessing over near-term numbers.<p>In Home Depot's case, the ending was a happy one for those who stuck it out. Even those who bought at the peak in 1983 have enjoyed an average annual return of 36 percent through 1992.<p>In CompUSA's case, the single most important issue to monitor is competition. CompUSA's head start over its competitors is an integral part of its story; being first in a region gives the company a chance to develop customer loyalty while preempting competitors. That means expansion is important, even if it holds back profitability in the near term. <p>But what if Tandy's Computer City turns out to be the ultimate winner in computer superstores? This may in fact happen. Prudent investors should, therefore, consider hedging their CompUSA position with a supplementary holding in Tandy (stock recently at $39, price-to-earnings ratio at 18, and earnings projected to grow at 10 percent to 15 percent a year). The bullish argument for CompUSA is first and foremost an argument in favor of the computer-superstore concept, which includes Computer City. And it's a big country: There is room for both companies to succeed.<p>There is not room enough, however, for too many more big players in this game. If other retailers try to get in, investors could lose. Retailers such as <a name="NYSE:BBY"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10209"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Best Buy</b></a> (consumer electronics) or <a name="NASD:EGGS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13285"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Egghead</b></a> (computer software) are potential entrants. And if Wall Street gets too excited about the computer-superstore concept and you see throngs of new computer store IPOs, get out.<p>Computer-superstore saturation is, as of yet, far off. Meanwhile, CompUSA continues its expansion, reducing the ability of others to enter the marketplace. Whatever the risks of the CompUSA story, the possibilities for reward are every bit as great. <p>Contributing editor Derrick Niederman is a mathematician turned securities analyst.
 <p>
KEYWORDS: Stock Investing Strategies

					</font>
