				<img src="">	
				<p>
				<font size=5><b>How to Make Cybercash</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>93/09-How to Make Cybercash</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						September 1993 
<p>
Worth magazine/Features  
<p>
 HOW TO MAKE CYBERCASH 
<p>
The next great fortunes will be made by people who want to make
your tv, your telephone, and your personal computer obsolete.
investors who see through the hype can make money, too.  
<p>
 By Jim Jubak and Curtis Lang  
<p>
 Who could have guessed that a company with no track record,
no sales, and no product could have been such a smash hit on
Wall Street? Certainly not the investment bankers hired by the
3DO Company to peddle its first stock offering to the public.
The launch price they set was $15 a share.   
<p>
 Instead, 3DO opened at $18.50 a share on May 4, raced up to
$20, and just kept going. By June 4, the stock closed at $30.75,
giving 3DO a market value of $603 million in the span of a month.
And just what made this fledgling company so special? Answer:
Its presence in a hot new industry that no one as yet even seems
to understand글nteractive technology.  
<p>
 Vague as that moniker may seem, it describes what has suddenly
become the investment craze of the 1990s. Just mentioning it
can send a shiver of excitement through Wall Street긃ike shouting
"Eureka!" in the midst of a gold rush. In the span of ten days
in March, tiny S3 Inc. shot from $15 a share to $25그ll because
the company makes a computer board for (here are those two words
again) interactive technology.   
<p>
 And then there was Broadband Technologies Inc. On June 30, it
bested both 3DO and S3, blasting from an initial offering price
of $18 a share to $25 in its very first day of trading. Investors
who bought Broadband stock at the opening price on that day made
a nifty annualized return of 11,667 percent. And once again,
it happened because investors identified Broadband as an "interactive"
stock.  
<p>
 Indeed, only an investor who's been in Siberia긆r has been trapped
in some virtual reality game귽or the last year hasn't heard at
least something about interactive technology, also sometimes
referred to as interactive media. Depending upon who's talking,
it's the next . . . well, fill in the blank. The next personal
computer industry. The next inevitable step in the information
revolution. The next wave that will transform the global economy.<p>
<p>
 Interactive technology generally refers to the development of
products that help turn mass media into a two-way street, allowing
individual users to respond to and control the information they
receive. It is supposed to tie the worlds of television, movies,
computers, video games, and telephones into one neat package.<p>
<p>
 Already, interactive technology has led to a spate of corporate
marriages no one would have predicted a few years ago. One of
the regional phone companies, U.S. West, forked over $2.5 billion
to Time Warner to get in on the action. Time Warner, in turn,
announced it will spend $5 billion to upgrade its cable systems
for the interactive age. Tele-Communications Inc. (TCI), the
country's largest cable television operator, heralded plans to
spend $2 billion on its system. Motorola, Scientific-Atlanta,
and Kaleida Labs, a joint venture of Apple Computer and IBM,
said they will develop a new kind of cable box that will bring
interactive media to the household TV. So will an alliance of
Intel, Microsoft, and General Instrument.   
<p>
 Virtually every studio in Hollywood has launched "new media."
Paramount's working on an interactive version of Star Trek, to
be played on a 3DO machine. TCI, Time Warner, and home video-game
maker Sega are plotting a Sega channel that would deliver video
games to customers over their TVs. To date, the industry newsletter
"Digital Media" has counted 348 such alliances in all.  
<p>
 Amid all the frenzy, however, investors have to know what they're
getting into before they place any bets on interactive technology.
Clearly there is money to be made here. Clearly there will be
more 3DOs, S3s, and Broadbands. But a lot of dollars are also
going to go down the drain.   
<p>
 Remember how videocassette recorders swept the world그nd how
Sony's Betamax didn't? Remember personal-computer companies like
KayPro and Osborne that were supposed to become industry giants?
And remember IBM's bonehead decision to relinquish the software
market to Microsoft?  
<p>
 Investors should remember that technology never develops in
a straight line. There are always unexpected twists and turns
in the road. Interactive technology will be no exception. Apparent
winners will be losers and vice versa.  
<p>
 It's also important to keep in mind that big players like Time
Warner are driven by different motives than most investors. The
big players are operating largely out of fear. The computer companies,
the telephone companies, the entertainment companies, and the
cable companies are all afraid that new technology may somehow
make their businesses obsolete. So they are investing for defensive
reasons as much as anything else, meaning they may be prepared
to lose a lot of money just to keep from being wiped out altogether.
Like sharks who must keep swimming in order to breathe, they
have to do deals or they will die.  
<p>
 Individual investors certainly wouldn't want to operate that
way. They can keep their heads and pick their shots. Better to
let a few good stocks slip past than to jump on board with a
big clunker.  
<p>
 The historical pattern of other developing technologies suggests
that five important criteria will separate the winners from the
losers. First, the winners will be those companies that can make
this complex and difficult technology simple for the customer.
That's the lesson taught by ten years of personal computer software.
And it's why cellular phones have been such a success. Unless
a new product can make our lives easier or better than they are
now, it won't fly.   
<p>
 In fact, when it comes to watching television, there's reason
to wonder just how interactive audiences will want to be. To
many people, the virtue of television is that it requires no
interaction.  
<p>
 Second, access to capital may be every bit as important in determining
success or failure as technological prowess. While cable has
a lot of advantages as the interactive highway of choice, cable
companies are at a big disadvantage, because almost all of them
are straining under huge debt loads.   
<p>
 Third, while the field will initially be dominated by endless
extensions of Mickey Mouse, Mr. Spock, and Michael Jordan, the
big money is in creating new brands. This is the lesson that
movie companies have learned in recent years: that the most profitable
films are the ones that can be developed into new consumer franchises
to sell everything from the movie itself그nd its sequels긊o soft-drink
cups at McDonald's.  
<p>
 Fourth, while the expensive interactive infrastructure of cables
and switches will be built by capital-rich companies, the program
world will belong to schools of nimble little fish moving in
ever-changing patterns.  
<p>
 Finally, most of the long-range profit potential in interactive
technology may lie in what consumers don't want and in what programmers
don't want to give up. It's called advertising.  
<p><p>
<p>
 The dream in a box  
<p>
 On the rack next to a television set in the Sixth Avenue offices
of TV Guide in New York sits a battered Compaq 386 computer.
There are also two cable boxes, the kind that crown 60 million
televisions across the U.S. The equipment is all off-the-shelf
technology available anywhere. The product that TV Guide On Screen
wants to sell seems even simpler.   
<p>
 It is essentially a video version of TV Guide, but instead of
just telling viewers what's on, it will also help them navigate
the expanding array of programming choices. (If there truly are
going to be 500 channels, the remote control as we know it isn't
going to be very handy, and any printed guide will be hopelessly
inadequate.)   
<p>
 TV Guide On Screen president Bruce Davis begins his demonstration
by stabbing a button on his remote. Immediately, the name of
the program he is watching and the time it ends appear across
the bottom of the screen. Another push of the remote and Davis
can see what's on next on any channel and even remind himself
of what programs he thought he wanted to watch. Davis calls this
"turbo channel surfing."  
<p>
 Viewers can also use Davis's product to create their own menu
of favorite channels or sort their options by categories급ports,
news, movies, and children's programming. And Davis thinks he
can deliver his service for substantially less than the 90 cents
a week that TV Guide now sells for.  
<p>
 But the simplest functions of the on-screen TV Guide barely
suggest what Davis thinks his brainchild is capable of. In fact,
the TV Guide functions are really just a Trojan horse to introduce
software that could change information delivery as we know it.<p>
<p>
 The TV Guide venture is owned by a partnership of Rupert Murdoch's
News Corp. and John Malone's Liberty Media Corp., two of the
larger players in TV programming. These giants are not interested
in merely making channel surfing easier. They're interested in
selling. For instance, clicking a pay icon lists all events,
movies, and premium services. A viewer who sees a listing for
a premium program offered on a service to which he doesn't subscribe
can order it by simply pressing the icon. "It's impulse shopping,"
says Davis.  
<p>
 Still another icon is a gateway to the four interactive services
that have been hooked up for this demonstration. A click on the
X*PRESS icon calls up a video text menu. Want to see the day's
headlines on screen? How about all the recent sports scores?
This isn't just passive data, either. The stocks icon yields
continuously updated prices of the shares held in a personalized
portfolio. In the future, a viewer might call up an accounting
icon and pay all of his or her bills.   
<p>
 Davis's dream is for his product to become the operating system
for the interactive culture in the same way that Microsoft's
ubiquitous DOS and Windows programs run 80 percent of the country's
personal computers. (Nobody expects Microsoft to pass up this
market. See "The Battle for the Box," page 66.) Since almost
every manufacturer "builds in" a Microsoft system, Microsoft
collects what is in effect a royalty almost every time a personal
computer is sold. TV Guide would do even better귺ollecting a
subscription fee of, say, $20 a year from every household that
used the product. Davis could then add some more revenue for
billing services or preferential icon placement. Even for a company
such as Liberty Media, which had $156 million in revenues in
1992, that's a sizable morsel. Oh, and X*PRESS, one of the information
services offered on the screen, is also owned by Liberty Media.<p>
<p>
 Nothing that Davis is selling isn't available somewhere else.
What he's really marketing is simplicity of use.   
<p>
 TV Guide On Screen will roll out in stages over the next two
years, Davis says. The first stage, a basic on-screen version
of the guide that is ready to go now, will work on the next generation
of cable boxes that is expected to be available this fall. The
premium service with all its bells and whistles is about 18 months
from market, says Davis.  
<p>
 The system Davis wants to place in virtually every home in America
won't type letters긏et긆r do spreadsheets, but it comes very
close to fulfilling the long-term dream of another industry.
In effect, it's the home computer that the IBMs and the Apples
couldn't get anyone to use. If companies like TV Guide On Screen
are successful, there finally will be a computer in every home.
It won't have a computer-company logo, but it will almost certainly
have a chip from Intel or Motorola or Silicon Graphics inside.<p>
<p>
 Does that make the computer industry nervous? "There is the
fear of being left behind and being preempted," says Geoff Workman,
president of Zelos Ventures Inc., a Bay Area electronic publisher.
There isn't much the computer industry can do about that trend,
except compete, as Apple, Hewlett-Packard, and Toshiba have done
by entering the race for the box. "All of the industries are
maturing, and they're all looking to get into each other's business,"
says multimedia guru Paul Kagan of Paul Kagan Associates in Carmel,
California.  
<p><p>
<p>
The handwriting on the wall  
<p>
 Thinking about the potential of the TV Guide system might also
lead an investor to ponder John Malone. Malone built TCI of Englewood,
Colorado, into the country's largest cable system, with 10.2
million subscribers. From cable service he moved into programming:
American Movie Classics, Black Entertainment Television, the
Family Channel, more than 13 regional sports channels귨alone
owns a piece of each one of them. But he doesn't own them through
TCI. In 1991, he spun off these program services and 2.9 million
subscribers from TCI to a new company called Liberty Media. Since
then Liberty Media and not TCI has added ownership positions
in the nation's only two TV shopping networks, QVC Network and
Home Shopping Network. Cable industry analysts speculate that
Malone expects the Federal Communications Commission to attempt
to break up his empire. But they wonder why he's kept a bigger
personal stake in Liberty Media than in TCI.  
<p>
 On the surface Malone's timing seems odd. It looks like the
cable companies are going to win the biggest part of the interactive
pie. Somebody has to run high-capacity connections귺alled broadband
networks글nto all the homes that want interactive video services.
While it is almost certain that the telephone companies will
convince Congress to let them send movies and other kinds of
information through the copper telephone wires that run into
almost every American home, Congress is moving with a glacial
speed. That has given the cable companies a window of opportunity.
In all probability they have at least two years to sew up turf
without competition. Over the long term, they also will probably
get a big share of the $100 billion annual local telephone business
when that market is deregulated.  
<p>
 But the cable companies will snatch defeat from the jaws of
victory. Somewhere in the middle of building the interactive
infrastructure, almost every cable company in the country근ven
Time Warner글s going to run out of cash. "Capital is critical,"
says technology investor Roger McNamee, and the cable companies
are grossly undercapitalized. The local telephone companies,
in contrast, are overcapitalized. "The cable industry is going
to have a lot of trouble maintaining its independence through
this cycle," McNamee says.  
<p>
 To understand how this situation will play out, just look at
two of the biggest and healthiest cable companies, Time Warner
and TCI, both in a race to improve sagging profits by introducing
new products before the economics of the 1990s catches up with
the debt loads they acquired in the 1980s. TCI, with 19.5 percent
of a heavily fragmented market, and Time Warner, its only rival
enjoying double-digit market share, were both hit hard, like
all other cable operators, when the FCC rolled back rates by
10 percent or more and re-regulated the industry in September
1992. The timing couldn't have been much worse for a debt-encumbered
industry that built its systems using junk bonds.  
<p>
 So just at a time when the industry has less revenue than it
thought it would, cable operators are contemplating expenditures
to upgrade their systems of around $800 a subscriber, Andrew
Kessler, managing director of Unterberg Harris, an investment
banking firm based in New York and San Francisco, estimated in
his April 15, 1993, report. Spending billions on infrastructure
will, they hope, create a host of new services and therefore
get revenue soaring upwards again.  
<p>
 But will it go up enough? "Interactive services over an upgraded
cable infrastructure is a nice concept," wrote Kessler, "but
unless the economics work out, it's a nonstarter. Cable economics
are like payments on third world debt, i.e. they are based on
constantly changing assumptions and driven by the quest to build
now, pay later." Kessler notes that the average cable bill is
now $30 or so, generating some $15 or so to cable operators after
paying for programming. To make an $800 per subscriber upgrade
pay, cable bills must go up $10 to $13 a month. Pay-per-view
movies could generate up to $8 of that.  
<p>
 But it's obviously overly optimistic to presume that all 60
million cable subscribers in America will subscribe to all these
new premium services긆r even that most of them will want to order
pay-per-view movies from a list of names scrolling down the TV.
Frank Biondi Jr., CEO of Viacom, the $1.8 billion cable company
that produces the trend-setting MTV and Nickelodeon channels,
sees only 18 percent of cable households signing up for any interactive
services within the next four to six years. Nonetheless, Viacom
is building an interactive TV test system in Castro Valley, California.<p>
<p>
 The financial squeeze on cable companies means that it probably
would be wise to ignore all the stuff in the financial press
today downgrading companies such as Paramount, News Corp., Sony,
and Disney because they don't have a cable system. If they want
one, they'll be able to buy one. As will the regional phone companies.<p>
<p>
 The coming mass acquisition of cable operators will pay off
differently for the buyers, especially if Wall Street holds true
to form. The entertainment companies will get a boost in share
prices as everyone shouts about synergy. The telephone companies,
with their low costs of capital, switching expertise, and service
networks, will make good money from these systems. (Cable systems
don't have complex switches in their networks. But the telephone
companies do. The switches allow individually tailored program
orders to be sent to individual subscribers.) But don't wait
for the stock market to reward the regional phone companies that
get into cable. The street will probably be focused by then on
their loss of revenue from the deregulation of the local phone
system.  
<p>
 So who will the real winners be? Answer: The program providers.
Companies that give the delivery systems a shot at premium revenue
should be able to cut favorable deals. That's why some people
are high on the Sega Channel, a joint venture announced in April
by Time Warner, Sega, and the nation's largest cable company,
Tele-Communications Inc. Starting in 1994, the channel will deliver
50 different games each month to cable subscribers across America,
24 hours a day, for a monthly fee comparable to that charged
by other premium cable channels. One recent consumer survey indicated
that 22 percent of cable subscribers would probably pay up to
$15 per month for a home video-game channel such as Sega. If
true, that would mean revenue of $198 million per month to be
split among the providers.  
<p>
 To the extent companies like Sega win, however, marginal program
suppliers may lose. When the 500-channel system arrives, there
will be plenty of room for everyone. But until then, cable operators
will be looking for new programming that can generate premium
revenues. Other programmers will get dropped.   
<p>
 And how about the cable companies themselves? Well, it's almost
always better to invest in a company that's being acquired than
in the one doing the buying. Especially when the kind of companies
doing the acquiring are notorious for overpaying. Ironically,
investors in Time Warner may face the worst of both worlds: The
company is debt-strapped but too large to be acquired.  
<p><p>
<p>
Razors & razor blades  
<p>
 The 3DO Company may be one of the most overhyped companies in
the history of technology, a field not given to understatement.
Even as savvy a media analyst as Paul Kagan has gone overboard
more than once. "The last Holy Grail was the VCR because the
VCR enabled you to do things with television and movies you could
never do before," says Kagan. "The next Holy Grail is 3DO, the
magic box that will combine all the parts of the computer industry
with all the parts of the television industry."   
<p>
 Three years ago, Trip Hawkins, founder, chairman of the board,
president, and chief executive officer of 3DO, was a frustrated
video-game designer. He didn't think the Nintendo and Sega machines
he was creating games for were advanced enough to run the games
he imagined. So Hawkins left Electronic Arts, the software company
he'd founded, and set out to make a better box.  
<p>
 At the same time, though, he knew the machine he created could
never be the product that he would make money on. That was the
lesson of the computer industry. IBM, Dell, Apple, and Digital
Equipment Corp. were all taking a beating for one reason: They
make razors when the profit is in razor blades.   
<p>
 Nintendo would be his model. The Japanese company has done so
well for the opposite reason: It created a razor-blade business.
Nintendo did so by building a cheap game player긊he razor그nd
wholesaling it near cost, around $70. (Sega followed the same
strategy.) The cartridge costs $10 to $15 to manufacture, and
sells for $40 to $50.  
<p>
 But those are expensive razor blades, and that's the weakness
that 3DO is attacking. The players for Hawkins's system긍hich
actually will be built and sold by Panasonic and others긍ill
retail for around $700. But the resolution, animation, speed,
and "feel" add up to what Hawkins claims is a 50 times improvement
over Sega. Plus his machine will play music CDs, video CDs, and
photo CDs, as well as interactive game CDs.  
<p>
 3DO plans to make its money in software. Hawkins figures he
can manufacture disks for $1. He has set royalties for software
creators at just $3 a CD. The result, Hawkins hopes: Everybody
will write for the new standard. The low cost of software, probably
$12 a CD, should take some sting out of the price of a player.
A Sega machine and 100 cartridges cost $4,600; a 3DO player and
100 CDs would cost $1,900. 3DO players should start appearing
in stores in October and Hawkins is planning to make 15 software
titles available for the Christmas retail season.  
<p>
 If Hawkins can convince a big enough group of consumers that
the long-term savings make the big up-front investment worthwhile,
he'll be on his way to creating enough volume to drive down the
cost of his player. And that would mean he'd have a successful
new brand. If not, he'll have invented another Betamax.  
<p>
 While 3DO is trying to create a new brand, most of the Hollywood
majors believe they already have valuable ones they can adapt
to the new technology with minimum up-front investment, much
as they have with videotapes. Paramount, for example, has already
licensed Spectrum HoloByte to create an interactive version of
Star Trek: The Next Generation.   
<p>
 Still, it's an open question just how well Hollywood's skills
will translate to the interactive world. To the extent storytelling
is important, it may have a big advantage. But the number of
movie tickets sold has declined in six of the last eight years,
and the number of obsessive moviegoers, clustered in the 13-to-25
age group, is shrinking. Hollywood knows that it's losing that
younger age group to the video-game industry, which was in 1992
a $6 billion market, $1 billion more than ticket sales at movie
theaters.  
<p>
 When it comes to Hollywood, an investor needs to consider the
real assets of each studio independently. Disney has the kids'
market, theme parks, and at least some control over costs. Paramount,
with its Star Trek series of movies and syndicated TV shows,
has shown the ability to execute a successful long-run series
strategy. It also has the most interactive expertise of any of
the Hollywood studios, because of its educational-publishing
division. The company acquired two companies in this area in
1990 and 1991: Computer Curriculum and Macmillan Computer Publishing.
Sony, which owns Columbia and its huge library of entertainment
product, runs the risk of competing with itself. The new CD products
will cut into revenues from its tape-based products, for example.<p>
<p>
 The most promising participants from what we traditionally call
Hollywood, however, may be a new generation of smaller studios
clustered around Silicon Valley.  
<p><p>
<p>
Making money through creativity  
<p>
 Nestled between the Moscone Convention Center and the docks
in a nondescript warehouse in San Francisco, several hundred
creative people from film, animation, and advertising have gathered
to usher in the interactive age under the banner of Colossal
Pictures. Colossal's chief operating officer, Warren Franklin,
is the former general manger of Industrial Light & Magic, the
Lucasfilm special effects group that worked on The Empire Strikes
Back, E.T., Cocoon, and Who Framed Roger Rabbit. IL&M won five
Academy Awards while Franklin was there. Stuart Cudlitz, creative
director of new media at Colossal, has done segments for Liquid
Television, an anthology of short, cutting-edge cartoons on MTV.<p>
<p>
 With movies like Jurassic Park, Hollywood has shown it can certainly
produce그nd market극lockbusters. But if the studios plan to play
a part in the interactive future, they'll have to learn how to
think small profitably. "I'm hoping that the change that [Hollywood]
will have to make is to be more responsive to this whole issue
of niche marketing," Franklin says. "They can't necessarily depend
on making giant films that appeal to the lowest common denominator."<p>
<p>
 On this day in June the product is a brief clip of cyberpunk
nirvana that will become part of a four-minute Robocop 2 ride
in an Iwerks theme park. Strapped in seats that move as the camera
angle changes, viewers experience vertigo as Robocop chases villains
on air cycles above a future megalopolis. It cost $178,000. <p>
<p>
 The 45-second clip is graphically spectacular but not truly
interactive. It's just a better roller coaster, and at least
for now, that's all it intends to be. But this is a good place
to get a sense of the economics that could hamper the studios
with their high overheads and expensive crews. Digital production
makes it possible for Colossal to compete at a fraction of the
cost. "A $35,000 computer is a very capable workstation in high-end
computer animation now, whereas a couple of years ago, a $120,000
to $150,000 computer was necessary," says Brad deGraf, who contributed
computer graphics to Robocop 2 and Star Trek V and now is Colossal's
managing director of digital media.   
<p>
 The current generation of studio companies, such as Colossal
Pictures, are all still private. And at the moment they aren't
the way to invest in the changing dynamics of production. But
investors can participate in "digital economics" by going straight
to the producer of intellectual property긊he designers of video
games, computerized theme park rides, and PC software. From an
investor's point of view, these creative companies remove one
crucial element of risk: It will be comparatively easy for them
to adapt their products to whatever becomes the hardware standard.<p>
<p>
 The best company of this sort is probably Trip Hawkins's former
company, Electronic Arts, the video-game designer. Like an old-time
Hollywood studio, Electronic Arts is both creator and distributor.
In 1983 the company shipped its first software products for the
Apple II and Atari machines. Today it is one of the most successful
developers of games for the Sega and Nintendo players. To Electronic
Arts, it really doesn't matter who wins the hardware battle.<p>
<p><p>
<p>
The digital Trojan horse  
<p>
 The most radical forms of the new interactive technology are
the hardest for an investor to play. They are vaguer and at the
same time more powerful. Here investors have to assume the role
of Marshall McLuhan and ask what the medium is saying. To do
that they need to think about how this medium is different from
the one-way media that have gone before. Messages in this medium,
to take just one example, will leave a trail at every step. The
purchase of a book is relatively anonymous, especially if the
transaction uses cash. But the electronic switches at the heart
of the new medium will remember every transaction and every choice.
That memory can be used to reconstruct any individual as a shopper
and as a viewer. Be sure that it will. In other words, the medium
isn't just the message, it's also the messenger.  
<p>
 Consider what's taking place right now in the Manhattan office
of John Reardon, the former president of MTV. When the pundits
talk about interactive TV, most of them foresee a new social
order in which consumers take control of programming and tell
Congress, TV networks, and telephone companies alike what they
want and when they want it. The rhetoric is all about individual
empowerment. Reardon, who is now chief of a new interactive television
company called ZING, sees much the opposite: empowerment for
advertisers.   
<p>
 The ZING device is handheld, sleek, and user-friendly. A tiny
LCD screen receives messages from the TV. When the ZING beeper
sounds and the ZING logo appears on the LCD screen, Reardon explains,
viewers will be able to pile up ZING points, which will be something
like green stamps, just by clicking. Of course, there'll be prizes
for the big ZINGers. And of course, a lot of the ZING moments
will occur during commercials, discouraging channel surfing by
ZING viewers intent on piling up ZING points. The entire ZING
system will sell for $150 per handheld unit.   
<p>
 Being at one end of the interactive ZING system is like having
beeper service with the world's big advertisers on the other
end. Every change of channel and every other entry into the ZING
system gets recorded. Imagine that a ZING viewer is watching
the fly-fishing channel on a 500-channel cable system. Suddenly
ZING provides an opportunity to buy the wizard worm that the
host has been using to haul in bass after bass.  
<p>
 "It asks me, Would you like to purchase this product, yes or
no?' And I press yes, enter," Reardon says. "And it asks in what
quantity, and I say one, enter. It says my state, my style, color,
and all those things. It's all downloaded in a flash. Now this
will do the calculations and come up with the sale price and
the total price and the shipping and handling and all that. And
to order press phone." Reardon points the ZING unit at the black
box near the phone. "Now that's the prototype of the ZING dialer."<p>
<p>
 The folks on Madison Avenue will have to reinvent the advertising
industry once advertising is judged on its ability to generate
impulse sales in hundreds or thousands of niches the instant
the ad is aired. "Madison Avenue is not set up to do this kind
of niche marketing," says Bob Allen, director of new business
development at Modem Media, a Connecticut direct advertising
agency that specializes in interactive advertising currently
available on CD-ROMs, telephones, and fax machines. From 1990
to 1992 Allen's company registered a 103 percent increase in
revenues to $1.4 million.   
<p>
 Say good-bye to the idea of programs and channels as we now
know them. A program will actually be an interface like TV Guide
On Screen only more transparent and easier to use. Watching an
entertainment show on an Australian effort to climb K2, a viewer
might want to buy the mountain parka on the lead climber or want
to know more about the tent the expedition set up at 12,000 feet.
Click and enter a shopping window that offers descriptions of
the gear seen in the program. Or click and enter a menu that
offers more information sources on tents. At least potentially,
interactivity will fuse categories that we now keep separate,
such as programming, advertising, and ordering.  
<p>
 Is it any wonder that everyone is waiting to see what former
Fox chairman Barry Diller will do with a merged QVC and Home
Shopping Network? Except for the major catalog operations, which
have little experience with television, no one else in retailing
has the back end to handle the volumes of orders generated in
short periods of time by successful TV shopping programs. Home
Shopping Network and QVC sold well over $2 billion in merchandise
last year. Big retailers like Macy's have just started getting
their feet wet in electronic shopping. But they'll have to build
their back-end operations from scratch. In addition, no other
TV retailer has the potential to build a fifth TV network, as
Diller does. That kind of program clout would give Diller big
leverage with the cable system operators.  
<p>
 If the future were easy to predict, nobody would make big money
from guessing right, and interactive technology companies just
out of the chute wouldn't trade for a price-to-earnings ratio
of infinity귾ive or take a zero or two. Ambivalence seems the
smart investor's stance. There's opportunity here. Integral Partners'
Roger McNamee scored big by buying 3DO's initial public offering
at $15. But many investors글ndividual and corporate긍ill wind
up taking a bath. "We have a pool in the office about who will
be the first to take a $1 billion loss" in this industry, says
McNamee.  
<p>
 None of the rules of investing긆r of business근ver get repealed
for a new technology. Customers still buy products that they
need or that make them feel good. Companies still need to sell
those products at a price that appeals to the market. Some companies
have advantages in raising capital or in the speed with which
they can adapt to the market that give them an edge over competitors.
And some managements are just better at executing a business
plan. Paying attention to these fundamentals is the best way
to invest in interactive technology.  
<p><p>
<p>
Jim Jubak is a senior editor at Worth; freelance writer Curtis
Lang is a frequent contributor.  
<p>
  <hr>  
