				<p>
				<font size=5><b>Auto Motive</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>93/09-Auto Motive</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						September 1993 
<p>
Worth magazine/Departments  
<p>
 AUTO MOTIVE 
<p>
Kirk Kerkorian took a chance on Chrysler and won. Then again,
he could afford to.  
<p>
 By Suzanne Costas  
<p>
 Big money can afford to be contrarian. Yet auto analysts were
surprised by the news in December 1990 that Hollywood billionaire
Kirk Kerkorian had acquired almost 21 million shares of Chrysler
stock, giving him a nearly 10 percent stake in the company. The
third-largest car and truck manufacturer in the United States
continued to face enormous financial pressures, including an
overdependence on North American sales and rising fuel costs
triggered by the Persian Gulf crisis. It was heavily in debt.
The market braced for a dividend cut.   
<p>
 Though Chrysler's third-quarter loss per share of $0.95 was
moderately better than the Street had expected, the outlook for
'91 remained grim. Analysts predicted that industry demand would
fall 7 percent, and they believed Chrysler would have difficulty
maintaining market share. The underlying problems remained: a
weakening economy and, at Chrysler, a shortage of new product.<p>
<p>
 Kerkorian was not deterred. A shrewd investor, he proceeded
to acquire what he considered an undervalued stock. News stories
cited his high regard for Chrysler chairman Lee Iacocca as the
principal reason for his betting on the troubled car company.
The shares were purchased through Kerkorian's Tracinda Corporation
between October 11 and December 12, at prices ranging from $10.50
to $13.30. Two years later, his $258 million investment was worth
approximately $558 million.  
<p>
  <hr>  
<p>
Copyright 1993 Capital Publishing Limited Partnership. All rights
reserved. 
