	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 93/08-Crude Blood</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b> </b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>93/08-Crude Blood</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 
Hard times in the oil patch forced survival of the fittest
By Suzanne Costas<p>
You don't have to be a good old boy to understand the oil business. When oil prices are high, there are barbecues and crawfish boils; when prices are low, things are considerably less festive. In other words, it's boom-and-bust. <p>
Oil companies have coped with the current downturn through cutbacks, consolidation, and revised strategic planning. They've looked for ways to improve domestic production and have expanded international exploration. <p>
Yet investors have avoided oil stocks like the plague. <p>
Too bad. Any ailing industry has its survivors. Strong management and clean balance sheets, for example, have benefited a number of oil service companies, as have rising natural gas prices and the increase in international exploration. <p>
<a name="NYSE:WII"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12447"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Weatherford International</b></a>, a worldwide leader in tubing and casing services, in addition to specialized rental equipment, reported 1992 net income of $13.8 million, or $0.31 per common share, compared with a 1991 net loss of $6.8 million, or $0.21 per common share. Tidewater Inc., which owns and operates the world's largest fleet servicing the international offshore oil and gas industry, has more than stayed afloat: long-term debt declined by 70% since 1988, while its fleet grew by over 60% through a merger with Zapata Gulf. Because the downturn in the oil business has fueled demand for more reliable seismic information__better data means fewer dry holes__Input/Output Inc. has seen record sales and earnings. The company manufactures geophysical data gathering equipment. <p>
Analysts who expect a rebound in the oil industry over the next few years also forecast a substantial, long-term rally in oil field service stocks. <p>
In the oil patch, patience truly is a virtue. <p>
KEYWORDS: Investing Strategies

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/2pages.gif"><br>About 2 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

<font size=+1><b>Company Index</b><br>
</font>						<a href="#NYSE:WII">Weatherford Enterra Incorporated</a><br>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
</td>
	</tr>
