<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 93/08-The Trouble With Pennies From Heaven</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>93/08-The Trouble With Pennies From Heaven</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 <p>By Andrew Gluck<p>Eighty percent of Tom Holtz's clients have AIDS. Most of the others have cancer, heart disease, or amyotrophic lateral sclerosis. They're all terminally ill and are financially strapped in their final days by the high cost of medical treatment. They need cash, and they get it by using their life insurance policies in an unusual way--selling their death benefits (the right to the money their insurance will pay after they die) to Holtz's Dayton, Ohio-based Q-Foil Inc. <p>The sale is called a viatical settlement, and Q-Foil is one of at least 44 companies in the burgeoning viatical settlement business. Since the first viatical settlement closed on April 4, 1989, Affording Care (a non-profit group that distributes financial information and education for the seriously ill) estimates that some 2,300 terminally ill people have sold policy benefits to viatical firms for $200 million, converting their death benefit into a living asset. <p>The catch? Holtz's typical client is expected to live four years and he pays them 25 cents for every $1 of insurance. That means that someone whose heirs could expect $100,000 when he dies, might receive $25,000 today from Holtz. And that's not an unusual discount in the viatical settlement industry.<p>"The business appears ghoulish," says John Freeman Blake, a Washington, D.C.-based attorney and financial planner. "But when you look at it from the standpoint of the terminally ill, these firms are sources of desperately needed capital." <p>By providing cash that helps people live out their lives with dignity and financial independence, viatical settlements unquestionably offer much-needed help. And while the majority of settlements have been made by AIDS patients, people with other terminal diseases are likely to use this new vehicle in growing numbers as word of it spreads. <p>But terminally ill people and their relatives or friends that assist them in financial matters should proceed with caution: Viatical settlement companies often offer wildly differing bids for the same insurance benefits, and the financial difficulties faced by the terminally ill make them vulnerable to profiteers now flocking to an industry where compounded annual returns of more than 25% are common. Although competition from a growing number of settlement firms is driving settlements up, it can really pay to shop around.<p>The term viatical settlement is derived from the lexicon of religion. A viaticum is one of the sacraments in last rites. And true to their lineage, viatical settlements are financial vehicles of last resort.<p>Even before exploring the sale of a life insurance policy, find out whether it's possible to receive an "accelerated benefit" directly from the insurance company. In the past couple of years, life insurers have started offering riders (amendments to policies) that would pay terminally ill people cash on their policies before they die__and they generally pay about 95% of the face value of a policy, far more than viatical settlement companies. <p>The problem is that only about 70 insurers have such riders, and they usually don't apply to employer-sponsored term life policies that most often are viaticated. What's more, they usually don't take effect until the insured has no more than six months to live. Yet with the high cost of medical care today, financial resources can run out long before that.<p>Another alternative to viatication is a loan from friends or relatives against a policy's death benefit. A personal loan or accelerating a benefit from an insurer is better than viaticating because, unlike viatication, the payback is tax-free. That allows for bigger payouts. (At this writing, some question about accelerated benefits remains, but the IRS has proposed rules to make them formally tax-free.)<p>But if an insurer says there's no chance of accelerating benefits and a loan isn't possible, then it's time to explore dealing with the viatical settlement firms. <p>Viatical firms use a simple formula to calculate how much to offer for a policy. Basically, they figure what the money would earn if it were invested elsewhere during the term of the policy holder's life expectancy. They then subtract their interest and profit from the face value of a policy and buy it at a discount. The longer the life expectancy, the less they will pay.<p>That puts a potential policy seller in the awkward position of convincing the viatical company that death is near, warranting a higher settlement, while the viatical company is more inclined to think the policy seller will live longer, decreasing the policy's value. <p>Q-Foil, like other firms, reviews client medical records and confirms life-expectancy assessments made by the insured's personal physician. Then, Q-Foil becomes the beneficiary of the policy and requires that all previous beneficiaries but one sign waivers forfeiting any benefits. As many other firms do, Q-Foil allows one other beneficiary to get between $2,500 and $10,000 in death benefits provided he notifies Q-Foil upon the death of the policyholder. <p>Q-Foil, however, is unique to the industry because it purchases policies from people with longer life expectancies. Most viatical companies buy policies from people with 18 months to two years to live and pay cash settlements of 60 to 65 cents for every dollar of coverage. Holtz will buy policies from people expected to live between three and a half and five years, but he usually pays only 20% to 35% of a policy's face value. He once purchased a policy from a man with a ten-year life expectancy, paying him 10% of the policy's face value.<p>Holtz can afford to take more risk because he uses a controversial approach: When Holtz purchases a policy from a terminally ill person, he sometimes asks them to apply for additional "guaranteed" life insurance policies. They cost a lot more than conventional life insurance but require no physical exams, nor disclosure of having a terminal illness. And a life policy on someone with a life expectancy of only a few years can be lucrative. <p>The practice of buying insurance on terminal patients is derided by some of Holtz's competitors, who say that Q-Foil should give clients a share of the proceeds it expects to make on the guaranteed life policy, and they warn that the tactic could cause financial problems for the small regional insurance companies that offer guaranteed policies. <p>Holtz responds that the point is becoming moot, because all but one insurance company that sells guaranteed life policies has begun asking applicants to disclose whether they know they are HIV-positive. But he adds that the additional insurance enabled him to offer higher settlements on longer life expectancies than anyone else, benefiting his clients.<p>For people in need, the differences in benefits can be critical. While the viatical companies all look at the same data, the conclusions they arrive at about the value of a particular policy can vary widely. For instance, a 38-year-old AIDS patient recently submitted applications to several viatical companies and received bids on his three life insurance policies ranging from 35% to 82% of their total face value. Per Larson, a New York City fee-only financial planner and health economist, says the large disparities in bids for the same policy illustrates that "there is an incredible opportunity to negotiate." <p>David Petersen, a New York financial planner with AIDS and cancer and a founder of Affording Care, recommends applying to at least five viatical companies. "Most of the hard work is done after you've filled out the first application," he says. <p>One option in shopping for a viatical settlement is to enlist the help of a broker. About half of the 44 companies listed by Affording Care are actually brokers, who often get 3% to 6% commissions. "It's okay to go to a broker," says Petersen. "But be sure to go to a true broker." Some brokers sell policies to only one or two viatical settlement companies, which limits the number of bids while adding a layer of expenses. <p>Another alternative is to deal directly with the purchasing companies, which use their own money to purchase policies or raise funds privately in a partnership. Only one of the approximately 25 purchasing companies, Living Benefits Inc. in Albuquerque, New Mexico, is publicly held. <p>"The money these firms have, including the publicly held company, usually comes in big chunks," says Petersen. "They go out and raise cash and are flush for awhile. A purchasing company that is sitting on a cash hoard is likely to offer a better settlement. But there's no way of knowing which are sitting on cash, and people just have to use the dartboard method or apply to all of them." <p>Petersen warns that some viatical firms have strung people along for weeks while they try to raise the money to buy a policy, and others have lowered settlement offers right before a deal is about to close. He recommends walking away from such companies.<p>Someone who is considering viatication but doesn't want to be directly involved in the negotiations may want to consult a financial planner. A planner can help with tax planning issues and usually can structure a settlement so it won't cut off government entitlements, such as Medicaid or Supplemental Social Security Income. While most planners don't have experience in making viatical settlements, they can sometimes make referrals to an advisor who has worked with terminally ill people. <p>
Worth Senior Writer Andrew Gluck reports from New York.<p>-----<p>CAVEAT PATIENT<p>The potential for abuse of terminally ill people in desperate need of cash has raised concerns among state insurance regulators. California and Kansas have enacted legislation that requires viatical companies to register and make consumer-protection disclosures about their business. According to David Lyons, who heads a National Association of Insurance Commissioners' subcommittee on viatical settlements, "there was enough concern relating to viatical settlements" for the NAIC to begin drafting a model law that all 50 states could adopt. With little regulation and no uniform disclosure rules, the present state of the industry demands caution from anyone considering viatication.<p>New York-based Affording Care offers the most complete list of viatical settlement companies and updates it periodically. But Affording Care doesn't rate the companies or report on which ones offer the best settlements and what diseases or stages of disease they specialize in. <p> <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Insurance Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

