<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 97/02-Columns: The Cost of Gridlock</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>97/02-Columns: The Cost of Gridlock</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						We elected a divided government -- are we now ready to let the market fix Social Security and Medicare?<p>
By Walter Russell Mead<p>
In November's campaigns, politicians lied about their intentions, distorted their opponents' records, kissed babies, and slung mud. The one thing they didn't do was talk about the real problems we're likely to face in the next four years.<p>
With so little of importance apparently at stake, one of the lowest percentages on record of those eligible to vote cast ballots to divide authority between a Democratic White House and a Republican Congress. The country -- or at least Wall Street -- suffered an outbreak of euphoria after the election. Powered by a new mantra, "Gridlock is good," the Dow Jones Industrials roared past 6000 on the way to 6500 between election day and Thanksgiving.<p>
I understand why this gridlock looks so attractive, given the propensity, for example, of U.S. senators to sing "Old MacDonald Had a Farm" into The Congressional Record. Republican control of Congress gives Wall Street confidence that there will be no letup in the pressure to balance the budget. At the other end of Pennsylvania Avenue, President Clinton will temper the more extreme initiatives of Republican revolutionaries -- and the market hates all revolutionaries, whether on the left or right.<p>
But gridlock is a lousy way to tackle pressing problems that demand real and perhaps unpleasant solutions. Given the murkiness of both parties' stands during the 1996 campaigns, neither Clinton nor Congress has anything like a mandate for what to do when we face the next recession or for how we should rein in entitlement programs, such as Medicare and Social Security. I'm afraid that the election results mean our divided government will tackle neither of these issues. Instead, the solutions will be worked out by the rough-and-tumble of the market -- a process that is likely to be extremely painful for many Americans.<p>
Let's start with the short-term problem: the dreaded r-word. Wall Street euphoria to the contrary, the odds are much better than even that we're going to have a recession in the next four years.<p>
Since World War II, the average economic expansion has lasted 50 months. The longest peacetime expansion occurred in the 1980s, when Ronald Reagan and George Bush presided over a 92-month business expansion between November 1982 and July 1990. The longest expansion ever began under President Kennedy and, boosted by the Vietnam War, ended 106 months later in 1969. Most of the others were much shorter: Half of the ten since 1945 lasted less than 39 months.<p>
The current business expansion was 68 months old as of Bill Clinton's second inauguration. That makes it already a little long in the tooth by historic standards; if it lasts until the next president takes the oath of office in January 2001, then it will be the Methuselah of American business expansions, at 116 months. Chances are that sometime in the next two to three years the economy is going to head south.<p>
Recessions have always been bad news for politicians. When millions of people lose their jobs, the voters get restive. But a recession in the next four years is going to have an unusually large impact on U.S. politics.<p>
Having sworn -- again -- to slay the deficit dragon in seven years from 1995, both parties loaded all the painful cuts into years four through seven. Those cuts will soon start to bite. Even without a recession, our divided government faces the deeply distasteful choice of either cutting the deficit (and offending millions of voters) or letting it grow (and offending millions of voters).<p>
Recessions, however, make deficits worse. The federal government collects about 20 percent of gross domestic product in taxes. With GDP now at roughly $7.6 trillion, every percentage point of growth means $76 billion of new economic output, of which $15 billion goes to Uncle Sam. The current balanced-budget scenarios assume annual growth of about 2.5 percent, meaning they count on government revenues to grow by about $38 billion every year.<p>
But if -- or when -- a recession comes, we won't get that growth. Assuming a relatively mild recession in which the economy shrinks by only one percentage point, we will see government revenues decline by $15 billion. Add that to the $38 billion a year in revenue growth that our current budget-balancing scenarios rely on, and a recession could easily increase the budget deficit by $53 billion -- almost half of the 1996 deficit of $107 billion.<p>
A recession will widen the gulf that divides the parties. Republicans will blame the recession on high taxes, excessive regulation, and, of course, the deficit. They will argue for tax cuts and spending cuts to get the economy moving.<p>
Democrats will sing a different tune, talking about government's responsibility to help the poor and scoffing at supply-side and trickle-down economics.<p>
Those deep ideological differences will make it difficult for Washington to do anything during the next recession. And while doing nothing may seem okay to most Americans and to Wall Street when the sun is shining, gridlock while people suffer and business activity drops will not produce optimism among consumers or investors.<p>
But this isn't the biggest problem of the next four years. The pitched battle over entitlements is likely to make arguments about how best to help people who are jobless and hungry seem absolutely polite.<p>
Entitlement programs provide a service to all those who need it no matter how much it costs. Social Security is an entitlement and so is Medicare.<p>
Entitlements are wildly popular, and voters are deeply suspicious of any effort to tamper with them. But the costs of Social Security and Medicare are both headed for the stratosphere as the American population ages. Medicare and Social Security costs combined are likely to rise from about 8 percent of GDP in 1996 to more than 15 percent of GDP in 2040.<p>
Both of these programs are currently funded out of special payroll taxes: 15.3 percent of total pay up to $62,700 for Social Security and 2.9 percent of total pay for Medicare. (These taxes are split 50-50 between employers and employees.) If we project current trends, by 2040 Social Security and Medicare withholding taxes could eat up nine-tenths of every worker's taxable pay.<p>
Clearly, that's not going to happen. If politicians proposed tax increases like that, they would be tarred and feathered. What makes things difficult is that the same fate awaits politicians who propose the kinds of cuts in Social Security and Medicare that would keep taxes at or near current levels.<p>
The first Clinton term saw both the White House and Congress wrestling in vain with this dismal arithmetic. The Clinton health-care plan was an attempt to rein in Medicare costs by structural reform in the health-care industry that would limit long-term federal costs. The health-care industry fought back hard. The White House lost that battle, and the Democrats were routed in the 1994 midterm elections.<p>
Next, the Republicans stepped up to the plate. Speaker of the House Newt Gingrich led off with an alternative approach to entitlements: scaling them back. The GOP balanced-budget plan aimed at slowing the growth in federal Medicare spending from 10 percent per year to 7 percent. A devastating series of Democratic campaign ads inveighed against the Republican assault on Medicare, and Gingrich became the most unpopular man in the country.<p>
Voters now clearly expect the two parties to come up with a joint plan. At least at the level of rhetoric, both parties have accepted that task. But each party is actually hoping that it can use the entitlements battle to end divided government in its favor. Democrats want to eliminate the Social Security wage ceiling, which would raise at least $58 billion a year -- and put most of the burden on the affluent. Combined with another Democratic idea -- raising the tax rate on the Social Security benefits collected by the affluent -- this would substantially relieve the burden on the federal Treasury and shift the costs to taxpayers who vote Republican.<p>
Republicans argue, in effect, that Democratic voters should pay more of the costs. Raising the retirement age will, for example, not affect professionals who hold mentally challenging but physically undemanding jobs. Investment bankers and, ahem, economic commentators might not mind working at 72, but steelworkers and day-care workers certainly will.<p>
Both parties are likely to support reducing cost-of-living increases in Social Security benefits to put such increases in line with new research that shows statistics overstate the rate of inflation. Partial privatization is another option, but designing a transition between the present system, which uses current taxes to pay benefits, and one based on compulsory savings isn't simple.<p>
If some of these problems and solutions had been honestly addressed during the recent elections, I'd have some hope that our politicians could hammer out workable compromises. But the campaigns didn't offer competing visions, and I don't look for Gingrich and Clinton to suddenly lead a meaningful policy discussion now. The choices are too ugly, the problems too far off, and the stakes too high to motivate any politician to engage in anything other than a quick fix.<p>
Like it or not, while Washington dithers, the economy will impose its own solutions. The real value of government retirement benefits for baby boomers will fall -- through inflation, official cuts in benefits, or some combination of the two -- to a sustainable level. Market forces will transform the health-care industry in ways that ensure that the America of 2040 has a health-care system it can pay for. For example, the most expensive forms of care will be rationed. The elderly will rely more on savings and the help of their families; those without supportive relatives or substantial savings will suffer.<p>
Both Wall Street and the public at large are likely to bemoan the gridlock that prevents Washington from taking effective action. But this is what we voted for. It's just that the gridlock we embraced in the feel-good part of the economic cycle won't seem quite as enticing when we face our real problems. <p>
Walter Russell Mead, a senior contributing editor to Worth, is the presidential fellow at the World Policy Institute at the New School. Research assistance provided by Noah Sternthal.<p>
KEYWORDS: 
economy, politics, red tape

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

