<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 97/01S-World Tour '97</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>97/01S-World Tour '97</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						By Todd G. Buccholz<p>
"Hell no, we won't grow!" seems to have been the fight song of the world's major economies the past few years, in defiance of perennial predictions for a synchronized global recovery. Look beyond the U.S. and the U.K. and you have to squint pretty hard to find much in the way of economic success since 1991. Japan has been struggling with a banking crisis and a stock market still more than 40 percent off its peak. Germany and France have been losing the fight to push their unemployment rates below 10 percent. And Latin America is still wincing from the devaluation of the Mexican peso in 1994. You could've slept right through 1996 and not missed a blip on the world's economic radar. Seldom have economists been so successful simply by extrapolating recent boring trends.<p>
And yet most major equity markets have appreciated this boring state of affairs. After a stellar 33 percent leap in 1995, the Dow Jones average jumped 22 percent through the first ten months of 1996. Over the same period, Germany's DAX climbed 21 percent and Sweden's OMX index 24 percent. Even Brazil staged a recovery, racking up a 53 percent gain for investors. There's little mystery here, however: It's about low interest rates. Lower rates make stock dividends seem larger, assets more powerful, and liabilities less threatening. If investors see that bank CDs and Treasury bills are paying a paltry 5 percent, they're more likely to put their money in the stock market.<p>
We've had gloriously low world interest rates for two reasons. First, governments are squeezing their deficits and borrowing less from the private sector. The U.S. budget deficit has dropped to about 1.4 percent of gross domestic product, and Europe is racing toward the ambitious goal of 3 percent of GDP; of the G7 countries, only Japan has actually pumped up its deficit. Second, and more importantly, we have low global interest rates precisely because so many economies are in the dumps. Few people or firms want to borrow when their economy looks feeble. In 1996, GDP growth in the developed world averaged just 2.2 percent, barely enough to prevent unemployment from rising. Yet inflation could not be found; it actually slipped from 2.4 percent in 1995 to 2.2 percent in 1996. This goaded central banks into cutting official interest rates. Perversely, this suggests we've got higher stock prices because these economies look so pathetic. As Oscar Hammerstein's King of Siam says, "It's a puzzlement."<p>
Will the puzzle pieces remain in place in 1997? Herbert Stein, an economic adviser to Presidents Nixon and Ford, once said, drolly, "If something cannot go on forever, it will stop." And the trend of sluggish growth and rising stock prices cannot go on forever. But what no one knows is whether it will stop with an exciting plunge into a recession -- complete with crashing equities -- or be replaced by the blissful synchronized global growth that makes money for people everywhere. The equity markets have been expecting the latter, counting on a delicate balance of events that will permit economies to grow and firms to return to profitability without triggering inflation or a surge in the demand for credit (either of which would punch up interest rates). I suppose this bliss is possible, but I'm doubtful. Among other dangers, three rather large factors will confront the world's markets with enormous risks during the year: (1) the flow of Japanese capital, (2) the impact of Asian economies on commodity prices, and (3) the political trends in Europe.<p>
Land of the Rising Bank Debts<p>
We've probably all heard about the "too-big-to-fail doctrine": When you owe the bank $100, you're in trouble; when you owe the bank $1 million, the bank's in trouble. Actually, financial markets everywhere might be in trouble in 1997. Japan has been the world's biggest creditor, but its banking industry has looked bankrupt. After years of stonewalling, the Japanese government admitted last year that the top financial institutions carry more than $117 billion in bad loans. Many private firms estimated that the figure is much higher. Nor are private-sector banks the only ones drowning in red ink. The government itself has seen its budget deficit explode to about 5 percent of GDP. Compare that with the U.S., where the budget deficit has shrunk to just 1.4 percent. Even Sweden has stomped its budget deficit from 10.8 percent of GDP in 1994 to just 4.4 percent in 1996.<p>
Despite the tide of red ink, Japan continues to shovel money out its doors to the rest of the world. Several forces are contributing to this movement. First, there's terribly sluggish bank lending, growing at less than 2 percent a year. The Bank of Japan pushed its official discount rate all the way down to 0.5 percent in September 1995. Normally such a drastically low rate would send bank lending off the charts, but not in Japan. Imagine: The central bank is practically giving money away -- and there are few takers. That's because business prospects continue to look dim, and borrowers don't seem too creditworthy during the fifth year of near-recession. Small and medium-sized businesses are finding it especially tough to qualify for loans, so the banks send their money abroad.<p>
Second, Japanese investors are shoveling their savings into foreign markets. Japanese financial institutions have been big buyers of U.S. Treasurys for years, of course, and own over $283 billion worth. But there's a new trend to grapple with: Ma-and-pa investors are now smitten with foreign bonds as well. Japanese brokerage houses have been offering seminars to inform small investors that they can earn big returns by buying government bonds from the U.S., Germany, Canada, and Australia. The Nikkei newspaper runs ads promising great results. And in the past year, these bonds have in fact been bargains. Not only have the prices of Australian bonds, for example, gone up significantly, but the Australian dollar appreciated 12 percent against the yen in the first ten months of 1996, giving investors a supercharged return. The word in Japan is that the mas and pas raking in these returns have been directing their friends to follow the yellow brick road to foreign investments.<p>
Finally, Japanese money takes vacations. Japanese tourists have more than tripled in number during the past ten years, supporting the service industries of major countries throughout the world. Though tourism is often dismissed here as a leisure activity, technically it's one of the biggest American exports -- when foreigners stay in a U.S. hotel, it counts as an export.<p>
All this adds up to a world so used to Japanese savers -- with their 15 percent savings rate underwriting the rest of the world's investments -- that shifts in Japan's behavior can rock the international economy. For instance, should the Bank of Japan decide that its 0.5 percent official discount rate is too low in the face of an imminent recovery, a rate hike might produce a credit squeeze in Japan, and foreign investments would look less attractive. Keep in mind that foreign investors, led by the Japanese, rushed to U.S. bond auctions in 1996 and purchased about three-quarters of our new debt. If the Japanese change their domestic interest rates, world interest rates will be driven higher. Remember when I said that equity markets have been nourished by extraordinarily low interest rates?<p>
The Mysterious East and Its NOT-SO-HOT Commodities<p>
That scraping sound you heard last fall was the sound of commodity prices skidding in response to disappointing world economic growth. Except in the case of oil -- prices are still bubbling from the dashed expectations of Iraqi oil exports -- soft commodity demand demonstrates that a synchronized global economic recovery is more a dream than a reality. From late April to early November 1996, the Commodity Research Bureau Index dropped nearly 10 percent. First the industrial economies struggled to move forward during the past few years, next Latin America hit a brick wall in 1995, then the one solidly growing region (non-Japan Asia) took a hit in 1996, and the pressures in the commodity markets relaxed.<p>
I'm not talking recession in Asia, but Asia's flying Tigers (Indonesia, the Philippines, Thailand, and Malaysia) and Dragons (Taiwan, Hong Kong, South Korea, and Singapore) have stopped roaring and breathing fire. South Korea slowed from 9 percent GDP growth in 1995 to about 6.5 in 1996, China from 10.2 percent to 8.5, and Singapore from 8.9 percent to 7. Nothing to be ashamed of, but Japan used to grow at similar stratospheric levels -- until its economy matured. Now Japan would feel lucky to post 3 percent growth in GDP. These Asian countries knew they, too, would someday mature and slow their pace. But they didn't expect to do so this soon.<p>
A lull in Asia's rapid growth could send ripples -- or tidal waves -- abroad. Precipitately slowing exports worry the financial markets and could lead to Mexico-like crises. During the first five months of 1996, Asia's exports inched along at 7 percent growth, compared with nearly 30 percent over the same period in 1995. But imports -- ranging from machines to equip new factories to consumer goods purchased by slightly wealthier workers -- didn't slow as quickly, and in 1995 Thailand and Malaysia registered current-account deficits greater than 8 percent of GDP. If this continues and their export machines can't get up to full speed again, investors may get nervous about the creditworthiness of these countries, driving up interest rates and further slowing investment and growth.<p>
On the other hand, if the now tamer Dragons and Tigers somehow rebound in 1997, a big bounce in commodity prices might give the world's central bankers the inflation jitters. Oil looks especially vulnerable to any Asian surge. In the past 20 years, Asia -- excluding Japan -- has tripled its oil consumption (from 3.6 million barrels a day to 11.2 million in 1995) and more than doubled its share of world oil consumption (from 6.4 percent to 16 percent). So far, this hasn't shaken oil markets much, because China has essentially been energy self-sufficient. But watch out: China will be a heavy importer of energy in the next century.<p>
True, higher commodity prices in the recent past have not sparked worldwide inflation. If you looked only at commodities in the spring of 1994, you would have expected a big jump in inflation when the CRB Index leaped 6 percent between April and May. Yet nothing happened, because this spike took place when most of the world was in recession. World output in 1997 might not be so flat. Last fall, the Bank of England raised interest rates, the only upward move by a G7 country in 1996 (every other G7 country slashed rates last year). If the BOE is seen as a leading indicator of global monetary policy, the relaxed and complacent commodities markets will liven up and signal a rebound in world growth.<p>
All Quiet on the Western Front?<p>
For now, European politics appears as dull as European economies. Where are the masses of striking Parisians paralyzing public services and leaving commuters stranded in their gridlocked Peugeots? Where are the fractious Spaniards accusing their former prime minister Felipe Gonz涇ez of aiding domestic terrorists? Where are the Social Democrats in Germany dismissing Chancellor Helmut Kohl as a bumptious relic of the past? And where are the Communists of Italy threatening to overturn the social order? Addressing just this last question dramatically explains how much Europe has changed. Believe it or not, the Italian Communists have become willing partners in a center-left coalition government that is straining to cut public spending!<p>
Put simply, Europe has adopted the "bond-market paradigm" that U.S. Treasury secretary Robert E. Rubin sold to President Clinton at the outset of his first term -- cut spending, raise taxes, cut the deficit, and let the resultant lower interest rates buoy the economy. But in Europe, there's a twist: The governments are trying to rein in deficits and inflation so Europe can adopt a single currency in 1999. So far, deficits are edging down, and interest rates have plummeted and converged. Spanish ten-year bonds yielded over 3 percent more than German bonds in October 1995; by November 1996, that margin had been cut almost in half.<p>
If this progress continues, a single currency and a single official interest rate will prevail in Europe (outside the U.K. and Sweden, which have opted out of the European Monetary Union). But a big speed bump looms on the road to European unity. And, to borrow a phrase from Clinton's 1992 campaign, it's the economy. Europe has lower interest rates and lower budget deficits coming, but it also has rising unemployment. The jobless rate in France climbed from 10.4 percent in 1992 to 11.8 percent in 1996, while in Germany it jumped from 8.5 percent to 10 percent. The bond-market paradigm may have delighted European Union bookkeepers in Brussels, but it isn't creating jobs on the Continent.<p>
The danger this year is that voters will become fed up with the theoretical benefits of tight fiscal and monetary policies and begin bellyaching about "trivial" matters -- like paychecks and jobs. But any sign that Europe is backing away from the bond-market paradigm will injure global bond markets. Kohl faces reelection in 1998, as does French president Jacques Chirac in 2002. You can trust Kohl to maintain his commitment to the European Union, but Chirac is under attack from his fellow center-right "allies," as well as from the opposition Socialists. Will he bend or break? Watch the streets of Paris: They've been awfully calm lately.<p>
There are, of course, other risks in the world that might roil the global equity markets. In Russia, Boris Yeltsin and his repaired heart may be regarded as a key test case for the durability of new capitalist countries after they've thrown out their Communist past. If Russia receives a failing grade -- by, say, relapsing into political chaos -- investors might sour on China's future. Investor confidence might be crimped in Germany, too, which is seen as economically vulnerable to Russian disaster. Here, as in other potential trouble spots, the echoing interconnectedness of the global markets is on display.<p>
The Olympic Games, with its interlocking rings and its ability to bring the world together, furnish an apt metaphor for the markets as they move from 1996 to 1997. The world economy walked a balance beam in 1996, carefully skirting recession on one side and inflation on the other. The routine received a high grade from the financial markets but a low grade from the citizenry, which cares more about jobs than about debt-to-GDP ratios. It's hard to imagine keeping this balance throughout 1997. The central bankers, who thrive in this kind of low-inflation sport, will probably be forced to take up a more stressful event this year. Like the modern pentathlon, perhaps, that run-and-shoot competition.<p>
Contributing editor Todd G. Buchholz is a managing director of a New York됵ased international investment fund.<p>
KEYWORD:  international, global, international relations, politics

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

