<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 97/01S-What Comes Next</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>97/01S-What Comes Next</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Maybe 1997 will be another perfect year -- low inflation, modest growth, and a great stock market. More likely, investors will get only two out of three.<p>
By Jim Jubak<p>
Does it get any better than this? At the beginning of 1996, investors worried that the economy would grow too fast, inflation would pick up, and the Federal Reserve would send the financial markets tumbling by raising interest rates. Or, just as bad, the economy would slow too rapidly, corporate earnings would fall, and that would take down the stock market. But the economy has avoided both the rock and the hard place. Growth has chugged along near the Federal Reserve's target of 2.5 percent. Inflation has hovered around 3 percent. And the Fed, professing itself content, left interest rates alone in September and November. Corporate earnings have not only continued to increase but have actually picked up a bit of speed recently. Even the election fulfilled Wall Street's dreams: It confirmed the status quo. In fact, the current economic recovery -- at 67 months (as of November), the second longest in United States history -- looked strongerat the end of the year than it did for most of 1996.<p>
It's no wonder that the stock market continued its winning streak -- now dating back to October 1990. On November 14, the Dow Jones Industrials blasted through 6300 for the first time, closing at 6313. "The perfect economy has got even more perfect," says Ben Zacks of Zacks Investment Research in Chicago, summing up the current view on Wall Street. <p>
And that's precisely the problem. At this level, the market is assuming that what has been dubbed the Goldilocks economy can spawn yet another great year in 1997. It had better. Only if this "just right" economy delivers the wildly optimistic corporate earnings that Wall Street analysts now predict will investors see returns of 10 percent on the Standard & Poor's 500 Stock Index for the year. Even a little imperfection will likely produce a flat to negative year -- as much as a 7 to 12 percent drop in the S&P 500 -- in 1997. "The risk-reward ratio is extremely unfavorable for 1997," says Michael Metz, chief investment strategist at Oppenheimer & Co.<p>
But investors don't have to stay blindly committed to this market or move in a rush to the sidelines. There is a third alternative. The upcoming year should reward not the indexer who mimics the entire market but the stock picker who targets specific sectors. A reading between the lines of the predictions of Wall Street economists and market strategists suggests the outlines of a winning strategy for 1997. Best of all, this strategy can be the foundation for a portfolio that should thrive for years to come.<p>
Try Not to Worry<p>
Why does Wall Street think the porridge is just right? Because it believes it sees the potential problems clearly enough to discount them. The possible threats fall into five areas. All will bear watching in 1997 -- both individually and collectively.<p>
Consumer spending. Consumers could turn reluctant. Susan Sterne, chief economist at Economic Analysis Associates in Greenwich, Connecticut, is a worrywart about the state of consumers' wallets. She feels that consumers are under more strain than the numbers show. Her evidence is admittedly anecdotal. Wal-Mart's television ads push a Christmas credit card rather than low prices. Sears, which records 60 percent of its sales on its store-brand credit card, is testing a co-branded MasterCard. "The only reason you do that is if you're afraid you've tapped out your own cardholders," says Sterne. If she's right, consumers might well frolic at Christmas and then abandon stores in January and February. That could result in rocky earnings in the first quarter of 1997.<p>
True, yet with consumer-confidence numbers at record levels and banks continuing to push new credit cards and higher limits at consumers, a mass decision to stop spending and pay off debt instead seems -- at least at the moment -- unlikely.<p>
Demographic shifts. Demographics could take a big bite out of U.S. consumption, slowing the economy. Richard Hokenson, demographer for Donaldson, Lufkin & Jenrette in New York, notes that in 1997 the number of 25-year-olds in the population will drop by about 10 percent. The last time there was a decline this big was 1973, not exactly a banner year for the stock market or the economy. The latest drop, Hokenson projects, could lead to a consumer recession.<p>
Even if Hokenson's forecast of a demographic recession in 1997 is extreme, his larger point is certainly valid. An aging population will drive down economic growth rates in the U.S. Most economists agree that as the baby boomers age they'll start saving more, and that reduces the demand for things. Consumer spending closely tracks consumer age. For example, the number of 25-year-olds in the U.S. population peaked in 1986 at 4.5 million. Not coincidentally, 1986 also marks a historic high in housing starts (at 1.8 million) and car and truck sales (at 16.3 million).<p>
All in all, though, the demographic argument seems to support a slow-growth rather than a negative-growth scenario. The aging of the U.S. population is probably one reason this recovery has been among the weakest on record, but it doesn't argue for no growth in the diversified U.S. economy.<p>
Inflation. A mere whiff of inflation could spook the Federal Reserve and the financial markets, since they already appear to have declared victory on the inflation front. The minutes of the September 24 meeting of the Federal Reserve's Open Market Committee show that Federal Reserve chairman Alan Greenspan argued against a rate hike, saying that inflation wasn't apparent in the numbers yet. A month later, at an October speech to the conference board, Greenspan strongly hinted that he believed current measures overstate the inflation rate. What's more, Wall Street assumes that the committee studying this issue, chaired by former Council of Economic Advisors head Michael Boskin, will go even further and declare that inflation is now effectively zero and has been for some time.<p>
Inflation could come from two sources: wages and raw materials. While the average number of hours worked held steady, average hourly wages increased in September, continuing a trend that began earlier in the year, and the Federal Reserve districts reported "steady pressure to increase wages" in most sections of the country. <p>
Oil prices climbed from August to October, rising about 25 percent, before retreating briefly in November. If the increase sticks, it could add as much as 0.3 percent to the inflation rate in the U.S. But with new oil supplies coming on-line, energy prices should rise only moderately in 1997, says Steven Strongin, director of commodities research at Goldman Sachs.<p>
Metals won't be the commodities pressure point either, unless economic growth picks up drastically in Japan and Europe. Grain? The current crop is the second largest in history. The global economy hasn't experienced significant commodities-based inflation for the past two years, says Strongin. But he also sees nothing on the horizon that strongly argues for a big change in 1997. Oppenheimer's Metz was alone among the analysts we talked to in suggesting that global growth would be strong enough in 1997 to start serious commodity-price inflation.<p>
Treasury trouble. Global investors and central banks could abandon the U.S. bond market. In the past three years, the U.S. has accumulated a current-accounts deficit (that's the value of goods and services we export minus the value of goods and services we import) of $436 billion -- about the total estimated savings accumulated in the rest of the developed world during that period. A good deal of the cash to finance that deficit has come from foreign central banks. They currently hold over $600 billion in U.S. Treasurys, up about 20 percent in the 12 months ended October 1996.<p>
Why are foreign central banks so willing to hold our IOUs? An October study by Goldman Sachs provides some interesting answers. Higher interest rates are important. With Japanese bonds paying just 0.5 percent and German interest rates also low, U.S. Treasurys are a great place to park cash. But, according to Goldman Sachs, that's just part of the reason. About half the balance is probably a result of central banks' buying dollars in order to weaken their own currencies against the dollar. That would make Japanese and German imports more competitive -- important to two governments trying to get their own economies rolling.<p>
The policy has had its effects. After hitting a high of 85 yen to the dollar in June 1995, the yen fell to 112 this October. In pure currency terms, an American orange in Tokyo is now 32 percent more expensive, and a Japanese Lexus in Los Angeles is now 32 percent cheaper. (In the real world, producers try not to pass on all of the higher prices caused by currency shifts. The price of a Lexus won't drop this much, because when the yen was more expensive, the car's maker, Toyota, found ways to cut costs instead of devastating sales by passing all of the price increase on to consumers.)<p>
Overseas holdings of U.S. Treasurys present two dangers for the "just right" economy. Foreign banks could decide their economies are on the road to recovery and stop accumulating dollars -- or even, gasp, sell some of their Treasurys. That would send U.S. interest rates higher. But this seems unlikely, since the Japanese economy recently slipped back into official recession after notching its second straight quarter of negative growth, and the German economy, while showing strength, is still in a borderline recovery.<p>
More likely, and more damaging to corporate profits, central banks could continue to keep the dollar at these levels or perhaps nudge it just a bit higher. That would crimp U.S. exports and put pressure on prices here at home as domestic products felt more competition from cheaper foreign goods. The weak dollar has provided a pricing umbrella for U.S. companies, says Metz. That could vanish if the dollar stays strong. Lexus, for example, recently cut prices in the U.S. on many models by 3 percent to 10 percent. Secretary of the Treasury Robert E. Rubin will be the key person to watch on this issue. If he starts to talk about the dollar's being overvalued, it's a sign he's worried about its strength. If the dollar keeps rising after he makes such statements, U.S. exports and domestic profit margins could be in trouble.<p>
How likely is this? Not very. U.S.-Japanese relations would have to take a major turn for the worse for exchange rates to pose a truly serious threat to the economy and the market.<p>
Politics. Washington could tie itself in knots again. This is probably the least theatening of the five disaster scenarios, because the rest of us wouldn't stand for it. Most economists and certainly most of Wall Street have simply assumed that the results of the November election mean our politicians will hammer out a reasonable deficit-reduction package, probably after appointing a bipartisan blue-ribbon commission or two to "save" Social Security and Medicare. Despite some post-election posturing, that still seems the most likely outcome. The bond market, which will swoon at the first sign of fiscal irresponsibility, should provide the necessary discipline.<p>
Robert Rubin is also the key figure on this front. With the departures of Labor secretary Robert Reich and National Economic Council head Laura Tyson, Rubin becomes the administration's main economic player. Fortunately, Rubin has spent the past two years building good working relationships with Republicans in Congress. The odds are that the pragmatic Rubin will be able to work out a compromise on reducing the deficit and balancing the budget.<p>
The Trouble With Slow Growth<p>
So if the market is correct, and the five dangers are overblown, does that mean the coast is clear? Not entirely. The problem with the slow-growth, "perfect economy" scenario is that it puts more downward pressure on corporate earnings than the sanguine market now reflects. Currently, Wall Street analysts are projecting a 13.4 percent increase in earnings for the stocks in the S&P 500 in 1997, says Arnold Kaufman, editor of The Outlook, an investment-advisory newsletter. S&P's top-down analysis (extrapolated from general economic assumptions) suggests that 3 percent will be more like it. "To expect anything better than a below-average year is wishful thinking," says Kaufman. (The average return on large-company stocks since 1926 is 10.5 percent, according to Ibbotson Associates.)<p>
Ben Zacks sees almost exactly the same outlook in the data collected by Zacks Investment Research. Wall Street analysts are projecting 14 percent earnings growth for the stocks in the S&P 500 (his numbers are a little different from Kaufman's), while Wall Street economists are calling for 6 percent. "That's a little wider spread than usual," explains Zacks. "There's usually a five- to six-percentage-point difference at this time of year. There's a likelihood that analysts will have to cut estimates in 1997 to 5 or 6 percent." <p>
Hugh Johnson, chief investment officer of First Albany, is more pessimistic. "The year 1997 is likely to be tough for earnings," he says. "There's a good chance corporate profits in 1997 could be below those in 1996."<p>
Why this pessimism? The explanation is embedded in both the slow-growth scenario and the five worries we've already reviewed. While none of those concerns is enough to derail the Goldilocks economy, each cuts into corporate profits. For example, it takes only slightly lower consumer demand to make it impossible for companies to raise prices. And it takes just a little less demand to foil efforts to build unit volume by cutting prices. In fact, price-cutting is already failing as a tactic to boost sales for many companies, says economist Susan Sterne.<p>
Or consider inflation. Wages and commodity prices may not rise fast enough or far enough to trigger a Fed interest rate hike, but when companies can't easily raise prices without losing sales to competitors, every penny in extra raw materials or wages puts pressure on profit margins.<p>
This pressure comes at a particularly bad time: The drive toward efficiency that has done so much to raise the profitability of U.S. corporations has already cut a lot of the fat out of them. "The easy stuff has been done," says Robert Sanborn, manager of the $4.1 billion Oakmark Fund. That doesn't mean effiency can't add to the bottom line, just that only the best-run companies will be able to pull it off and that the gains won't be nearly as large as in past years. The companies in his portfolio, Sanborn says, believe they can still wring more economy out of their operations, but they are talking about only a slight increase in margins of 1 or 2 percent.<p>
Look at how the numbers add up. A company that expands sales in step with the 2 percent growth of the economy and also increases its profit margin by 2 percent -- say from 8 percent to 8.16 percent -- would increase earnings about 4 percent, a bit above the S&P 500's top-down projection but well below the 13.5 percent Wall Street is expecting.<p>
The earnings-related factors that have driven this market upward are running out of gas. Downsizing and other cost-cutting efforts have raised margins until the return on equity -- a measure of how profitable a company is -- stands at 25 percent, a historic high well above the average of about 15 percent for the past two decades. Investors' willingness to pay more and more for a dollar of earnings -- a reflection of their increasing confidence in managements' abilities -- also seems at a peak. The price-to-earnings ratio of the S&P 500 recently stood at 20. (Its average high in the years since 1976 is just 15.8.) "The story has been expansion in margins and the uptick in multiples," explains Metz. "That's over."<p>
The bottom line is that the market faces the real possibility of having earnings evaporate. Soon. Profits disappeared overnight in the 1990 recession, points out James Stack, president of InvesTech Research in Whitefish, Montana. At the end of a recovery, corporate management tries to stretch out the good news as long as possible, Stack explains. The company will recognize profits early and push off the day of reckoning on costs. When that's no longer possible, management decides to write off everything in a single quarter. A big loss isn't that much worse than a medium-sized one, in Wall Street's eyes. Companies, in fact, often get credit for biting the bullet. And management looks great, a year or so down the road, when results are compared with the big losses of the past. Creating a big loss is now the way that companies end one growth cycle and form the groundwork for another. <p>
What's an Investor to Do?<p>
Actually, plenty. By taking the lessons of this slow-growth economy to heart, investors can lay the foundations for what should be a profitable long-term portfolio. In 1997, the market is likely to be transitional. The short term will be rocky as the market and individual stocks get re-valued, but investors who understand the kinds of rotations from one style of stock to another that go on in transitional markets should be able to navigate this without too much pain.<p>
First, the long-term perspective. The torrid returns of the past two years have actually hidden a profound shift in the kinds of companies that make the best investment in today's economy. But 1997 should hold enough challenges for corporate managers that investors will be able to identify the companies that are likely to thrive as the rest of this decade unfolds.<p>
Second, look for companies that are in the right place demographically or that can take sales away from competitors. U.S. companies seeking easy growth will have to look overseas and to the developing world. During the same period when the 20- to 29-year-old age-group is falling in the developed countries by 15 percent, it will be climbing in Latin America, for example, by 18 percent. "If you're looking at consumer-goods companies, the only place you can get growth is in emerging international markets," says demographer Richard Hokenson.<p>
Some companies will be able to grow domestically by hammering their rivals. Home Depot is expanding at the expense of other companies in the home-improvement market. Intel continues to capture market share in the chip market.<p>
But neither of these growth strategies adds up to easy increases in prices and profit margins. Markets in the developing world won't allow most companies to keep their customary U.S. profit margins. It's one thing to sell $120 Nikes in the United States and another to sell them in Indonesia. And even a dominant domestic producer, such as Intel, now realizes that it relentlessly has to drive down prices of its own products. <p>
Face it, in the global economy, there's no place to hide from margin pressure. In the consumer area, strong brand names with cachet won't be enough if management goes to sleep on costs or product development. Even consumer-product companies will have to devote a big piece of cash to research and development. The model consumer company in this economy is Gillette (which has an R-and-D budget like that of a high-tech company), rather than Coca-Cola.<p>
None of this is reason to abandon companies that sell things. It's just that global trends favor companies that sell services. That's especially true in the aging developed world, where the over-40 crowd calls the shots. Baby boomers may be buying fewer cars as they get older, but they're sending more and more dollars to the companies that run 401(k)s. An investor's portfolio ought to reflect that reality. That's true to a lesser but still significant extent in the developing world. As countries such as India grow richer, it's easy to see that more and more of their population will be able to buy Crest and Nikes. But smart investors will also notice that the expanding middle class in those nations will also need life insurance and mutual funds and phone service.<p>
Facing long-run excess capacity in consumer goods and a boom market in services, investors should pay very different multiples for stocks in each sector. Paint maker and retailer Sherwin-Williams sells for a multiple of 21. Discount-brokerage industry leader Charles Schwab sells for a multiple of 22. Which stock is overpriced for the long term?<p>
The short-term gyrations of the market are not only making it hard for investors to focus on this long-term change but actually leading to the mispricing of many of the stocks long-term investors want to own. As the economy has slowed, "a lot of investment professionals have started to talk about a new Nifty 50," says Kurt Walters, vice president of Safian Investment Research in White Plains, New York. Those companies, these investors believe, will be able to deliver a steady stream of predictable earnings forever. That's why the growth stocks Safian tracks are selling at price-to-earnings ratios that are 2.5 times their earnings growth rates -- pretty expensive since some of those companies aren't very well positioned for the aging slow-growth world. Many of those companies in the new Nifty 50 are consumer-product companies -- exactly those facing margin and growth pressures. Few of them are service companies marketing to aging baby boomers and the developing world's emerging middle class.<p>
Investors looking for slow growth at a reasonable price ought to consider cyclicals instead. Cyclicals are selling at an average price-to-earnings ratio of 13.6. In the ten-week period that ended in mid-November, growth stocks outperformed cyclicals by eight percentage points. "You've got to ask when traditional growth stocks get too expensive," says Walters, and when cyclicals get cheap.<p>
At these prices, some cyclical companies -- such as those that produce raw materials like paper and nickel for the products that the developing world demands -- are probably a better way to play global growth than many of the pricier consumer giants. <p>
Most cycles come to their ends with some kind of cataclysm. That could happen with this recovery, of course. If the bond market rallies enough to send yields on the 30-year Treasury to 6 percent or lower, the stock market could let loose -- rising spectacularly overnight to 870 on the S&P 500 by midyear, says Mark Arbeter, chief technical analyst at S&P. That would be a warning sign that this cycle has finally produced the clear excess that leads to disaster.<p>
But absent that kind of speculative frenzy, investors are left with an economy that may not resemble any in the past. Demographically, the world has never looked like it does now. The developing world has never been integrated into the global economy in precisely this way before. We are in uncharted waters.<p>
At 67 months and counting, this economic recovery feels old. Only the 198390 boom lasted longer. But age by itself doesn't mean the economic cycle has to end in 1997, nor does it mean that the market has to crash and burn. For better or worse, those crashes are extremely difficult to predict, and all the elements most common in past crashes have yet to fall in place for this market.<p>
But it doesn't take the looming shadow of a crash to make a market risky. The new year is likely to be riskier than 1996, with less immediate reward in exchange for that risk. But the short-term uncertainties of the market should present plenty of opportunities to the investor who keeps his eyes on the long term.<p>
KEYWORDS:
forecast, prediction

