	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/11-Till Debt Do Us Part</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						The Indebted Society
By James Medoff and Andrew Harless (Little, Brown, $24.95)<p>
The Truth About the National Debt
By Francis X. Cavanaugh (Harvard Business School Press, $22.95)<p>
By Matthew Miller<p>
To judge from these two recent books, debt is to blame for either everything that ails us or nothing at all. Somebody must be lying.<p>
In The Indebted Society, Harvard economist James Medoff and consultant Andrew Harless link debt at all levels to crime, unemployment, downsizing, divorce, low wages, federal high jinks, and the general premillennial blues. A series of debt-fueled "vicious circles," they claim, is the culprit. Citizens, beset by stagnant wages, stop saving and run up the Visa bill to hang on. Thus pinched, we scream for lower taxes and higher benefits, opening the spigot of federal red ink as fearful politicians refuse to address the incompatibility of our demands. The government squeeze, in turn, leads to cuts in basic research, education, and infrastructure spending, all of which underpin growth. At the same time, deficits drain scarce national savings away from business investment. Heavy corporate borrowing, spurred by tax-favored debt and a generation of CEOs unchastened by depression, yields a cash-crunch mentality that militates against long-term investment and new hires.<p>
The result? A low-savings, low-investment economy that produces wage stagnation and job insecurity, with the family stresses and social meltdown you'd expect. Worse, vested interests with a big stake in debt -- from credit-card companies that peddle profligacy for profit to a lending class that dreads inflation more than it loves growth -- make it hard for policies that might jolt us out of this mess to get even a hearing.<p>
Are Medoff and Harless right? In part. The destructive conditions they describe and the connections they draw between them are real enough (though there's too much psychobabble on the family for my taste). But they're unpersuasive in presenting debt as the exclusive cause, rather than one outgrowth, of the productivity crunch that still mystifies economists two decades after it began.<p>
Maybe that's why, for all the power of their "vicious circles" framework, their cures seem mostly stale or ineffective; their strengths are descriptive, not prescriptive. Like every blue-ribbon panel, they want more public and private investment. They say the Federal Reserve should stop strangling growth, failing to see that expecting a central bank to solve a productivity problem is like asking a hammer to turn a screw. More sensibly, they'd raise taxes on the wealthy to help balance the budget, protect the welfare safety net from bipartisan attacks, and scrap today's corporate-tax advantage for debt financing. Still, this stuff has been in the air for a long time -- which is why you can't help feeling that you've heard it all before.<p>
Francis X. Cavanaugh, fresh from three decades in the bowels of the Treasury Department, has heard it all before, and he's angry. In The Truth About the National Debt, the retired economist and federal-debt manager is out to debunk the myths he says make most worries about our debt and deficits a distracting sham. But with only two sensible complaints amid an otherwise intolerably long quibble, Cavanaugh's book is proof of the axiom that the best civil servants toil in anonymity.<p>
Cavanaugh explains that much debt rhetoric is, strictly speaking, misguided. Today's $5 trillion debt isn't, in itself, a "burden on future generations," because we're passing along assets as well as liabilities. Our interest payments aren't "unsustainable"; they're just higher than they once were and have little economic impact. Thanks to broad ownership of federal debt by mutual and pension funds, interest payments probably don't redistribute wealth from average Joes to idle coupon clippers. And foreigners, by virtue of holding just 23 percent of our debt, pose no imminent threat to the republic.<p>
There -- I've just saved you three hours. Sure, Cavanaugh's right that pols bend these points to get the public up in arms. But so what? There are reasons they're correct to get us exercised, and Cavanaugh pooh-poohs or ignores them. He's blind to the way spiraling interest payments divert federal resources from other public purposes at any given spending level. He wrongly dismisses the deficit's drain on national savings and investment, which is why deficits matter in the first place. And he barely acknowledges the colossal unfunded liabilities in our health and Social Security entitlements -- $14 trillion at last count -- which will indeed burden our kids with higher taxes and a wrecked economy if we don't act soon.<p>
Cavanaugh contributes most on two counts. He decries the creeping socialization of credit risk in the economy through such federally backed entities as Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac. And he notes that our deficit problem ultimately boils down to choosing the level of government spending we're willing to pay for, an issue both political parties continue to dodge by allowing more salient myths than Cavanaugh's to go unrefuted -- that welfare and foreign aid take up most of the budget, for example.<p>
Regrettably, both books suffer from prose styles that might charitably be described as dull. Their authors' few interesting arguments would have had more impact as articles, not books. Still, their insistence on saying their piece at length is a choice for which the paper industry, if no one else, should feel, well, indebted.
Keyword: Review

