	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/11-Site of the Month</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/11-Site of the Month</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						sWhere It's Tax-Time Forever<p>
By Ted C. Fishman<p>
As if to remind citizens that it's time to think about taxes (again), the IRS has spruced up its Web site (<a HREF="http://www.irs.ustreas.gov/prod/cover.html">www.irs.ustreas.gov/prod/cover.html</A>) for end-of-year tax planning. Previously, the site was most useful as a lending library of tax forms, with a smattering of tips on preparing returns. Now its home page, a mock tabloid called The Digital Daily, shows wit and style (really) and leads users to more services (forms are still available). In early fall, under "What's Hot," the site offered a kind of "Dear Abby" for filers; if this test succeeds, correspondents will be able to have questions answered by E-mail; those with the broadest applicability will make it into the site's FAQ (Frequently Asked Questions). Care to offer the IRS advice on new regulations? The agency promises that comments will reach the desk of the appropriate officials. And new this season is a section that posts the latest regulations. Soon the site will include a searchable index of all the nation's certified not-for-profit charities that qualify for tax-deductible donations. If you'd like aid with your taxes, help can be had on that front, too. You can get information on assistance volunteers and download bulletins that list suspended tax preparers. A final suggestion: Use the site early. Last year it was sometimes overwhelmed with requests for forms. Capacity, to be doubled by New Year's, shouldn't be a problem, but as with all things tax related, it never hurts to think ahead.

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
