<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/11-Getting It Right</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/11-Getting It Right</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Australia did everything wrong when its economy began to sour. So now it's a buy.<p>
By Jim Rogers<p>
In August, thousands of angry Australians massed in protest in the capital city of Canberra. The demonstrators tried to break through police lines and storm the parliament buildings. Rioters carried sledgehammers and a battering ram. Several got within 100 yards of the office of the new prime minister, John Howard.<p>
What had these folks so worked up?<p>
Nothing less than the possible return of fiscal prudence to Australia after a lengthy absence. In March, Australian voters kicked out the big spenders who were running the national government and handed control over to the Liberal-National Coalition for the first time in 13 years.<p>
The new government won the national election on the promise that it would slash waste, reduce spending, and cut taxes. Its tight new budget calls for $4.1 billion in spending reductions over the next two years. Prime Minister Howard has vowed to balance the Australian budget by the 199899 fiscal year, far ahead of our goal to do the same thing here in the U.S.<p>
"You don't turn around a nation's finances, a nation's future, without making some hard decisions," the federal treasurer Peter Costello recently told the Australian parliament. Yet, as he went on to note, "if we avoid the hard decisions now, they are only going to get harder."<p>
I guess it shouldn't be too surprising that some of these hard decisions, such as fee hikes for higher education and an 11 percent cut in support for the nation's 300,000 aborigines, would be unpopular enough to trigger the raucous demonstrations that have occurred in Canberra, as well as in Adelaide and Brisbane.<p>
What does surprise me, though, is that a nation of hearty individualists like Australia allowed its national budget to get so out of hand in the first place. Australia's 18 million people are the descendants of immigrants. They believe in hard work and self-reliance, just as we do in the U.S. How did they, of all people, ever buy into the notion of government bloat?<p>
Australia's economy industrialized rapidly after World War II. Manufacturing now accounts for 24 percent of the nation's exports. But Australia, roughly the same size as the continental U.S., is especially rich in -- and therefore heavily dependent on -- natural resources. Mining alone accounts for 45 percent of its exports. In the mid-1980s, approval was granted for the world's largest uranium mine to start at Roxby Downs, South Australia. Farming contributes another 29 percent of Australia's exports.<p>
This is a country that truly lives off its land, especially when it comes to international trade. As commodity and natural-resource prices go, so go the fortunes of its businesses and people.<p>
The key factors that shape a modern economy are foreign debt and trade with other countries, particularly as expressed in a country's current accounts. Unfortunately, Australia's current-account deficit has almost doubled in the past four years. Australia, thus, has been importing more and more of its goods on credit. Its exports haven't been generating enough income to pay off this debt.<p>
One upshot of this: Australia's foreign debt per capita is now four times that of the U.S. This isn't to say the U.S. has been doing such a great job managing its finances (regular readers know I've been sharply critical of our nation's spendthrift ways). It's just that Australia has been doing even worse. Australia's total foreign debt now stands at $152 billion -- up 30 percent in the past four years alone.<p>
One thing I don't expect Australia to do, though, is pull a cheap trick and devalue its dollar -- to make it easier to pay back its mounting international debt. Australia is not Mexico. Even with the problems it has today, Australia is a disciplined and principled nation.<p>
Australia's current problems began with the collapse of natural-resource and commodity prices in the 1980s -- the result of a worldwide glut. Lower prices for everything from bauxite to barley cut sharply into the amount of revenue that Australian businesses could generate from foreign trade.<p>
Unfortunately, Australia made things even worse for itself. Its citizens reacted by making the very mistake that so many other resource-rich nations made as commodity prices dropped: They elected politicians who promised to soften the blow.<p>
The right move, of course, would have been to trim government expenses and batten down the hatches until better times returned. That's what today's corporations have learned to do in cyclical downturns: Get lean and mean.<p>
But Australia's political leaders attempted to maintain the status quo and keep the citizenry happy. They passed laws, borrowed money, and imposed regulations in a destined-to-fail effort to thwart the fundamental laws of economics. They refused to acknowledge that the nation's troubles stemmed from a worldwide supply-and-demand imbalance that they could do little about.<p>
I suppose this is why statism -- the notion that the state can solve most of a country's financial and social problems -- always tends to gain popularity just as a nation's prosperity begins to wane; it's a ready answer for an economy that has begun to decline. The state tries to make things right, to keep the voters living in the style to which they have become accustomed, until better times return.<p>
What happened next was equally predictable: Australia's debt mushroomed, and economic growth slowed considerably. In Australia, unemployment now stands at 8.5 percent -- much higher than in the U.S.<p>
Yet all this may now be changing. As a result of the national elections earlier this year, the Australian stock market has begun showing new life. The currency is also rebounding, and inflation has slowed markedly -- to 3.1 percent from 4.7 percent just a year ago.<p>
Australia is even beginning to look like a potentially exciting place for investors -- not just because of the nation's newfound interest in fiscal prudence but also because natural-resource prices are on the upswing again, a trend I expect to persist for the next ten years. Investors in Australia have a very real chance of benefiting from these two positive trends.<p>
Australian stocks may well go down again before they begin to climb steadily. Biting the bullet -- that is, cutting government spending, which means injecting less money into the economy -- will cause pain and dislocations at first. But the economy may well revive and be stronger than ever, poised for solid growth.<p>
Darwin, Australia's northernmost city, the one nearest the Indonesian islands, is an example of just how promising this nation's future evolution may be economically. When I visited, I was struck by how multiracial, multieverything Darwin is. People from all over Asia have crowded into its neighborhoods -- Chinese, Koreans, Indonesians, Indians, and Pakistanis. It's a boomtown now, and it will be one for a long time to come. Its population has doubled in the past 20 years, and the Northern Territory -- the size of Alaska, with great weather and abundant natural beauty and touring sights -- is prospering as well.<p>
Two important influences on Darwin's growth are Papua New Guinea and Indonesia, both just to the north and both exploding and dynamic. Americans are surprised to discover that Indonesia is the fourth-largest country in the world. The Indonesians are excellent businesspeople, thriving in an old and crowded country. Australia sits only a few hundred miles south -- vast, empty of people, and chock-full of natural resources.<p>
All the abundant nickel, copper, undeveloped land, huge farms, huge ranches, huge everything need to be worked by somebody. Throughout the history of Australia, whenever a dam or irrigation system has been erected, the entire area around it has blossomed with prosperity.<p>
Australia should also benefit from the 2000 Summer Olympics, which will be held in Sydney. (Australians are an athletic bunch; they won more medals per capita than nearly anyone else in Atlanta.)<p>
Following the recent examples of Canada, Ireland, and New Zealand, three other former English colonies that put their fiscal houses in order, Australia may become a model for yet another former British colony -- namely, the United States.<p>
Jim Rogers is a contributing editor and the author of Investment Biker (Adams). 

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
