</DOCHDR>
<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/11-Storm Clouds</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/11-Storm Clouds</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Russia is tottering, South Africa is set to explode, and East Asia is stumbling -- pity the next U.S. president.<p>
By Walter Russell Mead<p>
Lucky Bill Clinton. Sure, he's had to send American troops into the Bosnian quagmire, defuse a financial crisis or two in Mexico, and send cruise missiles crashing into Iraq. But on balance, global events have helped his administration. The Japanese trade surplus, once the terror of American economists and industrialists, has declined steeply, and booming East Asian economies have absorbed more American goods, sending U.S. exports soaring. With the cold war over, everyone except knee-jerk red-baiters has agreed that working to extend democracy -- blemishes and all -- to Russia and Eastern Europe is a good idea. And the whole world breathed a sigh of relief when, with an astonishingly small amount of violence, apartheid turned into democracy in South Africa.<p>
**The winner of the presidential election will have a tough time with international politics in the coming years.**<p>
But that good luck is about to end -- for whoever fills the Oval Office during the next four years. The international situation is going to give the next president fits.<p>
The incoming administration is going to face crises of a totally different magnitude from those on the current roster of hot spots -- Haiti, Bosnia, Iraq. Problems in these areas aren't going away, of course, but by now American presidents and voters are habituated to these crises and their shopworn "solutions": Send in the marines, slap on an embargo, scramble the bombers. These actions don't fix the problem, but they reassure us that the president has everything in hand.<p>
The crises on the horizon in Russia, South Africa, and East Asia can't be addressed by any of these means. Paradoxically, these troubles are capable of arousing deeper fears and more heartfelt calls to arms among American voters but are less amenable to direct presidential action than an Iraq or Haiti. We cannot bring cruise missiles raining down on Moscow or send U.S. troops to keep the peace in South Africa. Worst of all, the economic crisis looming in East Asia will touch the wallets of Americans more directly than any crisis of the last two administrations. At the same time, it will weaken the president's political position by making it tough for him to deliver on his economic promises and by providing new ammunition for America Firsters, such as Pat Buchanan.<p>
**While Russia has been a feather in Clinton's cap, that's likely to change considering Yeltsin's shaky health.**<p>
Start with Russia. On balance, Russia policy has been a plus for Clinton. Russia's democracy might not be very elegant, or even remotely honest, but the country seemed to be moving toward a more consumer-oriented, less militaristic society. Even the worst recent event in Russia -- its bloody, miserable war with the Chechens -- has been oddly comforting. The Russian military proved to be as incompetent as it is nasty.<p>
But Russia is becoming less predictable every day. Boris Yeltsin is still president in name, but his failing health and erratic habits make it uncertain how long he'll be with us. Or what clout he'll have while he hangs on. Already his security adviser, Alexander Lebed, has overruled a presidential order, claiming that Yeltsin hadn't authored it. The struggle to succeed the ailing Yeltsin will be fought against the background of an economic crisis that weakens the pro-Western forces in Russia. Russia's inefficient companies, corrupt judicial system, and ramshackle legal structures can't cope with a mountain of bad debts. Its Wild West banking system is heading for a crash that will wipe out the savings of millions of Russians -- again.<p>
Russia, regardless of who is in charge, will continue on its present anti-Western, nationalistic track. Not that Russia will send tanks rolling across Central Europe. It can't police its own territory, much less take over anyone else's. But that doesn't mean Russia (and its thousands of thermonuclear weapons) can be ignored. A weakened and financially reeling Russia could provide terrorists with training facilities and safe havens. It could help countries such as Iraq and Iran develop sophisticated chemical and biological weapons. It could -- either intentionally or accidentally -- allow rogue states to amass critical quantities of weapons-grade nuclear materials.<p>
**In South Africa, a weakening economy threatens the peace in this nation.** <p>
Cut to South Africa, where another triumph of American values and policy is turning to ashes. The good news from South Africa is just about over. The economy isn't growing fast enough to both allow blacks to improve their standards of living and protect white incomes and jobs.<p>
The currency collapsed in 1996, but the South African central bank can't defend the rand without raising interest rates so high that growth screeches to a halt. But if South Africa doesn't defend the rand, its inflation problem will worsen, making it harder for the government to pursue strategies that could improve the economic situation of the restive majority.<p>
South Africa's leaders may well fail this test. Order seems to be breaking down in the cities. Recently, Muslim vigilantes fought street battles with drug dealers in the slums of Cape Town. Nelson Mandela is getting older, and after admitting that he secretly banked a $450,000 campaign contribution, he may have lost some of his political magic.<p>
If things go badly wrong, a U.S. president will face tremendous pressure to get involved. CNN already knows the way to South Africa; the leaders of all the country's major political factions are skilled at working with (or manipulating) Western media. In addition, the people and issues of South Africa matter intensely to tens of millions of American citizens. But it's not clear what the U.S. could do. South Africa isn't Haiti: It has more than 6 times the population and more than 40 times the land area.<p>
**A collapse of Indonesia's political and economic systems could further stretch U.S. involvement internationally.**<p>
Handling a meltdown in Russia or South Africa will become far more complicated if an economic crisis in East Asia eats away at U.S. domestic support for an activist international policy. For years, East Asia's dynamic economies (ranging from Taiwan to Indonesia) have been the wonder of the world and the envy of other developing countries. But suddenly the story seems less certain to end happily.<p>
The troubles in Indonesia have attracted the most attention lately. The corrupt regime of Indonesia's 75-year-old president, Mohamed Suharto (five years older than Fidel Castro and two years older than Bob Dole), is facing a succession struggle against a background of popular unrest. An emerging urban middle class increasingly wants its share of both political power and business contracts. The country's Muslims -- Indonesia has the largest Muslim population of any country on earth -- are a wild card. Some remain apolitical; others are increasingly radicalized. The last time Indonesia changed presidents, 500,000 to 1 million people lost their lives.<p>
Indonesia is just the most dramatic case of the East Asian blues. Even Asia's more democratic states have their political problems. Neither South Korea, where two of the country's former presidents were tried on capital charges last summer, nor Thailand, where corruption is about to bring down another government, is a showcase of stability.<p>
**To make matters worse for East Asia, economic growth in the region is slowing down after a period of rapid growth.**<p>
But this political turmoil wouldn't be nearly so significant if growth in the region weren't also slowing. The East Asian Tigers are discovering for themselves what Japan found out a few years ago: Export-oriented economies can't sustain rapid growth forever. Slow growth in the U.S. and Europe and the saturation of the consumer market for the goods on which the Asian Tigers depend -- VCRs, for example -- are taking their toll. Growth forecasts are being scaled back all across Asia. Economies accustomed to double-digit growth are now projecting single-digit increases -- or worse.<p>
The region's banks and businesses have built their plans on a continuation of the explosive growth of the past decade. Companies have built new factories -- and banks have loaned them money -- based on assumptions about market growth that now look shaky. Japanese-style banking problems could turn up in places like Thailand and South Korea.<p>
Some East Asian countries are waking up to discover that they could be facing Mexican-style currency problems. With export growth slowing and the middle classes snapping up foreign goods and indulging in foreign travel, countries such as Thailand and South Korea suddenly confront deficits in their current accounts as more money flows out than flows in. (Taiwan, with its massive currency reserves, is an exception.) Thailand has had trouble defending its currency, the baht, from attacks.<p>
**Currency devaluation -- a solution for many countries -- is not a valid option for East Asia.**<p>
One step that countries often take to restore the balance of payments -- currency devaluation -- seems virtually impossible in this region. Although devaluation would restore the competitiveness of Asian exports, it would decimate the portfolios of the foreign investors who prop up many of East Asia's faltering stock and bond markets.<p>
Some countries are responding to their trade problems with approaches that could cause a serious run-in with the U.S. South Korea is mounting anti-import and "Buy Korean" programs. China is following a similar route -- even as it replaces Japan as the country with the largest trade surplus with the U.S.<p>
This could lead to a new kind of Pacific trade war. So far, most Americans have been willing to allow East Asian products into this country despite the opposition of unions and manufacturers. Keeping our markets open has seemed the best way to open up Asia's markets to U.S. goods. But what will happen if Asia starts closing its markets to American products?<p>
**The odds overwhelmingly favor a recession during the next administration.**<p>
The next president of the United States will probably have to answer this question during a recession. The odds overwhelmingly favor a recession sometime during the next administration. If the present business expansion lasts until the end of the presidential term in 2001, it will become the longest-lasting one in American history. Voters who are worried about their jobs -- and who are counting on a rising stock market to make good the deficiencies they expect in Social Security and Medicare -- aren't likely to be in favor of aid packages for Russia or South Africa, or of patient diplomacy. Perhaps whoever wins this election ought to think twice before taking the oath of office in January.<p>
Walter Mead is the presidential fellow at the World Policy Institute at the New School. Research assistance provided by Andrew Weinstein.<p>
KEYWORDS:
international, investing, global, politics, worldwide, economy, forecast, election

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

