<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/11-A Bill of Goods?</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/11-A Bill of Goods?</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						The Taxpayers' Bill of Rights delivers less than it promises.<p>
By Elizabeth Macdonald<p>
President Clinton recently signed into law amendments that strengthen the Taxpayers' Bill of Rights Act of 1988. Upon signing the bill, the president told taxpayers, "You have rights, and we will shield them." Don't be fooled -- the bill is still shot full of holes.<p>
First, the good things. The IRS can now abate interest charges for "unreasonable" errors and delays caused by its own "managerial or ministerial acts." The new measure is a welcome plus. Previously, the only acts that would cause the IRS to turn off the meter were such things as correspondence between the IRS and the taxpayer crossing in the mail. Now the IRS can stop interest from accruing when, say, an official working a case gets transferred or takes a sick leave, although proving the cause of a delay will take some legwork. <p>
The bill also gives taxpayers a 21-day interest-free grace period -- up from 10 -- for first notices that demand less than $100,000 in taxes owed. And the IRS is now allowed to recognize private delivery services such as FedEx as a proper means for meeting the April 15 deadline. <p>
**A taxpayer advocate won't have much power over local IRS officials.**<p>
Now the holes. A new taxpayer advocate, replacing the old taxpayer ombudsman, has been given more authority to issue, modify, or rescind taxpayer-assistance orders, which are requests that an IRS official stop any action that causes a taxpayer significant hardship. But this advocate will still be appointed by the IRS commissioner, not the president. Likely candidate: an agency careerist -- a bureaucrat by any other name is still as slow to respond. Furthermore, the new advocate does not have direct control over local IRS officials, who decide who gets help and when.<p>
The IRS must now give taxpayers 30 days' notice before altering or killing an installment plan to pay off a tax debt, and it must give specific reasons for its actions. However, the 30-day-notification measure is a sop -- the IRS already adopted it prior to this bill. Plus, installment plans still come tied up with a tax lien and a running interest tab, and the IRS can still seize property from taxpayers who miss just one payment.<p>
Innocent spouses and ex-spouses supposedly get some relief under this new bill. These people typically run into trouble when joint filers split up and the IRS later concludes that one spouse cheated on his or her taxes. The bill gives either spouse the right to find out whether the IRS is trying to collect from a former mate -- an advance warning that he or she may be next in line. But the IRS won't automatically tell a joint filer it is investigating -- taxpayers must ask for this information in writing.<p>
**Taxpayers can now recover certain legal expenses incurred from IRS disputes.**<p>
The new law lets taxpayers recover certain legal expenses incurred from IRS disputes, and boosts, from $100,000 to $1 million, the amount of damages a taxpayer can get as a victim of what the IRS calls "reckless or intentional" action, such as an outright disregard of the tax law. However, reckless or intentional behavior, according to tax experts, is far more difficult to prove than carelessness -- taxpayers virtually have to be camped out in an auditor's office to amass sufficient evidence. <p>
In the past, when taxpayers have sued the IRS to recover legal fees, the burden of proof has been on the taxpayers to prove that the IRS was "substantially unjustified" in making its case. The new law says the agency must take on the burden of proof when it loses a case. If it fails to prove that its losing position had real merit or was "substantially justified" because it followed its own tax rules, a taxpayer can now recover legal fees. But taxpayers won't be reimbursed if the IRS follows its new opinion on a tax matter and ignores older but still pertinent rules that support the taxpayer's case.<p>
The bill also raises the maximum hourly rate for recoverable attorneys' fees, from $75 to $110, and indexes the amount beginning in 1997. But rare is the lawyer who will work for $110 an hour in taxland.<p>
KEYWORDS:
Internal Revenue Service, income tax, tax reform, dispute

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
