<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/10-Adios, Sayonara, Auf Wiedersehen, Adieu</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/10-Adios, Sayonara, Auf Wiedersehen, Adieu</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Foreign investors have boosted the U.S. economy by acquiring our debt. Are they starting to pull back? It's too soon to tell. But it sure won't be pretty if they start bidding us...<p>
By Jim Rogers<p>
Our towering national debt has turned us into a nation of amateur bookkeepers and economists. Many of us can cite (at least approximately) the amount our government now owes: $5 trillion. Or how much that amounts to per person: $20,000. We know that the Treasury must hawk scads of bonds, notes, and bills to finance this staggering sum. We know a huge chunk of our tax dollars (17 percent) goes toward paying the interest on all those bonds, notes, and bills. We know our national debt has handcuffed our markets and our economy and kept loan rates stubbornly high and deposit rates submerged.<p>
But how many of us also know that we've been getting help with financing all of this debt? A lot of help, in fact.<p>
This assistance has been coming from other nations, especially Japan, Germany, and the United Kingdom. According to U.S. Treasury statistics, foreign governments and other overseas investors now hold just shy of $1 trillion (or 20 percent) of our national debt.<p>
Never before in the history of the world has a nation owed as much money to foreign creditors as the United States does right now. Are we good for it? What would happen if these other countries decided to cut up our national credit card?<p>
Until recently, few people bothered to raise such questions. This may be, in part, because foreign lenders have appeared so eager to give us as much cash as we will take. In 1995 alone, foreign monetary institutions and investors scooped up $173 billion in U.S. Treasurys -- an amount that exceeded last year's entire federal budget deficit.<p>
Six years ago the total U.S. debt in foreign hands was less than half of what it is today. We now owe Japan $255 billion, the United Kingdom $142 billion, and Germany $64 billion. Believe it or not, China is our sixth-largest creditor. We owe China (where the average worker barely earns enough money in a year to buy a ten-speed bicycle) $34.3 billion.<p>
The U.S. government, of course, has been using all of this global moola to help pay for its unceasing deficit spending. The foreign cash has rippled through our economy and supported our spendthrift ways. It has also helped Americans like you and me spend more of our dollars on, say, stocks -- as opposed to having to pay more in federal income tax or buy more of those Treasury offerings ourselves.<p>
Certainly the U.S. economy has been showing signs of health lately. We've had solid growth, low inflation, and low unemployment. Over the past four years, we've added a net ten million new jobs. Homeownership is at a 15-year peak. Real hourly wages are rising for the first time in ten years. The misery index -- the unemployment rate added to the inflation rate -- hasn't been this low since 1968, notes The Wall Street Journal.<p>
These are all good things. Yet would our economy be humming along so nicely if we hadn't received so much international aid? Suppose we had had to scrape up that extra $173 billion ourselves last year. Would that have driven interest rates one percentage point higher, or two, or three, as the Treasury tried to persuade Americans to buy T-bills instead of, say, stocks? And how well would the stock market have done if we had bought all of those T-bills ourselves?<p>
We may be about to discover that these aren't just academic concerns. A critical development occurred in the second quarter of this year: Foreigners hesitated to lend us any more money. Beginning in March, the six-year skyward trend line that tracks foreign holdings of U.S. bonds suddenly turned ominously flat. In April, foreign central banks actually decreased the amount of U.S. Treasurys they held, according to the Federal Reserve. In June came another decrease and in August a third.<p>
Is this a short-term blip or the beginning of a dangerous trend?<p>
A brief flat period (or one down month) doesn't necessarily spell disaster. It certainly doesn't mean foreign countries will soon try to dump all of their U.S. debt. That would be foolhardy, since the fortunes of their economies are so closely tied to ours. Still, this is something all investors should watch closely.<p>
Those of you who are regular readers of my column in this magazine know that I am skeptical about the prospects for the U.S. economy unless drastic changes are made. This is primarily because of our nation's ongoing willingness to tolerate huge budget deficits. This article is another one of my signal flares along these lines. But it is also the most important one I've shot off.<p>
History shows that there have been times when foreign lenders have run for the hills when a debt-ridden economy has sat on its hands, letting its budgetary mess run amok. It happened to Britain and Italy in the 1970s, to France and Spain in the 1960s, and to Portugal in the 1940s.<p>
Our enormous debt to foreigners is a major point of vulnerability. By letting foreigners subsidize dollar-denominated debt, the U.S. has been postponing the economic housecleaning it needs to undertake. In fact, much of the deficit reduction that the Clinton administration touts has simply come from swapping higher-priced long-term U.S. debt for cheaper short-term debt, not from real fiscal prudence. Truth is, Bill Clinton owes much of his economic "success" to the willingness of Japan, Great Britain, and Germany to lend us money at low rates.<p>
Because we have been so rich for so long, we have deluded ourselves into thinking that foreign creditors do not present a threat to our financial system. For politicians, deficit funding carries little near-term political risk. Voters, too, have remained happily oblivious to the dangers posed by high federal deficits (an anomaly in the United States for most of our history). So we have welcomed foreigners who carry checkbooks. <p>
Of course, overseas investors haven't been buying U.S. Treasurys out of the goodness of their hearts. Each country has its reason for lending to us.<p>
Take Japan, far and away our largest creditor. To ease the problems of its strained banks, Japan began irrigating its economy with yen in 1991 (just as the United States created a blizzard of dollars to save the banking system during the savings-and-loan crisis). This liberal monetary policy yanked yen-based interest rates down to a microscopic low of a half percent annually. It's little wonder, then, that Japanese investors found dollar-backed debt, which paid as much as 15 times the interest, so attractive.<p>
More money came flooding into U.S. Treasurys from Japan's central bank, too. To hot-wire an economy shattered by its worst postwar recession, government officials in Japan have been determined to keep the value of the yen as low as possible. This makes Japan's exports to other nations less expensive for foreign buyers. Thus, the Bank of Japan has been buying American dollars that have piled up in Japan as a result of our trade deficit with that nation and been lending them back to us.<p>
Japan's strategy seems to be working. Over the past year, the yen has fallen in value, and economic activity in Japan has picked up.<p>
Meanwhile, as this extra liquidity has swooshed into the United States, it has buoyed our economy, helping it grow at about 2 percent annually over the past five years. Our loans from foreign investors, unfortunately, have risen still higher, increasing at an average rate of 14 percent annually during the same period.<p>
It's not just the amount of borrowing from Japan and other countries that's the problem; it's also how we've used the money as a debtor nation. In the 19th century, the U.S. received a great deal of foreign capital. These funds were put to use building railroads, canals, telegraph lines, roads, and factories. By 1914, these investments in our nation's productive capacity had created enough wealth to allow us to become a net creditor: U.S. companies and investors owned more assets in foreign lands than foreign investors owned here.<p>
The U.S. remained a creditor nation until 1987, when we passed back over the line and became net borrowers again -- thanks to the accumulated federal budget deficits of many, many years. This time around, though, we haven't used our loans to pay for productive assets -- investments that would enhance our ability to generate growth. Instead, we've spent the cash on things like armaments, social services, and, yes, paying the interest on the national debt.<p>
Because we were so wealthy and had been for so long, there were no major repercussions from those who loaned us money. U.S. investors, after all, owned $1.8 trillion in foreign assets in 1987, and they own $2.9 trillion today. The political risk in the U.S. was small; default risk seemed nonexistent; and foreigners, badly needing a place to park huge amounts of cash, could find no better haven.<p>
But the picture may be changing. Today, even a spot under a mattress may look better to some foreign investors than more U.S.-backed debt. As a chart of intermediate- and long-term-bond yields shows (see "Would You Keep Buying?"), Treasury buyers have earned a positive return in only 17 of the past 55 months; buyers in the other 38 months are underwater.<p>
I predict that it will be only a matter of time before the typical Japanese or German investor wises up and declares, "I've owned these stinkers for the past several years, and compared with other investments, I'm losing ground."<p>
Foreign investors have other reasons to pull back. As their economies become stronger, the Japanese and Europeans will need to bring their funds back home to finance growth. Foreigners are also rightly spooked by the Helms됙urton legislation, which condemns anyone doing business with Cuba. It's only one of several confiscatory bills before Congress. Other proposed laws would punish investors -- through asset seizures -- who do business with outlaw states like Libya, Iran, and Iraq. Businesspeople who traffic with these countries know they might as well paste a bull's-eye on their U.S. Treasury brokerage accounts.<p>
Of course, it's one thing if foreigners stop buying new U.S. debt and merely roll over what they're carrying. It's a much more serious matter if foreign dough starts to flow out of U.S. securities. We're not likely to have to hand over part of the country -- say, Yellowstone National Park -- to China to satisfy our debt. We'll simply get a new lender if the Chinese want their money back. But our new creditor is going to say, "Wait a minute. Your spending is out of control. You have no reasonable plan to balance your budget. Both major political parties promise to cure the deficit yet do nothing. Your Congress can't make any fiscal decisions without pandering to big business, the defense establishment, and a thousand other constituencies. Maybe we'll lend you what you need to repay your creditors, but not at the cheap rates you were able to con out of your lenders in the past."<p>
Our government will not have any choice but to pay higher interest rates.<p>
What can we do to fix this mess? Meaningful solutions won't be politically easy -- changing the tax code, for example, to encourage savings and investment and discourage consumption. We should cut government spending and balance the budget. We should privatize the holdings of the government, which owns two-thirds of the land in the West. The government could sell off Nevada, most of which it owns. Or why not sell the post office to someone who can manage it properly, as other nations are doing?<p>
What's an individual investor to do if, in fact, our foreign credit lines start drying up? Domestic stocks and bonds will most likely be battered by the eventual rise in interest rates. Manufacturing stocks may be all right for a while, but it will be better in the long term to look for good agriculture and mining stocks (investments that can profit from the coming boom in demand for natural resources). Apartment houses in financial citadels such as New York and Boston will be a disaster. If all of your money is in America, you may want to invest some of your assets out of the country, as an insurance policy if nothing else. Put some money abroad in a safe currency, such as German marks or Swiss francs.<p>
Meanwhile, I also urge you to keep an eye on the figures for foreign holdings of U.S. debt, which measure the United States Treasury holdings of foreign central banks and which are published regularly by the Federal Reserve. Each week they're reprinted in publications such as Barron's. If you keep a sharp eye on these numbers, you should be able to tell whether foreign businesses and governments are losing confidence in our economy (cutting back on their loans) or feeling more optimistic (upping their investment in the U.S.). I don't have much faith that our politicians will take the right steps should the trend turn sour, but a savvy investor can make the right moves no matter what happens.<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
