	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/10-Michigan: The Exception</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/10-Michigan: The Exception</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						By Andrew Tobias<p>
Michigan's no-fault, adopted in 1973, is widely regarded as the nation's strongest and best plan. It provides unlimited medical and rehabilitation benefits and substantial coverage for wage loss. Yet premiums in Michigan today are significantly lower than in California. This is possible primarily because Michigan also has the nation's strongest "threshold." You can sue for pain an dsuffering only in cases of "death, serious impairment of body function or permanent serious disfigurement."<p>
Still, there are problems. Until 1986, judges decided when the threshold had been met. Then the trial lawyers succeeded in getting the Michigan Supreme Court to rule that, because the law had not specified otherwise, this was a "question of fact" for a jury to decide rather than a "question of law" for the judge. The result was rising costs -- which the trial lawyers gleefully cite as an argument against no-fault -- as more cases went to jury trials (expensive even when you win) and some of those resulted in awards. <p>
Recently, some balance was restored by teh Michigan legislature that should at least partly rein in the lawsuits, and thus the costs, once again. <p>
Some thoughtful people felt Prop 200 should have allowed more lawsuits and unlimited benefits like Michigan. Fair enough. But lawsuits and unlimited benefits are expensive. How will low-income families pay the bill? We chose a middle ground.

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/1page.gif"><br>About 1 page

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
</td>
	</tr>
