<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/10-Executive Decision</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/10-Executive Decision</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Clinton and Dole face off on America's pocketbook issues<p>
By Elizabeth Macdonald<p>
Which presidential candidate will do the most for your finances? That's what we wanted to know when we asked President Bill Clinton and Republican presidential candidate Bob Dole to answer a series of questions about a variety of issues, from tax cuts to retirement security to medical savings accounts. Given the wide-ranging proposals on personal finance being offered by both sides, it appears that "It's the pocketbook, stupid" is the theme for the 1996 presidential race.<p>
Of course, the candidates are in sync on many financial issues. In a lot of respects, Tweedlebill and Tweedlebob seem to be reading from the same economic script. Clinton is for a $500 family tax credit; so is Dole. Clinton wants expanded IRAs as a hedge against potential financial catastrophes; Dole likes the sound of that, too. Clinton would rather dawdle and appoint a commission to study reforming the teetering Social Security system; so would Dole.<p>
But Dole has sought to provide a dramatic contrast between himself and Clinton with  a whopping $406 billion, 15 percent across-the-board tax cut. On other issues as well, the two candidates have hammered out strikingly different positions on what they would do to your finances. For example, Dole wants medical savings accounts and  a capital-gains tax cut. Clinton won't countenance such changes.<p>
As Clinton and Dole match, then raise  each other with proposals that have elect  me written all over them, use this guide during the dog days of the race.<p>
Middle-class tax breaks. Both Clinton and Dole now dabble with the electoral bribery of a $500-per-child tax credit. Clinton's credit amounts to just $300 in the first two years, moving to $500 in the third. Families earning less than $75,000 get the credit, which stops when the child reaches age 13. Dole's version starts at $250 and hits $500 in the second year. Couples earning up to $110,000 qualify for his credit, which is cut off when the child reaches 18.<p>
Clinton told us he wants to "expand access to college." He proposes giving families a $1,500 annual tax credit for the first two years of college or a $10,000 tuition deduction, phasing out for those earning between $80,000 and $100,000 a year. Taxpayers can take the write-off in later years after using up their credit.<p>
The $10,000 deduction is a good idea -- education costs have not had much help from the tax system. However, making the government chip in for more of students' tuition gives schools added incentive to hike costs. Also, Clinton wants to pay for this bill with airline taxes, although he already vowed to use those taxes for air safety.<p>
This $42.9 billion proposal comes with an interesting cosmetic twist: Clinton says his credit would be "performance based" -- the credit would  be allowed in the second year only if  the student has maintained at least a  B average and has no felony drug convictions. That's a laudable goal, but the program would be an administrative nightmare. We can only hope that taxpayers wouldn't have to staple report cards to their tax returns.<p>
Dole says he wants to let low- and middle-income taxpayers deduct student-loan interest and wants employers to give workers tax-free college-tuition assistance. He would let taxpayers plunk his annual $500-per-child credit into an education account, where earnings would accrue tax free as long as the money sits there for at least five years.<p>
Dole also wants to give taxpayers a teensy $50 credit for donations to anti-poverty charities ($100 for joint filers). Those amounts (paid for with welfare cuts?) would double in the second year and then vanish. He'd also give taxpayers who care for their elderly relatives  a $1,000 deduction. And he says he wants to let the self-employed write off 100 percent of their health-insurance costs -- but the break would take effect ten years from now.<p>
As for Dole's across-the-board cut, it would kick off at just 3.27 percent in the first year, then go to 8.27 percent, 13.27 percent, and finally 15 percent in the fourth year. About 28 percent of this cut would go to households making more than $200,000 a year, with an average cut of $25,200. Families making $50,000 to $75,000 would get an extra $1,800 tax shave.<p>
The retiree safety net. Retirement savings is a hot campaign issue. Clinton told us he wants to help the "51 million working Americans who are not now covered by an employer-provided retirement plan." First on the agenda: IRAs. Current law phases out deductible IRA amounts depending on a taxpayer's income. Clinton wants to double those eligibility limits. He also told us he wants to let workers "take their retirement savings with them" to help "the more than five million workers a year who change jobs and have an employer-provided pension." Portability, while great for workers, may be costly for employers; for those workers with 401(k)s, the law already lets them leave $3,500 or more in their accounts at their old jobs.<p>
Instead of qualifying more taxpayers for IRAs, Dole told us, he supports "increasing the amount that individuals may contribute to their 401(k) plans and individual retirement accounts so that they can save more." Hear! Hear! we say. The amounts taxpayers can annually sock away tax free is still paltry -- just $2,000 in an IRA for singles. Both Clinton and Dole want to allow penalty-free withdrawals from IRAs for things like education and major medical expenses. (You can now use IRAs for medical expenses, but you have to spend 7.5 percent of your adjusted gross income first.) Neither thought it problematic that using IRAs like regular passbook accounts would shrivel retirement savings. Dole also wants to repeal Clinton's 1993 tax increase on Social Security, which hiked (from 50 to 85 percent) the amount of Social Security benefits taxpayers must include in gross income when they earn more than a certain amount.<p>
The capital-gains standoff. Investors who sell or exchange assets held for more than one year now face a maximum federal tax of 28 percent on long-term net capital gains (the rate is as  high as 39.6 percent on assets held one year or less). Clinton has opposed Dole's efforts to cut the long-term rate to a top effective rate of 19.8 percent. Dole now wants to slash that rate to 14 percent; he claims this would turn back $13 billion to investors over five years. Sounding like a true flat-taxer, Dole told us he's all for "eliminating the double and triple taxation of capital, which discourages savings and entrepreneurship." He says he'd index the basis of certain assets for inflation, but not until 2001.<p>
Dole may model his cut after the 19.8 percent version still afloat in Republican bills before Congress. That version would let taxpayers deduct half of their net long-term gains, with no alternative minimum tax owed on the write-off. If Dole wins, he may let taxpayers deduct half their gains to arrive at adjusted gross income, which would lower the threshold taxpayers must hurdle to deduct miscellaneous and medical deductions, now restricted to 2 percent and 7.5 percent of AGI, respectively.<p>
Clinton told us that a previous Republican bill to cut the capital-gains rate "would not help the economy and was nothing more than a huge, retroactive giveaway." Even so, Clinton says he may let all taxpayers take a onetime $125,000 exclusion from capital gains on the sale of a principal home, now available only to those 55 and older. Clinton may try to sell this idea to middle-class and younger home buyers. But many homeowners already avoid this tax by rolling over their gains into property of equal or greater value. Only taxpayers who don't buy a replacement home or who trade down would benefit. Dole says he would let seniors exclude as much as $500,000 in gains from the sale of a principal residence.<p>
Estate-tax relief. Currently, individuals can pass on $600,000 tax free to heirs; couples, $1.2 million. Amounts exceeding those thresholds can be taxed at rates up to 55 percent. Experts widely agree that estate taxes are the worst kind of double taxation. But Clinton already vetoed Dole's Senate proposal to exempt from this tax the first $1 million in certain family-owned business assets per decedent. Dole still wants it.<p>
Even so, Dole's idea is loaded with caveats. For example, an heir must work at the business for five years in an eight-year stretch within ten years after the original owner's death. And Dole's exemption moves upward in increments of just $100,000, to $1 million in 2006.<p>
Medical savings accounts. MSAs are tax-free accounts from which people could withdraw funds to pay medical bills not covered by insurance. In 1997, Congress plans to test them on 750,000 people, mostly those who are self-employed and covered by a high-deductible or catastrophic health plan. Individuals will be able to sock away at least $1,500 and a maximum $2,250 per year to cover their deductible; families, $3,000 to $4,500. This deduction will also lower the floor for certain write-offs. Employers and employees will be able to make tax-deductible contributions to these accounts, but not both in the same year; workers keep any interest income but can't itemize MSA-covered expenses. <p>
Clinton dislikes MSAs; Dole favors them. Critics say these "medical shelter" accounts may draw healthy, rich people, leaving the halt and the lame in the regular insurance pool, thereby driving up insurance costs. Employers don't have to invest any money in these accounts, and insurers can always jack up co-payments and deductibles to their catastrophic policies.<p>
As the election picks  up steam, remember this: Federal Reserve chairman Alan Greenspan's policies will have more impact on the economy, and thus on voters' pocketbooks, than a president of either party. All of these ideas could evanesce into the Oval Office's air, no matter who sits down after the election. So keep an eye on Greenspan and on Congress, which must perform radical surgery on a metastasizing $4 trillion federal budget deficit. The constitutional power of the president is limited -- he has only the bully pulpit and the veto. What Congress does is what counts.<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
