	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/10-Do This Now: Money On the House</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/10-Do This Now: Money On the House</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Take advantage of the expanding reverse-mortgage program<p>
By Elizabeth Macdonald<p>
The Department of Housing and Urban Development has asked Congress to expand the HUD program that allows senior citizens to use the value of their homes to supplement their incomes. HUD wants the program -- now limited to 50,000 loans and effective through September 2000 -- to include all seniors and to extend indefinitely. People 62 or older who either own their homes outright or maintain a nominal mortgage balance can draw against the equity in their house in monthly payments, in a lump sum, or via a credit line. The loan doesn't have to be repaid until the home is sold or the borrower moves out or dies. These payments are based on certain factors: the equity in the home, the home's appraised value, and the borrower's life expectancy. The loans are particularly attractive to retirees or anyone on a fixed income.<p>
Reverse mortgages are complicated, so information is key. Seniors can get the free 45-page booklet Home-Made Money by writing to the AARP Home Equity Information Center, 601 E Street NW, Washington, D.C. 20049. The National Center for Home Equity Conversion puts out Reverse Mortgage Locator, a guide that lists reverse lenders and explains the different types of mortgages; send a self-addressed stamped envelope and one dollar to Reverse Mortgage Locator, 7373 147th St. West, Suite 115, Apple Valley, Minnesota 55124. To find out more about federally insured reverse-mortgage lenders in your area, call HUD at 800-217-6970.

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/1page.gif"><br>About 1 page

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
</td>
