<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/09-Growing Pains</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/09-Growing Pains</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
The economy has grown 2.5 percent a year during Bill Clinton's term. Is that the best we should expect?<p>By Walter Russell Mead<p>"It's the economy, stupid," read the famous sign in the Clinton campaign headquarters in 1992. Now, four years later, the election probably still hangs on the economy. But this time Bill Clinton is running on his record. The president looks at the economic performance of the last three years -- average growth of 2.5 percent a year -- and congratulates himself on a job well done. The economy is bumping along near the top of its long-term potential, he claims.<p>To nobody's surprise, the Republicans interpret the same numbers very differently. The economy's miserable performance is due to the failed policies of the Clinton administration, charges GOP candidate Bob Dole. It's time for a change.<p>The cynicism is, of course, breathtaking. If Clinton were 
the challenger and Dole the incumbent, does anybody doubt they would switch sides? Clinton would denounce slow growth, while Dole would defend his stellar record. Truth be told, it's a little strange to see happy-go-lucky Bill, the jolly uncle who always urges everybody to have another helping, siding with notorious ascetic Alan Greenspan. And it almost passes belief to see the acerbic, weaned-on-a-pickle Bob Dole telling everybody to help themselves to the punch -- the drinks are on him.<p>It makes you proud of our democratic system, in a sick sort of way.<p>But unlike a lot of political rhetoric this year, the economic debate in the campaign at least poses an interesting question: How fast can the American economy grow?<p>The Federal Reserve Board, of course, has an opinion -- a very important one. The Fed constantly measures the performance of the actual economy against a model of the potential economy. When the actual economy is underperforming its long-term performance potential, the Fed tries to pump things up. When it looks like the real economy is growing faster than its long-term potential, the Fed taps the brake pedal and raises interest rates.<p>So how fast does the Fed think the economy can grow? Roughly 2.4 percent annually. Score one for Bill Clinton.<p>To make his case against President Clinton on the economy, candidate Dole must convince voters that the Fed is wrong -- the economy can grow faster than 2.4 percent without igniting inflation. Fortunately for him, Dole can take his pick of three arguments. Unfortunately for him, the alternative most worth examining is the one least likely to fire up voters in November.<p>The first two arguments are rhetorically attractive -- but nonstarters as economic policy. Number one, Dole could don populist garb and argue that we should simply ease monetary policy in order to get more growth and not worry about the consequences. Or, number two, Dole could suggest, as he has, that tinkering with tax rates -- cutting rates but slashing expenditures by the same amount -- would increase growth. It's unlikely that Greenspan or the credit markets will buy either of these, although proposing a tax cut might gain Dole some votes.<p>Using alternative three, Dole could argue that the Fed's numbers are simply wrong. Productivity is higher than the Federal Reserve calculates, and the economy can therefore grow faster than Greenspan realizes. Don't expect to hear this argument as a sound bite on the 7 p.m. news anytime soon. As a campaign issue, it is nowhere near as attractive as a promise to cut taxes -- with the details on how to pay for that left deliberately obscure. However, it is the only one of these three alternatives actually worthy of attention.<p>Deciding how fast the economy can grow isn't a trivial exercise. If we could increase the annual rate of growth of the U.S. gross domestic product by just one percentage point for the next 25 years, in 2021 the economy would be almost $3.1 trillion bigger than economists now expect. Get the long-term growth rate up to 4 percent a year, and after 25 years the economy would be almost $5 trillion bigger. That would certainly help fund the boomers' retirement and give Generation X a lifetime of steadily rising standards of living -- the American dream would be alive and well. And 4 percent growth isn't out of the question. From 1960 to 1973, the economy grew at 4.2 percent. We did it once; why can't we do it again?<p>The economy's potential for growth, economists tell us, is roughly equal to the long-term average increase in productivity plus the increase in the labor force. The experts believe the labor force is growing about 1 percent annually, and productivity increased by 
1.4 percent a year from 1973 through 1990. Add them up and you get the magic number -- 2.4 percent.<p>To double-check the temperature of the economy, the experts look at another number. There is, economic theory states, a "natural rate of unemployment" -- the lowest level of unemployment that a given economy can sustain without causing inflation. Some people call this NAIRU, the Non-Accelerating Inflation Rate of Unemployment. If unemployment drops below NAIRU, inflation takes off, the theory claims. The Fed and most mainstream economists today believe that NAIRU is somewhere in the range of 5.5 percent to 6 percent unemployment. With the unemployment rate around 5.5 percent in the first six months of 1996, the economy, by this measure, too, is growing about as fast as it can without overheating.<p>The sad truth is that nobody really knows how to measure or even define productivity at the level of the national economy. NAIRU, the double check, is just as flawed.<p>Let's look at the hard numbers. At some level, productivity is clearly related to GDP growth, wages, and living standards. From 1960 to 1973, for example, the Bureau of Economic Analysis at the Commerce Department reports that  productivity on average rose 3.2 percent a year (more than twice the recent rate) and that GDP growth averaged 4.2 percent a year. Then productivity growth went into a tailspin, averaging only 1.4 percent per year between 1973 and 1990. Average GDP growth fell to 2.9 percent a year during the period. According to the most recent "Economic Report of the President," which is produced annually by the Council of Economic Advisers, productivity growth has averaged 1.2 percent a year since 1990.<p>But can those numbers be right? Our personal experience of the economy says no. Surely, we say, the computer revolution has increased productivity. We all know we're working much harder -- if we still have jobs -- to make up for all our colleagues who were downsized. How can this not add up to rapid productivity growth?<p>Productivity seems like it ought to be easy to measure. If worker A makes 100 widgets an hour and worker B makes 110, clearly worker B is 10 percent more productive than worker A. But try to apply this over any period of time. In 1960, the <a name="NYSE:F"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10597"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Ford Motor Company</b></a> had 160,181 employees and produced 2.2 million cars -- 13.7 cars per worker. In 1995, 185,960 Ford workers produced 3.5 million cars -- 18.8 cars per worker. On the surface, productivity is up 37 percent in 35 years.<p>But in 1960, a vertically integrated Ford prided itself on producing the parts used in its cars. In 1996, however, 62 percent of Ford parts came from outside sources. To figure out how many workers produced Ford's cars, we have to add in employment at outside -- including foreign -- suppliers.<p>Another way to go would be to look at operating income per employee or per dollar of employee cost, but here, too, there are problems. Ford lost money in 5 of the last 16 years. Does that mean that its workers produced nothing of value in those years?<p>Productivity is even more difficult to measure for service companies. How do we rate the productivity of a lawyer? Cases won? Cases settled out of court? Lawsuits avoided altogether by shrewd legal counsel?<p>Greenspan has argued that there is simply no evidence that new technology has put the economy on a track to faster growth. In testimony before the Senate Banking Committee, the Fed chairman compared the electronic revolution to the advent of electricity. Electricity, he pointed out, became available in the 1880s, but the productivity gains from the new technology did not really show up until the 1920s. At that rate, the economy could remain on a slow growth track well into the next century.<p>There's also no evidence that downsizing has upped productivity. Last spring, Stephen Roach, chief economist at <a name="NYSE:MS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11018"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Morgan Stanley</b></a> and a longtime advocate of productivity growth, changed his mind. Downsizing, he now says, is just downsizing. There might be one-shot productivity gains, but downsizing does not produce long-term productivity growth.<p>But just because we can't measure an increase in productivity growth doesn't mean it's not occurring. Go back to those workers at Ford. The car they built in 1995 is far more complex, far more efficient than the 1960 model. The worker using a computer to add graphics to a report -- something he wouldn't have attempted in 1960 -- is adding value to the product he produces, though we can't measure it. The truth is that neither the Fed chairman nor anybody else really understands what productivity is or how it should be properly measured.<p>NAIRU doesn't work any better. Start with the unemployment rate itself. For the first half of 1996, the Labor Department reported that 5.5 percent of the labor force -- which is estimated at 132.3 million people -- was unemployed. But many private economists, including Larry Mishel of the Economic Policy Institute, think the real rate is higher -- much higher. According to Mishel, the true rate of unemployment is somewhere near 10 percent. The official rate is lower only because the government doesn't count "discouraged workers" -- people who want jobs but have given up looking because they have no realistic hope of finding work -- among the unemployed. A recent study by the National Bureau of Economic Research concluded that NAIRU shifts over time in response to forces that at present are poorly understood. If there is a NAIRU for the economy, neither the Fed nor its critics knows what it is.<p>The more honest of the inflation hawks admit all this. Maybe the economy can get by with lower unemployment, they concede, but the risks of testing this theory are too high. Fed policy takes months, even years, to have an effect on the national economy. If the Fed waits until statistics show that an inflationary spiral has started, then the economy will already have lurched into another boom-and-bust cycle.<p>In the end, that brings us back to politics. Some Americans -- the owners of small businesses, borrowers, the unemployed -- want low interest rates and rapid economic growth even at the risk of inflation. Others -- bondholders and people living on fixed incomes -- want to see inflation controlled even if that means low growth.<p>Differences like these are supposed to be settled in elections. Vote for Bill Clinton and get four more years of slow growth with Alan Greenspan, or vote for Bob Dole and get four years of lower interest rates with whatever risks and opportunities that entails.<p>But in reality, Fed policy isn't on the table this political season. Greenspan will be chairman of the Federal Reserve for four more years no matter who wins in November, and, as president, Dole would be unlikely to deviate far from the cautious policies that Greenspan has followed -- and that Dole has preached throughout his public life. Vote for either candidate and what you will get is Greenspan's policy on growth.<p>One hundred years ago, the election of 1896 pitted soft-money candidate William Jennings Bryan against William McKinley, defender of the gold standard. Voters had a choice between two clear alternatives.<p>Today, the electorate is still divided between the advocates of soft and hard money, but the political system isn't providing meaningful choices. No wonder the voters of 1996 are more cynical about the political process than their ancestors were a hundred years ago.<p>
Walter Russell Mead is the presidential fellow at the World Policy Institute at the New School. Research assistance provided by Andrew Weinstein.<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Employment, Retierment, Government Adgencies, Legislaton, Inflation, Economy, Politics

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
