	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/09-Social Insecurity</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/09-Social Insecurity</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
Social Security, the most sacred of political cows, is about to change fundamentally -- or go broke.<p>By James K. Glassman<p>Inside Washington's infamous beltway, Social Security has long been known as the third rail of politics: Touch it, and the voters will kill you. But for the first time in the 61 years of its existence, politicians of all stripes are openly considering putting an end to Social Security as a retirement program funded with payroll taxes and replacing it with private pensions that Americans direct themselves. It's the hottest policy issue in town -- though it's likely our major presidential candidates will pretend the debate isn't even occurring, for fear of alienating the senior-citizen vote.<p>Still, Steve Forbes used privatizing Social Security as an applause line in the primaries, and Richard Lamm, the former Democratic governor of Colorado and a candidate for a third-party presidential nomination, is a privatization enthusiast. Representative Jim Kolbe, a Republican who sits on the powerful Appropriations and Budget Committees, heads a House caucus committed to restructuring Social Security along free-market lines, and most significantly, the bipartisan Advisory Council on Social Security, appointed in 1994 by the Clinton administration, also favors alternative forms of privatization.<p>Why the change in attitude? In part, it's licensed by the public perception that Social Security is failing -- a view underscored by a 1994 poll that found more Americans between the ages of 18 and 34 believe in UFOs (46 percent) than think Social Security will still exist by the time they retire (28 percent). But the real catalyst is a series of official projections showing that Social Security will go into the red (by 2012, at latest count) as baby boomers start retiring and the system begins paying out more in benefits than it collects. By 2029, the Social Security trust fund (now comprising less than two years' worth of benefits) will be hopelessly insolvent. <p>One way to keep Social Security afloat after 2012 would be to raise taxes -- almost no one's favorite option. The system could also survive longer if we let benefits rise more slowly, reduce payments to rich retirees, or raise the retirement age. Beyond just footing the bill, however, philosophical objections are being raised about the status quo. They can be summed up in two questions: Why should young workers, just starting out, pay the pensions of retired Americans, many of them well-off? And why shouldn't all Americans save for their own retirements, without the government's help? <p>On the first question, Kolbe says, "What we have now is a fairly immoral system. There is no connection between what you pay in and what you get out." That's true. An 81-year-old today has received a real rate of return of 5.5 percent on his or her payroll-tax contributions. By contrast, says Arthur P. Hall, senior economist for the Tax Foundation, an average-wage couple retiring in 2027 will receive a real return of negative 1.4 percent on what they've paid in. <p>The reason for this disparity is that Social Security is a pay-as-you-go operation. Three young workers, each making $30,000 a year, contribute about $3,500 each in Social Security taxes (half from their pay, half from their employers), all of which goes to one retiree. It's a pure transfer payment from one generation to another. <p>As life expectancy has risen and the retired population has increased, payroll taxes have had to keep pace. The original rate was 2 percent on the first $3,000 in income, for a maximum tax of $60. In 1996, the rate hit 12.4 percent on up to $62,700, for a maximum of $7,775. And the numbers are going to get worse. In 1950, there were 16 workers for every Social Security beneficiary; today, there are 3.3. By 2030, there will be two. <p>The second philosophical question is more basic. "It's paternalistic to assume that people cannot take action in their own self-interest," says Sylvester J. Schieber, a member of the Advisory Council on Social Security. Schieber wants to trim current benefits and let workers put part of their payroll taxes into IRA-style accounts. His plan includes a guaranteed minimum benefit (about two-thirds of the poverty level) for all, and a private account funded by 5 percent of a worker's annual income. <p>That 5 percent should generate a good deal more than does the current 12.4 percent payroll tax, which yields a return of just 3.5 percent, a figure that will soon decline to 2.5 percent. Martin Feldstein of Harvard, who heads the National Bureau of Economic Research, calculates that a privatized Social Security account (a combination of stocks and bonds) should yield 9 percent, or nearly $9,000, over 25 years (versus $2,000 at a 2.5 percent yield) from an original investment of $1,000.<p>This is the key to privatization: If you put your retirement money into stocks and bonds, the market return should be far higher than what Feldstein calls the "implicit return" under the current pay-as-you-go system. We're talking big bucks. <p>Using Social Security Administration figures, William G. Shipman, co-chairman of the Project on Social Security Privatization for the Cato Institute, a libertarian think tank, found that a baby boomer born in 1950 and currently earning about $60,000 can expect monthly Social Security benefits of $1,562 (in 1995 dollars) when he retires. But if, instead of paying taxes to the Social Security fund, he put the money into an all-stock retirement account, the result would be a $9,972 monthly benefit. An all-bond account would yield $5,243 a month (in 1995 dollars). <p>So in theory, privatization looks pretty good. But would it work? There is one interesting example of the theory in action: Chile. In 1981, Jose Pinera, then minister of Labor and Social Security, instituted a private retirement system, which lifted the personal savings rate from 9 percent to 25 percent (it's below 4 percent in the U.S.). This helped raise Chile's economic growth rate from 3 percent to 6.5 percent. <p>Pinera is an energetic proselytizer of the Chilean model. At a conference in Mexico earlier this year, he explained that in Chile "neither the worker nor the employer pays a Social Security tax to the state. Nor does the worker collect a government-funded pension. Instead, during his working life, he automatically has 10 percent of his wages deposited by his employer each month in his own individual PSA [pension savings account]. This percentage applies only to the first $22,000 of annual income.... A worker may contribute an additional 10 percent of his wages each month, which is also deductible from taxable income, as a form of voluntary savings."<p>The worker invests his PSA money in one of about two dozen private 
pension-fund administration companies -- basically, mutual funds -- that are regulated by the government to make sure they remain sound. Workers can shift in and out of them at will. The companies also provide insurance against premature death and disability for an additional mandatory contribution of 2.9 percent of salary. Workers with sufficient savings in their PSAs can retire whenever they want, while those with insufficient funds at retirement get a government pension after their accounts have been depleted.<p>"The system has been extremely successful," wrote John B. Shoven, dean of the School of Humanities and Sciences at Stanford, in a recent paper for the Investment Company Institute -- an association of U.S. mutual funds that would profit hugely if $300 billion to $400 billion a year in Social Security taxes were privately invested. But Shoven says, "I would warn that a 13- to 14-year history is a very short time frame if you're in the generational retirement business, so 
I think it's a little early to judge."<p>The transition from Social Security to a private retirement system would be difficult. First, we'd have to protect today's retirees by maintaining current benefit levels. We'd probably have to do the same for those verging on retirement -- people in their mid-50s and up. And what about everyone else who has made Social Security contributions? Shouldn't they get a credit paid into their new private accounts? Shoven figures that this could cost $11 trillion.<p>Is there any way to pay this sum and still privatize? One answer might be to require a mandatory 10 percent contribution by workers to their own accounts and another 10 percent tax to fund the old system until it withers away. Sam Beard, a former aide to Robert F. Kennedy, envisions a transition that could last 50 to 60 years. Beard, who runs the National Development Council in New Castle, Delaware, advocates a plan that would include returning previous Social Security contributions to affluent Americans in the form of "liberty bonds" -- which could go to their heirs, tax-free.<p>The debate will be a long one, and it should be. After all, the need to help the elderly remain financially secure created Social Security and must continue to be met by any reform. But in a society that succeeds by rewarding individual effort, there is another goal. As Jose Pinera says, "The pay-as-you-go pension system...destroys, at the individual level, the essential link between effort and reward -- in other words, between personal responsibilities and personal rights. Whenever that happens on a massive scale and for a long period of time, the result is disaster."<p>
James K. Glassman, a contributing editor, is a columnist for The Washington Post and the host of Capital Gang Sunday on CNN and Technopolitics on PBS.<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Government Legislation, Retirement, Internatoinal Government

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
