	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/06-Riding the Waves</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/06-Riding the Waves</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						When Alvin Toffler talks about the future, powerful people listen -- from Newt Gingrich to the aging communists in Beijing<p>By Walter Russell Mead<p>Change has been good to Alvin Toffler. Working in an intellectual partnership with Heidi Toffler, his wife of almost 50 years, he has written one best-seller after another, from Future Shock to The Third Wave to Powershift, about the way technological change transforms societies. His most recent book, coauthored with Heidi Toffler, is Creating a New Civilization: The Politics of the Third Wave.<p>In their work, the Tofflers have developed a structure for understanding and anticipating change. According to them, there have been three great changes, or waves, in human history. The first wave saw the development of settled agriculture. Many people in the world still live in peasant-based, first-wave societies, even though the first wave began 8,000 to 10,000 years ago. The second wave, the industrial revolution, began about 300 years ago and is still spreading through the world.<p>The economic and social upheavals now sweeping across the United States and the rest of the world, they argue, are the result of the third wave, the information revolution. Just as the first and second waves saw the development of economic, social, and political structures based on the agricultural and industrial technologies of those waves, the third wave is creating radically different institutions and ways of life.<p>In a recent interview with Walter Russell Mead, Alvin Toffler talked about how corporate restructuring, the crisis of American democracy, and the growing storm clouds over Asia all fit together.<p>Worth: As a freelance writer and consultant, you yourself are an example of the new ways of making a living that you talk about. How does this life compare to holding down a job?<p>Toffler: It's infinitely better. The last job I had was at Fortune from November '59 to May '61.<p>Q:
How did you get started as a freelance worker? It must have been more difficult in those days.
A:
My wife and I started out after working in factories for about five years -- auto plants, steel mills, and aluminum foundries. Heidi was a union member and became a shop steward. From there, I went to work for a labor paper.<p>Then we went to Washington and spent three years covering Capitol Hill and the White House for a small Pennsylvania newspaper -- but freelancing, always freelancing, on the side.<p>The three years we spent in Washington were a kind of graduate degree in American politics -- the only formal degree I have is a B.A. in English from New York University. After Washington, I went to Fortune.<p>Between '65 and '70, we wrote Future Shock. And that changed everything. It sold five million paperback copies in the U.S. So now we work like dogs, but not for someone else. <p>Q:
You were really one of the first to write about the evolution of the corporation. Is the restructuring of the corporation over?
A:
No. Oh no, there's a lot more to go. I think you'll see that corporations, having gone through successive restructurings, are suddenly confronted, once again, by the need to totally rethink their purpose in life. Take the recent passage of the telecommunications legislation. Every company in the telecom, computer, and related fields is now going to go through painful internal surgery and reconstruction.<p>Permanent internal reorganization is the name of the game. And that is reflected in the tremendous turnover not just of markets, not just of lines of business, not just of products, but also of organizational structures. When everything else changes as dramatically as is happening now, organizational structure must also change.<p>Q:
What will these new structures look like?
A:
We have only just begun to think imaginatively about all the possible alternative forms. For example, in the mid-80s, we began to hear about profit centers. Big, monolithic corporations began to break themselves into smaller units called profit centers, each of which was supposed to operate more entrepreneurially. However, if you look at them, almost all the profit centers are baby bureaucracies.<p>The next stage, I think, is that all these smaller units are going to take on their own organizational formats, and not all of them will be the same.<p>There are many models possible -- checkerboard organizations, commissar organizations. One of my favorites is the pulsating organization -- the U.S. Census Bureau is the example we used in Powershift. In a routine year, the Census Bureau has 8,000 to 9,000 employees. But in a census year, that number goes up to 300,000 employees. And then it goes back down.<p>Q:
Why is the bureaucratic model outmoded?
A:
Lots of reasons that are well-known. Slow. Anti-innovative. But at a deeper level the problem is that the people on top haven't a clue as to what the people down below need to know. Things today are so complex and fast changing that the people doing the actual work need freedom of information. They need to be able to go anywhere up and down the hierarchy, across to other departments, diagonally. As soon as you do that, however, you change the internal power structure. Because the people who then were gatekeepers, who sat on top of each little unit, no longer control the flow of information that gave them power. And so they no longer have a function.<p>Q:
So the layoffs of managers will continue and even accelerate?
A:
I'm afraid so. And government will have to restructure much more quickly as well.<p>Q:
That sounds like a stressful change for an individual.
A:
It will be. You have to be ready to learn new skills and to completely change how you operate. And here's the thing that is radically misunderstood. When we say displaced managers need new skills, the assumption is they need specific occupational skills. That isn't all they need. What they need are new cultural skills. They need to understand that they're going to operate in a different kind of culture, just as ghetto kids and gang members have to understand they have to show up on time if they want to hold a job. These are deep cultural changes that go far beyond simply learning how to use Windows 95.<p>Q:
It seems that education is going to be a key. Is our present system of education going to survive? Should it survive?
A:
No, to both questions. The current system -- one teacher and many kids --  is obviously not the model for the future. If we continue to think of education as schoolhouses, rows of seats, and a teacher in front of the classroom, we will fail.<p>When we created the mass-education system, it was a democratic and humanizing advance. When we set up this system, one of the assumptions we made was that most parents were ignorant, illiterate, and lived in backward, isolated villages. And so they turned their child over to the most educated, sophisticated person in the village. The person who had visited Chicago once. Or who was literate. Now middle-class parents frequently turn their kids over to teachers who are less educated than they are themselves. This changes one of the fundamental assumptions of the system: the assumption that schools are going to raise the educational level.<p>Q:
So today's school is a dumber environment than many homes?
A:
Yes. So what you must do is integrate parents into the process. But the most important change is you've got to de-massify the education system. What we are doing is educating kids for an industrial mass society. And it once made sense to do it the way we did it.<p>We created a school on the model of the factory. Because at least one of the functions of the education system is to simulate the future that children will live in.<p>When you put kids into a factory-style school and they're going into a factory world, you are simulating the future reasonably accurately. When you put kids into a factory-style education system and there aren't going to be factories out there, you are cheating them, misleading them, mis-educating them.<p>What we now have is a one size mis-fits all system. What we need more than anything is to let 100,000 educational flowers bloom. Different systems, different methods. That will better match the nature of the world that the kids are going to live in.<p>Q:
It's hard to pigeonhole you into any of the political schools out there. On some issues -- deregulation, government reform, and so on -- you can be classed with radical right-wing House freshmen. And yet the changes you see in society and the reforms you advocate would overturn many of the institutions and values that right-wing Republicans want to protect. For example, you suggest that the nuclear family is almost as outmoded as bureaucracy.
A:
We have to open the family system to multiple family forms. The family is not an independent variable. It is part of a larger social system. It is connected with how people work. How they finance and pay for their existence. How they connect to technology, to the communication system, to everything in our society -- because all of these form an integrated system. The family doesn't just exist out there as some kind of isolated cell.<p>The family cannot be isolated from the changes sweeping the broader society. When we wrote Future Shock -- it was published in 1970 -- we went to the leading family experts and simply asked, "What's going to happen to the nuclear family?" And the almost universal answer was, nothing. The nuclear family is an eternal model.<p>Well, this is so ahistorical that it makes me choke. Before the industrial revolution, the nuclear family was rare. First-wave agrarian societies typically have large households. They're not papa goes to work, mama stays home, two kids under the age of 18. They're big, multigenerational households. They are actually a production team. They work together in the fields or in the cottages. And that's the dominant family form in most agrarian societies. Even today.<p>With the industrial revolution, you need a labor force that's mobile. If there are no jobs in Birmingham, workers have to be able to go to Manchester. They can't go dragging 20 family members along with them. Gradually, the family size shrinks in every industrializing country.<p>In Future Shock, we wrote a chapter called "The Fractured Family"that did not say the family was going to die -- but that it was going to change. And this is happening now. We see today that the state of Hawaii is contemplating legitimation of homosexual marriage. To us, this isn't a question of gay or lesbian. It's a question of diversity of family structure.<p>We have families in which you have once-remarried adults and kids. Twice-remarried adults and kids. Those are different structures.<p>We believe that the family is a very important institution in society. We believe, along with the so-called right wing, that family systems should be strengthened. Kids do need households. They do need loving adults.<p>But the failures of the family are not primarily a result of welfare. Lots of people, middle-class and rich people, see their families go up in smoke also. They don't live in ghettos. Unless they're rich ghettos.<p>In first-wave societies, the family was the labor unit. It educated the child, healed the sick, took care of the elderly. In the second wave, without deliberate intent, we stripped the family of its most vital social functions. That has reduced the family's functions to sex, procreation, romance, and companionship. Not enough to make it a dominating institution among other institutions.<p>Q:
In Powershift, you both predict and call for a much more revolutionary kind of politics. Now, five years after Powershift, we see the American people deeply dissatisfied with politics as usual. What's going on? 
A:
I see the political parties as essentially obsolete vehicles that are engaged in hopeless ritual contests for control of the so-called levers of our democracy. But the American population is thoroughly disaffiliated from both the parties and the mechanisms that they compete to control.<p>Q:
So the political parties aren't really vehicles for the kinds of pressures and interests that need to be brought forward?
A:
No, they aren't. For example, a lot of the Contract With America just represents a redistribution of power among second-wave groups. It's the same old stuff.<p>It's a relic of an unfinished Republican agenda, left over from years and years of being out in the wilderness. Having said that, one of the consequences of the contract is a devolution of power and some decision making out of Washington. And that, I think, is extremely important. And that is why, despite itself, the contract has third-wave consequences.
Q:
If neither party has the answers, where do the answers come from?
A:
A hidden political battle is going on. We think there is a powerful, deeply rooted conflict between groups who have a stake in maintaining the smokestack world and groups that have 
a stake in moving to a new, third-wave information-based economy.<p>You can see that in the way the Buchanans and the Naders come together. What are the so-called right and the so-called left coming together in defense of? Essentially, the old rust-belt manufacturing world. As though protectionism and regulation could somehow restore it to vitality.<p>In order to compete effectively in the competitive global economy, we have to make use of our best advantage. That is high technology, information technology. Now, will there be dislocations entailed in doing that? Yes. Painful, horrible ones for many people. However, if you do not make these changes, you guarantee that many more people will suffer even more.<p>You would see a declining America. Not just economically but politically. And you also open up, I believe, the possibility for war.<p>Q:
Just where do you see the world going? What are the real dan-ger points?
A:
Okay, but with the proviso that my wife and I do not believe in linear projections and that nothing continues indefinitely, we think the really big and important and good news in the world is the rise of Asia. Asia shows that it is possible to raise a billion people out of poverty in a generation.<p>What could stop that is political and military instability in Asia. The Asia-Pacific region is almost encircled by nuclear weapons. You have Pakistan, India, Russia, China, and, maybe, North Korea.<p>So, you have the world's most rapidly changing region surrounded by the most dangerous weapons in the world. And you have a superpower, the United States, that has a president who doesn't pay enough attention to the region.<p>He agrees to go to a meeting of Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation in Osaka and to meet the Japanese prime minister. At the very last minute, he cancels his appearances at Osaka and Tokyo and goes to Ireland. He then says, "But I will come to Tokyo in January."Then he cancels the trip in January and says, "I will come in April."He is telling Asia, "We don't think you're very important."And China, therefore, believes that it can do as it wishes, and so do others. Having received that message, China then fires missiles into the sea near Taiwan.<p>Now, the idea that China is going to be the superpower of the year 2020, which The Economist devoted a whole special section to a year ago, was based on straight-line projections of current economic trends. But that's too simple. Wherever you've had big changes like those in China today, you also see battles between the second-wave industrializing elites and the traditional elites of the first-wave society.<p>However, the new revolutionary politics in China is even more complicated. In China, you have first-, second-, and third-wave economies and elites all rubbing elbows. In a situation like that, you can't extrapolate trends. You have to prepare for twists and turns, for surprises -- good and bad. Often history is made by the low-probability event that nobody thought was worth thinking about.<p>The most important of these low-probability/high-impact scenarios today is the possible disintegration of China. Now, will China disintegrate? Probably not. The odds are against it. Could it disintegrate? Yes. Would it have global implications? You bet.<p>American leadership radically underestimates the political struggle in China between the elites of different waves. Out in the boondocks, you've got 600 million or 900 million peasants who are still living first-wave lives under local leaders. Then, on the coast, a highly developed region, you've got a lot of second-wave businesspeople, who are peddling cheap labor to the outside world. Finally, you have an emerging third-wave elite, people with cellular telephones and computers tied into Silicon Valley and Singapore. These three different elite groups have quite different interests.<p>I see profound forces at work moving toward an upheaval 
of some kind in China. That would probably mean an end to the happy scenario of raising a billion Asians out of poverty. It probably would stop the development of Asia for 10, 15, 20, 50 years.<p>Q:
Now, let's quickly close the circle and bring this back to the U.S. Could closing the doors of the U.S. and the world economy to Asia trigger some kind of war?
A:
I think that the trade pressures that we put on Japan and China are not in the national interest. They're essentially in the interest of special-interest groups in the society. When we go to Japan and say, "You must open the rice market,"it doesn't matter one rice grain to the United States as a nation whether we sell rice to Japan or whether we don't. But it matters to some important lobbies.<p>Q:
Rice farmers in Arkansas?
A:
Exactly. To close America as a market to Asia in the situation we have described means that you are almost asking for the region to blow up. <p><p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Employment, Internatoinal Economy, Politics, Government

					</font>
