	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/06-Independents' Day?</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						It may get easier for contractors to show they're not employees<p>By Elizabeth Macdonald<p>The IRS loves taxpayers who get their taxes withheld, otherwise known as employees. It's not nearly as fond of taxpayers who receive Form 1099, otherwise known as independent contractors. But there's a movement afoot in Congress to force the IRS to learn to care more for its wayward children.<p>At present, the IRS routinely moves workers from independent-contractor status to that of employee -- 90 percent of all contractors the IRS investigates get reclassified as employees. The agency claims that contractors who don't have their taxes withheld underreport their income, cheating the government out of as much as $4 billion in revenue each year. Its reclassification schemes involve a vague and arbitrary 20-factor test that determines the tortured distinction between employees and contractors. One of these tests, for instance, asks how much time a worker spends at a work site, an archaic standard in the age of telecommuting. Often, the IRS makes different decisions on seemingly identical cases.<p>Despite the ambiguity in classifying workers, the IRS smacked them and their employers with $751 million in fines from 11,380 audits between 1988 and 1994. Another recent study says the IRS has collected $678 million in fines and taxes from 439,000 taxpayers redefined as employees since the mid-1980s.<p>Last March, the IRS introduced a program that would allow businesses to settle worker-classification issues as soon as the IRS suspected a problem. This would help the businesses avoid costlier fines and penalties, but the cost of the fines themselves would not change. An employer with classification problems can also qualify for an IRS settlement offer by "agreeing" to treat all its workers as employees, but this provides no real benefits to anyone but the IRS.<p>The good news is that several current congressional legislative proposals are trying to tackle the problem of classifying workers. A bill proposed by Republican representative Jon Christensen of Nebraska, and co-sponsored by more than 200 other representatives, stands the best chance of passing in some form. Christensen claims his bill would "sketch clearly and starkly" who is an independent contractor and who is an employee. He wants to offer a three-part test as an alternative to the IRS's 20 factors. The new rules would require independent contractors to sign a contract with a boss stating that they must not be treated as employees.<p>Until Christensen's bill passes, the best place to go for more information is the 32-page booklet Employee or Independent Contractor? Resolving the Dilemma, available for $6.50 from tax-law publisher CCH. Call 800-835-5224 for details.  <p><p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Taxation, Government Adgency, Employment

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
