	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/04-A Battle Without Honor</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>A Battle Without Honor</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/04-A Battle Without Honor</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						April 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Features  <p> A BATTLE WITHOUT HONOR <p>The balanced-budget debate is a meaningless farce that's diverting attention from the country's real problems  <p> By Walter Russell Mead  <p> It has been billed as the political fight of the century. For months, as markets have swooped and swooned, the brash Republican majorities in Congress and President Bill Clinton have been locked in a titanic struggle that will, all the pundits say, determine the fate of the republic. The GOP shut down the government; Clinton painted the Republicans as radical extremists. With elections approaching, both sides have threatened to appeal to the American people. Let the 1996 election be a great referendum on balancing the budget, they declaim.  <p> There's just one little problem with this scenario: The great budget battle of 1996 is a fraud. If Congress got everything it wanted, there would still be no guarantee that the budget would balance in 2002. If the president got everything he wanted, he still couldn't assure that his version of the Medicare program would last until then. An election fought over a balanced budget would be a grotesque abuse of the public trust. Apparently, both parties can live with that.  <p> So what makes me so sure that the budget battle is absurd?  <p> First, neither side actually has the power to balance the budget in seven years. Even if both houses of Congress pass a seven-year budget plan, and the president signs it on the White House lawn while the Marine band plays "The Star-Spangled Banner" and the Blue Angels stunt overhead, it doesn't matter. The plan has no legal binding force.   <p> Think about it. It's the year 2001. Congress is in session. Possibly it's more conservative than the one we have now, possibly more liberal. Whatever it is, it will be able to vote whatever budget it wants for the next year. It can vote a budget in surplus,a balanced budget, or a budget with a colossal deficit. It won't care two straws what the Congress of 1996 thought the budget should be. The Congress of 2001 cannot be bound by anything Congress does in 1996.  <p> This isn't just speculation. I remember the fate of the last deficit-reduction plan that a Congress passed and a president signed into law. Enough of these feeble campaign promises that are so soon forgotten, said all the politicians in 1985. We must enact a binding commitment, they said, something, by God, to force the damned deficit down.   <p> And so they passed a law, the Gramm-Rudman-Hollings budget amendment, not very different from the current proposals, mandating changes in spending to reach budget targets until one glorious morn in1991, when the brave new world of perpetually balanced budgets would begin. And there were sanctions in Gramm-Rudman to make sure the job got done.   <p> The toughest of these was sequestration. If the congressional budget in any given year failed to meet the Gramm-Rudman targets, automatic spending cuts would set in, reducing spending enough to meet the deficit targets. It all looked good on paper.  <p> But when the deficit target dates came up, requiring painful spending cuts, Congress found ways around the rules. Spending could be deferred; accounting gimmicks could throw costs into the next year; specific expenditures could be taken off the books. Congress decided, for example, that much of the cost of the savings-and-loan bailout shouldn't be counted as part of the budget deficit for Gramm-Rudman purposes.   <p> By 1987, though, even these efforts weren't enough. So Congress gave itself an exemption and pushed the balanced-budget date off until 1993. Under this reworking of the schedule, the permissible deficit target for 1991 jumped from zero dollars to $64 billion. When 1991 came around, however, the budget deficit wasn't $64 billion or even $100 billion. It was $267 billion.   <p> Was there mass sequestration and panic in Washington?   <p> No. By then, years of gimmicks and loopholes had turned Gramm-Rudman into a joke. Nobody mourned much when it was buried by the budget agreement between the Democratic Congress and George Bush. Congress and the presidents of the day had successfully nickled-and-dimed Gramm-Rudman to death.  <p> And that is exactly what the government especially Congress canand will do if any new budget plan gets in its way. It will amend, repeal, stretch out, or ignore any restrictions that it finds inconvenient.  <p> It's pretty easy to tell which restrictions a future Congress is likely to ignore. Budgets are divided into two parts. There's the section that deals with the next two years (the actual life of the Congress that passes the bill) and then there are the out-years: years three, four, five, six, and seven in the current plans.  <p> So here's Mead's First Law, and you can carve it in stone: The Out-Years Aren't Real. Whether it's an economic forecast or political plan, once you get beyond 18 months, it all fades into the mist. <p> In judging a budget plan, forget about the out-years. They are the pretty box and wrapping paper. The out-year proposals are the ones you never plan to implement: Worse than the New Year's resolutions you made this January, these are the New Year's resolutions you plan to make three years from now. With any economic program, look at what it says about the next two years. That is the part of the proposal that could actually happen.   <p> This is my second reason for believing the great budget debate of 1996 is a fraud: The cuts are almost all in the out-years. The real years, the first two in the plan, are about minimal spending cuts and fat, juicy tax cuts.   <p> This isn't a plan to cut spending at all. It's a plan to cut taxes while letting politicians look good by talking about cutting the deficit.   <p> In other words, it's Gramm-Rudman II.   <p> While Warren Rudman had the grace to retire, Phil Gramm campaigned for the presidency, telling voters around the country that this time, really, trust me, no fooling, the new improved multiyear plan would balance the budget and slay that demon deficit once and for all.   <p> Oh, and here's your tax cut.   <p> Third, this budget battle would be a fraud even if the politicians were serious about carrying out their plans and could force future politicians to meet these goals. The numbers behind the plans (those of both the Republicans and the president) are so vague as to be meaningless. The only thing we know is that the federal budget deficit in 2002 will not be what it is predicted to be in either plan.   <p> To know what the budget deficit will be in 2002, we have to know how the economy will behave in each of the years between now and then. What will the growth rate be for 1996 or 1997? When will the next recession come? What will interest rates be in 1999? How many people will be unemployed in November 2001? Will inflation go up or down between 1998 and 2000?  <p> We need to know all this and more in order to forecast the deficit in 2002. Both federal revenues and expenses move up and down with the rate of economic growth. If the economy grows faster, the government takes in more money in taxes. If the economy slows or goes into a recession, tax revenues don't grow as fast but many government expenses rise. Unemployment benefits must be paid to more people. Changes in interest rates affect what the government must pay on its debts.   <p> Events in foreign countries also affect U.S. economic performance. If, for example, the attempt to build a European Monetary Union collapses, and the deutsche mark falls dramatically against the dollar, U.S. exports to Europe will fall and U.S. imports from Europe will rise. That will affect the federal deficit in all kinds of ways. Revenues from tariffs will be marginally higher, but there could be lower employment at a given rate of economic growth throughout the U.S.   <p> It is, of course, impossible for either Congress or the president to predict accurately how the economy will be performing next year, much less in 2002. If they could forecast the future, then they'd be able to stop worrying about the deficit and simply invest the Social Security Trust Fund in the financial markets.If they really could predict economic behavior that well, they could make so much money from investments that they could abolish the income tax, double entitlements, and still show a profit.  <p> Let's look at the margins of error produced by the experts in the short term, the easiest period to predict. In a report issued in August 1995, the Congressional Budget Office, the agency whose numbers the Republican Congress insists are the key to an "honest" budget, bragged that between 197677 and 199394, its two-year growth forecasts were off, on average, only 0.9 percentage points. That made them slightly superior to the numbers produced by the president's Office of Management and Budget and roughly comparable to those of a consensus of blue-chip private forecasters.  <p> But that degree of error, which seems minuscule in a single year, is actually devastating. Although the CBO's forecasts of output were off, on average, by only 0.9 percentage points during this period, the average change in gross domestic product during those years was 2.62 percent. That means the predicted change in GDP missed the actual change by an average of 34 percent. <p> Rates of error vary tremendously from year to year. The banner year for the CBO was 1981; it predicted growth of 0.5 percent, and that's what we got. The next year, however, the CBO predicted growth of 2.1 percent, totally missing the recession that would cause the actual GDP to fall by 0.4 percent. In that year, the forecasting error was more than six times the size of the actualchange in output. Nine years later came another disaster: The CBO predicted growth of 2 percent, and the economy grew only 0.3 percent. The error, 1.7 percent, was 5.6 times the amount of actual growth.  <p> If we take the average rate of error forward through seven years, the margin of error becomes staggeringly large enough to turn deficit projections into worthless junk.  <p> Darts, anyone?   <p> Here's how all that uncertainty affects the final numbers. The CBO estimates that federal revenue will grow from $1.4 trillion in fiscal 1996 to $1.8 trillion in fiscal 2002 a growth of $422 billion. Now suppose that this estimate is off by the historical average of 34 percent. In that case, federal revenue could be$143.5 billion more or less than the CBO figure.  <p> The same uncertainty is at work on the expenditure side. The CBO projects federal expenditures to grow from almost $1.6 trillion in fiscal 1996 to slightly more than $1.8 trillion in fiscal 2002, an increase of $268 billion plus or minus at least $91.1 billion because of that pesky forecasting error. The potential range of error for the federal deficit in 2002 is $234.6 billion $71billion more than the total deficit for fiscal 1995.  <p> Neither the CBO, nor Congress, nor the president can know if any deficit plan will actually eliminate the federal deficit over the next seven years. Congress could pass the GOP budget plan, the president could sign it, and the Congresses and presidents of the next seven years could faithfully follow every jot and tittle of the 1996 budget plan, and we could still end up with a bigger deficit than we have in 1996. Or we could have a massive surplus. Your guess is as good as mine, and mine is as good as the CBO's.  <p> So what's the point of battling over whether one plan or the other is in "balance"?  <p> When one looks at these facts, it seems bad enough that Washington has been convulsed by debates over seven-year budget estimates. It seems truly obscene that the government should have shut down last fall over a difference in the estimates to be used. The White House wanted to balance the budget using OMB growth estimates; Congress wanted to use the CBO's. The truth is that over a seven-year period there is no significant difference between the two sets of estimates. Both are wildly inaccurate; both are shots in the dark. It's as if two people shooting at a target in a pitch-blackroom were to disagree on which of them had come closest to a bull's-eye and then agree to settle the dispute by mud wrestling, winner take all.   <p> The comedy doesn't stop here, either, which leads to my fourth reason for calling the budget debate a fraud. While the budget brouhaha has had Washington in its grip, economists have reached a consensus that the U.S. doesn't have a budget problem.   <p> This is a new development. In 1990, professional economists were in a panic. At that time, the U.S. budget deficit was 4 percent of GDP, and many economists uttered prophecies of doom. Three percent, economists warned in their gravest tones. Three percent! Any government with a budget deficit larger than 3 percent of GDP was on the high road to ruin.   <p> That magic 3 percent number still represents the economic consensus. It has been written into the European Union's Maastricht Treaty, for example, as the maximum deficit any country can have and still hope to join the deutsche mark in the Valhalla of the European Monetary Union.   <p> The prophesied doom didn't come, however. In fact, the situation improved. Spending rose, but thanks to economic growth, government revenues rose even faster. By fiscal 1995, the U.S. budget deficit had fallen to 2.3 percent of GDP, well below the magic number. The result today is that, from a macroeconomic point of view, the U.S. ranks at the top of the class among developed countries. As a percentage of GDP, our estimated budget deficit is lower than Japan's, Germany's, France's, and the United Kingdom's.  <p> So to sum up, Washington has been totally hypnotized by a false debate over nonsolutions to a nonproblem.   <p> And that's too bad. Because the country needs some serious debate about serious issues like demographics and wages.   <p> Demographically, the U.S. is headed over a cliff. Americans are living longer than ever and having fewer children. We are headed for a generation of skyrocketing medical bills, and unless we are going to float the old folks out to sea on ice floes or make Jack Kevorkian the secretary of health and human services, those bills are going to have to be paid.  <p> It isn't just health care, either. Social Security and other social-insurance programs assume that each generation will be larger than its predecessor and so able to pay for care for the elderly without undue burdens on the private and public sectors. Which just isn't true any longer. In 1955, the U.S. birth rate was 25 per 1,000. In 1993, it had declined to 15.5 per 1,000. As a consequence, the number of workers supporting each retired person has nose-dived. In 1955, there were 8.6 workers for each person receiving Social Security. By 1993, there were 3.2 workers per recipient. That ratio is projected to worsen as the century draws to a close.  <p> Then there's that other economic problem that Washington seems determined to ignore: the stagnation of wages for the American middle class. It is now 23 years since real weekly wages peaked in America. For a while, as more women joined the workforce, the increase in two-paycheck households kept family incomes rising even as individual incomes fell. Now family incomes are starting to suffer. And this is during an expansion. When the next recession comes and it will, in spite of all the stockbrokers and congressional flim flammers who want you to think that the good times will roll on forever the middle class will be standing in the path of a steamroller.   <p> Increasingly, talk about the budget deficit is to American politics what sand is to the proverbial ostrich: a comforting darkness into which one can plunge when the perils and pressures of the real world become too much to face. Over the years willful ignorance hasn't done much for the ostrich. It's unlikely to work much better for the American middle class.   <p> Research assistance contributed by Tomas Matza.  <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Legislation, Government, Economy, International Investing, Taxation, Employment
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
