		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Investors Beware</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/04-Investors Beware</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						April 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Cover Story  <p> INVESTORS BEWARE  <p> The thieves are back. The characters may be different and their crimes smaller (and therefore harder to detect), but there's little doubt that insider trading is once more an insidious force on Wall Street -- and the primary cause of those mysterious little blips that show up, time and again, in the price and trading volume of stocks prior to major corporate announcements. Though nothing less than the integrity of the market is at stake, the Securities and Exchange Commission acknowledges that it doesn't have the resources for keeping up with the crooks. Meanwhile, Congress has stripped investors of significant means of filing grievances and recovering losses, and is considering legislationthat looks even more ominous. If forewarned is forearmed, thebest protection for investors is to read the stories in this special section. <p>
KEYWORDS: Ethical Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
