<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/03-Budget of Lost Jobs</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Budget of Lost Jobs</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/03-Budget of Lost Jobs</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						March 1996
Worth magazine/Experts<p>BUDGET OF LOST JOBS
Balancing the budget could cost 29 million American jobs by 2002. Why isn't anyone worried?<p>By Walter Mead<p>Shuttered factories, deserted parking lots, rusting fences. I associate these sights with the decaying, low-tech factories of the rust belt__the steel mills of Pittsburgh and Bethlehem, for example, or the auto plants south of Detroit, all defeated in fierce international competition by the Japanese. <p>But on a recent trip to Los Angeles I saw huge empty high-tech factories baking in the sun. In the San Fernando Valley near the Burbank Airport, a Lockheed plant, grown large during the Cold War buildup of the 1980s, now stands idle.<p>That factory didn't succumb to more-efficient foreign competitors, and it wasn't left behind by a cost-cutting management eager to move jobs to the third world. Instead, it closed because of budget decisions made in Washington: Defense cutbacks that began in the late 1980s led to fewer orders to the factories that made the weapons of the Cold War.<p>It's important to think about the Lockheed plant and others like it, because the politicians in Washington are on the verge of another round of financial decisions that will ripple through local economies. The federal spending cuts projected by any of the seven-year budget proposals now under discussion dwarf the reductions in defense spending that devastated California in the early 1990s. So far, most of the debate about the effect of balancing the budget by 2002 has focused on such topics as the hope for lower interest rates and the probable increase in the number of children living in poverty. But the reductions in federal spending that will be written into any eventual budget agreement will change the nature of the U.S. economy. And we are doing nothing to prepare for the wrenching dislocations that will accompany that change.<p>Los Angeles County is a good place for understanding what the entire country faces in the next few years. Almost nobody thinks the world needs more weapons, and as taxpayers, most of us appreciate the savings that have slowly resulted from the end of the Cold War. But the defense cuts of the late 1980s sent the county's economy into a nosedive. According to Brad Williams of the Legislative Analysts' Office in Sacramento, federal procurement spending (that is, spending by the federal government to buy things versus the spending that results from, say, sending checks to people on Social Security) in Los Angeles County peaked in 1987 at an estimated $21 billion annually. By 1991, a recession year, procurement spending had dropped to $15.7 billion. <p>Regional economic analysts blame defense cutbacks for half of the jobs L.A. County lost in the 1990 recession, and the lingering effect of the cuts slowed the county's recovery from its worst recession since the Great Depression. Analysts in the region estimate that about 140,000 defense jobs were lost after the end of the Cold War__and took with them another 200,000 jobs in other industries. For example, without paychecks from defense workers to fuel the demand for housing, the construction industry went into a tailspin.
Fortunately, the Los Angeles economy has largely recovered. With an estimated 3,774,000 jobs at the end of 1995, Los Angeles County employment is now almost back to what it was before the collapse. Tourism, entertainment, international trade, and new small-business start-ups have taken up the slack.<p>Just in time to face a new round of federal spending cuts. As this column went to press, the president and congressional Republicans were still haggling over the final budget numbers, but estimates from the Congressional Budget Office show that the projected decreases will be far larger than the defense cuts of the early 1990s. If we apply the CBO's projections to Los Angeles County, total federal spending in 2002 will be about $9.3 billion less than under pre-budget-deal baseline projections__$4 billion more than the decline in annual defense spending between 1987 and 1991. The real cuts could be greater. For instance, because states are required to match a percentage of Medicaid funding, federal spending cuts in that program would lead to reductions in state aid as well. The total loss to the county economy could be as high as $12 billion.<p>Let's see what that means in terms of jobs. Unfortunately, it's hard to be precise about the relationship between federal budget cuts and jobs. Analysts who have studied the Los Angeles County defense cuts estimate that every billion dollars of spending cuts reduced employment by about 20,000 jobs. That figure is probably too low__it doesn't include jobs lost at out-of-state subcontractors. A study of Medicaid cuts in Massachusetts__which probably captured more of the effects of the cuts, since spending in health care is predominantly local__showed that about 50,000 jobs were lost for every billion-dollar cut in <p>federal spending. U.S. Department of Commerce figures for the California economy estimate that 60,000 jobs are lost for each billion-dollar reduction in federal spending. Since the point of this exercise isn't to predict employment levels in Los Angeles County but to illustrate the probable effects of the current budget, let's use a conservative figure of 40,000 jobs lost for each billion dollars in cuts.
Currently, Los Angeles County has about 3.77 million jobs. Before this latest round of budget cuts, economists projected an average annual employment increase of 2.1 percent, yielding a projected 4.4 million jobs by 2002. <p>Plug in the new numbers for federal spending in the county, and the 
situation changes dramatically. If the federal budget cuts go as planned and if the relationship between federal spending and jobs doesn't change, then by 2002 Los Angeles County will have only 3 million jobs__1.4 million fewer than currently anticipated and 770,000 fewer than exist today. Instead of growing 14 percent over the next seven years, employment could fall by as much as 20 percent. In other words, the budget cuts could wipe out all the economic growth__and then some__the county expects over the next
seven years. <p>Of course, L. A. County isn't the only region that will suffer from these cuts. Between 1950 and 1994, national employment grew at an annual rate of 1.16 percent; at the end of 1995 there were an estimated 124.5 million jobs nationwide. If we assume that this growth will continue through 2002, the economy will add 10.8 million jobs in the next seven years. <p>But that gain disappears if we consider the effect of budget cuts on the national economy. Projected national employment for 2002 falls from more than 135 million to 96 million. Instead of adding more than 10 million jobs in the next seven years, the economy could lose 29 million jobs. <p>Whose jobs are at stake? The next round of cuts will affect health 
care__in 2002, $102 billion (or 44 percent of the total planned decrease in federal spending from the current baseline) will come from Medicare and Medicaid. In Los Angeles County alone, that means $3.5 billion less in federal spending on health care that year. Cuts of this size will force the health-care industry into the kind of restructuring the aerospace industry faced. <p>In 1960, public and private health-care expenditures made up 5.3 percent of the gross domestic product. By 1993 they had reached 12.9 percent. <p>A major part of the government's looming budget crunch results from this growth and from the significant increase in the share of total health-care costs paid by the federal government__from 27 percent in 1990 to 30 percent in 1993. The federal bill for health care shot up from $186 billion in 1990 to $268 billion in 1993. 
Most commentators have rightfully been horror-struck by this growth. After all, health care is a cost for the government, most companies, and most households. The more money spent on health care, the less available for other goods and services. <p>But we need to look at the opposite side of the ledger, too. Health care doesn't figure in the national accounts only as a cost. It is also a source of income. Every dollar of health-care cost, whether paid by a private household, an insurance company, or government, is a dollar of income__to a doctor, a dental hygienist, or a private hospital corporation. <p>Health care has been one of the most important motors driving growth in the much-ballyhooed service economy. About 29 percent of all service jobs are in this field, and employment in health care is rising three times faster than all employment. And these are good, secure jobs. Average wages in health care are not only higher than for most service jobs__at about $12 an hour__but are rising more quickly.<p>Because health care is a non-cyclical industry__people need treatment during recessions as well as during expansions__a strong health-care industry plays an important role in keeping recessions short and relatively painless. In the recession year of 1991, national employment fell nine-tenths of a percent, but the health-care sector added 346,000 new jobs. In 1993, 20 percent of the nation's economic growth was attributable directly to growth in this field.
The deficit hawks who believe that nothing is more important than balancing the federal budget by 2002 argue that reducing federal spending will shift resources from the government to the private sector. This will drive down interest rates, encourage private capital formation, and lead to the creation of thousands of new jobs. In the long run, they argue, a balanced budget will produce more jobs than the cuts destroy. <p>Could happen. The Los Angeles County economy did, after all, bounce back from the earlier round of defense cuts. But enough has changed in the national economy since then that a repetition of that happy ending certainly shouldn't be assumed.<p>Los Angeles was pulled out of its long, deep recession largely because the rest of the country, following a short and shallow slump, recovered and entered a long expansion. Entertainment surpassed aerospace in the California economy during the 1990s because moviegoers and tourists in the rest of the country had money to spend.<p>The new cuts won't work that way. Neither Los Angeles County nor any other community can count on the rest of the country to help bail it out of a local slump; we'll all be in this together. 
Exports also helped free Los Angeles from its bind, and some experts expect that segment of the economy to help this time, too. Even if Americans are too broke to buy from one another, they argue, we can sell stuff abroad. <p>Unlikely. At the moment, all the major economies in the world are trying to cut their budget deficits. The European Union's Maastricht Treaty "encourages" budget-cutting programs almost as severe as ours. The Japanese Finance Ministry still wants to keep government spending down. Even China wants to slow its growth__and cut its budget deficit.<p>So here are the worst-case and best-case scenarios. In the worst, the deficit hawks are wrong. The budget cuts and such changes as a lower capital-gains tax rate don't produce a private-investment boom. Instead, the cuts devastate the sector of the service economy that has been the leader in providing good jobs for working people during the last decade. In the best case, the country as a whole follows the earlier example of Los Angeles County, and after some period of wrenching change__say, five years__job growth resumes. Of course, those jobs may require different skills, and many of the individuals who lose their jobs as a result of the budget cuts won't find new ones.<p>As I was picking up my rental car on my most recent trip to Los Angeles, two young men behind me were discussing their job prospects. Both were recent engineering graduates. 
"Aerospace has been hit hard," said the first. "A lot of companies have stopped hiring." <p>"Yeah," said the other, "but some of them have shifted into public transportation__you know, subway cars and things like that." 
So they have. At the Lockheed factory, one of the few areas of activity among the empty acres was in a building taken over by CALSTART, a private consortium attempting to use California's high-tech skills to design electric cars and other products to meet tough environmental standards. But the new round of budget and regulatory cuts is closing that route. Federal funding for mass transit will shrink in the new budget, and money for other defense-conversion projects is also on the chopping block.<p>I would be one of the last people to say that we have done an adequate job of helping workers displaced by defense cuts find new jobs. Now, however, when the change in the national budget is far more sweeping, we're doing even less. In fact, we're not even talking about the problem.<p>Walter Mead is the Presidential Fellow at the World Policy Institute at the New School. Research assistance by Tomas Matza.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Government Adgency, International Investing, Employment, Insurance Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
