	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/02-The Two Trillion Dollar Mistake</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b> </b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/02-The Two Trillion Dollar Mistake</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
There's a simple reason the U.S. is fighting over a budget deficit rather than enjoying a surplus:  We won the Cold War 15 years ago and didn't even realize it.  New evidence suggests that the defense buildup of the 1980s was the biggest financial blunder ever.<p>By Walter Russell Mead<p>"Gorbachev?" spits anatoly Gribkov, retired four-star Soviet general and former chief of staff of the Warsaw Pact. "A traitor. Stalin was the greatest leader we ever had." <p>The ornamental fountain tinkles beneath the Tiffany ceiling as the harpist plays in the breakfast room of Moscow's Metropol Hotel. It was here that Rasputin held his orgies in the waning years of czarist rule and that defecting Western spies routinely got their first taste of Soviet luxury. Now foreign businessmen flock to this landmark as they chase profits in the Wild East atmosphere of the Russian capital. That doesn't delight Gribkov. <p>"You Americans are disgusting," he says. "You think everything can be solved by money." <p>For Gribkov--lean, fit, and bitter at 76--the United States remains an evil foe. "It's not enough for two presidents to meet and speak kind words to end the Cold War," he says. "Even if they burn me at the stake, I will say it: Our enemy remains in the West." <p>But from beneath his chestful of decorations, Gribkov also has an extraordinary tale to tell--one with significant implications for the West. It focuses on a moment in 1981 when the highest levels of the Soviet leadership faced the possibility of losing Poland--and the entire Soviet empire in Eastern Europe.<p>The Polish crisis had erupted with a strike in the Gdansk shipyards in August 1980. The strike spread, led by a 36-year-old electrician named Lech Walesa, and the workers organized Solidarity, an independent trade union. Solidarity rapidly became a national movement.<p>The Soviet authorities quickly realized they had a serious problem. In October 1980, USSR foreign minister Andrei Gromyko warned his colleagues in the politburo that "we simply cannot and must not lose Poland." Labor unrest began to spread beyond Poland into the other satellites and finally into the Soviet Union itself. Ukraine and the Baltic states became hotbeds of discontent. By December 1981 the Soviet politburo was actively debating an invasion of Poland.<p>"At the time," Gribkov says, "I was chief of staff of the Warsaw Pact forces around Poland. Minister Ustinov [Dmitri Ustinov, Soviet defense minister under Leonid Brezhnev] called a group of leading military personnel to his office and asked us our recommendations. There was some discussion, but in the end we agreed that 녎ne Afghanistan is enough for us.' In the opinion of the military, there should not be an invasion." <p>Ustinov, Gribkov says, then went off to a meeting of the politburo. Two hours later, Gribkov was in his apartment when the telephone rang. "It was Ustinov," he says. "He told me, 넶he comrades in the politburo have accepted your recommendation.'" Even if Solidarity took power, there would be no Soviet invasion of Poland. The cost of defending Communism in Europe was just too high. <p>The significance of these events, as reported by Gribkov, is profound, for they strongly suggest that the Soviet Union effectively lost the Cold War far earlier than is widely believed in the West.<p>It wasn't until 1989 that the Berlin Wall fell and that U.S. political leaders and Western intelligence services finally abandoned their view that the Soviet Union was still on the march--and even, in the eyes of many, winning the Cold War. Ronald Reagan, continuing a buildup that had begun under Jimmy Carter, spent billions to counter what was actually a steadily diminishing Soviet threat. During the years after the Polish crisis, annual U.S. defense spending (in constant 1987 dollars) rose from $194 billion in 1981 to $285 billion in 1989.<p>Thus, if Gribkov is to be believed, the U.S. foreign policy establishment committed the biggest financial blunder in the history of the globe. Forget the savings and loan bailout and the waste in Medicare and Medicaid--these are dwarfed by the $1.84 trillion U.S. taxpayers spent to beat a foe ready to throw in the towel. If the effects of years of unnecessary military spending could somehow be subtracted, our federal budget today (for fiscal 1995) would show an $11 billion surplus as opposed to a deficit of almost $164 billion. <p>But is Gribkov believable? Generals retire and become cranky and forgetful. They embellish their reminiscences to dazzle foreign journalists. But two things make Gribkov credible. We know that he was in a position to hear firsthand the thinking of the top members of the Soviet leadership, and the documentary evidence bears out his account.<p>Anatoly Gribkov's life journey--from the collective-farm fields of Russia to the highest councils of the Kremlin--reads like the boy-meets-tractor idyll so beloved by Soviet propagandists. One of ten children, the young Anatoly was, by age six, riding horses with his father in the fields near Dukhovoe, a Russian village 350 miles south of Moscow. From there it was a short jump to driving Soviet tractors and then army tanks at the Stalin Armed Tank Institute.<p>Gribkov's star rose as the Red Army flexed its muscles on an increasingly global stage. He commanded tank troops in Stalin's 1939 invasion of Finland and then moved on to Latvia to help prepare Stalin's takeover of the Baltic republic. When Hitler invaded the Soviet Union in 1941, Gribkov again saw heavy action. He was promoted to the General Staff in 1944. <p>Following Hitler's defeat, Gribkov went to the front lines of the Cold War, first in Cuba during the missile crisis, where he shared responsibility for planning Soviet strategy, and then in Eastern Europe, where he served as chief of staff of the Joint Armed Forces of the Warsaw Pact alliance. <p>He wasn't doing badly on the political front, either. In 1976 he became a candidate member of the Central Committee of the Communist Party of the Soviet Union, and was a deputy at the eighth and ninth convocations of the Supreme Soviet. By the time of the Solidarity crisis, Gribkov had become a key member of the Soviet Union's leadership. Logically, he would have been present at the meetings he claims to have attended.<p>THE KREMLIN'S SECRET FILES SUPPORT GRIBKOV<p>Independent documentary evidence now emerging from Soviet archives backs up Gribkov's story. Mark Kramer of Harvard recently translated declassified top secret Soviet minutes of the December 10, 1981, politburo session, in which the option of invading Poland with Warsaw Pact forces had been debated and rejected. His work, published in the Woodrow Wilson International Center for Scholars' Cold War International History Project Bulletin, confirms Gribkov's statements about Soviet intentions.<p>By the December 1981 meeting, the Polish crisis was moving toward a climax. Soviet policy throughout the crisis had been clear. The Soviets bitterly opposed Solidarity, and they wanted it crushed--by Polish forces. But the Polish Communists understood that a crackdown would mean the destruction of their party. Even senior party members had enthusiastically joined Solidarity, and the regular army troops--young draftees--could not be trusted to obey orders for a crackdown. <p>For more than a year, the Soviets and their closest Polish collaborators conducted psychological warfare against Solidarity and the West while preparing a new secret police force that would be capable of imposing martial law without Polish or Soviet troops. Constant military maneuvers by Warsaw Pact forces kept Western and Polish attention focused on the regular military.<p>By the night of December 10, the Soviet politburo was in agony. Would Polish leader Wojciech Jaruzelski ever impose martial law? Would he succeed if he did? If the Polish Communists lost control, should Soviet troops invade?<p>The consequences of losing Poland to Solidarity were immense. Soviet troops in East Germany would be cut off. The unpopular regime in Czechoslovakia, installed by Soviet tanks in 1968, would totter. The Hungarians would undoubtedly use the chance to edge closer to the West. Yuri Andropov, who later succeeded Leonid Brezhnev as general secretary of the Soviet Communist Party, expressed the politburo's rattled, defensive mood at the December meeting. If Poland falls to Solidarity, Andropov said, the capitalist countries would step up their assault on the Soviet Union itself. "We must be concerned above all with our own country and about the strengthening of the Soviet Union," he declared.<p>But if invasion was the ultimate sanction, the Soviets weren't eager to use it. An invasion by Soviet troops--even if accompanied by other Warsaw Pact nations--would set off a worldwide outcry. The USSR's 1979 invasion of Afghanistan had already damaged Soviet prestige and isolated it politically; a second invasion would be a disaster. <p>Not just a political disaster, either. By 1980, the Soviet economy already showed the strains that would bring it crashing down at the end of the decade. The Soviet leadership depended on trade with the West for the goods and technology necessary to satisfy its restive consumers. An invasion of Poland would have shocked Germany and unified Western Europe behind Ronald Reagan's tough anti-Soviet line. The economic costs made the Soviets shudder. <p>Finally, there was the military problem. Polish officers--even loyal Communists--told their Soviet counterparts that Polish troops would resist and that any invasion of Poland would mean a bloody, drawn-out battle likely to degenerate into a protracted period of military and economic guerrilla warfare.<p>Faced with these consequences, Kramer's translation makes clear, the politburo blinked. Andropov was blunt: "We don't intend to introduce troops into Poland.... I don't know how things will turn out in Poland, but even if Poland falls under the control of Solidarity, that's the way it will be." <p>After Defense Minister Ustinov weighed in, chief ideologist Mikhail Suslov spoke. Suslov was widely regarded in the U.S. and USSR as a hard-liner, a guardian of Communist Party orthodoxy. "If troops are introduced, that will mean a catastrophe," he said. "I think we have reached a unanimous view here on this matter, and there can be no consideration at all of introducing troops."<p>Was the politburo really ready to "let Poland be Poland" in 1981? "I had a hard time believing it myself," says Kramer. "As a conservative, I have always been suspicious of Soviet intentions. But the documentary record is unambiguous and clear, and it supports the testimony of people like Gribkov." <p>THE U.S. MISSED ALL THE SIGNS<p>During the Polish crisis, the United States government completely misunderstood Soviet thinking. Jimmy Carter's national-security adviser, Zbigniew Brzezinski, reports in his memoir, for example, that the CIA issued a warning that an invasion was imminent. <p>"We were wrong about that," former CIA director Admiral Stansfield Turner now says. But he quickly adds that the CIA didn't miss every trick on his watch: "We were right about Afghanistan." Turner is also rightly proud of the CIA's success at that time in penetrating the Polish military establishment. A senior Polish official provided the U.S. with Gribkov's contingency plans for a Warsaw Pact invasion. At no time, however, did the Washington defense establishment focus on the real threat: that special Polish security forces were preparing to squash Solidarity from within. <p>This blindness had been decades in the making. By 1981 there was a consensus among much of the U.S. defense and foreign policy establishments that the Soviet Union was winning the Cold War. Western estimates of Soviet economic capabilities were fundamentally flawed. As late as the mid-1980s, the CIA believed that the Soviet Union and its Warsaw Pact allies were economically strong. In fact, the CIA estimated in 1981 that the Soviet economy was growing faster than that of the U.S. or Western Europe.<p>The CIA wasn't alone. In his 1980 book, The Real War, Richard Nixon warned that by the middle of the 1980s "the Soviet Union will be number one; the United States will be number two." "The Kremlin leaders," he wrote, "want the world. And they are rapidly moving into position to get what they want."<p>The Committee on the Present Danger, a foreign policy group whose membership list reads like a who's who of the Reagan administration, issued study after study warning that the Soviet Union was becoming the strongest power in the world. "Is America Becoming Number 2?" a CPD study asked in 1978. The answer was yes. In 1980 the CPD announced that the United States "no longer has the capacity to protect its interests and American citizens abroad." Blaming the Iranian hostage crisis on Soviet machinations, the CPD saw the world rushing toward general war as a result of Soviet strength and American weakness.<p>By 1982, despite the military buildup that had begun under Carter and accelerated under Reagan, the CPD still believed that the U.S. was a distinct number two. A report issued in June 1982 states, "The Soviets clearly believe that a major shift in the correlation of world forces in their favor has already occurred.... The Soviets now enjoy general military superiority over the West. The Soviets know they do, and they believe the United States also knows it." <p>The politburo might have been groaning with despair as it contemplated its options in Poland, but much of the U.S. leadership thought the USSR was on a roll. In fact, so pervasive was this view that questioning it could endanger a career. "You didn't win any points in the foreign policy debate by arguing that the Soviet Union wasn't on the march," says Gary Sick, a member of Jimmy Carter's National Security Council. Sick, who was responsible for NSC policy on Iran and the Persian Gulf following the Soviet invasion of Afghanistan, says that it was almost impossible to fight the hard-line consensus view of U.S. officials that the Soviet invasion was part of a calculated strategy to acquire ports on the gulf and dominate Middle Eastern oil.<p>"It was the same story in Iran," says Sick. "There were immense pressures to see an active, omnipotent Soviet hand in the rise of Khomeini. Never mind that Khomeini was a fanatical anti-Communist; you didn't win any points in Washington by arguing that this wasn't part of a grand Soviet plan." <p>THE SOVIET MILITARY DECLINE<p>At the height of the Cold War, Leonid Brezhnev and Richard Nixon squared off over control of a thermostat in the Western White House, Victor Sukhodrev, Brezhnev's official interpreter, tells me. Both had drunk heavily during dinner. Afterward, Nixon walked Brezhnev to his bedroom and showed him how to twist the dial to set the room temperature. "Turn it this way," Nixon said. <p>"No," Brezhnev insisted, and started to turn the dial the other way. <p>Nixon shoved Brezhnev's hand away and twisted the dial back. <p>Brezhnev shouldered Nixon, and the confrontation escalated. <p>"I was afraid they would knock the thermostat off the wall," says Sukhodrev.<p>By 1981 the Soviets may still have wanted to shoulder the U.S. aside. The Committee on the Present Danger may have even been right about Soviet desire to dominate the world. But no one thought to question the Soviet Union's ability to project military power beyond its borders.<p>Today's Russia is too weak to impose its will on its own territory. Its military has no coherent use-of-force doctrine, no plan to defend its territories, and no money to pay its utility bills.<p>Even Gribkov speaks with contempt and dismay about the current state of the Russian armed forces. "On the first day of the Chechen War," Gribkov says, "Dudayev [the Chechen leader] could have bombed Moscow. We made him a present of those planes. Our forces left them behind for him." <p>This disintegration didn't happen overnight. By 1981 there were clear signs of a breakdown in the Soviet military that should have led to a re-examination of the nature of the Soviet threat. The corruption and apathy that had spread throughout the Soviet Union under Brehznev's long reign did not spare the military. Units were under strength, and pilfering was so rampant that jets couldn't fly and tanks wouldn't roll. Morale was so low that officers hesitated to take their troops into battle. Ethnic tensions divided some units into warring camps. Draftees from central Asia formed gangs to exploit younger Slavic conscripts. The resulting poor combat and supply performances in the Afghanistan War shocked many Soviet officers and contributed to the caution with which they reacted to the Polish crisis. Many of those same facts were available in the West, but they didn't change Western estimates of Soviet military capability until later in the 1980s. By 1981 much of the Soviet Union's military strength existed only on paper.	<p>THE PERSISTENCE OF VISION<p>Perhaps it is too much to expect that in 1981 U.S. leaders and the analysts at the CIA could have abandoned a view of the world with which they had grown up. Policies and the worldviews that sustain them take on lives of their own. By 1981, U.S. leaders and citizens had spent 35 years interpreting the world through the lens of the Cold War. It would have taken extraordinary intellectual courage to abandon that mooring and set out on uncharted seas with only easily misinterpreted facts for a guide.<p>But changing policy in 1981 would not have required abandoning containment--the policy that had governed U.S. behavior toward the Soviet Union since the late 1940s--or scrapping a single U.S. warhead or shaving a single dollar off the defense budget. It wouldn't have even required U.S. leaders and intelligence officials to believe that the Soviet Union was prepared to surrender Poland. All it would have required was an ability to imagine an alternative policy and then take some measured risks to explore it. <p>What could the U.S. have done? If we had understood the Kremlin's position in 1980 and 1981, our policy would have been both tougher and softer than it actually was. On the one hand, we would have taken a much more aggressive position with Solidarity, and encouraged Lech Walesa--a man who had always been among the most moderate and compromise-oriented figures in the Solidarity leadership--to make a serious bid for national power. We would obviously have paid less attention to Gribkov's military bluff and worked much harder to help Solidarity develop a strategy against the special Polish security forces that ultimately crushed the trade-union movement. We might well have launched a tougher diplomatic and economic offensive against Jaruzelski's regime, knowing that the Soviets were unwilling to back it up with armed force. <p>On the other hand, our diplomacy with the Soviets would have been more active and forthcoming. If the Soviets allowed Solidarity to take power, we would have promised economic support for both Poland and Moscow. We would have offered to ensure that Solidarity agree to a defense treaty protecting Soviet defense interests--transit rights for troops based in East Germany, for example--and worked with the Soviet authorities and Solidarity to stabilize the situation. <p>CALCULATING THE COSTS<p>The Poles paid a price for the U.S.'s inability to see an alternative to the policies pursued since 1945. But so did U.S. taxpayers. The failure of the U.S. foreign policy establishment to understand that containment was working under the Carter and Reagan administrations was the costliest blunder in history--a blunder whose consequences are still with us. <p>Very much with us. The mistaken Carter-Reagan defense buildup has cost American taxpayers $1.84 trillion since 1981. Misguided foreign-policy-makers have wasted more money than all the federal bureaucrats and welfare moms put together. <p>Using 1976 dollars, the United States spent $89.6 billion (or $172.6 billion in constant 1987 dollars) on defense in 1976--the last year of the Ford administration. The Vietnam War was over, and the United States had cut spending back to a "normal" Cold War level. All the evidence we have now tells us that this was enough. <p>Unfortunately, defense spending didn't stay at that level. As hysteria mounted in U.S. policy circles about the Soviet threat, defense spending soared. By 1981, it had climbed (still in 1987 dollars) to $194.2 billion, and during the next decade--as the Soviet Union moved toward collapse--the defense budget skyrocketed past $281.9 billion in 1988 to peak at $284.8 in 1989, the year the Berlin Wall crumbled. <p>The unnecessary costs of that decade-long buildup have to be measured in two ways. First, there's the cumulative addition to the national debt. Let's say that the defense budget had hit $194.2 billion in 1981 and then, instead of rising until the fall of the Berlin Wall, had declined to a normal Cold War level--the $173 billion spent on defense in 1976--over the next two years. If Congress had held the defense budget constant until 1989 and then applied the cuts that it historically did after the fall of the Berlin Wall, the U.S. national debt would be $1.84 trillion smaller today.<p>Second, efforts after the fall of the Berlin Wall to reduce defense spending started with a defense budget bloated by the military buildup of the 1980s. Since the grotesque peak in 1989, the defense budget has dropped. And yet today, with no Cold War and no enemy, the U.S. is spending $31 billion more in constant dollars on defense than it did in 1976. If we had maintained the 1976 defense budget until 1989, and then cut from that level, in 1995 dollars the fiscal 1995 defense budget would be $164.6 billion rather than $271.6 billion--a savings of $107 billion. Add to that the additional $68.1 billion in interest costs on the debt from the excess spending of past years, and the fiscal 1995 federal deficit of $164 billion becomes a surplus of $11 billion. <p>THE WILL TO BELIEVE<p>In trying to understand how the American foreign policy establishment could have been so misguided for so long, it is tempting to look for scapegoats. But when great nations make great mistakes--and, especially, when they persist in these mistakes for many years--the responsibility rarely belongs only to a handful of people. There have to be reasons the Cold Warriors were so persuasive. <p>In 1981 the United States wasn't ready--psychologically or politically--for the Cold War to end. We had too much invested in the idea of an external enemy, Ronald Reagan's evil empire. The contrast with the Soviet Union defined us and our role in the world.<p>Unfortunately, we still haven't made the transition to a post섺old War view of the world. Gribkov is right. On our side at least, the Cold War continues. The United States is still mindlessly working to contain Russia, to freeze it out of Europe, and to keep it weak. And just as Cold War blinders cost the U.S. billions in the 1980s, this persistent belief in a global war against the Russian enemy threatens to cost us dearly as this century draws to a close.<p>To "defend" ourselves against this poor, distracted country, we are expanding NATO eastward and still maintaining the highest military spending of any nation in the world. NATO and the European Union are the two institutions that will shape Europe's future--we are determined to keep Russia out of NATO, and we support Western Europe's determination to keep Russia out of the E.U. <p>Fifteen years ago, American diplomats misread the Soviet Union's capabilities and intentions. Today they are misreading the balance of power in the world, acting as if the chief threat to American interests were Russia's excessive strength. In fact, it is Russia's extraordinary weakness that poses the greatest problem for the U.S. The disappearance of Russia from the balance of power in the Far East and the power vacuum that Russia's weakness creates in central Asia are much more important to the United States and dangerous to our interests than anything that could possibly happen in Eastern Europe.<p>Today the Russian military presence in eastern Siberia is a hollow shell. When I visited Vladivostok a couple of years ago, the fleet was rusting at the docks, and sailors told me that the ships could not sail for lack of fuel.<p>This amounts to a revolution in world affairs, one that has already produced unpleasant results for the United States. For the first time since the Opium War of the 1840s, China faces no superior forces anywhere on its frontiers. Since Russian power collapsed, China has become much more truculent in its dealings with the United States--and for good reason. With Russia out of the picture, China no longer has military reasons to cultivate good relations with the U.S.<p>That's not all. The enormous natural resources of Russia's thinly populated Far East are a constant temptation to militarists in China and Japan. During the civil war that followed the Bolshevik Revolution, Japan sent tens of thousands of troops into Siberia and, for a short time, occupied Siberia as far west as Lake Baikal. Control over the oil, gold, diamonds, timber, and other resources of eastern Russia would give Japan the self-confidence and strength it now lacks to become once again an independent and potentially dangerous Great Power in the Pacific. <p>Many Chinese, on the other hand, regard much of Russia's territory in the Far East as rightfully theirs. Russia gained Vladivostok and other strategic territories as a result of the treaties that Chinese leaders routinely denounce as "unequal." Chinese maps still show Chinese place names for the territories lost to the czars in the 19th century. Illegal immigrants from China are now entering lightly patrolled Russian territory along the 1,700-mile boundary between the two countries even as Russians retreat from Russian Asia to the European heartland, where economic conditions are better.<p>In central Asia a similar dynamic is at work. The central Asian countries are rich in oil and natural gas. Potentially, they are an alternative source to the Middle East for these strategic resources. Yet as Russian power receded in central Asia with the breakup of the Soviet Union, chaos broke out. Central Asia's governments are a long way from providing the legal and political stability that foreign investors need. Islamic fundamentalism poses a threat here and elsewhere in the region. In the longer term, Russia and China may compete for influence and control.<p>The United States needs Russia to be stronger than it is today. We do not want upheaval or change in Asia. This makes us, like it or not, allies of Russia in this part of the world. A Russian recovery will help us; Russia's continued weakness puts us in danger.<p>Current U.S. foreign policy, while waving a welcoming flag of rhetoric, continues to treat Russia as the enemy. We worry about containment when Russia is too weak to even subdue the rebels on its own border. Aid to Russia is stalled in Congress, held up by those who object to giving comfort to the enemy. Fifteen years after it could have ended, five years after it was proclaimed to have ended, the Cold War--as senseless and expensive as ever--continues.	<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
