	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/01-Goodbye, Glass-Steagall</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Goodbye, Glass-Steagall</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/01-Goodbye, Glass-Steagall</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						December/January 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Experts  <p> GOODBYE, GLASS-STEAGALL  <p> By James K. Glassman  <p> During the stock market crash of 1929, 4,000 banks failed as depositors fought to reach teller windows before the money ran out and their savings disappeared forever. Four years later, Congress passed the Glass-Steagall Act to ensure that such a tragedy would never be repeated.  <p> In the belief that the untrammeled pursuit of profits had betrayed the trust of individual Americans, Congress forced bankers to choose between the distinct businesses of commercial banking and investment banking. Commercial banks, such as Bank of America, would take deposits and make personal and small-business loans. The government agreed to insure deposits up to $2,500 ($100,000 today). Investment banks, such as <a name="NYSE:MER"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10990"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Merrill Lynch</b></a>, would underwrite and trade securities and issue large-scale corporate debt.  <p> A major goal of the legislation was that money placed with commercial banks would be invested conservatively, leaving investment banks to be more aggressive. And in fact, since the bill's passage, banking in the U.S. has been a relatively sound activity--despite inflation, oil embargoes, huge federal deficits, and poor oversight.Why then is Congress trying to repeal Glass-Steagall? After all,a rules change and lax regulation led to the savings & loan crisis.  <p> The reason is that most economists and much of the financial industry believe that the law raises consumers' costs, limits their returns, and puts the U.S. at a competitive disadvantage, since nearly all other nations permit commercial and investment banking under a single roof. In the words of Alan Greenspan, chairman of the Federal Reserve Board, the banking system denies Americans "lower prices, increased access, and higher-quality services."  <p>    The Senate has voted to lift Glass-Steagall's restrictions twice before, in 1988 and 1991, but the House didn't go along--in part because of the opposition of Democrat John Dingell, then chairman of the Energy and Commerce Committee. Dingell's father, elected to Congress in 1932, was a fervent New Dealer, and for Dingell, the devastation of the Depression remains a vivid memory.  <p>    But the Republicans are in power now, and they've shifted authority for Glass-Steagall to the Banking Committee, headed by Republican James Leach. Leach, along with many of his colleagues, quarrels with the view that banking practices caused the Depression. "Later historical review," Leach says, "has raised questions" as to whether the real problem in the 1930s was that banks bought and sold risky stocks.   <p>    George G. Benston's 1990 book, The Separation of Commercial and Investment Banking: The Glass-Steagall Act Revisited and Reconsidered, has changed a lot of minds on the Hill. Benston, a banking scholar at Emory University, studied the original congressional hearings and concluded: "The record does not support the belief that the pre-Glass-Steagall period was one of abuses and conflicts of interest on the part of banks involved with securities transactions." <p> Leach buys this analysis. "It's harder and harder to justify arbitrary barriers, and it's hard to deny the benefits that accrue from greater competition," he says. He has proposed a bill that would loosen Glass-Steagall's restrictions but impose a degree of separation between financial institutions. Anyone wishing to operate commercial and investment banks would have to do so through a holding company. The entities would be kept apart by legal fire walls and overseen by separate regulators. <p> Still, Leach does worry about financial institutions getting too powerful. This also worries Kenneth Guenther, executive vice president of the Independent Bankers Association of America, a group of 5,500 small banks who oppose the repeal of Glass-Steagall, but not the Leach compromise bill. Last year, Guenther points out, restrictions on interstate banking were lifted, and a series of mergers quickly ushered in an era of $300 billon banks. With the demise of Glass-Steagall, "we're looking at a world of half-trillion-dollarinstitutions," he says. And that means "systemic risk." The government can't let such institutions fail--the bailout would be enormous. Also, he says, "concentrated markets lead to higher prices and poorer service."  <p> Not all in Congress are content with Leach's moderate approach. Representative Richard Baker, who chairs a key banking subcommittee, believes a telecommunications revolution will soon transform banking, whether Congress likes it or not. "The trigger has been pulled," he says. "A bullet has been fired." Banking is coming to the Internet, he says, and companies like <a name="NASD:MSFT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14120"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Microsoft</b></a> and <a name="NASD:INTU"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=16001"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Intuit</b></a>  will figure out a way to electronically capture deposits, make loans, and sell securities. Baker, who is sponsoring a more thorough going deregulatory bill than Leach's, notes that banks have lost market share and profits as investment firms and nonbanks have moved into corporate and consumer lending, credit cards, and money market funds.  <p>    In response, banks are forming alliances with rival institutions. Merrill Lynch, Dean Witter, and Prudential are affiliated with banks that sell stocks and bonds, and the American Bankers Association reports that 41 bank holding companies operate "subsidiaries which underwrite and deal in securities."  <p> The fact is that since Glass-Steagall, the position of banks has eroded. In 1933, banks and S&Ls held about 75 percent of all financial-sector assets. Today, that figure is less than 40 percent. Lending by banks accounted for 65 percent of all short-term borrowing by U.S. corporations in 1970, but by 1992, with the rise of commercial paper, the figure was 36 percent.  <p> Advocates of Glass-Steagall reform say this has forced banks into riskier ventures to maintain their profits. "Currency, derivatives, options, swaps--all that can be done by commercial banks," says Ralph C. Bryant, an economist with the Brookings Institution in Washington. "We constrained banks through a set of rules that forced them to take unwarranted risks," says Baker. "It is a terrible irony."   <p> The fiercest opponents to change aren't bankers or brokers but insurance agents, who fear that the demise of Glass-Steagall will ultimately allow banks to sell insurance. Currently, with minor exceptions, they can't. "The insurance agents are fighting the hardest because they have the most to lose--their entire livelihoods," says a securities-industry player.  <p> "With that FDIC logo in the window, banks would have a major marketing advantage," says Robert A. Rusbuldt, a lobbyist for the Independent Insurance Agents of America. The insurance industry has enormous clout in Congress and, as Baker puts it, "extreme political skills." Leach knows this, and so far at least, he's protected insurers from banking competition.   <p> The third key player in the Glass-Steagall legislative drama is Senator Alfonse D'Amato, chairman of the Senate Banking Committee. D'Amato, whose state of New York is home to the nation's largest securities firms, is inclined toward reform, but Capitol Hill insiders say that the senator, who heads the 1996 campaign organization for Senate Republicans, is in no hurry, as banking reform is a golden goose of campaign donations from the three industries whose future is up in the air. D'Amato has said he won't schedule hearings on Glass-Steagall until the House passes its bill. That means repeal or reform won't occur before mid-1996, if then. <p> After that, a single, well-capitalized institution may handle your checking and savings accounts, mortgages, consumer loans, credit cards, stock trading, mutual funds, insurance, and retirement accounts. Reform may also lead to closer, more expert scrutiny of both banking and securities practices.   <p> Still, it's ominous that the issue of safety is being treated with such indifference. Has everyone forgotten why Representatives Carter Glass of Virginia and Henry Steagall of Alabama sponsored the law in the first place?   <p> James K. Glassman is a columnist for the Washington Post and the host of Capital Gang Sunday on CNN and Technopolitics on PBS.  <p>
KEYWORDS: Mutual Funds, Banking Industry, Government

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
