<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/01S-How Votes Can Steer Market</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>How Votes Can Steer the Market</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/01S-How Votes Can Steer Market</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						January 1996--Special Issue <p>Worth magazine/Features  <p> HOW VOTES CAN STEER THE MARKET <p>Like it or not, your investments involve you in Presidential politics. Here's what history says this could mean in 1996. <p> By Pam Black   <p> Want to wager on the 1996 presidential election? You can phone a London bookie. Or you can purchase a Bill Clinton or Bob Dole futures contract on the Iowa Political Market an Internet trading arena operated by the University of Iowa. Contracts on a Dole victory at the Republican convention recently were trading onthe IPM at a price of 41.6 cents each. If Dole gets the nod, these contracts would each pay a dollar meaning a profit of $702 for someone   <p>who invests the maximum $500 that the IPM allows.   <p> The academics and traders who make up this market were better than the opinion polls at predicting the outcomes for the 1988 and 1992 elections. Right now, prices slightly favor a Republican victory in November. A Republican contract sells for 47 cents vs. a Clinton future priced at 44.3 cents.  <p> Of course, simply being in the stock and bond markets at all is another way that investors bet intentionally or not on the outcome of the election. November's results certainly will have an important impact, for better or worse, on the direction of the markets, and therefore on every investor's portfolio.  <p> In 1996, the state of the economy, the rightward shift of politicians and the electorate, the lack of a clear leader among the Republican presidential hopefuls, and President Clinton's strategy to win reelection by running against the Republican Congress will all help determine how the markets react. History reveals certain time-honored patterns: The market and asset classes perform differently depending on which party is in power.  <p> The old saw is true: The markets do like Republicans, with their penchant for fiscal restraint, more than Democrats. But this may not be as important as many investors believe. Since 1900, the market has risen 11 out of 13 times in the six months following a Republican victory. Over the same period it has risen 5 of11 times after Democrats won, says Jim Bianco, director of research at Arbor Trading Group, a brokerage firm in Barrington, Illinois. That adds up to a clear edge for Republicans in average performance the market climbed 7.64 percent on average in the six months following their victories and only 0.39 percent following Democratic wins. But while the market climbed less frequently following Democratic triumphs, when it did, it rose further. The average gain in the five positive Democratic years was 11.57 percent, compared with 9.97 percent on average for Republicans.  <p> With this in mind, Gerald Hobbs and William Riley, researchers at West Virginia University, looked for the best short-term strategies for investing in Republican and Democratic victories. Using data from 1900 through 1976, they found that for the ten elections won by Republicans, the best tactic was to buy stocks 39 days before the election then sell 27 days after, for an average return of 7.3 percent. When Democrats were victorious, the ideal approach combined buying stocks 49 days before the election, selling them two days after the polls closed, and then shorting the market. Selling the shorts after waiting another 42 days resulted in an average total return of 5 percent.   <p> Measured over a longer time horizon, the Democrats win. During the past 48 years that a Democrat has been in the White House, the stock market has logged an average annual return of 13.2 percent, versus only 7.6 percent annually during the 62 years of Republican presidents, according to the Institute for Econometric Research. The margin of victory results primarily from the Hoover years of the Great Depression. Adjusting to remove the Hoover effect and the strong rebound under Roosevelt (1933-1936) brings the two parties neck and neck. The average stock market returnis then 9.6 percent for Democrats versus 10.7 percent for the Republicans.   <p> The last half of the four-year presidential term regardless of the party in charge tends to be better for the stock market than the first half. On average, the Standard & Poor's 500 Index has been nearly flat during years one and two of the term, logging 4 percent and 0 percent, respectively. But the third year has produced an average gain of 15 percent and the fourth year again of 10 percent, according to Tom McClellan, editor of The McClellan Market Report in Glendale, California. Indeed, the market has never lost money during the last seven months of an election year by the measure of Yale Hirsch, editor of the Stock Market Almanac in Old Tappan, New Jersey.  <p> That actually shouldn't be much of a surprise. Presidents always attempt to dispense the bitter pills of rising taxes and interest-rate hikes early in their terms so that the economy is humming by reelection time. Almost no party has kept office when an election year has been accompanied by a recession. From June 1959 to February1960, for example, the Federal Reserve raised interest rates to fight inflation. This helped drive the economy into recession in 1960. Eisenhower's designated heir, Vice President Richard Nixon, lost a tight race to John F. Kennedy. In 1980, double-digit inflation and a recession not to mention the Iranian hostage crisis knocked Jimmy Carter out of the White House. Although George Bush may have engineered a recovery for his last year in office, the public neither felt it nor believed it. "The economy had been growing since March of 1991, and yet surveys showed people thought we were in a recession or a depression," says Ray Worseck, chief economist at brokerage firm A.G. Edwards &Sons. Investors should assume Bill Clinton knows this history. Of course, so does the Republican Congress.  <p> This pattern doesn't play out in precisely the same way for Republican and Democratic administrations, or for the stock and bond markets. Fiscal restraint early in a presidential term often leads to a down market the following year and this rough patch is likely to be slightly earlier and worse under Republicans, possibly because the party of fiscal conservatism pulls in the economic reins a bit more tightly. That may also explain why the strongest market performances tend to arrive more quickly for Democratic administrations in the third year than for Republicans. The bond market, however, shows an entirely different cycle, thriving in the early belt-tightening years of the cycle and ailing in the growth-oriented second half, says Arbor Trading'sBianco.  <p> Distinctly different asset classes flourish under each party. Small-capitalization stocks tend to fare better under Democrats, while bonds and cash do better under Republicans, according to a study by Frank Russell Co., an investment-research firm in Tacoma, Washington. Although small-cap stocks follow the election-year cycle, returning more in the last two years of a term than the first two, their late-cycle performance soars during Democratic administrations. From 1929 to 1992, small-cap stocks returned an average of 24.9 percent in the last two years of a Democratic presidential cycle, versus 10.8 percent for Republicans. Fortuitous timing, rather than policy differences, may explain the gap."Democrats often come into office right about the time the economy is recovering from a downturn," says Claudia Mott, director ofsmall-cap research at Prudential Securities. "And small companies lead" the market into and out of recessions.  <p> Based on these findings, Frank Russell researchers tested an investment strategy of simultaneously switching asset classes with changes in party control of the White House. They invested a theoretical dollar in small-cap stocks during Democratic terms and switched to large-cap stocks when Republicans held office. The results: From 1942 to 1993, an investment of one dollar grew to $2,266. That compares with just $289 if the same dollar had been invested only in large caps or $1,066 if it had been invested only in small caps during the same time period. The study also measured what would have happened to a portfolio invested only in small-cap stocks during Democratic terms and only in bondsduring Republican administrations. Under this scenario, one dollar grew to $1,242, significantly more than the $103 return achieved with a standard balanced investment of 60 percent stocks and 40 percent bonds.   <p> How likely is it that any of these patterns will hold true in1996? The odds differ for each trend. So far, Clinton's term fits the presidential election cycle to a tee, and there's no reason to think it won't continue to do so. He raised taxes inhis first year, the Federal Reserve raised interest rates in his second year, and the market reacted by stalling for most of 1994. In Clinton's third year, the market took off like arocket propelled by spectacular earnings growth and a nudge from Fed rate cuts.  <p> If 1996 runs true to form, the stock market should deliver a less stunning but still impressive performance. "We won't have the type of appreciation we had in '95, which was way out of the ordinary," says Mickey Levy, chief economist for Nations BanK Capital Markets. "While I expect the market to go up, I urge investors to adjust their expectations and recognize that if the total return on the market is a third to a half of what it was, that's still very strong." That's a 10 to 15 percent return at or above the historic average for equities.   <p> The Federal Reserve probably won't push returns higher by making significant interest-rate cuts or stall the market by hiking them. It's virtually certain that Clinton will reappoint Fed Chairman Alan Greenspan to another four-year term in March, leaving Greenspan free to be Greenspan by keeping a keen eye on inflation while attempting to maintain annual gross domestic product growth of 2.5 percent. That's a tough act. But Greenspan's Fed has proved to be cautious and reactive. So changes in course are likely to be gradual and to occur late in the year.  <p> The market may be less likely to react strongly to the party affiliation of the electoral victor because economic distinctions between the Republicans and Democrats are now so blurred. Clinton came to office bent on recasting the Democrats as fiscal watchdogs from "tax-and spenders," and the 1994 Republican congressional sweep has pushed him further toward such traditional GOP positions as a balanced budget and welfare reform.   <p> The policy debate now focuses on how soon to balance the budget and how deep to cut entitlements such as welfare, Medicaid, and Medicare. "In 1993, people were talking about a big expansion of the welfare state with universal health care, and now they're talking about cutbacks in Medicare and Medicaid," says David Shulman, chief equity strategist at Salomon Brothers. "The initiative has switched to a Republican Congress, which is part of the reason for the market rally this year."   <p> The Republican majority in Congress is almost certain to grow in 1996, no matter who wins the White House. The political agenda,therefore, will be set by either a Republican Congress and a Democratic president or by a Republican Congress in cooperation with a president of its own party. "If the Republicans get a big enough majority, [they may] go after the rest of the social safety net," says Oppenheimer chief investment strategist Michael Metz. Millions of people might suddenly go hungry, Metz notes, but the market would likely reward that act of "fiscal responsibility" with lower interest rates and climbing stock prices.  <p> What could derail this market scenario? The unexpected. The market won't rejoice if a third, maybe even fourth, party emerges with a legitimate chance to win the White House. "The ultimate nightmare for the markets is that no one candidate gets enough votes to get elected, and the vote gets thrown into the House," says Stan Collender, director of federal budget policy for Price Waterhouse. "That's the kind of uncertainty the markets don't like." And of course such surprises as a worsening banking crisis in Japan, a coup in Russia, or a war in the Persian Gulf or the South China Sea could each send the market into a swoon. Domestically, consumers, especially retirement-conscious baby boomers, could court recession by paring down credit card debt and shopping less. Those are just some of the risks.   <p> Looking a little further out, domestic party politics, a relatively benign influence in 1996, could become dangerously partisan. The Democrats are clearly unable to propose and pass legislation capable of roiling the markets, but that's not true for a Republican party rife with radical economic ideas. Whether or not replacing the income tax with a flat tax, ending decades of U.S. commitment to free global trade, or eviscerating the Securities and Exchange Commission in a fit of deregulatory zeal is a good idea is almost beside the point. The financial markets hate revolutionaries.  <p> A second Clinton term could also unsettle the markets. Without the need to run for reelection, Clinton may finally stick to his guns rather than play the disinterested statesman who attempts to broker responsible deals with a Republican Congress. The congressional leadership is likely to be even more combative after the 1996 elections. A Bob Dole weakened by a failed presidential bid would have less control over the Gingrich-led House and less ability to control the younger troops in the Senate. Turning up the political heat so that the struggle on Capitol Hill turns from a game of chicken like that played recently over raising the debt ceiling in order to prevent a default by the government into deadlocked trench warfare would certainly send the dollar tumbling and undermine the bond market.   <p> Combine that possibility with what history says about the dismal prospects for the stock market in the first year of a presidential term as well as with the possibility that the Fed will start to increase rates late in 1996, and 1997 doesn't look too promising. The presidential tea leaves provide all the warnings investors need.   <p> Pam Black is the Investing Editor of Worth.  <p> THIRD PARTIES ARE NO PARTY  <p> By Pam Black  <p> The stock market hates third wheels in presidential politics, or so history would suggest. The three-party races of 1912 and 1948, in fact, brought on two of the worst six-month market performances of this century. Only in 1916 and 1940, when world war overwhelmed the effect of domestic politics, did the markets do worse following a presidential election. The confused political lineup for 1996 could produce another three-party race: Colin Powell is out of the picture and so, probably, is Ross Perot. Republican candidate Pat Buchanan may run with or without the party nomination, and Perot's followers have reserved ballot space for a third-party candidate, as of yet unnamed, in several key states.   <p> Back in 1912, onetime college president and New Jersey governor Woodrow Wilson rode to an overwhelming electoral college victory as a Democrat, although he failed to win a majority of the popular vote. Wilson benefited when civil war broke out among the Republicans, producing a three-way race. The conservative wing of the Republican party supported the reelection of William Howard Taft, whose 300-pound heft prompted one reporter to dub him a gentle bison. Liberal Republicans, meanwhile, had persuaded Theodore Roosevelt to run for a third term as the candidate of the newly formed Progressive Party (also called the Bull Moose Party). Both Taft and Roosevelt had credentials as "trust busters," but Wilson ranan even more antibusiness campaign. Predictably, Wilson's victory chagrined Wall Street. The Dow Jones industrials dropped 11.5 percent during the six months following his election. It was Wilson who signed legislation that created the Federal Reserve Board and the Federal Trade Commission.  <p> In 1948, incumbent Harry Truman's support in the polls was so low that some Democrats talked of drafting General Dwight D. Eisenhower as their party's candidate. Instead, the Democrats fragmented into three groups: The core of the party held on with Truman, the new Progressive Party nominated the liberal former vice president Henry Wallace, and Southern Democrats formed the States' Rights Party (popularly known as the Dixiecrats) and nominated Strom Thurmond, then governor of South Carolina. In a 31,000-mile, two-month, whistle-stop campaign, Truman attacked the intransigence of the Republicans, who had gained control of Congress in 1946. He also promised to continue Franklin Roosevelt's New Deal. With the opinion polls putting Dewey firmly in the lead, many Dewey partisans failed to turn out to vote. This gave Truman the victory with less than 50 percent of the popular vote. Within six days of the November election, the Dow Jones industrials fell 8.6 percent.   <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Market Trends 

					</font>
