		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/10-The Restless Freshmen</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>The Restless Freshmen</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/10-The Restless Freshmen</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						October 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Experts  <p> THE RESTLESS FRESHMEN  <p> By James K. Glassman  <p> It's mid-july in Washington, when Congress decides how to spend a half-trillion dollars on "discretionary" programs for the fiscal year that starts in the fall. (That's compared with about a trillion dollars that goes to "mandatory" programs like Medicare.) Inside the Capitol building, the House Appropriations Committee is determining the fate of the U.S. Department of Commerce, which since 1913 has, at least in principle, zealously promoted the interests of American business.   <p> Outside the hearing room, a 53-year-old entrepreneur and former drag racer named Dick Chrysler to all appearances, just the sort of fellow who could reasonably be expected to appreciate the government's assistance is taking a break from the proceedings. But Chrysler is a Congressman himself these days, not a businessman, and he is eager to eliminate not just Commerce but also the departments of Energy, Education, and Housing and Urban Development. That's just for starters. When asked about the Small Business Administration, Chrysler, who sits on the House Small Business Committee, holds out his right hand, thumb down.  <p> The Constitution decrees that spending and taxing bills must start in the House, the federal body most directly representative of and responsive to the voters. Chrysler, from the central Michigan town of Brighton, was just one of 73 GOP Congressmen who swept into town on the conservative tidal wave last November, and if Republican promises of smaller government and lower taxes do get enacted (as appears likely), it will be in large measure because of pressure from these political neophytes.  <p> The newcomers, at least for now, are very different from veterans of either party. They're not particulary impressed with Washington; in fact, they don't like the place much. As Washington Post reporter Joel Achenbach recently wrote of Zach Wamp, a 38-year-old freshman from Chattanooga, Tennessee, "Washington is not his city. He has no hangouts here. This is a common theme with Republican congressmen. They are here but they are not really here." When Wamp ran for the House last year, one of his proposals was to pay members of Congress the same salary as a lieutenant colonel and to billet them in officer housing.  <p> Something else marks these neophytes as different: Before entering public service, many of them were working stiffs, not lawyers or former Hill staffers or college professors. Wamp, who never graduated from college, was a real estate broker. Richard "Doc" Hastings of Pasco, Washington, ran Columbia Basin Paper & Supply. John Ensign of Las Vegas is a veterinarian who also managed a hotel. Sue Kelly of Katonah, New York, renovated buildings and owned a florist shop. Gil Gutknect of Rochester, Minnesota, sold school supplies and auctioned real estate.  <p> Chrysler is a true rarity a manufacturer. In 1976, he started Cars & Concepts, which converts standard, unfinished automobiles into convertibles for companies like <a name="NYSE:GM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10640"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b> General Motors</b></a>. Ten years later, when he sold the firm in a leveraged buyout to his 1,200 employees, it was turning out 95,000 customized cars and grossing $158 million a year. Two years ago, he launched RCI, a successful firm that customizes cars and makes environmentally friendly metal hydride batteries.  <p> Chrysler enjoys telling people that he's no relation to the famous automobile family. In fact, he went straight from high school to the assembly line of GM's Willow Run plant, where he spent six years bolting steering wheels onto rolling Chevrolets. He left GM to work for Hurst Performance, which makes parts for high-performance cars. There he rose from floor sweeper to vice president and, in 1982, bought the company. (He later sold it.) <p> With some of the money he made from Cars & Concepts and Hurst, Chrysler spent $1.6 million to run for Congress in 1992 against Bob Carr, an eight-term Democrat who headed the Appropriations subcommittee on transportation. Chrysler promised voters in the 8th District that he would cut spending and taxes, but his main appeal was generalized change. Carr squeaked through by 3,600 votes. <p>Two years later, Carr ran for the Senate, giving Chrysler his opening. This time, using the same themes and enthusiastically supporting the Contract With America he won easily. Now he believes he can apply the lessons of business to governing.  <p> "I've never used budgets in my business," Chrysler says. "You decide on your mission first. What is it you need to accomplish? Then you apply the resources in the most efficient way, pushing decision-making down as far as possible. No one can tell you better how to do something than the person on the shop floor.They'll tell you,  'You know, if you put the glue on first....'" <p> A belief that decisions are best made by those affected by them virtually constitutes Chrysler's politics. Government has no business promoting business that's the job of the private sector. "I've done business in 52 countries," he says, "but I've never called the Commerce Department, and it's never called me. The department is the mother of all corporate welfare. It's just not the proper role of the federal government, picking winners and losers."   <p> Similarly, he thinks housing and education should be left to state and local governments. "Programs like drug-free schools shouldn't be run from Washington," he says. "That's just to make people here feel warm and fuzzy." Job training? "There are 163 programs! What we need is programs that help entrepreneurs succeed. "In other words, lower taxes and fewer regulations. He mentions the Occupational Safety and Health Administration, despised by manufacturers nationwide. "You could eat off the floor of my plant," Chrysler says of his Cars & Concepts days, but OSHA inspectors could always find something to correct.   <p> Soon, thanks to efforts by the freshmen, Congress itself will fall under OSHA's purview and will learn what it's like to live under the laws it imposes on others. Chrysler points to a tangle of wires below the desk of an Appropriations Committee receptionist. Gleefully, he says, "See that: OSHA violations. Fire-code violations." <p> From Chrysler's point of view, there aren't many things the federal government should do. Right now, he's leaning toward a complete restructuring of the tax code, probably including a national sales tax that would eliminate the IRS. To reform Medicare, he likes the idea of medical savings accounts. Seniors would buy high-deductible insurance policies with federal help, setting aside a special account to pay out-of-pocket health costs up to the limit of the deductible say, $2,000. Any money not spent from the account would be theirs to keep. Chrysler has started such a system for workers at his RCI plant in Michigan. <p> What's the difference between being a business owner and being a Congressman? "In business, you put your head down, do a task, finish it, and go on to the next one," he says. "But in Congress, as soon as you start, you have to pick your head up. You keep being interrupted." For example, Chrysler's pet project of eliminating the Commerce Department seemed a done deal until defenders on the subcommittee in charge of the department's spending saved it. However, Chrysler and other freshmen received a letter from Speaker Newt Gingrich and Majority Leader Dick Armey promising that Chrysler's work on killing Commerce would be incorporated into the upcoming reconciliation bill the last word on the federal budget.  <p> There's no guarantee that Commerce will actually die, but Chrysler seems to be getting a handle on Washington, where the race is less often to the swift than to the persistent. "I look at this pragmatically," he says. "You have to eat the elephant one bite at a time. We're going to be back here in 1996."   <p> This flexibility is another way in which Chrysler is unusual. Norman J. Ornstein, a political scientist with the American Enterprise Institute, points out that while there is a long tradition of rich businessmen spending millions to get elected, there are still relatively few true entrepreneurs who have made it to Congress.  <p> "The idea of running for office is repugnant" to many of them, says Ornstein. "We set up our laws, rules, and culture so that people in the business world see no rewards in politics and potential devastation." Then, too, Ornstein says, the businessman-candidate has to live with the fact that "politicians are people you've vilified all your life, and you want to be one of them."  <p> Now, of course, Dick Chrysler is one of "them," and the big question is whether he and his classmates will become coopted by the Capitol Hill culture. The best guess is that the Republican freshmen, with their rough edges and their disdain for Washington, will resist assimilation at least for another three years. Time enough for some real changes?  <p>    <p>James K. Glassman writes a column on politics and finance for the Washington Post. He also hosts Techno Politics on PBS and Capital Gang Sunday on CNN. <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Government, Legislation

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
