	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/06-Up the Middle</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/06-Up the Middle</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Well, yes, the GOP tax bill helps the rich. But have you noticed what it offers the middle class?<p>By James K. Glassman<p>The republicans' contract with America zipped through the House of Representatives so quickly that the details of its most important bill, H.R. 1215, the Tax Relief Act of 1995, went largely unnoticed. The press focused on Democratic criticism that the bill benefits the rich. True enough, but it also provides spectacular tax savings for tens of millions of Americans. More important, it could induce us to invest at a rate that will help the country keep pace with our global competitors.<p>Let's start by considering a family of five (mother, father, three kids) with an annual adjusted gross income of $50,000. According to the accounting firm Price Waterhouse, this family currently pays federal income tax totaling $4,643. Under H.R. 1215, the family would receive a credit of $500 per child, reducing the amount owed to $3,143, a 32 percent cut. A family with two children would save $1,000, or 20 percent.<p>The bill, in fact, eases the tax burden on the middle and upper-middle class in a number of ways. It raises the estate-tax exemption from $600,000 to $750,000, makes the home-office deduction easier to claim, allows small businesses to expense $35,000 worth of capital equipment a year (up from $17,500), rolls back the tax increase on Social Security benefits enacted in 1993, and permits a tax deduction for those who sell their principal residence at a loss.<p>The Senate will undoubtedly alter the House version, and there's a chance President Clinton will veto the compromise bill. But if the major elements survive intact, H.R. 1215 will be the most influential tax bill at least since 1986. That law cut the top rate on income from 50 percent to 28 percent, but it raised the tax on capital gains (profits from the sale of assets like stocks, bonds, and real estate) from 20 percent to 28 percent, which may have reduced the incentive to invest. Since then, the top rate on income jumped back up__to 39.6 percent on income over $250,000 a year__but the top capital gains rate remains unchanged. The House bill lowers this rate while keeping the current rate on interest, dividend, and salary, thus reinstating a large differential between the two categories. In the past, a wide differential has raised long-term capital investing.<p>Currently, a couple earning $100,000 a year and filing jointly pays $3,100 in tax on $10,000 in interest from a certificate of deposit and $2,800 in tax on $10,000 in capital gains on the profitable sale of stock. Not much difference. But under H.R. 1215, this couple's capital gains levy would drop to no more than $1,550.<p>H.R. 1215 will affect what you pay on capital gains in two ways. First, your rate will be one half your current income tax rate. So, if you're in the 39.6 percent income bracket, your capital gains will be taxed at 19.8 percent. If you're in a 28 percent income bracket (in 1994, couples filing jointly earning from $38,000 to $91,850 in taxable income after deductions), your new capital gains rate will be 14 percent.<p>The second change is more complicated, and its significance appears to have registered with very few investors: If assets are held for at least three years, gains on their sale will be indexed to inflation. That is, you'll pay taxes only on the real increase in the shares' value, not on the increase caused by a cheapening dollar. Ending the tax on inflation is a big deal.<p>Say you buy 200 shares of <a name="NYSE:GE"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10634"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>General Electric</b></a> at $50 a share, an outlay of $10,000. You hold on to the stock for five years and sell it at $100 a share__a profit of $10,000. Assume you're in a 28 percent bracket. Under today's tax law, you would pay 28 percent of $10,000, or $2,800, in capital gains taxes. But if the capital gains provisions of H.R. 1215 become law, the picture alters substantially.<p>First, you would calculate the effects of inflation, using what is called the GDP deflator (similar to the consumer price index). Let's assume the deflator indicates inflation has been running at a 4 percent annual clip. Over five years, thanks to compounding, that's a 22 percent overall increase in prices. Since the original cost of your GE stock was $10,000, you adjust it for inflation by adding 22 percent. Your new basis for computing gains, then, is $12,200 instead of $10,000__so your profit, for tax purposes, is $20,000 minus $12,200, or $7,800. <p>Now, apply your new capital gains rate__half of 28 percent, or 14 percent__to the $7,800 gain. Total tax due: $1,092, instead of $2,800. That's a reduction of 61 percent.<p>The bill's IRA provisions may be even more ambitious. IRAs, or individual retirement accounts, were popular in the early and mid-1980s, but the 1986 tax law got rid of their main attraction: No longer could a single taxpayer earning more than $35,000 a year who has a retirement plan at work deduct his or her annual $2,000 contribution to an IRA account. Moreover, IRA withdrawals are taxable income. If you're 30 years old and start an IRA today, who knows what the tax rate will be in 30 years? That uncertainty argues against opening the account in the first place. <p>The new bill erases that dilemma, creating so-called back-loaded IRAs. These retirement accounts, called American Dream Savings Accounts in H.R. 1215, allow you to withdraw accumulated funds at age 59 and a half__tax free. If you and your spouse each put $2,000 a year into a back-loaded IRA that returns 10 percent annually, you'll have $252,000 after 20 years and $724,000 after 30 years. And 10 percent is not an outlandish return for a good growth-stock fund. Fidelity Contrafund, for example, has returned an average of 17.7 percent over the past decade, and Mutual Beacon has returned 15.4 percent. The new American Dream Accounts also allow tax-free, penalty-free withdrawals before age 59 and a half to buy a first home or to pay higher education or medical expenses.<p>The reasoning behind the new IRAs and the capital gains rate reductions is succinctly explained in the report of the House Ways and Means Committee on H.R. 1215: "The Committee is concerned about the national savings rate, and believes that individuals should be encouraged to save." That concern is wholly appropriate, given that the net national savings rate in this country is dismally low__an average of 4.8 percent of GDP annually from 1973 to 1991, compared with 19.1 percent in Japan and 10.7 percent in Germany.<p>Will these changes actually boost saving? No one knows. Ronald Reagan's rate cuts in the 1980s were supposed to do the trick, but instead the savings rate fell and consumption rose. The difference this time is that the the House bill specifically targets long-term savings and investments with its tax benefits. <p>Even if the theory is correct, however, there remains a major problem with this legislation. Over the next five years, the Joint Committee on Taxation estimates that H.R. 1215 will deprive the U.S. Treasury of $189 billion of expected revenues. Absent new spending cuts, the federal deficit will rise to $356 billion in the year 2000, instead of the $284 billion that's now projected. What's more, the politically palatable features in the bill (those that push revenue loss into the future, such as inflation indexing and the back-loaded IRA) could begin adding an extra $100 billion a year to the deficit between 2001 and 2005, according to the Treasury Department. <p>Republicans in Congress say they'll offset those losses with spending cuts large enough to keep their pledge to balance the budget by 2002. Well, maybe. The cuts they envision will have to be large, in some cases Draconian, and politically very difficult to realize. The pity is that the greatest losses stem from a provision of little economic but large political weight: the $500-per-child tax credit for families making up to $200,000. By 1998, those credits will cost the Treasury $24 billion, compared with $10 billion for capital gains reform.<p>This is where the House-Senate compromise comes in. The betting in Washington is that by fall the president will sign a bill with child credits for families making up to, say, $70,000; that preserves the back-loaded IRAs (and expands the deductibility for existing front-loaded IRAs); and that retains capital gains indexing and probably the rate cuts, too. <p>It's ironic that this sweeping new tax bill may become merely a historical footnote soon after it becomes law. That's because Congress is already turning to the biggest tax reform of all__a single-rate flat tax or a national sales tax. Both have influential supporters on the Hill and among the 1996 Republican presidential candidates. In the meantime, enjoy H.R. 1215. For the sake of the economy (and perhaps partisan politics), the government may let you keep a little more of your own money.
- - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - 
James K. Glassman writes regularly on politics and finance for the Washington Post and was for six years the editor of Roll Call. Gretchen Morgenson will return next month.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Taxation, Government Legislation, Politics

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
