		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Privacy and the Self-Employed</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/06-Privacy and the Self-Employed</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						June 1995 <p>Worth Magazine/Advisor  <p> PRIVACY AND THE SELF-EMPLOYED   <p> By Elizabeth Macdonald  <p> If you earn self-employment income, as 21 million Americans do, the IRS may regard you as a tax cheat. The agency claims the self-employed underpay their taxes, costing perhaps $37 billion a year in lost revenue.  <p> The principal culprits, say the IRS, are lawyers, accountants, construction workers, hairdressers, day-care providers, and doctors.What the IRS won't tell you is that in pursuing lost revenue, it may compromise the privacy of some tax returns. Moreover, according to the Treasury Department, the lost-revenue estimate may not be accurate.  <p> Employers are required to withhold income, Medicare, and Social Security taxes from employees' wages and pay a matching Social Security and Medicare tax. The IRS believes employers, eager to reduce administrative and benefit costs, intentionally misclassify many employees as independent contractors. These workers pay their own payroll taxes, which the IRS says makes cheating easier. <p> Since 1988 the IRS has been cracking down on employers who misclassify their workers. It has hit millions of taxpayers with assessments of 100 percent on taxes owed, plus penalties and interest. "It's found money for the IRS," says Jim Weidman, spokesman for the National Federation of Independent Business. "They've got withheld taxes for the future, plus tons of penalties."   <p> The problem is that the IRS, in its pursuit of revenue, is bending its privacy laws by releasing certain workers' tax returns to those who hire them. "Failure to safeguard taxpayer records is a major problem at the IRS," says Peter Sepp, spokesman for the National Taxpayers Union. "Everyone is at risk of having their return made public record. IRS information could ruin people's lives and put corporations out of business."  <p> A recent case first reported in The New York Times is illustrative. In 1993, the IRS reclassified 65 computer programmers as employees of JasTech, a Cleveland-based computer-consulting firm, and slapped JasTech with a $287,000 assessment for failing to send in payroll taxes for the programmers from 1987 through 1989. The IRS based its reclassification largely on 60 returns filed by the workers. <p> JasTech's attorneys, Craig E. Etter and Harvey Shulman, filed a Freedom of Information Act suit in federal district court to get the workers' returns. They used a loophole in the privacy law that said disclosure was allowable since the IRS had, ineffect, made the programmers' tax returns part of JasTech's filed return. By January 1995, the Justice Department had released information from 48 returns to the attorneys.  <p> This was the first reported instance of Shulman and Etter receiving confidential IRS material. However, in 1991, in a case involving a $200,000 payroll-tax dispute, the two persuaded an IRS district officer to give them income and tax payment amounts declared by about 20 programmers and analysts hired as independent contractors by a computer consulting firm. (Etter and Shulman declined to comment on the case.)  <p> Tax experts say the rules governing employee classification are the most subjective and arbitrary in the entire tax code. The IRS relies on a loose conglomeration of case law, workers' compensation law, and employer tort liability rules as well as its own 20 common-law rules (see "Proving You're an Employee").These 20 rules are used in a vague and unpredictable way: TheIRS looks for an overall pattern, weighting the first three rules most heavily. This complex method of classification results in a morphous tax-law categories such as "statutory employees" workers like truck drivers and life insurance salesmen who may operate as if self-employed.  <p> Furthermore, the pretext for this crackdown, billions in lost revenue, may be entirely unfounded. A 1991 Treasury study says that because independent contractors don't get the same fringe benefits and expense reimbursements as employees, they "tend to pay higher levels of taxes, especially Social Security and Medicare taxes, than employees and employers, provided the income and expenses are reported correctly."  <p> If you're hiring an independent contractor, keep in mind that a key IRS test is whether business owners have the right to control where, when, and how someone works. Spell out in writing the job to be performed, closely following the agency's 20 rules. And don't ask the IRS to help you figure out who is and who isn't an employee in most cases the agency will say workers are employees.  <p> - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - -- - - - - - - - -   <p> Proving You're an Employee  <p> The IRS might not consider you self-employed if you:  <p> *Work on the employer's premises <p>*Do not have a major investment in resources for providing <p>services <p>*Do not offer your services to the public <p>*Comply with employer's instructions about the work <p>*Receive training from or at the direction of an employer  <p>*Provide services integrated into the business operations <p>*Must render your services personally <p>*Hire, supervise, and pay assistants for the employer <p>*Have a continuing working relationship with an employer <p>*Work full time for an employer <p>*Follow set hours of work established by an employer <p>*Work for one employer at a time <p>*Work in an order or sequence set by an employer <p>*Submit regular reports to an employer <p>*Receive payments of regular amounts at set intervals <p>*Get reimbursed by an employer for business and travel expenses<p>*Rely on the employer to provide tools, materials, or other equipment to do the job <p>*Cannot make a profit or suffer a loss from the services <p>*Can be fired by the employer <p>*Can quit working without incurring liability  <p> Source: Internal Revenue Manual 4600  <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Government, Taxation, Small Business Ownership, Employment

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
