<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/05-Beyond Economics, Beyond Politics, Beyond Accountability</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/05-Beyond Economics, Beyond Politics, Beyond Accountability</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						May 1995 <p>
Worth magazine/Cover  <p>
 BEYOND ECONOMICS, BEYOND POLITICS, BEYOND ACCOUNTABILITY  <p>
 By Michael Lewis  <p>
 It's hard to imagine anyone more unintentionally disruptivethan Alan Greenspan as he enters a crowded room.  From the momentthe chairman of the federal reserve bank walks through the doorand blinks into the television cameras, he looks less like apower broker than a clerk who's been dragged from some dingyvictorian counting house.  The closer he draws, the less plausiblehe seems as a center of attention - and yet the more clearlyhe is just that.  Never mind that his skin tone is a pale gray;that his bald spot resembles a prelate's cap; that he wears thesort of plain blue suit that anyone who has even the slightestflair knows to avoid.  Never mind the large, cartilaginous earsthat would suggest the possibility of human flight if only thebody beneath were not so unflappable.  When Alan Greenspan walksinto a room, the room changes.  <p>
 It's difficult to believe until you see it, but even U.S. senatorsare distracted by his presence.  When he shows up for a congressionalhearing, as I watched him do one morning this January, conversationsstop cold.  A newly elected Republican primps his hair and beatsa path from the dais, hoping to chat with a man who will likelybe the linchpin of our global economy as it enters the next millennium. The crowd cranes to see a man who, more than anyone but theirwon employers and spouses, has his hand in their wallets.  Allthis fawning merely makes Greenspan seem even less comfortable- which is saying something.  You get the feeling he wishes hecould be accounted for without having to be present.  <p>
 It is the first day in the reign of the new chairman of theSenate Banking Committee, Alfonse D'Amato of New York.  Greenspanhas been called upon to tell the senators how a small-time publicservant in Orange County, California, could have blown $2 billionin the spectacular collapse of the bond markets last year.  Atthe sound of the gavel the hearing begins and the Fed chairmanassumes his testimonial post: He slouches in hi chair and leanshis nose heavily on his left index finger, as if it were theonly thing preventing him from sliding to the floor.  I've leafedthrough perhaps 40 different photographs of Greenspan testifyingbefore the congressional committees.  In more than half of thesehe is propping himself up by the nose.    <p>
 For the next hour, Greenspan listens almost motionless as senatorsstake out a range of positions on the need for more regulationof the markets.  At last his own turn comes at the microphone. For a moment the chamber stops dead, as if someone is aboutto say something truly important.  <p>
 But then Alan Greenspan speaks.  <p>
 The typical Greenspan sentence runs on for a hundred words ormore, with three of four switchbacks, and ends up several milesfrom where it started.  You try to follow, but the words simplyvanish as soon as they are spoken.  All that sticks in you memoryare weird fragments filled with clauses, spoken in the raspytone of a Catskills comedian: "We will very importantly findthat we are not capturing the rapidity of change which is happening,which is a consequence...." That kind of thing.  Flashes of meaningare obscured by these giant multi-clause swells, like small boatsin high seas.  <p>
 The ability to talk forever without saying what's on you mindhas long been a job requirement for the Federal Reserve chairman,so no one pays this much heed.  Even Greenspan's friends willtell you his diction is merely a clever ruse.  They say thingslike "You know that funny way he talks, well, that's just a put-on,of course."  But it isn't.  Well before he arrived in Washington,Greenspan spoke in code.  "You had to listen to him really hardto figure out what the hell Alan was talking about,"  says NathanielBranden, a friend and intellectual sparring partner of Greenspan'sfrom the early 1950s.  "Instead of saying, 'I'm going to getthe keys in the car,' he'd say, 'One would think that inasmuchas the keys are located in the automotive device, perhaps itwould be advisable if one were to leave by the back door, findone's way to said device...' Compared to then, he is a modelof simplicity and clarity today."  <p>
 The effect of this impenetrable language on the Senate hearingis almost immediate.  You can see that the senators think theirinability to follow him is their fault - not his.  ChristopherDodd of Connecticut begins to squint.  D'Amato leans back andasks a pretty young woman to fetch him a cup of coffee.  PaulSarbanes of Maryland, who promised during his last campaign toend the Federal Reserve as we know it, slowly sinks into hischair.  Concentration flickers, then dies.  In less than halfan hour Greenspan has numbed any interest in Orange County rightout of the United States Senate.  <p>
 And so by the time the Fed chairman says something worth hearing,nobody much is listening.  Referring to the disastrous advicegiven by a Merrill Lynch broker who sucked nearly $100 millionin commissions from Orange County, Greenspan declares that bothbrokers and their customers should be "unburdened by any perceivedneed to take into consideration the interest of their counterparties."  It sounds dull enough - until you realize what he'sdriving at.  Greenspan expressed this same radical belief moreclearly during the 1960s in a book of essays assembled by hismentor, the novelist and free-market zealot Ayn Rand.  "It isprecisely the greed of the businessman, or, more appropriately,his profit-seeking, which is the unexcelled protector of theconsumer," wrote Greenspan.  Since greed is good, in short, let'snot worry too much about its uglier consequences.  <p>
 The senators, few of whom would endorse such a sentiment, nodright along - as does the chairman of the Securities and ExchangeCommission, whose very job it is to make sure that Merrill Lynchbrokers consider the interest of customers.  Alan Greenspan issubverting the hearing's mission without anyone noticing - andgiving everyone the impression that he had nothing to do withthe fallout from the first genuine hog-stomping financial panicsince the stock market crash of 1987.  <p>
 But in truth, the Orange County fiasco was partly Greenspan'sown doing.  In raising interest rates last year to fend off aninflationary bogeyman that may or may not have existed, his FederalReserve collapsed the bond market by mistake.  That's what madelife hell for the aptly named treasurer of Orange County, RobertCitron - and for a bunch of other bond junkies besides.  What'smore, Greenspan had predicted that no such disaster would happen. In a private meeting in January 1994, he told Senator Sarbanesthe bond market would fall maybe two or three percentage pointsif interest rates were raised but would recover within a fewweeks.  He had a highly complex Fed study to support it, he said. <p>
 But if such a study existed, Greenspan never handed it over- and he never mentioned it again.  (Greenspan declined to beinterviewed for this story.)  Two weeks later the Fed hit thebrakes and the bond market tanked.  It was a good, old-fashionedpanic:  First the hedge funds, then the Wall Street bond traders,then the mutual funds sold their bond positions.  The bond marketstill hasn't recovered.  Greenspan stuck a pin into the air topop a small balloon but sank a zeppelin instead, apparently withouteven knowing it had been up there.  A year later several thousandpeople on Wall Street are now literally on the street; some ofthe world's biggest investors have flirted with ruin; hot moneyhas flowed out of the U.S. bond market to wreak havoc in Mexico;and a formerly rich county in California faces bankruptcy.  <p>
 That no one has presented the Fed with a bill - or called onit to explain the miscalculation - is a tribute to Alan Greenspan'sgrowing freedom to make the world conform to his own peculiarsense of how it should be.  <p>
 There is a tendency in Washington for peoples' pasts to dryup and blow away.  The assumption is that once you've run theinitial gauntlet of electoral politics - or Senate confirmation- everything prior to your arrival ceases to matter:  You'vepassed inspection and are ready to play the Washington game. In many cases this may even be true, but not in Greenspan's. His ideas and beliefs have not been much shaped by his presentsurroundings.  Indeed, the events that molded the Fed chairmanoccurred before he ever thought of entering the government bureaucracy. If you wish to understand what's running through the brain ofthe most powerful man in America, you need to dig way back intothe past.  To 1952, to be precise, the year Greenspan met andmarried his first and only wife, a lithe blond painter namedJoni Mitchell.  <p>
 It was one of those whirlwind mistakes that you don't readilyassociate with the American 1950s.  It started when Mitchellgot a call from a friend asking her if she'd like to be fixedup.  "She said, 'I know an unusual man, and I wonder if you mightbe interested in meeting him.' 'Unusual how?' I said.  'He'svery, very intelligent,' she said. 'It's hard to find a girlfor him.'"  <p>
 A few days later Greenspan called Mitchell.  "He was unusual,"she recalls, laughing.  "First, he talked to me for about halfan hour before he asked me out.  Then, instead of just askingme out, he asked me which of three kinds of activities I wouldprefer."  She doesn't remember the two options she rejected,but a concert at Carnegie Hall was her choice - followed by marriage,followed by intense evening conversations with a group of Mitchell'sclose friends who had gathered as a fanatical salon around Russian-bornauthor Ayn Rand.  <p>
 The group, known to themselves as the Collective and to Randas the Class of '43 - after the year her breakthrough novel,"THE FOUNTAINHEAD," was published - consisted of Rand and herhusband Frank; Nathaniel Branden and his wife Barbara, who wasa childhood friend of Mitchell's; Leonard Peikoff, who now runssomething called the Ayn Rand Institute; Harry Kalberman whobecame Greenspan's broker, and his wife Elaine; and Allan Blumenthal,a psychiatrist who would marry Joan Mitchell after she and Greenspanagreed they had little in common and had their marriage annulledafter less than a year.  For more than a decade the Collectiveconvened every Saturday night in Rand's apartment on 36th Streetin New York City to discuss whichever novel Rand was workingon.  <p>
 This would appear to be the last time that Greenspan formeda circle of truly intimate friends.  More to the point, it wouldbe the last time he was persuaded that another way of lookingat the world was superior to his own.  The new worldview he adoptedwas that of Rand, who had cast herself not so much as a novelistbut as a thinker who proselytized her views through novels. Her philosophy, crudely put, made a kind of religion of self-interest. But Rand's message couldn't be boiled down completely to self-interest. It was more like: The self-interest of a handful of pure, productivespirits is good, while those who leech off them are repulsive. <p>
 The hero in an Ayn Rand novel - with whom all in the Collectiveidentified - was the embodiment of this philosophy.  He forsookordinary rewards such as degrees and money to follow the TruePath in an industry of their choosing.  The many evil characterswho opposed him did so in the name of a greater good, such asequality, but their sham altruism was a cover for barren inadequacy. Rand's villains included government officials, academics, civicleaders, writers, union bosses - a conspiracy of mediocre elites,united by their exploitation of Randian heroes such as engineers,inventors, railroad builders, and steel barons.  The masses,meanwhile, were little more than sheep to be led.  <p>
 What Rand had to say was interesting, but 40 years later itis not nearly so interesting as the group that sat at her knee.Greenspan had entered into "a very, very spiritual subculture,"says Nathaniel Branden.  "It was like sitting in on the dawnof time," recalls Harry Kalberman.  "We would take whatever Ms.Rand had written and read it.  And she would watch our faces- to see whether we got it."  They got it, all right.  Aftera few months, for example, it seemed logical for Rand and Brandento announce to their spouses that they planned to have an affair,just because it served their self-interests.  <p>
 But while he shared with the Randian an eagerness to subordinatehis life to an idea, Greenspan's ideas a the time were the antithesisof theirs.  When he joined the Collective, says Branden, Greenspan"announced that logic was empty, the senses were untrustworthy,and degrees of probability are all that is possible.  'I thinkI exist' he state, 'but I can't be certain.  In fact I can'tbe certain that anything exists.'"  He sounded just like a villainousacademic in one of Rand's books.  But bad as this was - "Howcan I talk to someone who doesn't know whether he exists?"  Randonce griped to Branden - Greenspan arrived with a corollary attachmentthat was even worse.  <p>
 He admired John Maynard Keynes.  <p>
 Greenspan had been born in the Washington Heights section ofManhattan in 1926, the year that a Yale economist named IrvingFisher first identified the trade-off between inflation and unemployment. When Greenspan was four, his father, an economist, divorcedhis mother, who raised him alone  in near-poverty that was heightenedby the most dramatic economic collapse in American history. Thus straitened,  Greenspan attended Washington Heights HighSchool, where he preceded Henry Kissinger by several years. He spent a year at the prestigious Juilliard School of Musicand briefly played the tenor saxophone in a jazz band.  He wasenough of a trained musician that when he whistled along witha tune, he could follow a minor theme rather than the main melody. But he was enough of a born economist that other members ofthe Henry Jerome Band remember him for preparing their tax returns. <p>
 When Greenspan folded his music tent - he'd decided he'd nevertruly excel as a musician - he went to study at New York University'sSchool of Commerce.  There commenced his formal education forhis current job.  And there, well before it was fashionable,he discovered Keynes, an economist who had come to prominencefor his analysis of what, for Greenspan, had been an intenselypersonal event: the Great Depression.  <p>
 Keynes's take on why Greenspan had grown up poor was, broadly,that free markets are unreliable.  Much as panic can feed onitself in a financial market, Keynes said, pessimism can feedon itself in an economy.  Some external shock causes people tofear a downturn; they respond by buying less than usual; thedecline in consumption causes a further slump; and this in turnleads people to buy even less.  Such a cycle caused the Depression,said Keynes - and the only way to kick the economy out of itsfunk was for the government to step in and stimulate it, withdeficit spending if necessary.  What the money was spent on didn'treally matter to Keynes.  He famously suggested that men mightbe paid to dig holes and fill them back up, or that the authoritiesmight hide bottles of cash to be found by young boys - for whomKeynes had a taste.  <p>
 After graduating from NYU in 1949, Greenspan started, then quit,Columbia University's Ph.D. economics program.  Although identifiedby his professors as a brilliant student, he was unable to affordthe tuition and instead took a dull job at the National IndustrialConference Board, a propaganda outlet for big business.  Aftertheir marriage in 1952, Greenspan and his wife began living ina small apartment in Forest Hill on $4,000 a year. He was bynow an ambitious young man with little prospect of success: The sought-after men of the era were well-rounded and sociableleaders of men; clearly that was not the antisocial, maladroitGreenspan.  "Alan did not have intimate relationships," saysNathaniel Branden.  "My feeling is that the personal realm probablyprovoked anxiety in him."  <p>
 Indeed, if you ask anyone who has known Alan Greenspan, theyall say the same thing: The man finds his deepest happiness innumbers.  The statistics of the immediate economic past resonatein his mind like the motif of some secret symphony - they constitutea truth he understands but others do not.  "Saturday morningshe loved to wake up and study numbers," says Joan Mitchell Blumenthal. "He loved being in control of all these numbers."  The youngman was plodding toward a reputation as an economic analyst,of the steel industry in particular.  <p>
 After an inauspicious first meeting, Rand referred to Greenspanas the Undertaker.  "That," says Barbara Branden, "was becauseof the gloom that emanated from him."  Branden's ex-husband,Nathaniel, recorded his own first impression as follows: "Hewas tall and solidly built, with black hair, dark horn-rim glasses,and a propensity for dark, funereal suits.  He was sombernessincarnate, looking chronically weary, resigned, and unhappy." But the Collective took a liking to Greenspan anyway and convincedhim that the world wasn't as ill-disposed to him as it seemed. <p>
 Rand's views redefined Greenspan's universe, painting him asa pure individual trying to stay afloat in a sea of mediocrity. In his memoir Nathaniel Branden recalls Greenspan's enthusiasmover "THE FOUNTAINHEAD" - and his thrill at being invited toread the mythic "ATLAS SHRUGGED" as it was being written.  "Hecame alive with excitement no one had every seen in him before. Shyly and reluctantly he began to yield to the romantic sideof his nature.... He rarely voiced his feelings about anythingof a personal nature, and his language tended to be detachedan passive.  Complimenting Ayn on some passage in the novel,he might say, 'On reading this ... one tends to feel ... exhilarated.'Or 'The reader is inspired here.'  But occasionally he wouldbreak down and exclaim, 'Ayn, this is incredible.  No one hasever dramatized what industrial achievement actually means asyou have.  What you've written is a hymn to human intelligence. This is fantastic.'"  <p>
 Greenspan quickly revised his Keynesian view of what the governmentshould do.  He adopted an objectivist (as Rand called her creed)love of free markets, a deep suspicion of do-gooders, and a righteoushatred of the state apparatus.  Greenspan has said that Rand"demonstrated to my satisfaction that [laissez-faire capitalism]was not only practical but moral."  This was his critical breakwith Keynes, who stressed the amoral nature of markets.  Randhad little truck with those who chose their economic views onpurely pragmatic grounds - in her view, laissez-faire was theonly morally acceptable system.  "I think Alan was searchingfor a total philosophy that would put a foundation under hisideas," says his ex-wife.  "That's what Ayn did for him."  <p>
 Nathaniel Branden published "THE OBJECTIVIST NEWSLETTER," towhich Greenspan contributed one article praising the gold standardand another attacking government regulation.  In the late 1950sthe Brandens founded an institute to spread Rand's ideas.  Bynight Greenspan lectured there; by day he generated economicforecasts for a consulting firm he had joined.  In early 1961Robert Bleiberg, then editor of "BARRON'S," attended a lectureby Greenspan.  He, too, was persuaded of Rand's rightness andreprinted some of Greenspan's writings in "BARRON'S."  but heresisted entreaties from members of the Collective to becomemore closely allied with them.  "It became evident to me thatthey were a cult," he now says, "or that there was a cultlikeatmosphere about them."  <p>
 One day in late 1967, or perhaps early 1968, while walking downBroad Street in lower Manhattan, Greenspan bumped into the managerof his old jazz band, Leonard Garment, who was now an advisorto the presidential campaign of Richard Nixon.  (Garment wouldbecome better known as Nixon's law partner and a star in theWatergate hearings.)  The two friends lunched at the Banker'sClub, and before long the self-certain Randian found himselfin an office with Nixon himself.  "I'm not sure I was even there,"says Garment, "and if I was, I wouldn't have understood whatAlan was saying to Nixon.  He talked Nepal Katmandu language. But after the meeting Nixon said to me, 'That fellow is a whiz. I want to see more of him.'"  <p>
 It was the first of Greenspan's many political conquests - andit illustrated the gap between what universities produced andwhat the world demanded of an economist.  His gift was an abilityto persuade politicians that he was so smart they couldn't livewithout the numbers in his head.  Says a person close to theNixon campaign, "Alan came in with the idea that you could havethis black box that explained it all - inflation, unemployment,GNP.  He'd sit around with guys like [Nixon advisor John] Ehlrichmanand say, 'I've got this black box....'"  <p>
 At Garment's behest Greenspan worked for Nixon's 1968 campaignas a part-time volunteer.  Most people throw themselves intopolitical campaigns with the vague hope that they will receivean important job in government.  Greenspan's interest in Nixonseems to have been more purely principled: After the victoriouscampaign, he turned down entreaties to work in the Nixon administration,including an offer to head the president's Council of EconomicAdvisors.  <p>
 Greenspan had been attracted, it seems, by Nixon's verbal commitmentsto fight inflation.  This devotion to the dollar's integrityhad a spiritual dimension that owed more to Greenspan's linkwith Rand than to any formal training as an economist.  As taughtin universities, inflation is a potentially meaningless event. As long as everyone expects it, everyone can adjust for it. In Rand's Saturday evening sessions, however, inflation wasas great a threat to freedom as alcohol was to virginity.  Itwas the mechanism by which the corrupt political class separatedthe pure from the product of their efforts, by debasing the moneythey had earned.  And deficit spending by the federal government- which floods the economy with unearned dollars - was the corrupts'Trojan Horse.  Pegging the value of the dollar to gold, the Randiansbelieved, was the only defense against political manipulation. <p>
 Nixon, however, became the first in a line of American presidentswhose commitment to fighting inflation was more rhetorical thanpractical.  The new president felt that the Federal Reserve'stight, anti-inflationary grip on the money supply had cost himthe 1960 presidential election, when he ran as the incumbentvice president against John Kennedy.  When at last Nixon gainedthe Oval Office, he came determined to install in the Fed someonemore responsive to his political needs.  That man was ArthurBurns.  <p>
 Burns had taught Greenspan at Columbia, where Greenspan madehis abortive run at a Ph.D.  The defining moment came when heasked Greenspan's class a simple question:  What causes inflation? The students took turns offering answers until they had provedthey didn't know much.  Finally the master boomed: "Excess governmentspending causes inflation!"  But as Nixon's Fed chairman, Burnsproved there was another cause.  At a crucial moment in the 1972presidential election cycle, he began predicting an economicslowdown that few other economists could see looming.  Over manyobjections, he insisted that the Fed ease the money supply toheat up the economy.  Money growth nearly quadrupled, makingan inflationary surge inevitable, but Burn's Fed rejected morethan 20 calls from member banks to slow down money growth.  <p>
 What happened next was delicious to all students of hypocrisyand politics.  By 1974, the price of green eyeshades and everythingelse was out of control, and Alan Greenspan must have been scratchinghis head in disbelief.  The he got a call.  It was Arthur Burns,telling his former student that this objection to becoming abureaucrat was all very sweet but that it was time for him toenter politics.  "Arthur not only asked him to go," says JudyMackey, one of the four women to whom Greenspan subsequentlyentrusted his economic consulting business.  "He told him thatit was his duty to go - that it was their last chance to fightinflation."  <p>
 And so, on the morning of Richard Nixon's resignation, AlanGreenspan left his Washington pied--tierre - at the Watergate- and came to testify before the Senate Banking Committee atconfirmation hearings to become chairman of the president's Councilof Economic Advisors.  Though he lacked a Ph.D. in economics,no one questioned his qualifications.  There is a tradition ofmen becoming experts simply by being put in positions that requireexpertise, and something like this eased Greenspan's anointmentas a Washington player.  He was, and remains, the second andlast economist without a doctorate to head the CEA since itscreation in 1946.  (A couple of years later Greenspan finallyreceived his Ph.D. from New York University.  His thesis wasa collection of articles the academic merit of which we can onlysurmise, since NYU has lost all three copies.)    <p>
 Sightly more at issue were his political beliefs.  Greenspanheld no only that government was more or less immoral but thatthe new inflation was almost entirely a result of Great Societyspending and other social programs.  As he explained that summer,"In the last 10 or 15 years there has been an extra-ordinarybuildup of ... special interests in our society who have ongoingcommitments from the federal budget [that are] running in excessof the revenue-raising capacity of our tax system.... I wouldsuspect that it may account for anywhere from 80 to 90 percentof the inflation in this country."  <p>
 Robert Kavesh, a former classmate and now a professor at NYU,recalls trying to dissuade him from coming on too strong.  "Isaid, 'Alan, you're going to get up there and start on all thatstuff you believe and they're not going to like you,'" he says. To his credit, Greenspan stood firmly by his beliefs.  But somehowon the way from Greenspan's brain to his mouth, his statementsgot so marvelously garbled that they were difficult for anyoneto understand - much less object to.  Nixon resigned that evening,and Greenspan had even more room to maneuver.  "When Ford becamepresident," says William Seidman, a close friend of Gerald Ford'swho subsequently headed the new president's Economic Policy Board,"one of the first things he did was ask me to decide whetherAlan was suited for the [CEA] job.  Alan was not well regardedby academic economists.  But we had enough problems without goingout and finding someone else."  <p>
 And so in September 1974 the man without a Ph.D. in economicswas sworn in as the nation's leading economist.  The man whodefined himself by a moral objection to bureaucracy went intogovernment service.  In the front row of Greenspan's swearing-inceremony at the White House sat Ayn Rand herself, who must havebeen amused by the sight of the ardent atheist placing his righthand on a Talmud held by his aged mother.  <p>
 But somehow Rand seemed sure that Greenspan wouldn't join thecorrupts.  Just a few days before, she had told a reporter: "Alanis my disciple."  <p>
 It is now more than 20 years since Alan Greenspan first cameto Washington and was stuck with his second unflattering nickname:The Creeper.  It could hardly have been a less accurate descriptionof his progress in politics, but it stuck for a while anyway. It had to do with his quixotic way of working a party.  Everynight Greenspan, who was then 48, would attend some fashionableevent with all the relish of a man being forced to eat a cockroach. <p>
 "He does not flow easily from one major conversational groupof celebrities to another," wrote a "WASHINGTON POST" reporter,"but walks through various rooms looking as if he is going somewherein particular - then you see him later heading back with thesame purposeful expression."  Greenspan quickly became the sortof person who knew everyone but whom no one really knew.  Hissocial ineptitude led his colleagues in the White House to wonderwhy on earth he bothered.  "He had such bad breath," recallsWilliam Seidman, "that what social life he had took place ata distance of ten feet."  <p>
 Before long, however, Greenspan was escorting Barbara Waltersaround town - but in such a detached way that rumors began thatthe economist was somehow different from the other policy hustlersin town.  His former wife recalls a visit she received in 1974from a pair of FBI agents.  "They were asking all sorts of vaguelypersonal questions about Alan," she says, "and I could tell theyweren't getting what they wanted.  They didn't seem satisfied. 'Oh, I get it,' I said.  'You want to know if Alan's homosexual.' They said, 'Well, his ex-wife usually knows these things, ifanyone does.' 'Well, he's definitely not,' I said. 'There havebeen a lot of women since me.' And there have!  It's just hewould never carry on with a woman in public.  He's incrediblydiscreet - the most discreet person I have ever known.  I toldthem that if they were worried about whether he would divulgesensitive information, they had lost their minds."  <p>
 An economist might call Greenspan's style niche marketing. In a city filled with charming men with mint on their breath,he stuck out like an oak in an evergreen forest.  And maybe becausehe was so different, he had a fantastic ability to seduce presidents. Just as he seduced Nixon with the numbers in his head, now heworked on Ford.  Scrap-metal prices! Steel inventories! "He hasthe greatest economic bedside manner of anyone in politics,"says Seidman.  "Extraordinary.  That was his favorite word. He'd go in to see Ford and say, 'Mr. President, this is an extraordinarilycomplex problem.'  And Ford's eyes would get big and round andstart to go around in circles."  <p>
 If there has been a theme to the dance between Rand's discipleand American presidents other than his ability to dazzle themwith numbers, it has been his talent for making their lives difficultwith his principles.  Greenspan's career as an advisor is a niceillustration of how unpopular - and how dangerous for a president-deeply held beliefs can be.  Back in 1968, for example, Greenspanhad landed Nixon in trouble when he masterminded a proposal toset Wall Street free from regulation.  It turned out that a lotof voters thought Wall Street needed as much watching as possible,and Nixon had to backpedal quickly.  <p>
 Now as Ford's economic advisor, Greenspan traveled the landpreaching the need to swallow the economic cost of disinflation,and his singular passion once again landed his boss in trouble. In response to a hostile question from a civil-rights leader,Greenspan explained how Wall Street brokers would suffer muchmore than poor people, as a percentage of their incomes, froma war on inflation.  The ensuing outrage prompted CongresswomanBarbara Jordan of Texas to suggest that Americans send Greenspantheir grocery receipts.  <p>
 For his next trick Greenspan helped conduct Ford's WIN ("WhipInflation Now") publicity campaign, which, in addition to beingan ineffectual stunt, very nearly led to another embarrassment. Leaving the White House with Seidman, Greenspan fainted deadaway.  "He was known to faint under pressure," says Seidman. "I had to drag him out of Pennsylvania Avenue and into the OldExecutive Office Building before the press got pictures of theleader of the war on inflation stretched out in the street." <p>
 Finally, Greenspan persuaded Ford to propose a reduction ingovernment spending for fiscal 1977 - election time.  His reasoningwas sound on paper: Any additional spending would fuel inflationaryexpectations, which in turn would raise long-term interest rates,which in turn would dampen the enthusiasm of businesses for investment. But it was kamikaze politics.  Unemployment already stood at8 percent, and lower inflation would mean higher unemployment- a trade-off Greenspan has always been willing to make, butwhich spells suicide for his political masters.  <p>
 To this day, many believe that Ford's budget helped lose himthe election in 1976.  If so, it also lost Greenspan his job. As he left office in January 1977, three things were clear. First, despite all his efforts, inflation was out of control. Second, to rein in inflation you had to control the FederalReserve Bank.  And third, to control the Fed you had to takeit out of the hands of politicians - and, by extension, the citizenry. The Randian view that the masses of men were being led by waywardelites had been proved to be true.  All that was needed now wasa hero to save them.  <p>
 South of Washington, D.C., in the Northern Virginia suburbs,you can find whole neighborhoods teeming with free-market ideologueswho have made their careers shuttling between jobs in governmentand sinecures in conservative think tanks where they attack peoplewho work in government until it is time to return to public servicethemselves.  Ayn Rand's disciples were mainly this brand of talkinghead.  Their certainty that the market was the only moral systemwas buttressed by a near-complete ignorance of how it felt tobe inside a market.  Among them Alan Greenspan was somethingof an exception, and luck for it.  <p>
 After hooking up with the Randians in the early 1950s, Greenspanhad left his job grinding numbers for the National IndustrialConference Board to join an economic consulting firm owned byan old Wall Street hand named William Townsend.  (Greenspan tookit over when he died.)  Throughout the 1950s and 1960s, Townsend-Greenspanmet with modest success.  Along with the firm's half-dozen professionals,Greenspan provided a steady color commentary on U.S. economicdata - going so far as to recalculate the statistics generatedby the Commerce Department.  When the U.S. government was publishingquarterly estimates of GNP, Greenspan himself had generated monthlyestimates.  Now he returned to Townsend-Greenspan and positionedhimself as a forecaster.  <p>
 Despite his grasp of statistics and trends, however, Greenspannever had any talent for economic prediction - no one has.  Economicdata are descriptions of the immediate past.  At their best theytell you what was which isn't always a good guide to what is,and is often a terrible guide to what will be.  The tea-leafbusiness was harmless enough; it kept Greenspan's name in thepaper and enabled him to earn a living.  And no one seemed tomind that most of his predictions turned out to be wrong.  Butit's odd that a character so obsessed with objective facts woulddevote himself to divining the future, and the move suggestsa certain unreality at Greenspan's core.  The forecaster is toeconomics as Ricardo Montalban is to acting.  He lingers on thefigures and may be thought of as an important economist by peoplewho don't know better, but his credibility among knowledgeablepeople is zero.  He is merely a man of affairs.  <p>
 But what affairs!  Greenspan now occupied the great gold corridorbetween Washington and New York, in which financiers from NewYork pay for advice about Washington and politicians from Washingtonpay for advice about New York.  Greenspan ruffed the two citiesagainst each other like a bridge hand.  He was invited to jointhe board of J.P. Morgan, perhaps the bluest-chip posting onWall Street.  More poignantly, he built a business consultingfor the savings-and-loan industry.  And so in 1982, when CharlieKeating gave him a hefty fee and asked him to write a letter,it seemed only natural to accept.  <p>
 Three years before, Keating had bought Lincoln Savings & Loanin Phoenix.  There he dreamed of building golf courses and $500-a-nighthotel rooms in the dunes.  As we know now, Keating lost about$3 billion of other people's money on such schemes, all coveredby U.S. taxpayers.  But at the time, he seemed a free-markethero of the sort lionized by Ayn Rand.  His only problem wasthat some government bureaucrats wanted to block Lincoln fromdiversifying out of home-mortgage lending and into anything itwished to buy.  <p>
 At Keating's behest, Greenspan penned an impassioned pleas forsavings-and-loan freedom.  The letter concluded with an offerto lobby in person on Keating's behalf: "I am prepared to meetwith [regulators] in Washington at the earliest possible time." It was a beautiful thing, an act of stunning innocence, andmaybe that's why no one has every held it against him.  Greenspanbelieved what he said: Around the same time, he earnestly explainedto a congressional committee that "a time bomb is ticking awayin the financial system.... The whole thrift-institution systemwill undergo a massive crisis."  He was right, of course.  Whathe couldn't imagine was that freeing heroes such as Charles Keatingfrom the shackles of bureaucracy would only make matters worse. It was a prime example of how the Randian view can collide withreality.  <p>
 Greenspan was just as incapable of imagining the other big financialshift of the 1980s, Fed chairman Paul Volckner's successful attackon inflation.  Maybe he didn't believe that an honest war oninflation was politically possible, but he underestimated Volckner- and politics.  In August 1979, just two months before the Fedhiked interest rates and caused property prices to collapse,Greenspan told the American Statistical Association the oddsof such an event were "no more than one in four."  Then in April1981, he told the Electronics Industry Association of Japan thatinflation wouldn't drop soon.  Again in May 1983 he was quotedas saying that "the extraordinary price calm is over."  <p>
 But until Volckner's second term ended in the middle of 1987,the inflation rate held steady at around 4 percent - down frommore that 12 percent in 1979, a tremendous achievement.  Greenspanwatched in perpetual surprise as it became clear that inflationhad finally gotten so bad that the Fed chairman had been givena mandate, and a level of independence, that was previously unthinkable. <p>
 Now that was a job worth having.  <p>
 No one operating in a culture of manipulation wants to be thoughtnaive.  In Washington there is a tendency to believe that everyonewho clambers into some position of power is the beneficiary ofsome sinister strategy.  A senior advisor to Ronald Reagan hastold me that though he "never felt that Alan would backstab,there was one exception.  He engineered the demise of Paul Volckner. I don't know how.  But he did it.  There was no reason why PaulVolckner was not reappointed."  <p>
 But the truth is that people often land in very important jobsby default, and there was every reason why Paul Volckner wasnot reappointed.  In restoring the credibility of the FederalReserve, Volckner had begun to wrest control of the money supplyfrom politicians.  The process was not complete and could reverseitself at any moment.  But it was painfully clear to everyonein the Reagan White House that, while Volckner's goals were consistentwith the administration's, the lifelong Democrat wouldn't bebullied into ensuring the reelection of a Republican president. <p>
 According to journalist William Greider's best-selling account,"SECRETS OF THE TEMPLE," Volckner was already vulnerable whenhis first term expired in 1983, despite his popularity on WallStreet.  Half of Reagan's inner circle had grown to loathe theFed chairman's high-handedness; only intense pressure from theother half saved his job.  By 1987, however, control of appointmentswas drifting into the hands of George Bush loyalists.  They wantedsomeone they could count on to hit the economy's gas pedal beforepresidential elections - someone who made the right noises aboutinflation, so that the markets didn't go berserk, but who mightin a pinch compromise his principles for the sake of his politicalfriends.  <p>
 Astonishingly, their candidate was Alan Greenspan.  Greenspanhad two things going for him.  First, he wanted the job; indeed,his whole life seemed a preparation for it.  Once a week forthe previous 11 years he had made a trip to Washington, and oneach trip he made a point of massaging the people who mattered. "Alan kept up on his contacts with congresspeople in both partieswhen he would go to D.C.," recalls Judy Mackey of Townsend-Greenspan. "He had one life - and that was it," says former Reagan crony. "I don't think I was in the White House once where I didn'tsee him sitting in the lobby or working the offices.  I was absolutelyastounded by his omnipresence.  I was there once every few weeks. For eight years!  He was always huddling in the corner withsomeone.   <p>
 But more importantly, Greenspan seemed to the Bush camp thesort of character who could be molded by his superiors.  To allexternal appearances, they say now, he had been malleable foras long as they knew him.  "In the White House,"  says the seniorReagan advisor, "he never expressed any particular view strongly. In our meetings with the president he never, ever took a hardline on anything.  He wasn't moderate; he was average.  [That'show] he ingratiated himself with the Bush people.  They feltas if they were getting a friend.  <p>
 It was one of the most dramatic miscalculations in the historyof Fed appointments.  The Bush people put Greenspan into Volckner'soffice thinking they were getting an Arthur Burns-style chairmanwho would monkey with the money supply to help fiends win elections. Instead they got a fanatic whose entire adult life had beendedicated to the principle that inflation was evil.  In August1987 Alan Greenspan took over as chairman of the Federal Reserve. The past did not dry up and blow away.  <p>
 The standard evaluation of Greenspan's tenure as Fed chairmanruns something like this: Over the past seven and a half years,his gift for analyzing economic data and his talent for consensusbuilding have helped America to avert crisis.  Having expungedfrom his character any trace of imprudence, he now acts on financialmarkets as a sort of human stabilizer.  Perhaps his finest hourwas during the stock market crash that occurred just after hisascendancy in 1987, when the Fed flooded money into the bankingsystem and offset the effects of a growing panic.  <p>
 During Greenspan's tenure the Fed also has brought down theannual inflation rate from 4 percent, where it has been since1983, to 2 percent - the lowest level it has reached since ayoung Alan Greenspan first met Ayn Rand.  The economic cost ofthis continued war on inflation has bee substandard growth: Recessionshave been longer and recoveries have been briefer than wouldotherwise have been the case.  The political cost was the defeatof George Bush by Bill Clinton in 1992.  <p>
 On the surface, all of this is perfectly plausible.  Just below,it is not.  For a start, it is clear to insiders that Alan Greenspanis a consensus builder only in the sense that Napoleon was aconsensus builder, and that the Fed is less a republic than anempire.  Our nation's monetary policy is made by a body calledthe Federal Open Market Committee, which consists of Greenspan,six top Fed officials called governors, plus a rotating castof five regional Fed presidents.  The FOMC dictates a coupleof key interest rates - including mortgages and car loans - arebased.  This gives FOMC an enormous lever over the economy: Thehigher the cost of borrowing money, the less economic activitywill naturally occur, especially in credit-sensitive areas suchas housing.   <p>
 To a great extent, Greenspan can muscle the votes of his regionalpresidents, who ar elected by private bankers and work out ofgrand buildings in places like Dallas and Boston.  Regional Fedpresidents make the most important economic decisions in ourdemocracy, yet they are not democratically accountable.  Aboutonce every two years some politician point this out and threatensto introduce a bill that requires them to be appointed by thepresident and confirmed by the Senate, like other top Fed officials. About once every two years, Alan Greenspan stops that proposalin its tracks.  In exchange for protections of their clubby world,the presidents pretty much behave themselves.  <p>
 The six Fed governors, by contrast, are appointed by the presidentand, like Greenspan, work from offices along a corridor in abuilding in Washington.  But while the governors can count onlyon their secretaries for support, Greenspan has authority overa staff of 1,700 permanent Fed employees whose driving instinctis to protect their boss.  There is a long tradition of paddingthis staff with former military men, and the blind loyalty ofthese soldiers fits naturally with Greenspan's method of rule. The troops provide superior information, support Greenspan'severy position with statistics, and glare at recalcitrant governorsin the hallways.  <p>
 In short, any Fed consensus will always confirm Greenspan'sown position.  "Chairman Greenspan," says Walker Todd, a formercounsel for the regional Feds in New York and Cleveland, "hasgot his way on just about everything."  The transcripts of Fedmeetings bear Todd out, invariably showing that the regionalpresidents and Greenspan's fellow governors get dragged alongon whatever ride Greenspan wants to take.  To Mexico, for instance. <p>
 Around every Mexican national election since 1976, the Fed hasloaned dollars to the Bank of Mexico; it's an arrangement thatled naturally to the current $40 billion bailout.  The moneyis typically returned one month after the election.  Where itgoes in the meantime, no one says, but i's a fair guess it hassomething to do with ensuring the outcome of the election - amatter of interest to U.S. presidents.  Greenspan has escalatedthe sums involved in this little favor-granting game, over theobjections of his board.  "He would come to meetings," recallsTodd, "and say that he had promised his friends at the Treasurythat he would do this and that the reputation of the Fed wason the line.  Each time he did this the board would say, 'Okaythis time, but next time tell us before you do it - not after.'Next time he did exactly the same thing."  <p>
 The FOMC transcripts that describe the load of 1988 illustratethe point nicely.  In a conference call that October, Greenspanexplains that "it's important that Mexico be supported throughthis period to whatever extent is reasonable." The committeeresponds skeptically, and governor Robert Heller finally cutsto the nub of the matter.  "Mr. Chairman," he says, "I thinkit's very difficult to make a judgment on the appropriatenessof the program in the absence of a briefing on what's going onin Mexico.  I for one would have very much appreciated eitherto have a briefing  like that or to have a background paper sowe can form some considered judgement.... As it is now, I'm happyto go along with it, but it's blind faith."  <p>
 Two weeks later, on November 1, the subject rises again - afterthe loan has been made.  This time governor Martha Seger expressesher concern.  "The day that this bridge loan was announced inthe newspaper, I happened to have breakfast with a congressmanfrom the House Banking Committee," she says.  "He said, 'Whatin the world is the Federal Reserve doing in that?  Why wouldthey be involved with the bridge loan?' And I didn't know howto answer, I'll be honest with you."  Cleveland regional presidentLee Hoskins chimes in.  "The concern is that we would be subjectto being viewed as perhaps circumventing Congress" by doing favorsfor the White House, he says.  "In that sense, I don't thinkit's appropriate to continue those kinds of relationships." <p>
 Although these are serious concerns, Chairman Greenspan isn'tinterested.  "Any further questions for Mr. Truman [the Fed functionaryresponsible for Mexico]? If not, let's move on to the domesticdesk.  Mr. Sternlight?"  <p>
 That's the sound of a consensus being reached in Alan Greenspan'sFederal Reserve Bank.  <p>
 The main flaw in most appraisals of Alan Greenspan is the focusthey place on his economic skills.  Even the management of the1987 stock market crash - supposedly his greatest achievement- required little in the way of his finesse.  Ever since MiltonFriedman and Anna Schwartz demonstrated that the correct responseto a market crash was to flood the banking system with money,the Fed has been poised to respond to a crisis by throwing cashat it.  Similarly, the market has been poised to believe thatthe Fed could offset the effects of a crisis by throwing cashat it.  These twin beliefs were self-fulfilling.  Put anotherway, the reason the financial world was stabilized so quicklyby the Fed in October 1987 was that everyone believed it couldbe stabilized by the Fed.  And of that belief we have to thankFriedman and Schwartz.  <p>
 More generally, monetary policy in the Greenspan years had beenlargely a matter of erring on the side of tight money.  That'swhy inflation has fallen, and it's not especially notable.  Whatis notable is that Greenspan has pretty much singlehandedly beefedup the power of the Fed and removed it further than ever fromanyone's control but his own.  That's a political achievement- a huge one.  <p>
 Studies have shown that, under different administrations, thesame Fed chairman acts differently.  In other words, the nation'smonetary policy is pretty much democratically controlled; itscourse usually has more to do with who is president than whois chairman of the Fed.  The single exception to the rule hasbeen Alan Greenspan.  This is his real achievement, from whicheverything else follows.  It amounts to a shift in power fromelected officials to unelected ones, and it has a self-propellingmechanism.  In the same way that "Hollywood Squares" celebritieswere famous for being famous, our Fed chairman now is respectedfor being respected.  Liberated from having to pander to merevoters, he is a stable currency surrounded by debased alternatives- he's above the trash-talking of daily politics, willing tomake hard choices.  This has given Greenspan an almost mysticalpower over those who might remove him form office.  <p>
 In August 1994, Alan Blinder learned this the hard way.  Newlyappointed as vice chairman of the Fed, Blinder had been widelyviewed as a possible rival to Greenspan.  (Bill Clinton chooseshis own Fed chairman early in 1996.)  Then the former Princetonprofessor gave a speech to fellow central bankers in JacksonHole, Wyoming.  Blinder argued that, in the short run, one mighteasily purchase a few years of more jobs with just a little bitmore inflation - precisely the belief of his fellow FOMC members,including Greenspan.  <p>
 Blinder's crime was to speak reasonably about inflation.  Inparticular, he had suggested that, at its current low levels,inflation was unworthy of the hysteria that attends it at thetop of the Fed.  As a result, he found himself painted as aninflation lover by an amazing flurry of unattributed quotes frominside the Fed.  He isn't, of course.  But Fed politics aren'tabout reality.  They're about perception: the perception of theFed by financial markets, and the perception of that perceptionby politicians.  <p>
 In the political imagination, the financial markets are a suicidewaiting to happen.  From the moment Alan Blinder tried to speakas thought they were a well-adjusted adult, he was accused ofpushing Wall Street onto a ledge - and discredited as a possiblesuccessor to Greenspan.  The more extreme a Fed chairman is aboutinflation, the more reassuring he is to the markets.  And sinceno one is more extreme about inflation that Greenspan, no oneis better suited to head the Fed.  Fusion of man and institutionhas never been so complete.  In protecting the Fed, Greenspanprotects himself.  In advancing himself he advances the Fed. The end result is single-mindedness unmatched in our government. <p>
 Take, for example, a Clinton administration proposal to consolidateall bank regulation into a single new agency.  Four agenciescurrently handle the task; the Fed is one of them.  Forwardedin early 1994, the idea would have reduced the size of governmentand eliminated some arbitrary differences in how banks are regulated. It enjoyed enthusiastic backing from Democrats and Republicansalike.  The proposal had only one flaw: Alan Greenspan was againstit.  It would strip the Federal Reserve of authority over manyof the nation's banks - and in losing control of these banks,Fed official feared, they would lose their best tool for strong-armingCongress. Bankers are large campaign contributors and powerfullobbyists.  <p>
 This threat galvanized the Fed chairman and within a coupleof months a worthy reform had vanished.  A senior Clinton administrationofficial explained the process to me:  "Here is what happenswhen you get into a fight with the Fed on an issue it reallycares about.  First, Alan Greenspan personally visits about halfthe Senate Banking Committee.  The he contacts the board of directorsat his member banks.  These boards consist of leaders of Americanbusiness.  The leaders of American business then call their membersof Congress, who all of a sudden start to waver in their support. <p>
 "If this doesn't suffice, the Fed then contacts foreign centralbanks, who let it be known in various ways that the new ideaisn't such a good one.  If that doesn't work, you find that allof a sudden the finance ministers of G-7 countries are callingthe White House.  Before you know it the president gets callsfrom the British prime minister, the French president, and otherforeign heads of state. And all of a sudden everyone you thoughtwas on your side is questioning your judgement.  <p>
 "By virtue of its contacts and interrelationships, the Fed hasa public-affairs apparatus that is simply unrivaled by any organization,public or private, in the country.  This has enabled [Greenspan's]Fed to pursue a policy of incremental acquisition of authority. Their objective is the control of everything, for all time,through undemocratic processes."  <p>
 Putting a democracy's most important economic decisions beyonddemocratic control isn't easy - or pretty.  In October 1993 theHouse Banking Committee, chaired by Henry Gonzalez of Texas,invited Alan Greenspan to testify.  The sole purpose of thishearing was for Fed officials to tell Congress, under oath, whatrecords they kept of their eight meetings each year.  Under oath,Greenspan said that those meetings were taped - but that thetapes were erased immediately after a loose description of eventswas typed up.  <p>
 This in itself was revealing:  Some of Greenspan's fellow boardmembers had been unaware they were being taped; he told themabout it in a conference call only a few days before the hearing. But the more important implication of Greenspan's testimonywas that there were no precise records of Fed meetings.  Thiswasn't true.  As it turned out, a verbatim transcript of eachmeeting was kept in a drawer down the hall form Greenspan's office. In a letter to Gonzalez a week after he testified, Greenspanadmitted he had misspoken: He knew about these transcripts buthad forgotten.  <p>
 It was, according to a top congressional staffer who subsequentlyvisited the Fed and examined the documents, hard to interpretas anything but "a very conscious strategy to mislead."  EconomistAnna Schwartz agrees that "it was not Alan Greenspan's finesthour.  when that whole crowd form the [Clinton] White House wassummoned and asked if they had any knowledge of interferencein savings-and-loan investigations, it reminded me of all theFed people lined up before the House committee saying that theyhad no idea they kept records."  <p>
 Underlying the incident was Greenspan's apparent convictionthat the mechanics of his fight against inflation are in somesense private.  The Randian view - that it's perfectly moralfor a pure-intentioned hero to outflank an elected elite - hasseldom been so clearly articulated in our public policy.  Butwhile America in the 1990s finds itself in a different position. It's not at all clear that anyone wants to reduce inflationto zero from today's meager levels: The costs might well outweighthe benefits.  If put to a vote it's unlikely the Fed chairman'spolicy would every be implemented - and not because the massesare being duped.  <p>
 What's odd about Greenspan's reluctance to let anyone know whathe's doing inside the Fed is that it magnifies his power to stripwealth arbitrarily from its rightful owners - just what he hassaid he hates about government.  As the Fed chairman forms sentencesdesigned not to be understood, he can't possibly make himselfclear to the markets that depend on his signals.  The inherentcontradiction leads to absurd situations such as that in Februaryof 1994, when the Fed raised interest rates to preempt inflationbut caused inflationary expectations in the process.  <p>
 If the markets surprised Greenspan by collapsing and devastatingthe nation's bond portfolios, it was only because no one hadany idea what was inside his head.  <p>
 The day after his hearings on Orange Count, Alan Greenspan returnsto Capitol Hill and seems, for once, to be playing the Washingtongame. Everyone takes it for granted that he appears in the samenavy-blue suit of the day before: When he testifies before Congress,Greenspan seldom wears anything but a navy-blue suit, for thevery good reason that it's pretty much the only type of suithe owns.  His ex-wife Joan Mitchell Blumenthal, with whom he'sstill close, recalls helping clean out his closet several yearsago.  "I found a long row of identical navy suits," she says. "I said, 'I want to get rid of ten of these.  Which ones shouldI take?' He said, 'You choose.' And so I did.  It didn't matter!They were all the same."  <p>
 Leaning heavily upon his nose, Greenspan now offers the Republicanparty a plum: The new Congress might cut $50 billion a year fromthe deficit, he says, simply by instituting a more accurate cost-of-livingindex for Social Security payments.  The idea gets front-pageattention - and it's a measure of Greenspan's credibility thatno one asks the obvious question:  Why now?  Greenspan has beenadvising the Clinton administration on deficit reduction fromthe start.  As former chairman of Reagan' Commission on SocialSecurity, he certainly knew the facts all along.  <p>
 One thing can explain it: The Republicans now control Congress. Treated nicely, they're more likely to act on his proposal torequire the Fed by law to reduce the inflation rate to zero. What's more, they're more likely to insist that Clinton appointGreenspan to a third term at the Federal Reserve.  "People insidethe Fed," says former Fed staffer Walker Todd, "assume that beingrenominated for a third term is the driving goal of Alan's life- and that everything he does now is to that end."  <p>
 Most people in Washington will tell you that Alan Greenspanis just another player.  The system has worked Greenspan morethan Greenspan as worked the system, they'll say.  After all,he came to Washington  opposing regulation, and he's now themost powerful regulator in town.  He's picked up a tennis gameso he can schmooze on the court - occasionally in black socks. He's even found himself another powerful newswoman, Andrea Mitchellof NBC.  <p>
 But to me a more persuasive view is that Greenspan has builta better Randian mousetrap.  He has preserved a hard core offanaticism y encasing it in a shell of pragmatism.  No more waitingfor everyone to realize that extreme laissez-faire capitalismis the best system: He's taking control of the process himself,every so quietly.  "Alan believes that there needs to be a transitionperiod," Joan Mitchell Blumenthal told me.  "He thinks we willget to where he wants to go - but that it will take time."  <p>
 Still, not long ago his former wife suggested to Greenspan thathe might be growing soft in his old age - that politics mighthave compromised him more than he thought.  "I haven't changedmy mind," he said. "About anything."  <p>
  <hr>  <p>
