<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/03-Wal-Mart Government</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Wal-Mart Government</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/03-Wal-Mart Government</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						March 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Experts  <p> <a name="NYSE:WMT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11600"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>WAL-MART</b></a> GOVERNMENT <p>Yes, government has to become smaller. So that it can later become bigger and more powerful than ever.  <p> By Walter Mead  <p> As the exhilarated Republican majority filed into Congress last January, it had one overriding goal: to shrink the federal government. Some functions would be turned back to state and local governments, some would be abolished altogether, and some would be placed in private hands. Anguished Democrats howled in pain; the sacred cows of the New Deal state were destined for the butcher's block. Much of this Democratic breast-beating, as well as much Republican rectitude, was simply political posturing, of course. Not all the sacred cows will end up as hamburger. Republicans have special interests, just as Democrats do; hardly anybody really wants to get rid of all government waste.  <p> Like most U.S. taxpayers, I'm accustomed to studied rhetorical poses followed by carefully contrived votes, so the current congressional debate doesn't offend me on the grounds of either morality or good taste. But I am deeply worried by what I've heard so far. I'm increasingly convinced that both the triumphant Republicans and the shattered Democrats badly misunderstand the crisis of government that the nation faces as it heads into the 21st century. <p> Many readers of this column probably expect me to side with the Democrats, so let me begin by saying that Newt Gingrich and his allies are right: Government has got to go under the knife. We can no longer tolerate either the bureaucratic inefficiencies of the New Deal state or the economic waste that results from the tangled and irrational system of subsidies and regulations that proceed from it. We need to stop warehousing surplus corn in Iowa and "surplus" people in public-housing projects.  <p> But the new Republican majority in the U.S. Congress is wrong to think that we will need less government in the future than we have had in the past. Actually, the opposite is true. We will need even more government in the 21st century than we do today. We need government reform so urgently because the explosive, inevitable growth in government that is rapidly approaching could bankrupt our country.  <p> Let me suggest a way to think about this crisis. The U.S. government is a giant service company. Over the years, as its customers asked it to deliver more and more services--adding Social Security in the 1930s and environmental protection in the 1970s, for example--the expense of government climbed. Now, there's nothing wrong with expenses going up in a situation like that--in most businesses selling more products or providing a greater volume of service costs more. But in successful businesses, as volume increases, unit costs go down. Overhead--rent, utilities, and such--gets amortized over a larger customer base; managers discover ways to serve 11 customers well with the staff that once served 10; assembly lines steadily run at top speed so that each widget costs less to produce. Companies that grow revenues but that allow their cost per unit produced to climb also eventually become high-cost producers. And they either go out of business, savaged by more efficient competitors, or reorganize themselves.  <p> How has the government done in these terms? In constant 1987 dollars, the federal budget has grown to $1.121 trillion in 1993 from $832 billion in 1980. At the same time, the country's population has climbed to 258 million from 227 million. On a unit-cost basis--dollars of spending per capita-- the cost of government went up to $4,345 in 1993 from $3,665, almost a 20 percent increase after correcting for inflation. To judge from the last election, very few taxpayers feel that the quality and quantity of services the government delivers justify that kind of price increase.  <p> Anybody who believes that we can reduce the unit cost by providingless government in the future is swimming against the tide of history. Survey the reasons we have government at all--to ensure national security, to preserve public order, to defend the political, religious, and property rights of individuals, and to provide "common goods" such as universal education and a healthful environment. Providing each of these services is more complicated and expensive in the 20th century than it was in the 19th, and it will be more expensive still in the 21st.  <p> Two basic forces drive this process: demographics and technology. The American population is getting larger and older, and American society is getting more complex. It all adds up to a demand for more of what government provides.   <p> A larger population, obviously enough, needs more government than a smaller one, just as it needs more homes and more food. But the population won't just be larger. It will also be older--and old people need more protection and care than young ones. Unless we plan to put the old folks on ice floes, we are somehow going to have to find a way to feed, clothe, protect, and offer medical services to a much larger elderly population. Some of their needs will breed profit-making companies in the private sector. But some of the increased services that this aging population needs will be provided by the government--or by no one at all. And the voting power of this age group guarantees that their needs will be met.  <p> The growing technological complexity of modern life will also create new demands for expensive government services across the board. Just look at education, for example. As recently as 1960 only about 40 percent of Americans over 25 years old had finished four years of high school; in 1993 more than 80 percent did. While the percentage of Americans who had finished high school was doubling, the percentage of Americans finishing college quadrupled. In 1960, American junior colleges, colleges, and universities awarded a total of 477,000 degrees; they are projected to award 2,355,000 in 2003.  <p> Tomorrow's economy will require an even better-trained work force--one in which workers will have to be taught new skills several times during their working lives. Private institutions will not be able to handle the numbers of students who will need advanced education in the United States, and most students will not be able to afford the tuition charged by private institutions. Our society could, of course, decide that it won't pay the bills for educating these citizens. But a country that won't pay to train its future wage earners faces a dark future in a globally competitive economy.   <p> But no matter how many billions our children and grandchildren spend on education, they are likely to find that the problem of welfare refuses to go away and that the portion of the population needing at least temporary aid is, in fact, growing. As machines take over more low-productivity work, what will today's low-wage workers do? The answer is certain to involve more government money.  <p> At the same time as technological progress makes it harder for some people to compete in the job market, it also increases the minimum level of goods and services that poor people need, if they or their children are to have any chance of participating in our economy. A century ago nobody thought of electricity and central heating as necessities; today, telephones and sophisticated medical care figure into our calculations of how to care for the poor. In 2010 the right of all school children to have access to computers will be as important as their right to textbooks is today; only government can pay for these new necessities for those unable to afford them.   <p> We might as well face it: The electronic revolution and the third wave aren't going to abolish our dependence on government. Our grandchildren will consume more government than we do. There is nothing new in that; we use more government than our grandparents did. Progress defers death at the cost of higher taxes; it's a good bargain, all things considered.  <p> The Republican task today is not so much to shrink the amount of government we consume as to cut the unit cost of government. This effort to reform our government is part of the broader restructuring of the economy. In a postindustrial society productivity grow thin services increasingly determines a country's overall growth in living standards. Government--state, federal, and local--is the largest employer in the country; changing it from a sclerotic bureaucracy to something leaner and meaner--from a tortoise into a velociraptor--won't make it weaker or smaller but will enable it and us to survive in the 21st century.   <p> There is no escaping the irony. In bringing down the unit cost of government, in stripping it to its essential functions, in restoring its legitimacy by bringing it closer to the people, the Republicans in Congress are not, as some of them think, permanently reducing the size of the federal government. Instead, they are preparing the way for the government of the future: bigger and more powerful than anything Americans have ever seen. Whether he knows it or not, Newt Gingrich is the servant of generations of bureaucrats yet to be born.  <p>Walter Mead is the Presidential Fellow at the World Policy Institute at the New School. Research assistance: Adam Feibelman.  <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Government Legislation, National Politics<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

