<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/10-Loosening the Purse Strings</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Loosening the Purse Strings</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/10-Loosening the Purse Strings</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						October 1994
Worth magazine/Features<p>LOOSENING THE PURSE STRINGS
Emily's List founder Ellen Malcolm wants other women to realize their financial power -- and use it to change politics.<p>By Maureen Down<p>Next month, Ellen Malcolm faces the first major election cycle since her nine-year-old fund-raising group, Emily's List, helped define 1992 as the media-friendly Year of the Woman. In that year, Emily's List became the largest contributor to congressional campaigns via its innovative strategy of collecting members' donation checks and presenting them en masse to candidates early in a campaign. ("Emily" isn't a person; it's an acronym that stands for "Early money is like yeast.") <p>Malcolm's group had a huge effect on the Washington landscape in 1992; its policy of supporting only pro-choice woman Democrats helped swell that group's representation in Congress -- threefold in the House. For the 47-year-old heiress to an <a name="NYSE:IBM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10796"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>IBM</b></a> fortune, the intervening years haven't been trouble-free. Campaign-finance reforms have threatened the loophole that allows Emily's List members to make checks out to specific candidates so they're counted as individual donations, avoiding the $10,000 lid on PAC donations. Malcolm also has been tagged as the queen of a new machine -- substituting another exclusive network for the old-boy's club she set out to smash. <p>To explore the new financial heft of women in politics and its effect in 1994 and beyond, Maureen Dowd visited Malcolm at her elegant home on a leafy street in northwest Washington, D.C.<p>Q: Emily's List supplies a kind of backing no power broker can dismiss -- cold cash and plenty of it. How did you kick start giving to women candidates?<p>A: We began with a lot of assumptions about how women had changed. One was that we had outgrown the bake-sale mentality of the 1970s -- that there were many women out there who, with a little encouragement, would write a $100 check rather than a $10 one. Our entire effort was to get women to write $100 checks. Now that amount is almost the coin of the realm.<p>Q: Why hadn't women added zeros before?<p>A: I think there are two parts to it. One is that women didn't have economic power until the late 1970s and 1980s, when they began to make their own money. But they also had to make a psychological shift -- to understand that they had the resources and they could do what they wanted with them.<p>Q: Does this have a parallel in your own life? It wasn't until ten years ago that you came to terms with your own money. You kept your wealth a secret, fearing people would dislike you if you used it publicly.<p>A: Well, I did come out of the philanthropic closet, as I put it, in the early 1980s. I finally told people I was the one making all those anonymous contributions. And when I could see the usefulness of my money, I became much more comfortable doing things with it that I thought were important.<p>Q: But why did it take so long to see the link between your money and your goals?<p>A: I think part of it was growing up and maturing, understanding that I didn't have to be concerned about people's stereotypes. In a lot of ways, Emily's List has empowered me just as much as it has helped our members and the candidates we support.<p>Q: Perhaps you hesitated to use your wealth because society trains women to spend money, not to use it.<p>A: Certainly women are not taught to wield financial power -- or political power. It's something we have to learn and teach ourselves. And we have to do it in a way that's comfortable for us.<p>Q: So what's a comfortable style for women when it comes to political giving?<p>A: I think women find ways to do things collectively. That's certainly what Emily's List has done. It's not about having three people writing $100,000 checks; it's having a collection of people writing their small checks, all of us doing it together, making a difference. Women candidates rely on small contributors, people writing $25, $35, $50 checks. What we need is for women to write larger checks -- to seize their economic power and write the checks they can afford. So now we're seeing $100 checks and $1,000 checks.<p>Q: But it takes a lot of those to add up to one $100,000 check. How can this kind of giving ever be efficient?<p>A: Suppose you're a schoolteacher in Omaha and you want to be represented in Congress by women. You may not have a woman running in Omaha -- but you know about a Lynn Rivers running for the House in Michigan or an Ann Wynia running for the Senate in Minnesota. Emily's List lets you support these women effectively. We empower our members by combining all their small contributions to build a powerful resource. That's grass-roots participation.<p>Q: It's also threatening, apparently. What do you say to people who want to ban your "bundling" of checks as an end run around the rules on special-interest giving?<p>A: I don't think they look at the differences between how men and women raise money. They think anyone who can figure out how to get money flowing into the political system must be doing something wrong and should be stopped. I disagree.<p>Q: It's funny this issue should arise just as money is being used to gain power -- not just to preserve power via the fund-raising prowess of incumbents.<p>A: I was surprised, too. We came out of the 1992 elections showing we could bring women into the process. And all of a sudden we were decried by so-called reformers.<p>Q: Emily's List now has a big pot of cash; that means everyone is your friend. For a woman who grew up not wanting to be treated differently because of her money, all this sucking up must be bothersome.<p>A: Yeah, I don't care for it much. I don't like being schmoozed or having people be nice to me because they want something. But it's the way the game is played, and you identify it for what it is. I spend my private life separating myself from that world.<p>Q: But if women gain power just because they now have money to spend, is there any real moral victory?<p>A: I think what we're doing gives women a lot of power, and I think that's a very good thing. Ultimately I think it means women everywhere will be treated more seriously. We're building a very visual, visible picture of women with power. That's a healthy thing for this country.<p>Q: Does it matter that the most visible woman in Washington right now derives her power from being a wife?<p>A: She also derives her power from being very smart and very effective.<p>Q: Okay, but when will we have a woman as president? Is there enough money in the world to pull that off?<p>A: I think we're closer than we may realize. As we begin to get women into top office, we're building a field team for the presidency. I wouldn't be surprised in the next eight years to see a woman as a major contender for president.<p>Q: Is raising money harder now that you have more friends in Washington? Do women respond better when they're fighting a villain, as in the aftermath of the Anita Hill controversy?<p>A: I think some issue groups are having a harder time. But we're now about 34,000 members, compared with 24,000 in 1992, the so-called Year of the Woman. We've just broken the $5 million mark for money to candidates, so we'll certainly raise more money in 1994 than we did in 1992. I think women are sticking with it. 
---------------
Maureen Dowd covers politics for The New York Times.<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Politics

