<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/09-Why Shareholder Suits Don't Pay</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/09-Why Shareholder Suits Don't Pay</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
They make lawyers rich, but investors get a pittance.<p>By Bruce Upbin<p>Settlements in securities class-action suits topped $1.4 billion last year, just shy of the $1.5 billion record set in 1992. With all that cash being wrung from alleged wrongdoers, you might think that shareholders, the victims in these cases, are being compensated for their troubles. <p>Guess again.<p>A little investigation shows that class-action suits almost always result in a settlement so small as to be a fraction of the shareholders' total financial loss. After the court determines what fees it will be deducting -- for plaintiffs' attorneys, the claims administrator, and the costs of serving notice -- investors split what remains, which is not a lot. According to a study conducted last year by National Economic Research Associates, a consulting firm in White Plains, New York, shareholders receive an average of 7 cents on the dollar when they sue.<p>When negotiations for settlements in a case begin, defendants and plaintiffs must agree on how much money shareholders actually lost to fraud versus how much was lost because of volatility in the stock or the overall market. This agreement is usually a compromise, struck after vehement arguments from both sides. Expert witnesses are called in to study stock-price patterns and trading volume for the period involved, and they come up with the amount of losses shareholders can legally claim.<p>"What you have to look at is the recoverable damages, which can be much less than what you lost in the market," says William Lerach, a plaintiff's lawyer with Milberg Weiss Bershad Hynes & Lerach in New York City and California.<p>Once losses are determined, plaintiffs' attorneys begin negotiating for the class award. In theory, they're dealing on behalf of the shareholders, but in truth, having a horde of clients is like having no true client. <p>In the case of a company that has little to offer the plaintiffs, lawyers may negotiate an award of stock. If this happens, defrauded investors and their lawyers are both paid in stock rather than cash.<p>"The plaintiff bar is experienced in what kinds of moves would find a better audience, they know what people are willing to agree to, and then they get their fees," says Roberta Romano, a professor at Yale University's law school. <p>In isolated cases, attorneys have earned bonanza settlements for defrauded clients; in S&L crook Charles Keating's Lincoln Savings case, investors received close to 100 cents on the dollar. But that, says Lerach, was a "remarkable recovery because we were able to sue the accountants and lawyers, too."<p>Such stellar recoveries now may be a thing of the past. A U.S. Supreme Court decision last spring restricted the plaintiff bar's ability to go after deep-pocketed law and accounting firms associated with fraudulent companies.<p>A catch-22 of class-action suits is this: If you have any qualms with the settlement and want to hire your own lawyer to negotiate, you must opt out of the plaintiff class before you know what your share of the settlement would be. If you stay in to find out, you must abide by the judge's decision and the approved settlement. <p>"Bringing your own case would only be beneficial if you can convince the defendants in negotiation that you'll be willing to go all the way to trial," says Boston class-action attorney Glen DeValerio. His firm, Berman, DeValerio & Pease, has represented shareholders with substantial individual holdings who broke off from the larger class and, in some cases, extracted a higher per-share recovery. <p>The key to success in a class-action suit is to get in early. If your broker is forthright, he or she should tell you if a company in which you own stock is being sued. Newspapers and financial documents, such as annual reports or quarterly statements, are two other places to look for notice of pending litigation. Once you know the story, get in touch with the plaintiff attorneys and stay in touch with them. Ask questions about what they're negotiating for. What kind of inquiries are they making? Are they doing anything at all? After all, they're supposed to be representing you.<p>If they don't give you straight answers, feel free to write the judge presiding over the case. "If a lawyer is unresponsive, the judge will consider that in his fee decisions and the next time around when that lawyer asks to represent a class," says DeValerio.<p>Because you'll need to prove that you were a shareholder of record during the time of alleged fraud as designated by the court, good record keeping is a must. Occasionally plaintiff classes are divided into separate time periods, and one class may be entitled to a larger recovery. You'll have to submit copies of your trade confirmation slips or account statements, which could be two or three years old. <p>Given the minuscule amounts typically won by shareholders in these suits, it's obvious that the only folks getting rich off class-action suits are the litigators. And considering the not insignificant amount of energy that participants need to expend to get what's coming to them in a claim, you're probably better off taking your losses and moving on. Winning a case against a fraudulent management may satisfy your sense of justice, but it will do very little for your net worth.<p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

