<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/08-Grandmother's House They Go</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/08-Grandmother's House They Go</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						July/August 1994 <p>Worth magazine/Features  <p> TO GRANDMOTHER'S HOUSE THEY GO <p>Lyndon LaRouche is out of prison. As he prepares to reenter politics,his fund-raisers are accused of pressuring the elderly -- again.Is your parents' nest egg at risk?  <p> By Christopher Byron  <p> Follow Route 7 west as it meanders out of Alexandria, Virginia,and eventually you'll arrive at a wide spot in the road calledRound Hill. The village lies at the foot of the Blue Ridge Mountains,about 12 miles west of Leesburg, the Loudoun County seat. There'sa post office, an Amoco station, a coffee shop. And that's aboutit for this rusting and run-down embodiment of every backwateron every two-lane country road that time has passed by.  <p> Make a few turns, however, and soon you'll lurch down a stone-stubbleddirt lane and into today's headlines. At the end of this roughroad dwells Lyndon LaRouche, 71, the first man since legendarylabor leader Eugene Debs to run a semicredible presidential campaignfrom a federal penitentiary. Recently released on parole afterserving five years on charges of conspiracy, tax fraud, and mailfraud, the charismatic LaRouche is now gathering federal fundsto match donations he amassed during his last run for the presidency.As the tax dollars start flowing toward his little-known retreat,LaRouche prepares for a sixth assault on the White House -- andhis cultlike organization shows signs of blossoming once more.On a recent spring day, this rebirth seems a grim counterpointto the crocuses and daffodils that swell with life in hedgerowsacross the Loudoun County countryside.  <p> LaRouche is unrepentant for his crimes, believing he was railroadedbecause of his political agenda. And what an agenda it is: Thoughhe sometimes sounds thoughtful, as with his calls for an investmenttax credit and a 1 percent tax on certain Wall Street trades,many more of his pronouncements verge on lunacy. Most famously,he has tarred Queen Elizabeth II as a drug dealer.  <p> But to focus on LaRouche's curious politics is to miss the point.The crimes that landed him in prison with disgraced televangelistJim Bakker were altogether mundane -- a perfect case study ofan increasingly common fraud: sucking the wealth from lonely,vulnerable old people. According to court records, LaRouche directedhis followers in a systematic and illegal effort to bamboozleelderly folk into giving large "loans" to his cause.  <p> As a result, LaRouche is now a felon who won't be allowed tovote for himself in the 1996 election. Most law-enforcement authoritiesconsider his case to be closed. But a three-month Worth investigationindicates that LaRouche's followers never stopped pressuringold people for cash even while their leader was behind bars.Indeed, an emerging pattern of lawsuits and investigations showsthat, at least until last winter, the LaRouchies continued toraise money using methods only slightly different from the schemethat put LaRouche himself away.  <p> This time, however, old people are largely being left to fendfor themselves. Why? In part because the LaRouchies have droppedthe illegal pretense that contributors would get their moneyback. Meanwhile, strained by drugs and violent crime, the criminal-justicesystem has little time for folks who get talked into giving alltheir money away. Only one criminal investigation, in New Mexico,is known to be underway against LaRouche fund-raisers.  <p> As a result, civil suits against the LaRouchies have been sproutingacross the country. Court documents allege that LaRouche followershave improperly taken hundreds of thousands of dollars from elderlycontributors -- in extreme cases, hitting up mentally impairedpeople and even a patient in a nursing home. LaRouche refusesto be interviewed by Worth. A spokeswoman says he has never beeninvolved in any illegal or improper fund-raising tactics, includingthose for which he served time.  <p> But it's clear that LaRouche draws heavily on elderly peoplefor his financial support. Consider this fact: LaRouche receivedless than 1 percent of the votes in the 1992 presidential election.Yet from a prison cell he gathered more than $1 million in contributionsfrom people listing their occupation as "retiree." That's almostas much as George Bush and Bill Clinton combined. LaRouche officialssay this is because older people love LaRouche's politics. Maybe.But in court documents more evocative of the telemarketing industrythan of mainstream politics, a number of elderly contributorssay they were simply flustered out of their money by fast-talkingLaRouchies.  <p>   <p> Not so long ago, middle-aged parents feared that their teenagechildren would fall into the clutches of a mind-grabbing cultsuch as the Moonies. Today, it's their elderly parents who areat risk. The reason is simple: money.  <p> Three decades ago, the plight of America's elderly was the shameof the world's wealthiest nation. In their landmark study Generations:The History of America's Future, 1584 to 2069, William Straussand Neil Howe describe old age in the 1950s and 1960s as "America'sunhappiest, loneliest, and poorest age bracket." But thanks tothe indexing of Social Security benefits and the welfare activismof the 1970s and 1980s, the elderly poverty rate "has fallenfrom the highest of any age bracket to well below the rate forchildren and young adults," write Strauss and Howe. Accordingto U.S. census data, the median net worth of households headedby people 65 or older was $73,500 in 1992 -- more than twicethe national average.  <p> As a result of their remarkable progress, the elderly are nowprime targets for aggressive fund-raisers of all stripes. A recentstudy by Princeton Survey Research Associates found that people75 or older are nearly five times as likely to be victims offraud as are people ages 18 to 64. At congressional hearingslast year, Kenneth Eikenberry, former attorney general of Washingtonstate, testified that the elderly are the biggest target of the$40-billion-a-year business of telemarketing fraud. And thisisn't likely to abate anytime soon. Thanks to advances in medicine,the elderly are also the fastest-growing segment of the population. <p> Elderly women are particularly susceptible to financial scams.Margaret Singer of the University of California at Berkeley,a well-known authority on pressure tactics, notes that many womennow in their 70s or 80s have gone through life with little orno exposure to financial decision making. Because women livesix years longer than men on average, many elderly women inheritlarge estates but have no idea what to do with the money. Oftensuggestible and sometimes not of completely sound mind, suchwidows are uniquely vulnerable to smooth talkers who ask formoney.  <p> By coincidence or design, these individuals are a favorite fundingsource of the LaRouche organization.  <p>   <p> LaRouche doesn't welcome visitors to his bucolic Round Hillcompound. An electrically operated gate bars the driveway; asurveillance camera scans from the trunk of a tree. On a postby the gate sits a metal box with a telephone linked to the housebeyond, a large but seemingly neglected fieldstone affair that'sbarely visible amid a stand of trees. Ask for admittance, butdon't expect much sympathy from the young man at the other end.Mr. LaRouche, it seems, is not receiving. In a farmhouse acrossthe lane, an elderly woman peers from behind lace curtains, thencautiously cracks the door to confirm her neighbor's identity."I don't pay him no mind," she declares as a chicken cackleson her front stoop. Out in the driveway, a dog crawls from undera dilapidated old car that's filled with cardboard and rags. <p> Not long ago, LaRouche lived in far lusher surroundings. Hecounted Saudi Arabian royalty among his neighbors and held forthfor the U.S. presidency from a luxurious 170-acre estate in Leesburg,Virginia. According to court testimony, he used plentiful fund-raisingproceeds to feed prime cuts of meat to his dog; donations werealso used to construct a swimming pool and to buy china and silverware.The property itself was bought, with LaRouche organization money,in the name of a right-wing Oklahoma oilman. But when LaRouchestarted tangling with the feds, his organization fell behindon payments and ultimately abandoned the lush property. Todaythe house lies empty, its grounds growing over with vines andweeds.  <p> Despite its diminished circumstances, the LaRouche organizationisn't nearly as dormant as its former HQ. High-profile prosecutionshave made it hard for LaRouche to attract new recruits. But still,even after four years on hiatus, as they say in Hollywood, he'sstarting to draw attention once more. For one thing, there'shis apparent resolve to start a sixth consecutive presidentialcampaign. That's business as usual. LaRouche supporters alsoplan to run in state and local elections across the country thisautumn, says LaRouche spokeswoman Dana Scanlon. The candidates'theme: "Lyndon was right," a blow-by-blow accounting of all theLaRouche positions that have been borne out by events. The groupcould make itself a pest in Virginia's senate race, where disenchantmentwith Democratic incumbent Charles Robb and his Republican challengerOliver North runs high.  <p> Meanwhile, the LaRouche organization continues to put its stampon the issues of the day. A recent example: LaRouchies believethe Whitewater scandal is a fabrication of British intelligence,in league with Wall Street, the Zionist conspiracy, and the Anti-DefamationLeague of B'nai B'rith. Also high on the current LaRouche hitparade: The activities of international business figures suchas George Soros and Edgar Bronfman, who have been attacked asLaRouche enemies. And in recent months, LaRouche supporters haveformed an ominous alliance with Louis Farrakhan's fiery Nationof Islam, jointly picketing the ADL's offices in Washington,D.C.  <p> With such feverish activity, it's easy to miss the real LaRouchenews: a largely unreported but growing number of allegationsthat LaRouche operatives have again been raising money unethically.A search of courthouse and media records, along with interviewsof contributors and their families, reveals a discernible pattern.Claims range from the Pacific Northwest to New York's Long Island,but they share a common theme: the befriending of elderly peoplewho are alone and looking for comfort. Says Singer, the Berkeleyexpert on pressure tactics: "In America more than in any othercountry, the elderly are isolated and cut off from their ownchildren. They're lonely and vulnerable. That's when you getNew Age groups, scam artists, cults, and opportunists movingin."  <p> All the following cases, which span a period from 1989 to lastautumn, arose after LaRouche was convicted of fund-raising fraud: <p> -> In Pennsylvania, an ailing 86-year-old named Herbert Royergave away virtually all his life savings of $80,000 after a fund-raiserbegan visiting him in a nursing home and showed him a LaRouchevideo. Royer's daughter, Ann Coleman, didn't figure out whatwas happening until, on a visit from Connecticut, she saw a thank-younote from a LaRouchie. Realizing his mistake, former accountantRoyer sank into depression and died soon afterward. Coleman suedthe LaRouchies and won an out-of-court settlement.  <p> -> In Illinois, an 86-year-old widow named Harriet Driver waspersuaded by LaRouchies to hand over $70,000. A criminal prosecutionfollowed, but on her first day of testimony Driver, who livedalone, keeled over in the witness stand from a stroke. A mistrialwas declared, and the prosecutor dropped the charges rather thansubject Driver to another trial. The LaRouchies promptly suedthe prosecutor for $30 million, claiming he was part of a conspiracy,but the suit was thrown out.  <p> -> In Oregon, an 81-year-old widow, Vida Trout, was talked outof nearly $80,000 by two young LaRouche fund-raisers from LosAngeles. They began by taking her shopping and out to lunch --activities her own children no longer had time for. The moneystopped flowing only when Trout's son Bill kicked the LaRouchiesout of his mother's house. The case was investigated by the Oregonattorney general, but no charges were filed.  <p> -> In Minnesota, Jane Young, an 86-year-old widow sufferingfrom dementia, wound up giving a fortune to LaRouchies. Courtdocuments allege that fund-raisers approached Young for a $35donation and within six weeks had talked her out of 1,400 sharesof CPC International and 600 shares of Exxon -- a total takeof about $117,000. Young sued to recover the money and settledout of court.  <p> -> In New York, 79-year-old retired telephone operator LydiaBaldasar forked over $70,000 to LaRouchies, then suffered a pangof remorse and told her son-in-law, a lawyer. He froze her assets,fired writs in all directions, then sued and recovered a settlementfor almost 95 percent of what had been taken.  <p> There are more stories. Perhaps most startling is the well-publicizedcase of Helen Overington, an 86-year-old widow from Baltimorewho, according to a lawsuit filed in late March, was targetedin 1989 by a star LaRouche fund-raiser named Rochelle Ascher.At the time, Ascher was free on bail, pending appeal of an 86-yearsentence for fund-raising fraud. By the time Ascher was done,Overington had become the LaRouchies' very own sugar grandma,handing over three quarters of a million dollars in all. As describedin court records and interviews, Ascher's work was an objectlesson in exploiting the elderly.  <p>   <p> Helen and Bruce Overington were the perfect Currier & Ives couple:hardworking, God-fearing Republicans who raised five childrenon their Pennsylvania farm near the Maryland border. When Brucedied in 1970, his family was amazed to find just how much hehad salted away -- a portfolio worth almost $1 million in thebest bonds and blue-chip stocks. He left it all to Helen, thena spry 63.  <p> Overington showered her children and grandchildren with giftsand gave grants to worthy causes. In 1974, seeking perhaps torecapture her youth in Baltimore, she bought an apartment thereand returned to her college town. Overington enjoyed life asan independent woman of means, and the bull market of the 1980sensured that her wealth kept swelling no matter how generousshe was. Until the LaRouchies came to visit, that is.  <p> "Even to this day we don't know how they got Mom's name," saysher daughter, Margaret Weller. "But we're fairly certain it wasbecause of all these mailing lists she was on. She would givemoney to almost anything -- $10 to this, $20 to that." In fact,say law-enforcement officials, mailing lists for conservativecauses are a classic starting point for LaRouche fund-raisers.(Senator Jesse Helms's contributor list is a particular favorite.)And the successful sale of a subscription to a LaRouche-affiliatedpublication is a classic tip-off that there's more money to behad.  <p> This is exactly what happened to Overington. The telephone rangat her Baltimore apartment one day in January 1989, and a mantold her about a LaRouche magazine called Executive IntelligenceReview. The price, Overington learned, was "two-fifty," whichshe took to mean $2.50. Overington offered to mail a check, butthe man wanted the money that afternoon -- and he was willingto send a messenger around to collect the payment. Overingtonleft a check with her doorman and departed for some errands. <p> When Overington returned, the man phoned her again. There wasa misunderstanding, he said: The price wasn't $2.50 -- it was$250. Could he send someone around to collect the correct amount?In about, say, an hour? Uncertainty gave way to embarrassment,and she agreed. In the following weeks, LaRouchies called onher often. Overington says they reminded her of her own children,whom she didn't see much anymore. They'd talk for hours on eachvisit, railing sympathetically about drugs and Communism, twoof her greatest fears.  <p> "They gave me a book on the German philosopher Schiller," Overingtonrecalls in a voice that's sweet but bone tired. "They were sointelligent and well-versed. They flattered me and made me feelsmart. They knew just what buttons to push." She wrote more checks.For $1,000. For $6,000. For $10,000. Before long, the LaRouchieshad convinced Overington to give them an accounting of everythingshe had in her portfolio -- a veritable gold mine. At that, theybrought in one of the organization's heaviest hitters, convictedfelon Rochelle Ascher.  <p> "The first time I met her she didn't even ask for any money,"Overington remembers. But on her second visit Ascher asked Overingtonto drive to Waynesboro, Pennsylvania, where Overington kept mostof her stocks and bonds in a safe-deposit box. Overington tookout 500 shares of Atlantic Richfield and sold them, later handingmore than $45,000 to Ascher. "It made me feel good to give sucha big amount," Overington says now. And so it went for months:the CSX stock, the Colgate, the General Motors, the IBM, untilmore than $740,000 had slipped through Overington's fingers andinto LaRouche operations.  <p> Overington says Ascher and the other LaRouchies always visitedin the late afternoons and evenings. That's when old people areless alert and more easily confused. "They would stay for hoursand hours, sometimes until after midnight," Overington says."It was as if I had to pay them to leave. They constantly askedme about my children and grandchildren. But they also asked menot to tell my family because they wouldn't understand."  <p> Small wonder: Within nine months, Overington had given awayalmost all of the nest egg that she and her children had expectedwould put the grandchildren through college. The crisis camewhen Overington couldn't afford Christmas presents -- or herhealth insurance, or her apartment, or anything else in her life."I just didn't realize what I was doing until it was too late,"she says sheepishly. Overington decided to sue, but not untila few months ago could her family find a lawyer willing to tanglewith LaRouche and Ascher on a contingency basis -- the LaRouchiesplay hardball and they keep little wealth in seizable assets. <p> Ascher hasn't filed a response to Overington's lawsuit; shedidn't reply to messages left with her attorney and probationofficer. According to news reports, however, she has defendedher fund-raising tactics in court, saying she would "only solicitfrom people who express sympathy for [LaRouche's] politics andgive willingly."  <p> If Helen Overington is an instance of the LaRouchies' prowessat big-ticket fund-raising, Nora Keith appears to be an exampleof their shamelessness. Keith, 87, lives alone on a meager fixedincome in the Oregon logging town of Vernonia, population 1,700.About the same time fellow Oregonian Vida Trout was being relievedof $75,000, two LaRouche fund-raisers from Los Angeles paid Keitha visit in her modest home, apparently drawn by her history ofgiving to just about every charity or political group that senther a letter.  <p> According to her companion Patricia Schmidlin, Keith had beenscraping by on $600 a month from Social Security and a retirementpension. But it wasn't quite enough to live on, so she had recentlysold off the wooded front yard of her house for $25,000. Accordingto Schmidlin, no sooner did Keith get the money than she begangiving it away. Before long there was only about $5,000 left.That's when the LaRouchies arrived.  <p> "Nora has had many strokes, and her mind is going," says Schmidlin."These two people came and got her to donate $65 to publish politicalpamphlets. Then they came back a couple of weeks later and talkedher out of $500 more. They told her it was to help get LyndonLaRouche out of prison. Then they came back the next day andfixed her lunch, and buttered her up, and found out she stillhad some money in an insurance annuity -- $4,823.99 to be precise.So they got her to cash that out and give it to them too. Thenthey left."  <p> The Oregon attorney general's office looked into the case butdecided not to file charges. "Nora hadn't been forced to handover the money," explains Schmidlin.  <p>   <p> Who is Lyndon LaRouche, anyway? Like the unsavory details ofthe LaRouchies' money-raising tactics, it's a question that getslost amid his constant stream of quotable paranoia. But ridiculeof LaRouche's theories doesn't begin to address the phenomenonof a man who has tapped extremist views -- from Marxism in the'50s to ultra-rightism from the '70s on -- to gain the platformfrom which he heads a cadre of the nation's most aggressive politicalfund-raisers.  <p> One person who admits puzzlement is LaRouche's first wife, Janice,who met him through socialist friends in 1954 after he movedto New York from his hometown of Lynn, Massachusetts. Trackeddown in her new life as a career consultant, Janice LaRouchesays she knows little of the man she was married to for eightyears, saying they didn't live together for much of that time.But press her on the matter and she haltingly presents an imageof a man drawn to Marxism out of genuine concern for the troubledand downtrodden. "He was from a Quaker family," she says. "Hewas very nice, very kind. He spent astonishing amounts of timebeing helpful to people -- people with problems." She says she'samazed at the transformation of her ex-husband from far-leftistto far-rightist in the years after their 1962 divorce.  <p> Others say they aren't surprised at all. Christian Curtis, aformer longtime LaRouchie who was a star witness against LaRoucheat one of his trials, says his old boss is motivated by nothingbut a lust for power and influence. When the country swung awayfrom liberalism in the 1970s, says Curtis, LaRouche found theeasiest way to remain in the game: "He simply changed sides andbegan rationalizing it."  <p> Whatever his motivation, the constant in LaRouche's life hasbeen a need for political involvement. As with so many politicianstoday, his defining time was the late 1960s. It was a time ofupheaval: The Berkeley free-speech movement had sparked campusturmoil nationwide. The civil-rights movement, Students for aDemocratic Society, the Vietnam protests  -- all were symptomsof the most dramatic social convulsion in generations. And LyndonLaRouche, a gentle-souled Marxist who was older than most ofthe era's activists, desperately wanted to be part of the action. <p> Freed of his marriage, LaRouche became a university hanger-on.A college dropout himself, he served without pay as a self-described"professor of physical economics" for a leftist group in NewYork City, attracting several students from elite Columbia University."We started out in 1966 with less than a dozen people, meetingin a living room of about 10-by-14 dimensions," he recalled ina courtroom more than 20 years later. LaRouche cozied up to theColumbia students and used them in his first grab at nationalattention. Playing wise elder to his living-room clique, LaRoucheurged the youngsters to foment a student strike at Columbia in1968 -- remaining out of the spotlight himself should thingsgo wrong. He never quite got control of the political firestormthat followed. But as he would later acknowledge under oath,"Friends of mine actually started the Columbia strike."  <p> Starting around then, LaRouche's followers somehow became convincedtheir leader was an intellectual giant, possessed of a vast andunified vision of economic history from Babylonian times onward.Students from some of the best colleges -- Columbia, Harvard,Williams, Swarthmore -- began clamoring to do "research" forhim. On the cusp of adulthood, these favored few saw in radicalLaRouche, as others saw in the Black Panthers, a thrilling rejectionof America's diseased social order. "When you're 22 years old,that kind of stuff is so impressive it can blow your mind," saysChristian Curtis. "When you're 42, you see it for what it is-- a lot of crap."  <p> Many of LaRouche's original followers left in disgust and aretrying to blot the past from their resumes. Some of the brightestwent on to work at Polyconomics, think-tank home of Jude Wanniski,a darling of the Reagan era. One former early LaRouchie, DavidGoldman, now works as chief of fixed-income research for BearStearns on Wall Street. Another is a civil engineer in California. <p> But LaRouche attracted new recruits and signs of cultdom beganto appear. Former insiders say LaRouche activists were allowedno private property and no money beyond a stipend for rent andfood. Nothing was to detract from loyalty to LaRouche -- noteven children. LaRouche's embrace of Marxism began skidding towardan authoritarian, paranoiac ultra-rightism. Suddenly, it seemed,demons were everywhere. Once, says a former follower, LaRouchebecame convinced that armed Cuban frogmen had jumped off a freighterin New York harbor and were swimming up the Hudson River to gethim. The group became almost paramilitary: Surrounding himselfwith armed bodyguards, LaRouche organized hoodlums to break upCommunist rallies. Some LaRouchies were encouraged to carry nunchakus-- weapons used in martial arts -- and to attend counterterrorismschools. Says Curtis: "I suppose we were all insane."  <p>   <p> By the start of the 1980s, LaRouche had settled his group intothe effective agitprop operation it remains today. Located onseveral floors of a warehouse in Manhattan's fur district, andlater further uptown at Columbus Circle, the operation involvedmore than 100 young activists and organizers. With the ascensionof Ronald Reagan to the presidency, the LaRouchies would reachthe pinnacle of their political influence.  <p> The LaRouche organization had tried for years to cultivate friendsin the Reagan camp. When the new administration opened shop,therefore, LaRouchies suddenly had access to all sorts of informationthey had never seen before. They became a kind of Reagan administrationgrapevine, trading rumors for yet more rumors. The group lovedboasting of its links to schmoozers like Bobby Inman of the CentralIntelligence Agency, who had a meeting with LaRouche himself,and Secretary of the Interior James Watt, who attended a breakfastwith LaRouche operatives. But the exaggeration-prone LaRouchieswere overstating matters, as usual.  <p> All this new activity required more money than ever before.And in 1984 LaRouche launched a major bid for the presidency,forcing his organization to push fund-raising even harder. Soon,abuses were occurring as overaggressive LaRouchies scrambledto meet their leader's goal -- raising enough money to denounceDemocratic candidate Walter Mondale as a Soviet agent on nationaltelevision. The LaRouchies started to catch the eye of the law:The Justice Department received complaints from hundreds of peoplewho claimed they were charged $1,000 each after making credit-carddonations of only $10 or $20 to LaRouche. A federal grand jurybegan hearing evidence.  <p> Around this time, LaRouche decided to move his entire operationcloser to Washington, where he apparently felt destiny was callinghim. The chosen retreat was Leesburg, in the foothills of theBlue Ridge Mountains. The place was tranquil and rural, yet amere 40-minute drive away from the seat of world power and influence. <p> Leesburgers didn't hew to New York's "don't ask, don't tell"approach to neighbors. Through an agent, the LaRouchies had renteda pristine mansion with manicured lawns from ballet legend RudolfNureyev. The first thing they did was put an ugly row of electricallyactivated spikes in the sweeping driveway -- to defend againstunwelcome vehicles. Then the LaRouchies surrounded the groundswith chain-link fencing and surveillance cameras. The groundswent to seed as jeep-loads of armed LaRouchies rumbled to andfrom an office in the town center. LaRouche was photographedwith a pistol strapped to his hip.  <p> Eventually the LaRouchies moved to even grander quarters, a170-acre spread overlooking all of Leesburg. That didn't impressthe peeved locals, including Don Moore, the town's deputy sheriff.The more Moore heard about the new arrivals, the less he likedthem. A quick check told him the LaRouchies were under federalinvestigation; soon he was feeding information to the feds andto a separate state investigation of LaRouche-related frauds.Then the IRS got involved, and LaRouche became the target ofa joint task force based in nearby Alexandria.  <p> The authorities finally moved in on a Monday morning in October1986. About 400 officers cordoned off downtown Leesburg and raidedthe LaRouche offices. Luckily, there was no violent confrontation.The next 36 hours were spent lugging box after box of recordsfrom the building -- the detritus of nearly a decade's worthof LaRouche fund-raising. Two years later LaRouche and six ofhis top aides were indicted on federal charges of conspiracy,mail fraud, and tax fraud. The goverment claimed they had bilkedsupporters out of more than $30 million. The basic swindle involvedborrowing money from contributors -- many of them elderly --on a false promise to repay the funds later. The documents seizedin Leesburg helped prove that the fund-raisers knew they couldn'trepay the loans, yet kept soliciting them anyway.  <p> In fact, the LaRouchies' own records supported the feds' contentionthat for all LaRouche's bluster, his group was little more thana huge, rather paranoid boiler-room operation. field operativesgathered leads at shopping malls and airports across the country,funneling data on good prospects to offices in New York, Baltimore,Houston, Los Angeles, and Leesburg. In Leesburg alone, up to20 LaRouchies worked the phones daily, trying to push the politicalhot buttons of potential donors. If they sensed a likely mark,the prospect's card would get red-flagged and sent to the "starroom," where LaRouche's top fund-raisers would take over.  <p> Convictions on all counts followed, and in early 1989, aftertheir various appeals were exhausted, LaRouche and the otherswent to prison -- in LaRouche's case, on a 15-year sentence.Meanwhile, the companion state-level case in Virginia broughtconvictions for 15 more individuals in the scheme. They too woundup being sent to prison, with sentences ranging from 60 daysto 77 years.  <p>   <p> "Who will support us? Who will rally to us?" The question wasposed by Lyndon LaRouche, as memorialized in notes taken by CritonZoakos at a 1987 rally in Leesburg. Now an analyst for the Polyconomicsthink tank, Zoakos served as a top LaRouchie from the late 1960suntil the late 1980s, when he grew disenchanted with his leader. <p> "We were all in this big barn," says Zoakos. "It was one ofLaRouche's typically mesmerizing two-hour speeches, and I wastaking notes as best I could. Then he veered off into somethingI'll never forget. It was really frightening, a man in the gripof his own messiah complex. He said, 'Only we can save the world!Nobody else even knows what the job is! I was chosen ... youwere chosen ... not with fanfare, not with the blaring trumpetsof the Archangel Gabriel. It doesn't happen that way. It happensas you walk down the street thinking of the problems of the world,and you realize that only you can do the job.'"  <p> Then LaRouche gave explicit instructions on who his followersshould tap for help in this vital mission: "The emotionally crippled,the gray-faced, the neurologically impaired -- those who, rallyingto us, will do the only worthy thing to give meaning to theirlives. Thus they will be able to say: 'I was not important, butI contributed to victory!'"  <p> At his trial, LaRouche insisted he had no involvement in, orresponsibility for, the fund-raising tactics of his followers.But his own previous testimony hurt him: In an earlier case,he testified that nothing happened in the organization withouthis knowledge and approval. And it was certainly no secret thatold folks were being hassled to fill the LaRouchies' coffers."There is no doubt about it, we specifically targeted the elderly,"says Christian Curtis. "We were all given briefings on exactlyhow to rip them off."  <p> It's possible that LaRouche doesn't know anything about thefund-raising tactics that have continued in his name since hewent to prison. Possible -- but unlikely. Former LaRouchies saythe organization's officials reported to him throughout his imprisonment.And on August 5, 1990, LaRouche issued a 3,000-word message viahis group's Leesburg headquarters. In this "morning briefing,"LaRouche urged followers to remember that he was still very muchin charge -- and that anyone who believed otherwise was "sick"and suffering from "cultural pessimism." (The message went onto rail against "Episcopalian animal-rights cults," among otherthings.)  <p> Despite a reluctance to begin any criminal investigation, somelaw officials don't hesitate to warn against LaRouche and hisfollowers. "Whether or not what the LaRouche people have beendoing is technically illegal, they certainly remain a major andcontinuing threat to the financial well-being of the elderly,"says John Russell, who was chief prosecutor in the Virginia casesagainst LaRouche fund-raisers.  <p> Meanwhile, LaRouche remains ensconced in rustic Round Hill.When he ventures forth, it's not to kiss babies but to checkin with his parole officer. Still, he keeps chasing his darkdreams -- dreams that are on display weekly, via satellite, on57 cable channels in 21 states. Spreading this message of hateand foreboding takes a lot money, to be sure. But the LaRouchieshave proved time and again that they're nothing if not dedicatedfund-raisers -- especially when they can find a lonely, neglected,elderly donor.  <p> So with LaRouche free and his organization gearing up for anotherpresidential campaign, ask yourself this: When's the last timeyou called your mother? <p>--------------- <p>Christopher Byron is a contributing editor of Worth.  Thoughhe earned a law degree from Columbia University in 1972, he turnedto journalism and never looked back.  He has worked as an editorat Forbes and Money and written a column for New York magazine.<p> <hr>  <p>Copyright 1995 Capital Publishing Limited Partnership. All rightsreserved. <p>
