					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
Can an ordinary citizen understand the president's reform package in a 40-hour workweek? Not if the president has his way.<p>By Richard Todd<p>I had been following the health care "crisis" for several months before it occurred to me that my ignorance on the subject was almost complete. The president's speech in the fall had stirred me, and I supported his goals as I understood them. Nothing in my experience justified calling the situation a crisis, but the problems the president pledged to solve did seem a kind of national shame, which may be worse. Surely, I figured, universal coverage would rectify a bad situation. But as to how the proposed reforms would actually work ... I had only the vaguest understanding. This was disconcerting. Those of us who read more than we watch television are in the habit of thinking ourselves well informed. Of course, it is just as easy to watch the news in the newspapers as on TV, and that's what I was doing with the health care issue -- watching. I knew where the plan stood in Congress at any given moment. I knew that Dan Rostenkowski's reelection loomed large in the president's efforts, and how exasperated the Clintons were at the insurance lobby's clever ads, and what an astounding polymath Ira Magaziner was. In short, I knew the score. I just didn't know the game.<p>So one long winter night I decided to bear down. I started reading newspaper features detailing the Clinton proposals. Invariably I got lost. Somewhere in the middle -- often at the place where they described the "health alliances" -- a little dizzy feeling would happen at the center of my forehead, and I would dutifully start again at the beginning.<p>It was some comfort to know that I was not alone. I took to quizzing my friends and tried in vain to find someone who could talk me through this thing. I asked my dentist just at the moment when novocaine and his handiwork would make it impossible for me to talk -- I thought this would be a fine way to spend the next, otherwise silent, half-hour. He started in but discovered he had to gesture with his hands to say anything (not ordinarily a problem of his), and the oral surgery stopped, and he looked more and more perplexed until he admitted he really didn't understand the Clinton plan. Everyone's ignorance seemed as abysmal as mine, as they all candidly and cheerfully admitted. Most people, to be sure, held positions. Even among the doctors in this liberal neck of the woods -- the college-infested hills of western Massachusetts -- the consensus was that the Clinton plan didn't go far enough, that a single-payer scheme would be much preferred. No matter that no one understood the scheme on the table.<p>That's all I wanted to do: understand it. My frustration gave birth to a strange interlude in my life I now think of as Health Care Week. It began with a simple question: How long would it take to understand health care reform? Suppose you took a whole week and did nothing but read, take notes, really go to school on this. What would you learn? I decided to find out.<p>From the moment of my decision I was infused with great purpose. I had ground rules: no interviews, no efforts to get privileged information. I wanted to read, not report. I would limit myself further to the administration proposal, the Health Security Act, which I suppose made my effort seem all the more quixotic. Were we not being told by everyone that the plan was dead on arrival? Indeed, during my Health Care Week, the plan was bottled up in a House Ways and Means subcommittee, while a Republican counterattack known as the Stark alternative was being negotiated. But have you tried to understand the Stark alternative? How can you, without understanding what it proposes to alter? And how was I going to understand any of the myriad twists and turns the legislation would take during the summer and into the fall without knowing what was at the heart of the matter? That was where I hoped I was headed. <p>By Monday morning I had cleaned out my office (I work at home) and assembled in the dining room a harvest table full of literature. (In honesty, the literature had been assembled by the research department of this magazine; had I done it myself, Health Care Week would have lasted at least a fortnight). My reading included all of the administration's official publications on the subject; the administration's draft reports on the subject, not originally meant for publication but now available at local bookstores; and the report of the Congressional Budget Office. I supplemented these basic materials with a syllabus of secondary sources. That list included a packet of Republican party fusillades entitled X-raying the Clinton Plan, a raft of interest-group PR material, miscellaneous newspaper and magazine clips, and an inch-thick Nexis file, just in case. <p>In the center of this ragged landscape stood the imposing mesa of the plan itself, the Health Security Act Senate Bill 1757. At 1,364 pages it is a rather co-opting presence. Confronted with the prospect of actually reading it, I felt a sudden wave of partisanship; if I were to go to all that trouble, the least Congress could do was pass the thing.<p><p>MONDAY. I cannot describe the exhilaration I feel. Cannot and will not try to, either, because when I spoke of the upcoming adventure over the weekend, people looked at me as if I had announced plans to become a Franciscan friar. There is something monkish about this endeavor, and you must grant that monks have their own single-minded joy.<p>I begin just as the administration would have me begin, with its own literature designed for the citizenry -- two publications, one a brochure, the other a little book of about 100 pages called Health Security: The President's Report to the American People. (Note to youth: Here I violate a basic law of studying -- skim everything first. But I'd been skimming for months.)<p>The first thing that strikes me is how the drafters of this plan really want to please. The administration's work shines with an eagerness to make things simple. In chapter 1 we learn: "Today tens of thousands of dedicated health professionals apply their unmatched skills to the world's most advanced technologies and procedures." The voice owes a great deal to the narrators of grade-school documentary films. The authors (who are supposedly the White House Domestic Policy Council, but I don't think so) seem determined not to confuse us. <p>This leads to some odd moments: "While the American health care system features some of the world's best quality care, the constant improvements in quality are now threatened. Today, we have no clear sense of what treatments work best, and which treatments should be used in different situations." We don't? What about those medical professionals with unmatched skills? What's going on here? It's as if the guy doing the voice has lost his script and is now just kind of making it up.<p>Despite that slur at the profession, doctors come off rather well in the report. Not so with the insurance companies (and their brothers and sisters in pharmaceuticals). These louts really take it on the chin: "Irresponsible behavior in our current system begins with those who profit the most: insurance companies that search for the healthiest people to cover while excluding the sick and elderly."<p>Attacks against the current system alternate with visions of the world to come after the benefits of the Health Security Act are enumerated. Soon I know by heart the major principles of the plan: Security! Simplicity! Savings! Quality! Choice! Responsibility! More specifically I hear -- not for the first time, but it's welcome information -- that insurance will no longer be terminated, new applicants will no longer be denied coverage, and there will be a standard package of benefits -- dental care and eyeglasses for children, hospice care, prescription drugs -- that will exceed many current insurance programs. And of course, the most important point: This coverage will be universal, mandatory for employers to provide, available to the self-employed for a fee, subsidized by the government for the poor and unemployed.<p>But the mechanics of the plan remain frustratingly vague. The book is rather like a Buddhist koan, smooth and unyielding as the river-washed pebble: "For the first time, consumers will be in the driver's seat when it comes to finding quality health care." What can this mean?<p>Savings will be achieved because waste will be reduced and fraud will be punished, but most importantly because "the Health Security Act increases competition," the President's Report notes bitterly, "providing health plans the incentive to compete on price and quality instead of on who does the best job excluding sick or old people."<p>How is this competition achieved? Through health alliances. What are health alliances? Well, they are "groups of individual families and local businesses who use their combined purchasing power to negotiate for high quality affordable health care."<p>How will they do this? Well, that isn't spelled out, but then it may not be necessary, because the government is going to put caps on insurance-company premiums. If the insurance companies are going to take on all applicants and limit their premium costs, couldn't we quickly get to a situation in which there is less money available to pay for more care?<p>(What about these insurance companies? They sit in the middle of this discussion like a big dumb beast. Safe to make fun of him, even to poke him, but watch out. All the book's arguments suggest he should be killed, but instead they seem to be draping a big net over him.)<p>This little book is only about100 pages long. Embarrassingly enough, I have spent most of the day reading it, sentence by sentence, listening to its sonorous prose, thinking that if I concentrate a little harder, I will see what after all sounds so simple. Is there something these people don't want to tell me?<p>Before the close of business I am determined to open a new book, the next on my list: The President's Health Security Plan. This is the real, not the pretend, report of the White House Domestic Policy Council, prepared for internal use, then leaked and published by Times Books. The people of the Domestic Policy Council do not, it turns out, write reader-friendly prose. They are patronizing in an entirely different way: "If an alliance's anticipated weighted-average premium exceeds its per capita budget target, an assessment is imposed on each plan whose premium increase (adjusted upward to reflect the previous year's assessment) exceeds the alliance's premium inflation factor."<p>Let's knock off, shall we? The news is on soon, and maybe it will be about something simple, like Whitewater.<p><p>TUESDAY. That sentence I noted yesterday may not be perfectly clear (thanks to the bureaucrat's friend, the passive voice, you can't tell who's doing what to whom). But it's helpful nonetheless. Like a lot of others in the same mode, it lets you know through its mimesis of organizational tangle that life in the alliances will not be as simple as one might have imagined. It's a little thing, but I wish the people behind these proposals could have simply said that X will be in charge of regulating Y. At any rate, it seems that the alliances will not be utterly in control of their own destinies. <p>Who is in control? Suppose that health reform has happened -- how then does the new system operate? Who's in charge here? I decide to organize the next few hours around that basic question. <p>Chapter 5 of the Domestic Policy Council report introduces the National Health Board. A not insignificant creation, it seems. According to the draft report, the board will consist of "seven members appointed by the President by and with the advice and consent of the Senate." The board in turn appoints "an executive director, additional officers and employees...and hires sufficient staff to carry out the functions described above." One trusts the staff will be large, since the "functions described above" include overseeing "the comprehensive benefit package," "the state system," "the national budget for health care spending," and "the national quality management system," among other obligations. I strongly doubt that the National Health Board will get by with just hiring a few temps.<p>I read this section with mixed feelings. There's something ominous about the National Health Board, constituted as it is like the Supreme Court -- I imagine myself standing cap in hand before the board trying to explain why I haven't eaten more fiber -- but something wholly logical about it, too. Based on what I've read so far, all these proposals unmistakably imply a need for some direction from above. <p>I don't know how I feel about the National Health Board just yet, but my pique at the administration is beginning to build. I spent an entire day poring over the president's report. I pardoned its patronizing tone, I maintained my faith, and now I realize that the administration has gone out of its way not to mention this board. I find myself getting very impatient with the administration's not-in-front-of-the-children approach to the issue. Had the gentle art of pamphleteering been as subtle in 1789, citizens would have read about the virtues of republican democracy without ever learning about the executive branch. ("Your local representative, chosen from your village or a village near you, will help assure that you have the whip hand in Congress.")<p>Still trying to find my way up and down the organization chart, I turn to the Domestic Policy Group's chapter on alliances. It defines their function as follows: "Representing the interests of consumers and purchasers of health care services...structuring the market for health care to encourage the delivery of high quality care...and assuring that all residents in a state are enrolled in health plans."<p>Again -- thanks to another of the bureaucrat's friends, the expansive gerund -- we have a lot of action without any visible actors. I am confused about the relationship between federal and state governments and ordinary citizens within an alliance (if that usage is idiomatic, which I doubt). Now I notice in the litter of my desk a torn-off corner of yellow note paper with this pathetic note to myself written yesterday, re alliances: "What is an a. really? How you start one? Who runs?"<p>I still don't know the answer, and this moves me now to make my first foray into scripture, S. 1757. It's been a long time since I've read a piece of legislation, and it takes a while to get used to that curious convention under which everything always seems to get explained in terms of other subsections, all of which seem to come later in the bill, so that you half think the authors were writing from right to left as if in Arabic. Nonetheless, it feels good to have reached the source. Let's see how the act defines an alliance: "A nonprofit organization, or an independent state agency, or an agency of the state...." Hmm. Its general function is defined a few pages later: "In order to assure the availability of the comprehensive benefit package to eligible individuals residing in the alliance area in a cost-effective manner...each regional alliance shall negotiate with any willing State-certified health plan to enter into a contract with the alliance for the enrollment under the plan of eligible individuals in the alliance area."<p>Let's give this a rest. <p><p>WEDNESDAY. I awake with one of those disconcerting cases of anxiety in which you know you are worried but for a moment can't remember why. Then it all comes back. I am worried about not understanding S. 1757! Relax. There have been worse mornings in my life. But this subject has gotten to me, and the fresh-faced eagerness I brought to the project has long since fled.<p>This morning, after a restorative breakfast, I make a good, if lucky, decision. I will move outside the self-defined world of the administration and read a secondary source. My logical choice is a report called An Analysis of the Administration's Health Proposal, published in February by the Congressional Budget Office. I am not far into this when I feel the stirrings of comprehension. <p>The CBO reminds me of a remark of Einstein's: "Everything should be made as simple as possible, but no simpler." The CBO analysis is clear in part because it is sufficiently complicated. It provides an overview of the plan's objectives and methods without invoking the evils of the present system or promoting the balms that await us. Also, it explains health reform functionally. It traces the lines of authority, follows the flow of money. Significantly, its first paragraph points out that the reform would "fundamentally restructure the current health care system." This is a welcome acknowledgment that the wand of reform will produce not just benefits but change of all sorts.<p>In the tiresome mystery of alliances, the CBO leads me to the dawn of understanding. It actually confronts my biggest question -- how will the alliances' spending be accounted for? And it argues persuasively that the money the alliances spend will probably come out of the federal budget. "On balance, the new program seems to represent an activity of the federal government that relies on the exercise of sovereign power.... CBO's analysis has concluded that the health alliances would be more like federal agencies than state or private agencies."<p>With this perception, much falls into place. I realize to my chagrin that since that crisp autumn evening when the president first lulled me with his health care promises, I have been allowing myself to be fooled by a word: alliance. Every time I heard the word mentioned in connection with the health care issue, some preverbal -- indeed previsual -- part of my brain conjured up a parade of diverse folks. They'd be carrying lunch pails and briefcases, pushing baby carriages, banding together for their common good.<p>Doublespeak has been with us as a concept for 50 years, and yet how heroically the mind resists seeing it. No, the Domestic Policy Council was never talking about voluntary alliances. These alliances will be an arm of the federal government. They are meant to administer a program, to regulate an industry. They could just as easily have been called commissions, bureaus, regional offices, or some other innocuous, stuffy name, and we'd all be better off if they had been. <p>The CBO -- its task after all is budgetary analysis -- is helpful in pointing one toward (I speak with deliberate caution) an understanding of the savings side of health reform. It defines the objective of the plan with far more precision than the administration could muster on its own behalf: "to provide a universal entitlement to health insurance...and to slow the growth of spending for health care." The analysis points out that the entitlement will obligate the government to an estimated $173 billion in subsidies in 2004. This figure will be reduced considerably by the absorption of much of the current Medicaid program into the new system. But the largest single item of projected savings (some $57 billion) comes from reduced Medicare costs, which will not be part of the new system. These will result from new caps on allowable charges by hospitals and doctors. <p>Although this has been a day that has actually answered some questions, I am left with a fresh one: Are these reductions practicable? And what happens to the plan if they're not? In any case, it's interesting that these reductions were mentioned nowhere in the President's Report to the People. Like the National Health Board, the issue of Medicaid reductions seems to be an item with which they simply chose not to trouble us.<p>Wednesday evening: Up till now, I have tried to leave my subject behind at the table, but tonight I fail. Students of conversation know that you can count on certain topics to bore your listener. These include exotic places you have been and the listener has not, books you have read and the listener has not, lovers you have had and the listener has not, etc. To this list I can add with confidence the Congressional Budget Office. As I praise my new heroes at the CBO, my wife gives me a smile of paralyzing politeness. <p><p>THURSDAY. Feeling some marginal confidence about the way health reform might be organized -- it has taken me only about 30 hours -- I am bold enough to ask how it might affect my life. My tracks into the woods up till now have been straightforward if plodding, but now I start to double over my trail and dart from government documents to lobbyists' tracts, from the turgidity of S. 1757 to the truculence of the Republican party (whose substantive points seem more cogent when detached from their tone -- how often it is thus with the GOP and me).<p>To help order my thoughts, I turn to a landmark piece of journalism from this season, Elizabeth McCaughey's broadside against the administration proposal in The New Republic. (I had "read" it at the time, i.e., spent an agreeable half-hour with it, delighting in the magazine's contrarian excursion, noting that the author raised some troubling points.)<p>As with everything else concerning this infernal bill, the only real way to read the article is to have a copy of S. 1757 at your side. McCaughey is a sort of Beelzebub of health care reform. Her argument directly inverts the what's-in-it-for-you approach of the administration. Her point is that it will be a bad deal for you. For instance: "The bill guarantees you a package of medical services but you can't have them unless they are deemed 'necessary' and 'appropriate.'...That decision will be made by the government, not by you and your doctor."<p>McCaughey writes with a certain suspect vengeance, but her arguments, when examined against the actual bill, continue to give pause. On the one hand, her contention that the government will decide what treatment is appropriate and necessary in each case is a vast overstatement. On the other hand, she rightly points out that Clinton's bill provides the National Health Board with some pretty heavy artillery. This board would have the authority to issue guidelines about specific procedures in specific situations. This makes me think that although certain procedures or tests might be covered under the benefits package, your doctor, or mine, might not always be authorized to do them. On you. Or me.<p>McCaughey makes bitter sport of the administration's claim that the federal government would not impose price controls on doctors' fees. And it does seem that this claim was, if not outright deception, a case of epic weaseling on the part of the administration. The act requires the alliances to establish a fee schedule for physicians. These controls on private doctor's lives and incomes combined with high premiums for fee-for-service plans will, McCaughey points out, have the effect of driving patients and doctors alike into HMOs, to the detriment of quality care.<p>Of course, there is something skewed about this whole argument. Whether or not you will be worse off under the reform plans depends on who you are. For those of us who enjoy private health insurance, though, it's hard to resist the idea that Health Security will represent compromised medical care.<p>So I seem, late in the day, to have reached another of those hard-won revelations that appear obvious once stated. Nonetheless, I think it's an essential premise for thinking about reform: The plan is not about extending benefits so much as it is about redistributing them. In this, the reform plan differs greatly from Medicare or Social Security, to both of which it is often compared. The plan attempts not to shelter a vulnerable group, but to rationalize an entire system. It proceeds from the never-stated assumption that not only are some people underinsured but that others are in effect overinsured. This may, at least in some Benthamite greatest-good sense, be true. But it would be hard to find anyone who would consider himself in the overinsured category. <p><p>FRIDAY. Forty hours isn't enough. I realize this morning that there are scores of things I don't yet understand. There is the plan for enhancing preventive medicine. Who could oppose it? But the scheme calls for unprecedented control over the number of medical students who are allowed to enter specialties, and I do worry about that. There is the national data bank, another good idea: Wherever you go, your medical records can be summoned by computer. But every doctor must record every visit: Is there any possibility of a private visit with a doctor? And above all there is the black hole of Medicare reform. <p>I perhaps have accomplished my most modest goal. True, I could not go toe to toe with Ira Magaziner or survive on The McLaughlin Group, though I could explain the administration's plan to a docile audience. After acknowledging that it subsidizes universal coverage, that it is organized around the workplace with employers picking up at least 80 percent of the bill, and that it makes important provisions prohibiting discrimination against individuals because of their health history, I would probably not speak in terms the administration -- or even my dentist -- would approve. I would point out that two of the virtues most touted by supporters of the plan -- choice and quality -- are the two things most threatened. That competition will be largely illusory. (Fine with me: I'm not sure I want my providers working all night to save money on my care.) Prices will be controlled by government guidelines, and one can be confident that prices will rise to meet the ceilings. Finally, despite local figureheads, control over the system will rest firmly with the federal government. This -- the centralizing of power -- and universal coverage are the two bedrock accomplishments of the plan. In a word, we will buy security and pay for it with freedom, not exactly an unprecedented transaction. <p>I think I've also learned something about why this program is so hard to understand. It's complicated, true, perhaps fatally complicated, but that's not the only or even the main reason why we've had such a hard time getting it. I'm afraid they haven't entirely wanted us to get it. In presenting their plan to us, the president and Mrs. Clinton and their fellows have veered between patronizing simplicity and pointless obfuscation. Thanks to euphemism, parental prose, hidden agendas, doublespeak, and commonplace deceit, they have managed to cast doubt on even the truly admirable parts of the plan. It would of course have been too much to ask for candor. But think what a candid description of the plan's rationale could have accomplished. The framers of this contraption know where the weak spots are -- their frank account of the compromises that went into its making would have made the whole thing clear in about ten minutes. Impossible, I know. But then couldn't they simply have laid it out for us, and let us make our own judgments? Instead, the administration has spent months trying to sell us something, when all they had to do was explain it.
---------------
Richard Todd is a contributing editor of Worth. Formerly executive editor at the Atlantic Monthly, he currently teaches writing at Smith College and is a consulting editor for Houghton Mifflin.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Government Adgency

