	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/01-Bad Medicine</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/01-Bad Medicine</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						To large employers and the uninsured, the Clinton health-care package looks like progress.  But to someone who owes his doctors his life, it looks fatally flawed.<p>By Jonathan Kwitny <p>In a country where the most common medical problem is getting and paying for medical insurance, the health care package offered by Bill Clinton last fall can look promising. Most people are well most of the time, so the issues of cost and coverage have dominated discussion of the package.<p>Less attention has been focused on the price the plan carries in times of serious illness--which none of us really expects but which is the reason we need health insurance. For all the debate about what the plan will do to insurance premiums and taxes, the real price won't emerge until patients and their families confront a health crisis and learn that opportunities for quality care have been reduced in ways that will cost lives. The shock will be particularly great if the crisis involves one of the many conditions for which medical science hasn't yet settled on a single answer.<p>A growing number of patients and their families have already paid this hidden price, because employers and health insurers long ago sensed what was happening and began positioning themselves for the new world of medicine the Clinton administration's plan promises them. The plan's basic idea, known as managed care or managed competition, is to strongly encourage most patients and doctors to join large groups. Each group of patients comes under exclusive contract for treatment to a group of physicians and one or more hospitals. <p>Doctors in these group practices may be employees of a health-maintenance organization or may work from private offices in a network known as a preferred-provider organization. Ten years ago, these group practices were contracted to treat only about 1 in 20 Americans. Now it's 16 percent and rising. The aim of the Clinton plan is to drive it toward 100 percent. <p>"A managed-care operation is terrific if you're slightly sick, and awful if you're very sick," says Dr. Burton J. Lee III, George Bush's former White House physician and now medical director of the Cancer Treatment Center at Greenville Memorial Hospital in South Carolina. "Even in the Kaiser plan," he says, referring to Kaiser Permanente, which many consider the standard-setter in the relatively new managed-care industry, "you get up to a certain level of problem, and they're not going to have that many experts. If you've got something serious, you want to go to the best." (A Kaiser spokesperson says Kaiser has "some of the top-notch people in the country.")<p>I know Lee because in 1972, at Memorial Sloan Kettering Hospital in New York, he successfully treated me for Hodgkin's disease, a lymph cancer. He made me healthy again by prescribing radiotherapy, one of several treatment options available. <p>Not many years before I was treated, Hodgkin's was usually fatal. Even now, it kills many of those who are treated. Different doctors will provide a different mix of treatments, sometimes adding the more toxic chemotherapy to radiation and altering the amounts of each. Studies don't yet show why some people are cured and others die, but the factors involved are obvious. Some, like the makeup of the particular cancer cells and the genes and health of the patient, are for now uncontrollable. But other factors include the skill and judgment of the doctors on the treatment team and the equipment and experience of the treatment center. Until managed care came along, that was in the control of patients, who could pick their doctors and hospitals.<p>In 1972, my longtime family doctor in Indiana, suspecting but not knowing that I had Hodgkin's, sent me to Memorial before a biopsy was even done. My doctor--who was, in fact, my father--thought it was the best hospital in the country for Hodgkin's and that I ought to be diagnosed there. I saw Lee, head of the Memorial Hodgkin's team, merely by calling and requesting an appointment. The United States has long offered probably the world's best medical care for the greatest number of people. It saved my life. I got it with what was at the time ordinary insurance coverage.<p>If managed care had been around in 1972, I probably couldn't have done this. I might be dead from the disease or disabled from excessive treatment now.<p>The administration says 37 million Americans, roughly 15 percent of the population, are uninsured at any given time. Some are between jobs and health plans. Others have been cut loose by the insurance industry because they developed an expensive health condition--the very thing they thought they were insured against. Covering these uninsured people is a serious problem. Making medical coverage available to the uninsured and uninsurable is a task the country is properly ready to own up to. But changing the way the other 85 percent of the country gets its medical care, in most cases with success, is a drastic and unnecessary solution. That is what managed care does.<p>Dr. Joseph Simone, the physician in chief at Memorial Hospital today, is, like Burton Lee, angry about the restrictions placed on a patient's choice of doctor under managed care. "Just this week," Simone told me recently, "an orthopedic surgeon here saw three bone-cancer patients, rendered an opinion, suggested a line of treatment, and then was told the patients would not be treated here." The patients had been sent to Memorial for consultation by local managed-care organizations. Now, for treatment, they would be sent back to their community hospitals, where the managed-care contracts were. "I don't know about the community hospitals," Simone said, "and it may not sound good for me to say, 'We can do it better than those guys out there,' but that's just the way it is. We are experts in cancer care."<p>Most is the driving force behind the managed-care movement. Managed care is in large part the brainchild of big corporations that aren't in the health-care field but that pay much of America's health-care bill as a fringe benefit to their employees. In photographs of the Jackson Hole Group, one of the most important of the skull sessions at which the Clinton administration's plan was hammered out last winter, executives from General Electric and Pepsico work alongside executives from Prudential, Cigna, and the Pharmaceutical Manufacturers' Association and White House aides. <p>American corporations are worried that the rising expense of health insurance for their employees hampers their competitiveness in selling cars, food, computers, industrial hardware, and other products in international markets. They're right. Health-care expenditures are the fastest-growing component of employee compensation, going from 15 percent of corporate after-tax profits in 1960 to 48 percent in 1980 to 107 percent in 1991. That means American corporations now spend more on just the health care of their employees than they earn as profit, with the bulk of the expense incurred by the largest, most heavily unionized companies. Perhaps the best-known statistic in this area, because former Chrysler chairman Lee Iacocca bellyaches about it in speeches, is that $1,100 of the price of every Chrysler car goes to pay employee health-insurance premiums. Not surprisingly, Chrysler is a big backer of managed care.<p>As are most large employers, for reasons made clear by some simple numbers: The traditional system of reimbursing employees for medical expenses cost companies $4,080 for each employee in 1992. Preferred-provider plans cost only $3,708. HMOs cost only $3,313. And that's just the beginning. Although the new minimum-care standards of the Clinton plan are still being tinkered with, suggestions to date require significantly less care than is offered by most major corporate plans, even HMO plans. When less care becomes a government standard, it's safe to assume less will be provided. The kicker is that under the administration's plan, corporations will be relieved of their obligations to fund the health care of many early retirees. A government program will take up the slack.<p>It's a serious problem that American corporate competitiveness is suffering because of the high cost of employee health care. But that doesn't mean that the simplest solution for the corporations--reducing the quality of the health care they pay for in order to lower the cost--is necessarily the best solution for the country.<p>Alternative plans are on the drawing board. Some of them look very good. But the managed-care idea is moving swiftly to co-opt the field, and doctors are already being coerced into joining the big group practices of managed care. "We're being kind of herded into these," says Dr. David Senechek, a veteran HIV/AIDS specialist in San Francisco. Similarly, he says, "Patients are being herded into insurance groups. What we're seeing on the horizon is a mass of conglomerating insurance companies who are tightening their control over the medical system to where they are basically going to dictate to patients and doctors and work in conjunction with the pharmaceutical companies to control medicine. We're kind of pawns in this massive corporate movement."<p>That is a severe assessment but an educated one. AIDS, Senechek's specialty, offers an excellent window into the downside of managed care. I learned this while researching my most recent book, Acceptable Risks, which tells how unorthodox medicine benefited a group of patients infected by HIV, the AIDS virus. Unfettered by managed care and guided by maverick doctors, these patients greatly extended their healthy lives by using promising treatments that weren't yet considered "proven" by the medical establishment. <p>Now that AIDS seems less a threat to most Americans, there's a danger of dismissing too quickly the powerful message that the AIDS epidemic carried for the health-care system. New diseases or conditions have always come along. Next time the spread may be traced to hot dogs or cellular telephones instead of unsafe sex and intravenous drug use. The radiation that was used in the 1950s to shrink swollen adenoids and measure shoe sizes now causes increases in leukemia and thyroid cancer. When it was less understood, AIDS was a valid metaphor for the great unknown health condition that none of us expects to suffer but that many of us invariably will, which is what health insurance is needed for.<p>A recent study discussed at the Ninth International Conference on AIDS in Berlin in June showed that the most significant characteristic shared by HIV patients who survive long-term is not any blood marker or infection pattern; rather, it is the patient's active participation in choosing his physicians and treatments. As Martin Delaney, founding director of Project Inform, a San Francisco AIDS treatment organization, puts it, the patients who live longest "are the ones who fired their doctors." (And found new ones, of course.)<p>Under managed competition, a patient's ability to pick doctors will be severely curtailed. New York AIDS specialist Dr. Howard Grossman says he's already "lost 10 or 15 patients this year, easy, who have had to change doctors because their employers went into HMOs or preferred-provider organizations. I don't know anybody who's had a positive experience. Lots of them come back to me at their own expense to look over their [test results] or just talk to me on the phone. When you look at the lists of doctors [in managed-care organizations], it's rare to find anybody with a big HIV practice. You certainly don't find anybody who's expert in the field, at least in New York."<p>In Los Angeles, Michael Gottlieb, one of the country's best-known AIDS doctors, says that when his patients are forced to change doctors they often come to him with a list of other doctors provided by a managed-care organization. "Sometimes you look at the book and there is literally no one you recognize with expertise," he says.<p>That is no accident, either, he adds. Since the object of managed care is to save money, and since everyone knows that HIV patients often need expensive care, the large health-care corporations don't want to be associated with HIV specialists. "Under managed care," says Gottlieb, "if a physician wanted to express an interest in HIV, it's unlikely he would be allowed to."<p>In fact, another California AIDS specialist says he lost so many patients to managed-care plans that he tried to join a managed-care group to reestablish his relationship with them. Yet despite a stellar career including high honors from Harvard Medical School, he was rejected by the group. (He is still trying to get into the group, this time with a lawyer's help, and asked not to be identified.)<p>This has implications for all of us. "The doctor-patient relationship is the critical piece in health care," says Dr. Sharon Lee, an AIDS specialist in Kansas City, Kansas. "It's not something people should be forced to leave on the whim of whatever insurance company the workplace chooses to go with. There are many instances where people go into an emergency room and, because they don't have an ongoing relationship with the physician, very important pieces of information are overlooked." <p>The result can be tragic. One AIDS patient of David Senechek's, after suffering dizziness, nausea, and vomiting, went to an HMO emergency room because it was paid for under his new group insurance plan. Four times he was diagnosed with a routine stomach disorder and sent home; the emergency-room doctors knew he was an AIDS patient but apparently weren't widely experienced with the disease. Finally, returning to Senechek's office in desperation and paying his own money, the patient was quickly diagnosed as having adrenal failure, an occasional AIDS complication that would soon have killed him. "It's completely treatable," says Dr. Senechek. "We just put him on replacement adrenal hormones; he gained his weight back and went back to work." <p>The measurable effectiveness of medical treatment is not the only issue. There is a value on the feelings of patients and their families in a crisis. When the Hodgkin's sword hung over me, my wife and family and friends, and even Jerry Bishop, the science reporter at the Wall Street Journal, where I worked, scanned popular and professional journals for the latest information. We knew I was stage A (without fever and other symptoms) rather than stage B (with symptoms), and that was good; but it wasn't clear whether I was stage II (only above the diaphragm) or stage III (spread below the diaphragm). That made a big difference in how much toxic medicine I would be given--medicine that might wreck me later in order to save me now. As test after test failed to resolve my staging, and eventually major surgery was needed to determine that I was in stage II, it meant a lot to us to know that the best authorities in the country would make the determination.<p>The ability to choose and trust one's doctor can have a profound effect on the quality of life, and on life itself, far beyond facing down the threat of fatal disease. Back when I was being treated for Hodgkin's, my first wife was battling the kidney disease that would later kill her. Her first attempt at pregnancy led to a term stillbirth and predictions by doctors that she would be childless, which left her despondent. But she researched the issue and found a nephrologist in Brooklyn experienced at kidney-problem motherhood. With a Manhattan obstetrician he often worked with, the nephrologist guided her through a pregnancy and induced premature labor at the right time. The result was my daughter. Under managed care, my first wife would not likely have been able to go to either of the doctors who produced our daughter, let alone both.<p>I recently called Jerome Porush, the nephrologist who helped my first wife. Porush is now chief of nephrology at Brookdale Hospital in Brooklyn and a consultant for the Health Insurance Plan of Greater New York, or HIP, the largest HMO in the metropolitan area. I asked him about his experience with managed care. "HMOs stink," he said.<p>What makes him say that? The plan refers kidney patients to his team for consultations, he says. "We can only recommend lab work. If we want to use a hospital lab, the patient has to pay. So things don't get done, we don't get feedback, we don't see the patient in a year, and they didn't do anything in the interim. The blood pressure isn't monitored. The creatinine has gone from two to six, and they didn't do anything." A rise in creatinine shows that the kidneys aren't getting rid of poisonous substances that healthy kidneys eliminate. When the kidneys weaken, diet and medication can help slow the deterioration. When creatinine shoots up, the patient requires costly blood dialysis to live. "Sometimes patients don't come back to us at all, because HIP doesn't send them back," Porush says. <p>(A spokesman for HIP says the organization does follow through with patients and monitor blood pressure where warranted. HIP's medical director, Dr. Jesse Jampol, says that in many years of dealing with HIP, Porush has never complained to him about such problems, or "they would have been taken care of." The spokesman says HIP does its own lab work because it costs less. And he praises Porush's "high reputation," which he says is typical of the quality of doctors HIP works with. He says, however, that Brookdale Hospital, where Porush works, "is being phased out of the HIP system because we don't feel that the quality they provide is up to our standards.")<p>Porush is the kind of doctor who cares enough that 20 years later he remembers my first wife's case well. Like other superspecialists I talked to, he told of trying unsuccessfully to get on the rolls of an HMO recently in order to care for a patient in crisis. The patient had been referred to him by a physician who worked for the plan. But when Porush called the plan he was simply told that the rolls were closed. The patient reluctantly went to a nephrologist already on the plan.<p>Not only does managed care threaten patient access to the doctors they need most when their lives are on the line, but many doctors I talked to worry about the dampening effect such a system would have on medical research. Perhaps the most important such research takes place not in drug-company laboratories but in patient care, especially at major research hospitals.<p>When we hear on television about a daring operation that costs many hundreds of thousands of dollars, and we wonder whether a single life justifies such expense, we usually don't hear about the experimental value of the procedure. If it works, it will become more routine and the price may come down considerably. When my first wife received her two kidney transplants in the mid-1970s, she was assured that the surgery was safe and routine. Looking back on it now and at the failure rate of the operations then, I can see that her operations were really experimental. <p>But largely because of those expensive, experimental operations back then (our insurance company did argue with the surgeon and persuade him to drop his price), the procedure is now almost truly routine. The lawyer who just handled my house sale popped into the hospital for a kidney transplant while the papers were still being shuffled and was back in his office in a couple of weeks. <p>Existing managed-care institutions generally won't pay for experimental medicine--which is what worries the research-oriented doctors I talked to. Many don't want to talk on the record about it because their institutions are now lobbying in Washington for a way to maintain their research abilities if a new managed-care system is adopted.<p>But the treatment policies of most managed-care institutions are set by administrative boards that don't meet patients face to face. Business considerations, including the desirability of uniform handling of similarly diagnosed cases, often predominate over the professional interest that many physicians have in meeting the needs of individual patients and perfecting their craft.<p>And the truth is that most experimental medicine has nothing to do with the complicated surgery and the eye-popping bills of the most publicized cases. Rather, it involves experimental medicine with drugs that often don't cost much more than accepted drugs of limited effectiveness. Independent physicians will try them out when it seems appropriate and the standard therapy doesn't seem to be working. But managed-care concerns are designed to save money and work uniformly; if the Food and Drug Administration hasn't approved a treatment yet, that provides a good excuse not to pay for the cost of a drug and of a physician to monitor its use.<p>By many estimates, about half the prescription drugs sold in the United States today are used for what's known as "off-label" application. That means the doctor, knowing the drug and the patient, has prescribed the drug for a different use than the one the FDA has approved it for. FDA standards for drug approval are extremely rigorous: Typical drugs require ten years of testing, costing several hundred million dollars. Much of this testing isn't for safety, which can be established relatively quickly and cheaply; it is to prove, to a high scientific standard, that the drug works on a very specifically defined condition.<p>Once a drug passes that standard, doctors can use it to treat slightly different conditions, and this is how a great deal of medical progress occurs. A few doctors who use a drug successfully in a new way write a letter to a medical journal, it gets published, and word spreads. The White House says plenty of money will still be available for medical research if its new plan passes. But the doctors I spoke to, most of whom work on the advance edge of medicine, fear that the cost-cutting, minimal-treatment orientation of managed-care institutions will pose a barrier to the everyday experimentation through which medical science advances. <p>Here, too, the beginning of the AIDS epidemic offers a clear glimpse into how the system works successfully now and how managed care could obstruct it. For most of the 1980s the medical establishment--the big teaching hospitals, the big drug companies, and the FDA--offered AIDS patients nothing but hopelessness. By their standards, no treatment had proved itself beneficial. Patients and their families, however, did research on their own. They came up with a stream of promising remedies, often medicines sold abroad but not approved here. Underground networks sprang up to smuggle in these drugs from Mexico, Europe, and China. <p>Some of the drugs were later shown in FDA-approved clinical trials in the U.S. and abroad to slow the progress of the AIDS virus and significantly extend the good health of patients who took them. Some effectively stopped various illnesses that attack HIV-infected people and are now approved by the FDA for use against these illnesses.<p>Other drugs, of course, were worthless--and, worse yet, dangerous. To halt toxic side effects and measure the benefits, patients needed the supervision of doctors. Most doctors weren't experienced in AIDS and knew nothing of these drugs. But, as with most diseases, certain doctors, because of the nature or location of their practice, encountered the disease unusually often. <p>And as with most diseases, some doctors saw a challenge. Those who were so inclined acquainted themselves with various under-the-table remedies (most of which weren't very expensive) and monitored the patients who took them. The office visits, blood work, and other tests were covered by patients' insurance even though the experimental drugs weren't. As word spread, these doctors became magnets for new patients with HIV. If a patient was uninsured, it was not uncommon for a doctor to waive or reduce the fee. If insurance was there and it became necessary, such a cooperative doctor could admit a patient to the hospital where he or she practiced, sometimes continuing the unorthodox therapy there. Every one of these doctors, of course, was an independent practitioner.<p>Though the FDA didn't approve the drugs for sale, neither did it interfere with what the doctors were doing. Under the law and FDA regulations, doctors may treat patients in their offices as doctor and patient see fit, so long as the doctor doesn't sell unapproved drugs or engage in practices considered blatantly dangerous. Privately, many FDA and other government officials expressed thanks for what these doctors were doing--providing medical and psychological benefit where the official system offered none.<p>Under managed competition, however, such doctors would mostly be driven out of business. The day of the pioneer physician, offering patients the option to fight back with specialized information against a disease most doctors are powerless to challenge, would be over.<p>The Clinton Administration says there will be freedom of choice under its plan. By that, it means that an individual will be able to choose which patient group he or she joins, and the patient group (or employer) can choose which provider company it signs up with. One trouble with these choices is that if, say, your allergist is in one group, your spouse's gynecologist or urologist is in another, and the only dentist your child will sit still for is in a third, two of these three trusted doctors will have to go. Still more important, however, is that the individual or his employer must make the choice before illness strikes, after which there would be little choice at all. Choosing a provider company will be quite a commitment. When you're well, managed care may seem like a life preserver. But when you suddenly face AIDS, kidney failure, or another life-threatening illness, it can turn out to be a cinder block chained to your ankle.<p>Would you be free to go see the independent doctor of your choice if you were willing to pay the bills on your own? Legally, yes, if you were rich enough. Problem is, they probably won't be there. Doctors, no matter how independent of mind, will face enormous pressure to join a group, as has happened already to some of the doctors mentioned above.<p> Medicine is not a mere craft, subject to procedures taught from a manual. Patients, even those infected by the same virus, bring radically different genes and psychological dispositions to the examining room. To tell doctors that they themselves are to adopt identical personalities and follow uniform recipes set by an administrative board is to discard a fundamental of good medicine. <p>Two years after my successful treatment for Hodgkin's disease, I came down with fever and other Hodgkin's-like symptoms and had a marginal lymphangiogram, a test for swelling of the lymph nodes. Burton Lee, head of the Memorial Hodgkin's team, sized up all the evidence and concluded I'd had a probable relapse. He suggested a course of chemotherapy. My Indiana physician, my father, suggested second opinions, particularly because an antibiotic had cleared up the fever and other symptoms. I consulted experts he located at two other renowned cancer centers, Massachusetts General Hospital and Stanford. Scrutinizing my case, those doctors advised standing pat and avoiding the life-shortening effects of chemotherapy unless further regression proved I needed it. I took that advice. It was a close call, and either way was a gamble. As it turned out, I won, but I respect each of the doctors who weighed that decision. <p>Just as a personal physician can come up with an occasional wrong answer, managed-care organizations can come up with many right ones. Philip Madvig, physician in chief at Kaiser in San Francisco, is proud that his hospitals have the fewest deaths of any hospital group in California both among newborns and among open-heart-surgery patients. "There is absolutely no question in my mind that we are capable of and do provide the highest-quality medical care within our organization," he says. <p>Others caution that Kaiser is a dangerous example because its relatively long record of care under the old environment isn't being matched by other organizations in the new environment. Madvig doesn't really dispute this. "There are many organizations where you are told by bureaucrats you need to justify that test or you need to justify that admission to the hospital," he says. "That is not the case within our organization." He also says he disagrees with other managed-care organizations that allow nonmedical officials to set medical policy, which he says also isn't the case with Kaiser. <p>Madvig says organizations like Kaiser improve on traditional medicine because they make sure that members' money is spent cost-effectively so as to keep rates down. That means keeping a check on what treatments get administered. But should a patient be irrevocably subject to one board that decides which treatments get administered, even if the board is made up of medical personnel? That question is easier to answer in the abstract than it is in the case of oneself or one's child.<p>What I have seen, both personally and professionally as a journalist, is overwhelming evidence that rule-book medicine set by administrators costs lives. It would have cost my daughter hers and many of the patients I wrote about in my book theirs and probably would have cost me mine. What's that worth? The taxes I've paid since 1972 have dwarfed that old hospital bill, big as it seemed then, and through her volunteer work my daughter may already have paid back what was invested in her, with the prime of her life still to come. And what is the value of love, joy, and feeling secure?<p>Americans do need protection against the growing power of insurance companies to cut off benefits when confronted with illness. One thing that helps the companies get away with this is the growing anachronism of tying one's medical insurance to one's place of employment. We now lose or change jobs much more often than the previous generation of Americans did. Each time we do, or our employers decide to switch insurance plans, companies that insured against an illness are allowed to escape its continuing costs. And new companies are allowed to exclude it from coverage. <p>But a law could require insurers to live up to their contracts and continue to pay the costs of illnesses they have insured against, regardless of where the patient chooses to work. Fixing this problem does not require dismantling the private-practice medical system that many patients, and former and future patients, would like to have around, just in case their lives depend on it. <p>Jonathan Kwitny's most recent book is Acceptable Risks (Simon & Schuster,  1992). He is working on a book about  Pope John Paul II.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Government Agencies, Politics, Legislation

