<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 93/11-How Will They Nab Me?</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>93/11-How Will They Nab Me?</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
The new IRS is shrewder, sharper, and a little bit scarier than ever before<p>By Joseph B. Darby III<p>Tanned, rested and ready.That's what the Internal Revenue Service is today. No longer the butt of bumbler jokes or the focus of congressional wrath for its ineptitude, the IRS has entered the age of efficiency in total quality management. <p>Do we really want the best-run agency in the federal government to be--gulp--the IRS? You have to think that most taxpayers would prefer inefficiency to reign at the agency charged with collecting taxes. But these days anyone asking themselves "How will they catch me?" had better think twice.<p>The IRS is not yet the well-oiled enforcement machine that it hopes to be. For example, the Service still has difficulty communicating with itself. One former commissioner, who requested anonymity, acknowledges that, even today, if an IRS agent wants a copy of a past return for an audit, he has to wait for a response from the IRS Service Center, just like a taxpayer would. "And that," says the former commissioner, "is assuming the service center can even find a copy of it." <p>Slowly, though, the IRS is becoming more efficient, particularly in the way it uses the reams of taxpayer information it has in its files. For example, the Service is much better these days at cross-checking W-2 forms and 1099s against individual tax returns, a simple but effective test of the accuracy of tax returns. The IRS is also getting better at using computers to screen tax returns, scanning them for characteristics that might flag a cheater. Thanks to this program, the IRS now collects additional taxes on 80 percent of the returns it audits. <p>Another IRS change: A modification in the 1040 asking taxpayers to supply Social Security numbers for each dependent claimed. As if by magic, 7 million dependents disappeared from tax returns the year this change was made. <p>Many taxpayers are finding out--the hard way--how much more efficient the IRS has become. Owners of cash businesses, who can hide income more easily than wage earners, often find themselves targeted. When auditing coin-operated car washes, for example, IRS agents have been known to pull several years' worth of water bills and compare water usage with reported income. If the water consumption doesn't add up, penalties can flow.<p>Restaurant owners are also feeling the IRS's heat. Agents today routinely check inventory and food orders against reported income and interrogate employees. In one case, an IRS agent suspected that the proprietor of a pizza shop was padding deductions for pizza dough, tomato sauce, and cheese. The agent simply did not believe that the pizza tasted as expensive as its ingredients cost. How did he prove it? He bought a pizza and had it tested in a laboratory to determine the amount and the quality of the ingredients used.<p>The new IRS thinks nothing of checking the veracity of a taxpayer's returns against phone records or credit card bills. For instance, a taxpayer tried to claim his vacation home was a rental property, arguing that he had used it less than 10 percent of the year. The IRS obtained the telephone records for the residence and found that phone calls had been placed from the home on approximately 150 days out of the year and that almost all of those calls could be traced to family members or friends of the taxpayer. The IRS also found that the taxpayer had used his Visa and Mastercard to charge meals at restaurants near the vacation home throughout the year. Gotcha!<p>The IRS also loves to look over your shoulder when you're applying for car loans, credit cards, and mortgages. Taxpayers usually fill out these applications quickly, and the Service has found that even a conscientious taxpayer will frequently show a different income number on a loan application--when a larger income is advantageous--than he will on his tax returns. Lesson here:Be consistent.<p>Taxpayers aren't the only targets in IRS crosshairs. Rogue tax preparers, when identified and prosecuted, give the IRS a big bang for its enforcement buck. In one case of particularly profitable sleuthing, agents caught a tax preparer who was working on a commission basis. Because his fee consisted of a percentage of the refund owed the client, he had an incentive to be aggressive in his accounting. Although the IRS did not prosecute the clients criminally in this case, it did collect the tax, interest, and penalties owed by each. Clients of other aggressive tax preparers may not be so fortunate.<p>Another common method of catching tax offenders is working from tips. The IRS offers rewards, depending on the value of the lead. Information resulting in a recovery can be worth 10 percent of the first $75,000 recovered, 5 percent of the next $25,000, and 1 percent of any additional recovery. Last year the IRS recovered almost $84 million this way, at a cost of $1.7 million in rewards. But even without rewards, people are often willing to turn in others for a variety of reasons, including jealousy and revenge. <p>More than one case has been generated by a tip from a secretary or a disgruntled employee. Customers, neighbors, and friends have been known to take action when another taxpayer seems not to have been paying his share. One IRS staffer recalls a bookkeeper who turned in a boss who was keeping two sets of books. <p>Paying your taxes needn't be frightening. There are plenty of situations where the law is gray, and it is permissible, and even appropriate, for taxpayers to take an aggressive reporting position. But if you find yourself asking, "How will they catch me?" you're better off to just pay the tax.<p>
Joseph B. Darby III is a Boston-based attorney who represents taxpayers with the IRS.<p><p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Government Adgency

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
