	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 93/09-Look Before Leaving</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>

				<img src="">	
				<p>
				<font size=5><b>Look Before Leaving</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>93/09-Look Before Leaving</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						September 1993 
<p>
Worth magazine/Advisor  
<p>
 LOOK BEFORE LEAVING 
<p>
Don't be surprised by the rights that the new Family Leave Bill
doesn't give employees  
<p>
 By Virginia Applegarth  
<p>
 Scene 1: The obstetrician's office. Due date is oneweek away.
An expectant mother has planned to return to work full-time two
months after the baby is born. Now she has to make that plural;
her sonogram shows two babies, both underweight. On the way home,
she and her husband agree that they will each need to take a
two-month leave of absence, as they think they are entitled to
under the new Family Leave Bill. The next day, however, reality
hits: It turns out he has no right to any unpaid leave, and his
boss says the company can't spare him for more than a week, maybe
two, because production is behind schedule.   
<p>
 Scene 2: A managers' meeting to assign duties for a major new
project. An assistant appears at the door looking anxious, and
delivers the bad news: The father of one of the managers has
fallen and broken his hip. The hip must be surgically repaired,
and a long recuperation will follow. The manager is the only
relative close by. A leave of absence is quickly arranged, thanks
to the Family Leave Bill, and she instantly feels relieved. Then,
on the way to the hospital, financial reality hits: She will
have no salary for the next two months. After-tax cost at her
$120,000 a year salary: $12,000. Hidden cost: By the time she
gets back, she'll have been left out of the biggest project of
the year.   
<p><p>
<p>
Welcome to the reality of the family leave bill, which took effect
on August 5. Widely touted as a giant step forward for working
families, it's far from a panacea for people who have to take
time off. Employees who need a leave of absence had better figure
out their rights and their finances in advance, or they can be
in for some expensive and long-reaching surprises.  
<p>
 The Family Leave Bill presents employees with two basic problems.
First, although the bill has been portrayed as "universal," the
Clinton administration estimates that fewer than half of American
workers are covered by it. Indeed, 95 percent of American businesses
do not have to comply, although many offer some time off to their
employees during a family crisis or transition.  
<p>
 Second, employees who are covered by the bill still have to
pay for it. For an executive earning $100,000 a year, a 12-week
unpaid leave can cost as much as $16,800 after taxes. And, of
course, lost wages aren't the only costs; employees, especially
executives, can end up paying for a leave of absence for the
rest of their careers.   
<p>
 Studies quantifying these hidden costs have focused primarily
on women, because women more often leave work and come back.
According to one recent study, women who temporarily leave the
work force average a one-third drop in wages when they return,
and their pay never catches up with that of women who do not
interrupt their careers.  
<p>
 But it's not only a women's issue. According to Fran Rodgers,
founder of Work/Family Directions, a leading dependent-care consulting
firm in Boston, "A man's career is even more dead than a woman's
if he takes family leave or wants to back off a bit at work."
Rodgers's studies show that 50 percent of managers say they view
an employee who asks for flexible hours or family leave as someone
who is "not serious about their career." Even workers who take
time off to be with a seriously ill child or care for a dying
parent often return to find they can come back to the same job
title, but their power has been subtly reduced or anticipated
promotions don't materialize.   
<p>
 When a leave of absence is necessary in spite of the tangible
and intangible costs, it's important to know the law. Fortunately,
as laws go, the mechanics of the Family Leave Bill are relatively
straightforward. Every employer that has 50 or more employees
who work within a 75-mile radius must offer 12 weeks unpaid leave
each year to any employee going through adoption, birth, or care
of a seriously ill family member. During the leave of absence,
the company must continue health-care coverage, although the
employee must continue to pay his or her share, if any, of the
premium. When the employee returns, the same or a comparable
job must be waiting with no loss of seniority. To be eligible,
an employee must only have worked for the employer for at least
a year, and for at least 1,250 hours (25 hours a week) during
the previous 12 months.  
<p>
 Because of the media attention surrounding the Family Leave
Bill, most people are probably under the impression that they
are covered by it. They may not be. Employees may work for a
company that is large but has fewer than 50 employees working
within 75 miles of one another, or for a firm that formerly had
50 employees but just fired one person so it wouldn't have to
comply. (According to the Wall Street Journal, Senator Bob Dole
suggested this tactic for the 70-odd companies with exactly 50
employees in his home state of Kansas.)   
<p>
 And there are a host of other exceptions. A "key" employee,
defined by Congress as one who is among the highest 10 percent
of a company's wage earners and whose leaving would cause substantial
economic disruption to the company, can be denied leave. Teachers
aren't guaranteed immediate leave. And if both spouses work for
the same employer, their combined leave can be only 12 weeks,
unless a member of their immediate family is seriously ill, in
which case they each get up to the full 12 weeks.  
<p>
 And, of course, the people who do qualify for leave still have
to figure out how to finance the time off. For many people, finding
out that they qualify for leave time is like having a kid get
into Yale: It's great, but who's going to pay for it? Relying
on savings for the duration is difficult or impossible for most.
But there are ways that families can finance these leaves, both
indirectly and directly.  
<p>
 Indirect financing can be as basic as having the spouse with
the lower income take the leave. Another method is to arrange
a shorter full-time leave with additional part-time leave. A
little-publicized but creative way to finance a leave is to work
reduced hours for 12 weeks. This could mean working a few hours
during the day, two or three days a week, or whatever schedule
suits your needs. The period allowed depends on the reason for
the leave. If it's for birth or adoption, the total leave period
is 12 weeks, so an employee cannot stretch it to 24 weeks by
working two-and-a-half days a week. For medical emergencies,
however, the total time off allowed is 12 weeks, even if it stretches
over many months. Many employers are not aware of this difference.
Chances are, an employer will prefer to have someone in the office
part of each week rather than not at all for an extended period.<p>
<p>
 Employers can require employees to use up paid leave (accrued
vacations, personal days, sick days, and comp time) before starting
their unpaid leave, but most employees do this anyway, to help
with cash flow. Employees should be careful about documenting
overtime and other work for which they could get comp time, because
it will provide income if leave is needed.  
<p>
 When care of an aging parent is the reason for leave, it may
be possible for siblings who are not providing care to provide
a "substitute salary" to the one who is. This can also do wonders
to reduce resentment by the child actually providing the care.
Another option for financing family leave is to borrow from retirement
plans, such as 401(k)s. Plans vary, so employees should check
to make sure what they offer before taking leave. People can
also temporarily withdraw money from an IRA without penalty as
long as they repay it within 60 days. And if the reason for the
leave is important enough, it may even be worth taking money
from the retirement plans as an outright distribution and paying
the tax and penalty (10 percent).  
<p>
 Another financing technique families are using if they have
advance notice for a leave is to draw against a home equity line
of credit, although most advisors discourage this. People who
need to take this route should apply for the loan before they
take leave, if possible. At the same time, employees who are
planning to quit should be careful about taking family leave
just to extend medical insurance for a few more months. If an
employee quits after taking a leave, in most cases he or she
must repay the company for any premiums it paid.  
<p>
 For all its flaws, the Family Leave Bill is a step forward.
But as Fran Rodgers says, we need to dispense with the political
rhetoric and move on to the real issue of the '90s긍ork flexibility,
not "accommodation." Americans work an average of one month more
per year than they did 20 years ago, and families are paying
the price. Perhaps in the future more companies will join Xerox
Corporation, which recently announced a subsidy program that
offers employees up to $10,000 in additional income over the
course of their employment for family and personal expenses.
In the meantime, most families can protect themselves best by
coming up with a plan that allows them to finance "doing the
right thing" for themselves, their parents, siblings, and children.<p>
<p>
  <hr>  
<p>
who isn't covered?  
<p>
 The Family Leave Bill applies to everybody except:  
<p>
 Teachers  
<p>
 Employees who work for companies that employ fewer than 50 people<p>
<p>
 Employees who work for companies (no matter how large) that
employ fewer than 50 people within a 75 mile radius  
<p>
 People deemed "key" employees. 
<p>
----------------------  
<p>
 Virginia Applegarth is a financial planner and insurance consultant
in Boston and author of How to Protect Your Family with Insurance,
published by Houghton Mifflin.  
<p>
 ------------------------------------------------------------------------<p>
