<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 97/02-Investing: The Great No-Fear Market</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>97/02-Investing: The Great No-Fear Market</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						By Scott Burns<p>
It's been an amazing run. Since October 11, 1990, the Dow Jones Industrials have climbed from 2365 to the 6400 level. Too bad so few 401(k) participants went along for the ride.<p>
For years, employee-benefits consultants have preached that more people should participate in 401(k) plans, that participants should save more, and that they should take more risk to get a higher return. According to an annual study by Foster Higgins, a benefits-consulting firm, employees directed only 40 percent of plan assets into equities in 1995. That's up from 31 percent in 1993, but it's still far less of a commitment to stocks than investors need to replace current income at retirement.<p>
To many investors, the market's current lofty level is just one more reason to delay putting their 401(k) money into stocks. It's too late and too risky to start investing in the stock market now, they think; new players will be greeted with a crash.<p>
So let's ask a rude question: Should you be afraid of a crash?<p>
Absolutely not -- provided that you are investing in stocks through a typical 401(k) plan. The employer's matching contribution to the average 401(k) works to protect investors from real losses even during a major market decline.<p>
Consider how you would have fared in two of the worst market declines in history if you had been investing in stocks through a 401(k) plan.<p>
Suppose it's December 31, 1930, and you, poor soul, are trying to make an investment decision: You can put $1,000 of pre-tax income into stocks through an investment plan in which your employer matches your contribution dollar for dollar. Or you can put the after-tax equivalent -- $720 -- in crisp new bills into a vault.<p>
Unlike everyone else alive in 1930, you know that 1931 will turn out to be the worst year in the history of the stock market. Prices will plummet 43.3 percent.<p>
What do you do? Even knowing what you know, you put your money in the plan. You do this convinced that even as others jump from high places your account will do better than plain cash. Indeed, despite the crash you will earn more than the average historic pre-tax return on common stocks.<p>
Why? Because of the massive buffer provided by tax dollars and your employer's contribution. During the year, your $1,000 -- $720 of after-tax savings plus $280 in deferred taxes -- and your employer's $1,000 contribution decline in value to a miserable $1,134. If you closed the account (to, say, take up your new career selling apples) and paid taxes at 28 percent, you would be left with just $816. <p>
But that's still a profit. Since you invested just $720 of real after-tax income, your books actually show a gain of $96, a 13 percent return on the only money that was really yours, the after-tax $720. Because you are in a 401(k), your personal return during the worst year in market history was better than what most investors reap in an average year.<p>
While the example is extreme, what you've just seen is the mathematics behind the current Great No-Fear Market. It's not that we all believe that stocks are better than bonds and that bonds are better than cash, as countless charts tell us. It's this buffer thing. Now that 401(k) plans have superseded defined-benefit pension plans to become the investment vehicle of choice for working Americans, the equity market is much less risky.<p>
The math works even when the employer's contribution is reduced to 50 percent -- the most common match, according to Buck Consultants, a New York됵ased employee-benefits consulting firm. Let's say you had the choice of putting cash into a vault before the dismal year of 1974 or investing in stocks through a 401(k) plan with a 50 percent employer match. An investor in stocks would have seen a nest egg of $1,500 -- $720 of his own money, $280 of deferred taxes, and $500 of employer match -- decline to $1,103 before taxes. If you cashed out and paid 28 percent in taxes, the account's value would have fallen to $794 -- still better than simply holding $720 in cash. Your return would have been 10.3 percent -- an after-tax return similar to the long-term pre-tax return on common stocks.<p>
With just a 50 percent employer match, an investor would have to experience a withering 33 percent market decline before he or she would be better off socking away after-tax income as cash than investing in equities through a 401(k). <p>
How many times has the market declined 33 percent or more? Twice in 70 years, according to data from Ibbotson Associates in Chicago: 43.3 percent in 1931 and 35 percent in 1937. Every other decline was less, usually a lot less. The worst performance in the postwar period is the 26.5 percent drop of 1974.<p>
Still worried? Let's see what happens if we get one of those infrequent long periods of sagging prices -- the kind of market that scores the soul and that can keep an investor out of equities for decades. According to Ibbotson Associates, the worst long-term periods in history all began in the late 1920s: In the 5 years from 1928 to 1932, large stocks lost ground at an annual rate of 12.47 percent; in the 10 years from 1929 to 1938, they lost 0.89 percent a year; in the 15 years from 1929 to 1943, they returned only 0.64 percent a year.<p>
If we were about to start one of those periods today, would you be better off stuffing your cash into a mattress?<p>
Again, the answer is no. As long as you've got the money you would have paid in taxes and your employer's 50 percent match, the best choice is to push ahead in stocks. Suppose the next ten years duplicates the misery of 1929 to 1938. On after-tax contributions of $7,200, your after-tax net for the entire period would accumulate to $10,331. Your effective return would be 7.8 percent a year.<p>
During the same historical ten-year period, the return on T-bills was only 1 percent, pre-tax. The return on intermediate government bonds was 4.7 percent pre-tax and 3.38 percent after-tax.<p>
What happens if disaster doesn't strike and the market just matches its long-term average performance? An investor's annual after-tax contribution of $720 a year will grow to $404,209 over 40 years at a return of 10.5 percent, or 14 times the total investment of $28,800. The same money invested in intermediate government bonds at 5.3 percent will grow only to $96,511. Note that this doesn't count the additional accumulations from the $280 annual deferred-tax contribution or the $500 annual employer's match.<p>
Can a 401(k) investor carry his enthusiasm for equities too far? Certainly. The buffer provided by employer contributions isn't an excuse for blindly investing in bad equities or in equity funds that underperform the market even in good years. (The <a name="FUND:SOCNX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/SOCNX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Steadman Technology Growth Fund</b></a>, for example, has managed to lose a little more than 22 percent a year every year for the past five years.) Nor will this buffer protect the investor who has built up a big position in cash or bonds inside a 401(k) and now wants to invest that money in equities. That transition still needs to be carried out with attention to the riskiness of the equity markets at the moment.<p>
Just remember that for your regular contributions to a 401(k) plan it's best to stop worrying about the market.<p>
THE TEN WORST ANNUAL MARKET DECLINES IN HISTORY
