	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>97/01-What They're Buying Now</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Eight acclaimed mutual-fund managers tell Worth readers about their current favorite stocks. Assume that the manager has bought the stock for his fund at a price lower than the one mentioned here -- the maximum at which he considers it attractive. The manager also may have sold the stock after October 25, the publishing deadline. The approaches of these managers are meant to illustrate a range of successful investing styles. Before readers buy stock, Worth recommends they conduct their own due diligence.<p>
Preston Athey
T. Rowe Price Small Cap Value
Invests in value stocks with market capitalizations under $250 million.
<a name="NASD:RAUT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14566"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Republic Automotive Parts</b></a>  (NASD: RAUT)  Up to $22
Republic Automotive Parts (Brentwood, Tennessee) distributes replacement auto parts and accessories such as spark plugs and windshield wipers through its 16 distribution centers and 94 stores located in 16 states. Through expansion and acquisitions, Republic has recently moved into automotive crash parts -- such vital items as bumpers, fenders, and taillights. Republic is one of only two publicly traded companies in the crash-parts industry, and this move should increase Republic's corporate growth rate and raise its return on equity into the low teens. The stock is still a bargain at 1.3 times book value and 11 times my 1997 earnings estimate of $1.65 a share. <p>
James P. Craig
<A HREF="http://www.janusfunds.com">Janus Fund</A>
Invests primarily in large growth companies with the idea of preserving capital over the long term.
<a name="NYSE:HTG"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12018"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Heritage Media</b></a>  (NYSE: HTG)  Up to $17
Heritage Media (Dallas) is the national leader in what's called targeted marketing: in-store advertising and promotional services. The stock recently took a tumble because of news that a competitor will begin pushing in-store coupon machines. Even if Heritage should lose its share of the coupon market, the company's ownership of six network-affiliated television stations and 23 radio stations in major markets makes this stock highly attractive. Recently, Heritage announced the re-purchase of five million, or 14 percent, of its shares. I expect the stock to earn 65 cents a share in 1996, 95 cents a share in 1997, and $1.20 in 1998. My 12-month target for Heritage is $23.<p>
Shelby M. C. Davis
New York Venture Fund
Invests in large companies using a value-oriented style.
<a name="NYSE:MLM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=41940"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Martin Marietta Materials</b></a>  (NYSE: MLM)  Up to $24
Martin Marietta Materials (Raleigh, North Carolina) is the second-biggest producer of materials called aggregates -- the sand, granite, crushed stone, and such used in large construction projects. Lockheed Martin has just spun off its 80 percent interest in Martin Marietta to Lockheed Martin shareholders in an exchange offer. Martin Marietta has little competition from imports -- these aggregates are too hard to move, literally. I expect the company to earn $1.60 a share in 1996 and $1.90 a share in 1997. The company has strong cash flow and a clean balance sheet, so investments in Martin Marietta should be rock solid. My target price for the stock is $30.<p>
Daniel B. Leonard
Invesco Strategic Portfolios Technology
Seeks growth stocks in technology and related fields.
<a name="NYSE:ECI"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=48058"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Excel Communications</b></a>  (NYSE: ECI)  Up to $40
Excel Communications (Dallas) is the fourth-largest provider of domestic long-distance service and is growing faster than AT&T, MCI, or Sprint. The company, which went public last May, markets its service through an enormous pool of network marketers -- estimated at over 900,000 strong. Currently, 4.1 million subscribers use Excel's service. The company earned 37 cents a share for the third quarter of 1996, a 208 percent increase over  third-quarter earnings in 1995. Excel should earn $1.50 a share in 1996 and $2.05 in 1997. With its new pager services coming on the market and revenues on track to cross $1 billion this year, Excel is an attractive buy. <p>
William J. Nasgovitz
<a name="FUND:HRTVX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/HRTVX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Heartland Value Fund</b></a> 
Buys stocks of small domestic companies believed to be undervalued.
<a name="NASD:WLFI"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=16600"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>WinsLoew Furniture</b></a>  (NASD: WLFI)  Up to $9
WinsLoew Furniture (Pelham, Alabama) designs, manufactures, and sells casual furniture for the residential and institutional markets. The company was formed at the end of 1994 as the result of a merger between Loewenstein Furniture Group and Winston Furniture Company. Earnings growth at WinsLoew is strong: The company should earn 80 cents a share in 1996, twice 1995 earnings. The company recently bought back a million of its own shares and approved the re-purchase of another million. The stock is currently trading at $8.50 a share, just above its book value of $7. This is a well-run company; I agree with the many insiders who think it's undervalued.<p>
Eric E. Ryback
<a name="FUND:LDDVX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/LDDVX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Lindner Dividend Fund</b></a>
Seeks current income first, capital appreciation second.
<a name="NYSE:NU"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11088"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Northeast Utilities System</b></a>  (NYSE: NU)  Up to $11
Northeast Utilities System (Hartford), the largest utility in New England, provides electric service through its subsidiaries in Connecticut, New Hampshire, and western Massachusetts. The company suffered from the shutdown of three of its four nuclear facilities in 1995 and 1996, but those operations should be back on line soon. The current stock price of $10 a share reflects the possibility of a dividend reduction, but risk-tolerant investors should recognize this as a classic value-investing scenario: Northeast Utilities System trades at about 50 to 55 percent of book value and two and a half times cash flow. My 12- to 18-month target price for the stock is $20. <p>
Ralph Wanger
Chuck McQuaid
<a name="FUND:AUSAX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/AUSAX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Acorn Fund</b></a>
Holds stocks of small companies that may benefit from favorable economic trends.
<a name="NASD:ATVI"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=42465"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Activision</b></a>  (NASD: ATVI)  Up to $15
Activision (Los Angeles) develops and markets interactive software for personal computers and for video-game systems such as Nintendo, Sony PlayStation, and Sega. With the consumer-software industry growing at better than 25 percent a year and the holiday season upon us, Activision should continue to benefit from a strong tailwind. Intel's MMX chip and new technologies like 3-D graphics and multiplayer interactive capabilities should drive growth and earnings. I'm looking for Activision to earn 50 cents a share in the fiscal year ending March 1997 and 80 cents a share in 1998. Activision could put a smile on both your face and your children's faces. <p>
Donald A. Yacktman
<a name="FUND:YACKX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/YACKX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Yacktman Fund</b></a>
Seeks long-term growth in companies with market capitalization of at least $1 billion.
<a name="NYSE:MO"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11179"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Philip Morris</b></a>  (NYSE: MO)  Up to $96
Philip Morris (New York) isn't just the world's largest cigarette company. It's also a major food producer, with such household names as Kraft (the largest American processor and marketer of food) and Miller Brewing (the second-largest brewer in the U.S.). If you combine a 72-cents-a-share goodwill charge on the income statement and earnings estimates of $8.95 a share for 1997, investors in Philip Morris will actually earn $9.67 a share next year. Also, the stock pays a generous dividend: $4.80 a share for 1996, a yield of roughly 5 percent at the current price. The stock is down from around $104 in March; it's a cheap buy. <p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
