<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 97/01-A Value Buyer's Shorlist</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>97/01-A Value Buyer's Shorlist</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						With so many closed-end funds selling at deep discounts, investors can afford to be extremely choosy<p>
By Joanmarie Kalter<p>
To create a shortlist of closed-end funds that are selling at rock-bottom discounts and that qualify as good investments now, we subjected the 567 funds in Morningstar's closed-end-fund universe to several tests. <p>
First, we identified funds that are selling at wide discounts to their net asset value: more than a 20 percent discount for equity funds and more than 14 percent for bond funds. Second, we compared the current discount to the average discount that prevailed during 1994 and 1995 and, for each asset class, picked the one fund from each sector that currently sells for the largest discount relative to historical levels. Finally, we screened out any fund that compromised on investment quality -- why settle for second-rate? <p>
An investor can use this list either to pinpoint the best play in an asset class or as the basis of a diversified closed-end portfolio. <p>
One thing to keep in mind, however, is how difficult it is to buy a fund at a discount once the transaction fees are taken into account. That's why experienced closed-end investors use discount-brokerage services whenever possible and try to purchase funds with an NAV of $10 a share or more -- to limit the bite taken out by bid됴sk spreads.<p>
But even so, investors who purchase these funds shouldn't expect a quick bounce. "Be patient," cautions Chris Grant of Grant Strudwick, an investment advisory firm in Baltimore. "That's what value investing is all about."<p>
Nowhere is that value more striking than in closed-end bond funds. The most profitable strategy for investing in any bond fund is to buy when interest rates peak and reap the capital appreciation as rates fall. But who can pick rate peaks?<p>
Buying a closed-end bond fund at a discount is a way around this dilemma. A fund that has a yield of 7 percent and sells at a discount of 13 percent -- or at 87 cents on the dollar -- actually yields 8 percent. <p>
Robert Gavrich, an investment adviser at Seasonal Strategy in San Francisco, explains, "You can wait a long time [for rates to turn or a discount to narrow] with that kind of income coming in."<p>
<img src="/imgs/GRAPH1127c.GIF" width=475 height=210><p>
KEYWORDS: 
Strategy, investor, bargain

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/2pages.gif"><br>About 2 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
</td>
	</tr>
