<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 97/01-Keeping Up With the Bradys</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>97/01-Keeping Up With the Bradys</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						By Leland Montgomery<p>
Returns from Brady bonds, which package emerging-market debt, have been good this year: Many of the funds that invest in these bonds are up more than 33 percent since January 1. But investors should think twice before they buy into this sector in the hope of earning those kinds of returns in the future. A volatile asset like emerging-market debt gyrates wildly between extremes of undervaluation and overvaluation. The best time to buy is at the low point in the cycle. Investors must now ask if these funds -- which reaped their returns from investments in such risky issues as Russian export-import bank loans, Peruvian bonds, and other exotica -- can continue to perform. Russian debt holdings are a big concern.<p>
Two years ago was the time to buy emerging-market debt, says Jean-Marie Eveillard, manager of the SoGen International Fund. "In early 1995, we were being paid very nicely to bear the risks," he says. "Today, we're not." And Ken Gregory, editor of No-Load Fund Analyst, based in Orinda, California, advises selling emerging-market-debt funds. While they could still deliver low-double-digit returns, he says, "the potential for big downward spikes remains." Eveillard, who is holding his positions, doesn't go that far. But he says, "It is a good time to get out of the weaker credits."<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
