	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>97/01S-Top Picks for 1997</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						It's no easy task finding solid opportunities in today's volatile market. Here's what the experts are buying for 1997.<p>
By John Fried<p>
Among the most popular regular columns in Worth are "What They're Buying Now" and "What They're Recommending," in which 12 acclaimed investment professionals discuss their favorite stocks. For this special outlook issue, we have asked our investment pros to be more expansive and offer not just their two favorite stocks of the moment but also their thoughts and insights on the economy, interest rates, and corporate profits for the upcoming year. The results cover 24 carefully argued stock picks and many nuances of opinion.<p>
Don't be surprised at the lack of agreement: We weren't interested in a consensus. We were interested in thought-provoking views and companies that deserve consideration regardless of the direction of the market, the economy, or interest rates.<p>
These professionals are worth listening to not only because of their track records but also for another reason: Each of the eight mutual-fund managers and four newsletter writers follows a carefully honed investing style. To understand each of these styles is to appreciate the breadth of successful stock-picking techniques. There are many ways to pick stocks well, none of them easy.<p>
Some caveats and explanations: It should be assumed in each case that the manager or writer picking a stock has bought it for his fund or portfolio. He may, however, have sold all or some of his shares after the publishing deadline of November 22, 1996. Worth always recommends that readers conduct their own due diligence before investing. Below each stock name is the maximum price at which the stock picker considers it attractive.<p>
PRESTON ATHEY
Athey, who manages the <a name="FUND:PRSVX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/PRSVX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>T. Rowe Price Small Cap Value Fund</b></a>, looks for reasonably priced stocks with market capitalizations under $500 million. His fund received a $$$$$ rating in Worth's November 1996 survey of mutual funds. <p>
Outlook: The economy will grow slowly in 1997, with corporate profits hard-pressed to match those of 1996. The stock market should be fine in the first half of the year but could fade in the second. I doubt full-year returns will surpass 8 percent. After the major gains of 1995 and 1996, 1997 may be a year in which we re-balance the scales. <p>
<a name="NYSE:CSS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11790"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>CSS Industries</b></a> 
Up to $26
Philadelphia-based CSS Industries (NYSE: CSS) is a leading producer of Halloween masks, holiday gift cards, ribbons, and bows. In late 1995, CSS acquired gift-wrap manufacturer Cleo from <a name="NASD:GIBG"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13571"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Gibson Greetings</b></a>. Cleo lost money for Gibson, but CSS has made it solidly profitable. With abundant cash flow of about $2.50 a share, CSS can continue to reduce debt and make additional acquisitions in the years ahead to boost earnings. The stock has little Wall Street sponsorship and currently trades at an attractive 11 times estimated 1997 earnings of $2.20 a share.<p>
<a name="NASD:POBR"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=17055"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Poe & Brown</b></a>
Up to $30
Poe & Brown (Nasdaq: POBR) is a rapidly growing insurance broker focused on providing property and casualty insurance directly to commercial and professional customers. Headquartered in Daytona Beach, Florida, Poe & Brown has the largest share of Florida's insurance market and is expanding in other Sun Belt markets, such as Atlanta and Phoenix. The company has a return on equity of over 25 percent and is rapidly gaining market share against its rivals. Nevertheless, the stock sells for only 11 times 1997 earnings estimates of $2.20 a share. Chief executive officer J. Hyatt Brown is one of the most impressive managers I have ever met, and his single-minded focus on building a profitable business bodes well for Poe & Brown in 1997.<p>
JAMES P. CRAIG
Craig manages the Janus Fund, which earned a $$$$ rating from Worth in 1996. Craig seeks capital gains from large companies with outstanding growth prospects.<p>
Outlook: The market is walking a tightrope. If the economy continues to grow at around 2 percent or less, interest rates should remain stable and the market will be robust. If the economy accelerates, rates will rise and there will be downside risk for stocks. With almost full employment and low interest rates, there is little room for improvement and tremendous potential for volatility in the market. <p>
<a name="NYSE:WFC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11619"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Wells Fargo</b></a> 
Up to $300
Wells Fargo (NYSE: WFC) is way ahead of its peers as it moves its banking business toward lower-cost forms of distribution. This has allowed the company to free up a great deal of capital, which it returns to stockholders through substantial stock repurchases: The company has authorized the repurchase of up to 10 percent of its shares. I'm expecting the April 1996 merger with First Interstate Bancorp to add to earnings within 18 months, and yet the stock still looks cheap at its current price of around $275 a share. The only worry for this company is a significant recession in California, which would bring credit issues to the fore. Barring this, Wells Fargo should trade in the low to mid $300s in 1997.<p>
<a name="NYSE:HTG"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12018"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Heritage Media</b></a> 
Up to $18
Shares of Heritage Media (NYSE: HTG), the Dallas-based leader of in-store advertising and promotional services, have been pummeled recently (down to around $14 from $22) because of the entry of a competitor into the in-store couponing market. Yet this business makes up only 20 percent of Heritage's cash flow, while the rest of the business -- including Actmedia in-store marketing, direct mail, TV, and radio -- is posting consistently strong growth. Earnings and cash flow remain high, and the company recently announced the buyback of 14 percent of its shares. I've known management since the 1980s; with such capable people behind Heritage, its stock should shoot right back into the $20s in 1997.<p>
SHELBY M. C. DAVIS
Davis is the manager of the New York Venture Fund, which earned a $$$$$ rating from Worth in 1996. He invests in large companies whose earnings are growing faster than those of the average company but that are selling at below-average multiples of earnings or book values. <p>
Outlook: It all hinges on corporate profits. If we head into a recession because we run out of steam, or the Fed wants it, then all bets are off. It won't be the end of the world -- just a traditional bear market. But I'm betting the good news will continue. <p>
<a name="NYSE:AXP"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10085"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>American Express</b></a> 
Up to $50
This New York됵ased financial-services giant (NYSE: AXP) is in the midst of a determined turnaround of its credit-card business. It has plans to offer more co-branded cards with other companies, expand its frequent-usage rewards, and more. I remain impressed with CEO Harvey Golub, who has taken strides to expand the acceptance of the American Express card and is determined to double card usage by the year 2000. With the stock currently trading at only 12 times 1997 earnings, it's a good value in today's market. <p>
<a name="NYSE:IBM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10796"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>International Business Machines</b></a> 
Up to $137
After disappointing earnings in the first two quarters of 1996, IBM (NYSE: IBM), based in Armonk, New York, delivered an impressive third-quarter earnings performance that has revived investors' interest. Moreover, Big Blue announced a focus on selling "solutions" -- services designed to help customers in every aspect of the tech world, from buying a computer to saving a document. Computer services industry-wide are estimated to grow 25 percent a year for several years, so this strategy seems right on target. What's more, IBM has a strong balance sheet and an active stock-repurchase plan.<p>
AL FRANK
Frank's Prudent Speculator is the top-performing newsletter for the past 5 years and the past 15 years, according to The Hulbert Financial Digest. Frank looks for deeply undervalued stocks that sell at a fraction of their intrinsic value.<p>
Outlook: I expect 1997 to be about half as good as 1996, producing overall returns around 10 percent. Historically, the year after a president's reelection is rarely as good as the following three. While it's almost unheard of to have seven straight years of rising stock prices, the stock market is unlikely to drop unless the Federal Reserve raises rates at least twice.<p>
<a name="NASD:BELF"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12760"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Bel Fuse</b></a> 
Up to $11.88
The shares of Bel Fuse (Nasdaq: BELF), a Jersey City manufacturer of low-end electronic components -- such as fuses, filters, and transformers for computer networks and other high-technology products -- are a bargain. Low demand in the second and third quarters of 1996 produced disappointing earnings, driving the stock down 50 percent from its April high of over $22 a share. The stock is now priced at only seven times Bel Fuse's temporarily depressed earnings and below net asset value of $12.08 a share. The company has no long-term debt and more than four dollars a share in cash and marketable securities. Our three- to five-year target is $24. <p>
<a name="NYSE:SCR.A"></a><b>Sea Containers</b> 
Up to $21
Bermuda-based Sea Containers (NYSE: SCR.A) has recently come down into the value basement. The company owns and operates ferries, trains, and ports; leases cargo containers; and owns hotels and resorts worldwide. It recently secured a seven-year franchise to provide high-speed rail service between Scotland and London. The deal is valued at $450 million a year, which will more than double the company's current annual sales. Yet the stock has since drifted down because of weakness in the marine-container business, leaving the stock valued at only two times cash flow and less than its net asset value of $20 a share. Yet it pays a dividend yield near 5 percent. My three- to five-year target is $40.<p>
DANIEL B. LEONARD
Leonard manages the Invesco Strategic Portfolios Technology Fund, rated $$$$$ by Worth when we last rated sector funds in 1995. He currently favors established technology leaders and service firms that use technology to gain a competitive edge. <p>
Outlook: I think profit margins have plateaued, so it's going to be tough for companies to increase earnings in 1997. If the economy grows at its current rate of 2 to 2.5 percent and keeps producing relatively full employment, the market will remain in a growth mode. If growth accelerates beyond that, you'll see wage pressure, inflation, and the threat of rising interest rates. <p>
<a name="NYSE:CNC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10391"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Conseco</b></a> 
Up to $55
Conseco (NYSE: CNC), based in Carmel, Indiana, is an aggressive acquirer and operator of life-insurance companies throughout the U.S. It is renowned for buying lackluster companies at low prices, cutting costs aggressively, and ditching underperforming businesses in order to quickly boost return on equity. Conseco made six acquisitions in 1996, focusing on life insurance, annuities, and health insurance. I expect these to add to earnings this year. I'm forecasting earnings growth of 19 percent in 1996 and 33 percent in 1997. My 12-month target for the stock is $75.<p>
<a name="NYSE:STT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14795"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>State Street Boston</b></a> 
Up to $65
This Boston-based bank-and-trust operation (NYSE: STT) acts as custodian and provider of security-transaction services to mutual funds, annuities, and money managers. With $2.7 trillion of assets in custody and $280 billion under management, it is one of the largest and most profitable companies in the bank-and-trust industry. The recent acquisition of Princeton Financial Systems, which provides management software for the insurance and investment industries, should enable the company to continue to produce earnings growth in excess of 16 percent in both 1996 and 1997. The stock should go to $90 a share by year-end. <p>
JIM McCAMANT
McCamant has extensive experience in the fields of biotechnology and venture capital and focuses on biotechnology investments in his Medical Technology Stock Letter.<p>
Outlook: I'm looking for a favorable environment for stocks in 1997 -- further slow growth with continuing low inflation. The big winners should be smaller-company growth stocks, particularly those biotech companies that are just starting to show profits. After a mid-1996 correction, many of the group's stocks have been brought back down to bargain levels.<p>
<a name="NASD:CHIR"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12972"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Chiron</b></a> 
Up to $30
Chiron (Nasdaq: CHIR), based in Emeryville, California, is our favorite among the large and profitable biotechs. The company is skilled in four promising new-product areas -- diagnostics, ophthalmics, therapeutics, and vaccines. Heavy research expenses and the cost of filing five new-product applications with the Food and Drug Administration penalized earnings in 1996. In 1997, most of these products should get the green light, fueling a sharp increase in net income. With over $1 billion in current revenues, an outstanding research team, and a large number of new products in development, Chiron is one of the best and least risky ways to participate in the growth of this industry. Our 18- to 24-month target is $50. <p>
<a name="NASD:XOMA"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=15185"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Xoma</b></a> 
Up to $8
Previous product disappointments have left this biotech (Nasdaq: XOMA), based in Berkeley, California, undervalued and out of favor. But 1997 should be a breakthrough year. I anticipate positive news coming out of the testing of Neuprex, a promising new drug for treating trauma associated with major blood loss and for fighting antibiotic-resistant bacteria. The company also expects to get approval in Japan for E5, a drug that treats severe bacterial infection. Our 18- to 24-month target price for the stock is $16.<p>
MICHAEL MURPHY
Murphy is editor of California  Technology Stock Letter, one of the top five newsletters of the past ten years, according to The Hulbert Financial Digest. <p>
Outlook: I don't see any big problems in the U.S. economy in 1997 in terms of either inflation or recession. Any pullback in the U.S. stock markets will likely fall on cyclical or domestic consumer stocks like restaurants and retail. With the Far East and Europe bouncing back from a flat 1996, companies that sell technology products or that have a high export component are going to do especially well in 1997.<p>
<a name="NASD:PMAT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=47170"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Plasma & Materials Technology</b></a>
Up to $16
Plasma & Materials Technology (Nasdaq: PMAT), based in Chatsworth, California, produces semiconductor equipment for a process called high density/low pressure. The process is used to etch semiconductor chips with the microcircuit lines that carry electronic currents. As chips get smaller, making this process more delicate and difficult, this technology is becoming necessary for most chip manufacturers. The company is already strong in the U.S. and Far East and is in the process of extending its reach throughout Europe by acquiring British-based Electrotech. If the technology sector picks up in 1997, Plasma & Materials will be on the cutting edge.<p>
<a name="NASD:INSV"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=16596"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>InSite Vision</b></a> 
Up to $7
This Alameda, California됵ased pharmaceutical company (Nasdaq: INSV) has developed a time-release delivery system to feed drugs directly into the human eye to fight glaucoma. Clinical trials on this system, in which drugs are placed inside the eyelid and released during the day, are already complete. InSite has entered into a marketing partnership with <a name="NYSE:BOL"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10187"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Bausch & Lomb</b></a> and Ciba-Geigy. If all goes well, the company could have two products, BetaSite and PilaSite, on the market by year-end 1997. Although I expect losses through 1996 and 1997, this kind of stock trades on new-product news. Currently down from a 12-month high of $8.25 a share to just above $4, the stock is cheap. My 18-month target is $20.<p>
WILLIAM NASGOVITZ 
Nasgovitz, manager of Heartland Value Fund, which earned a $$$$$ rating in our 1996 mutual-fund survey, primarily buys very small companies selling at low multiples of their earnings or book value. <p>
Outlook: Overall, the stock market may be a bit feeble in 1997. With many investors buying large global stocks, the small-company market has been left at the gate for some time. We think this trend is close to turning, and we note that long periods of lagging performance by very small companies are historically followed by long periods of above-average returns.<p>
<a name="NYSE:ICN"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10763"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>ICN Pharmaceuticals</b></a> 
Up to $22
ICN (NYSE: ICN), based in Costa Mesa, California, makes a broad range of prescription and over-the-counter drugs and markets them in more than 60 countries, particularly in the emerging markets of Eastern Europe and Latin America. While I expect revenues and earnings to continue growing at 25 percent a year or better, the stock remains remarkably cheap. Major drug companies trade at an average of 20 times 1997 earnings, but ICN sells for only 7.5 times my forecasted 1997 earnings of $2.75 a share. Also, ICN hopes to get FDA approval for a drug to treat hepatitis C, developed in a joint project with <a name="NYSE:SGP"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11326"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Schering-Plough</b></a>. My 12-month target is $30.<p>
<a name="NYSE:ALW"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12563"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Allwaste</b></a> 
Up to $5 
Allwaste (NYSE: ALW), based in Houston, provides industrial-waste handling, processing, and transportation as well as container-cleaning services for major industrial facilities. After several troubled years, new management has successfully introduced programs aimed at improving profitability. I expect Allwaste to earn 40 cents a share in 1997 -- which would value the shares at a reasonable 11 times 1997 earnings. The company currently services 12,000 facilities and has a large share-buyback program under way. Our 12-month target is seven dollars.<p>
LOUIS NAVELLIER
Navellier, editor of MPT Review, uses modern portfolio theory to identify high-return, low-volatility stocks. According to The Hulbert Financial Digest, Navellier's model portfolios had the highest return among all newsletter portfolios for the past ten years. <p>
Outlook: I don't think the Federal Reserve will tighten rates in the next few months, so we should have a solid earnings-driven market. But with expectations down, it's not going to be a rip-roarer. I expect only a few areas to do well: the oil-service and -drilling sectors and consumer stocks.<p>
<a name="NYSE:NKE"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14254"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>NIKE class B</b></a> 
Up to $68
Athletic-shoe and -apparel maker Nike (NYSE: NKE) has been living up to its slogan: "Just do it." The Beaverton, Oregon됵ased company ended its May 1996 fiscal year with earnings up 39 percent from 1995; sales for the domestic apparel division were up 99 percent. The company is at the head of the class in the fast-growing retail sector. With earnings forecasts of $5.11 a share for 1997 and $6.07 for 1998, I believe Nike is ready for another banner year. <p>
<a name="NYSE:RIG"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10082"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Transocean Offshore</b></a> 
Up to $78
This Houston-based company (NYSE: RIG) provides contract drilling of oil and gas in offshore areas worldwide. Transocean operates 27 offshore drilling units, including 18 submersibles (drilling vessels that float below the water's surface and operate in rough water), 6 jack-up rigs, and 3 ships designed to drill in deep water. The drilling boom will continue in 1997, so I'm looking for earnings of $2.50 a share in 1996 and $3.77 in 1997.<p>
ERIC E. RYBACK
Manager of the Lindner Dividend Fund for over a decade, Ryback has been earning solid returns while assuming little risk. His strategy emphasizes current income first and capital appreciation second. The fund earned a $$$ rating in 1996. <p>
Outlook: I'm not positive on the outlook for 1997 -- the market is trading at particularly high levels, and I'm not sure they can be sustained. Rates could rise and slow down the economy and depress earnings. Investors should err on the side of caution, putting money into defensive funds. <p>
<a name="NYSE:KNE"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10829"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>KN Energy</b></a> 
Up to $40
KN Energy (NYSE: KNE), based in Lakewood, Colorado, is a fully integrated natural-gas company that transports gas from the field to consumers in Colorado, Kansas, Nebraska, and Wyoming. While much of the industry still sells gas at regulated rates, approximately 60 percent of KN's operations are unregulated, allowing the company to earn heftier profit margins. I look for annual earnings growth of 15 percent, which will raise profits from 1996's $2.15 a share to $3 as early as 1998. <p>
<a name="NYSE:EEX"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10522"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Enserch Exploration</b></a> 
Up to $12
Dallas-based Enserch Exploration (NYSE: EEX) is one of the major players in the potentially huge exploration effort in the deep waters of the Gulf of Mexico. The shares trade at a discount to the value of the company's current reserves, to say nothing of the potential from new exploratory wells. The shares are worth at least $13 to $14, and the company makes an attractive acquisition candidate -- which could place an even higher value on the stock.<p>
RALPH WANGER & CHUCK McQUAID
Wanger and McQuaid, along with Terence Hogan, manage the acclaimed Acorn Fund, which received a $$$$$ rating from Worth in November 1996. They look for small-company stocks that will benefit from favorable economic and business trends. 
Outlook: We think there are three trends to watch in 1997: Video programmers will benefit from the increase in specialized programming; the move toward home health care will gather momentum; and there will be a continued push toward outsourcing computer services.<p>
<a name="NYSE:LBTYA"></a><b>Tele-Communications Liberty Media Group</b>
Up to $32
With interests in more than 90 fast-growing cable-TV and satellite channels, Liberty Media Group (Nasdaq: LBTYA), based in Englewood, Colorado, is one of the most promising companies we own. Over the past 12 months, the value of Liberty's investments in other companies has grown substantially. The Learning Channel has become profitable after years of losses. The Discovery Channel, whose cash flow is up more than 15 percent, will benefit from the newly launched channel Animal Planet and the to-be-launched Kids. Regional Sports Channel's cash flows have grown more than 50 percent, and QVC's cash flows have increased more than 15 percent. Liberty holds interests in <a name="NYSE:TWX"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11482"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Time Warner</b></a> (worth about $10 a share of Liberty stock), <a name="NYSE:HSN"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12024"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Home Shopping Network</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:SKTV"></a><b>Silver King</b>, International Family, and BET Holdings. While Liberty's underlying value has grown from $36.50 a share to over $40 in 1996, the stock has risen just $1, making it an even better buy.<p>
<a name="AMEX:TDS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12376"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Telephone and Data Systems</b></a>
Up to $40
Chicago-based TDS (ASE: TDS) has a hand in almost every aspect of the telecommunications business: a thriving rural telephone service in 37 states and ownership stakes in three hot wireless markets, including an 82 percent stake in United States Cellular, an 80 percent interest in American Paging, and an 83 percent interest in the new wireless personal-communications-service company American Portable Telecommunications. Cash flow for TDS's cellular service grew more than 50 percent in 1996. We believe the stock's total underlying value is at least $70 a share, making TDS one of the cheapest stocks we own.<p>
DONALD A. YACKTMAN
Yacktman runs the acclaimed Yacktman Fund, which seeks long-term growth from companies with market capitalizations of at least $1 billion. Worth hasn't rated the fund, because its track record goes back only three years.<p>
Outlook: Rising credit-card delinquencies and approximately a million bankruptcies filed last year are the economy's Achilles' heel. If banks start to tighten their credit standards, consumer spending and the economy will slow. Whatever happens to the economy, the investor should remain focused on one quest: looking for great companies at great prices. <p>
<a name="NYSE:FNQ"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=15674"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Franklin Quest</b></a>
Up to $24
This Salt Lake City됵ased company (NYSE: FNQ) provides highly effective time-management products and seminars for businesses, government agencies, and the public. Earnings for the company, whose trademark product is the Franklin Day Planner, grew nearly 30 percent a year but had a poor 1996. Franklin should earn about $2.15 a share in calendar year 1997, and cash earnings are close to $2.50 a share after write-offs for goodwill are added. The market is undervaluing the company's enviable market niche and strong balance sheet.<p>
<a name="NASD:BARE"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=15449"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Barefoot</b></a> 
Up to $12
With more than 400,000 customers in the central and eastern United States, lawn-care provider Barefoot (Nasdaq: BARE), based in Worthington, Ohio, is prospering by bringing professional management to what has traditionally been a mom-and-pop business. While weather-influenced sales fluctuate widely, the company always manages to generate a lot of free cash, which it consistently uses to buy back shares. Adding goodwill charges to Barefoot's 1997 estimated earnings produces cash earnings of $1.20 a share and one of the market's lowest valuations for a steadily growing company.<p>
KEYWORDS: prediction, pick 

					</font>
