		<title> Worth OnLine - 97/01S-Come on Home</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>97/01S-Come on Home</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						You didn't give up hope, did you? Thanks to the overall strength of the economy and the trends in demographics and real estate, home prices are climbing again.<p>
By Nick Ravo<p>
Have you hugged a baby boomer lately? After years of sluggish sales and falling or flat prices, the residential real-estate market is finally moving upward. And it's boomer behavior, fueled in large part by a healthier economy, that's nudging the value of houses across the country. <p>
Almost every homeowner stands to benefit from the upcoming market trends. Sales in starter homes are taking off, more people are trading up to better houses, and the demand for second homes is strong. The outlook is so rosy, in fact, that many folks are even starting to abandon the fixation with remodeling that they picked up in the recession-hammered early 1990s. <p>
"It has been a banner time for home sales all over," says John Tuccillo, chief economist with the National Association of Realtors, a trade group in Washington, D.C. "Even the Northeast is doing better." Don't think this is a replay of the cash-bloated mid-1980s; a cookie-cutter condo behind a strip mall isn't going to appreciate by 30 percent over the next 12 months. But you will be able to have some confidence -- and be a little aggressive -- as you put your house on the market.<p>
In fact, in 1996 the rise in median prices for existing homes (as opposed to newly constructed homes) bested the national inflation rate of 2.7 percent in every state except California, Hawaii (the only state in which prices fell, by 3 percent), New York, and Rhode Island, plus the District of Columbia, according to Regional Financial Associates, a Pennsylvania-based economic forecasting service.<p>
It may not sound like great news that price increases are staying ahead of inflation, but don't underestimate the wonders of leverage, which makes even a smidgen of an increase meaningful. For example, if you have 25 percent equity in a home, a 4 percent rise in value produces a 16 percent gain on the money you have invested. Moreover, the mortgage interest is tax deductible. Even better, if President Clinton's campaign promise becomes law (and in this case the GOP has no reason to oppose him), most capital gains on home sales will be eliminated. <p>
"After years of worrying about declining prices, people were put off about buying a home," says Mark M. Zandi, chief economist with Regional Financial Associates. "Now people are feeling better about the housing market." Zandi credits low unemployment and low interest rates for the surge in consumer confidence. The federal government's aggressive promotion of affordable-housing programs, particularly those that have eased restrictions on loan qualifications, has helped, too. <p>
Even real estate in Southern California, which alone represents 5 percent of the nation's housing, has begun to pull out of a devastating five-year slump. Median sale prices there posted a 0.7 percent gain in 1996 over 1995. The future looks even better: Prices are expected to rise by 4.6 percent in 1997.<p>
That slow but steady improvement in Southern California, however, will be a drag on home prices in other regions. Price growth in the mountain states, which had been rocketing because of refugees from California, has already started to plateau. So don't expect prices to increase as quickly as they did in 1996 -- don't, that is, expect another year of 12.3 percent growth in Utah (the national leader for the year) and 8.8 percent growth in Arizona. "Those states are still building, but the California influx has about stopped," cautions Zandi. <p>
It has also slowed in the northern part of California -- another place Southern Californians have been congregating. But in this case the outlook is bright. In the San Francisco Bay area, recession-stung developers are chary about building, even though housing demand is on the rise. In effect, there's a shortage of housing in that region, and prices reflect that. <p>
Overall, 1997 will be a little less inspiring than 1996. Zandi projects that prices nationwide for existing homes will jump 3 percent in 1997 versus 5.3 percent in 1996. Still, new-home prices may inch up more than those of existing homes, in part because of quotas on Canadian lumber imports. <p>
A sector not to be overlooked is the second-home market. In New York's coastal Hamptons area, prices have already surpassed the levels they hit in the gilded 1980s. "There is an abundance of buyers and a lack of product," says Gary DePersia, a real-estate agent with the East Hampton firm Allan M. Schneider Associates. "And the higher the price, the less there is."<p>
DePersia notes that only at the bottom of the market -- the $300,000 to $400,000 price range -- are homes available in any significant quantity. He also points out that today's buyers are steering away from the stark, angular contemporary designs that sprouted like postmodern weeds in many second-home communities, particularly in beach areas, a decade or two ago. "People want something more traditional," says DePersia.<p>
But it's not just weekenders who are behind the rising second-home market. Those in search of a faraway vacation home, most often in a warm climate and possibly in a future retirement area, are snapping up bargain homes. This is especially true in Florida (with the northwest part of the state leading the way). That's because real-estate prices there still pale in comparison with those in Arizona and California. Again, Florida can salute the boomers for this boon. The state will see a real-estate explosion once the generation takes up shuffleboard in a decade or so. Historically, about 25 percent of all retirees who move to the Sun Belt have headed to Florida. And that may mean huge demand and translate to even huger profits if you beat the crowd.<p>
But you needn't be on the cusp of retirement to profit from Florida's growth. Here's a suggestion some financial advisers are making to northern homeowners who have big, valuable houses and are at least 55 years old (and thus able to exempt $125,000 in capital gains from their federal income taxes, as current law allows; the expected capital-gains change would open this up to younger people, too): Sell your house now, and buy a smaller one in Florida. Rent out the Florida house. Invest the money left over from selling the house and use the income, along with income from the Florida rental property, to rent yourself a northern home. When you're ready to retire, move into the Florida house.<p>
This slightly offbeat strategy not only positions you well for the impending migration but also takes you out of the northern housing market when the baby boomers in the north will be trying to sell their homes en masse. As they say in the business, there is one rule for making money in real estate: Get in front of the baby boomers' demand. <p>
Oh, and the clamor for housing those boomers will make. About 70 million Americans will celebrate birthdays number 33 through 51 in 1997.<p>
With all the boomer-led good news in one part of the economy, you had to figure there would be boomer-led bad news elsewhere, and there is: Home improvement is on the decline. Americans spent $97.5 billion on home upkeep and improvements in 1991. The figure reached $115 billion in 1994, but it fell to $112.6 billion in 1995, the last year for which figures are available from the National Association of Home Builders.<p>
One reason for this declining interest in renovations may be that in many cases homeowners don't recoup their improvement expense when they sell. Swimming pools, for example, don't increase a home's sale price. Nor do skylights, which are bad news for energy bills.<p>
That's not to say that the right improvement won't pay off. Home offices, media rooms, and mini-gyms top the list of must-haves for many homeowners. Creating a larger kitchen, often by combining it with a living room into something we're all being encouraged to call a "great room," is the renovation du jour. <p>
If there's any room more deserving of attention than the kitchen, it's the bathroom, which has increased in size and splendidness. Few things, apparently, beat a double-sized Jacuzzi or a sexy all-glass shower with twin showerheads. "Bathrooms have become the place to retreat to," explains Gopal Ahluwalia, an economist at the National Home Builders Association. "They make or break the sale of a home."<p>
Then again, there's something to be said for doing what you want. Your house is your kingdom, that BarcaLounger your throne. "The concept of 'home' is changing," says Peter Miller, author of How to Sell Your Home in Any Market. "More and more of us work from home, we shop from home, and a growing number of us seem to vacation at home. So why shouldn't home have more amenities and luxuries?"<p>
So give a boomer a hug. After all the recent years of no or low returns, your patience is finally being rewarded.<p>
Nick Ravo is a frequent contributor to Worth and a reporter for The New York Times.<p>
