<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/11-Finding Your Family in Cyberspace</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/11-Finding Your Family in Cyberspace</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
By Jim Jubak<p>
Acorn, <a HREF="http://www.fid-inv.com/mutual/fund_data/fund_data.html"> Fidelity</A>, <a HREF="http://www.gabelli.com/">Gabelli</A>, <a HREF="http://networth.galt.com/www/home/mutual/iai/">IAI</A>,  <a HREF="http://www.janusfunds.com/cgi-bin/genobject">Janus</A>, <a HREF="http://www.kemper.com/">Kemper</A>, <a HREF="http://networth.galt.com/www/home/mutual/neuberger/">Neuberger & Berman</A>, <a HREF="http://www.rsim.com/index.html">Robertson Stephens</A>, <a HREF="http://networth.galt.com/www/home/mutual/scudder/">Scudder</A>, <a HREF="http://www.cts.com/browse/poirier/seligman.html">Seligman</A>, <a HREF="http://networth.galt.com/www/home/mutual/steinroe/">Stein Roe</A>, <a HREF="http://www.strong-funds.com/">Strong</A>, <a HREF="http://www.templeton.ca/">Templeton</A>, <a HREF="http://www.twentieth-century.com/">Twentieth Century</A>, <a HREF="http://www.vanguard.com/">Vanguard</A>
 -- sometimes it seems every mutual-fund family has launched its own site on the Internet. Any investor who doesn't make a regular habit of buying magic beans and bridges to Brooklyn knows these are marketing vehicles. But some fund companies have realized that they need to do more than just promote their funds if they want anyone to read their pages. This means that many of these pages now offer a surprising array of free tools and information.<p>
The World Wide Web site of Twentieth Century Mutual Funds and the Benham Group (<a HREF="http://www.twentieth-century.com">www.twentieth-century.com</A>) is one of the best -- and a sign of things to come. As you might expect, you can sign on to order a prospectus for any one of the company's funds, review your account, or move money from one fund in the family to another. You can click on a menu of funds to get a brief profile of a specific fund -- with return numbers for the year to date and 1, 3, 5, 10, even 20 years, as well as similar numbers for a benchmark index. You can also get data on the fund's top ten holdings and five most heavily weighted industries and receive rankings of the fund against its peers.<p>
All that is a pretty straightforward, but informative and accurate, marketing pitch. The site offers more. There's a free portfolio tracker that can update the prices, volume, and market value of up to ten portfolios of 30 stocks, mutual funds, and options each. The tracker will even let an investor set alerts to ring when a stock or fund crosses a price threshold. (Unfortunately, the tracker won't calculate returns on an investment.)<p>
The site also has sections on setting goals and calculating how much you'll need to invest to reach them. It's standard financial-planning advice, and there aren't any spreadsheets that do the calculations for you after you've filled in the data. But this is a solid reference.<p>
Other fund companies have equally strong offerings, with the specific strengths and weaknesses of each reflecting the personality of the family. For example, Fidelity Investments (<a HREF="http://www.fid-inv.com">www.fid-inv.com</A>) piles information on top of information -- planners, prospectuses, even news with market commentary. Janus (<a HREF="http://www.janusfunds.com">www.janusfunds.com</A>) opens with a photo of a skier and asks an investor to navigate the slopes to find information in "Buzz" sections. For a thorough list of the fund families on the Net, search "Mutual Funds" with the search engine Yahoo! (<a HREF="http://www.Yahoo.com">www.Yahoo.com</A>).
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

