<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/10-"Only the Paranoid Survive"</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/10-"Only the Paranoid Survive"</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						"Mean Business"
By Albert J. Dunlap 
(Times Business, $25)<p>
"An Eye for Winners"
By Lillian Vernon
(HarperCollins, $23)<p>
By Greg Critser<p>
Business biography is a uniquely American art form. Confessional, quirky, often full of bluster, it is a literature with its own distinct narrative beats. Inspiration and will are inevitably followed by trouble and temptation; next comes the crashing in of a cruel, Schumpeterian world and the reign of chaos; finally, renewal and redemption triumph. You don't have to listen too hard to hear the Puritan overtones.<p>
True, some stories are more redemptive than others: The humorously self-effacing David Ogilvy's Ogilvy on Advertising, for example, will do more for the soul than Lee Iacocca's shameless self-hagiography. Yet good or bad, these books are all exhortations -- or cowboy jeremiads, in some cases -- and many of us can't seem to get enough of them. That's because we want to believe in them, of course, and that's why, predictably, so many of them fail to live up to our expectations. <p>
Certainly this is the case with <a name="NASD:INTC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13787"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Intel</b></a> CEO Andrew S. Grove's Only the Paranoid Survive. Grove details how Intel, the world's leading producer of semiconductors, was forced into what he calls a "10X" change. A "10X" change occurs, we learn, when the very fundamentals of a business are challenged. In Intel's case this happened in late 1994, when relatively minor flaws were discovered in the company's newest product, the Pentium processor. So vociferously did Intel's customers protest that Grove reversed long-standing Intel policy and gave every customer a new chip. (Past exchanges had depended on Intel evaluations.) As a result, Intel, once driven purely by technology, became a customer-driven business and therefore more responsive to the fast changes shaping the ever evolving technology business.<p>
Grove's account of how the Intel staff met this challenge will come as an encouraging read for executives and middle managers: Rapid change can be attained, Grove is saying. But his book fails miserably in its greater ambition, at least as expressed in its subtitle, How to Exploit the Crisis Points That Challenge Every Company and Career. This suggests that Grove can teach readers to intuit such changes, yet the best he can muster are chestnuts on the order of "Look for changes in the power, vigor, and competence of customers." Grove's reliance on this kind of business mumbo jumbo seems to express a belief that merely repeating buzzwords elevates them to the status of Eternal Truth. "Before the strategic inflection point, the industry simply was more like the old," he reveals at one point. "After it, it is more like the new."<p>
Oh.<p>
Readers won't have to endure any such icky nostrums in Mean Business, by turnaround artist and former Scott Paper CEO Albert J. "Chainsaw Al" Dunlap (ably assisted by co-writer Bob Andelman). For those who've been vacationing on the planet Pluto (or contemplating strategic inflection points), Dunlap is the Hoboken-born ex-paratrooper that Wall Street loves (because he is single-mindedly dedicated to increasing shareholder value) and management hates (because he is always firing them). He's not interested in some mysterious carpe diem or weird "10X" factor; he just wants to get the maximum bang for every invested dollar -- even if that means making life hell for everyone around him.<p>
Consider Dunlap's most acclaimed and controversial achievement, the turnaround of Scott Paper. In 1994, when Dunlap was brought in to save the 115-year-old firm, Scott had just registered a stunning $300 million loss. Its stock was in the can. Dunlap applied his vinegar, laying off 11,200 "unproductive" workers -- 35 percent of the company's payroll -- and selling off unrelated assets. The result: By 1995, Scott had experienced record earnings and a 163 percent jump in its stock price. Eventually, <a name="NYSE:KMB"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10856"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Kimberly-Clark Corp</b></a>. bought it for $7 billion. For his trouble -- and there was a lot of it -- Dunlap pocketed $100 million.<p>
Color abounds in Mean Business. Red, mainly. Dunlap's response to learning that Scott has a corporate-morale officer? "Get rid of her!" The fate of a narcoleptic in-house lawyer? "A few days later, he was memory." Charitable donations? "They should also be history." There's a certain visceral glee in Dunlap's story, particularly for anyone who's tried to change a corporate dinosaur. This book makes you feel like swearing a whole bunch -- proudly.<p>
Still, most contemporary discussions of Dunlap pivot on one point: Did he deserve $100 million when, at the same time, so many loyal Scott workers were...history? To that Dunlap has offered the irrefutable logic that without his cutting there would be no jobs. But that's the great dodge in this book; he fails to answer the question of how long these short-term solutions can keep a company afloat. A better question concerning the futures of the companies he rescues might be "What hath Al wrought?" Dunlap tells of goading purchasing agents to "practice brinkmanship" with vendors, to "narrow suppliers to a handful," and to "leverage volume." All seemingly good advice in the short term, but what happens when, perhaps during a paper shortage, vendors again hold the upper hand? Reading all this in the light of Dunlap's credo -- "I think of every dollar as a brother" -- one wonders if that isn't because the dollar is the only thing that will have him.<p>
After all this heavy stuff, <a name="AMEX:LVC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12111"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Lillian Vernon</b></a>'s somewhat haimish An Eye for Winners comes at just the right moment. Vernon, who built a $220 million mail-order business from the simple idea of selling monogrammed purses and belts, offers her own, rather humble advice to the budding entrepreneur (get a good accountant, watch cash flow, etc.). But it's her heartfelt personal story that really carries the book and that reminds us that lives -- not businesses -- have narratives we care about. Vernon and family fled the Nazis in the early 1930s, and the tale of how these expatriate, upper-class German Jews re-established themselves in the New World in New York never flags in communicating the joys of running an enterprise -- something a few other CEOs seem to have forgotten about entirely.<p>
Keyword: Review

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/4pages.gif"><br>About 4 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

<font size=+1><b>Company Index</b><br>
</font>						<a href="#NASD:INTC">Intel Corporation</a><br>

						<a href="#NYSE:KMB">Kimberly-Clark Corporation</a><br>

						<a href="#AMEX:LVC">Lillian Vernon Corporation</a><br>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
</td>
	</tr>
	<tr><td width=390>
	
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  
		<a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  
		<a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  
		<a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b><p>
		<font size=-1><i>&copy; 1996 Capital Publishing Limited
		Partnership</i></font>
		

		</center>
	
	</td>
	<td width=150 valign=top align=center>
		<b><a href="#top">Top of page</a></b>
