<DOCNO>WT14-B09-61</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA032-000663-B024-188</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.worth.com:80/articles/Z9609I01.html 204.141.48.165 19970209122907 text/html 5664
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Sun, 09 Feb 1997 12:29:57 GMT
Server: Apache/1.1.0
Content-type: text/html
Set-Cookie: Apache=2063391855491397442; path=/
</DOCHDR>
<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/09-Who Is the Market?</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/09-Who Is the Market?</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
Market makers put buyers and sellers together -- but certainly not for free.<p>By Jonathan Butler<p>Imagine if getting rid of shares of stock was as difficult as 
selling a used car: classified ads, phone calls, in-person meetings. Luckily for investors, all it takes to buy or sell stock is a call to a broker, who, in most cases, calls in the order to a "market maker." <p>"The market maker is really just a meeting point between the buyer and seller," says Art Bonnel, manager of the <a name="FUND:ACBGX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/ACBGX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Bonnel Growth Fund</b></a>. Using a brokerage firm's capital, a market maker buys securities from sellers and then resells them to buyers. To compensate the firm for risking its own capital, a market-making dealer will sell a stock at a higher price (the asking price) than he paid for it (the bid). 
Although orders for a specific stock on the New York Stock Exchange 
are handled and matched by a single assigned "specialist" on the floor of the exchange, over-the-counter stocks have multiple dealers (the average Nasdaq stock has 11).<p>In theory, that competition should keep the spreads relatively small, but a study conducted at Vanderbilt University in July 1995 that compared more than 5.4 million transactions on the Nasdaq and the New York Stock Exchange in 1991 found the average spread for Nasdaq trades was almost double that for exchange trades__49.2 cents versus 25.8 cents. The Justice Department and the Securities and Exchange Commission have been investigating the National Association of Securities Dealers for a variety of unfair practices, ranging from price-fixing to backing away from posted prices. Says Brian Berris of Brown Brothers Harriman in New York, "There's a built-in divergence of interest: The client wants the best price, and the market maker wants to maximize the profit."<p>The Small Order Execution System adopted by Nasdaq in 1984 was supposed to address some of these problems. It allows brokers to enter small retail trades (up to 1,000 shares) electronically and requires market makers to honor their quoted prices. But the system hasn't done much to help small investors trade inside the spread. NAqcess, a new system currently under consideration, would allow small investors to automatically post limit orders -- that is, orders to buy or sell at a set price -- on 300,000 terminals worldwide. Orders would then be matched by computer. But NAqcess certainly won't be up and running this year.<p>Meanwhile, investors who want to get the best price on a trade need to find a broker who will shop around to get the smallest spread on each transaction. Don't assume that only a high-commission broker will do this hard work either. Discount brokerage firm <a name="NYSE:SCH"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10320"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Charles Schwab</b></a> (800-435-4000) promises that its Schwab Assurance Trading program will search the log of 3,600 Nasdaq stocks traded by Schwab's own market maker to find the best price on orders of 100 to 5,000 shares. If the system fails to find a way to improve the price internally, it will scan the National Market System for a better deal.<p><p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
