	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/05-Can This Market be Trusted?</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Everything about the current stock market is unprecendcented,and that's cause for both anxiety and hope  <p>
 By Jim Jubak  <p>
Anxiety is as commonplace on the New York Stock Exchange as the torn order slips that litter the trading floor.  Monday, March 11, the atmospheric angst was even thicker than usual among the brokers and specialists who make their living trading stocks.<p>
Throughout the day, the scurrying and gesticulating market professionals kept nervously glancing up at the overhead electronic scoreboards to see if the longest stock-market rally in U.S. financial history was about to come to an end.  <p>
 The previous Friday, the Dow Jones Industrial Average had plummeted 171.24 points to 5470.45, a sign to many that the end was at hand. As if by way of confirmation, the market opened 14 points down on Monday. Then the Dow began to climb. It was up 39 points at noon, then faltered, then appeared to rally again late in the session.  <p>
 By 3:42 -- 18 minutes before the close -- the eyes on the scoreboards saw a Dow up 93.93, then, a minute later, up 95.38. Would it stick? Or would a wave of computer-generated selling swamp the gains of the last half hour?  <p>
 At 3:45, a cheer went up from the floor as the Dow broke 100 points for the day. One broker shook his fist in the air, as if in defiance of the fickle market gods. Another flashed a thumbs-up sign at the CNN and CNBC cameras in the gallery. As the exchange's clocks counted down the seconds to closing, brokers and specialists applauded and whistled. At the bell, the Dow stood at 5581, up 110.55.  <p>
 The rally was still on.  <p>
 Wall street, of course, has always worshiped the market. To the rest of us, however, the Dow's gyrations used to be more like a spectator sport. That's no longer true. Today, the retirement dreams of millions of Americans ride on stocks. In 1992, the New York Stock Exchange estimated that 51 million individuals owned equities, up from 30 million in 1980, and the number of share owners is undoubtedly much higher in 1996. The Federal Reserve Board estimates that individuals own $3.7 trillion in stocks directly and, as of December 1995, another $1.3 trillion worth through mutual funds -- $400 billion more than a year earlier, according to the Investment Company Institute.  <p>
 For many, the stock market has become the only game in town. Bonds paying 6.7 percent and certificates of deposit yielding even less won't provide for a comfortable retirement or foot the bill for college. Stocks are riskier but not terribly so, according to conventional wisdom, which rests on stocks' having returned an average of 10.5 percent annually from 1926 through 1995. In this view, downturns and corrections are nothing more than pesky short-term annoyances. The market will always bounce back -- just as it did after the crash of October 1987.  <p>
 Will it? Can the market really be trusted to behave in this way? Will it continue to deliver lofty annual returns? Or have investors become too complacent?  <p>
 A dark undercurrent of opinion, most of it coming from authorities well off  Wall Street, says that the current stock market issubstantially overvalued and needs a correction of at least 10 percent -- or 560 points on the Dow from its current level of around 5600. Otherwise, the market might climb so high that a disastrous crash will become inevitable.  <p>
 Louder still, however, are the optimists at the big Wall Street investment houses, among the thousands of retail brokers, and in the financial press. Look at the cash flooding in from baby boomers finally starting to save for retirement, they say. It's all going into equities. This rally could continue for the rest of the decade and beyond.  <p>
 Who's right? with so much riding on the answer, it's critical to understand the character of this market -- its soul, if you will. <p>
Statistically, there has never been a stock market like this one. On October 11, 1990, often cited as the starting date for the current rally, the Dow stood at 2365 and the Standard & Poor's 500 Stock Index at 295.46. Since then, the market has climbed for five years and five months without even one 10 percent correction.The previous record was the three-year-three-month-long rally that ended with the crash of 1987. Also, during the past 12 years,the Dow has never dipped below the previous year's low. That, too, is unprecedented.  <p>
 Meanwhile, the relationship between the market and the economy has grown bizarre. The two other longest sustained rallies --between 1922 and 1929 and between 1983 and 1987 -- occurred amid economic booms. The current market, however, has galloped ahead while the economy proceeds at a sedate trot. Between October 1990 and the end of 1995, the gross domestic product rose (in current dollars) from $5.782 trillion to $7.248 trillion, an increase of 25 percent. During the same period, the S&P 500 rose from 295 to 615, an increase of 108 percent.  <p>
 The result is that "the size of the stock market in relationship to the size of the economy has never been larger," says James Bianco, director of research for Arbor Trading Group in Barrington, Illinois. During the past 70 years, Bianco notes, the capitalization of the equity markets averaged 48 percent of U.S. GDP. By the end of 1995, the ratio had risen to 87.5 percent -- higher than it was in 1929, 1968, or 1983.  <p>
 This suggests that the strength of the current market is based far less on the wealth of the nation than on the expectations and behavior of investors themselves.  <p>
 The lunch time crowd at <a name="NYSE:SCH"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10320"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Charles Schwab & Co.'s</b></a> World Trade Center office in Manhattan often includes a wide cross section of investors. On Monday, March 11, Richard Mautner, 62, is here to monitor the market with much the same emotion as the traders at the Big Board a few blocks away. Wearing a tweed jacket and graying at the temples, Mautner, a computer consultant, could easily be mistaken for a college professor. "The market's been good. How can anyone complain?" he asks. "I've been in for 39 years, and Friday's dip didn't rattle me at all. It would have to drop 15 to 20 percent to do that."  <p>
 Not that Mautner is expecting that kind of drop. "I feel good about the economy," he says. "America's genius is in coming up with ultimate applications for computer and telecommunications equipment. It's phenomenal." Mautner now has about 75 to 80 percent of his portfolio in stocks -- "an aggressive strategy for someone my age," he admits. But he figures the risk is well worth it:He anticipates earning a 10 to 12 percent annual return.  <p>
 Lily Gong is also watching the tape at the Schwab office. The 45-year-old computer programmer has been investing for about five years. She figures she suffered a paper loss of about $2,000 to $3,000 on Friday. No problem, though, she says. "Three years ago I switched $20,000 in my IRA from CDs to stocks. It's worth more than $50,000 now, so I can't complain. I'm planning for my retirement. I buy options and occasionally an individual stock. No bonds of any kind."  <p>
 Novice investor Michelle Lin bought her first mutual fund last year on the advice of a colleague. "Money in the bank or CDs is like nothing after taxes," says the 41-year-old researcher, who works at City University of New York. If the market dropped 20 percent tomorrow, she says, "I'd stay with it, and I might even purchase more. I have confidence in the market." She expects to earn 15 percent a year.  <p>
 And then there's Chris Centrella, a 36-year-old motion-picture cameraman from Santa Barbara, who says he put $50,000 into one mutual fund ten years ago and lost. "I wasn't knowledgeable about funds in general, so I didn't realize they could go down. Basically, I bought high and sold low," he says. Now he owns two funds and about a dozen stocks. "Over the long run, I'd like to make 20 percent a year."  <p>
 Are these folks kidding themselves? Perhaps, but the hopes expressedby the Schwab investors are also grounded in an appreciation of the financial realities they face as they plan for retirement. In fact, the psychology of investors like these may be the key to understanding the likely performance of the market over the next two decades.  <p>
 Millions of Americans are confronted with a choice between two types of risk -- market and lifetime. Yes, there is a possibility the stock market will perform below expectations, perhaps even well below expectations. At the same time, more and more people, especially baby boomers, are becoming aware of the risk that low-returning investments pose to their goals in life. These goals may include putting their children through college, paying off  the mortgage, and retiring comfortably. As threats to these goals come into focus and the chances of failure appear to mount, the comparative risk associated with owning stocks seems to diminish. <p>
 "There's the risk that you can lose your money," says Nancy Teeven, a vice president at Scudder Stevens & Clark, who directs the mutual-fund company's efforts to educate 401(k)-plan participants at client companies. "But there's also the risk that you can't get from point A to point B."  <p>
 According to Teeven, investors who are more educated about risk and their financial futures are more likely to put their money into the stock market. She notes that 56 percent of the $3 billion that Scudder handles in 401(k) plans is in equities, significantly above the national average of 43 percent, according to Access Research.  <p>
 Whether baby boomers are saving enough for retirement is one of the hottest topics of debate in retirement-planning and financial circles. A recent study by the Congressional Budget Office found that most baby boomers are likely to enjoy higher real incomes in retirement than their parents. (This isn't a very compelling piece of data, however; in 1992 the average income for an individual in the U.S. 65 years or older was just $14,899, according to the Employee Benefit Research Institute.) But the CBO's conclusions were based on the highly questionable assumptions that real wages will continue to grow, that Social Security and private pensions will remain intact, and that health-care costs will not climb faster than the rate of wage increases.  <p>
 Since boomers probably won't be able to count on Social Security and Medicare, let alone the above-average appreciation in housing prices that helped previous generations, pursuing higher returns in the stock market may be a rational adaptation to a changed financial landscape. We asked Michael Chasnoff , a financial planner at Advanced Capital Strategies in Cincinnati, to do a quick back-of-the-envelope savings plan for a couple, ages 45 and 42, with $100,000 in income. "They'll be able to retire at their current lifestyle level if they save $15,000 a year toward retirement in tax-deferred accounts and another $10,000 in taxable savings," said Chasnoff.  <p>
 But saving $25,000 a year on a pretax income of $100,000 is a tough task. Saving for retirement gets a lot easier if a couple assumes a higher rate of return. For example, if a couple saves $25,000 annually and puts the money into a portfolio of stocks and bonds that earns 8.5 percent, they'll have $1.21 million in 20 years. If they put that money into a portfolio consisting solely of stocks and assume the 10.5 percent return that has been the annual average since 1926, they need to save only $20,000 a year to accumulate the same nest egg.  <p>
All of this is important because the strength of investors' hopeshas become the defining characteristic of the stock market. <p>
 Looked at in any other way, by any measure, this market is highly overvalued. The price-to-book ratio for the stocks on the S&P 400 Industrials -- a measure of what investors are willing topay for the assets of these 400 companies -- isn't just at anall-time high; it's 50 percent higher than it was at the market peaks in 1929 and 1987. The ratio of the prices of the stocks in the S&P 500 to their dividend payouts is also "by far the highest in history," says James Stack of InvesTech in Whitefish, Montana. This ratio, which peaked at 33 in 1929 and 35 in 1987, stood at 45 in early March 1996, calculates Stack. The yield on the S&P 500 is also at a record low.  <p>
 "We're in uncharted waters," says Stack. "Each investor has to sit down and ask, Are we in a new era of unprecedented opportunity with a new paradigm [for the market and the economy], or are we in an era of unprecedented risk?"  <p>
 The 14.5 percent average annual return earned by the S&P 500 over the past 10 years is well above the 10.5 percent average annual return of the past 70 years. But the higher return of the past ten years is partly the result of a historic decline in interest rates that is now drawing to a close. Like a mountain climber who abandons his support team for a solo assault on the peak, this market is now climbing without the aid and comfort of its longtime companion.  <p>
 In 1981, the yield on long Treasury bonds hit 14.14 percent. On January 18, 1996, according to Ryan Labs Inc., the yield fell to just 5.52 percent. Notwithstanding some temporary blips, rates have fallen steadily for more than 14 years. That adds up tothe fourth major interest-rate wave to roll through the market this century. From 1900 to 1920, interest rates rose steadily.From 1920 to 1946, they declined, with the yield on 30-year Treasury bonds sliding from 5.32 percent in 1920 to 2.19 in 1946. From 1946 to  <p>
1981, bond investors suffered a steady erosion of the price of their bonds as rates rose steadily toward that 1981 high of 14.14. <p>
 As a result, the past decade has been extremely kind to equity investors. But bond investors haven't done too shabbily, either, since bonds have far outperformed their long-term track record of 5.17 percent average annual total return since 1926. For the past ten years, ten-year Treasury bonds have returned 8.49 percent annually -- not that far below the long-term historic returns on stocks.  <p>
 The problem is that this trend just cannot continue. If interest rates on the ten-year bond slide from their current level of about 6.5 percent to 5 percent by year-end, investors will reap a total return of about 15 percent, says Chip Norton, managing editor of IBC's Bond Fund Report. And that could happen if Congress and the president reward the bond market with a budget deal that really cuts the deficit.  <p>
 But, after that, what would the bond market do for an encore? Just to keep rates steady at 5 percent, history suggests, the Federal Reserve would have to hold inflation to no more than 3 percent a year. Nothing in the experience of the current generation of investors, who can easily remember the double-digit inflation of the late 1970s and early 1980s, shows that the Fed will be able to keep inflation on that tight a leash -- let alone drive it downward to the levels necessary to bring interest rates onthe ten-year bond significantly below 5 percent  <p>
 The outlook for corporate earnings (the other driving force behind the current market rally) is also beginning to blur. Earnings on the S&P 500 exploded out of the blocks at the end of 1991, climbing from $3.74 in the third quarter and $2.55 in the fourth quarter to $5.36 in the first quarter of 1992 -- more than justifying the expectations that had started the rally a year earlier. Earnings climbed again in 1993 (by almost 15 percent), 1994 (by 40 percent),and 1995 (by 11 percent).  <p>
 How much will earnings rise in 1996? Investors may be overestimating the pace of real growth. The profits that companies report publicly get a boost from different sources as a market and economic cycleages, according to Kurt Walters, vice president of research at Safian Investment Research in White Plains, New York. As an economic cycle reaches its later stages -- and growth begins to slow --companies start doing things to keep their earnings moving forward.They buy back stock, make acquisitions, and reshu쎤 their balance sheets. These and other activities give the impression that acompany's core business is doing better than it is. Walters believesthis is what's happening right now.   <p>
 The Bureau of Economic Analysis publishes numbers that attempt to factor out some of this static. For the second quarter of1995, the figures show a difference of 40.4 percent between reportedand real profits. This divergence is second only to the 49.1 percent recorded in the third quarter of 1974. For the third quarter of 1995, the most recent period available, the differenceis still 22.12 percent. Earnings will grow at just 7 to 9 percent this year, Walters believes.  <p>
 Few investors are focusing on this potential earnings problem. In fact, the market has pretty much decided to ignore such short-term calculations and instead place its faith in the presumed increased productivity and global competitiveness of U.S. business. Unfortunately,these qualities are remarkably hard to document.   <p>
 Manufacturing productivity did increase 4 percent in the U.S.in 1994, according to the Bureau of Labor Statistics. But ofthe ten foreign economies the bureau tracks, seven matched or beat the U.S., and four -- Denmark, France, Germany, and the Netherlands -- had productivity gains of above 7 percent. There cord on unit labor costs isn't much better -- or much more definitive. Manufacturing labor costs in the U.S. decreased by 2.3 percent in 1994. The biggest increase in costs among U.S.competitors came in Japan at 7.5 percent, but that was clearly a result of the 9 percent rise in the value of the yen. In fact,only 3 of the 12 foreign economies the bureau tracks for this statistic showed increases after the data was corrected for currency fluctuations. Long-term investors should be asking how much of the vaunted U.S. competitive edge is due to the weak dollar and how much to changes within U.S. corporations.  <p>
 Right now, the liquidity factor -- the sheer volume of money chasing stocks -- has rendered many traditional ways of valuing equities virtually irrelevant. Or so many investors insist. They trust that the vast amount of money baby boomers are putting into the market will, in and of itself, drive stock prices up. It's a pure supply-and-demand equation.  <p>
 Certainly, the figures are impressive. In January 1996 alone,$29 billion in new money flowed into equity mutual funds. For all of 1995, the total was $123 billion. That's a net figure:the amount of money going into funds minus the amount withdrawn.To put this in perspective, the assets invested in all equity mutual funds in 1985 -- the total amount -- equaled $117 billion.  <p>
 This green tide seems practically assured to keep rising for some time. "For the average client, equities are pretty much the only game in town," says Ron Rog, a financial planner in Centereach, New York. Investors have gotten religion about this market, says Michael Chasnoff . "A lot of my clients believe there really is not as much risk to stocks and the economy as I perceive there to be."   <p>
 Giles Almond, a financial planner in Charlotte, North Carolina, shows what this means in day-to-day life: "Every payday here, we're a buyer [of equities] because we're investing our 401(k) and pension money. That's going on all over the country. And until that changes, there will always be buyers."  <p>
 The demand for stocks keeps growing. But what about the supply side -- the number of shares available to buy?  <p>
 Last year, according to Securities Data, companies issued $29 billion in new stock in initial public offerings, plus an additional $52 billion in secondary offerings (sales of new stock by existing public companies). But corporations announced 1,108 stock buy backs worth $99 billion over the same period. Net the two out, and you'll discover that the supply of stock potentially shrank --if companies actually complete their buybacks -- by about $18 billion.  <p>
 Granted, there isn't much historic evidence showing a true relationship between cash flow and rising markets. Net cash flows into equity mutual funds, for example, were positive all through 1987 up until the October crash. Equity-fund cash flows turned negative in 1971, long before the major market correction of 1973 to 1974. And at $6.4 trillion the total value of the stock market dwarfs all these numbers.  <p>
 So it's really the mood, or psychological state of the investing public, that's the true force driving this market.  <p>
 Investors today believe in the stock market in much the sameway Dutch investors in the 17th century believed in tulip bulbsor English investors in the 18th century believed trading companies would reap the riches of the South Seas. In those markets, prices lost all connection to value. "Once you've lost that anchor, any price-to-earnings ratio is justified," says Paul Samuelson, winner of the Nobel Prize for economics in 1970 and a professor emeritus of economics at MIT. "You're in a financial bubble." <p>
 Very few of today's investors in the U.S. have first hand experience with a bubble. Japan's bubble, which broke in 1989, was far away geographically. The collapse of the go-go funds and the Nifty Fifty stocks of the late 1960s and early 1970s is no more than a childhood memory for many baby boomers. Also, many investors who pooh-pooh the possibility that the current market could burst don't understand what a financial bubble really is.  <p>
 Bubbles have some surprising characteristics, according to Vernon Smith, director of the economics science laboratory at the University of Arizona, who has created more than a hundred financial bubbles in model stock markets.  <p>
 In one of his experiments, Smith issues his students shares and cash. The students can do nothing and simply collect the dividends on their shares: an average of 24 cents at the end of each of 15 periods (though some shares, selected randomly, pay as little as nothing and others as much as 60 cents). Or they can trade each share once each period, either buying or selling, at prices asked by the other student traders. These ground rules should make it easy for a student to calculate the fundamental value of a share. To make certain they know how, Smith explains the fundamental value at the end of each period. The fair price of a share is simply the average dividend timesthe number of remaining trading periods (15 times 24 cents, or $3.60, in the first period, $3.36 in the second, and so on). <p>
 Students who take part in the experiment for the first time almost always begin bidding for shares below their fundamental  value -- hoping for bargains -- during the early rounds. As the periods go by, however, they raise their bids, having been shut out on dividends in earlier rounds because their low ball tactics failed to get them the shares they wanted. So at this point,they bid what the stock is really worth -- only to discover that other students, also shut out, have raised the price. Eventually,the students produce a market bubble that finally bursts. "There's no misunderstanding about the fundamental value of a stock,"says Smith. "They just don't pay attention."  <p>
 Curiously, the same group of students typically does worse on a second run through the experiment. They produce a bubble more quickly, and it breaks more abruptly. (By the third time through, they've usually learned their lesson and trade at fundamental value throughout the experiment.)   <p>
 From post-experiment interviews, Smith reconstructs the students'reasoning. As the game progresses, the students begin to realize that "the market is overvalued, but there's no reason in their minds to get out. They're collecting dividends. They've seen  that stocks can trade above fundamental value," Smith says. The stock is worth what they can get for it, they tell Smith, sowhy would they sell? "All that theory about what it should beworth makes no difference." This, of course, is why the bursting bubble always comes as such a surprise. (Something to keep in mind the next time someone tells you that today's investors are too sophisticated to create a bubble.)  <p>
 Bubbles, however, can also remain inflated for a long time, which is precisely the problem investors face today. We know the bubble will burst eventually, but when? Should we just sit out the action in the meantime?  <p>
 From speculative boom to frenzied bust, the Florida real-estate bubble lasted two years. Investing in tulips reached full-fledged frenzy in the Netherlands in 1634. The bubble burst two years later when bulbs that had sold for 4,600 florins, a new carriage, two horses, and a harness just a short time before couldn't find a buyer -- the market's excesses had gradually built up in the years since the bulbs first became fashionable in the 1560s. The Japanese financial bubble ran for a decade. "My suspicionis that we're early in this game and not late," says Samuelson, pointing out that price-to-earnings ratios are not that far out of line yet.   <p>
 Any projections about what year the baby boomers will stop being a net source of liquidity to the stock market and start making net withdrawals are almost total conjecture at this point. Such forecasts depend heavily on assumptions about the rate of corporate downsizing, the average retirement age, the future of Social Security and Medicare, and the level of inflation in general and in college and health-care costs in particular. Current estimates point as far ahead as 2025 before stock-market cash flows begin to reverse direction.  <p>
 The trouble is that it's impossible to predict the end of a pyramid scheme. Logic doesn't help. If you rationally decide to get out in two years, then it makes sense that an equally rational investor might decide to get out in two years less one day. Follow that logic to its conclusion, and the only safe choiceis to get out tomorrow (or yesterday, if we're too late to the news stands with this issue). That's why bubbles collapse so quickly.(For strategies on investing in a long bubble, see the side bar below.)  <p>
 Fundamentals won't help predict the end, either, since the issue isn't real earnings or the ratio of yield on the S&P to the yield on the three-month Treasury bill. As long as people have faith, all will be well. But the instant they cease to believe in themarket, their apostasy will prick the bubble.  <p>
 What makes this bubble especially hard to figure out is the peculiar psychology of the baby-boom generation itself. This group is used to being the demographic tail that wags the dog, having turned its issues -- the Vietnam War, feminism, late child bearing, the need to care for elderly parents, environmentalism -- into the nation's issues.  <p>
 So far, the boomers appear to have convinced themselves that the financial world will be the way they wish it to be until the moment when the last among them has pulled his money out of the market and tucked it away in a Swiss bank.   <p>
 But that's almost guaranteed not to happen. At the moment this cynical scenario starts to gain credence, the bubble itself is doomed. At that point, a smart boomer who doesn't want to be the last one out of the pool will realize the time to pull out of the market is next year at the latest. A friend or competitor knowing that will decide to get out one day less than a year from now. And the rout will be on -- like the real-estate boom and bust of the late 1980s.  <p>
 Until then, here are three axioms to live by: All bubbles burst. No one can predict when, except by chance. And the door is neverwide enough to let all those who want to get out rush through at once.  <p>
 Additional reporting by Jonathan Butler, John Fried, Andrew Gluck, and Ken Kurson.  <p>
<p><a name="SUB1"><b><font size=+1>HOW TO BEAT A BUBBLE</font></b><p> <p>
The key is discipline -- buying only when the numbers look good, selling as soon as they look bad  <p>
 By Jim Jubak  <p>
 The standard financial advice -- ignore market cycles, and buy and hold for the long term, and if you can't do that, then get out and sit on your cash until the dust clears -- isn't well suited to the market that seems to be unfolding now. If we are indeed in the early stages of a serious bubble, investors could wind up parked on the sidelines for years. On the other hand, ignoring the way a bubble distorts valuations is just asking to be blindsided.  <p>
 Fortunately, even in this kind of market, basic investing principles will serve an investor well. Equity investors who tightly discipline their buying and stick to tough guidelines for deciding when to sell should be able to weather a bubble. They'll automatically move out of the market as valuations get increasingly out of line in the bubble's later stages.  <p>
 A market like this changes the ratio between risks and rewards. For example, because of price appreciation, equities are now showing historically low dividend yields, and that makes equities more risky for the long-term investor. Investors in large-cap stocks who suffered through the 1929 crash had to wait until 1943 to see the value of their assets recover to the level of 1928. If those stocks hadn't paid dividends and investors had been forced to rely on capital gains alone to make them whole, they would have been in the red until 1952.  <p>
 The best way to manage equity risk in a market like this is to avoid over paying for a stock. But that's a hard discipline to maintain as a bubble develops and stocks that are overpriced on their fundamentals keep going up and up. <a name="NYSE:KO"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10359"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Coca-Cola</b></a>, for example,is without doubt one of the great growth companies in the world, exactly the kind of safe stock many investors want for their retirement portfolio. But it recently traded at a price-to-earnings ratio of 35, perhaps a bit pricey for a company that just projected unit sales growth for the long term at 7 to 8 percent. That's a higher p/e ratio than the company received on average for any year as far back as 1979. Yet this hasn't stopped 13 of the 27 analysts that follow the company from giving the stock a buy or strong-buy rating, according to Zacks Investment Research. <p>
 Historic price-to-earnings ratios are a good starting place for valuing stocks in this market. One simple rule might be not to buy any stock trading at a p/e above the stock's highest average annual p/e dating back through 1979. That covers a number of economic and market cycles.  <p>
 An investor who sets out to follow this rule (you'll find historic p/e ratios in Value Line) will uncover lots of surprises. <a name="NASD:INTC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13787"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Intel</b></a>, for example, trades at a p/e of 15. Its p/e was, on average, 29 in 1987. <a name="NYSE:MOT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11023"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Motorola</b></a> trades at a p/e of 19. You'd have to go back to 1991 to find a year when, on average, the stock was cheaper.(For more ways to think about the price of growth stocks, see the "Investing" section in this issue and the February issue, as well as Peter Lynch's February column.)  <p>
 But valuations based on historic p/e's -- and any other earnings-based formula -- will work in this market only for investors who dig into financial statements deeply enough to distinguish between companies that are showing real earnings growth in their continuing operations and those that have used accounting rules to change reported earnings. For example, for the fourth quarter of 1995, PepsiCo took a $520 million pretax write-off -- what it called a charge against impaired assets. The company decided to write off the restaurants in its Taco Bell, Pizza Hut, and Kentucky Fried Chicken chains that weren't doing well. The charge lowered earnings for the quarter, but it will also appear to increase earnings in the future, since the company won't have to depreciate these restaurants year to year against earnings.   <p>
 Puzzles like this are why some analysts are looking at cashflow to judge the real earnings of a company. Look for cash-flow growth at the rate of 12 percent, advises Kurt Walters of Safian Investment Research. "If cash flow is growing at that rate,"he says, "earnings should be growing at a similar rate." (Value Line and Standard & Poor's report annual cash flow per share. Investors can calculate a growth rate from those figures.)  <p>
 As for the other side of prospering in this market, timely selling, it's relatively simple to set a target selling price for a stock. Estimate an annual growth rate for earnings over the next five years, using sources such as Value Line, Standard & Poor's, and company reports. Compound current earnings per share at that rate to calculate earnings per share five years from now. Looking at historic price-to-earnings ratios, pick a high p/e that the market might award the stock five years hence. Multiply thatp/e by earnings to determine a target price for five years out.Keep the target updated as the company reports new earnings.If the company hits the target or shows signs of faltering, sell. <p>
 Investors who maintain strict buying and selling disciplines will have a harder time finding stocks to buy and reasons notto sell as a bubble develops. They will actually be forced to the sidelines without ever having to make a market call. And that's the point.    <p>
KEYWORDS: Retirement, Economy, Market Trends, Investing Strategies, Mutual Funds Investing
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

