		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>The Lowdown on DRIPs</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/02-The Lowdown on DRIPs</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						February 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Investing  <p> THE LOWDOWN ON DRIPS   <p> By Doug Garr  <p> Q: What is a DRIP?  <p> A: In the investment world, a DRIP can certainly be a whiny, annoying person, but the initials are more likely to refer to a dividend-reinvestment plan. A DRIP lets individuals buy shares in a company directly from that company without a brokerage fee. <p>  <p>Do all companies offer DRIPs?  <p> No. But since the Securities and Exchange Commission relaxed filing regulations, making it easier to set up these plans, more companies have begun offering them to attract long-terminvestors. Currently, about 1,000 companies, including <a name="NYSE:MOT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11023"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Motorola</b></a>,<a name="NYSE:XON"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10537"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Exxon</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:MCD"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10974"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>McDonald's</b></a>, and Procter & Gamble, offer DRIPs.  <p>  <p>What is a no-load DRIP?  <p> In the past, investors had to buy the initial shares in a company through a broker and pay a commission before they could sign up for more shares directly. But companies have begun offering DRIPs that enable investors to buy even the first shares directly. About 80 companies, including Exxon and McDonald's, now offer no-load DRIPs. (Some impose restrictions such as requiring an investor to be a customer of the company.)  <p>  <p>Discount brokers are starting to offer DRIPs that provide a consolidated statement. How do they work?   <p> The DRIP plans set up by brokerages work differently from company plans. An investor can automatically reinvest dividends through the brokerage plans without commissions, but those who use cash to buy more shares will be charged the usual fees.   <p>  <p>What are the disadvantages of DRIPs?  <p> DRIPs can create a lot of paperwork because investors must keep track of the statements and stock certificates sent out by each company. Some companies also charge a small annual fee.  <p>  <p>How do I get a list of companies offering DRIPs?  <p> Contact Evergreen Enterprises, P.O. Box 763, Laurel, Maryland, <p>20725, (301) 549-3939. Its directory costs $29.95.  <p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Stock Investing Strtaegies<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
