				<font size=5><b>Beer Blast</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/02-Beer Blast</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						February 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Investing  <p> BEER BLAST <p>Investors are drinking up these IPO's here that stands for Initial Pub Offering   <p> By Doug Garr  <p> Wall Street is having a keg party. in the past year, at least a dozen beer companies have gone public, many selling small blocks of stock directly to investors. <a name="NASD:HOOK"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=44090"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Redhook</b></a> of Seattle;  <a name="NASD:WIKD"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=41353"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Pete's Brewing</b></a> of Palo Alto, California;<a name="NYSE:SAM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=40674"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b> Boston Beer</b></a> (the maker of Samuel Adams);and others have investors in a froth.   <p> The offerings are tapping into the national enthusiasm for microbreweries, small regional companies that market their lagers, ales, porters, and stouts as distinctive alternatives to mass-market national brands. Boston Beer, the nation's largest microbrewery,  first priced its shares at $10 to $15 each but, sensing huge demand, upped the offering price to $20 when the stock  first traded in November. The stock surged $8 a share on day one, closing at $32 by the end of the week. It has since settled into the $26-to-$27-a-share range. Redhook and Pete's experienced similar first-day frenzies.   <p> Boston Beer sold part of its offering directly to beer drinkers by inserting a coupon into a six-pack of Samuel Adams, earning goodwill from investors who might otherwise have been unable to buy shares. Boston Beer's stock was quickly oversubscribed: Some 60,000 investors had their checks returned.   <p> Microbreweries are hot now, but how long will they keep rewarding investors? "You'll see the end of it when some companies reportless than stellar earnings," says Tricia Reebs, portfolio manager for Sea first Investment Counselors in Seattle. Many of these stocks have been bid up out of proportion to earnings, she says,and current growth is probably not sustainable. She compares the microbrewery phenomenon to the coffee fad sparked by the success of <a name="NASD:SBUX"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=15745"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Starbucks</b></a>. A slew of companies went public in Starbucks'wake, and so far investors have been left tossing and turning over lackluster returns.<p>
KEYWORDS: Market Trends

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
