<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/06-Club Nasdaq--Special Report</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Club Nasdaq--Special Report</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/06-Club Nasdaq--Special Report</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						June 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Features  <p> CLUB NASDAQ--SPECIAL REPORT <p>It calls itself the "stock market for the next 100 years." Butin the here and now, it operates more like a clip joint. Thechief regulator is a big part of the problem.  <p> By Gretchen Morgenson  <p> The National Association of Securities Dealers spends millionsof dollars on sleek-looking, fast-paced ads touting its computerizedNasdaq system as "the stock market for the next 100 years." Andperhaps it is. <a name="NASD:MSFT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14120"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Microsoft</b></a>, <a name="NASD:INTC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13787"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Intel</b></a>, <a name="NASD:MCIC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13996"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>MCI Communications</b></a>, and otherleaders in cutting-edge industries list on Nasdaq. NASD's revenuein 1993, the most recent year for which data is available, was$332 million, more than double its revenue in 1988. In the lastfive years alone, the number of securities traded on Nasdaq,once home to only the most obscure companies, grew by over 22percent to 5,761 issues.   <p> This burgeoning operation would certainly astonish the NASDfounders, who decided in 1938 to "promote the investment bankingand securities business" by creating a corporation to run whatbecame the over-the-counter trading system. Two thirds of thecorporation's revenues come from market-information and transactionservice fees, issuer fees, and member assessments. In additionto Nasdaq, the NASD today oversees the operations of 5,300 memberbrokerage firms, with 46,000 branch offices and almost half amillion registered employees.  <p> The NASD's achievements are certainly noteworthy. But only inpart. Hidden behind the glossy public image is another NASD,one that uses its growing wealth and reach to shield the intimidationand overcharging of individual investors while zealously pursuingthe interests of its powerful members, such as Merrill Lynchand Morgan Stanley. Indeed, despite its privileged status asthe nation's largest self-regulated organization, the NASD sofar has shown little inclination to act in anyone's interestbut its own.  <p> The NASD's mandate states that the organization should promote"high standards of commercial honor and observance of federaland state securities laws among its members." But it is in thisvenue that the NASD now finds itself under assault. Ongoing investigationsmounted last year by the Justice Department and the Securitiesand Exchange Commission are exploring whether the NASD may havehelped nurture an insider-oriented market that condones pricefixing and other techniques for separating customers from theirmoney.  <p> Much of the problem springs from the NASD's lax self-regulatoryactivities. Supreme Court Justice William O. Douglas wrote thatindustries could police themselves effectively only if the governmentkept a "shotgun ... behind the door, well-oiled, cleaned, readyfor use."In this case, there isn't one핦nly the amiable and understaffedSEC. When it comes to the NASD, the SEC is more like a popgun. <p> Ever since the fox and the henhouse, self-regulation has beena dangerous proposition. But it has worked in some cases. TheNYSE, for example, policed itself quite closely during the late1980s, according to a study published last year in Administration& Society, an academic journal. By contrast, the NASD often doeslittle to address problems that are brought to its attention,many sources say.  <p> "Working with the NASD on enforcement matters was not satisfactory,"says Stephan Hodge, who served as head of the Indiana State SecuritiesCommission until last December. "They were not aggressive withenforcement actions even when regulators presented them withstrong evidence against one of their members. They're a membershiporganization, and they're controlled by their members. They onlygo after the worst actors하nd even then, not aggressively." <p> Faced with such a track record, smart investors won't be reassuredby some recent noises the NASD has been making about internalreform. And the SEC may not be mollified, either. In any self-regulatedorganization, "there is an inherent tension between members'self-interest and the public interest," says Brandon Becker,the SEC's director of market regulation. "We share the concernthat an SRO not allow its structure to disadvantage the public." <p> As a result, the individual investors who trade on Nasdaq arelargely at the mercy of the NASD. And despite its rhetoric, theNASD doesn't often go out of its way to police members. The organization'strue constituency is found in big and midsize brokerage firms.Executives at these firms fill the NASD's board of governorsand its 29 committees. They run the show.  <p> Predictably, the NASD has been good to these folks. Take theexample of The Sherwood Group, a brokerage that trades approximately4,200 Nasdaq stocks in New York City, Denver, Minneapolis, Chicago,and Los Angeles. Sherwood's narrow focus on Nasdaq issues providesa telling window on that market's economics. The company's revenueballooned almost 50 percent last year, to $85 million. Even morenotable was Sherwood's 20 percent net profit margin합ignificantlyhigher than the margin at brokerage houses that trade securitiesin other markets as well. Clearly, the NASD's system rewardsits member firms abundantly.  <p> These are the same people who now claim the organization willreform itself without outside intervention. Doubtless, othertelevision ads will hail such efforts. But investors should bewary.  <p> David Whitcomb, a finance professor at Rutgers University andexpert on the microstructure of markets, has made a study ofNasdaq and has been critical of its recent attempts at reform.Whitcomb is not surprised that Nasdaq hasn't come up with much."NASD has no incentive to do anything," he says, "because asan SRO it is first and foremost respecting the interest of thedealer firms핪hey are very satisfied with the status quo."  <p> The NASD undoubtedly would take issue with much of the contentof this story. It's unlikely, for instance, the organizationwould admit publicly that it operates more like a club for insidersthan a guardian of public trust. Yet despite repeated requestsfor interviews핪he first made more than a month before this story'sdeadline핦fficials at the NASD elected to remain mum about thespecific issues raised here. Twice, the NASD also was providedwith a list of questions핦ne of these was given ten days beforethe due date; the other gave the NASD a full business day tooffer even a general response. Yet throughout this back-and-forth,the only comments forthcoming from NASD officials were complaintsthat the organization wasn't being given enough time to respond.(The SEC, by comparison, took only a few days to respond to ourquestions.) At one point, an NASD official offered to schedulean interview, but not until after the magazine was scheduledto go to press. In the absence of any substantive comments, certainopinions expressed by the NASD and its officials in the pasthave been inserted below in an effort to reflect the organization'spublic views.  <p>  <p>yesterday and today: The spread  <p> John Brooks, author of The Go-Go Years, a study of the marketsof the 1960s and 1970s, describes the over-the-counter marketof that era as a "thicket of rumor, confusion and secrecy." There,writes Brooks, "the opportunities for manipulation were endless."Brooks describes deals "conducted in windowless back rooms byexcitable hagglers, many with a full measure of larceny in theirblood, and policed only negligently by the overworked and understaffedSEC..." Although technology brought a modicum of order to thisunruly scene, Brooks would find much to recognize in Nasdaq tothis day.  <p> The NASD's trading system is an amorphous creature. Unlike theNew York and American stock exchanges, it doesn't have a tradingfloor핦r any easily observable, centralized location where ordersare paired off. Instead, price quotes are transmitted via phonelines and flashed on the computer screens of brokers around thenation. To trade the stocks, Nasdaq relies largely on a hostof brokerage firms to carry out the buying and selling of individualissues. The NYSE and AMEX use an auction method. Each assignsa single specialist working on the floor of the exchange to eachstock. The specialists match up orders from buyers and sellers,and step in to make up the difference when demand on one sideis exceeded on the other.  <p> Nasdaq's cybersystem, however, allows for multiple market makers하naverage of 11 for each stock학ased in more than 500 locationsaround the country. This diffuse, hard-to-monitor web resultsin a market that's lucrative for the NASD's member brokerages학utnot so rich for their clients. To understand why this is so,it's helpful to explain the concept of spreads.  <p> Rather than match up similarly priced buy and sell orders, Nasdaqmarket makers quote two prices for every stock: The "bid," orwhat a buyer is willing to pay, and the "asked," or what a selleris willing to accept. The difference between the prices is calledthe spread핪he territory where these middlemen make money frominvestors. If you sell to them, they pay the lower price. Ifyou buy from them, you pay the higher one. What's important hereis that the Nasdaq system has consistently wide spreads, makingit by far the most expensive exchange on which to buy and sellstocks. One way to put those higher costs in perspective is tocompare Nasdaq's biggest, most liquid stocks핪hose found on itsNational Market System list핪o shares in identical price categorieson the AMEX. In February, stocks trading for under $10 a shareon the NMS list carried an average spread of 8.2 percent, versus6.1 percent on the AMEX. NMS shares priced between $10 and $20carried average spreads of almost 4 percent, compared with 1.7percent on the AMEX. And NMS shares at $40 and up carried anaverage spread of 1.6 percent, versus 0.9 percent on the AMEX.The Nasdaq market makers take a bigger cut at every level.  <p> Another way to measure the same thing: Trading costs for institutionalinvestors were two and a half times greater on Nasdaq than onother listed markets between 1991 and 1993, according to a studypublished in February by the Rodney L. White Center for FinancialResearch at the University of Pennsylvania's Wharton School.And institutions don't often trade in obscure, thinly tradedstocksNasdaq's usual scapegoat for its wider-than-average spreads. <p> As an illustration of the phenomenon, consider Semtech, a semiconductorcompany based in Newbury Park, California. Trading in Semtech'sshares moved to the Nasdaq market from the AMEX earlier thisyear. Before the move, the stock usually carried a spread ofone quarter of a point. Once Semtech was on Nasdaq, however,the spread in the stock jumped to a full point$1 a share. InMarch, this was equivalent to 7.5 percent of the stock's price,meaning that investors who purchased Semtech shares would lose7.5 percent if they sold immediately, not even counting commissions.In most Nasdaq stocks, investors start out deep in the hole whenthey buy.  <p> The issue of why companies want to have their shares listedon Nasdaq is an interesting one, particularly given the highcosts of trading there. (See "Forward Thinking" on page 11.)MCI Communications has long been on Nasdaq and plans to stay.MCI spokesman Kevin Inda says: "We're pleased with Nasdaq; theservices they provide us parallel our technology." Inda rejectsthe notion that MCI's continuing support of Nasdaq has anythingto do with a recent $150 million contract the company won torun Nasdaq's phone operations.  <p> Not everyone pays huge premiums to trade on Nasdaq, mind you.Spreads in the Nasdaq insiders' market핪rading among market makersthemselves하re much more favorable than in the outsiders' market.And since each stock has numerous market makers, active "discounted"trading is possible, and Nasdaq insiders can flourish at theexpense of outside investors they're supposed to serve.  <p> Nasdaq's public customers can't really avoid giving these middlemena piece of the action, either. On the NYSE and AMEX, investorsoften meet and complete trades without paying anything at allto a middleman. The specialist system facilitates this action,known as a cross. Crosses happen about 90 percent of the timeon the two exchanges. But on Nasdaq, crosses happen in only 1.8percent of trades, according to an article published last yearin the Stanford Journal of Law, Business & Finance. That meansthat in 98.2 percent of Nasdaq trades, someone is skimming offcream.  <p> The money made off investors in this little game is enormous.Exactly how enormous is hard to quantify: NASD members' profitsfrom market making are not publicly available하nd big, publicbrokerage firms don't break down their results that way. TheSherwood Group's 20 percent margin provides a clue.  <p> Wide Nasdaq spreads aren't just harmful to investors' profits;they go to the heart of the Justice Department's ongoing investigationof possible collusion among market makers. The inquiry boilsdown to this: Is Nasdaq actually a competitive market, as itclaims? And if so, how come different market makers' quotes fora particular stock tend to mirror each other all day long, everyday? Why, when one market maker moves his bid up, does the packtend to follow suit? Some of the possible answers to these questionsare worrisome.  <p>  <p>old cowboys never die  <p> Like other big stock markets, Nasdaq requires its market makersto report their trades within 90 seconds of execution. Peoplemiss deadlines in any helter-skelter business, of course. Buta pattern of systematic lateness is troubling because it providesa golden opportunity for cheating. To understand this, imaginea market maker with "a full measure of larceny," as John Brooksmight say.  <p> When a market maker fulfills a customer's buy order학y sellinghim the stock핪he market maker should report the transactionimmediately. But suppose the stock is going up. The market makermight wait a short while and execute a new trade at a higherprice. He could then report the second trade as a late executionof the customer's order하nd keep the lower-priced shares, onwhich there is already a paper profit, for his own account. There'sno risk in this strategy: If the stock's price falls insteadof rising, the market maker simply sticks the customer with theinitial trade and doesn't make a second trade. This scenario,known in industry parlance as "painting the tape," is whollyunprofessional. But because the NASD has policed its membersso loosely, the temptation to fudge is huge. In January alone,more than 11 percent of Nasdaq trades came in late. Measuredunder identical standards, just 0.22 percent of the AMEX's tradeswere late. The NYSE reported that 0.6 percent of its trades camein after the deadline. It's impossible to determine what percentageof the late trades on Nasdaq, if any, involve painting the tape.But from a customer's point of view, what's important is thatit is impossible to know that it is not happening with greatfrequency.  <p> Another of the Wild West practices from the old OTC market iscalled "backing away"항hen market makers refuse to honor theirown quotes (because doing so would result in a loss). On theNYSE or AMEX, this can't happen: Specialists are obligated tolive up to their bids and offers. The NASD supposedly prohibitsbacking away, too, but it doesn't always act firmly when a firmbreaks the rules.  <p> On January 31, 1994, Datek Securities, a small but aggressiveNew York City brokerage, called huge Morgan Stanley on the carpetfor backing away from quotes on six occasions. After a year ofinvestigation, the NASD sided with Datek. Yet even though theNASD's own guidelines called for a $5,000 penalty for five suchviolations, Morgan Stanley's six violations earned it only a$1,000 slap핟ardly a sign of strong self-regulation. Executivesfrom Morgan Stanley sit on 7 of the NASD's 29 committees, notesAnthony Sanzio, an official at Datek. Datek isn't representedon any NASD committee.  <p> None of the NASD's recently proposed changes specifically addresseither painting the tape or backing away.  <p>  <p>big problems, half solutions  <p> By allowing for multiple market makers, the NASD encouragesits members to buy and sell customer orders as well as stocks.Nasdaq participants routinely pay to be allowed to execute eachothers' trades. "Payment for order flow," as this practice iscalled, has distinct advantages for Nasdaq market makers: Inessence, it guarantees them a steady volume of business. Andthe price for this predictability is low핫sually a few centsper order.  <p> But payment for order flow adds disproportionately to investors'trading costs on Nasdaq. Why? Because market makers don't competeas strongly against one another. Once a firm has lined up a steadyflow of trades학y paying for them할t loses the strongest incentiveto execute every trade at the best possible price핪he need toensure repeat business.  <p> Joseph Hardiman, the NASD's chief executive officer, has saidthat payment for order flow doesn't hurt individual investors.As evidence, he has cited an NASD study concluding that suchpayments "actually encourage lower execution costs and enhanceservices to investors." But Marshall Blume and Michael Goldsteinfound just the opposite in a 1992 study published by the WhartonSchool's Rodney L. White Center. The study said that brokerswho receive payments for order flow "have an incentive to sendorders to that market even when another market might on averageprovide better prices." And executives from the NYSE and AMEXhave testified against the practice on Capitol Hill. In May 1993,Richard Grasso, then president of the NYSE, urged that paymentfor order flow be banned entirely because it "harms the marketas a whole."  <p> The SEC doesn't go this far; it recently floated the idea ofrequiring brokerage firms to inform their clients about paymentsfor order flow, without changing the practice itself. The NASDwill have to go along, if grudgingly. But even this half-measurehas now been postponed by at least six months. It is set to beunveiled in October; the SEC's Brandon Becker says the delaywill allow for more discussion of improvements to the plan. <p> Meanwhile, have you ever heard of something called a 19c-3 security?Most investors haven't. It's a stock that was first listed onthe NYSE or AMEX after April 26, 1979. The SEC's rule 19c-3 allowsmarket makers to trade these shares on Nasdaq학ypassing the moreprice-efficient stock exchanges. And this happens more oftenthan most investors realize, because the incentives for brokeragesto do it are huge.  <p> The brokers themselves benefit as well. Take, for instance,a Smith Barney customer who wants to buy an NYSE-listed stocksuch as RJR Nabisco. Justifiably, he might imagine that his tradewill occur on the NYSE. But if that happens, his broker willget just 33 percent of the gross commission. If the broker directsthe RJR trade to his firm's 19c-3 desk, by contrast, he keeps40 percent. And he's free to do that as long as the customer항houltimately pays the freight핛oesn't specify otherwise.  <p> Earlier this year, the NASD responded to SEC concerns aboutits members' 19c-3 practices. Indeed, according to NYSE and AMEXsources, Nasdaq market makers who trade in listed stocks oftendo so at a price outside the proper bid-asked range핞iving customerswoefully bad executions. The NASD's solution? Not to ban such"trade-throughs," certainly. Instead, it would continue 19c-3trading under more limited circumstances.  <p> In return for this modest gesture, the NASD wants a big favor:It wants no restrictions on the number of NYSE and AMEX stocksit is allowed to trade. As a self-policing measure, this amountsto promising to take less from more people.  <p>  <p>the watchdog that doesn't bark  <p> Making sure brokers follow the rules is a crucial part of NASD'sjob as a self-regulated organization. Yet according to stateregulators, securities lawyers and even executives at some ofits member firms, the NASD is alarmingly lax in this regard.In Indiana last summer, regulators got so mad at the NASD thatWoody Burton, a member of the state's House of Representatives,tried to scupper Nasdaq by introducing legislation that wouldhave required all companies trading on Nasdaq to register theirfinancial filings with the state securities commission. The ideawas to create a blizzard of red tape.  <p> This may have been an extreme move, but Burton says he was simplyfed up with the NASD's do-nothing approach. "Brokers sell securitieshere that are close to being a scam하nd when the heat turns on,they shut shop, move, and start up again in another state," hecomplains. "The NASD won't supply us with information about thesepeople. When asked, they said it wasn't proper. I wrote the NASDa letter, and they didn't even reply."  <p> Ultimately, Burton withdrew his bill, feeling he had made hispoint. But state regulators such as Stephen Diamond, securitiescommissioner for Maine, have similar complaints. "Cooperationfrom the NASD has been mixed," he says. "We license people andthey license people. We have about 300 people annually whoseapplications are withdrawn because of our questions. But theNASD has issued licenses to them."  <p> Before 1991, state regulators provided the public with whatamounted to background checks on brokers. Investors could learnabout a broker's employment history, all adjudicated or settledlawsuits, and any run-ins with regulators. Today, the NASD runsa hot line that is supposed to provide the same service. Butit is not nearly as educational. "Disciplinary information abouta broker is sometimes not being made available," CongressmanEdward Markey of Massachusetts wrote in a letter last Septemberto the General Accounting Office, a sort of government auditor.Markey asked the GAO to investigate the hot line last September,citing cases involving brokers in Massachusetts and in Michigan. <p> In the Massachusetts case, state regulators had taken swipesat broker Gerald Swirsky. According to correspondence betweenMarkey and regulators, these included a 1993 action barring Swirskyfor two years from discretionary trading in customer accountsand from acting as principal, officer, director, supervisor,or manager of any securities firm that employed him. Massachusettsofficials had also suspended Swirsky from selling securitiesthere at all for two months as punishment for having sold securitieswhile he wasn't registered. Swirsky had similar restrictionsplaced on him by the state of Florida. Yet none of this appearedon records the NASD made available to investors who called itshot line. Asked why, the NASD replied: "The Florida and Massachusettsrecords are not 녃isciplinary actions' covered by the NASD'sdisclosure policy. Rather, they are informal restrictive agreementsnegotiated between the state and the individual."  <p> The case of Thomas Bandyk was even more alarming to Markey.Although the hot line report on Bandyk mentioned three pendingor completed disciplinary actions, it failed to disclose morethan a dozen financial settlements involving the broker. Thesesettlements had resulted from arbitration initiated by disgruntledcustomers and amounted to nearly $750,000 in total. Accordingto the Markey correspondence, Bandyk had a pattern of behaviorthat any prospective investor would want to know about. But theNASD says that "such disclosures could inhibit the ability orwillingness of parties to reach a settlement."It also says itspolicy "recognizes that there many be many valid business reasons,other than an admission of wrongdoing, to settle a dispute." <p> In a letter to Markey, the NASD did concede that Bandyk's casewas "especially disturbing" because of the large number of settleddisputes하nd the big money involved. But, perhaps in the beliefthat the Bandyk case was an aberration, the NASD's letter concluded:"We continue to believe ... that the answer to the problem-brokerissue is not making the entire [disciplinary] record availableto the public." The NASD wants to continue limiting the informationit reports to investors.  <p>  <p>rough justice, nasd-style  <p> Thanks to a landmark 1987 Supreme Court case, Shearson v. McMahon,arbitration is virtually the only game in town for customerswho want justice from NASD member firms and their brokers. Doinvestors get a fair shake from this self-regulated organization?Wayne Klein, Idaho's securities regulator, doesn't think so.Neither do lawyers who have seen the NASD's arbitration fees핧ayableeven if the NASD member is found liable합kyrocket in recent years. <p> Not long after the Shearson decision, the NASD revised its feestructure upward. Since 1990 the organization's revenue fromarbitration fees has more than doubled, rising to $7.5 millionin 1993. Aggrieved investors also must pay costs of duplicatingtranscripts and tapes, expenses for any experts who may testify,and lawyers' fees.  <p> These costs might not matter so much if justice seemed to beserved. But NASD arbitration isn't exactly a balanced process.Investors must take their gripes before a panel of arbitratorsselected for each case. According to the NASD Manual, these judgesshould be "impartial persons knowledgeable in the areas of controversy."Sources familiar with the panels, however, say the same groupof arbitrators are used time and again.   <p> Keeping arbitrators in line may not be as hard as it might seem.Arthur Schwartzstein, a Washington, D.C., securities lawyer,says that during training sessions he attended, potential arbitratorswere not encouraged to be impartial. Instead, they were indoctrinatedinto the industry mindset. For instance, trainers said that bigpunitive damage awards aren't in the industry's interest. Trainersalso stated that investors ought not be allowed to recoup commissionsin cases where a broker is found to have "churned" an account,or made an excessive number of trades.   <p> The dice may be loaded in the NASD's internal proceedings핪heSEC found that  in at least one case. In 1992, the NASD chargedmember firm Datek Securities with splitting large orders intoparts before entering them on an automated trading system calledthe Small Order Execution System. A disciplinary panel foundthat Datek had split the orders to circumvent order-size limitson SOES. It suspended Datek's head trader, Sheldon Maschler,and disconnected the firm from SOES for three months.  <p> Datek appealed the NASD's finding to the SEC, claiming therehad been a conflict of interest on the disciplinary panel. Twoof the three panelists were from Smith Barney and Shearson LehmanBrothers, which had participated in almost 20 percent of thetransactions in the case. This in spite of the fact that theNASD Manual states: "No member of the Board of Governors or ofany committee of the Corporation shall directly or indirectlyparticipate in any adjudication ... which would ... substantiallyaffect ... the interests of any person in whom he is directlyor indirectly interested."  <p> The NASD told the SEC that the panelists had acted fairly despitetheir obvious conflict. But the SEC ruled that the NASD "failedto confront directly the issue of bias." It reversed the NASD'sfindings and overturned the sanctions against Datek.  <p> The NASD, meanwhile, doesn't propose any changes in either itsarbitration or disciplinary proceedings. Furthermore, it's backon Datek's trail. It recently reopened the case핪his time witha new, conflict-free set of panelists.  <p>  <p>protecting the guilty  <p> In another instance of siding with brokers over the public,the NASD last year submitted a proposal to eliminate punitivedamages in arbitration cases brought against brokers.   <p> Wayne Klein, Idaho's state securities regulator, calls the NASDproposal an example of the organization's brokerage-industrybias. In a letter to the NASD, Klein wrote: "If the NASD is goingto make a proposal that would so favor its members and so disadvantageindividual investors who are victimized, I think the Associationshould make it clear that it is acting as a trade associationand is not acting in its capacity as a regulator."  <p> Klein believes investors should be able to seek punitive damagesagainst brokerage firms because arbitration is now the mandatoryroute to redress for wronged investors. Remedies under that systemshould not be limited, he says, adding: "Having made arbitrationmandatory, the firms항ith the assistance of the NASD핟ave thetemerity to seek to limit the remedies of investors in that forum." <p> Problem brokers and securities-firm employees would seem tobe an issue that the NASD should pursue with alacrity and a vengeance.But two very different situations illustrate that such is notalways the case.  <p> One pertains to a smallish firm whose principal, when relayingthe story, asked for anonymity out of fear of retribution bythe NASD. Last year, this person's firm fired several high-levelemployees after learning that they had broken securities regulations.Among other things, they had arranged side deals for themselves,hidden documents from management, and stolen management feesdue the firm. The firm reported the details to the NASD.  <p> Later, however, our source learned that the dismissed employeeshad simply set up a new brokerage firm down the street, registeringas a member with the NASD. Baffled, the principal telephonedthe NASD to ask how it could let such people loose on the public,knowing what it did about their recent behavior. According tothis person, the NASD responded: "We can't stand in the way ofpeople making a living."  <p> The second example involves an arbitration case brought successfullyby investor Susan S. Erb against Oscar J. Leon, a broker formerlyemployed by Legg Mason in McLean, Virginia. According to thecase summary, Leon forged his client's name on checks, whichhe then cashed himself. He also prepared a false portfolio reportto deceive Erb about the value of her holdings, all the whilechurning her account. Erb suffered $164,000 in trading losses,$20,000 in margin expenses, and $83,000 in losses from forgedchecks and wire transfers.  <p> After seven hearings in the NASD district office in Washington,D.C., NASD arbitrators awarded Erb $420,000, plus interest. Nevertheless,Arthur M. Schwartzstein, Erb's attorney, was outraged by theproceedings. First, he says, the investigator initially assignedto the case하n aggressive, professional individual in Schwartzstein'sview항as pulled off the case by the NASD. Why? According to Schwartzstein,someone objected to this investigator and persuaded the NASDto come up with a replacement.   <p> Then, after the arbitration proceedings were concluded, in theface of evidence of forgeries and churning, the NASD closed itsown disciplinary case against Leon, taking no action whatsoeveragainst him. Says Schwartzstein: "Once you've reported forgeries,the NASD has an obligation to look into it." According to courtdocuments,  Leon had also forged checks and stolen money fromthree other clients' accounts in addition to Erb in 1993.   <p>  <p>What's in store for the NASD?   <p> With the Justice Department on its trail, the NASD of tomorrowcould look very different from that of today. A complete overhaulof the Nasdaq dealer system could be in order. In a 1975 amendmentto the Securities Exchange Act of 1934, Congress essentiallyordered the SEC to find a way to make public orders meet withoutthe intervention of a dealer. Section 11A states: "It is in thepublic interest and appropriate for the protection of investorsand the maintenance of fair and orderly markets to assure ...an opportunity ... for investors' orders to be executed withoutthe participation of a dealer." To the detriment of the public,this mandate has not been achieved at Nasdaq. Dealer intervention항ithall its attending problems핟as continued, full force.   <p> - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - -- - - - - - - - -   <p>   <p> Trade NASDAQ Like a Pro  <p> By Gretchen Morgenson  <p> Trading in Nasdaq stocks can be a costly proposition할n moreways than one. Nevertheless, shunning all Nasdaq stocks isn'trealistic for most investors, either. Here are some ways to makesure your interests come first when trading on the Nasdaq:  <p>  <p>Don't buy or sell Nasdaq shares "at the market."   <p> This effectively gives your broker a license to execute yourorder in the worst way possible (for you). Market orders makesense only if you want to get in or out of a stock at any price.  <p>  <p>Do use limit orders.  <p> If you trade through a full-service broker, ask him or her to"work" your trade핧utting it in at a price between the bid andasked. If your broker values your business, chances are goodthat you'll get your price. Some patience may be required.  <p> Discount brokers are less likely to help with this. Most smalldiscounters aren't market makers, so they have to send tradesto other firms for execution. Also, since discounters chargereduced commissions, they have less incentive to help investorscut costs in other ways. Discount houses with market-making subsidiaries,like Charles Schwab and Olde Discount, don't like to work tradeseither, because that means giving up a portion of the money theyearn on the spread. People who trade Nasdaq stocks in large amountseasily can save money using full-service brokers even thoughtheir commissions are higher.  <p>  <p>Ask your broker to send your trades to the Chicago Stock Exchange.  <p> This exchange now trades 100 top Nasdaq stocks. By matchinginvestors' orders, the Chicago exchange can get you a betterprice. Not all firms will let you send your shares to Chicago,but some discount firms will.  <p>  <p>Specify that your trades for stocks listed on the NYSE and Amexactually go to these exchanges.   <p> This way, you can ensure that you won't be victimized by thehigh costs associated with 19c-3 trading practices.<p><p><p>

