		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Derivatives and the Bogey Monster</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/10-Derivatives and Bogey Monster</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						October 1994
Worth magazine/Advisor<p>DERIVATIVES AND THE BOGEY MONSTER
Ignore the hype: Derivatives aren't always disastrous.<p>By Liliana Nealon<p>Derivatives are being vilified as investments from hell, much like program trading was in the '80s. Problems that crop up in money market funds, international and domestic bond funds, pension funds, and staid and conservative corporate treasuries are often blamed on derivatives. <p>As with many trends in the investment world, this is overdone. Derivatives have pros and cons, as do all investments. And remember, the same investment strategies that caused portfolio losses in 1994 created millions of dollars in gains in recent years. <p>A derivative, in general, is a contract that derives its value from another financial instrument. In most cases, derivatives are agreements that give the buyer a future claim on an underlying asset (or the cash value of an underlying asset) and the seller an obligation to meet a corresponding liability, also in the future. There are no orphans in the world of derivatives -- every instrument has a parent. For example, the popular TIGRs, or deeply discounted Treasury strips favored by investors in retirement accounts, are derived from U.S. Treasury bonds. When you pay a $250 charge to lock in a mortgage rate, you're really buying a call option on that interest rate, banking on it rising rather than falling. <p>In fact, there's hardly a financial instrument around that is not a derivative. Says Varick Martin, senior vice president at NatWest Markets in New York: "In my opinion, there is only one financial transaction that is not a derivative -- when you stick $100,000 in cash in a bank account."<p>According to a May 1994 report by the General Accounting Office, between 1989 and 1992 the dollar amount of the derivatives market skyrocketed 145 percent. Today, the worldwide volume of outstanding derivatives amounts to $17.6 trillion. The GAO also says 14 major U.S. banks and securities firms faced $114 billion in gross credit risk because of their derivatives portfolios as of year-end 1992.<p>Derivatives can certainly be labyrinthine. Consider one of the more common derivatives trades: selling a naked call option. Say IBM is trading at 60.63, and you think the company's prospects are dimming. To act on your hunch, you sell ten call options with a strike price of 60 and a two-month maturity. You borrow on margin, meaning you borrow money from your broker to execute your transaction. The buyer of the options pays you a total of $2,875. <p>Effectively, you have just promised to sell over the next two months 1,000 shares of <a name="NYSE:IBM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10796"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>IBM</b></a> that you do not own, at $60 each, or $60,000. If IBM's stock price steadily rises over the next two months, you will be forced to sell 1,000 shares of IBM worth $60 each at a loss. Since you do not own the stock, you'd have to go into the open market and buy the shares at a higher price. One good earnings announcement could wipe out the money you put up on margin. <p>Since it's impossible to pinpoint the downside risk of this simple IBM transaction, imagine how difficult it is to measure the potential losses related to the highly sophisticated derivatives transactions whirling through thousands of computer banks daily. The GAO study splits derivative risks into four categories: credit or counterparty risk, market risk, legal risk, and operational risk. Of these, market risk is responsible for most of the losses suffered by investors this year -- when it bites, it bites hard. This is the risk that the market, as in the IBM example, moves against you. <p>Given this piling on of risks, you may be tempted to cast aside anything that remotely resembles a derivative in your portfolio. Should you abandon your holdings in a corporation because its treasurer is investing in derivatives?Should you automatically sell out of any mutual fund that uses derivatives?<p>The answer to both questions is a firm no. Instead of panicking, do a little investigative work to find out whether the derivatives in your portfolio are likely to harm you: <p>-> Watch out for neophyte risk managers. You must be confident that the people managing your investments know what they're doing. The GAO report states, "No comprehensive industry or Federal Regulatory requirements exist to ensure that U.S. derivatives dealers follow good risk management practices." Mutual fund investors in particular should be concerned about novice managers. Unlike corporate treasurers, many funds only recently began dabbling in derivatives. If your fund's money manager has less than two years of experience trading derivatives, head for the door.<p>However, even the pros can lose; many of the corporations reporting losses this year were known for their savvy and expertise in the field of risk management. Markets give and markets take away. Just because derivative trading is generating losses now doesn't mean it will forever. Although numbers are difficult to get, most observers believe the losses generated this year don't begin to negate the gains made trading derivatives in the past.<p>-> Check your fund's liquidity. Ask your fund manager about the liquidity of the instruments in which your fund invests, especially derivatives. Lack of liquidity is a major factor in derivatives losses. If any more than 5 percent of your fund is invested in derivatives, question it. If derivatives are used solely as hedging vehicles, such as to hedge against currency risks associated with holding foreign stocks or bonds, you can breathe more easily. Such techniques actually reduce a portfolio's risk and are commonplace. If your fund is using derivatives as a way to bet on market moves, stay away. One way to identify a gambler: Fund returns that are much higher than average. Outsized gains, though appealing, should raise a red flag. <p>-> Stick to big institutional names in money market funds. Until the Securities and Exchange Commission takes regulatory action to protect investors, venerable firms are better able to absorb or even pay back losses. <a name="NYSE:PWJ"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11148"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>PaineWebber</b></a>, First Boston, and BankAmerica made refunds to shareholders who suffered losses because of derivatives trades in their short-term funds. While it's not guaranteed that refunds will continue, big funds are more likely to do this than smaller ones. <p>In spite of the hoopla surrounding derivatives, remember that these vehicles have been around for a long time, with little incident. When investors find a new investment to fear and loathe, the dread that is derivatives may be forgotten.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Investing Strategies, Stock Investing, Mutual Funds Investing, Bond Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
