<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/09-The "Perfect Area" for Fraud</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/09-The "Perfect Area" for Fraud</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
Why scam artists love to target retirement money.<p>By Kathleen Murray<p>During his career as an insurance-marketing rep, John Keeler, 67, switched jobs so many times that he never had a chance to build up much in the way of retirement savings. So when he stumbled upon First Pension Corp., based in Irvine, California, he thought he'd found a great way to make up for lost time. Here was a company that offered to set him up in limited partnerships investing in pools of mortgages -- and purported to earn between 13 percent and 28 percent a year. The company had splashy brochures and a 14-year track record. Keeler plunked down $6,000 in savings.<p>Earlier this year, on April 22, First Pension filed for bankruptcy. Three weeks later, the Securities and Exchange Commission sued the company, charging that its officers had defrauded investors out of some $124 million through an elaborate pyramid scheme. Instead of investing incoming funds in new mortgages, regulators alleged, company president William Cooper and his associates used at least some of the money to pay off old investors. The company operated a network of 218 partnerships, though it actually owned just 17 properties, regulators also said. Keeler and 9,000 other First Pension investors -- some with more than $100,000 at stake -- are now awaiting the outcome of bankruptcy and legal proceedings to learn if they'll be able to recoup any of their money. <p>The saga of First Pension underscores the importance of checking out the administrator of a retirement plan carefully before committing any funds. It also highlights the perils of "direct participation" programs, where the company administering a retirement account is also a company that sells investment products.<p>"This is a perfect area [in which] to commit fraud," says Lisa Gok, assistant regional administrator with the SEC in Los Angeles. The reason is that investors in retirement accounts plan on keeping their money in the same place for a long time; if con artists take it, the investors may not even realize it's gone.<p>Most retirement-plan administrators, of course, are legitimate, and their direct-participation programs pose minimal risks. Big mutual fund companies like Vanguard, Fidelity, and T. Rowe Price and brokerages like Charles Schwab and Merrill Lynch regularly sell their own mutual funds and help clients set up retirement accounts. But even with these trusted companies it's a good idea to check with local securities regulators for evidence of any problems.<p>Investors who investigated closely would have turned up several danger signs at First Pension. One clear warning was interlocking ownership with other entities. The same people who owned First Pension also owned Vestcorp, the company that sold the partnerships. In 1992, the National Association of Securities Dealers fined Vestcorp $7,500 for, among other things, not disclosing its relationship with First Pension and improperly withdrawing funds from escrow. In addition, Cooper, a politically connected real estate developer, was president of three different firms that acted as general partner for some of the limited partnerships. Cooper also was affiliated with the custodian bank that acted as trustee for the funds.<p>More red flags: The investments were unregistered. By limiting the number of investors in each partnership to 35, the company was able to sidestep state disclosure requirements about the properties. These investments also failed the too-good-to-be-true test: With past returns of up to 28 percent, the partnerships were doing too well, considering that the real estate market in Southern California was in the tank. "You've got to ask yourself if the performance makes sense," says the SEC's Gok. Regulators now believe that promoters were using incoming funds to make their numbers. <p>If someone wants to commit fraud, it's difficult to detect. But there are ways to protect yourself.<p>Read the prospectus and offering materials, particularly sections that discuss risk factors and conflicts of interest. If this information is not disclosed, as in the case of First Pension, ask for it. If you can't get answers that way, look for another place to put your money. <p>Offering materials should also provide detailed information on how your funds are being invested. When his documents didn't identify specific mortgages, Gordon Reiter, a retired aerospace engineer from Torrance, California, who had invested in excess of $100,000 in Vestcorp partnerships, contacted Cooper to ask if he could get more information about the properties in question. Cooper brushed him off, saying that he had to protect the property owners' confidentiality. "Looking back, I should have pressed him," Reiter says. Steven Gourley, a Los Angeles attorney who was a state regulator in the 1980s, recommends asking to see evidence of hard assets in a limited partnership -- appraisals, who owns the properties, and what their payment record is, for example.<p>Check with regulators. You can often investigate operators of even unregistered securities if they're licensed with other agencies. For example, Vestcorp and First Pension dealt in real estate. California's Department of Corporations had no records of disciplinary action against Cooper or his companies, but the state Department of Real Estate revoked Cooper's license in early 1984 for misappropriating $577,000 in investor funds. <p>If you can't get your money out of an investment within a reasonable period of time, report it to the Department of Labor. The SEC has received letters from investors who tried to withdraw their funds from Vestcorp partnerships in 1984 and 1985 and were put off by First Pension. At the same time, the investors continued to receive phony statements showing that their principal was growing each year. The SEC believes this trick was designed to keep them from pulling out their funds. It should never take you more than a couple of months to transfer funds out of a pension plan.<p>This may seem like a lot of sleuthing, but as investors with First Pension have learned, the price of not doing your homework can be steep.<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Ethical Investing, Retirement<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
