<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/06-The New Blue Chips</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/06-The New Blue Chips</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
The old standbys have let investors down. Here's a new group that should provide solid growth in a sometimes volatile market.<p>By Jim Jubak<p>Blue-chip stocks, like old soldiers, never seem to die. They just fade away, eventually metamorphosing into what James Craig, portfolio manager for the <a name="FUND:JANSX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/JANSX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Janus Fund</b></a>, calls "the big uglies." But the U.S. economy is a dynamic one -- and every so often a new blue chip is born. <p>With this in mind, we set out to refresh the blue-chip list for the '90s and beyond. Our goal: Identify 50 prime stocks that meet the definition of blue chip as investors have understood it for most of the 20th century. <p>This was no small task. To merit inclusion on such a list, a stock would have to be able to provide steady capital gains, hefty dividends, and rock-solid safety. These were the characteristics that made the blue chips of yesteryear so highly prized that the stocks were often passed on from one generation to the next.<p><a name="NYSE:K"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10841"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Kellogg</b></a> was once such a stock. Starting in 1955, its upward trajectory was so reliable that an investor could have acquired the cereal maker's shares and then gone to sleep for the next three decades. While slumbering, the fortunate owner would have raked in average annual price appreciation of 10 percent plus dividends. <p>H.J. Heinz was another. Its stock appreciated by an average of 15 percent a year from 1967 to 1985. The story was much the same for other blue chips: <a name="NYSE:GM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10640"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>General Motors</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:IBM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10796"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>IBM</b></a>, Procter & Gamble. On occasion, hot growth stocks such as Xerox would outshine the chips. Yet in market drops, the aggressive-growth stocks would fall in frightening fashion, while the blue chips, sustained by their dividend yields, edged down with reassuring dignity. <p>Are there stocks today worthy of being called blue chips? For help in finding out, we consulted some of the investment community's best minds, including professional investors, market strategists, and securities analysts. We asked Paul Greenwood and Rolf Agather of the Frank Russell Co., the Tacoma, Washington, market-research firm that produces the Russell stock market indexes, to run a series of studies for us on large-capitalization stocks going back to 1978. Standard & Poor's Compustat, which keeps financial data on 8,900 companies dating as far back as 1950, identified companies that met criteria for margin growth and improvements in profitability. Gail Dudack, U.S. market strategist at S.G. Warburg, an international money-management firm, made another important contribution when she led us to look for companies that have kept their production costs low; growth in the 1990s will depend on increasing profit margins even as prices charged to customers fall.<p>The product of our research, we believe, was a fresh method for selecting stocks with the optimal combination of safety, yield, and growth -- hallmarks of the classic blue chips. Some of the names that made our list were hardly surprising, among them <a name="NYSE:G"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10655"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Gillette</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:AUD"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10148"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Automatic Data Processing</b></a>, and <a name="NYSE:RBD"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11294"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Rubbermaid</b></a>. Others were less obvious as blue chips, if not exactly unknown as growth vehicles, such as <a name="NYSE:HD"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11470"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Home Depot</b></a>, <a name="NASD:INTC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13787"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Intel</b></a>, and <a name="NYSE:ABS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10049"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Albertson</b></a>'s. Blue-chip investors might erroneously consider those stocks too volatile for their portfolios. Yet we found their short-term volatility has disguised a steady and almost predictable long-term appreciation. Other high-profile stocks -- including many that investors may still regard as blue chips -- failed to pass our tests. A look at blue-chip history will help explain why.<p>On July 3, 1884, Charles Dow put together the first index of leading stocks -- a list that many investors would come to associate with the term blue chip. It included 11 railroads plus Western Union and appeared in what was then called the Customer's Afternoon Letter, a publication that would later become The Wall Street Journal. In May 1896, Dow split an expanded list in two: One list focused on railroads, and the other exclusively on industrials. That first Dow Jones Industrial Index included speculative growth companies such as <a name="NYSE:GE"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10634"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>General Electric</b></a>, a high-technology company financed with venture capital that had staked its future on Thomas Edison's scheme for electric lights. The list also included huge trusts like American Sugar and U.S. Rubber, which wielded control over entire industries. Others, like Tennessee Coal & Iron and Chicago Gas, typified the muscle of the newly industrializing nation.<p>What characterized these early blue chips? Central Leather, which joined the Dow in 1912 and left the list in 1924, was a corporate Croesus: Its balance sheet showed $56.8 million in property and timberlands. The company owned tanneries, lumber mills, extract factories, finishing plants, glue works, machine shops, and the entire capital stock of the Susquehanna and New York Rail Road. In 1917 Central Leather paid a regular dividend of 5 percent and declared a special dividend of 4 percent on its common stock.<p>Stocks like these helped establish the parameters for blue-chip investing. The most obvious: A company must have a certain substance, usually measured by size. Yet size can be misleading. Over the years, many investors have erred in thinking of mass as intrinsically desirable, a guarantee of safety. But size is important only when it contributes to competitive advantage, a key characteristic of all blue chips. The big companies that came to be identified as blue chips had sterling balance sheets that enabled them to absorb short-term shocks, to invest in new technologies, and to wage war against their rivals. They typically had large and loyal customer bases, as well as octopus-like distribution systems that assured that their products would always get presented to consumers, often in preference to rival goods that were cheaper or better.<p>Size thus translated into might -- an advantage that enabled blue chips to dominate their markets, earn higher returns, and offer hefty dividends. In 1978, for example, the 50 largest-capitalization stocks yielded 5.5 percent, according to the Frank Russell Co. Those dividends were a crucial part of the appeal of blue chips for conservative long-term investors. Even if the stock encountered tough times, shareholders knew that their dividend would cushion the fall.<p>Size still offers an edge. For all the talk of big-company layoffs and the emergence of an entrepreneurial economy, large corporations still usually manage to reward their shareholders. An investor who put $1,000 in the Russell 1000 index of large-capitalization stocks in 1978 would have had $8,850 worth of stock at the end of 1993, assuming all dividends were reinvested along the way. During the same period, an investor in small caps would have earned slightly more -- his $1,000 would have been worth $9,190. The big-cap investor, however, would have slept more soundly. In the small caps' worst year of those 15 years, their prices as measured by the index lost 19.5 percent of their value. The worst dip in the big caps was 5.1 percent.<p>In constructing our list of the new blue chips, we began with some of the historical blue-chip virtues and added some new criteria to reflect the changing economy. We started off by limiting the list to companies with market capitalizations (the price per share multiplied by the number of shares outstanding) of at least $600 million, the size of the smallest company on the Russell 1000 index. We also eliminated utilities and financial concerns: Interest rates influence their share prices too strongly to make them blue chips. Of the 1,000 candidates, 640 made our initial cut.<p>Then we looked for the strongest balance sheets. Perhaps not surprisingly, only 13 companies of the 640 had senior subordinate debt with a Standard & Poor's rating of AAA, the strongest indication of safety and management prudence. Wincing, we recalibrated our financial scales to accommodate the releveraging of corporate America that took place in the 1980s. Eventually we decided to draw the line at a single-A rating. This requirement alone struck from our list such struggling industrial giants as <a name="NYSE:BS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10210"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Bethlehem Steel</b></a> and <a name="NYSE:UAL"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11520"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>UAL</b></a> (the parent of United Airlines) and some current growth-stock favorites, such as retailer <a name="NYSE:BBY"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10209"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Best Buy</b></a>.<p>While the payment of dividends was once an important part of what made a stock a blue chip -- and the higher the dividend the better -- we felt this part of the definition also needed revision. In today's economy, companies must reinvest at a faster rate to remain competitive. No longer can they afford to sit on huge piles of rusty assets. It made sense, or so it seemed, for U.S. Steel to pay $3 in dividends on the $5.16 a share it earned in 1960. Today it is at least as reasonable that Intel pays out 20 cents in dividends on the $5.20 a share it earned in 1993. <p>Still, we felt the payment of at least a modest amount was important; it does suggest a certain confidence in the future on the part of corporate directors. Consequently, we struck such growth-company stars as <a name="NYSE:CPQ"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10381"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Compaq</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:SGI"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11735"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Silicon Graphics</b></a>, and <a name="NYSE:TOY"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11495"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Toys "R" Us</b></a> from our list, because they didn't give us this indication.<p>To weave the safety net tighter, we looked at profit margins. Companies can no longer rely on simply selling more of their goods or services to increase their earnings. Certainly they cannot rely on upping prices. A true blue chip, we decided, should be able to raise profits by becoming more efficient. To reflect this, we excluded from our list companies with growth in either gross margins or operating margins of less than 0.5 percent a year.<p>Stability alone doesn't make a blue chip. Stability plus performance does. Earnings increases for a blue chip should certainly beat the increase in gross domestic product over the past five years. That growth in GDP, reflecting real output plus inflation (just as corporate earnings do), averaged 5.4 percent a year. We set the bar 200 basis points higher, requiring earnings growth of at least 7.4 percent a year to qualify as a blue chip.<p>We wanted to see a proportional increase in the candidate's price. Over the five years ended December 31, the Russell 1000 returned 14.8 percent a year in price gains plus reinvested dividends. A blue chip ought to do at least as well. We kept on the list only stocks with an average annual return of 15 percent; with bulls dominating the stock market for most of the five years, that seemed the least we could ask. This requirement further shortened our list, to 75 companies.<p>Finally, we required predictability and determined which of those 75 showed the steadiest earnings growth. As a measure, we used standard deviation, a statistical calculation that in this case showed how far a company's quarterly earnings growth strayed from its average annual growth over five years. The 50 companies with the least volatile quarterly earnings growth made up our final list.<p>Stock price is conspicuously absent from our selection method. This is a list of stocks a blue-chip investor may want to own but not necessarily to buy tomorrow. When, then, should an investor buy? In the table, we've rated each stock for timeliness. The ratings are one asterisk for stocks that seem fully priced to us at present (wait to buy them), two asterisks for stocks that seem fairly priced (buy them now if you really like the company), and three asterisks for stocks that represent value at their current price (clear buys now at this price). <p>To arrive at the ratings, we considered several indicators of reasonable price. One was the five-year range of each stock's price-to-earnings ratio. Stocks are buys near the low end of that range. We also calculated the ratio of each stock's p/e to its growth rate, showing which stocks are trading at prices that seem disproportionately low relative to their growth prospects.<p>We also applied the relative-dividend-yield system employed by institutional money managers Anthony Spare and Nancy Tengler to those stocks with substantial dividends. The firm Spare, Tengler, Kaplan & Bischel manages $2.2 billion using this system. According to Callan Associates, an investment-consulting firm, for the 15 years ended December 31, 1993, Spare, Tengler's portfolio beat the S&P index in annual return -- 17.7 percent to 15.7 percent -- and showed lower risk as well.<p>The details of that system are explained in Spare and Tengler's book Relative Dividend Yield. To simplify, the system uses the ratio of the yield on a specific stock to the average yield on the S&P 500, in a way that produces buy and sell signals. The yield on individual stocks historically fluctuates greatly, sometimes reaching a level much higher than the S&P, sometimes reaching a level much lower. The extremes represent periods when the stock is out of favor with investors, whose selling has reduced its price and increased its yield, and when it is overvalued by investors, whose buying has driven up the price and reduced the yield. Stocks are buys when relative dividend yields are high and sells when they are low.<p>That's it: our guide to the new blue chips, from their definition to the timing of their purchase. The list begins below.
---------------
Jim Jubak is Worth's financial editor.<p>
