	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/05-The Humbling of John Sculley</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/05-The Humbling of John Sculley</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						When he stepped down as Apple chairman, he was looking to restore his good name--and get rich, too. Instead, he met a small-timer named Peter Caserta.<p>By Jesse Kornbluth<p>The tale of John Sculley's brief, reputation-shattering tenure at a tiny company called Spectrum Information Technologies has enough curious characters and moral lessons to fill a book of fables. But it begins modestly, with a pain in the neck.<p>Peter Caserta's neck.<p>It was late May 1993, and the Spectrum chief should have been basking in glory. After hustling clients for years in what he called "a breakthrough in investment banking" but a recent federal complaint describes as a fraudulent boiler-room operation, Caserta had finally gained control of an entire company from one of his customers. Spectrum was no prize, but it owned some intriguing patents concerning the transmission of computer data over cellular-telephone networks.<p>Now, using persuasion and flint, Caserta had managed to land a dream endorsement for these minor assets: a deal with giant AT&T to license Spectrum's patents. <a name="NYSE:T"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10103"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>AT&T</b></a> had warned Caserta not to overstate the deal's value, vetoing the phrase "hundreds of millions of dollars of royalties for Spectrum" in his proposed press release. But in an interview after the May 11 announcement, Caserta got carried away, talking about "one of the most important licensing agreements of the decade, generating"--yes--"hundreds of millions of dollars in royalties."<p>Did Spectrum stock move as a result? Only from $4.75 to $13 a share. And Caserta looked like a genius. But soon afterward, AT&T issued a harsh reality check that valued the deal at only a few million. In a flood of disappointment, investors dumped their Spectrum stock. <p>The result should have been the end of Caserta's brief career in high tech. He had triggered what was then the biggest-ever selling spree for an over-the-counter issue, with 34.4 million Spectrum shares changing hands in a single day as the stock fell to $6 a share. Lawyers lined up to file class-action suits against him and Spectrum. And the Securities and Exchange Commission launched an investigation into what looked like a stock manipulation.<p>Caserta's response to all this? He hurried to his chiropractor for an adjustment.<p>For a year, Caserta had been treated by Lynn Petronella, a 39-year-old chiropractor's assistant. And during his time on her treatment table, they had become quite friendly. He cheered on her dreams of producing a semi-autobiographical movie about a female runner, even offering to help get financing. Naively thrilled, Petronella returned his encouragement--this time telling him to "get back in the saddle again" with some good news.<p>What neither of them realized was that Petronella herself held the key to that good news. It took a few more months for Petronella to learn that Caserta idolized <a name="NASD:AAPL"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12644"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Apple Computer</b></a>chairman John Sculley, who had become the nation's best-known advocate of wireless communications. A licensing arrangement with Apple--now that would be great for Spectrum.<p>To Caserta's amazement, Petronella offered to make the connection.<p>Was she daffy? Not at all. Fifteen years earlier she had been a competitive runner sponsored by PepsiCo and had sometimes jogged with Sculley, then Pepsi's president. She hadn't talked to him since, but that was no problem: She had, after all, once cold-called Peter Ueberroth and gotten through.<p>In late September, Petronella phoned Sculley. And just as she had predicted, he took her call. Better yet, he took a follow-up call from Caserta--and invited Caserta to his home in Greenwich, Connecticut, to demonstrate Spectrum's technology the very next morning.<p>Caserta couldn't have dared to imagine what came next. In a farce of the highest magnitude, the Long Island nobody would soon be making millions off Sculley's name and reputation--only to end up being named in a fraud investigation by the U.S. Attorney.<p>Meanwhile, Sculley, afflicted by self-doubt and more than a touch of greed, would be dragged into a hell of his own making. Angling desperately for the business hall of fame, he found instead a place in every business-school lecture about the need for due diligence. A mere year after sitting beside Hillary Rodham Clinton at her husband's first big address to Congress, the self-styled visionary would face the future with his image shredded and a nickname that may prove indelible.<p>Numbsculley.<p>Readers of Philip Roth's "Goodbye, Columbus" will remember the difference a few miles can make. The narrator lives with his aunt and uncle in a muggy Newark apartment; his lover lives in a lush and breezy mansion in an elite suburb. It's cooler there. Life is more refined. As he travels to see her, the young man can't help feeling as if he's literally ascending.<p>So it was for Peter Caserta as he went to visit John Sculley on the morning of October 1, 1993. The Caserta home, in Plandome, on the north shore of Long Island, is hardly a slum. But Plandome is just a starter community compared to exclusive Greenwich, across Long Island Sound, where Sculley lives on four acres among the great names of American business. Sanford Weill, head of Travelers, lives close by; the Hirschhorn mansion is down the street.<p>Sculley is tall and lean. He favors crewneck sweaters, khakis, and boat shoes. If it weren't for the perpetually haunted look in his eyes, he could be stepping out of a Ralph Lauren ad. And that's no affectation: Sculley has a classic upper-class WASP background, sheltered and discreet--childhood homes in New York and Bermuda, the best private schools, an Ivy League education. It's not surprising, therefore, that he chose not to buy an ostentatious estate in Greenwich but went instead for an expanded clapboard farmhouse with dairy barns. His third wife, Leezy, has equally perfect pitch: The overall effect in their home is of muted opulence.<p>Caserta is Sculley's opposite. Bald and bespectacled, he's a relentless, street-smart, thick-skinned salesman. He has said that his philosophy is "Commit like your life depended on it. And at the end, remember it's just a game." A more fitting motto for him might be "Always be closing"--the line at the start of David Mamet's devastating play Glengarry Glen Ross. For Peter Caserta, no is merely foreplay for yes.<p>For his visit to Sculley, Caserta excitedly hired a limousine of the length that teenagers favor on prom night. And he brought along a cheering section: his son Peter, Lynn Petronella, and Dana Verrill, Spectrum's Dallas-based chairman and one of its founders. Knowing he was an outsider in Sculley's dining room, Caserta played up the fact and made it charming. Mostly, though, he caught Sculley's attention with his persuasive talk about Spectrum and its wondrous patent portfolio.<p>Sculley was mesmerized by Caserta--as he has told friends, the experience was "hypnotic." His most recent project at Apple was a handheld electronic device called Newton, a kind of supersmart cross between a pocket telephone and a Filofax. Despite his repeated requests to Apple engineers, the newly launched Newton couldn't yet send a wireless fax. Now here was Caserta hooking Sculley's own Newton to a device Spectrum had been marketing for years and handing the gadget across the dining table.<p>"Send yourself a fax," Caserta said. Sculley wrote a fateful line on the Newton's screen--"To Peter Caserta: Let's make this a success, John Sculley"--and activated its phone function. Seconds later, from the home office, came the crunching sound of his fax machine.<p>Sculley was so dazzled that Petronella thought he would get in the limo and come right back to Long Island with Caserta. He shouldn't have been. Commercial wireless data networks and other companies have been working on comparable technology for years, and analysts were briefed on Apple's own plans in the area in late 1992.<p>But Sculley sometimes likes to play the naif. And, as a former colleague says, "With John you have to remind yourself: naive in the service of whom?" In fact, Sculley already knew a bit about Spectrum. Just weeks earlier he'd gotten an enthusiastic report about the company from a young Connecticut stockbroker named Sean Dockery, who had been dating his niece. Dockery had described Spectrum as a neat little business with interesting prospects. So when Petronella called, it was synchronicity Sculley couldn't resist. And indeed, the five-hour meeting had elements of fate.<p>For all his talk about the pleasures and rewards of entrepreneurship, Sculley's career is a model of advancement through astute corporate maneuvering. He had barely arrived as chief executive at Apple, for example, when he became a rival to his charismatic recruiter, Apple cofounder Steven Jobs. Sculley felt he had misread Jobs's ability to manage Apple and, only months later, forced Jobs out.<p>Now, in Sculley's Greenwich dining room, Peter Caserta seemed another charismatic corporate rookie, albeit with far less talent than Jobs. But once again, Sculley misread a benefactor's character. And this time, it was Sculley who was the chump. Unaware that Caserta was a brilliant persuader who owned what the feds now call a fraudulent money-raising operation, he smiled credulously as Caserta looked him in the eye and uttered words that were, at that moment in Sculley's life, magic: "You can have this company and run it any way you want."<p>Sculley was even more vulnerable than Caserta knew. His golden career was going sour, and its 54-year-old proprietor didn't quite know what to do. Sculley in trouble? Few would have believed it just months earlier, but by the time he met Caserta it was undeniably true. Having been stripped of his chief-executive position by the Apple board of directors, Sculley was left pondering his future while clinging to the fig-leaf title of chairman.<p>It was quite a comedown. When Sculley arrived at fast-growing Apple in 1983, he was a sugar-water marketeer who knew little about computers. But after taking on a technology tutor and ousting Jobs, he began to guide Apple to its present-day status as a Silicon Valley institution and an $8 billion corporate giant. His success was unarguable. "He took a bunch of computer hackers who run around in sandals and jeans and married them to Wall Street," says Andrew Seybold, editor of Outlook on Mobile Computing. "It takes a smart human being to marry cultures like that."<p>In 1992, Sculley had a year that--on the surface, at least--exceeded even the most hallucinatory CEO fantasies. Bill Clinton apparently eliminated him as a running mate only because he had been divorced twice. International Business Machines mulled giving Sculley its top job, and American Express also tried to woo him. After Clinton's election, he was asked to join the new cabinet. Sculley has acknowledged to friends that he should have left Apple for <a name="NYSE:IBM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10796"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>IBM</b></a>. But back then, he didn't know he was about to be blindsided by Apple's board of directors.<p>In retrospect, there is no shortage of reasons for the board's displeasure with Sculley in early 1993. His much-touted Newton project was floundering because he had set expectations impossibly high, and Apple's core Macintosh computer business was under assault from cheap IBM-compatible machines that had finally duplicated the Mac's famous ease of use. Yet Sculley, in what many took to be a sign of terminal hubris, had anointed himself Apple's chief technology officer, a strange title for a man who'd had no technical training.<p>Despite his techno-fervor, Sculley was becoming disconnected with the talent at Apple. Greg Smith, who heads an electronic-publishing company called RoundBook, recalls attending the first meetings of an Apple-affiliated spin-off called General Magic. He was stunned to see that Sculley had allowed dozens of Apple's top-flight engineers to abandon the parent company. "That told me Sculley was either indifferent or didn't know how to keep these people," Smith says.<p>Ironically, the incident many consider Sculley's greatest triumph--sitting beside Hillary for Bill's first big speech--marked the beginning of the end for the former cola warrior. To Silicon Valley, the myriad newspaper photos and TV images of that moment were evidence that Sculley's true agenda had little to do with Apple.<p>"Before that, John was just a Friend of Bill," says Tim Bajarin, an analyst and consultant who has known Sculley since his first days at Apple. "After that, he was targeted."<p>Suddenly, everything about Sculley seemed wrong at Apple. Now he was an outsider, an elitist who kept his personal Lear 55 jet idling so he could escape to the East Coast on weekends. His wife was known to be sick of the myopia and infighting she saw at the heart of Silicon Valley culture and was removing herself to more genteel Greenwich. And a self-important Sculley kept telling reporters of a future in which wireless mattered a great deal to him--and computers didn't.<p>In June 1993, after an uncharacteristically heated board meeting, Sculley finally resigned as Apple's CEO. Everyone believed he had been pushed, of course, and that he would, in time, resign as chairman. The crowning blow came in August, when the Newton made its debut to withering reviews.<p>Silicon Valley functions on the Hollywood model, with reputation even more important than accomplishment. In that insular but media-conscious world, the Newton debacle was like a verdict on Sculley's entire career--overnight he became a has-been who needed a box-office hit, and fast, to certify his comeback.<p>Apart from the enormous reversal of fortune, Sculley's impending departure from Apple was worrisome for another reason. A decade earlier, when he was preparing to leave <a name="NYSE:PEP"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11166"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Pepsi</b></a>, Sculley had told Donald Kendall, his mentor and PepsiCo's CEO, about Apple's huge pay offer. "The only thing that's a big deal is the stock options," said Kendall, cutting to the heart of the matter. "What guarantees do you have? I don't think the money should be taken that seriously--it's all bet on the come."<p>Kendall's insight was keen. Thanks to Apple's roller-coaster ride, the eastern transplant would return home far less wealthy than he had hoped. By the time he was set to leave Apple, the options he was holding were worth just $2.4 million. His departing settlement would be mingy, too: $1 million severance, a one-year "consulting fee" of $750,000, plus a commitment from Apple to buy his California home and his jet. He didn't get any pension.<p>Compared with his Greenwich neighbors, Sculley seemed a financial underachiever. Although his wife owned only four horses and his yacht was just a 100-footer, he felt strapped. He had built Apple into a titan but hadn't really shared in its success. And so his attention turned to Barry Diller, the Hollywood executive who had abandoned traditional media for QVC, the home-shopping cable-TV channel. With that leap, Diller had become Sculley's model: "He found a small company that no one had noticed," Sculley has said. "When he joined up, he got an equity position in the company, and a lot of people saw its potential."<p>Before the door slammed behind him at Apple, Sculley was determined to find a Diller-like situation that served two pressing needs.<p>Vindication was one.<p>Wealth creation was the other.<p>Sculley was off to Japan right after his introduction to Spectrum, so it wasn't until October 7 that he next saw Caserta. This time the pair met on Caserta's turf--Spectrum's Long Island headquarters, a crisply renovated suite in a building that was also home to the Caserta firm that would later be raided by U.S. postal inspectors looking for evidence of fraud.<p>Sculley was upbeat that day, and he saw what he wanted to see. He would later say he considered Spectrum "a little gem," a company with $125 million in revenue, almost no debt, an appealing tax situation, and a patent portfolio that was finally accumulating licensees. And he liked Caserta, who struck him as a little rough around the edges but solid and good-hearted.<p>For his part, Caserta was--as always--ready to close. His speedy negotiating tactics parallelled those of the allegedly fraudulent operation he owned. According to a federal complaint, that operation made its money by pressuring prospective clients to sign agreements before they had adequate time to reflect.<p>"We'd love to get you involved" at Spectrum, Caserta told Sculley. "Want to go on the board? Be a consultant?"<p>"No thanks," Sculley replied. "I'm looking to do a start-up--something I create and own myself."<p>"Well...you could run Spectrum," said Caserta. "If you'd come on board, I'd step down."<p>Sculley repeated his position. They were at a stalemate.<p>So Caserta shrewdly told Sculley about the preferred shares. There were 25 million of them floating around, he said, authorized but unattached to any individual. But not for long: They were due to be extinguished on October 20, the date of Spectrum's annual meeting. If Sculley put off joining Spectrum until after the meeting, he'd still get the $1 million salary that's de rigueur for first-tier CEOs, plus a nice options package, of course--but those options would be in Spectrum common stock.<p>The men discussed an intriguing possibility: What if Spectrum were to offer Sculley options to buy all those preferred shares--at a significant discount? If the company did well, the shares would trade easily and bring him more profit. Sculley's interest rose.<p>Spectrum's accountants vetoed that approach a day later, and Sculley agreed to skip the discount. But price, for Caserta, had never been the point. What mattered was that he had successfully led Sculley to a significant shift in his thinking. Now the question wasn't whether Sculley should join Spectrum--but at what price. Caserta had him hooked.<p>"How many options can I get?" Sculley asked.<p>"Ten million," Caserta said.<p>"Twenty."<p>They compromised at options for 18 million shares, about 20 percent of Spectrum's common stock if exercised. Sculley would be allowed to cash in 3 million of them right after he joined. (Had he done so, he could have had an instant profit of about $20 million.) The rest could be redeemed at the rate of 3.75 million shares a year over the following four years. Potential profit: $75 million plus. Small wonder that it took Sculley only days to agree in principle to jump from Apple to a company with a central office staff of 38.<p>Then, and only then, did he start his due diligence.<p>His focus was on Spectrum's patents. Were they really so strong that all the other wireless companies wouldn't be able to get around them, assuring the company a role in the future? Sculley's experts--including Raj Singh, an authority on cellular-telephone technology--came to a quick conclusion: The patents were rock solid.<p>That was debatable. What followed wasn't. Assuming the patents had integrity, Sculley figured the people behind them did, too. But Peter Caserta and his team hadn't developed Spectrum's technology. And even if they had, Sculley's idea of due diligence was laughable: According to people involved in the matter, he simply asked Caserta whether there were any problems in the company or in his past.<p>Here the story diverges. Caserta has said in court records that he told Sculley about the class-action suits and the SEC investigation, both arising from the AT&T brouhaha. In his legal response, Sculley insists he was told only of the class-action suits, which Caserta claimed were about to be settled. And when Sculley asked Caserta if the company used any aggressive accounting practices, Sculley says in his suit, he was told it didn't.<p>Whatever the truth, the fact remains that there was a vast amount of information available about Spectrum--and about Caserta. Sculley and his lawyers could have discovered it by tapping into almost any on-line data service or by running a background check. They did neither. As they saw it, Sculley wasn't buying Spectrum; he was just going to work there.<p>Again, Sculley's mentor Don Kendall was on hand with a gruff and prescient warning. "I hope you checked the people as thoroughly as you checked the patents," he said. But Sculley was too busy figuring out how to become the Barry Diller of wireless to listen. It took him a few weeks, therefore, to realize there was a great deal he didn't know about Peter Caserta.<p>By then it was too late.<p>
While John Sculley was climbing the silken path that led from St. Mark's School through Brown University and the McKinsey consulting firm, Peter Caserta and his brothers were fighting their way out of Little Italy with whatever tools they could find. Clem Caserta became an actor, appearing in character parts in some of Robert De Niro's movies. Frank Caserta gravitated to business. Peter abandoned his dream of becoming a professional baseball player and went through the two-year course of study at the now defunct RCA Institute of Technology.<p>Today, Peter Caserta describes himself as an engineer, a credential that usually requires four years of study. But then, he's never been very good with details--he even lies about his age, says a Spectrum spokesman. Caserta has described his role in the Apollo space program in so many grandiose ways that it's hard to remember he was actually working as a subcontractor to Grumman, a Long Island aerospace company, during those years.<p>But Caserta's involvement with NASA--however marginal--went to his head. Literally: It was there, he says, that he achieved a philosophical breakthrough he likes to call Apollo Transfer Technology, which he describes as "a visionary management technique that has been proven to be one of the most effective tools ever created to enhance the profitability of small to medium-sized companies."<p>Using this "management science," executives are supposedly able to address problems precisely even as they ask large questions. "We operate in two domains, the sequential and the instantaneous," Caserta has said. "The instantaneous is the domain of creativity and innovation. You look at a process and have an instantaneous insight that allows you to achieve what has never been done before."<p>Of course, this is all mumbo jumbo. It's not even original--unless Caserta somehow invented the language and themes of the Forum, Werner Erhard's most advanced est seminar, about 15 years before Erhard himself did.<p>Erhard, a self-described con man until he founded est and discovered that "transformation" could be profitable, knew that you don't need to make sense to draw a crowd. All you need is language--the more esoteric, the better. Erhard's philosophical musings were dense blends of Husserl, Heidegger, and Wittgenstein; his epigrams were sheer nihilism. "There are only two things in the world: nothing and semantics," he said. Audiences actually paid to ponder this mock-Zen balderdash.<p>In fact, in his est days Erhard used the rhetoric of liberation to destabilize hundreds of people who paid nearly $500 to sit in locked hotel ballrooms for two weekends of harangues and "sharing." The aim was to use hours of talk to break down long-held beliefs. At a certain point, est trainees would experience a spiritual crisis. Then, just as life seemed meaningless, a seminar leader would drop in a new theology that transformed trainees into converts.<p>Erhard and Caserta share many common phrases and ideas: "paradigm power shifts," "What we don't know, we don't know," and so on. They share the Forum, another Erhard seminar that Caserta attended and liked. They share Howard Schor, who once worked for Erhard and, as a "world-renowned consultant," became a managing director of a Caserta concern and, more recently, handled licensing for Spectrum. And they share a willingness to claim outrageous benefits from their services.<p>From 1978 to 1988, according to his promotional material, Caserta used his Apollo Transfer Technology techniques to produce "ten straight years of profitability" in "22 different high-technology entities." Using different math, these turn out to be a single company, Interglobal Technical Services, which Caserta and his brother Frank started in 1976 to provide short-term help for engineering companies. Interglobal was reasonably successful, and they sold it in 1988.<p>Caserta brought his Apollo techniques into his next enterprise, the Caserta Group, which he and his wife, Terri, then 31, formed in 1987. This company was the only business Caserta ever named for himself. It's also his Achilles' heel--the place where Caserta's character would find its most overt expression and the target of the U.S. Attorney's fraud investigation.<p>"He's a very persuasive talker," says David Fox, president of Nestor, a small company that works on handwriting-recognition software. "He told me that once he approved something, raising money was a snap. But after we paid him a fee and did a lot of work on a business plan, he never introduced us to a single investor."<p>Fox's experience of Caserta's "management breakthrough" isn't unique: A two-month Worth probe anticipated--and confirms--many of the U.S. Attorney's allegations. What we found is best summed up by a Caserta client who paid $24,000 but never got financing: "I'm a New Jersey guy," he says, "but this was ten pounds of shit in a five-pound bag."<p>There's good reason for such discontent: The Caserta Group had great difficulty raising money for anyone but itself. Using Erhard-like techniques, it buried clients in meaningless noise. There was a flurry of paperwork to "qualify" from a pool of companies vying for introduction to potential investors--a vision statement, "power questions," a financial profile.<p>And, mirabile dictu, virtually everyone seemed to qualify. Because that's how the Caserta Group got its money. Qualified clients were instructed to show up at the operation's offices with a blank check. Hungry for financing, they complied, only to learn that all the hurdles they'd passed entitled them to... pay Caserta. Up to $25,000, occasionally more, for careful due-diligence services before the Caserta Group felt comfortable presenting the company to possible investors. But according to the U.S. Attorney's complaint and the bleating of angry clients, close vetting was seldom, if ever, performed.<p>By the time they got through this last maze, Caserta Group clients tended to discover they'd found the egress and that there were no investors in sight--but for a price, the Caserta Group was still willing to provide additional consulting services. At this stage, the clients became an angry bunch, mostly at themselves. Says a peeved customer: "This is the biggest mistake I've made in 30 years of being in business. And it's my fault: I got snowed."<p>Caserta was never available when dissatisfied clients called, but in his own way he shared their disappointment. Remembers a former Caserta Group associate: "He used to say, 'One day we'll hit it big. We'll find a company that looks good, we'll take a share, and we'll make millions.'"<p>In 1991, such a company finally appeared: Spectrum.<p>"When we started in 1983, Dallas didn't even have cellular-phone service," says Alan Weinkrantz, Spectrum's first public relations consultant. "I was there with Orville and Wilbur Wright."<p>Well, that's a PR guy speaking. But in its infancy, Spectrum actually did have something quite novel: a way to send data across the airwaves error-free. It later acquired a patent for a nifty cable that could simulate a dial tone for toneless cellular phones, allowing them to be used with the modems, or communication devices, found in many portable computers.<p>Spectrum's dilemma was that it entered the market too soon--in the mid-1980s, no one much needed technology that was great for things like sending faxes from limos. To keep afloat, the company engaged in questionable business practices that failed to produce revenue or new products. In 1991, people close to Caserta say, a struggling Spectrum finally called the Caserta Group after hearing about its amazing ability to raise money--a pretty unlikely scenario. More probably, someone from the Caserta Group cold-called Dana Verrill, Spectrum's affable chief executive, and wondered whether he was looking for money.<p>And was he ever! The previous year, Verrill had seen Spectrum's stock delisted by the Nasdaq trading system for its inability to meet minimum capital requirements. Now he was once again experiencing a capital crunch.<p>Caserta saw the opportunity and went into overdrive. A typical Caserta Group arrangement called for it to get two board seats, a consulting contract, and some stock when it succeeded in obtaining financing for a client. But by the fall of 1991 Caserta had performed an incredible feat of persuasion, even by his standards. Without providing any financing for Spectrum, he and several of his advisors somehow managed to get elected to the company's board. Caserta had his foothold.<p>With Caserta's encouragement, Spectrum soon went looking for an acquisition target with good cash flow--and quickly found it in much bigger Computer Bay, a Wisconsin-based computer reseller that was for sale in part because of its board's dissatisfaction with the founder. According to Joe Frigon, Computer Bay's former top financial officer, Caserta used the takeover to wrest control of Spectrum from founder Verrill when some side issues in the deal went sour almost immediately. A former Spectrum board member says Caserta blamed Verrill for the screw-up. Three months after the Computer Bay deal went through, Verrill was kicked upstairs to chairman and Caserta became Spectrum's CEO.<p>With Computer Bay providing--then as now--80 percent of Spectrum's revenue, Caserta focused on signing up licensees for Spectrum's patents. "Make no mistake about it," he said that November, "Spectrum intends to enforce [our] patent rights and not deprive ourselves of revenues estimated in the billion-dollar-plus area." The method he chose to achieve his goal: pestering established technology companies until they paid for Spectrum's patents--usually just to get him off their backs. <p>The strategy was based on a sad reality. Spectrum's technology was aging badly as more versatile approaches blossomed in wireless data transmission. And there was nothing comparable in Spectrum's pipeline. In fact, there was nothing in Spectrum's pipeline at all: Between 1988 and 1992, the company spent only piddling amounts on research and development.<p>Caserta's talk of a billion-dollar revenue stream was utter nonsense. In 1993, the company's patent portfolio produced only $8.7 million in licensing and royalty fees, a number that will hardly grow much if the deals Caserta touted last year are typical. Spectrum's arrangement with Rockwell International, for example, calls for Spectrum to get $2.5 million plus royalties--but also says half of those royalties will go straight back to Rockwell until the $2.5 million has been repaid. A deal with U.S. Robotics brings Spectrum $1.5 million in fees, plus royalties. But Spectrum agrees to repay $1.25 million to cover advertising costs.<p>This is the shape Spectrum was in when Caserta triggered the AT&T brouhaha. And matters hadn't improved in the months between then and Sculley's appearance on the scene. Just ask workers at Data One, a once-promising systems-integration unit of Spectrum that wilted under Caserta's management. In late summer of 1993, 20 of its employees were summoned to meet with Caserta. The main purpose was to get sales commitments from each employee--the higher, the better.<p>But what the Data One folks found most memorable was Caserta's renewed passion for Werner Erhard's teachings. "He went around the room and asked us one by one, 'Would you take the Forum?'" one employee remembers. "Then we were all asked to close our eyes and think about the Forum."<p>Sculley knew none of this when he stepped before the media as Spectrum's new chairman. Indeed, some of it may still be news to him--just as so many other facts were news to him when the New York Times called on his first day to wonder why he had ever joined Spectrum.<p>In short order, reporter Susan Antilla told him about Spectrum's 1990 delisting and a more recent SEC investigation of Gene Morgan, Spectrum's underwriter. "It sounds like you know more about it than I do at this point," Sculley said sheepishly.<p>His education was about to begin.<p>Believing that few Spectrum officials understood wireless technology, Sculley took on a tutor: Arjun Gupta, who had graduated from Stanford with two degrees in computer science and then gone on to get an M.B.A. and work at the McKinsey consulting firm. Gupta had long dreamed of joining forces with Sculley; after hearing him speak at a conference in early September 1993, Gupta buttonholed his idol. Halfway through the conference, Sculley had to  leave for the airport. Undeterred, Gupta jumped into the car with him--then bought a plane ticket at the airport and talked all the way to Sculley's destination. In a strange twist, this 33-year-old consultant would become the Spectrum chairman's chief advisor and confidant, without ever accepting a dime from Spectrum or Sculley.<p>While Gupta brought Sculley up to speed on industry issues, Spectrum acquired a firm run by Caserta's nephew. It also agreed to buy a consulting company. And at Sculley's direction, it tried to settle many of its outstanding lawsuits, including the shareholder suit from Caserta's AT&T incident.<p>Every new event was accompanied by a Spectrum press release lavishing more attention and praise on Caserta--praise often attributed to the new boss. Meanwhile Sculley seemed missing in action, unavailable to reporters and unwilling to say exactly what he was doing. People started to wonder: Was Sculley the Patty Hearst of high tech?<p>In truth, Sculley and Gupta were traveling extensively and meeting the major players in wireless. But the way Spectrum people read this hermetic friendship, all Gupta really wanted was to separate Sculley from his new job so the pair could go into business together. Caserta was openly skeptical of Gupta's talents--"He's never run anything or managed anyone! What's his experience?" he'd say--but he wasn't about to butt heads with Sculley. This was, after all, the logical time for him to make a graceful exit.<p>Dana Verrill and two other longtime Spectrum executives had already left. Caserta was to be next, so he approached Sculley with an offer. "Do you want Sal, Al, and me to go?" he asked, referring to the company's chief financial officer and an executive vice president. "If you do, we will."<p>In fact, Caserta had already taken preliminary steps to leave. Early on, he had received Sculley's blessing to exercise almost half of his 2 million options, now bloated in value because of the Apple boss's arrival. In November he unloaded them, reaping an $8.6 million payout. There was very little to hold him at Spectrum anymore.<p>By contrast, Sculley was becoming increasingly desperate to keep Caserta around. If Caserta left, he felt, he would be locked in. Huge amounts of Spectrum stock were moving toward him: Without Caserta and his crew aboard, Sculley would look less like an employee--and more like Spectrum's only true owner.<p>How had this happened, he wondered? Did Caserta hire him so he could leave? Just a month into his job, say people familiar with his thinking, Sculley twigged to the real game at Spectrum. It was like a cartoon lightbulb clicking on: This is a race for the doors. And the more Sculley thought about it, the less he wanted to be on the losing side.<p>But how could he justify an exit?<p>In early December, Bloomberg News Service said Spectrum had recorded some future licensing revenue as if it had all been paid--but then spread a balancing payout to the licensee over several years, boosting Spectrum's short-term profit. Arthur Andersen, Spectrum's accountant for a decade, had signed off on the approach, but to Sculley it smacked of aggressive accounting. And back in September, he recalled, Caserta had specifically denied that Spectrum trafficked in such measures.<p>With that, the endgame began.<p>Sculley made it clear he regarded the accounting issue as a valid reason to quit and promptly holed up in the office of his lawyer, Arnold Burns. Caserta and his crew decamped to LeBoeuf, Lamb, Greene & McRae. And Chris Franco, Spectrum's young general counsel, scurried back and forth as a go-between.<p>Franco finally brokered a peace, but only by reminding Sculley that the consequences of leaving would be dire. The executive's arrival had added nearly a quarter-billion dollars to Spectrum's market value, he noted. If Sculley were to leave, the stock would surely drop again and there would be shareholder suits against him--not to mention a suit from Spectrum for breach of contract.<p>Ever conscious of money issues, Sculley backed down. But he still directed KPMG Peat Marwick, which he had hired to replace Arthur Andersen as Spectrum's accountant, to reexamine how the company recorded licensing revenue. He also began focusing on the daily grind at Spectrum, letting Arjun Gupta drift out of the picture.<p>For a while, things appeared almost normal. Sculley looked for a Manhattan office that would accommodate a pared-down Spectrum staff. He and wife Leezy thought up new names for the company. In a mid-January speech to the Massachusetts Software Council he sounded upbeat, joking about his new company's status as an unknown but noting that "there are lots of little companies out there in the wireless world--just as there were in the computer business 15 years ago. So it's an extraordinary opportunity."<p>Then, in late January, Sculley got fresh reasons to leave. The Peat Marwick recommendation was in, and it was grim: Spectrum had to restate its earnings for two quarters, changing a profit into yet another loss. And it wasn't until Sculley embarrassed himself in an interview that he found out--from a reporter--that the SEC was continuing its investigation of Spectrum over <p>the AT&T matter. In fact, he later learned, the investigation had been bumped up to formal status.<p>But no one at Spectrum, he would later claim in court documents, had bothered telling him.<p>Early in February, at Sculley's direction, Spectrum informed the SEC that it would restate its earnings on February 7. The weekend before the announcement, Sculley faced a difficult choice. On one hand, he was on the verge of signing a lease for a new Spectrum headquarters in the Seagram building in Manhattan. He had even settled on an image-cleansing new name for Spectrum: GlobalWave. On the other hand, Sculley no longer trusted Caserta to tell him the truth.<p>Just before the market opened for trading that Monday morning, Sculley submitted his resignation. He also sued Peter Caserta--but not Spectrum--for $10 million. Spectrum promptly upped the ante, countersuing for $300 million. And as Franco had predicted, class-action lawsuits against Spectrum were expanded to include Sculley.<p>For an executive with big expenses and no salary, there wasn't much more that could go wrong.<p>"Despair is the only cure for illusion," writes sociologist Philip Slater. "Without despair, we cannot transfer our allegiance to reality. It is a kind of mourning period for our fantasies."<p>Peter Caserta probably wouldn't understand that. By late March, the feds had moved against the Caserta Group; Caserta took a leave of absence from Spectrum the following day. His successors at Spectrum say he's a man of integrity who will ultimately be vindicated. Right up to the denouement, Spectrum associates described him as ever cheerful, a man who sees blue skies today, bluer skies tomorrow.<p>But most of the other key participants in the Spectrum follies are licking wounds and struggling to become reacquainted with reality. Dana Verrill and two of his key Spectrum associates, for example, are back in Dallas. No more high tech for them--they've hooked up with a small chain of Italian restaurants and hope to take the company public. Then there's Lynn Petronella. She wrestled a $300,000 finder's fee from Spectrum, invested heavily in its stock, and lost $100,000 when the stock tanked on the news of Sculley's departure. Now, with eyes opened, she wants to develop a film called In the Company of Men, about her 7.5 minutes of fame.<p>Spectrum will not be easily healed by new CEO Edward Maskaly, a longtime unpaid advisor to the Caserta Group. In the U.S. Attorney's charges, Maskaly is described as an investor who the Caserta Group claimed was interested in financing a client's company. Apparently, the client never received any financing. Even if his intentions are found to be honorable, however, Maskaly's prior connection to Caserta may prove to be unfortunate, for it perpetuates the link between a company that promotes clear communication and one with a reputation for obscuring it.<p>The Caserta Group, meanwhile, has acquired a new name (the Paradigm Group) and a new owner (John Bohrman, Caserta's son-in-law). But its problems continue--Bohrman was one of those arrested in a recent raid on Paradigm by U.S. postal inspectors. A few days before, he was frantically trying to distance himself from his father-in-law's linguistic technology. "That was Peter's thing," he said. "I'm not into semantics. I tell it like it is. Companies come here to find capital, and I know that. I have no intent to boggle anyone's mind, nor do the people I work with."<p>No one, in all this, fell further or hit the ground harder than John Sculley. He has done what he can to put his lost months at Spectrum behind him, dropping his lawsuit against Caserta when Spectrum dropped its lawsuit against him. (As a condition of the settlement, both Sculley and Caserta agreed not to speak to the press.) But although Sculley is still a defendant in the shareholders' suits, he has told friends he can't bring himself to hate Caserta. He has, however, cooperated with the feds' investigation of Caserta's business.<p>Sculley, at least, has learned something--in this fable there are no victims, only volunteers. <br>
---------------<br>
Jesse Kornbluth has just completed a screenplay based on his book, "Highly Confidential: The Crime and Punishment of Michael Milken."<p>Reporting assistant: Emanuel Howard<p><p>

