	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/05-Financial Noise Obscures Market Trends</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
Short-term moves aren't useful indicators now<p>By Jim Jubak<p>Where are interest rates headed? Is inflation coming back? Divining answers to those questions is particularly difficult when the various markets send mixed messages, as they are doing now. Long-term investors watching the short-term news may be reading the wrong signs.<p>Interest rates on 30-year bonds have climbed almost without pause since the Fed first boosted rates on February 4. Meanwhile, gold, the traditional inflation hedge, actually declined in price. The bond market seems to be believe that the Fed sees inflation everywhere. The gold market, however, seems to be saying that inflation isn't really a worry.<p>Which market should you believe? We'll go with the gold. Why? There's a high level of leverage in the bond market now. According to the Federal Reserve Bank of New York, clients of the  dealers who sell government bonds had borrowed approximately $180 billion as of March. The collateral on these government-bond borrowings is - you guessed it - more government bonds, which fluctuate in value. That kind of pyramid magnifies profits when investors guess right, but also boosts losses when they guess wrong. As a result, the short-term swings of the bond market, which come as the pros try to avoid big losses when rates don't behave, are likely to be overdone. Wall Street carries every trend to extremes.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Economy, Bond Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

