	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>93/11-How to Succeed in Business Without Leaving Home</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
Five Domestic Policies that Work<p>By Jean Godfrey-June<p>In his 1982 best-seller, megatrends, John Naisbitt noted that more and more people were choosing to forgo the camaraderie of office life to work at home. This was one trend, he figured, that wasn't going anywhere. Who, after all, would choose social isolation when they could spend their days under the glaze of fluorescent lights, drinking bad coffee and fighting petty corporate battles? <p>Quite a few people, actually. The Bureau of Labor Statistics estimates that some 20 million workers across America commute no farther than down a hallway or up a flight of stairs.That number is growing by as much as 13 percent annually, as sophisticated desktop computers, modem lines, and fax machines change the nature of the traditional office. Many of these workers are self-employed--they have even earned their own demographic moniker, "lone eagles"--but organization men and women are getting a chance to unbutton their collars, too. According to LINK Resources, a research and consulting firm in Manhattan, 7.6 million company employees work at home at least part-time. Jay Chiat, who owns Chiat/Day, a Los Angeles-based advertising firm, is all but kicking his employees out of the office. He is refitting the agency's headquarters as a "virtual" office, which means that most of the people who work there only need to drop by for meetings. Otherwise, their work space is wherever their notebook computer happens to be. "People can be creative anywhere,"Chiat says. "I don't care, as long as the work is good."<p>As the nature of work changes, the very nature of the home office is changing, too. Increasingly, a home office is not just an afterthought but an integral part of home design. We have chosen five lone eagles who have transformed their homes into stylish offices. Here's a look inside.<p>
THE ART DEALER<p>William Beadleston left big-city life seven years ago to live in a log cabin in the Rocky Mountains. Not, at first blush, a wise move for an international art dealer. But Beadleston's log cabin is in fact a palatial 6,000-square-foot home he designed himself, and it's located in Aspen, Colorado, in the heart of the world's least-isolated remote mountain valley. Beadleston buys and sells pieces by artists such as Picasso and Miro. To stay in touch with the market, he keeps an office in New York and works with dealers all over the world to orchestrate purchases for collectors and museums. His office is on a hilltop 50 yards from his home. He's usually on the phone to Europe early in the morning and doing business with Japanese clients late into the evening. And the hours in between? "If it's a nice day, I'll go hiking or skiing." <p>
THE FASHION DESIGNER<p>While her colleagues duke it out on seventh avenue, fashion designer Han Feng stays home. Set in an apartment high among the turrets of Manhattan's landmark Ansonia building (you might recognize it from the movie Single White Female), her combination home, showroom, office, and design space seems a world away from the hustle and bustle of the rag trade. Whereas most designers attempt to keep clients away from their work areas, Feng's spaces flow right into each other. A cook prepares lunch in the kitchen while Feng's six employees laugh and gossip at their workstations. "It's comfortable," says Feng, who sees her off-the-beaten-path location as an asset. "Everyone said the fashion people wouldn't come, but they have." Only two years in business and Feng's designs have been featured in the windows of such high-end retailers as Saks Fifth Avenue. She has also appeared in Vogue, Harper's Bazaar, and the New York Times.<p>After emigrating from China in 1985 with her American husband, banker Stuart Schonberger (they met when he was teaching English in her hometown of Hangzhou), Feng started small with scarves and home accessories. She moved quickly to the simple, fluid clothes that are now her trademark. The informality of the home office fits her approach to design: "I start with a square or an oblong shape for all of my pieces," she says. "People's bodies give the clothes shape."<p>
THE CONSULTANT<p>Joe Boyd and his wife, DeAnna, who run J.A. Boyd & Associates, a construction-management and litigation-support firm based in Northern California, spend a good part of their workday out of the office. On the porch, that is, overlooking vineyard-dotted Napa Valley. And when they need to be further afield visiting clients on-site, for instance, their private plane is at an airstrip just three quarters of a mile away. <p>For nearly 30 years, the Boyds ran their business out of an office in San Francisco. But two and a half years ago, when they realized that computer technology could untether them from the office, they hired San Francisco architect Steve Geiszler to design a home and office that could work as one. The result: A three-room office suite--containing an office, library, and "technology room"--connected to the house by a long hallway. The office walls are covered by custom paneling and the rooms are filled with hand-painted furniture, but the signature feature is the deck, which has hookups for phone, fax, and computer. <p>"I'm out here, under the trees, enjoying the view and working most nice days," Boyd says. "It's an incredible way to live."<p>
THE TRADER<p>In his 20s, Mike Meldeau drove race cars. In his 30s, he built a company that made high-performance tires. Now, at age 47, he trades stocks. If that sounds like a comedown, consider the fact that his home office is a 104-foot luxury yacht, the Temptation, which he sails through the Bahamas.<p>Since selling his tire business to <a name="NYSE:GT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10668"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Goodyear</b></a> in 1991, Meldeau has developed a substantial stock portfolio, which he trades himself, whether in port at Marsh Harbour, Abaco, the Bahamas, or anchored off the shores of a deserted island. "I was frustrated trying to find someone who could manage the portfolio better than me," he says. "And I love trading. I meet other yachtsmen and get tips I wouldn't normally run across--many of these people are involved with major corporations."<p>Even from an offshore anchorage, Meldeau stays as informed as anyone on Wall Street--though his monthly phone bills run upwards of $5,000. He is the first person to receive real-time stock information on a yacht, thanks to a satellite hookup from Data Broadcasting. Like millions of investors, he watches CNBC compulsively.<p>And how does Meldeau structure his trading day? That's easy, he says: "It depends on the weather."<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Employment, Small Business Ownership, Art Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
