	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 93/09-Ten Stocks for Tough Times</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b> </b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>93/09-Ten Stocks for Tough Times</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 <p><a name="NYSE:ABS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10049"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Albertson's</b></a> 
ABS-$53
The company operates some 650 retail grocery stores, primarily in the West. Albertson's is a favorite of Brian Suher, a vice-president at Piper Jaffray Inc., because of the company's 15-year string of sharp yearly increases in revenue, profit, and dividends. Based in Boise, Idaho, Albertson's sells many of the necessary items in the family budget. Although it has a high price-to-earnings of 22 (about the current market average), its low debt (24 percent of assets) puts Albertson's far ahead of its largest competitor, Safeway, which is still loaded with mountains of LBO financing. During the 1987 crash, Albertson's took but five months to come back to its pre-crash level.<p><a name="NYSE:CLX"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10354"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Clorox</b></a>
CLX-$55
Investors have to admire any company that's willing to take a securities analyst out to lunch on the day the stock market crashes. Growth in earnings and dividends has been steady, the company's product is not a big-ticket item, and people buy cleaning products even in a depression. Plus, the company has very little debt. The dividend: 3.7 percent.<p><a name="NYSE:KO"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10359"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Coca-Cola</b></a> 
KO-$44
The company's one bonehead move__messing with Coke in 1985__was shrugged off by investors, and growth in revenue, profit, and dividends has been uninterrupted for two decades. Foreign operations account for two-thirds of the business, meaning global diversification. The stock has split three times in the last seven years, but it has been under pressure lately__as have all brand names: Coca-Cola hasn't moved since 1992. <p><a name="NYSE:CPQ"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10381"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Compaq Computer</b></a>
CPQ-$48
One of the best performers of 1987, Compaq makes <a name="NYSE:IBM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10796"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>IBM</b></a>-compatible personal computers. But that's where the similarity between Compaq and Big Blue ends. Compaq is heading towards record earnings this year, according to Value Line. Yet the stock is selling at half the market multiple__a P/E of just 10 and price-to-book of 1.3. The stock had its correction recently when the company's earnings were cut from $4.87 per share in 1990 to $2.62 in 1991. But Value Line is forecasting $4.90 in 1993. <p><a name="NYSE:EFS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11872"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Enhance Financial Services</b></a>
EFS-$19
Enhance is a reinsurer of municipal bonds. The stock sells at about eight times earnings and right at book value. With taxes going up, says Pittsburgh money manager David Hunter, "municipal finance is here to stay." <p><a name="NASD:INTC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13787"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Intel</b></a>
INTC-53
A leading semiconductor maker based in Santa Clara, California, Intel was one of the best-performing stocks in 1987. After some rocky times in the mid-1980s, Intel's profitability is accelerating, tracking the booming worldwide sales of personal computers. In the semiconductor industry nearly all costs are fixed, so when sales get above break-even, everything drops to the bottom line. With continuing growth forecast for the 1990s, Intel is a cheap stock with a price-to-earnings ratio of just 11. <p><a name="NYSE:KM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10830"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Kmart</b></a>
KM-$20
Here's a good example of a retailer that's getting dragged down by softer earnings forecasts throughout the industry. Since peaking at $28 in late 1992, Kmart shares have sagged to $20. At just nine times earnings and 1.2 times book value, Kmart stock is discount merchandise. Kmart, with its 4.2 percent dividend, shouldn't be confused with Wal-Mart, which still sells at a price-to-earnings ratio of about 30. <p><a name="NYSE:PFE"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11175"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Pfizer</b></a>
PFE-$64
Pharmaceutical stocks have had a huge correction," says Tom Mudge, vice-president of equity research at Bailard, Biehl & Kaiser in San Mateo, California. "One concern is that drug companies won't be able to raise their prices under a new health-care system. But if you can sell enough new drugs, particularly overseas, then raising prices isn't that important." Pfizer is selling below the market multiple, historically unheard of for drug stocks. It has rarely sold below a steep premium during the past two decades. And it has many new drugs in development, which is more than can be said for most industry leaders.<p><a name="NYSE:RD"></a><b>Royal Dutch/Shell</b>
RD-$91
This worldwide oil company has "tremendous free cash flow," says Scott Black of Delphi Management. The stock sells at about 15 times earnings, about seven times cash flow, and only 1.5 times book value. That cash flow is largely responsible for Royal Dutch's impressive 5.2 percent dividend. What's more, oil is an inflation hedge, and, of course, oil stocks did very well during the 1970s.<p><a name="NYSE:WEC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11645"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Wisconsin Energy</b></a>
WEC-$27
Wisconsin Energy barely felt the 1987 stock-market crash, rebounding to pre-crash levels by year-end. It sells at slightly under the market multiple, yields a 5 percent dividend, and has smooth-as-silk price appreciation. Wisconsin Energy is a vanilla utility, with none of the unwise diversification that has harmed many in its industry. Dividends have risen every year since the mid-1970s. Rate increases percolate nicely, too, so earnings and dividends are likely to continue upward. <p> <p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Stock Investing Strategies

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
