	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 93/09-Sacred Cows</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>

				<img src="">	
				<p>
				<font size=5><b>Sacred Cows</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>93/09-Sacred Cows</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						September 1993 
<p>
Worth magazine/Departments  
<p>
 SACRED COWS  
<p>
 By John Rothchild  
<p>
 I had a chat with Joe Oddlot the other day. we go way back,
Oddlot and me, back to the days when a broker was a broker and
a good investment was a stock. Those days, of course, are long
gone. A broker hasn't been a broker since they all became financial
consultants in a mass ceremony in the 1970s, when Merrill Lynch
was still bullish on America.  
<p>
 But I'm getting ahead of myself. Oddlot was still a broker the
first time he phoned me up, out of the blue, on my private line.
No friend or relative, lost or otherwise, has ever gushed at
the sound of my hello the way Oddlot did. And after the gushing
stopped, the serious business of pitching began. He told me that
IBM was poised for an upward move, and that he had identified
me as the kind of highly successful person who could benefit
from opening an account and buying some IBM from him.  
<p>
 We met at a bar with a happy hour, where the meatballs on toothpicks
were free. Oddlot said that his purpose in life was to put highly
successful people like me, who could make their own investment
decisions, into stocks like IBM, which were poised for an upward
move. "It sounds like you're reading from a script," I said.<p>
<p>
 He didn't respond at first, but after his third beer he admitted
that he'd been quoting from "Opening Lines for Equities," which
he'd memorized in broker's school.   
<p>
 I complimented him on his diligence: Memorization has always
impressed me. But I said that since I was only moderately successful
and my wife made most of my decisions, all his efforts would
be wasted on me. By then, I'd had my fill of free meatballs and
Oddlot had picked up the bar tab.   
<p>
 Time went by, and the stock market went up and down, and one
day while browsing through my Rolodex I found Oddlot's number.
This reminded me how far IBM had fallen off the edge of its upward
move. In fact, the stock price was half what it had been when
Oddlot first mentioned it.  
<p>
 I dialed Oddlot's number for old time's sake, and also to find
out if IBM was doubly poised for an upward move. A secretary
told me Oddlot no longer worked for Merrill Lynch. He'd gone
to Prudential-Bache.  
<p>
 So I called Prudential-Bache and asked for Oddlot. He didn't
seem to remember me. I reminded him about the happy hour we'd
spent eating free meatballs on toothpicks. "They don't serve
the meatballs anymore," he said. "Now they have spicy shrimp."<p>
<p>
 So we met for spicy shrimp. "Just out of curiosity," I said,
"I wonder if you're still recommending IBM to highly successful
people who can make their own investment decisions?"  
<p>
 "I couldn't do that," he said. "It would be wrong."  
<p>
 "You sound like President Nixon," I said. "But you're not a
crook긏ou're a broker."  
<p>
 "Not anymore, I'm not긅ow I'm a financial consultant. As your
financial consultant, I don't advise you to buy a single stock
before we have built up a relationship." He became quite serious.
"Stocks are fickle, but a good relationship can last a lifetime.
As a matter of fact, I'd like to begin to build a relationship
with you."  
<p>
 "I didn't know you cared," I said, but we set up a second meeting
at his office to discuss my long-term financial goals. "What
are your long-term financial goals?" he asked. "More money,"
I said, but that wasn't enough. He had me fill out a questionnaire
in which I told all: my net worth, my insurance coverage, my
monthly mortgage payment, and the like. At the end of an hour,
Joe Oddlot knew more about my private business than my parents,
my sister, or any of my friends.  
<p>
 "Funny thing about this relationship," I said. "You know all
about me긊he monthly tax bite for my house, the cost of my kids'
braces, everything. But I know zilch about you, except that you
wear suspenders and you dine out on happy hours." So he told
me a little bit about himself. He hadn't always been part of
America's investment community. For one unhappy spell between
Merrill Lynch and Prudential-Bache, he'd worked in a shoe store,
helping clients with their podiatric goals.  
<p>
 Oddlot punched all my numbers into his desktop computer, which
determined that my financial goals would best be met by my investing
in an oil-and-gas limited partnership. "What about all the stocks
that are poised for an upward move?" I asked. "A limited partnership
is better than a stock," Oddlot said. "It is a product. A product
has tax benefits, and is perfectly suited to a person with your
financial profile and long-term financial goals."  
<p>
 Somehow, the idea of an-oil-and gas limited partnership made
me think of Texas, which made me think of Lyndon Johnson, who
was exposed by author Robert Caro as a conniving, foul-mouthed
boor who stole votes and rigged elections. "I can't buy your
product," I told Oddlot, "because I don't trust Lyndon Johnson."
This did not help our relationship-building.  
<p>
 In fact, I didn't hear from Oddlot again. Then recently, I saw
a Prudential ad on TV (they'd taken away the hyphen Bache). The
ad showed a man about to dive into an empty swimming pool and
break his neck because he could no longer support himself on
his life savings. Apparently, he would have been spared this
agonizing death if he'd opened an account with Prudential, where
the most important thing they earn is our trust.  
<p>
 This ad reminded me of the oil-and-gas limited partnerships
that Oddlot had tried to sell me way back when, and of the many
Prudential clients who had filed class-action suits to recover
their life savings, which were lost when the oil-and-gas product
failed to help them achieve their long-term financial goals.<p>
<p>
 Once again I contacted Oddlot, and I asked him if we could start
rebuilding our relationship over a bowl of spicy shrimp. "It's
not spicy shrimp anymore," he said. "It's tapas."  
<p>
 So we met over tapas. After his second beer, Oddlot said he
was sick of tapas, having taken five all-expenses-paid trips
to Barcelona, Seville, and Madrid as rewards for selling the
most product in five different months. "That's what I wanted
to talk to you about," I said. "The oil-and-gas product. Could
it be poised for an upward move?"  
<p>
 Oddlot said he was no longer in the business of recommending
products or in the business of building relationships. Now he
was in the business of earning trust. And the best way to earn
my trust, he said, was to make sure my money was getting all
the attention it so richly needed and deserved, not from him
but from a reputable money manager with a proven track record.
He gave me a list of money managers approved by Prudential. <p>
<p>
 "What's in this for you?" I asked. After his fourth beer, he
told me. By connecting me with an approved money manager, he
would get an up-front commission plus a "trailing fee" paid every
year for as long as I stuck with the manager. This would help
Oddlot reach his financial goal of steady income그nd keep him
out of the shoe store.  
<p><p>
<p>
Contributing editor John Rothchild is the author of Going for
Broke (Penguin/Viking), the story of financier Robert Campeau.<p>
<p>
  <hr>  
