	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>97/01S-1996 Picks Revisited</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Below, the pros (minus Al Frank, who joined the panel in 1996) evaluate their picks from last year. The numbers following company names are the total returns. As always, the stock picker may have sold shares after the publishing deadline.<p>
Preston Athey<br>
<a name="NASD:ELRC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13294"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Electro Rent</b></a>  +13.6%
<a name="NASD:CMRO"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13033"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Comarco</b></a>  +19.1%
Electro Rent is the largest holding in my fund. It's a great value and still undiscovered by Wall Street analysts. Comarco may not be the slam-dunk value it was in 1996, but it's still a solid hold with 20 percent growth potential. <p>
James Craig<br>
EDS  -9.7%
<a name="NYSE:CCI"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10345"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Citicorp</b></a>  +43%
I've reduced my position in data-processing giant EDS, but I still hold it and Citicorp. <p>
Shelby Davis<br>
<a name="NYSE:EQ"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13307"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Equitable</b></a>  -2.7%
<a name="NYSE:GM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10640"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>General Motors</b></a>  +13.2%
I still hold the stocks and like the companies, but these turnaround stories have developed slowly. Reorganizations don't always hew to the schedule we'd like them to. <p>
Daniel Leonard<br>
<a name="NYSE:CHK"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12049"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Chesapeake Energy</b></a>  +209%
<a name="NYSE:NEC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11050"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Natl. Education</b></a>  +106.4%
Both are keepers for 1997. Oil-and-gas explorer Chesapeake keeps hitting new wells and growing rapidly. National Education has excellent products and services and is just now scratching the surface of the educational-software market. <p>
Jim McCamant<br>
<a name="NASD:SMTG"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13506"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Somatogen</b></a>  -23.4%
<a name="NASD:ISIP"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14081"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Isis Pharm</b></a>.  +42.9%
Somatogen's stock rose 65 percent in 1996 before falling because of temporary delays in clinical trials. I'm holding. Isis's progress in inflammation and anti-cancer treatments is promising, and we're raising our buy limit to $20 a share.<p>
Ralph Wanger<br>
Chuck McQuaid 
<a name="NYSE:OAK"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11108"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Oak Industries</b></a> +5.2% 
<a name="NASD:LBTYA"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=51395"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Liberty Media</b></a>  -8%
New products will help Oak in 1997. We took some gains but continue to hold. We're holding Liberty because, no matter who wins the war between cable and satellite, penetration of specialized programming will increase. <p>
Michael Murphy<br>
<a name="NASD:ADSK"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12689"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Autodesk</b></a>  -34.5%
<a name="NASD:EUPH"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=44511"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Euphonix </b></a> -44.1%
We still like both of these stocks. Autodesk is a good buy, despite temporary problems. Euphonix has encountered delays in a line of promising new broadcast products, but we're holding on and expecting higher revenues in 1997. <p>
William Nasgovitz<br>
<a name="NYSE:SKO"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13430"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>ShopKo Stores</b></a>  +45.1%
<a name="NASD:DESI"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13199"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Designs</b></a>  -23.8%
I'm holding these stocks. ShopKo is building a solid franchise in the rapidly consolidating pharmacy industry. Apparel retailer Designs upgraded its newly acquired Boston Traders line of stores, and I expect better earnings in 1997. <p>
Louis Navellier<br>
<a name="NASD:SMTC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12316"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Semtech</b></a>  -51% 
<a name="NASD:ZIGO"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=15204"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Zygo</b></a>  +22.4%
I've sold Semtech because its earnings slowed toward the end of the year, and it now has a negative risk-reward ratio. Zygo still has attractive fundamentals, but the stock is too volatile now, and I've sold it as well. <p>
Eric Ryback<br>
<a name="NASD:MCOM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=15760"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Metricom</b></a>  -10.3%
<a name="NASD:CHRS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12948"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Charming Shoppes</b></a>  +100%
I still own these two stocks. Charming Shoppes' new management is reducing debt and turning the stores around. Metricom just opened new wireless systems in Seattle and Washington, D.C., raising its subscriber base substantially. <p>
Donald Yacktman<br>
<a name="NYSE:UAM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=42135"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>United Asset Mgmt</b></a>. +34% 
<a name="NYSE:FNQ"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=15674"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Franklin Quest</b></a>  +7.3%
UAM is still the second-biggest holding in my account, and I can't buy anymore, although I would if I could. Franklin Quest has produced disappointing net income, but I still like the company and recommend it again.<p>
Data from 11/30/95 to 10/31/96. Source: Zacks Investment Research.<p>
KEYWORDS:
prediction, stock picks, expert

					</font>
