<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/08-Letters</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/08-Letters</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Whom Do You Trust?
I really enjoyed "can this market be trusted?" by 
Jim Jubak (May). I believe it was Sir Isaac Newton who led us to the phrase "What goes up must come down," and then a distant relative, 
Alfred E. Neuman, gave us "What, me worry?" Somehow, I survive 
in the current market keeping these two axioms in mind.
Jack Lefkowith
Wyomissing, Pennsylvania<p>Jim Jubak makes historical comparisons to determine market valuation. Using these measures, he suggests that the current market is overvalued. He then undermines this assertion by stating that current conditions have rendered such measures "irrelevant." He goes on to attribute the spectacular rise of the market to the massive amounts of cash that have poured into equities, yet he admits that no evidence of such a relationship exists. While I don't disagree with his thesis, Jubak seems to contradict himself throughout the piece.
Andrew Glocker
St. Louis Park, Minnesota<p>Credit Revolution
Did Mike Steere, the writer of "Soul of the Revolver" (May), have his tongue in his cheek? I have had one credit card for more decades than I care to count. Never have I paid a charge for an open balance. According to Steere, I should not be a target for more credit cards. So why do I receive, at least twice a month, solicitations from every card issuer in the country to have me accept another credit card?
V. Porter
Boca Raton, Florida<p>I was once a credit-card transactor, but ever since creditors introduced balance transfers into the interest-rate wars, I've been a kiter -- I regularly incur enormous balances (for my income level) and cycle them among several high-limit cards. I clear each balance every month by transferring it within the grace period; needless to say, by being such a "good" customer, I've been rewarded with limits that are not even remotely commensurate with my actual ability to pay. No matter -- since I never accrue interest, paying off my principal would be a waste of money! To suit my purposes, a credit card must carry no annual fee, offer the option of transferring balances as a regular service (cards with onetime or infrequent special offers to consolidate debt are of limited use), charge no transaction fee for the transfer, and allow for a grace period on balance transfers. These bank cards are my Holy Grail, as much as the high-income revolver is the debt pushers'. By applying a modicum of forethought to such specifications as billing cycles and credit limits, any sports fan with enough credit cards can watch thousands of games on his new 48-inch TV while the bill bounces around in plastic land ad infinitum! Someone with a less cavalier attitude, who fears each bank might eventually seal the kiters' loophole by eliminating any of the above criteria, can still take advantage of this method by making a large bank deposit with one of his cards' convenience checks. He can save for the TV with the interest he earns, secure in the knowledge that the debt can be paid in full if need be. True, the wellspring of balance transfers may dry up someday, but the interest-free deferral of financial obligations for an indefinite period of time is surely a more prudent strategy than revolving. And if it never stops, the kiter enjoys a free lunch courtesy of the consumer-credit industry!
Rob Leder
Stamford, Connecticut<p>Notes From Underground
Jim Rogers's column "Safety Nyet" (May) reminds me of the two-inch pile of Moscow subway bonds I inherited. Purchased in 1909 by a relative now long deceased, these bonds will probably never have value except as wall decorations. Russian investments won't be in my portfolio.
Daniel C. Bolger
Lancaster, Ohio<p>Digital Equipment
After reading "Little By Little" ("Review," May), I wondered if Laurence Hooper had used any of the personal digital assistants he discusses. In a case smaller than my old Filofax, I carry an Apple Message Pad 120, a PC-card modem, a charger, and cables. If Hooper insists on carrying a desktop charger and keyboard, he's missed the point of the MP 120. It also does just fine recognizing my handwriting and allows me to accomplish some tasks more effectively than ever, and I've been using computers since 1967.
David Howe
Milford, Massachusetts<p>Bonds to Stay
Susan Lee's "Bonds Away!" (May) misleads the small investor. How can transaction costs be killers when you can buy or sell five bonds for less than $40 or ten bonds for only $50? I also disagree that bond investing isn't for amateurs. I can't believe bond managers concur with Eduardo Haim when he says it's almost impossible for nonprofessionals to do well on their own. Since the mid-1970s, more than half my investments have been through the bond market, with only one loser: a savings-and-loan bond. As interest rates rise, bond prices fall, and vice versa. I've bought and sold numerous issues more than once, and every day you own a bond, you earn the coupon rate of that issue.
Walter G. Shaver
Phoenix, Arizona<p>The Securities and Exchange Commission has launched an investigation into L.B. Import Export, a company recently looked into by the Advocate (May). Several readers had sent money directly to L.B., expecting to receive stock, and found that the company was apparently nonexistent.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Bond Investing, Banking Industry, International Investing, Stock Market Trends

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

