	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/08-Gushing Over Oil & Gas Stocks</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						By Anne Field<p>Energy stocks climbed 16 percent in the six months ended May 15 -- but it's not too late to tank up. Wall Street has shunned many independent oil and gas producers because of small size or poor past performance. Low inventories and high demand should continue to lift energy prices, making these producers a good bet. In the first quarter of 1996, the spot natural-gas price rose to $3.17 per thousand cubic feet from $1.34 the year before, and oil leaped from $19.79 a barrel to $24. Gas could hit five dollars by 2010, and oil could double, says First Albany's Michael Smolinski. <p><p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
