	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/08-The New Blue Chips Revisited</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Our old system was good at picking stocks headed up -- this version adds a better way to avoid stocks going down.<p>By Jim Jubak<p>In our June 1994 issue,we set out to identify the new blue chips. We picked 50 stocks that met the definition of blue chip as investors have understood it for most of the 20th century. To merit inclusion on our list, a stock had to provide steady capital gains, growing dividends, and rock-solid safety. These were the characteristics that made the blue-chip stocks of yesteryear so highly prized that they were often passed from generation to generation. At the same time, we tried to adapt those timeless goals to today's
fast-paced global economy. That battleground has become so competitive that even a blue chip can no longer coast on its name or balance sheet.<p>So how did that list do? From May 6, 1994, the earliest date any reader could have acted on our recommendations, through May 17, 1996, our picks returned 46.4 percent, including reinvested dividends.<p>That's not bad at all for a group of stocks selected in large part for their safety and low risk.<p>Yes, the Standard & Poor's 500 Stock Index did even better during the same period, returning an amazing 57.3 percent. But in a red-hot market -- such as the one that ruled 1995 and the first five months of 1996 -- blue-chip stocks should climb more slowly than the broad index. It's a price well worth paying as long as they live up to their promise of remaining more buoyant when the wider market turns down.<p>The only thing that troubled us about our earlier list was that six stocks actually showed negative returns. H&R Block lost 12.3 percent, <a name="NYSE:SUP"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12352"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Superior Industries International</b></a> was down 13.2 percent, and <a name="NASD:CBRL"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13128"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Cracker Barrel Old Country Store</b></a> fell 4.8 percent. Also, a few of our 50 made only minimal gains. <a name="NASD:AGREA"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12591"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>American Greetings</b></a> and <a name="NASD:ASAI"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12682"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Atlantic Southeast Airlines</b></a> returned just 1.8 percent and 2.9 percent, respectively. Even <a name="NYSE:RBD"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11294"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Rubbermaid</b></a>, a company whose earnings per share had increased every year for more than a decade, suddenly faltered in 1995. Rubbermaid's earnings fell almost 30 percent, and the stock returned only 12 percent during the period of our study.<p>So even though our system delivered high returns, as intended, in a soaring market, we decided to make a few modifications to further improve the safety and predictability of our choices. The result, we believe, is a system that maintains the heart of the method developed in 1994 but gives more attention to the specific competitive advantages of each company. In addition to our earlier insistence on size, financial strength, and growth, our newest blue chips are market leaders and low-cost producers, are gaining market share at the expense of competitors, and have readily identifiable sources of future growth.<p>We began our 1996 search for the new blue chips with data from S&P's Compustat and the Frank Russell Co. of Tacoma, Washington, the investment research firm that produces the Russell stock-market indexes. Our research universe comprised the 500 stocks with the largest market capitalization -- size isn't everything, but it still provides an edge and often indicates a company's financial strength. We asked Compustat for data that measured each company's growth and profitability: growth rates in earnings, sales, and dividends and profitability in terms of gross and operating margins. We also asked for the standard deviation of earnings (a measure of the variability of earnings) over the past five years. And we asked Compustat to calculate how well an investor would have done holding the stock for the past five years.<p>Using these data, we applied the series of screens that we designed in 1994 to eliminate companies that couldn't jump simple hurdles. (We used the characteristics of the companies in the Russell 1000 to set the level of each hurdle.) We eliminated companies whose earnings per share had grown more slowly than the 5 percent annual growth rate (including inflation) of the U.S. economy as a whole. That knocked out, among others, defense contractors <a name="NYSE:GD"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10633"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>General Dynamics</b></a> and <a name="NYSE:NOC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11093"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Northrop Grumman</b></a>. Another screen allowed us to discard companies, such as <a name="NYSE:F"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10597"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Ford Motor</b></a>, that had shown a big slowdown in the growth of earnings in the past 12 months.<p>A third screen removed companies whose operating profit margins had declined over the past five years. Some of the companies eliminated at this stage, such as publisher <a name="NYSE:TMC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11483"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Times Mirror</b></a>, were obvious candidates. Others, such as computer makers <a name="NASD:SUNW"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14833"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Sun Microsystems</b></a> and <a name="NYSE:CPQ"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10381"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Compaq Computer</b></a>, were surprises -- they were the victims of falling computer prices.<p>The next screen eliminated companies whose stocks had trailed the 14.95 percent annual average return on the S&P 500 over the past five years. Finally, we dropped companies with weak balance sheets (rated B or lower by S&P), companies with highly variable earnings, and companies that had cut their dividends in the past five years.<p>Only 199 stocks passed these tests.<p>Then, in a step new for 1996, we looked at each of the remaining companies in detail. Was there evidence that past success could be duplicated in the future? Could we identify of new growth? How likely is it that a company can successfully defend -- or even expand -- its margins? On the negative side, we looked for declining market share, overcapacity in an industry, and management complacency.<p>More than any of the screens we'd designed, this subjective review searched for trends that would make (or fail to make) past growth in corporate earnings sustainable -- and more predictable to an investor.<p>Our 1994 screens didn't clearly identify dangers that lurked in the future of some companies with illustrious pasts. Not all events are predictable, of course. We couldn't have known that an Atlantic Southeast Airlines plane would crash in August 1995. But we should have considered the airline's lengthy and expensive transition to jets from turboprops for its business customers. We didn't pick up on the implications for Rubbermaid of <a name="NYSE:WMT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11600"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Wal-Mart</b></a>'s resistance to higher prices on plastic household products. Nor did we consider the risk in Superior Industries' dependence on <a name="NYSE:GM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10640"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>General Motors</b></a> and Ford in the relatively volatile market for specialized wheels.<p>Our subjective study should significantly improve the quality of our latest picks. It led us to eliminate recent hot performers, such as motorcycle maker <a name="NYSE:HDI"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10706"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Harley-Davidson</b></a>, when we saw evidence of developing pricing pressures. We dismissed otherwise attractive stocks, such as <a name="NYSE:CSC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10385"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Computer Sciences</b></a>, because a company was not a clear market leader. We looked at the pattern of earnings year by year to see how companies behaved when the economy slowed as 
a whole and when their industry turned down. We rejected companies, such as <a name="NYSE:CLX"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10354"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Clorox</b></a>, that had prospered because of turnarounds that now essentially appear to have run out of steam.<p>This stage eliminated 84 stocks.<p>To arrive at our final 50, we determined which of the remaining 115 companies had a combination of traits most likely to result in growth, safety, and predictability. Using a system that awarded points on a scale of 1 to 100 for increases in earnings per share, sales, dividends, and profitability, we ranked our finalists. (Yields have continued to decline in this market, so this year we didn't automatically eliminate stocks without dividends. The safety aorded an investor by a yield of 1 percent seems an insufficient reason by itself for preferring a stock.) We added points to the scores of companies that are market leaders, are stealing business from competitors, or are low-cost manufacturers or retailers, as defined by analysts.<p>The final list of 50 is both predictable and surprising. Thirteen companies return from the 1994 list: <a name="NYSE:AUD"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10148"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Automatic Data Processing</b></a>, <a name="NASD:CTAS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12979"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Cintas</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:KO"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10359"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Coca-Cola</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:GPS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11469"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Gap</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:G"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10655"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Gillette</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:HD"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11470"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Home Depot</b></a>, <a name="NASD:INTC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13787"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Intel</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:JNJ"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10824"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Johnson & Johnson</b></a>, <a name="NASD:LLTC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13973"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Linear Technology</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:MCD"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10974"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>McDonald's</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:OMC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14326"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Omnicom Group</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:SHW"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11350"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Sherwin-Williams</b></a>, and <a name="NYSE:WIN"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11642"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Winn-Dixie</b></a>.<p>The newcomers include technology giants, such as <a name="NASD:CSCO"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13494"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Cisco Systems</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:HWP"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10723"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Hewlett-Packard</b></a>, and <a name="NASD:MSFT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14120"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Microsoft</b></a>. In each case, the high risk associated with fast growth is mitigated by the company's dominance of a market sector (networking, computer printers, and software operating systems, respectively). Other newcomers are hardly household names, but <a name="NASD:AMAT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12647"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Applied Materials</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:AVY"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10150"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Avery Dennison</b></a>, and <a name="NYSE:DBD"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10460"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Diebold</b></a> each leads its industry. These companies made the list because leadership gives a company a significant edge and assures the investor of greater predictability in earnings. Diebold's automatic-teller machines, for example, continue to capture market share as banks close branches run by humans and install ATMs.<p>Other companies, such as <a name="NYSE:MA"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10969"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>May Department Stores</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:NUE"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11098"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Nucor</b></a>, and <a name="NYSE:LUV"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11377"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Southwest Airlines</b></a>, pursue business strategies of demonstrated success. May will bring its low costs to the soon-to-be-acquired Strawbridge & Clothier chain. <a name="NYSE:NUE"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11098"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Nucor</b></a> has become the fourth-largest U.S. steelmaker by aggressively using the newest technology to keep costs low. Southwest has created a low-cost structure that none of its competitors can match.<p>As we did in 1994, we kept stock price out of the selection method. This is a list of stocks that a blue-chip investor may want to own but not necessarily want to buy tomorrow. In the table that follows, we've rated each stock for timeliness (how attractive they are right now). Stocks that seem fully priced to us (wait to buy them) get one star. Stocks that seem fairly priced receive two stars. Stocks with three stars represent clear buys at their current price.<p>To arrive at these ratings, we considered the five-year range of each stock's price-to-earnings ratio in the context of the current market. Stocks at the low end of their five-year range generally were given better ratings than those at the high end. We made exceptions only when a stock appeared to have a good reason for a higher-than-usual p/e ratio (it had to have recently improved its earnings growth in a way we felt was sustainable).<p>Investors should remember that any system that attempts to compare a stock's price to its fundamental value is at the mercy of the stock market. For example, in 1994, we called Coca-Cola overvalued at $39.38. In mid-May 1996, it traded at $46.13 -- after a two-for-one stock split. In 1994, the stock's price-to-earnings ratio was 23; recently, it was 38. If the market as a whole continues to roar ahead, Coca-Cola could well climb from its current price. But at a level like this -- one clearly above any value supported by the stock's fundamentals -- even a blue chip becomes a risky investment.<p>That's our revised -- and we think improved -- guide to the new blue chips. <p>---
The following list was taken from a chart in Worth magazine. Due to the text-based nature of <a name="NASD:AMER"></a><b>America Online</b>, we are unable to reproduce this graphic in its entirety.
