<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/06-Call in the Cavalry</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/06-Call in the Cavalry</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
Which credit-card issuers really go to bat for you?<p>By Gail Liverman<p>If you've ever fought over a disputed credit-card charge, you know there's a limit to what you can do yourself: It's your credit-card issuer who fights the battle for you. So it's important to know which banks will take up your cause in earnest. "The ones that
invest in customer service and put time, effort, and dollars into that area do a better job, like <a name="NYSE:T"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10103"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>AT&T</b></a> and <a name="NYSE:AXP"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10085"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>American Express</b></a> and <a name="NYSE:WB"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10581"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Wachovia</b></a>," says Ruth Susswein, executive director of Bankcard Holders of America, a consumer group based in Salem, Virginia. <p>One of those trying to bolster its customer service, NationsBank, recently became one of the first card issuers to establish a customer-advocacy group specifically designed to handle cardholder disputes after traditional routes have been exhausted. "We take on the role of advocate," says Mallory Anderson, vice president and manager of cardholder disputes for the company. "That's the way we see our role, and we hope our customers see us the same way." NationsBank handles most of its cut-and-dried cases -- the wrong amount appearing on a statement, double billing -- by phone or fax. The advocacy group gets involved in more complex cases, such as when a customer refuses to pay for a poor-quality item or never receives a product a merchant claims to have sent.<p>AT&T also makes life easy for a cardholder looking to dispute a charge on its Universal Card, which received the highest ranking for overall customer satisfaction in a recent J. D. Power & Associates survey (see box). AT&T will mail a form, called a ballot box, to a disgruntled cardholder who telephones. This way, the cardholder needn't go through the trouble of composing a letter to exercise his or her legal rights.<p>Legally, interest can't be charged while a bill is in formal dispute, but it can be charged retroactively if the cardholder loses. Despite its customer-advocacy position, NationsBank does assess interest retroactively. With American Express's Optima cards and AT&T's Universal Card, interest charges resume if the cardholder loses the dispute but aren't assessed for the period of appeal.<p>Of course, many issuers aren't responsive to disputed charges. Fortunately, the law is on the cardholder's side. Under federal truth-in-lending regulations, you have the right to get an error corrected on your credit-card bill provided you notify the issuer in writing within 60 days of the postmarked date on the statement. While your claim is being investigated, you don't have to pay the charge, and your credit record can't be adversely affected. You also have the right to put in a claim on a purchase you feel is of poor quality, as long as you have made an attempt to resolve the dispute directly with the merchant. <p>In the scramble to keep good customers, some issuers have automatically ruled in favor of valued cardholders in disputes up to a set dollar limit, says Michael Auriemma, president of Auriemma Consulting Group in Westbury, New York, a credit-card-management consultant. But issuers are loath to admit they do this. NationsBank's policy on the matter is "proprietary information." American Express director of communications Marcos Rada says Amex might absorb all or part of a charge for "an extremely highly valued card member who has been a member for many years and is under a compelling situation beyond their control." <p>So if you've been a good customer, it's worth taking any dispute, no matter how minor, to your issuer. <p>
SIDEBAR--SERVICE MASTERS: RANKING THE CARDS
J. D. Power & Associates surveyed 7,200 credit-card users to determine which issuers ranked highest in overall customer satisfaction. A score of 100 is average.<p>-->The Best 
113  AT&T  
106  Discover  
106  Household Bank   
102  <a name="NYSE:BK"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10177"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Bank of New York</b></a>   
101  <a name="NASD:BONEO"></a><b>Banc One</b>  
101  Citibank 
100  First Union National   <p>-->The Rest
Rating below average: American Express, Optima True Grace, Bank of America, <a name="NYSE:COF"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=42309"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Capital One Financial</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:CMB"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10322"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Chase Manhattan</b></a>, <a name="NASD:CHFC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12961"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Chemical Bank</b></a>, Colonial National, <a name="NYSE:FBS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10567"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>First Bank System</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:FCN"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10571"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>First Chicago</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:FUS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=15687"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>First USA</b></a>, GE Capital, <a name="NYSE:KRB"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12449"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>MBNA America</b></a>, NationsBank, Wachovia, and <a name="NYSE:WFC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11619"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Wells Fargo</b></a>.<p><p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Banking Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


