	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Toolbox</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/05-Toolbox</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						May 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Investing  <p> TOOLBOX  <p> By Maxwell Dale  <p> Q: What is a stock split? <p>A: A way for a company to lower its apparent stock price. For example, the <a name="NYSE:GPS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11469"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Gap</b></a> recently announced a two-for-one split. An investor who owned one share at $56 before the split will own two shares priced at $28 each afterward. Nothing has really changed.  <p> If nothing changes, why does a company split its stock? <p>Lowering the price by a split can make a stock seem more desirable to a larger number of individual investors, and many companies want to attract this type of long-term investor.  <p> Is a stock split good? <p>The reason for a split하 strong run-up in the stock pricereflects strong earnings growth and management's confidence in the future,but it doesn't mean the stock will continue to rise.   <p> Is it better to sell the stock before or after the split? <p>According to academic studies, the actual split doesn't have a direct impact on the stock price. The price usually runs up until the split and then continues to rise only if earnings increase. If the split is accompanied by an earnings increase, the stock may move up slightly for a brief time close to the announcement. <p> What's the difference between a stock split and a stock dividend? <p>A stock dividend is a dividend paid in stock instead of cash. Like a split, it doesn't increase the value of a share but gives an investor additional shares, each of which is worth slightly less. An investor with 100 shares worth $10 each who receives a 10 percent stock dividend will now own 110 shares worth $9.09 each.   <p> What's a reverse split? <p>Companies may reduce the number of shares by consolidating them into higher-value units. Just as a stock split reflects positively on a company, a reverse split can be a warning: The company is trying to avoid a low stock price, which might prevent institutional investors, who may have limits on how little they can pay for shares, from buying. Only the number of shares an investor owns (not their total value) changes. <p>
KEYWORDS: Stock Investing<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
