	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/05-Riding the Cycles</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Riding the Cycles</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/05-Riding the Cycles</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						May 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Investing  <p> RIDING THE CYCLES <p>If the economy grows faster than expected, then cyclical stocks should prosper  <p> By Constance Gustke  <p> Cyclical stocks are the market's roller-coaster plays. Driven by the engine of the national economy, the earnings of cyclical companies climb peaks and then fall into valleys. The reason: These companies traffic in durable consumer goods such as autos and homes -- or the raw materials that go into these items --and sell in mature markets where demand fluctuates with economic conditions.   <p> In the 1990 recession year, for example, cyclical stocks swooned, falling 20.13 percent versus a 6.56 percent decline for the Standard & Poor's 500 Stock Index. Regardless of product niche or management style, cyclical companies slow down when the economy does --and so do their stocks. The stock price of <a name="NYSE:GM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10640"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>General Motors</b></a> dropped over 40 percent during 1994, when consumers pulled back on high-ticket expenditures because interest rates rose by almost three percentage points.  <p> Investors usually flee to growth stocks when they fear a recession. Because these companies are in less mature markets -- young industries where demand will grow even if the economy stagnates -- their stocks stay steady or decline less rapidly than cyclicals doin an economic downturn. During the 1990 recession, when cyclicals plunged, growth stocks gained 2.48 percent, according to Safian Investment Research in White Plains, New York.  <p> When the economy rebounds, though, cyclicals shine. As the economy recovered from the recession in 1992 and 1993, cyclicals beat the S&P 500 handily, registering double-digit gains.  <p> Cyclicals are treading water now because investors aren't sure where the economy is heading. "Investors are hedging their bets between growth stocks and cyclicals," says Kurt Walters, vice president of research at Safian.  <p> The extreme volatility of cyclical stocks makes them poor buy-and-hold investments. For example, GM eked out an 8.62 percent annualized return compared with 15.2 for the S&P 500 during the ten year sending on January 31, 1996. "Cyclicals are bought to be sold," says Joseph Barthel, an analyst at Fahnestock in New York.  <p> Investment strategists recommend buying cyclical stocks when their prices are low on a historic basis and their price-to-earnings ratios are high, as they are when the economy is in a recession or the market is anticipating one. Buying stocks with high p/e's may seem the wrong thing to do, but for a cyclical, a high p/e is the result of depressed earnings and can often signal the trough just before earnings turn around.  <p> Savvy investors don't overlook the fundamentals, either. They seek out industry leaders with rock-solid balance sheets and minimal debt loads. Quality stocks are apt to rebound fastest once the economy regains its luster. Studying a company's fundamentals is the best way to tell the difference between a sound company that is riding the waves of the economy and a troubled enterprise in danger of going under.  <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Stock Market trends, Economy

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/2pages.gif"><br>About 2 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

<font size=+1><b>Company Index</b><br>
</font>						<a href="#NYSE:GM">General Motors Corporation</a><br>

