<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/05-Sic 'Em</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/05-Sic 'Em</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Newly appointed regulator Mary Schapiro says the NASD is finally committed to doing right by investors -- and that she's the proof <p> The National Association of Securities Dealers hasn't enjoyed much credibility as a self-regulatory organization. The Nasdaq stock market, which it operates and supposedly oversees, has long been known as an insider-oriented club where powerful trading houses thrive and small investors can get cheated. Part of the problem, according to the Rudman Commission, a high-level task force that recently released a report on the NASD's problems, is that the world's largest SRO routinely fails to put "substantial daylight" between itself and the Nasdaq market it is charged with regulating. Last fall, however, the NASD promised to clean up its act. In November, it formed a new regulatory arm, NASD Regulation, and gave 40-year-old Mary Schapiro the job of running it. At the time, Schapiro was chairwoman of the Commodity Futures Trading Commission. She is also a former commissioner of the Securities and Exchange Commission. While at the CFTC, she won a reputation for rigorous enforcement by boosting the commission's number of investigations by more than half. "She can be tough when she needs to be," says former SEC commissioner Rick Roberts. Recently, Schapiro talked with Worth financial editor Elizabeth Macdonald about her plans to address the interests of investors as president of the NASDR.  <p> Worth: How would you respond to people such as Alan Davidson, president of the Independent Broker Dealer Association, who says that the Nasdaq market is beyond reform? <p>Schapiro: I think Nasdaq has been a phenomenal engine of growth for some extraordinary companies. It has offered a lot to the investing public in only 25 years. I think one of the very legitimate criticisms in the Rudman report is that the focus of the energy of the organization has largely been on the growth of the business. Now our focus is clear; it's regulation, not, say, new listings or Nasdaq technology. I care about market development the way any investor would, but I have no responsibility for it. It won't take one scintilla of my attention.  <p> What persuaded you to make financial regulation your occupation?<p>In the winter of 1979 and 1980, Nelson and Bunker Hunt were charged with manipulating the silver market. It made me angry that a small group of people would attempt to manipulate the market to the detriment of thousands of people. I was fascinated, too, that two people could have such an impact on a market that was presumably big, deep, and liquid. So right after I graduated from George Washington law school, I went over to the Commodities Futures Trading Commission in D.C. and got a job as a trial attorney.  <p> Any tough moments in your career? <p>It didn't discourage me, but last August, The Wall Street Journal ran an editorial that was pretty nasty. They criticized my enforcementaction against Metallgesellschaft AG. The company had lost hundreds of millions of dollars trading energy products, and its actions had almost brought down the New York Mercantile Exchange. Sowe fined them $2.5 million and forced them to institute certain controls before they could begin trading again. Has the Journal ever liked an enforcement case brought against a big company? Probably not. But it was the meanness and the inaccuracies in the editorial that bothered me.  <p> Criticism comes with the territory. But I try to turn it into a positive if I can. In 1994, Tom Donovan, the president of the Chicago Board of Trade, reportedly said in one of his board meetings that he wasn't going to be intimidated by some blond, five-foot-two-inch girl. When the Chicago press called me to get my reaction, I said, Well, I'm not five two, I'm five five. Tom and I have gotten along better ever since.  <p> What will you initially focus on to fix the NASD's less than stellar reputation?  <p>I want to concentrate on the issues in the Rudman report, such as upgrading the disciplinary process. We'll be supplementing the hearing committees in the NASD's 11 district offices with professional hearing officers, who will conduct disciplinary hearings to determine whether brokers have violated the law and,if so, what sanctions should be imposed. Also, we will be filling half our board of directors with non-industry members.   <p> What about enforcement? <p>We're going to devote more resources to this area. Regulation is meaningless unless you're willing to back it up. At the end of the day, people aren't going to use the market unless they think it's fair.  <p> What will it take to persuade investors that you are making a difference? <p>We have to prove we're committed to the highest-quality regulation of the market. We have to demonstrate that in how we examine sales practices at brokerage firms, in our surveillance of the Nasdaq market, and in our handling of customer complaints.  <p> How will you fix some of the systemic problems that currently exist, such as incentive programs that encourage brokers to take advantage of their customers?  <p>We must hold accountable the people up the chain of command at brokerage firms. Too often, we get cases where branch managers choose to ignore red flags because a broker is generating a huge amount of revenue. Some firms aren't as diligent in cleaning their own houses as they should be. So we'll discipline firms for failing to supervise their employees.  <p> You're talking about 507,000 brokers at 5,400 firms trading a daily volume of 524 million shares. Can you really be  effective policing such a large beat as a self-regulatory organization? <p>I don't know of any other industry where self-regulation has been as effective a tool as in the securities industry. Take the medical profession. How many times have you read about doctors who have made repeated, tragic errors before there's action by their peers? We've sanctioned thousands of brokers for violating the rules. Also, if we're not there to examine sales practices,look at the books, and check internal controls, who's going to do it? The SEC has 200 examiners. They can't do the whole job. <p> What sort of a standard do you think the investment industry should be held to?  <p>In my seven years at the SEC and CFTC, I've read thousands of enforcement cases, and it's disturbing to  see how investors are sometimes treated. It has given me  a sense of focus. I believe that when people entrust their money to  a broker, money that they've worked hard for, they have a right to be dealt with fairly and honestly. A broker must adhere to a standard of integrity and fairness. If a broker does not live up to that standard, he or she ought not to be working in the business anymore. We must take them out of the industry.  <p> Do you think mandatory arbitration  adequately redresses investors'problems? <p>My view is, if we're going to have mandatory arbitration, then we darn well better be running a first-class arbitration operation.We're looking at major procedural changes to improve timing and efficiency, and to keep disputes out of the courts. Litigating in court isn't really an ideal solution, either. The expense is extraordinary. Also, going to court can be a delaying tactic, and investors often lose out that way, too.  <p> Investors receive virtually zero information from the NASD hotline on crooked dealers. Such requests often fall into a blackhole. Any plans to fix this mess? <p>We are working on it. We will soon be able to offer better and more complete information on complaints against brokers, arbitration awards, and disciplinary actions. I also want to make this information available to investors on the Internet.  <p> Can you say anything more about your plans to improve your response to customer grievances?  <p>Last year, the NASD received more than 4,500 customer complaints. My concern is that if we have a market decline you will see the volume of complaints shoot up dramatically. We need to be prepared to handle that event when it happens, rather than scurrying around after the fact trying to clean up the back log. So I've asked for an internal report on how we can improve the process and how we  can deal with an increased volume of complaints, if necessary. I also want to be able to use the complaint information more effectively for enforcement cases and to get a better sense of what's going on across the country, to see trends in bad practices. <p> Do you plan to pursue more "message cases"핪hose with maximum deter- rent value?  <p>Yes, I'm a big believer in message cases. That was my approach at the CFTC, where we had an enforcement staff of 145 to police a huge industry. It sends a clear message about what is not acceptable and helps people modify their behavior before they get into trouble. Also, it has a punitive effect. We have to bring more than message cases, though; we need a higher quantity of cases. We need to do both.  <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Ethical Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/5pages.gif"><br>About 5 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
</td>
	</tr>
