<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/04-The Muni Minefield</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>The Muni Minefield</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/04-The Muni Minefield</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						April 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Investing  <p> THE MUNI MINEFIELD <p>Flat tax. Schmlat tax. The real threat to municipal bonds lurks at the local level.   <p> By Greg Millman  <p> In 1994, many bond-fund investors were blindsided when Federal Reserve interest-rate hikes revealed unexpected risks in their portfolios. This year could be d茯 vu all over again. Risks in the municipal-bond market have been creeping upward, and the methods for warning investors aren't flagging the problems.  <p> To many investors, national politics appears to be the biggest threat to munis. Like a sword of Damocles, newly fashionable flat-tax proposals hang over the market, threatening to eliminate munis' unique tax advantage. This fear dampened muni returns during the bond-market rally in 1995. Janet Yuen, fixed-income analyst at Lipper Analytical Services in New York, says that general muni-bond funds were up 16.84 percent, while general U.S. Treasury funds were up 22.21 percent.  <p> But the income consequences of the flat tax are fully priced into the market. The real risk in munis is coming from state houses and city halls and a potential liquidity crunch in muni-bond funds.  <p> This is not obvious --  which is a  major part of the problem. Some states and cities are enjoying their most robust health in years. Sunny California, which looked like a financial mudslide a year ago, surprised everyone  by turning up a budget surplus. Meanwhile, states such as Maryland, Pennsylvania, New Hampshire, and Massachusetts have been setting aside "rainy-day funds" to protect against such emergencies as recessions and budget strains that may develop as Congress sends more responsibility their way.  <p> On the other hand, Standard & Poor's downgraded 21 municipal issuers of general-obligation bonds in the third quarter of 1995 alone, affecting $30 billion of debt, mostly from Los Angeles County, New York City, and the state of Louisiana. Throw in the downgrade of Washington, D.C., paper early last year and Orange County's bankruptcy travails, and there are some deep credit potholes on the muni highway. "This is a period of great uncertainty. Investors who don't want to worry about their money don't want to invest in places where things can turn around quickly," says Claire Cohen, vice-chairman of Fitch Investors Service in New York.   <p> What should you look out for? Some states have been hampered by popular initiatives and referenda. "Watch states that use these means frequently," Cohen advises. California voters, for example, have successfully limited tax increases and now spell out how tax revenues are to be spent. Investors need to monitor local political news closely in such states as California, Oregon,Washington, Massachusetts, and Colorado, says Cohen.  <p> For their part, fund managers can no longer rely on the taxing authority of municipalities to secure debt on general-obligation bonds, once considered very safe. Instead, they prefer so-called special-purpose issues such as water, airport, and electric-power bonds, secured by a definite revenue stream. Two words explain why --  Orange County. "Textbooks have always told us that general-obligation bonds were preferable to revenue bonds because issuers can always levy taxes," says Dick Berry, senior portfolio manager for AIM Management Group in Houston. "That may be true legally, but political realities may make it impossible." On the other hand, people will always have to drink water, flush toilets, and turn on lights.  <p> But as deregulation opens once protected industries to competition, special-purpose bonds aren't what they used to be, either. For example, bonds used to finance public hospitals are less secure: Hospitals now face competitive threats as well as changes in Medicare and Medicaid. "The only thing riskier than a hospitalis a nuclear power plant," says Jeff Schaub of Fitch Investors Service in New York.  <p> In many cases, investors aren't being properly compensated. Chuck Nellans, senior health-care analyst at John Nuveen & Co., notes that a hospital bond rated A yielded only 6.07 percent in December versus 5.86 percent for an  A-rated water-and-sewer bond.  <p> Even worse, the muni funds with the greatest risks frequently have five-star ratings for performance in Morningstar's widely followed fund listings. Morningstar measures downside volatility, the price movement of the bonds in a fund, says Mark Wright, fixed-income analyst at Morningstar. That works well for high-rated bonds that trade regularly, but lower-rated bonds don't respond to interest-rate changes as quickly. And unrated bonds --  those that haven't been evaluated  by a ratings agency, such as Moody's Investors Service, because  the issues are small or the issuers are leery of a negative rating --  don't trade enough for their prices to reflect any change in value.  <p> "When you look at Morningstar, every fund that has 50 percent or more unrated municipals is considered low-risk because its prices don't move," says Sanford Bragg, managing director of the Managed Funds Group at Standard & Poor's. "If they had to sell these unrated munis, you could have a situation similar to mortgage derivatives in 1994." In that fiasco, fund managers who owned mortgage derivatives couldn't find buyers when they were desperate to sell. That sent muni-fund values south -- fast.  <p> If a sudden sell-off were provoked by any number of pending tax-law changes, muni-bond-fund managers would be hard-pressed to raise the cash to meet redemptions.  <p> Despite credit and liquidity risks, muni-fund managers have been buying credits of lower and lower quality to gain yield. This has narrowed the price differences between high and low credits. "Right now, with credit spreads tight, you're not getting paid to step down in credit quality," says B. Clark Stamper, portfolio manager of <a name="FUND:VMPAX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/VMPAX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Davis Tax Free High Income Fund</b></a>. "Back in1990 and 1991, [bonds rated] BBB were yielding 150 basis points more than AAA munis. Now it's more like 40 basis points."  <p> As a result, muni investors need to take a careful look at the credit ratings of muni issues in funds. Investment-grade bonds of AAA to BBB carry relatively minor credit risk. Grade BB and below is the realm of junk bonds. <a name="FUND:AMHIX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/AMHIX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>American High-Income Municipal Bond Fund</b></a> had 29 percent of its portfolio in BB  bonds and 5.4 percent in B bonds as of December 31, 1995 --  not a good choice for investors focused on preserving principal. Portfolios with large positions in unrated bonds carry even more risk. <a name="FUND:BCHYX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/BCHYX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>The Benham California Municipal High-Yield Fund</b></a>, for example, had 28 percent of its portfolio in unrated bonds as of December 31, 1995.  <p> "It's very important for muni investors to know what they are looking for," says Arthur L. Schwarz, a principal at Weiss, Peck and Greer, a New York investment-banking firm. "You can buy a 20- to 30-year portfolio of low-grade bonds to maximize returns or put the same money into a one-year AAA security to maximize preservation of capital. Our clients take their risks in other sectors --  the muni portfolio is an anchor to windward when everything else goes to hell."  <p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Mutual Funds Investing, Bond Investing, Investing Strategies

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

