<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/04-The Return of Insider Trading</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>The Return of Insider Trading</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/04-The Return of Insider Trading</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						April 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Cover Story  <p> THE RETURN OF INSIDER TRADING <p>It's the 1980s all over again -- only worse -- and the top cop on the beat can't stop it  <p> By Christopher Byron  <p> During the last full week of August 1995, the common shares of a small and nearly comatose media company named <a name="NASD:GBFE"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=15150"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Western Publishing Group</b></a> barely budged on the Nasdaq electronic stock exchange. Each business day that week, no more than a paltry 20,000 or so shares changed hands -- always within a narrow band between $9.875 and $10.125 a share.  <p> Then, on Tuesday, August 29, the shares of Western Publishing abruptly awoke from their torpor. Volume jumped to 37,200 shares, with the stock closing at $9.75 a share. The next day, 73,700 shares of the company traded, lifting the closing price to $10.375. Thursday and Friday were much the same, with both the price and volume of the stock continuing to rise. Then, when the markets reopened after the Labor Day weekend, on Tuesday, September 5, an astonishing 191,200 shares of Western Publishing changed hands, with the stock closing at $11.75 a share, up nearly 21 percent in just six days.   <p> Why these mysterious volume and price surges in the stock? The company hadn't been in the news and hadn't even put out a press release in months. In fact, the one Wall Street analyst who bothered to follow Western Publishing had had nothing to say about the stock all summer. Was the company about to make an important announcement? And if so, were insiders driving the stock up, seeking to profit illegally on their advance knowledge?  <p> Investors hadn't long to wait for an answer. The very next day,Wednesday, September 6, the world learned what some still-to-be-identified players had apparently known all along: Western Publishing was the target for a takeover by a Wall Street셕acked buyout groupled by the former head of Simon & Schuster, Richard E. Snyder. <p> The public disclosure of the proposed $14-a-share buyout, distributed on the afternoon of September 6, had exactly the effect the insiders wished. It kicked the stock into orbit. On the first full day of trading after the announcement, volume in Western Publishing rose to nearly 1.5 million shares, with the price spurting to $14.50 a share.   <p> It has been eight months since this piece of insider profiteering lurched into view, yet neither the Securities and Exchange Commissionnor the National Association of Securities Dealers -- the two oversight bodies charged with policing the trading in companies such as Western Publishing -- has done anything about it. They're not likely to, either, because small- to medium-sized theft from the public market is no longer a big enough crime to warrant the attention of the cops who police the financial markets. There gulators have all they can do to keep up with the virtual crimewave of new and much bigger fraud now spreading through Wall Street.  <p> As a result, situations similar to the Western Publishing affair now occur almost every day, and the inability of regulators to go after the cheaters is helping to send a disturbing message: The potential profits are so high and the risk of getting caught is so low that insider trading is once again worth the gamble. It's a risk-reward calculus that any first-year MBA student caneasily understand.  <p> No one knows that better than SEC chairman Arthur Levitt, Wall Street's top cop. Levitt knows what he's talking about -- and leaves much unsaid -- when he asserts, "We're doing a good job with the resources we have." Coming from the SEC chief, such a comment amounts to an admission that he lacks the resources to go after any but the biggest and most flagrant offenders. It's a different message entirely from the one the chairman deliveredas recently as a year ago, when he repeatedly pronounced that U.S. securities markets were more honest than ever before.  <p> Not long ago, in a distinctly downbeat speech on the securities industry at mid-decade, Levitt told a gathering of NASD officials and stockbrokers in Washington, "We have every right to be proud of the industry that has been so good to us, and is so good for America. But we must also be realistic about its problems. Fundamental to our markets is investor confidence that they are fair, that they are open, and that they are level. And lately, that reputation stands threatened."  <p> Levitt's scolding of the industry for everything from criminality to aggressive sales practices is both on target and clearly overdue. But the bigger problem facing regulatory enforcement officials these days is the lack of manpower and other resources needed to keep up with all the bad guys -- on the Internet, over the airwaves, in the penny-stock market, in the mutual-fund industry, in the new-issues market for such techie-sounding exotica as wireless-cable franchises. In arena after arena, the crooks are on the march, while the cops are barely holding their own.  <p> "Sure," says a top NASD enforcement official on the insider-trading beat, "we looked at the Western Publishing thing informally when it occurred. But the situation was complicated, and it would have taken a lot of time and effort to get to the bottom of it, so basically we made a judgment call not to pursue it."  <p> Who were the insiders in the Western Publishing affair? They could have been company officials or investment bankers at Warburg,Pincus Ventures, the firm that put together the deal. They could have been lawyers working on the terms of the deal, or family, friends, and acquaintances of anyone involved. Insiders could have bought the shares in their own names or blindly through offshore shell companies in Caribbean island nations such as the Caymans or the Netherlands Antilles. And the influx of their orders could have alerted sharp-eyed stockbrokers everywhere to place their own "free-riding" orders behind them on the assumption that something was up.  <p> Insider trading is at once devilishly difficult to prove and the next most lucrative activity to trafficking in crack cocaine. No wonder it has once again become the thing to do on Wall Street, as if the lessons of the 1980s have already been forgotten. <p> Thus, one day before <a name="NYSE:IBM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10796"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>IBM</b></a>  announced its hostile $3.3 billion bid for Lotus Development last June, shares in Lotus jumped three and a quarter points, on close to four times normal trading volume. And on June 10, 1995, two days before <a name="NASD:CEPH"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14307"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Cephalon</b></a>, a drug manufacturer, revealed testing results for a breakthrough medicine to treat Lou Gehrig's disease, Cephalon's trading volume more than doubled (the price of Cephalon's shares doubled in the days following the announcement).  <p> Variations on that theme were seen over and over again in 1995-- in cases involving Mitek Surgical Products, <a name="NASD:QKTN"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=16677"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Quickturn Design Systems</b></a>, DOVatron International, Adesa, <a name="NASD:SMSC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14785"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Standard Microsystems</b></a>, Leaseway Transportation, Columbia First Bank, Legent, and many others.  <p> All those situations and others became the subject of NASD market-surveillance referrals to the SEC, but they barely scratch the surface. Wall Street veterans say that not only is there more cheating among the Street's clients and customers but the same is true for the brokers and dealers. "I've been on Wall Street 36 years," says Louis Ehrenkrantz, president of Ehrenkrantz, King, Nussbaum Securities,"and I can tell you for sure that the level of chicanery is worse now than I've ever seen it. You have to go all the way back to the era of blind pools in the 1920s to find something comparable." <p> The fact is, in a world of deregulated global markets, with instant access to information in virtually every country on earth, the regulators increasingly find themselves outgunned and outwitted by a new class of hustlers. They may operate out of Wall Street itself, in corporate boardrooms, or even in the media, where financial talk-show personalities such as Sonny Bloch (see Worth, June 1995), now awaiting trial on interstate mail- and wire-fraud charges, give investment advice without revealing their private financial interests in the investments they promote.  <p> Drawing a perverse and unintended lesson from the Wall Street mega-prosecutions of a decade ago, these new charlatans of high finance have discovered that it's much easier to get away with pocketing $100,000 ten times in a row than with bagging $1 million once. Not only aren't the exchanges bringing enough cases to have much deterrent value, but of those they do bring, most can't be pursued by the overextended SEC.  <p> Those few cases that are followed up involve years of evidence gathering before a case is ready for trial. It took more than six years before the SEC and the Justice Department, working together, could gather enough evidence to break up a ring ofinsiders that began trading illegally on <a name="NYSE:T"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10103"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>AT&T</b></a> takeover targets as early as December 1988. The ring came together when an AT&T vice president tipped a friend regarding a planned bid for Paradyne, according to court records. When the ring members traded in and out of the run-up in the Paradyne shares and no one seemed to notice, they got bolder and were soon trading illegally in one AT&T deal after another. It wasn't until last summer that the SEC and the U.S. Attorney's Office in New York announced arrests and secured confessions from some of those involved.  <p> Now as ever, the principal breeding ground for insider tradingremains mergers and acquisitions, since advance news of a pending bid inevitably spreads to dozens of individuals -- bankers, lawyers, and corporate officials -- before the deal is announced.  <p> Last year the M & A arena was hotter than ever, with a record-breaking 8,954 deals worth $458 billion, greatly eclipsing previous totals. Yet the NASD developed and referred only 107 cases of suspected wrongdoing to the SEC, fewer than the 115 referrals it made a decade ago in its peak referral year of 1986. Since then, Nasdaq trading volume has more than tripled. The same general pattern repeats itself at the New York Stock Exchange, which referred only 26 insider-trading cases to the SEC in 1995. Meanwhile,the SEC brought only 45 insider-trading cases in total last year. <p> That 1980s-era effort, targeted at such individuals as Ivan Boesky, Martin Siegel, and, ultimately, Michael Milken, was designed to drive home the message that corruption in general -- and insider trading in particular -- would not be tolerated on Wall Street,where small investors invariably feel the deck is stacked against them anyway.  <p> The lesson has come and gone, and today there is virtually open defiance of insider-trading laws. Take the case of Tivoli Systems, a software company that was the object of a late-January takeover, at $47.50 a share, by IBM. The bid represented a premium of more than $10 a share over the prevailing market price, so it was hardly surprising that in the five trading days prior to the announcement, share volume in Tivoli more than tripled, lifting the price from $35.50 to nearly $37.75 a share.  <p> Whether the target of inside-trader attentions has a large market capitalization seems to make no difference. Thus, though rumors were everywhere last spring that Capital Cities/ABC was about to become takeover bait, on only two occasions from the beginning of May through the middle of July did trading volume exceed 400,000 or so shares per day.  <p> Then, starting on July 21, the stock began racking up more than 500,000 shares in trading volume almost every day, with volume on some days approaching a million shares. Why?  <p> The most likely explanation is that news had begun to leak out that a bid for the company, at a huge market premium, was imminent from . On July 31, <a name="NYSE:DIS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11603"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Disney</b></a> unfurled its bid for Cap Cities -- at more than $26 a share over the prevailing market price.  <p> The situation was exactly the same last autumn when Australian-owned Broken Hill Proprietary bid $28 a share for Magma Copper. From the beginning of October through the middle of November -- a period of more than 30 trading days -- Magma stock experienced only two days in which volume exceeded 500,000 shares; on nearly every other day, volume was less than half that, sometimes totaling fewer than 75,000 shares.  <p> On November 21, though, volume jumped to 791,900 shares and then to 2.1 million the next day. The price, meanwhile, began to climb, from $16.75 a share to $20.125 a share by November 29. On November 30, after the close of business, Broken Hill announced that it was offering a full $28 a share for Magma Copper. <p> In recent years, trading on inside information has grown more sophisticated, with more and more new ways to "game the system." For example, there are "equity swaps" and "zero-cost collars"-- techniques that allow a stockholder to transfer ownership without trading through an exchange -- which are just the ticket for corporate insiders who think their company's stock price might soon drop but want to get out with less risk of being noticed. "These kinds of schemes are now commonplace on Wall Street," says Bob Gabele, the publisher of a closely followed newsletter that tracks buy and sell decisions by corporate insiders.  <p> "It's the Wild West down here," adds Thomas Pirro, who runs the New York office of Compliance Data Center, which maintains an extensive database on securities fraud and functions as a clearinghouse for investment firms wanting to check out the bonafides on prospective new clients. "There's scarcely a day that goes by when we don't come across at least one new multimillion-dollar swindle unfolding somewhere."  <p> Pirro mentions so-called Reg. S swindles, designed to use unregistered offshore stock as collateral for margin loans, sapphire-bondscams, Nigerian banknote scams, wire-transfer scams, initial-public-offering hedge-fund scams, and so on.  <p> Faced with this blizzard of malfeasance, William McLucas, chief of enforcement for the SEC in Washington, says, "We have to pick our fights where they'll do the most good. We have to keep sending the message that it's not okay to have road warriors on Wall Street. We can't have the place break out in the financial-world version of extreme fighting."  <p> His boss, SEC chairman Levitt, says, "We just can't bring every case we'd like to, and we have to assign priorities." Levittis a rare bird in Washington these days: a Clinton appointee to a federal agency who has managed to escape the budget-cutting enthusiasms of Newt Gingrich. At the same time, though, his resources are increasingly inadequate for the job of policing the nation's securities markets.  <p> Levitt is on the spot. As a result of the enactment last winter of Republican-sponsored reform on litigation in the securities industry, plaintiffs' lawsuits will now be more difficult and costly to pursue (see "Insecure Securities"). That will make the SEC more than ever the last line of defense between the investing public and those who want to take their money and run.  <p> A recent study by the Congressional Budget Office sees reform as putting yet more strain on the SEC's resources, concluding it will saddle the agency with as much as $250 million in additional enforcement-related costs through 2001. And that doesn't include the nearly certain quantum leap in enforcement referrals in the year ahead from the NASD, which has beefed up its computerized market-surveillance system and can now instantly spot suspicious changes in the trading patterns of stocks. The man in charge of the operation, Lynn Nellius, says he expects referrals to the SEC to increase in 1996.  <p> The SEC's budget for the fiscal year beginning in September will be essentially the same as it was on the day Levitt became chairman almost three years ago. Without additional muscle --and a visible determination to use it against the white-collar criminals of Wall Street -- the capitalist marketplace will get only dirtier. Says Meyer Berman, the doyen of Wall Street short-sellers:"The SEC tries to do its best. But I really believe they don't understand what's happening. Crime on Wall Street has gotten out of control. The inmates are now running the prison. There is nowhere else in the world that you can steal so much money so fast and never get caught."  <p>
TOUGH TIMES FOR THE CHAIRMAN  <p> Is this man happy? In late January, Arthur Levitt, the chairman of the Securities and Exchange Commission and the nation's top market cop, was sitting for a photo shoot when he got the news that Linda Quinn, the SEC's longtime director of corporate finance, had decided to leave for a job in the private sector.  <p> Levitt has drawn fire over several recent top-level resignations from the SEC, though there seems to be nothing to them beyond the normal ebb and flow of senior personnel from government to the private sector. In reaction to the criticism leveled at Levitt, Quinn herself says, "That stuff is all bunk. Arthur's a great boss and colleague, and I'm only leaving because the offer was too good to pass up. There's nothing more to it than that." <p> In fact, Levitt deserves high marks for much of the work he has done during his three years in the job. He's given top priority to investor protection and education and has spoken to dozens of investor groups around the country. Levitt uses these appearances to urge his listeners to ask tough questions of their brokers. "There's an implicit conflict of interest built into the very manner in which brokers are compensated by their firms," says Levitt. "The more stock they sell, the more commission dollars they pocket. Investors need to understand that their own interests are not necessarily shared by their brokers."  <p> Few people can speak about the brokerage industry with the authority of Levitt, a man who can claim to have played a major role increating the Wall Street of the late 20th century. Levitt was recruited to the business as a young man in the early 1960s by Arthur L. Carter, a partner in the fastest-tracking boutique investment firm of the go-go years, Carter, Berlind & Weill (which later became Carter, Berlind, Weill and Levitt).  <p> "Arthur Carter was an absolute genius, but he pretty much kept to himself," recalls Russell Rosen, a Florida real-estate man, who worked as a broker at CBW&L.  "As a result, the man we mostly saw around the office was Arthur Levitt. He was an absolute class act, and you could tell that he was definitely going to go far. "CBW&L was one of the first orchestrators of the mega셕lock trade. It also pioneered the hostile takeover when it helped financier Saul Steinberg buy Reliance Insurance in 1967.  <p> At CBW&L, Levitt met and befriended just about every important person on Wall Street, from his partner Sanford Weill, now the chairman of Travelers, which owns Smith Barney (CBW&L's eventual successor), to ex섾oldman, Sachs chairman John Whitehead, and from Paul Volcker and David Rockefeller to John Phelan, Alan Greenspan, and Sol Linowitz. In 1978, Levitt departed CBW&L, accepting an offer to head up the American Stock Exchange, which he ran until 1989. Before joining the SEC in 1993, Levitt owned and published Roll Call, Capitol Hill's daily newspaper of record. <p> At the SEC, Levitt has worked hard to get firms to abandon such cheesy practices as single-product sales contests, in which a company with a moldering inventory of, say, guaranteed investment contracts tries to move them off the shelf by giving incentive bonuses to its brokers for selling them. He has also had success persuading firms to discontinue the practice of paying larger commissions to brokers for moving in-house merchandise than for selling goods available on the open market.  <p> Another Levitt initiative: the long-overdue cleanup of the municipal-bondmarket, where pricing information is often hard for investors to come by and where for generations bond houses have nailed down deals by paying kickbacks and bribes to local officials. To that end, the SEC has proposed rules requiring greater disclosure of, among other things, the broker's commission in a bond sale. Under Levitt, the SEC has also become much more interested inthe mutual-fund business, which now accounts for close to 20 percent of all investment savings in this country. Levitt openly worries that too much of the industry's assets -- which total $2.8 trillion -- are becoming concentrated in markets whose liquidity can change rapidly.  <p> Ordinarily, investors would be in excellent hands with an SEC chairman who seems to have the best of intentions. But these aren't ordinary times on Wall Street, and Arthur Levitt's good intentions alone may not be enough.   <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Ethical Investing
					</font>
