	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Insecure Securities</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/04-Insecure Securities</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						April 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Cover Story  <p> INSECURE SECURITIES <p>The bad news? Congress made it harder for stock investors to detect fraud or fight back after being ripped off. The good news? It could have been worse.  <p> By Michael France  <p> On December 22, Congress passed the Private Securities Litigation Reform Act of 1995. Among the law's many provisions is one that makes it harder for investors to file fraud lawsuits against companies suffering sharp drops in share prices.  <p> Eleven days later, <a name="NYSE:SGI"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11735"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Silicon Graphics</b></a> made a surprise announcement: Quarterly profits would fall 29 percent short of Wall Street estimates. Its stock plummeted 16 percent in a matter of hours.<p>Two days after that, <a name="NASD:ADBE"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12518"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Adobe Systems</b></a>, too, disclosed disappointing earnings. Shares took a 35 percent dive. Over the next few days,this pattern repeated itself at <a name="NASD:INTC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13787"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Intel</b></a>, <a name="NASD:DELL"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13193"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Dell Computer</b></a>, <a name="NASD:CYRX"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=16430"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Cyrix</b></a>, and <a name="NASD:AAPL"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12644"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Apple Computer</b></a> -- many of the same companies that had lobbied hardest for the new law.  <p> Was it a coincidence?  <p> Opponents of the legislation, which passed when Congress stampeded over President Clinton's surprise veto, had contended all along that the bill was a disaster for investors. Representative John Dingell, for one, had declared the bill "conceived in sin," and a consumer group dubbed it "the Crooks and Swindlers Protection Act." This miniature technology meltdown, they said, proved their point.  <p> "It's my belief that certain companies -- especially those involved in lobbying for this legislation -- in fact held back bad news until after it passed," says famed San Diego plaintiffs' attorney Bill Lerach. On January 26, he filed a fraud suit, the first major test of the new law, against Silicon Graphics.  <p> Lerach's accusations enrage Ken Glueck, the lobbyist for the American Electronics Association, a key supporter of the law. "To say that companies were withholding bad news until after the legislation is complete nonsense," he snaps. "Are we talking fraud or are we talking about the dynamics of a market that has risen more than 1,000 points in nine months?"  <p> The new securities legislation, supporters say, is good news for ordinary investors. They contend it will reduce the amount of money honest companies spend fighting frivolous claims and free managers from wasting their time in court. To get their message to Congress, the computer, accounting, and securities industries have, since 1993, made more than $10.5 million in political contributions. But not everyone who agrees with them was paid. Even the matrons of the Beardstown Ladies investment club in Illinois have pronounced the legislation "a great deal for investors."  <p> So which side is telling the truth? Neither.  <p> This legislation is bad for investors -- no matter what the Beardstown Ladies say. It's likely to lead to a modest increase in investment fraud, while decreasing the amount of money injured investors can recover in court. It may also make it riskier to invest in some industries. But the 1995 securities act is hardly "a license to cheat small investors," as Money magazine recently claimed. Lying to shareholders is still a crime. And although the legislation will cut back on private class-action fraud suits, it will not eliminate them. Nor does the act restrict the enforcement powers of the Securities and Exchange Commission, state securities agencies, or self-regulatory authorities such as the New York Stock Exchange.  <p> "Even after this legislation, America still has the cleanest stock market in the world. I don't think anyone else comes close," says Henry T. C. Hu, a University of Texas Law School securities-law expert. "The basic securities-law system that has worked so well is not being tampered with in a fundamental way."  <p> Still, the stock market now poses three new risks: Companies can hype their prospects more freely; the licensed professionals who are supposed to prevent corporate wrong doing -- particularly accountants -- may have less incentive to play their watchdog roles; and defrauded investors may have a harder time suing. Understanding these risks will help investors assess the safety of their existing portfolios and make intelligent cost-benefit decisions in the future. There are also a few new legislative land mines lying around, which, if they explode, could cause more harm than the 1995 securities bill.   <p> RISK ONE: HYPE <p>"In February, 1987, we commenced a television advertising campaign in the Southern California market. We believe this television advertising could have a significant impact on increasing average revenues per service location. We are confident of achieving record revenues, income and earnings per share교nd confident of these record results continuing through fiscal 1988." -- a press release from Barry Minkow, chairman of the board of ZZZZ Best, March 16, 1987  <p> Minkow's now infamous claims are what securities lawyers call forward-looking statements, a category of information that may include everything a company says -- whether divulged in a press release, buried in a prospectus, or whispered to an analyst over lunch -- about its future concerning projected revenues and dividends, new product announcements, or disclosures of potential liabilities. <p> This type of information is of obvious importance, which is why securities regulations encourage companies to make forward-looking statements and investors to scrutinize them.  <p> But forward-looking statements can also be dangerous. In the month after the above press release was issued, for example, the price of the common stock in ZZZZ Best climbed from $10.50 to $17.375 a share. But less than three months later, the company filed for bankruptcy, and its claims were revealed to be completely fraudulent. Minkow was sent to jail, but investors lost an estimated $100 million.  <p> Of the approximately 125 companies sued each year for securities fraud, Bill Lerach estimates that about a quarter are accused of making misleading forward-looking statements. The single most dangerous thing about the new securities law -- the provision that almost caused SEC chairman Arthur Levitt to withhold support for it -- is that it offers unprecedented protection to companies that lie about their prospects. Under this law, investors can't sue a corporation for inaccurate forward-looking statements as long as the statements are "accompanied by meaningful cautionary statements identifying important factors that could cause actual results to differ."  <p> This sounds reasonable, but in practice, companies will be able to make grandiose claims about potential earnings, then bracket the hype with boilerplate disclaimers to insure themselves against liability. According to Manhattan plaintiffs' attorney Edward Labaton, the new law might have permitted Minkow to insulate his forward-looking statements by tacking the following language,which actually appeared in another ZZZZ Best document, to his public statement: "Competition in the carpet-, upholstery-, and drapery-cleaning business is intense, and the cost of entry into the industry is relatively low. ZZZZ Best expects to continue to face severe price-cutting and other competitive practices from its competitors in most, if not all, of its locations." <p> Most of the fraud generated by the new law will not, however, be perpetrated by con artists but by legitimate companies whose executives have a strong personal interest in boosting share prices. In the Silicon Graphics suit, for example, it is alleged that CEO Edward R. McCracken repeatedly told the public that his company's revenues would grow by 40 percent in fiscal 1996. Meanwhile, the plaintiffs' lawyers claim that he failed to disclose that the company would be unable to manufacture enough computer workstations to meet this target. Why would McCracken do such a thing? So that he and other insiders could sell $14 million worth of stock at inflated prices, according to the plaintiffs' lawyers. Silicon Graphics spokesman Harry Pforzheimer calls Lerach's lawsuit "frivolous" and says, "There is no merit to the allegations" it contains.   <p> Regardless of how the Silicon Graphics case turns out, the new law means you'll probably be seeing more cases of companies' making rosy forecasts, then disclosing a bolt of bad news seemingly from out of the blue. As Columbia University law professor John Coffee says, corporate fraud "does respond to different levels of risk, and I think we will see somewhat more of it." How much more is hard to predict, but there are reasons to believe it will not become anything close to routine. The new law does not restrict the SEC's ability to sue companies that exaggerate their prospects, even if individuals will have a harder time doing so. And many people think the agency is going to do just that. <p> "The SEC is going to be waiting for a high-visibility forward-looking-statement case, and it's going to bring a very aggressive enforcement action just to make a point to the business community," predicts Donald Langevoort, a law professor at Vanderbilt University. And while the SEC is stretched thin these days (see "The Return of Insider Trading"), there are powerful market incentives for companies to be honest, even if they don't fear prosecution. "If you are a publicly held company or just becoming one, chances are very high that you are going to have to tap the capital markets a second time and a third. It is a relationship, and therefore companies and their executives have a reputation to protect --separate and apart from any statutes," says Hu.  <p> Finally, the new law does not apply to many types of investments, including initial public offerings, partnerships, limited-liability companies, penny stocks, and tender offers. Nor does it protect companies or executives that have run into trouble with the SEC in the past three years. Most important, it's still illegal for executives to make untrue "historical statements" -- that is, to lie about last quarter's earnings or any other facet of a company's actual financial performance. In short, cooking the books remains a crime, a fact that many critics of the legislation have overlooked.  <p> Bottom line: The new securities law won't start an epidemic of fraud, but beginning today, investors should be more skeptical about companies whose primary appeal is a hot new product or is based on a sweeping social trend (say, the rise of the Internet). Such firms are most likely to be found in the sectors that sell the future, such as high technology, communications, biotechnology, and entertainment.  <p> As a general principle, small companies are riskier than large ones. "It is not the Fortune 500 that is going to be presenting problems here," says Coffee. Small firms must create excitement about future prospects in lieu of present accomplishments. Moreover,small-cap stocks receive less scrutiny from analysts. It's not that investors should avoid small companies and growth stocks. Rather, they should take the simple precaution of assuming that everything a company says about its future is false unless supported by independent evidence. "Securities are not bought in this country; they're sold. Somebody's broker calls them up and says buy XYZ stock, and they just buy it," says John Fedders, a Washington,D.C., lawyer who is the former director of the SEC's Division of Enforcement. "Investors need to start reading more about the stocks they are buying."  <p> RISK TWO: SLEEPING WATCHDOGS <p>The collapse of Koger Properties, an office-park developer once traded on the New York Stock Exchange, illustrates the second major problem with the new securities law. During the real-estate recession of the late 1980s and early 1990s, CEO Ira Koger boasted that his Jacksonville, Florida, company was achieving record returns. Then in September 1991, it declared bankruptcy, driving the share price down from about $23 to 69 cents in a matter of days. Koger now faces up to 31 years in prison on tax-evasion charges, if convicted.  <p> The accounting firm of Deloitte & Touche had audited Koger Properties from fiscal 1987 to fiscal 1990, and found itself a co-defendant when investors sued for securities fraud. In March 1995, a Florida jury found that Deloitte had failed to disclose Koger's fraudand ordered it to pay up to $81.3 million in damages. The verdict is under appeal.  <p> Deloitte could be held responsible because of a legal doctrine known as joint and several liability, which says that even though Deloitte is not the only wrong doer it is still liable for all investor losses if no other defendants can pay. Because the main conspirators are often broke by the end of litigation, joint and several liability has been a lifesaver for investors in many of the most notorious securities-fraud cases, including that of Charles Keating and his Lincoln Savings & Loan.  <p> Joint and several liability, for obvious reasons, is wildly unpopular with such professionals as accountants, lawyers, and underwriters, who help the Kogers and Keatings of the world hide their scams. Accountants have been hit hardest, because they are theoretically in the best position to blow the whistle on fraud. From 1990 to 1992, the Big Six accounting firms spent $517.6 million on awards and settlements in just one major category of audit-related federal securities cases.  <p> Under the new legislation, accountants and other secondary parties will no longer be on the hook for every penny investors lose unless, as in a small minority of cases, they were fully aware of or participants in the scam. Otherwise, when the role of professionals is limited to recklessly or negligently overlooking fraud, jurors will assign liability -- probably in the range of 25 percent or less, estimates Coffee.  <p> Proportional liability, as this is called, is worth millions to the accounting industry, which paid millions to get it. According to the Center for Responsive Politics, accountants and their political action committees gave at least $4.8 million to congressional candidates from January 1993 to June 1995.  <p> Because of the new law, investors caught in a ZZZZ Best or Lincoln Savings nightmare have much less chance of being made whole. Only those who have lost more than 10 percent of their life savings and have a net worth of less than $200,000 will retain the right to joint and several liability.  <p> The broader risk is that this decrease in liability will reduce the incentive of professionals to blow the whistle on wrongdoing. However, even though accountants won't face as many $81 million losses, the potential for $20 million verdicts should still get their attention. In addition, the cost to accountants and lawyers of defending themselves against securities-fraud suits, and paying for judgments and settlements, is commonly several times higher than their original engagement fees. One firm mentioned during the accounting industry's lobbying campaign for the 1995 securities bill had received a $91,000 audit fee, but spent $8.4 million defending itself in a lawsuit before paying out a settlement of $997,500.  <p> State regulations, too, keep professionals in line, and those who participate in fraud can lose their licenses. Proportional liability "is less bad than it sounds, even though it may well hurt investors at times," says Columbia University law professor Harvey J. Goldschmid. "The key issue for me is deterrence, and no accountants or lawyers should feel comfortable putting their heads in the sand."  <p> Bottom line: This second risk -- the related hazards of sleeping watchdogs and reduced liability -- is a lot like the first in that it's going to make investing a bit more hazardous, but not so much that you should cash in your stocks and buy gold coins. History has shown that this risk is greatest in financial-services companies such as insurers, banks, and brokerages. They sell intangible products that are hard to keep track of and difficult to value, making it easier to hide losses and fabricate gains.This was illustrated recently by the revelation that Daiwa Bank's New York branch suffered $1.1 billion worth of losses through fraudulent bond trading.  <p> "Daiwa shows just how easy it is to hide billions of dollars' worth of losses in financial companies," says Coffee. "That's where accountants are critical: where there is no visible evidence of losses. If <a name="NYSE:F"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10597"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Ford</b></a> stopped producing cars, people would notice. But Daiwa could lose its shirt, and unless the accountants do a good job, you wouldn't know."  <p> RISK THREE: THE CLOSED COURTHOUSE  <p>President Clinton claimed that the reason he vetoed the securities legislation was not the increased risk of hype or shoddy accounting. It was because of a provision governing "pleading standards"-- the rules setting forth how much detail about an alleged fraud the plaintiffs' lawyers must provide in initial court papers to get a judge to hear a case. Because the bill requires so much up-front information, the president feared investors would never make it through the courthouse doors.  <p> The new legislation says that attorneys can't bring cases unless they describe the alleged scam "with particularity." This means they have to provide all five W's about the fraud: who, what,when, where, and why. Under prior standards, judges would let cases proceed even if a couple of W's were missing, allowing plaintiffs to begin the discovery phase of litigation and reviewinternal corporate documents that might reveal corroborating information. Plaintiffs' attorneys claim the new pleading standards will make it almost impossible to file lawsuits. "You have to have an insider to really start to be able to file a securities-fraud case," complains Patricia Hynes, a partner at the New York law firm Milberg Weiss, which is known for its work in securities-fraud class-action lawsuits.  <p> The evidence suggests she's exaggerating. The new pleading standard is essentially the same one that has been used for years by federal courts in New York, Connecticut, and Vermont. And plenty of securities-fraud cases are successfully brought to court in those states. Well-known Ardmore, Pennsylvania, plaintiffs' attorney Richard D. Greenfield thinks that only about 10 to 20 percent of the cases will bestruck down. "I don't expect that most judges are going to change their fundamental inclination, which is to let good cases go forward and to knock out bad ones," he says.  <p> Bottom line: No one will have a handle on how judges will interpret the new law -- which explicitly states that they are not bound by the federal rulings in New York, Connecticut, and Vermont-- until the initial round of cases slogs through the system, and that could take well over a year. Until then, a smart thing investors can do is keep meticulous records -- saving physical evidence of all the information used to make a particular investment decision, whether it be a newspaper clipping in which an executive hypes a company or marketing material touting a real-estate partnership. <p> Also, take notes after you speak to your broker. They'll help your attorney fill in the five W's. This advice is especially important for residents of Illinois, Indiana, Wisconsin, Maine, Massachusetts, New Hampshire, and Rhode Island, where federal judges have traditionally been hostile to securities suits. You can keep track of the Silicon Graphics suit and other securities-fraud cases by visiting the National Council of Individual Investors' Web site (http://www.ncii.org/ncii).  <p> FUTURE SHOCKS  <p>Last July, Republican congressman Jack Fields of Texas, the powerful chairman of the House Telecommunications and Finance Subcommittee, aimed a shotgun at American securities law. His "Capital Markets Deregulation and Liberalization Act" (H.R. 2131) was intended to hit a wide range of rules governing brokers, corporate raiders, institutional money managers, and companies that issue stocks and bonds.  <p> The majority of the proposals in H.R. 2131 are not particularly threatening to small investors, but one element could make the markets far more dangerous: a plan to gut state securities regulation. Fields, who believes that the cost of raising money is too high in the U.S., wants to eliminate many of the laws that state securities agencies enforce, as well as cut the fees they receive for registering investment advisers and investment companies. Almost inevitably,legislatures would respond by shrinking state securities agencies. <p> That would be very bad news for investors. State securities regulators are the first line of defense against investment fraud. In 1994, they initiated 6,379 enforcement actions, compared with a mere 497 by the SEC. More to the point, while the SEC lacks the resources to investigate cases in which investors lose less than $1 million, state securities agencies are geared toward stopping small boiler-room operations.  <p> "Individual investors would feel the impact of the Fields bill in a far more direct way than they are going to notice securities-litigation reform," says Gerri Detweiler, policy director for the National Council of Individual Investors. And at a time when the SEC is facing possible budget cuts, she says, state securities cops are more important than ever.  <p> Consumer groups have energetically opposed Fields's bill, forcing him to redraft it and to surrender some key provisions, but not, it appears, the attack on state securities law. Still, H.R. 2131 faces an uphill struggle, having attracted little support in the Senate. Moreover, many congressmen feel they've already done enough for the securities industry with the litigation-reform bill. "The general feeling is likely to be. We gave you a big banana already and it caused a big commotion. We had to override the president. Now we've got other issues to deal with,'" says John Fedders.  <p> However, Fedders says that both Fields and the securities industry appear eager to pass the legislation this year. In addition, Fields has announced that he will step down at the end of his current term, and this could prompt a sympathy vote for the legislation. "He's been a good soldier, and the party leadership may try to give him a departing gift," says one D.C. insider who has been involved in negotiations over the redraft of the Fields bill. Still, this source thinks that the distraction of an election year will prevent the Fields bill from becoming law in 1996."I think you could very well see the bill pass through the House this year," the source says. "But whether it could pass through the Senate and make it to the president's desk is an altogether different question." Individual investors have a critical interest in seeing that it doesn't.  <p> The National Council of Individual Investors' other top legislative priority in 1996 is defeating a California initiative called Proposition 201. It's backed by the same Silicon Valley interests that lobbied for federal securities-litigation reform and is intended to choke investor law suits at the state level.  <p> Proposition 201 requires the loser in a shareholder law suit to pay the winner's attorneys' fees. If passed, this measure would just about wipe out investor lawsuits in California statecourts, leaving victims there with sharply reduced legal options. Faced with the risk of paying for millions of dollars in defense fees, most plaintiffs are not going to file cases without hard evidence of fraud, something rarely available before attorney shave gone through discovery. That's why the House of Representatives-- although zealous to eradicate frivolous litigation -- dumped a similar "loser pays" provision from the federal legislation. <p> "Litigation is speculative. You never know how it's going to turn out," says A. Lee Sanders, executive director of the Citizens for Retirement Protection and Security in Los Angeles. "This initiative will kill investors because there is a lack of parity in financial resources: The people who perpetrated the securities fraud will have the money, and the victims won't."  <p> While plaintiffs' lawyers have not traditionally brought many securities-fraud cases in state court, they are now expected to do so more frequently to get around the new federal securities law. That's why high-tech companies have spent $3.5 million backing Proposition 201 -- and why the National Council of Individual Investors is committed to stopping it.  <p> The vote on Proposition 201 is scheduled for March 26, around the time this issue hits the newsstands. If it passes, expect a string of copycat proposals in other states. And even if it doesn't, Pepperdine Law School securities-law professor Benjamin J. Stein says that recent victories at the federal level have emboldened opponents of securities regulation to continue the fight against fair investor laws in the states. "The blood is in the water and the sharks are circling," says Stein.   <p> Sharks? Blood? Stein's imagery may be exaggerated, but his fundamental point is sound. The securities act of 1995 does mark a watershed. After passing major securities bills increasing investor protection in 1978, 1984, 1988, and 1990, Congress reduced this protection for the first time in recent history. "The fact that both [Senators] Ted Kennedy and Chris Dodd supported this legislation tells you something about how thoroughly frustration with the securities-regulation system infects all parts of the political spectrum," says Donald Langevoort of Vanderbilt. And this bodes ill for investors in the future.  <p> Paradoxically, this political disillusionment comes at a time when the capital markets are at historic highs and ordinary consumers are entering them in record numbers. Although there's no reason for investors to do an about-face, their recently acquired sense of security about the marketplace could turn out to be dangerous. If there's one lesson investors should take from the 1995 securities act, it's that they can no longer assume the government will protect them. Instead, they may have to start getting used to defending themselves.  <p> "We seem to be moving from a world of seller beware to one of buyer beware," warns Gerri Detweiler. "The problem is that many people still don't recognize that."  <p>  <p>A SELF-DEFENSE PRIMER  <p> Your stock drops 40 percent in two weeks, or your dividend check bounces, or your broker audibly gulps when you announce plans to sell shares in that great oil-field partnership he trumpeted and then he stops returning your phone calls. A scary thought forms: Maybe you've been defrauded.  <p> HERE'S WHAT TO DO NEXT  <p>Write your broker: Send a certified letter seeking an explanation and a refund for any money lost. Include your account information, copies of any relevant documents, and a brief description of the problem. If there's no response, mail the same letter to your broker's branch manager, then to the brokerage agency's national compliance manager. "Give these things short fuses," advises Philip A. Feigin, Colorado securities commissioner. "Say something like, I'd like a response in ten days.'"  <p> Contact state authorities: If you're not happy with the brokerage's response, or if you didn't use a broker, call your state's securities agency. Then follow up with a written complaint. "Don't put it off," says Gerri Detweiler of the National Council of Individual Investors. "Your complaint could be the one that sends up a red flag at the agency."  <p> Alert the SEC and the NASD: After alerting the state agency, call the SEC's Office of Investor Education and Assistance at 800-SEC-0330. If you purchased the investment from a broker, also complain to the National Association of Securities Dealers (NASD) at 202-728-8000.  <p> Get a lawyer: If all of the above fails, as a last resort retain a lawyer. This will cost at least a couple of thousand dollars, and possibly much more, but it's the best way to recover your money. Ask for references, and hire only attorneys with experience in securities-fraud cases.  <p> If you receive a letter in the mail indicating that you area plaintiff in a class-action suit against a company in which you own stock, there's little choice but to stick with the attorney handling the case. Most investors don't have enough money at stake to file their own lawsuits.   <p> NOTE: Procrastination in these matters is not an option. The law gives you only one year after you discover the problem to file a suit -- or three years after the scam began. "It will never get better tomorrow. Act as soon as things start looking suspicious," says Feigin.  <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Ethical Investing, Legislation, Technology Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
