				<img src="">	
				<p>
				<font size=5><b>Junk-Bond Funds Can Jazz up the Mix</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/03-Junk-Bond Funds Jazz up Mix</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						March 1996 
<p>
Worth magazine/Investing  
<p>
 JUNK-BOND FUNDS CAN JAZZ UP THE MIX 
<p>
Junk bonds aren't as risky as they seem--every fixed-income portfolio
should have some.  
<p>
 By Teri Karush  
<p>
 Income-hungry investors fled into high-yield-bond mutual funds
last year, swelling junk-bond fund assets from $43 billion at
the end of 1994 to $53 billion by the end of November 1995. It's
easy to understand why: As of December 31, the annual yield on
the average junk fund was 9.25 percent versus 5.8 percent for
the average Treasury fund and 5.95 percent for the average corporate-bond
fund.  
<p>
 Are junk-bond investors chasing yields over a cliff? After all,
these bonds pay such high yields because they were issued by
companies with shaky credit ratings. Do they have a place in
the conservative investor's portfolio?  
<p>
 Junk bonds don't behave much like other bonds and consequently
have a different risk profile. For example, the prices of junk
bonds don't fall as far as those of Treasurys when interest rates
rise. In 1994, when the Federal Reserve raised the discount rate
by 1.75 percentage points and ten-year Treasurys limped to a
negative 8.3 percent return, high-yield bonds posted only a 1.17
percent loss. That's partly because the higher yields paid by
junk bonds offset falling prices.  
<p>
 But there's another reason. Junk-bond prices, like those of
stocks, are affected more by the health of the issuing companies
than by interest rates. The price of a junk bond will climb if
the issuing company starts to make more money, improving the
chances that it will be able to pay off the bond.  
<p>
 However, when the economy slows긍hich looks likely in 1996긁unk
bonds and junk-bond funds suffer. In the recession year of 1990,
for example, junk bonds showed a negative 4.35 percent total
return versus 6.68 percent for ten-year Treasurys. Corporate
earnings growth could fall from about 16 percent in 1995 to 10
to 12 percent in 1996, says Charles Lemonides, portfolio manager
with Sterling Advisors, a division of Gruntal. That will increase
the danger that financially shaky companies could default on
their bonds.  
<p>
 How great is the potential damage? Not enough to outweigh current
yields, say the experts. Lemonides, for example, doesn't expect
enough of a slowdown to make the default rate soar: It may edge
up from 4 percent, he says, but should stay below 5 percent this
year. Even the crop of bonds that are two years old or more그n
age when unwelcome surprises tend to occur, according to King
Penniman, executive vice president of Duff & Phelps Fixed Income
in Montpelier, Vermont귿ails from companies that were healthy
enough to survive the recession of 1990.  
<p>
 John Bianchi, manager of the Smith Barney High-Income fund,
says that investors should put no more than 25 percent of their
bond portfolio into high-yield funds and diversify the rest among
government, corporate, and international debt. Mark Wright, a
Morningstar fixed-income analyst, recommends three high-yield
options: Vanguard's Fixed-Income Securities High-Yield Corporate
fund (800-662-7447), which buys bonds with an average maturity
of 7.8 years and has delivered a total annualized return of 15.33
percent for five years; Northeast Investors Trust (800-225-6704),
which buys bonds with an average maturity of 7.3 years and has
returned an average of 17.07 percent annually; and MASFunds'
High Yield Portfolio (800-354-8185), which has an average maturity
of 9.5 years급lightly riskier극ut has given investors an average
annual 19.64 percent.   
<p>
  <hr>  
<p>
Copyright 1996 Capital Publishing Limited Partnership. All rights
reserved. 
