	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/03-Bonds for a New Year</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Bonds for a New Year</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/03-Bonds for a New Year</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						March 1996
Worth magazine/Investing<p>BONDS FOR A NEW YEAR
The heyday for bonds may be over. Here's the best portfolio for today's low-yield environment.<p>By Clint Willis<p>What's a fixed-income investor supposed to do now? Back in November 1994, bondholders had the best of both worlds. Long-term issues offered decent yields of 8 percent; better yet, the subsequent plunge in interest rates caused bond prices to rise, handing investors fabulous capital gains: The total return on long-term Treasurys reached more than 30 percent in the 12 months through November 1995.<p>That was then. As of January 2, yields on 30-year Treasurys were a piddling 5.96 percent, only eight-tenths of a percentage point higher than the 5.15 percent offered by the average money-market fund. Moreover, the decline in long-term rates has left little room for further capital gains. And while interest rates appear steady, higher inflation can't be totally discounted. "This is not a friendly part of the economic cycle for fixed-income investors," says Henry Gailliot, chief economist for Federated Investment Advisers in Pittsburgh.<p>A rush to money-market funds isn't the solution. If interest rates fall, taking bond yields with them, investors may regret that they didn't lock in that paltry 5.96 percent coupon__and they'll miss any capital gains to be had. Nor is this the time to load up on long-term bonds, hoping for a repeat of past increases. Investors need a portfolio designed for today's economic climate.<p>This requires assessing where inflation is headed, since bond prices will take the opposite tack. The good news is that it's hard to find a market watcher who thinks inflation will rise. The 51 economists who participated last December in a survey by the newsletter Blue Chip Economic Indicators voiced a consensus that the consumer price index would increase by 2.9 percent. That's identical to the estimated inflation rate for 1995 and even lower than the 3 percent rate that prevailed when this economic recovery began in 1991.<p>"Ordinarily, inflation increases as the economic recovery matures and productive capacity grows tighter," says Leslie Nanberg, chief fixed-income officer at Massachusetts Financial Services. Why is this time different? Take your pick:low worldwide demand for credit and labor; technology-driven productivity increases; balance sheets fattened by corporate downsizing; increased baby-boomer savings; or lower government spending here and abroad.<p>If the United States slips into a recession (only a one-in-three chance, Gailliot, Nanberg, and others estimate), inflation could drop to 2 percent and 30-year Treasury yields to 4 percent. There's also a chance (most prognosticators put it at one or two in ten) that inflation will climb suddenly if, for instance, a revolution breaks out in Saudi Arabia and oil prices soar. <p>That said, it's likely inflation and interest rates will rise only modestly in the next few years. Unfortunately, this rosy outlook is already built into the price of long-term bonds. In the near term, investors expect interest rates to decline and drive up bond prices even more. That's why they're willing to buy long bonds despite a yield that's little more than that of safer money-market funds. If those investors start worrying about inflation again, long-term-bond prices will plummet. "If something happens to overturn the consensus on inflation, we'll end up with some pretty severe losses for bondholders," says James Stack, editor of InvesTech Market Analyst in Whitefish, Montana.<p>What kind of fixed-income investment is best suited for that combination of stable inflation and flat or falling interest rates? The appropriate portfolio would concentrate on intermediate issues, capturing a total return of 6 to 13 percent in the expected environment while protecting against serious losses if rates rebound sharply. According to Los Angeles based Capital Management Sciences, which provides fixed-income analysis, such a portfolio calls for a 60 percent stake in bonds that mature in 5 to 10 years (Treasurys in this range recently yielded 5.5 percent; investment-grade corporates, 6.1 percent); 20 percent in 20- to 30-year bond issues (6 to 6.6 percent); and 20 percent in 3- to 5-year bonds (5.4 to 5.9 percent). <p>Investors can build this portfolio fairly easily by putting 60 percent in Vanguard's <a name="FUND:VBIIX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/VBIIX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Bond Index Intermediate-Term Bond</b></a> fund (6.38 percent; 800-662-7447); 20 percent in the <a name="FUND:PRULX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/PRULX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>T. Rowe Price U.S. Treasury Long-Term</b></a> fund (5.97 percent; 800-638-5660);and 20 percent in Vanguard's <a name="FUND:VBISX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/VBISX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Bond Index Short-Term Bond</b></a> fund (6.19 percent; 800-662-7447).<p>If interest rates stay steady, this mix will deliver a total return of 5.7 percent to 6.3 percent, significantly better than that of money-market funds. If long rates fall by a full percentage point, investors will pick up 12.3 percent (Treasurys) to 12.7 percent (corporates). Meanwhile, a rise in rates of one percentage point would cut the portfolio's total return to less than a percent, and if inflation doubles to 6 percent, and long rates rebound to 8 percent, the portfolio would lose 6 to 7 percent of its value.<p>Although this portfolio won't deliver the stunning 30 percent gains of last year, it should prove a slow but steady earner for conservative fixed-income investors. "The gunslingers are going to get driven back out of the bond market," says San Francisco money manager Steve Janachowski. "We're heading back to the days when bonds were for income and stocks were for capital gains."<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Bond Investing, Economy, Mutual Funds Investing, Retirement Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/4pages.gif"><br>About 4 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

					<p>

<font size=+1><b>Mutual Fund Index</b><br>
</font>						<a href="#FUND:VBIIX">Bond Index Intermediate-Term Bond</a><br>

						<a href="#FUND:PRULX">T. Rowe Price U.S. Treasury Long-Term</a><br>

						<a href="#FUND:VBISX">Bond Index Short-Term Bond</a><br>

					<p>
	
		
</td>
	</tr>
	<tr><td width=390>
	
