<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/02-When Does a Bad Year Say Sell?</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>When Does a Bad Year Say Sell?</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/02-When Does a Bad Year Say Sell?</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						February 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Investing  <p> WHEN DOES A BAD YEAR SAY SELL? <p>Despite a roaring market last year, some superstar growth funds stumbled   <p> By Tim Middleton  <p> In a year when the Standard & Poor's 500 stock index put on a heavenly performance, some of the mutual fund industry's brightest angels lost their wings. Longtime top-performing funds such as <a name="FUND:ACRNX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/ACRNX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Acorn</b></a>, <a name="FUND:CHAAX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/CHAAX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Crabbe Huson Special</b></a>, and <a name="FUND:BEONX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/BEONX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Berger100</b></a> failed to match the 29.85 percent returned by the average diversified equity fund. More troubling, in 1995, each of these funds trailed its ownlong-term track record and was outperformed by almost all other growth funds. Acorn gained 18.75 percent versus its five-year average gain of 22.42 percent. Berger 100 sank to a 19.18 percent output from a five-year level of 23.64 percent. Crabbe Huson Special eked out a mere 7.95 percent return compared with a five-year average gain of 21.61 percent, according to Morningstar.  <p> Is it time for investors in these funds to start looking elsewhere? Obviously, a single year of weakness is no reason to dump a fund that has performed well over time. But it does call for at least some investigation.  <p> In two cases Acorn and Crabbe Huson the funds' weak 1995 returns resulted from managers' following the same strategies that had earned them success before. Investors who bought these funds because of their iconoclastic managers should stick with their choices. "Part of the price you pay for above-average performance in certain years is below-average performance in others," says Earl Osborn, an investment adviser with Bingham, Osborn & Scarborough in San Francisco.  <p> But in the case of Berger 100, the fund's recent performance could signal problems.  <p> Acorn's fall from grace reflects manager Ralph Wanger's continued preference for global stocks, which faltered last year, and his indifference to technology stocks, which fueled much of 1995's market gains. In 1995 the fund put about one quarter of its assets into foreign stocks, around six times the average for a  small-company fund, according to Morningstar analyst Susan Paluch. At the sametime, Acorn, which recently reopened to new investors, maintains a relatively light technology allocation of 17.9 percent, compared with 25.2 percent for the typical small-company fund in 1995, according to John Rekenthaler, the publisher of the newsletter Morningstar Mutual Funds.   <p> That's consistent with the strategy that earned Acorn its dazzling long-term record. In 1993, for example, Acorn's heavy international weighting helped Wanger garner an exceptional 32.32 percent return."That seemed like genius," says Paluch, "and he's still thinking the same way, but the market isn't."   <p> Wanger acknowledges this: "I think international markets will do better than the United States in 1996, if for no other reason than the U.S. did better in 1995," he says. "These things tend to equalize." Investors of like mind will stick with the fund for its exposure to foreign growth stocks.  <p> Investors appear to be taking a long-term view at Crabbe Huson Special. Even though the fund's year-to-date return is dismal, it still enjoyed net inflows of cash each month in 1995. "This was obviously not people chasing hot performance," says fund manager James Crabbe. "This was people who have agreed with what we're doing."  <p> Crabbe missed the party last year by remaining true to his contrarian vision. Having bought technology stocks in 1991 before the herd piled in a move that earned the fund returns of 33.4 percent in 1992 and 34.6 percent in 1993 Crabbe sold them in 1994 before the sector started its latest run. He even went as far as short selling technology stocks to the tune of 25 percent of fund assets. <p> Crabbe remains certain the sector will tank when Wall Street begins to focus on fundamentals. For example, he expects the current shortage in computer chips to reverse in 1996 as chip-makers from Texas to Asia begin production at new plants and the economy slows. "The semiconductor industry's customers, from lighting ballast [in fluorescent bulbs] to autos, are cyclical. Why shouldn't semiconductors also be cyclical?" Crabbe asks.  <p> While Acorn and Crabbe Huson Special appear to have been merely out of sync with the market, the troubles at Berger 100 raise some questions about the basic direction of the fund.  <p> The year was full of missteps for Berger fund manager Rod Linafelter. An investment in Mexico cost shareholders when the peso collapsed. Then HMO and nursing-home stocks tumbled at the prospect of lower government reimbursements. Finally, Cyrk Inc., a company that specializes in market promotions, melted down because of a short fall in orders from client <a name="NYSE:MO"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11179"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Philip Morris</b></a>.  <p> Berger's record may be the result of more than a stretch of bad luck. The fund will begin 1996 with assets of $2.2 billion 23 percent of it in cash well above the $15 million it had at the beginning of 1991. And that may simply be too much money for a fund that built its reputation by investing in small, aggressive growth companies.  <p> Although Linafelter sees no correlation between his soaring assets and his sinking performance, Berger 100 is not the same fund it was in such golden years as 1989, when it returned 48.3 percent, and 1991, when it shot up a whopping 88.8 percent. (Assets that year ballooned from $15 million to $200 million.)  <p> Back then, it was a pedal-to-the-metal small-cap fund. Now it stop holdings are such giant growth stocks as <a name="NYSE:MRK"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10986"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Merck</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:MOT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11023"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Motorola</b></a>, Gillette, and Fannie Mae. The median market capitalization of the stocks in the fund's portfolio was recently $4.7 billion."I think it's pretty obvious they've had a problem managing growth," says Sheldon Jacobs, editor of The No-Load Fund Investor.  <p> Berger 100 could, of course, recover, but it may never return to the small-cap style that produced its long-term track record. <p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Mutual Funds Investing, Stock Market Trends

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
