		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/02-Sometimes Growth Isn't Enough</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Sometimes Growth Isn't Enough</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/02-Sometimes Growth Isn't Enough</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						February 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Investing  <p> SOMETIMES GROWTH ISN'T ENOUGH <p>A study of the Nifty Fifty shows that it's possible to pay too much even for great companies  <p> By Jim Jubak  <p> How much is too much to pay for a great growth stock? It's an  impotant question for long-term investors, especially at a time when technology favorites such as <a name="NASD:CSCO"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13494"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Cisco Systems</b></a>, as well as consumer stalwarts such as <a name="NYSE:KO"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10359"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Coca-Cola</b></a> and Gillette, are trading at sky-high prices. We set out to find an answer using a recent historical study of the famous Nifty Fifty growth stocks of the late 1960s and early 1970s. In the process, we learned that the best means for identifying reasonably priced growth stocks is a sophisticated but far from obscure measure called the sustainable earnings growth rate. It's just what it sounds like:  a way of calculating a company's potential for growth over the long term. (For another view with a shorter time horizon on how  to value growth, see Peter Lynch's column on page 29.)  <p> The Nifty Fifty were, as far as Wall Street was concerned, one-decision stocks: Buy them for the long run and reap the benefits of double-digit profit growth year after year. This idea appealed to so many people that by the end of 1972 <a name="NYSE:PRD"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11198"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Polaroid</b></a> traded as high as 97 times trailing 12-month earnings and <a name="NYSE:MCD"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10974"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>McDonald's</b></a> at 81 times earnings, versus 18 times earnings for the Standard and Poor's 500 stock index. Every student of the market knows what followed: 1973 ushered in a dive that wiped out 40 percent of the S&P's value over a two-year span. The highfliers got creamed even more severely. Polaroid dropped from $126.12 a share on December 31, 1972, to $18.62; McDonald's plunged from $76.25 a share to $29.37. Not too nifty.   <p> The perspective of history, though, provides some lessons to be learned from the collapse of the Nifty Fifty. Wharton's Jeremy Siegel, who conducted the Nifty Fifty study, recently calculated that even investors unlucky enough to have bought these stocks at their peak would have done okay if they had simply held onto them. Through May of 1995, the end of Siegel's study, a portfolio of the 50 stocks bought on December 31, 1972, would have returned 10.08 percent a year, compared with 11.23 percent for the market as a whole.  <p> The goal of Siegel's study was to demonstrate the superiority of stocks as an investment over all other asset classes. When we looked at his numbers, however, we found they contained a second lesson of value to investors.  <p> What we saw was that, on average, the best-performing growth stocks in the Nifty Fifty from 1972 through 1995 were those that traded for the lowest price-to-earnings ratios on December 31,1972. The ten stocks on the list with the lowest p/e ratios showed a mean annual return of 11.71 percent over the 22 years, while the ten with the highest p/e's returned an average of just 6.35 percent a year.   <p> The implication is that investors who refuse to pay too much for growth will do far better than those who are less discriminating. <p> Is there a technique an investor can use to know where to draw the line? To explore this issue, we asked Standard & Poor's Compustat to reconstruct the financial data for the Nifty Fifty stocks that an investor would have known at the start of the study period on December 31, 1972. Our subsequent analysis showed that the ten worst performers over the following 22 years had certain elements in common.  <p> The first was falling profit margins. While only 9 of the 41 stocks in our sample (9 Nifty Fifty companies no longer exist or trade publicly) had declining profit margins in 1972, 5 of those were among the 10 worst performers over the next 22 years.  <p> Second, the losers had high payout ratios, which measure the percentage of earnings being paid to investors as dividends. Investors pay a premium for growth stocks because high-growth companies are expected to reinvest current earnings to produce even higher future earnings. That can't happen, though, if a company  is devoting a large percentage of its  net income to dividend payments. Among the ten worst long-term Nifty Fifty picks, for example, <a name="NYSE:AVP"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10152"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Avon Products</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:LLX"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10917"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Louisiana Land</b></a>, and <a name="NYSE:IBM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10796"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>IBM</b></a> paid out extraordinarily high dividends  as a percentage of earnings in 1972: 62 percent, 58 percent, and 49 percent, respectively. <p> As a third measure, we calculated what's known as a sustainable earnings growth rate for each company. This measure is based on a simple assumption that over the long term a company's growth rate can't be higher than the return earned on investors' equity (a ratio known as return on equity, or ROE).  <p> For example, during the 12-month period ending on November 30,1995, the earnings of <a name="NASD:SUNW"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14833"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Sun Microsystems</b></a>, a computer maker, grew121 percent. But the company's return on every dollar of invested equity was just 22.56 percent. This suggests that, over the long term, earnings will probably decrease to an annual growth rate closer to 22.56 percent.  <p> Calculating a sustainable growth rate, then, involves taking the figure for a company's return on equity and multiplying it by the percentage of earnings that the company is retaining instead of paying out in dividends. This number forecasts a company's likely maximum long-term growth rate.  <p> Sustainable earnings growth rates can be very different from current rates of earnings growth. For example, <a name="NYSE:EK"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10500"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Eastman Kodak</b></a> had commendable earnings growth of 30.39 percent in 1972. But because its return on equity was just 19.8 percent that year, and because the company was paying out 41 percent of its profits in dividends, its sustainable growth rate was only 11.68 percent. Kodak ended up among the ten worst stock market performers over the next 22 years.  <p> On average, the ten best of the Nifty Fifty (over the 22 years) showed a higher average return on equity than the ten worst 19.32 percent compared with 17.97. That translates into a higher rate of sustainable growth for the top performers, 11.5 percent versus10.32.  <p> The figures on sustainable earnings growth rate also show that most of the historic two-to-one performance difference between both groups resulted from investors' over paying for stocks with inferior fundamentals back in 1972. This mistake is captured graphically by another simple formula, one of our own devising: the price-to-earnings ratio divided by the sustainable growth rate. The average result for the top Nifty Fifty stocks comes to 3.21; for the worst it's 5.44 a sharp distinction. In otherwords, investors in the stocks that turned out to be the poorest performers over the long haul were paying almost 70 percent morefor each unit of sustainable growth than were investors in the top performers.  <p> What do these measures tell us about growth stocks in today's market? To put our theories to use, we created two lists of stocks after screening the entire universe of 7,471 issues on Morningstar's U.S. Equities database. We first looked for the highfliers of the moment:  stocks with price-to-earnings ratios of at least 34.5 (or twice that of the Standard & Poor's 500), positive earnings growth for at least five years, and market capitalizations of at least $1 billion. We found 49. Second, we built a list of classic growth stocks: those with high p/e's (above the market norm of 17.25), five-year earnings growth rates averaging more than 15 percent a year, and market capitalizations of at least $5 billion. Of these we found 44.  <p> We then took both lists and calculated sustainable earnings growth rates for each stock.  <p> Among the highfliers, many current market favorites showed poor results. <a name="NASD:SBUX"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=15745"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Starbucks'</b></a> sustainable growth rate is just 8.71 percent;<a name="NASD:BSST"></a><b>Baby Superstore's</b> is only 12.8 percent. In the past year, both had huge increases in earnings 163.6 percent and 96 percent, respectively. But both also reported low returns on equity of 8.71 and 12.8. (Since neither company is paying a dividend, the sustainable growth rate of each is equal to its return on equity.) The explosive earnings growth at both companies is coming from rapid expansion and as expansion opportunities dry up, growth will fall toward the current return-on-equity numbers.  <p> <a name="NASD:ESST"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=44543"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>ESS Technology</b></a>, which makes sound-processing chips and boards, and <a name="NYSE:DST"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=44563"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>DST Systems</b></a>, a computer data-processing company, had the highest sustainable growth rates. Two more familiar names, Internet hardware maker Cisco Systems and <a name="NASD:BROD"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11907"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Broderbund Software</b></a>, followed hard on their heels with sustainable growth of 35.61 percent and 30.60 percent, respectively.  <p> Using our newly created ratio of p/e to sustainable growth, investors can compare our two lists to see which stocks offer the most sustainable growth for the dollar. Highfliers such as ESS Technology and DST Systems hold their own, showing ratios of 0.79 and 0.65, respectively. Even though these stocks have p/e's that make them seem expensive 52.78 and 39.38 their sustainable growth rates are high enough to provide strong growth for the buck. Cisco Systems and Broderbund, with ratios of 1.28 and 1.20, respectively, also deliver growth relatively cheaply.  <p> Some of the traditional growth stocks also yield high growth for each dollar invested. The top of this list is dominated by familiar names such as Coca-Cola, Gillette, <a name="NASD:AMGN"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12623"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Amgen</b></a>, and Sun Microsystems. Sustainable growth rates for these companies range from 34.68 percent for Coca-Cola to 22.56 percent for Sun Microsystems. <p> Coca-Cola, for example, shows a ratio of p/e to sustainable growth of just 0.94. Companies with relatively low current earnings growth, such as Gillette and <a name="NYSE:PFE"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11175"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Pfizer</b></a>, both promise more growth for the buck, with ratios of 1.27 and 1.52, respectively, than such high-tech favorites as Fore Systems (10.91 ratio) and U.S.Robotics (3.94 ratio).  <p> The lessons of the Nifty Fifty suggest that the true long-term investor will earn better results by buying stocks that deliver the most sustainable growth for the dollar. Gillette, for example, may not be flashy, but it offers strong odds for superior long-term returns. <p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Stock Investing Strategies, Technology Industry, Stock Market Trends 

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
