<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/02-Investing Briefs</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Investing Briefs</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/02-Investing Briefs</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						February 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Investing  <p> INVESTING BRIEFS  <p> Vanguard Gets Pricier  <p> Vanguard Group, loved by many skinflint investors for its low fees, is raising its minimum investment from $500 to $1,000 on new IRAs. In June, Vanguard will also automatically deduct a $10 annual fee on non-retirement accounts with balances of less than $2,500. To avoid the fee, investors can boost a fund above the $2,500 level or set up an automatic plan to deposit $50 a month or more. The fee will also be waived for investors who have at least $50,000 in Vanguard funds. Fidelity Investments and <a name="NYSE:SCH"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10320"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Charles Schwab & Co.</b></a> added similar fees in the fall of 1995.  <p>  <p>A Stock Ticker of One's Own  <p> Personal-computer users can now put a stock ticker on their screens, thanks to a new CD-ROM called Internet Mania. QuoteScan, one of eight components on the CD-ROM, provides 20-minute-delayed quotes on up to five stocks at a time users pay no extra per-quote fees. In addition to quotes, owners of the CD-ROM package can search for news articles and create Web pages. The CD-ROM, put out by software-maker Corel, in Ottawa, and PC Quote, in Chicago, sells for $24.95 (800-772-6735).  <p>  <p>Financial Jottings  <p> The <a name="FUND:ACRNX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/ACRNX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Acorn Fund</b></a> and its sibling, <a name="FUND:ACINX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/ACINX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Acorn International</b></a>, have both reopened to new investors. The small-cap Acorn Fund has returned an average annualized 14.8 percent over the past 15 years, <a name="FUND:JAVLX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/JAVLX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Janus 20</b></a>also reopened. The fund regained respect in 1995 by beating the Standard & Poor's 500 Index with a 37.6 percent return through December 7 after underperforming the index from 1992 to 1994. Ron Elijah, manager of the sizzling <a name="FUND:RSCOX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/RSCOX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Robertson Stephens Value+Growth Fund</b></a> up 47.9 percent for 1995 as of December 7 has been tapped to run a new technology fund, the Robertson Stephens Information Age Fund. In January, Vanguard put out the  first of 12 new simplified, plain-English prospectuses.   <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Technology Industry, Mutual Funds Investing

					</font>
