<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/01S-Top Picks for 1996</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Top Picks for 1996</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/01S-Top Picks for 1996</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						January 1996--Special Issue <p>Worth magazine/Features  <p> TOP PICKS FOR 1996 <p>To get an early glimpse of the coming year, we assembled our regular panel of topflight investment pros and asked for their thoughts about the markets. They provided not only that but also their favorite stock selections for the year ahead.  <p> Reported by Jonathan Butler  <p> In each issue of Worth, a panel of acclaimed investment pros share their favorite stock picks with readers. For this special issue, they've agreed to comment on the upcoming year as well as to disclose their two best bets for 1996. The price listed in parentheses with each choice is the maximum at which the pro considers it attractive. It should be assumed in each case that the fund managers have bought the stock for their funds. The newsletter writers may also own or control shares in the stocks they recommend. We selected the members of our panel for both their demonstrated skill and the wide range of investment styles they represent.  <p> PRESTON ATHEY <p>Athey, who runs the <a name="FUND:PRSUX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/PRSUX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>T. Rowe Price Small Cap Value Fund</b></a>, is rapidly gaining a reputation as a hot portfolio manager, specializing in value stocks with market capitalizations below $250 million. Small Cap Value was Worth's top choice in 1995 for funds of this type.   <p> ATHEY'S OVERVIEW: The coming year will be a positive one. I don't see the Federal Reserve tightening the money supply because inflation doesn't look like a near-term threat. The combination of modest economic growth and a reasonably accommodating Fed should lead to a respectable performance by the market. Growth companies (foods, health care, consumer non-durables) will benefit because their earnings will look relatively good. But cyclical companies (steels, metals, autos) will be hurt as economic growth slows. I expect a fairly strong dollar, so smaller companies should do better than larger companies. It won't be a time to bet on major corporate turnarounds. Instead, invest in the Steady Eddies.  <p> <a name="NASD:ELRC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13294"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Electro Rent</b></a> ($22) <p>Headquartered in Van Nuys, California, this $230 million company leases and rents electronic equipment, primarily personal computers and work stations. This is a growth business with expanding margins.The only competitors are local mom-and-pop stores. Electro Rentis national, so customers know it is up-to-date, has national warehouses to replace machines and parts, and has the best service and selection. People are willing to pay a little extra for these advantages. No Wall Street firms follow the company, so it trades below its potential. I expect the company to earn $1.70 a share during the fiscal year ending May 1996, up from $1.23 a share a year earlier. That puts the stock price at a reasonable multiple of 11.5. Return on equity is an attractive 17 percent and rising. Electro Rent is my fund's No. 1 holding.  <p> <a name="NASD:CMRO"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13033"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Comarco</b></a> ($12.50) <p>Comarco, located in Yorba Linda, California, has two businesses. It manages facilities for government installations, performing services that range from monitoring high-tech systems to hiring janitors. But it also has become a player of sorts in the cellular-phone business. Comarco developed a product that evaluates the quality and consistency of a cellular company's network. The cellular business accounts for less than half of Comarco's revenues, but more than half of its profits. Within a year, 75 percent of Comarco's profits could come from cellular. This is a small growth company with a $50 million market capitalization. Yet the Street still regards it as if it were a value play: The trailing 12-month price-to-earnings ratio is about 13 (far below what's typical for most wireless companies). The company's return on equity is about 20 percent. I think earnings will grow at least 20 percent annually over the next couple of years. Comarco is basically undiscovered. When investors finally do take notice, the stock could double.  <p> JAMES P. CRAIG <p>Craig, who manages the <a name="FUND:JANSX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/JANSX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Janus Fund</b></a>, invests primarily in large growth companies with the goal of preserving capital. His fund earned a five-$ rating from Worth in 1995.  <p> CRAIG'S OVERVIEW: The economy is not as woeful as is widely believed. Look for slower but consistent growth with lower interest rates in 1996. I have the most confidence in companies that have shown steady and stable growth. But cyclicals could rebound when it becomes clear that fears about a recession are overblown. The best sectors to be in will be financials, drugs, and possibly papers and airlines. My outlook is predicated on stable interest rates.   <p> <a name="NYSE:EDS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=41915"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>EDS</b></a> ($50) <p>Data-processing giant EDS (listed as <a name="NYSE:GM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10640"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>General Motors</b></a> E shares on the New York Stock Exchange) will be a huge beneficiary of the rising demand for outsourcing. Over the next 12 to 18 months it will bid on $30 billion worth of business and should get a good chunk of it as the dominant player in the field. Dallas-based EDS should have 20 percent earnings growth and 18 percent sales growth in the years ahead. I think it will earn $2.25 a share in 1996 and $2.65 a share in 1997. With a price-to-earnings multiple in the low 20s, the stock should get to $60 by the middle of next year a 30 percent gain from current levels. I also expect GM to spin off EDS in 1996, which will be a good thing for EDS shareholders.  <p> <a name="NYSE:CCI"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10345"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Citicorp </b></a>($70)  <p>Keys to the success of this huge U.S. banking company will include strong international growth and the stability of its U.S. credit card operation. I think that recent fears about credit card delinquencies have been exaggerated. New York셕ased Citicorp's aggressive, $3 billion share-buy back plan also should provide a lot of support for the stock. The current program should be over by the fall of 1996, at which point the company will probably launch another $3 billion plan. If this happens, I expect earnings of $7.65 a share in 1996 and $9 in 1997. Unless interest rates collapse, the stock could trade at $90 a share within a year or so.   <p> SHELBY M.C. DAVIS <p>Davis, who runs the <a name="FUND:NYVTX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/NYVTX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>New York Venture Fund</b></a>, invests in large companies using a value-oriented style. His fund earned a four-$ rating from Worth in 1995 and has racked up average annual returns of19.6 percent during the past five years.   <p> DAVIS'S OVERVIEW: With the economy on autopilot, the market will be defined by slowing, but not collapsing, gains in corporate profits. We'll probably see slightly lower interest rates early in the year, but rates should return to current levels by the end of 1996. Inflation will remain a nonissue. Politics will be a noise factor but won't really influence the direction ofthe market. The investing theme of the year: "Turning around battleships takes time."  <p> General Motors ($45) <p>Detroit giant GM is a cyclical-value turn around story. The automaker is cutting costs and repairing its balance sheet. It still has a long way to go to achieve margins comparable to its competitors', but its North American market share is stabilizing. GM is now putting more emphasis on marketing and is improving the way it launches new products. This is a huge industrial company, but it is learning more and more about how to operate like <a name="NYSE:PG"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11211"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Procter & Gamble</b></a> when it comes to things like brand management and savvy promotion. I think the stock could get as high as $75 a share in the next few years.  <p> <a name="NYSE:EQ"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13307"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>The Equitable Companies</b></a> ($23) <p>Equitable, which I recommended in Worth last month, is a fast-growing New York셕ased financial company with three excellent businesses: annuity and life insurance, money management (Alliance Capital), and investment banking and securities brokerage (Donaldson Lufkin & Jenrette). This broad spectrum of growth deserves a higher valuation than other insurance companies. I think this will be the year Equitable attracts more believers it's so big people can't ignore it any longer. I'm still looking for earnings of more than $2 a share for 1996. I think this could be a $30 stock by mid-1997.  <p> DANIEL B. LEONARD  <p>Leonard manages the <a name="FUND:FSFSX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/FSFSX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Invesco Strategic Portfolios Technology Fund</b></a> and has an eye for growth stocks in technology and related fields. His fund earned a five-$ rating from Worth in 1995, with an average return of 29.5 percent over the past five years.  <p> LEONARD'S OVERVIEW: The market has had some wonderful years recently, so we're due for a cold shower. I think we'll be lucky to get a 5 percent rise in stock prices over the course of 1996. If any theme will continue, it will be the merging and restructuring of American industry. No sector will be immune, especially not banking.  <p> Chesapeake Energy ($34) <p>Based in Oklahoma City, Chesapeake is one of the three most active drillers of onshore wells in the country, and investors are returning to the energy sector. This $330 million company with rapid reserve growth and good expense control has had a high success ratio at finding oil and gas. The stock, at around $30 a share, is trading at roughly 20 times my earnings estimate of $1.96 a share for the fiscal year ending in June. Yet with Chesapeake's profits growing at roughly 50 percent a year, the stock could be up to $45 within six months. Earnings should hit $2.92 a share for the fiscal year ending June 1997.  <p> <a name="NYSE:NEC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11050"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>National Education</b></a> ($10) <p>New management has turned around this company by cutting costs. Headquartered in Irvine, California, it makes educational software for technical and industrial employee training. It is the largest company of its kind with over 7,000 clients and few competitors. Targeting new small- to medium-sized clients and emphasizing client/server and networking products should boost revenues. Once the Street notices how quickly this company's earnings are improving, the stock could jump to between $12 a share and $15 a share.  <p> JIM McCAMANT <p>McCamant has a wide range of experience in the fields of technology and venture capital. His "Medical Technology Stock Letter" focuses on investment opportunities in biotechnology companies.  <p> McCAMANT's OVERVIEW: 1996 will be a good year for smaller stocks. Except for some technology outfits, smaller companies generally haven't been big winners as of late. In a continued slow-growth environment, investors will be looking for stocks that can do better than average. Improvement in small-company stocks started in 1994, but we had a correction this past fall. I expect a rebound in 1996.  <p> <a name="NASD:SMTG"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13506"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Somatogen</b></a> ($20) <p>Somatogen, with a market capitalization of $400 million, is the leader in developing a blood substitute that has the potential to be the largest single product in the biotech industry. The Boulder, Colorado, company has a great partner in <a name="NYSE:LLY"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10509"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Eli Lilly</b></a> and has just finished a successful early phase-two trial. When the biotech industry was last hot in 1992, the stock sold at $50. The company has made tremendous progress since then and now sells at $15. My 18-month target is $50.  <p> <a name="NASD:ISIP"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14081"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Isis Pharmaceuticals</b></a> ($12) <p>Based in Carlsbad, California, Isis develops therapeutic compounds. The company has the best antisense technology (which turns off RNA in the cell to prevent production of disease-causing proteins). Initial products are antivirals and anticancers. A partnership formed in 1995 with Boehringer Ingelheim focuses on anti-inflammatory drugs. The stock is around $10, off its 1995 high of $15.25. My target is $25.  <p> MICHAEL MURPHY <p>Murphy, who holds a U.S. patent on a securities-value calculator, has been writing the highly regarded California Technology Stock Letter since 1981. His focus: Identifying high-growth companies. <p> MURPHY's OVERVIEW: The big question is whether Windows 95 will finally lift off, causing corporations to up-grade large numbers of computers. Everything unrelated to PCs (semiconductors and parts) is doing fine. If Windows does start gaining ground, as I think it will, it sets us up for another year of 20-plus percent growth for PCs and semiconductors, which is more than the Street is expecting.  <p> <a name="NASD:ADSK"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12689"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Autodesk</b></a> ($38) <p>Autodesk is a major software company that makes AutoCAD software for architects and engineers. Located in San Rafael, California, the company is currently in the midst of a transition from there lease of version number 12 of its software to the release of version 13. Wall Street is nervous about how fast this change overwill occur. But this is a real growth company. The numbers are super: Pretax margins are almost 20 percent; annual earnings growth is about 18 percent. I expect the company to earn $2.40 per share for the fiscal year ending Jan-uary 1997, which means it's trading at around 16 times earnings. This is very cheap for a company that's growing fast and dominates its business. <p> <a name="NASD:EUPH"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=44511"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Euphonix</b></a> ($10) <p>Because Euphonix, based in Palo Alto, California, is a relatively recent offering, it's not well understood yet. It is a niche company that incorporates digital technology in mixing boards used in sound studios. There's a lot of opportunity because its two largest competitors make significantly inferior products. It has a well-defined market, so its marketing expenses are relatively low. I project sales to grow at a rate of 50 percent annually. Pretax margins are about 10 percent now but should be over 15 percent in a couple of years. I expect the company to earn 40 cents per share in 1996, which puts the stock price at 20 times earnings, or less than half the company's growth rate. Euphonix has two or three years of growth ahead of it regardless of what happens with the economy.  <p> WILLIAM J. NASGOVITZ and HUGH F. DENISON <p>Nasgovitz and Denison are one of our favorite stock-picking duos. Their <a name="FUND:HRTVX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/HRTVX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Heartland Value Fund</b></a> was one of Worth's top five fund picks in 1994. The two focus on acquiring the stocks of domestic small-cap companies they believe to be undervalued by the market.  <p> NASGOVITZ AND DENISON'S OVERVIEW: Retailing stocks are out of favor and unloved because they have repeatedly disappointed the Street with their earnings. Performance-driven institutions have been dumping the group, and so have individuals for tax-loss reasons. But retailers may bounce back in 1996 as they emerge from a period of considerable downsizing. Their stocks are now selling at good values.   <p> <a name="NYSE:SKO"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13430"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Shopko Stores</b></a> ($12) <p>This specialty discount retailer out Wal-Marts <a name="NYSE:WMT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11600"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Wal-Mart</b></a>. It operates130 stores in 15 northern states (it is based in Green Bay, Wisconsin) that are better looking and offer better service than a typical Wal-Mart. The stock is a great value, trading at only 3.5 times cash flow and 7.5 times 1996 earnings estimates of $1.20 a share.It also has great downside support: At $10 a share, it is trading well below its book value of $13 and paying a roughly 4 percent dividend yield.   <p> <a name="NASD:DESI"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13199"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Designs Inc.</b></a> ($8) <p>This specialty retailer offers a broad selection of Levi Strauss & Co. products plus its own Boston Traders label. The stock plunged from a 1993 high of $25 a share after earnings went into a tailspin. But things have turned around. Same-store sales at this Chestnut Hill, Massachusetts-based company are showing improvement. We expect earnings to increase roughly 30 percent to $1 a share in 1996 and to more than $1.25 a share in 1997. The stock currently is trading barely above the company's book value.  <p> LOUIS NAVELLIER <p>Navellier, who writes the popular MPT Review, uses modern portfolio theory to identify high-return, low-volatility stocks. His newsletter has been ranked No. 1 for its performance over the past ten years by The Hulbert Financial Digest. In April 1994, he launched the <a name="FUND:NASCX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/NASCX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Navellier Series Fund's Aggressive Small Cap Equity Portfolio</b></a>.  <p> NAVELLIER'S OVERVIEW: Economic growth has been accelerating faster than we once imagined. I'm finding that my buy list contains a lot more large-capitalization stocks than just a couple of months ago. The stock market's breadth and power is expanding; bonds have been strong and appear to be supporting the market. Earnings are accelerating as well. The market tends to rally in an election year. Price-to-earnings ratios are reasonable. I would guess that the Nasdaq will be up 20 percent in 1996, the Dow and the Standard & Poor's 500 indexes each up around15 percent.  <p> <a name="NASD:SMTC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12316"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Semtech</b></a> ($35) <p>Sales at this semiconductor maker (located in Newbury Park, California) are growing at over 60 percent. Margins are expanding, so profits are growing even faster than sales. The stock is just being discovered by institutions. This should really drive the price up over time. The other positive for the stock is that its on-balance volume is high, which means that there are more upward than downward ticks in the stock.  <p> <a name="NASD:ZIGO"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=15204"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Zygo</b></a> ($42) <p>Professional investors are starting to notice this Middlefield, Connecticut-based producer of precision optical equipment for monitoring manufacturing quality. As I mentioned in the December Worth, the company's profit margins are expanding and fourth-quarter sales increased 71 percent over last year's. Like Semtech, Zygo is also attracting more institutional ownership. The stock has also been behaving well its on-balance volume is very strong.  <p> ERIC E. RYBACK <p>For more than a decade, Ryback has been earning solid annual returns for the <a name="FUND:LDDVX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/LDDVX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Lindner Dividend Fund</b></a> while assuming little risk. His approach is to look for current income first and capital appreciation second.  <p> RYBACK'S OVERVIEW: Bill Clinton will want a strong economy, so he'll do everything in his power to convince the Fed to make that happen. Greenspan's election comes up early in 1996. I'd assume he'd want to stay in office, but who knows, maybe he won't. I really don't expect a very good year because I see a lot of uncertainty hanging over the market.   <p> <a name="NASD:MCOM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=15760"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Metricom</b></a> ($25) <p>Metricom installs commercial wireless data networks in large cities (San Francisco, Seattle, San Jose, Washington, D.C.) and on a growing number of college campuses. Operating in a license-free spectrum, the Los Gatos, California, company attaches its small radio units to streetlights. This enables it to provide high-speed,two-way communications and unlimited Internet access to customers for under $30 a month. Its modem configuration is included in Windows 95. Handheld communicators incorporating voice mail are under development as well. Metricom is a viable company on its own, but it is also a buyout target. The company has no earnings yet, but this could easily be a $50 stock.  <p> <a name="NASD:CHRS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12948"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Charming Shoppes</b></a> ($5) <p>Charming Shoppes, based in Bensalem, Pennsylvania, is a strip-mall retailer of women's clothing, located predominantly on the East Coast. Unaccustomed to borrowing money, the company is arranging financing that will carry it through a restructuring program to close poorly performing stores and replace a stale merchandise assortment. This plan will be carried out under the new leadership of a proven apparel executive from <a name="NYSE:S"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11338"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Sears</b></a>, Dorrit Bern, who took over as president and CEO of Charming Shoppes in October. Earnings may take a year to recover but the stock will strengthen on any sales rebound. Buy up to $5 for a return to the $7 to $9 level. <p> DAN SULLIVAN  <p>Sullivan, who has published The Chartist since 1969, has one of the most impressive long-term performance records in the investment-advisory business. He relies on technical analysis to identify long-term equity investments.  <p> SULLIVAN'S OVERVIEW: Consumer spending constitutes two thirds of the economy. So the prospects for 1996 will be muted by: 1) slow job growth, 2) record levels of household debt, 3) record low household liquidity, and 4) the impending large-scale changes in tax laws aimed at lowering the deficit through reduced governmentspending on welfare and Medicare. Cyclical and discretionary-product companies will not be able to maintain profit growth in this environment. A lower capital-gains tax would favor long-term growth stocks with recession resistance.  <p> <a name="NYSE:MDT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10981"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Medtronic</b></a> ($62) <p>If this company had a theme song, it would be "The Beat Goes On." Not only do its pacemakers keep the heart pumping properly, but it has repeatedly delivered exceptional earnings growth year after year. Located in Minneapolis, Medtronic is a leading medical technology company (about half the pacemakers in the world are produced by Medtronic). It also maintains an impressive pipeline of other cardiovascular and neurological products. It does business in more than 120 countries; almost 50 percent of its sales come from overseas markets. The success of Medtronic lies in its extensive research and development efforts. Its impressive string of new offerings has helped the company achieve an annual earnings growth rate of 19 percent over the past 5 years. The Jewel implantable defibrillator and the Thera bradycardia pacemaker have allowed the company to exceed earnings expectations of late. This positive earnings momentum should carry over through the end of the decade. <p> <a name="NYSE:UNH"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=15007"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>United Health Care</b></a> ($64) <p>United Health Care, a Minnetonka, Minnesota-based HMO company, will not be able to sustain the phenomenal growth rate it achieved during the past five years. Still, I do expect it to continue posting solid gains. As a national leader in a growing industry, UNH has positioned itself to capitalize on the switch from traditional fee-for-service insurance plans to HMOs. Its membership base has grown faster than its competitors' while at the same time its costs have remained among the lowest in the industry. The company's accelerated membership enrollment is a result of a successful strategy of growth through acquisition. It has madea science of purchasing smaller companies and effectively integrating them into its system. Its successful ways should continue, with earnings growth in the neighborhood of 20 to 25 percent over the next three to five years.  <p> RALPH WANGER AND CHUCK McQUAID  <p>Wanger and McQuaid, along with Terence Hogan, run the acclaimed <a name="FUND:ACRNX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/ACRNX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Acorn Fund</b></a>. Acorn got a four-$ rating from Worth in 1995. Wanger and McQuaid look for stocks of small-cap companies that stand to benefit from favorable economic trends.   <p> WANGER AND MCQUAID'S OVERVIEW: As we look to the future, we like the prospects for what we call downstream technology. Yes, the semiconductor stocks have been very hot. But we think that at some point capacity will match demand, and profits will suffer. The commodity-like semiconductor companies will be plagued by price-cutting and low margins. There's going to be a shift away from these types of outfits. As a result, we are focusing on the companies that will benefit from what the semiconductor companies are doing. Cable programmers and cellular franchises are examples.  <p> <a name="NYSE:OAK"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11108"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Oak Industries</b></a> ($25) <p>Headquartered in Waltham, Massachusetts, Oak produces key basic components for the information superhighway: connectors for coaxialcable, pump lasers for optical amplifiers used in fiber-optic networks, and oscillators for wireless-communications base stations. All three markets are growing rapidly as cable and telecom companies improve their infrastructure worldwide. The stock is off from its ten-year high of $32, perhaps because of a new accounting rule that requires Oak to report higher taxes than it actually pays. On our estimate of fully taxed 1995 earnings of $1.95 a share, the stock is cheap. We think it should trade at at least15 times 1995 earnings, or $29 a share.  <p> <a name="NASD:LIBT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=16058"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Liberty Media</b></a> ($32) <p>Liberty, which owns interests in 71 cable channels, was our top pick in November, and it remains one of our favorites for 1996. The joint venture it recently formed with News Corp. will be able to bid against ESPN for major sports events. The venture also will provide new broadcast outlets for Liberty's current sports programs. What's more, Englewood, Colorado-based Liberty will own 61 million shares of the merged Turner/<a name="NYSE:TWX"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11482"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Time Warner</b></a>, a company that should benefit from a number of synergies. We believe the private market value of Liberty's investments is equal to $36.50 a share.   <p> DONALD A. YACKTMAN <p>Yacktman was named Portfolio Manager of the Year in 1991 by Morningstar. In 1992, he launched the independent <a name="FUND:YACKX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/YACKX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Yacktman Fund</b></a>, which seeks long-term growth in companies with market capitalization of at least $1 billion.   <p> YACKTMAN'S OVERVIEW: Historically the market tends to correct10 percent every two to three years. The last time was in 1990, so we're definitely overdue. It's a lot like an extra-inning ball game: Will it last 10 innings or 15 innings? Fed tighteningsiphons money from long-term investments (Treasurys and stocks). So if the Fed gets worried about inflation, the market will suffer. <p> <a name="NYSE:UAM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=42135"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>United Asset Management</b></a> ($39) <p>Boston-based UAM is a holding company with 44 investment-managementsubsidiaries. The stock has gone nowhere since I recommended it in June, but I still believe in its potential. It has been pretty flat lately: The rising stock market and aggressive acquisitions have balanced out the market's fear that the company's money managers have had a decline in assets. Reported earnings for1996 will be $2.50 a share, but cash flow (which includes goodwill) is closer to $5.50 a share.  <p> <a name="NYSE:FNQ"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=15674"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Franklin Quest</b></a> ($25) <p>This is a true small growth stock; the Salt Lake City company's earnings have been growing at close to 20 percent or more formany years. Even though this growth may slow to 15 percent, it's still a very profitable company with great potential. I'm looking for the company to earn about $2 per share in 1996. The company is very focused on its main product Franklin Day Planners and is expanding its business by gradually adding seminars and retail outlets.  <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Mutual Funds Investing, Technology Industry, Stock Investing

					</font>
