				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/01S-New Year's Resolutions You Can Keep</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						We'll admit it. We're no better at keeping New Year's resolutions than anyone else. We're probably going to keep eating prime rib and chocolate cake, slicing our drives, and postponing those repairs on the roof . But one pledge: If we're going to be tubbies with wild swings and leaky roofs, we should at least have our financial house in order and earn as much as possible on our investments. that's why we asked ten respected financial planners to share their best advice for 1996. The result is a list of timely and sensible recommendations no investor should ignore. <p> By Andrew Gluck and Timothy Middleton  <p> 1. TAKE YOUR 401(K) TO THE LIMIT. Michael J. Chasnoff, Cincinnati, Ohio. There's absolutely no reason not to increase your contribution to your 401(k) plan to the limit, says Michael J. Chasnoff, a financial planner at Advanced Capital Strategies in Cincinnati. "It's a no-brainer," he says. "I see clients who are well-to-do now, but they're not saving enough for retirement. They may wind up impoverished and relying on Social Security in their old age." <p> In 1996, 401(k)s will become even sweeter deals. Federal law prevented employees from socking away more than $9,240 in a 401(k) for 1995, but for 1996 the limit rises to $9,500. The additional $260 a year of contributions may not sound like much, but crunching some numbers shows how the benefit will compound over time. For an employee who is paying 40 percent in combined federal and state taxes, whose employer is matching 50 percent of her contributions, and whose account earns a 10 percent return, that $260 a year, over 25 years, amounts to $42,191.  <p> Chasnoff emphasizes that 401(k) participants must contact their employers to maximize their contributions. "It won't be done automatically," he says. "If you don't tell your employer to go to the $9,500 limit, you might be letting tens of thousands of dollars fall by the wayside."  <p> 2. INVESTIGATE YOUR INSURANCE. Roy Ballentine, Wolfeboro, New Hampshire. Life insurance, like any other aspect of your personal finances, deserves regular scrutiny. Roy Ballentine of Ballentine & Co. in Wolfeboro, New Hampshire, advises clients to contact their insurers and request a disclosure document called an in-force policy ledger. This ledger is a statement that strips a life-insurance policy to its bones and can reveal just how secure your policy is.  <p> An in-force ledger shows a policy's current cash value. (Cash value is a feature of all life insurance except for term policies. It represents the investment side of a life-insurance policy inother words, the "extra" that represents the difference between a whole-life policy and a term-life policy.) The statement also projects how much cash the policy should accumulate in the future. For example, for a universal life policy, the in-force ledger will forecast the amount of interest income the insurer expects you to earn on your cash value after subtracting administrative and other expenses.  <p> The problem to watch out for is the potential for an erosion in the cash value of your policy. If projections show that the cash value is going down instead of up sometime in the future, you might find that your insurer will inform you that you must start paying additional premiums or face having the policy expire."We've seen lots of in-force illustrations where the projections show that unless the client puts additional funding into the policy, it will lapse well within the life expectancy of the insured," Ballentine says.   <p> Conscientious life insurance agents provide this kind of in-force analysis for their clients annually, Ballentine says. If yours doesn't, talk to two or three other agents and ask them to analyze your policy.  <p> 3. SHARPEN YOUR MUTUAL FUND FOCUS. Deena B. Katz, Coral Gables, Florida. When William Sharpe won the Nobel prize in economics in 1990, he was recognized for some brilliant insights about investment risk. Deena B. Katz at Evensky, Brown & Katz in Coral Gables, Florida, recommends applying his brain power to your own portfolio of mutual funds by using a calculation known as a Sharpe ratio to assess just how efficient your funds are.  <p> A Sharpe ratio measures how much profit you reap for every unit of risk you take. Essentially, it takes a fund's annual return rate, subtracts the return on risk-free Treasury bills, and divides the result by the fund's standard deviation. (Standard deviation is a statistical measure used to gauge a fund's volatility by showing how widely its returns tend to vary from its average return.) In practice, calculating the ratio requires crunching a lot of monthly numbers. Fortunately, you can just look up your fund's Sharpe ratio in Morningstar Mutual Funds, which is available in most libraries.  <p> Once you've found the Sharpe ratio for your funds, you can compare them against other funds to determine how much risk you're taking to earn your returns. For instance, someone might view <a name="FUND:LLSCX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/LLSCX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Longleaf Partners Small Cap Fund</b></a> and <a name="FUND:KSCAX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/KSCAX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Kemper Small Cap Equity Fund</b></a> as essentially interchangeable. Both are small-company stock funds, and both gained about 15.7 percent annually over the past three years. But the Kemper fund's three-year Sharpe ratio is 0.79 while the ratio for Longleaf Partners Small Cap is 1.23. The higher the Sharpe ratio, the less risk you've taken to get your profits. "This is arguably the single most important evaluative tool for a fund investor," Katz says.  <p> 4. TAKE YOUR CUE FROM CONGRESS. Robert Wacker, San Luis Obispo, California. With tax reform all the rage in Washington right now, it appears likely that Congress will pass some sort of capital-gains tax cut. Robert Wacker at R.E. Wacker Associates in San Luis Obispo, California, is betting that legislators will allow investors to exclude half of their capital gains from taxation. "That means it will be critical to rethink your allocation of equity and fixed-income investments between taxable and tax-deferred accounts," he says.  <p> The current system taxes all long-term capital gains at either your income-tax rate or at 28 percent, whichever is lower. That structure has prompted many investors to put more equities into tax-deferred retirement accounts IRAs and 401(k)s with the idea that those are longer-term investments. Typically, such investors would tend to put tax-free fixed-income investments usually municipal bonds or bond funds in their taxable accounts, with the idea that those funds need to be more stable and liquid.  <p> But if a 50 percent exclusion on capital gains is adopted, investment planning will be turned on its head. Wacker recommends that investors essentially reverse course, changing the emphasis of their taxable accounts to equities and putting fixed-income investments taxable bonds and bond funds into tax-deferred accounts. With the lower effective capital-gains tax rate, it's no longer quite as attractive to shield your gains on equities in the tax-deferred accounts. And, having freed up those tax-deferred accounts from equities, investors can use them to shelter the income on taxable bonds. Essentially, all this switching around gives investors the chance to move into higher-yielding taxable bonds from lower-yielding municipals without watching that edge get eaten by taxes.  <p> For an example, Wacker examined the hypothetical case of an investor whose $500,000 portfolio allocated 65 percent to equities and 35 percent to bonds. Prior to any capital-gains tax cut, this investor might be likely to have his entire tax-deferred retirement account devoted to equities, his taxable account invested 30 percent in equities and 70 percent in tax-free muni bonds. Wacker would recommend that this investor flip-flop the entire taxable account to equities while placing 30 percent equities and 70 percent taxable bonds in the tax-deferred account. It takes a fair bit of number crunching, but Wacker can show that, with a 50 percent exclusion in capital gains, switching the allocation as he recommends will net the investor around $60,000 more over15 years an increase of about 4.7 percent over the old, pre됶apital-gains cut allocation method.  <p> Wacker warns that the strategy works best if the switch doesn't involve large sales charges for either buying new investments or selling existing ones. Concentrating on no-load funds can make switching the funds around less painful. Of course, given such a complex strategy, it's wise to consult with a financial professional before making any changes.  <p> 5. BET AGAINST INFLATION WITH BONDS. J. Michael Martin, Columbia, Maryland. Bond market investors seem to be expecting a rise ininflation. J. Michael Martin of Financial Advantage in Columbia, Maryland, thinks they're wrong, so he's advising clients to buy bonds now, wait for them to rally, and then sell.  <p> Is there a deal to be had? It depends. Long-term Treasurys have been yielding about 6.4 percent while inflation has been holding around 2.5 percent a spread of nearly four percentage points. From a historical perspective, Martin argues that spread between the long bond and inflation is high. According to his research, over the last 60 years, the yield on long-term Treasurys has averaged 1.8 percentage points higher than the inflation rate. So the current spread would seem to imply that bond investors anticipate higher inflation. If they're wrong and Martin is right, then, as he says, "Bonds are on sale."  <p> "In 1996, people are going to see that we've just completed an entire business cycle without inflation flaring up," says Martin, a former research director at mutual fund company T. Rowe Price Associates. "They're going to realize inflation isn't the bugaboo it was in the 1970s and early 1980s."  <p> So Martin is telling clients to expect a major bond rally in1996, with long-term yields sinking a percentage point or more. For investors who want to speculate on the possibility of a bond rally, Martin suggests purchasing long-term zero-coupon Treasury bonds or the <a name="FUND:BTTTX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/BTTTX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Benham Target Maturity 2020 Fund</b></a>, which invests in zero-coupon Treasurys maturing in 2020. Zeroes are bought at a deep discount from their face value of $100 but pay their full face value at maturity. Because zeroes don't pay interest annually, their price fluctuates more than the price of traditional T-bonds.  <p> Of course, that cuts both ways. Consider a 30-year zero yielding 6.4 percent now. The bond is priced at $15.55 and will be worth $100 when it matures. If the yield on 30-year Treasurys jumps a full percentage point, the zero's value will dip to $11.75, a decline of 24 percent. But if a rally materializes and the30-year bond yield sinks a percentage point, the price of the zero rises to $20.64 a 33 percent gain. Either way, keep in mind this is a trading play: If Martin's predicted rally does materialize, you'll make money by selling not by holding.  <p> 6. LAND SOME INVESTMENTS IN REAL ESTATE. Judy Lau, Wilminton, Delaware. In 1995, the real estate investment market finally began to revive. Judy Lau of Lau & Associates in Wilmington, Delaware, is telling clients not to neglect real estate as part of a balanced investment strategy.  <p> "I always like to have some real estate in the portfolio," Lau says. "And this sector still hasn't had the run-up that stocks have." Property is replacing gold as the inflation hedge of choice among investment advisers, and it also produces an income stream of 7 to 9 percent a year. How much to own? Lau says 10 percent of total assets is the right amount for most investors. But some of her clients fear the entire sector. She encourages them to nibble at real estate until they feel more comfortable.  <p> The two most sensible options for participating in this new land grab are real estate investment trusts and the mutual funds that invest in them. The problem with buying individual REITs directly is that they tend to be highly focused on specific kinds of real estate, and therefore tough to assess. One REIT might own a string of shopping centers or malls nationwide, the next a complex of office buildings in a single region. Each requires different analysis: Retailers are filing Chapter 11 in droves, but some developers, particularly in North Carolina, are booming. Also, about one REIT in 20 owns mortgages, rather than properties, making analysis even more difficult.  <p> Given all that, Lau much prefers real estate mutual funds for her clients. "With REITs, there's too much even for a professional to keep up with," she says. "So I let somebody else pick the REITs to own." She's partial to <a name="FUND:CSRSX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/CSRSX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Cohen & Steers Realty Shares</b></a>, which used to have a high initial minimum but has been bringing it down; the fund is now available through <a name="NYSE:SCH"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10320"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Charles Schwab</b></a> for a minimum of $2,000. The number of real estate sector funds grew from 22 to 35 in 1995, so there are plenty of options for investors to choose from.  <p> 7. FINE-TUNE YOUR WITHHOLDING. Peg Downey, Silver Spring, Maryland. Until a George Bush-inspired reform compelled the IRS to bring withholding into line with taxpayers' likely income-tax bills, over-withholding was chronic particularly for families and homeowners. Now, however, the opposite is true. "We're seeing more and more clients in danger of being under-withheld," says Peg Downey of Money Plans in Silver Spring, Maryland. "Some are even facing penalties."  <p> Properly filled out, today's W-4 forms should result in withholding at close to the correct amount, even when husband and wife both work. But exceptions abound, especially for those who've changed jobs recently. Different employers may withhold at different rates. Also, employers are particularly prone to make withholding mistakes on state taxes. "Sometimes the headquarters of the business is in a different state, and they inadvertently send your money to that state," Downey says. She advises her clients to fillout W-4 forms carefully, scrutinize pay stubs to judge whether withholdings are appropriate, and file a revised W-4 if necessary. <p> 8. TRIM YOUR EXPOSURE ON ESTATE TAXES. If you own a business or have substantial real estate investments, Gary Pittsford of G.L. Pittsford & Associates in Indianapolis recommends that that you consider setting up a family limited partnership or limited liability company. Doing so can help you save on estate taxes and pass along more to your kids instead of Uncle Sam.  <p> Here's how it works: Real estate holdings and stock in any closely held family businesses are placed inside the partnership. Parents continue to control the assets as general partners. But because the partnership's interests aren't marketable and neither parent holds a majority of votes in the partnership, the value of the interests can be sharply discounted when they are gifted to heirs, cutting estate taxes drastically.  <p> For instance, take a couple with two kids who set up a partnership to own a small business and real estate valued at $5 million. Each parent has a $600,000 lifetime exclusion from estate taxes, so the two of them can pass up to $1.2 million tax-free to heirs. But by discounting, the couple can actually give away a lot more than $1.2 million of their assets without incurring estate taxes. Because the gifted partnership interests won't give voting control to an heir, the courts say the value of the interests can be discounted by perhaps 25 percent or more. Take another discount say around 35 percent because the partnership interest isn't marketable to the public. The parents can actually give away about $2 million of assets and discount it to stay within the $1.2 million lifetime exemption. This avoids the 55 percent estate tax rate on an extra $800,000 a savings of $440,000.  <p> 9. DON'T MISS THE POINT ON FEES. Ginger Applegarth, Winchester, Massachusetts  All investors should take the time to figure out exactly what they're paying for investment advice," says Ginger Applegarth of Applegarth Henderson Advisors in Winchester, Massachusetts. All else being equal identical investments, identical returns an extra percentage point in fees and expenses is a percentage point off your investment return.  <p> What's the big deal about one percentage point a year? Simple: Just like with compound interest, the cumulative effect can be staggering. Take the case of two investors, each earning 12 percent annually on their original portfolios of $100,000, for 20 years. To simplify things, we'll lump all fees together and assume that the first investor pays fees totalling 3 percent of her assets each year. That investor winds up with $560,441 after 20 years. But if the second investor pays 2 percent in fees each year, he'll accumulate a total of $672,750 an increase of $112,309 over the investor paying more fees.  <p> Even if your adviser is using no-load mutual funds to assemble a portfolio, you're still paying the adviser's fee plus fund-company expenses. And if a stockbroker is advising you on investments, you're paying trading commissions. A money manager investing your funds in individual stocks and bonds will likely tack an advisory fee on top of commissions.   <p> Applegarth recommends that investors add up all investment fees they've paid in the last few years and come up with the average annual amount that they're paying. Include fees to your adviser, stockbroker commissions, money-management fees, and any fund charges, such as load fees. Applegarth believes that, generally speaking, fees shouldn't total more than 2.25 percent of assets annually. (If you have more than $500,000 invested, your fees shouldn't exceed 2 percent.)  <p> What should you do if you're over that limit? Talk to your broker or investment adviser, Applegarth says. You can discuss ways to minimize fees, such as relying more on no-load funds and index funds. And if you aren't satisfied with the performance of your investments and the service you've been getting, Applegarth recommends that you seriously consider moving your money elsewhere.  <p> 10. LOOK BEYOND YOUR OWN BACKYARD. Joel Isaacson, New York City. If you haven't already looked overseas for some new investment opportunities, now is the time, says Joel Isaacson of Joel Isaacson & Co. in New York City. He thinks a repeat of1995's stock market run-up is unlikely, so he's telling clients to take some profits on top-performing domestic stock funds and shift cash into diversified foreign stock funds and emerging-markets funds.  <p> "The best investment opportunities arise when there is uncertainty," Isaacson says. One of his favorite spots is the Japanese stock market, which is down about 50 percent from its high. Diversified emerging-markets funds are also promising, Isaacson says. Data from Morningstar Mutual Funds examining 41 such funds shows them down more than 18 percent for the year ended October 31.  <p> Meanwhile, stock markets in recovering European economies have lagged behind the U.S. equities markets, with the average price-to-earnings ratio of European stocks about 22 percent below U.S. stocks. Isaacson thinks European stocks are poised to catch up in the next year or two. Asia also offers opportunities. While the U.S. economy is expected to grow at a moderate 2 percent to 3 percent in 1996, Isaacson says the Asian Tiger countries, including Malaysia, South Korea, and Hong Kong, will grow 6 to 8 percent, making them a good investment through 2000. "The greatest growth potential for the rest of this decade is outside the U.S.," says Isaacson. <p> He has been advising clients to put up to one third of their equity-fund portfolios into diversified foreign and emerging-market stock funds. Even conservative investors, he says, should put at least 10 percent of their assets into these funds. His two no-load favorites: <a name="FUND:WPIEX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/WPIEX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Warburg Pincus International Equity</b></a> and <a name="FUND:PPEEX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/PPEEX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Pierpont Emerging Market Equities</b></a>.  <p> Andrew Gluck is a Senior Writer at Worth. Timothy Middleton writes about personal finance for The New York Times and other publications.  <p><p>  <p>
KEYWORDS: Mutual Funds Investing
