		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Convertibles From the Top Down</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/09-Convertibles from Top Down</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						September 1995
Worth magazine/Advisor<p>CONVERTIBLES FROM THE TOP DOWN<p>By Jonathan Butler<p>If the market teaches anything, it's that nobody is infallible and that the prospect of rising returns carries the certainty of rising risk. Still, there is a way to get high yields and equity-like returns with relatively low risk--through the hybrid financial instruments called convertibles. Convertibles (the term covers convertible bonds and convertible preferred stocks) are securities that can be exchanged for a set number of shares of common stock. For example, the owner of Alaska Air 6.5 percent convertible bonds due in 2005 has the option to convert each bond into 46.5 shares of common stock. When they were issued at par on June 21, the common stock was trading at $17.63, making the conversion value of the convertible bonds $820.<p>According to Ibbotson Associates in Chicago, convertible bonds had annualized returns of 11.8 percent between 1973 and 1992, half a percentage point better than stocks and more than 2 points above bonds. <a name="NYSE:MER"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10990"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Merrill Lynch</b></a> estimates all convertibles yielded the same 11.8 percent annually from 1988 through March of 1995. And a March 1995 Salomon Brothers study found that, since issuance, convertible securities have realized 118 percent of their underlying stocks' gains and only 50 percent of their losses.<p>While converts, as they're called, have grown more attractive to investors (between 1991 and 1994, the market value of outstanding convertible issues rose 44 percent), they are still the Rodney Dangerfields of asset classes. Brokers don't like them because they're complicated and illiquid. Wall Street firms don't like to spend a lot of time (and money) researching them because they're generally issued in relatively small amounts. Consultants and financial advisors shun them because they don't fit neatly into traditional asset-allocation models.<p>But since convertibles' returns do not correlate closely with those of stocks and bonds, they are an excellent way to diversify most portfolios. And despite the low credit ratings assigned to most of these securities (more than half are below investment grade), shifting money to them from stocks actually increases the security of a portfolio, because converts are higher in the capital structure--meaning they will be paid off before stocks in the event of bankruptcy. <p>Most convertibles yield 1 to 2 percent less than straight corporate bonds of the same maturity. Because they are exchangeable for common stock, convertibles move in the same direction as the underlying stock. They're usually less volatile, however, in their price swings: On average, convertibles match up to 70 percent of the common stock's price appreciation, but because the price of the convertible is unlikely to fall below its value as a fixed-income investment (called the investment value), convertibles rarely suffer more than 40 percent of a decline in the common stock. <p>This positive risk-reward relationship is known as favorable leverage. As a rule, unless the common stock goes up more than 40 percent over the life of the convertible, you're better off owning the convertible.<p>The downside protection of convertibles allows you to invest in a more speculative or volatile company with less risk. Let's say that back in September 1993 you wanted to invest in the technical-training company National Education but were nervous about the stock's recent slide. Instead of buying the stock, which at the time was at $6.75--down from over $30 five years earlier--you could have bought the 6.5 percent convertible bond due in 2011. This would have looked smarter in hindsight: While the stock fell 44 percent over the next 20 months, the convertible lost less than 10 percent of its value and, after factoring in its 9.25 percent current yield, turned in a flat total return over the period.<p>Most firms that analyze convertibles do so through models that estimate their potential upside and downside. For example, Value Line Convertibles Survey is currently recommending Air Express International's 6 percent convertible bonds, due in 2003. According to Value Line's calculations, the Air Express convert is a good bet because it should share in 80 percent of the common stock's rise but in only 38 percent of a drop. "This tilts the odds greatly in your favor," says Value Line convertibles research director Barry Nelson. <p>The Air Express converts are also attractive, says Nelson, because of their low conversion premium. This is the percentage by which the price of the convertible exceeds its conversion value, its value when converted into common stock. It usually reflects the convertible's yield advantage over the common stock. As a rule of thumb, the smaller the premium, the more closely the convertible tracks the movement of the stock. At 7 percent, Air Express's premium is far below the average convertible's premium of 30 percent. With the bond currently yielding about 5.5 percent (the mean for converts), the investor needs to hold on to the bond for just over a year to break even, assuming the stock remains flat.<p>In case this all sounds too good to be true, investors should keep in mind a couple of potential problems. First, most convertible bonds are callable: The company has the option to buy back the bonds at a fixed price after a set period of time, usually three years. The Air Express bonds, for example, are callable in January 1996 at 104.2. Since the bonds are currently trading at 110, the holder would give up the 5.8 point spread if the company called the bonds, earning only the coupon yield over the remaining months.<p>Only about a quarter of convertible bonds are called and redeemed for cash, however. "Most managements don't want to cough up the cash required to buy in the bonds," says Nelson. Instead, they prefer to have investors exchange bonds for stock, which they may do only when the conversion value is above the call price. In fact, most companies wait until the conversion value exceeds the call price by at least 20 percent to guard against the possibility of stock declines during the 30-day redemption period.<p>The ideal environment for converts is falling interest rates and rising stock prices. This meant double trouble  for the group in 1994, when Fed hikes and stagnant corporate profits gave the group its worst performance, down almost 4 percent, since 1987. But for the same reasons, converts, already up 7 percent this year, are a good bet right now, says Michael Rosen, manager of the Rochester Bond Fund for Growth.<p>Since converts are less liquid and less closely followed than stocks--only about a third of the converts in Value Line's 585-company universe of convertibles are listed on an exchange--they are often priced less efficiently. For example, the bid-ask spread (the difference between the price at which buyers are willing to buy and sellers are willing to sell) on California Microwave stock rarely gets wider than three quarters of a point. The convertible bonds (5.25 percent, due 2003), however, recently traded with a 5-point spread. This means that if you bought $10,000 of the convertibles one minute and wanted to turn around and sell them the next, you would have an immediate loss of $500.<p>Individual investors may have a hard time finding buyers and sellers of small lots and, as a result, will have to pay higher prices than the larger traders. For these reasons, unless you have a lot of time and money to devote to convertibles, experts recommend sticking with one of the 32 convertible mutual funds out there. But make sure you know what you're buying: Many funds own common stocks as well as converts.<p>
