	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Stocks on TV</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/05-Stocks on TV</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						May 1995
Worth magazine/Features<p>STOCKS ON TV
Something revolutionary may be going on here, but is this any way to get investment advice?<p>By Richard Todd<p>I wonder at what point in his career Louis Rukeyser, the host of the television show Wall Street Week, became aware of his growing resemblance to George Washington and began, with the fluffing of his silver hair, the downturning of his mouth, and the studied elongation of his face, to cultivate this image. In any case, the transformation is now complete, and Rukeyser could easily take his place on the dollar bill, making him, as one senses he would like to be, perfectly emblematic of money.<p>Wall Street Week With Louis Rukeyser (its proper name) is TV's oldest money show, and for a long while it was virtually alone in covering the financial world. This year it celebrated its 25th annual new year's party, a look at the year that was, with Rukeyser and guests in black tie, none more splendid than the host himself.<p>But how long can this elegance continue? Business broadcast journalism is changing fast, and thanks to the miracles of cable and satellite you can now watch something about finance 24 hours a day. PBS offers not only Wall Street Week but Adam Smith and the business-news show Nightly Business Report. These are somewhat staid shows; the pace quickens when you turn to CNN--with its daily Moneyline and Business Day and Your Money (along with its own weekend wrap-up, Money Week) and coverage of the markets throughout the day. Then there is CNBC, which from dawn well into the evening devotes most of its odd mix of programming to business and keeps a blue line of stock quotations running across the bottom of the screen. For total immersion you go to the hyperkinetic Bloomberg channel, broadcasting around-the-clock worldwide financial intelligence.<p>I have been spending a lot of time before the screen lately, and there may well be something revolutionary going on here, but it seems important to issue one caveat. This new surge of reporting is "journalism" of a very gentle sort. It is relentlessly uncritical. Television news grows out of newspaper traditions, and the financial pages have traditionally been among the meekest in the paper. Somehow, publishers have always been more sensitive to the feelings of the president of the local department store than to those of the president of the United States. When this docile enterprise takes to the airwaves, the result is more theater than investigation. One can't, in any case, look to anything on television for adversarial coverage of business. It's like expecting an astrologer to criticize the stars. And in all fairness, that doesn't seem to be what most viewers are after.<p>Coziness with the subject has been one of the hallmarks of Wall Street Week. The show still commands great loyalty from its viewers, 8 million to 10 million of them, though they may as a group be aging more or less in step with their veteran host.The fascination Rukeyser holds for viewers, the way in which he serves as some sort of icon, remains one of those enticing little mysteries of popular culture. Rukeyser is famously overbearing and smug, in persona anyway--he's doubtless a lapdog at home. The persona must be at least part of his appeal. After all, he and his viewers aren't married to each other; people can't have stuck with him all these years despite his attitude.<p>The show has become ritualistic, beginning with a monologue from Rukeyser in which he reviews the week's news in tones of high contempt. Rukeyser is the only performer I can think of who actually sniffs in disdain. These performances are distinguished by his Tourette's-like compulsion to pun his way through loonily extended metaphors. <p>On Super Bowl weekend he went through a dozen or so football analogies. "Nickel back--in the stock market, that's what you get for each thousand dollars you were foolish enough to invest in the Elliott Wave Theory. The retailers and automakers are claiming unnecessary roughness, and many of the nation's credit card chargers are limping off the field." Later in the show Rukeyser took questions from viewers; one wrote inquiring about nursing-home stocks, and Rukeyser ended the segment by saying, "If your personal finances could use some of that tender loving care, we'd be happy to help you nurse them along. So don't be a pill; if you think you're getting the fever, just press the buzzer for one of our angels of financial mercy here at Wall Street Week."<p>Right. You feel a little bit as if you're laughing at the boss's jokes during these shows. I had ouched and grimaced my way through a number of these moments before I got the basic idea. We're invited to appreciate more than the cleverness of our host. It's an entire attitude--sportif--toward money that Rukeyser offers. <p>Here is a basic principle of money shows on television, which I think Rukeyser pioneered: They never involve the suggestion that money could actually be, well, sort of a problem. It is instead the object of a grand game. Everyone on the show, God knows, has a lot of it, and the viewer is invited to pretend that he or she does, too. One of Rukeyser's recent guests, pension fund manager George F. Russell Jr., remarked of age-appropriate investment strategies, "My grandson is 100 percent in equities, and my 86-year-old mom is 90 percent in T bills." <p>The drawing-room tone that Rukeyser maintains begins to seem kind of odd if you think seriously about the venue--television's leveling demographics mean that not everyone in the audience can have children with portfolios. Indeed, you would imagine that a number of people, in a nation that tends to live from paycheck to paycheck, might tune into this show and want to throw a brick through their screen, so distant is the program's sense of reality from the one they daily inhabit. But you can often go awry expecting people to act on their class interests in our country--it's a constant wonder, our belief in the possibility of the sudden rise that makes most Americans indulge their betters. Wall Street Week plugs right in to these cultural conditions, and what it provides is a feeling of clubbiness. Even the information it imparts comes this way, conversationally, allusively, and I'm happy to have it. To be perfectly candid, you have to sit around my dinner table for a very long time before someone will bring up the Elliott Wave Theory. For that I have to go to the table of Mr. Rukeyser.<p>Wall Street Week's rival for pride of place among long-running, influential money shows is Adam Smith's weekly production. Smith is actually Jerry Goodman, a onetime fund manager who started writing under a pseudonym, got more famous than he expected, and is stuck with his act. We are what we pretend to be. Smith earned a reputation for colorfulness, if not irreverence, in his early days as a print journalist, but now he is very reverent indeed toward the establishment he reports on.<p>The virtues of the Smith show start with his relatively self-effacing style, which leads to general liveliness. Also, the show is lavishly produced, with on-camera jaunts around the world and lots of graphics when there's no place to go. And most important, because of years in the trade and his ability to sound saucy but be nice, he has access as good as anybody's in business journalism. Thus his old friend Warren Buffett sits still for a long and quite charming interview in which the reputation of America's favorite billionaire investor is polished like an old fire engine. Smith has also recently interviewed the secretary general of the United Nations, the president of the <a name="NYSE:F"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10597"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Ford Motor Co.</b></a>, and the former prime minister of France; he tends to go to the top. <p>Smith got his start in journalism in the 1960s at New York magazine, with jaunty pieces that became his first book, The Money Game. The pieces featured fictive characters whose doings made sense of the obscure world of finance. International crisis? Blame the "gnomes of Zurich." Business was far more faceless then, and Smith provided personality. He still does, and the show is at its best when it's got a strong figure to present. <p>When the subject can't be so easily personified, Smith gets into difficulty, chiefly because he tries to do so anyway. Recently he took on the not inconsiderable burden of explaining derivatives to his audience. Presumably the audience included some people who already understood derivatives, but I think they were in danger of unknowing by the end. This was a confusing show, which illustrates another truth about finance on television: It's hard to explain anything.<p>Smith's gambit was to call the derivatives experts "rocket scientists." "Well, I think some people have used that term," said one of the interviewees, the genial David Shaw of D.E. Shaw & Co., "but I certainly wouldn't know how to get a rocket in orbit myself."<p>The show featured no fewer than half a dozen film clips and graphics of rocket liftoffs, along with a couple of shots of falling dominoes (to illustrate the domino effect) and some interesting miscellany: a clip from a Frankenstein movie and a square-dancing sequence.<p>I was probably a bad viewer; being literal-minded, when I see a picture of square dancers, I think that that's the subject, and I was watching the delicate way the old coots held their hands and almost missed Smith's explanation of why derivative trading resembled this venerable American custom. Then I realized he was talking about "swaps," just like changing partners. Oh. <p>Later I began wondering why financial questions of any complexity seem so damnably hard to get at on television. I'm not sure it's entirely the medium's fault, though linear thought of all kinds has had a notoriously bad time of it on TV. Directors and producers worry constantly about the boring presence of the "talking head." But sometimes the talking head is just what you need, particularly when you're talking about something that can't be illustrated because it can't be seen. We tend to forget that money and its instruments are themselves symbols, a language invented to represent wealth, and that by the time we get to square dances and derivatives we have symbols of symbols of symbols of symbols. Maybe you could find a good metaphor for derivatives in television programming about money: Each is a game based on what happens in another game.<p>In any case, Adam Smith is your man for entertaining scenes from current business, but not for analysis. Then again, analysis doesn't appear to be the wave of the future. The wave of the future is information, and we want our information now.<p>To my mind, the best business-news show on television is the Nightly Business Report, also a product of PBS. If this program were a person, its virtues would be self-awareness, a sense of focus and limits. It's got a mission and sticks to it--a sensible ordering of the day's financial news, a summary of the markets, major corporate developments, personnel changes, along with a nightly feature story or two, generally involving an interview keyed to the news. This is the closest television comes to rendering tomorrow's financial pages.<p>Something good happens at the subliminal level on the Nightly Business Report, which began in 1979 but enjoyed a major reformatting four years ago. A certain genius went into the casting of the show, which features Paul Kangas, broadcasting from Miami, where the show was created, and his young co-anchor, Cassie Seifert, in New York. Kangas, a former stockbroker, handles the market analysis, and he has the lingual talents of an auctioneer, which makes listening to the numbers easy. Seifert does the newsier side.<p>This is a Dan and Connie team that works. They unite the generations. Kangas is 57 and looks the way 57-year-old people used to look, unapologetic of girth and jowl, hearty of manner. ("Wishing you the best of good buys" is his corny closure.) Seifert, who's 32, is one of those post-yuppies who seem determined to transcend their age, or at least not be like the hectic, edgy generation that preceded them. With her Breck-girl hair, she could be a reincarnated spirit of the 1940s. There's a charmingly old-fashioned but competent quality to the two of them; you can picture them as a father-daughter team running a fabulously successful financial-services firm in Ohio. <p>The show has also achieved good access in the corporate world, with, to be sure, the usual price. I recently saw a Nightly Business Report interview with Louis Gerstner, the <a name="NYSE:IBM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10796"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>IBM</b></a> chairman, that couldn't have been cozier. The show's reporter asked softball questions to which Gerstner gave winningly real-guy answers. <p>"Is it time to call the restructuring a success?"<p>"Well, it's time to say that it really is taking hold. We said to the analysts early on [we had to] keep getting our gross margins to stop declining, to lower our expenses, and finally get revenues growing. And now all three are kicking in."<p>This was a reasonable exchange, a couple of guys talking about problem solving: We gotta spend less and make more! I too was feeling sort of buddyish with the shirt-sleeved Gerstner, having to remind myself that this fellow had gotten rid of 35,000 people, that there are things about his life I couldn't begin to know, that he is unimaginably powerful--and yet he was strangely miniaturized by this powerful medium. <p>By contrast to the Nightly Business Report, CNN's daily coverage of business, though more extensive, seems rather pale. CNN is, of course, on morning, noon, and night with business news, along with sports, politics, entertainment, and whatever comes along to fill the time. The network's flagship money show is Moneyline with Lou Dobbs, supplemented by the morning show Business Day, with various shorter financial segments during news programming. The CNN business correspondents--Dobbs, Stuart Varney, Deborah Marchini, the commentator Myron Kandel--have about them that melancholy look that seems to haunt so many CNN announcers, an air of small but inescapable tragedy: no date tonight, no date tomorrow.<p>Perhaps what CNN needs is a good financial crisis analogous to Desert Storm or the O.J. Simpson trial, some sort of meltdown of the Hang Seng with the crisis rolling across the time zones and a Wolf Blitzer in every panicked market--now a devaluation of the pound, now German banks failing like lemonade stands. God forbid, I know, but this would doubtless be the making of CNN business. <p>But for the moment CNN earns the faint praise of our age: It's there for you. <p>CNBC takes it to another level. For years before there was cable television, there was the dream of cable, "the wired nation" and all sorts of fanciful predictions about the glories we would see--but no one could have quite predicted the Nashville Network, or QVC, or the Golf Channel--or CNBC. CNBC advertises itself as "First in business, first in talk," signaling its bizarre mix of daylong business news and the likes of Geraldo Rivera and Charles Grodin and Phil Donahue by night. Whatever merriment goes on in the evening, from 5:30 a.m., with Before the Bell, for the next 15 hours, CNBC is all business, ending with Money Tonight. The network has just added a new personal-finance program promisingly called The Money Club.
CNBC does interviews on its noontime show Inside Opinion and corporate news on Today's Business--but the thrust of the programming is to keep the viewer as close to the markets as possible. During trading hours a ticker runs across the bottom of the CNBC screen continually, with quotations from both the New York Stock Exchange and Nasdaq. <p>Almost every money show on television at one moment or other talks about stock picks, by soliciting the views of experts, but on CNBC this is the meat and potatoes of daytime programming. Twice each day the channel's master tout, Dan Dorfman, appears live with freshly gathered intelligence on individual stocks, and these segments are repeated from time to time. Dorfman, like Adam Smith, got his start as a print journalist; he has worked for the Wall Street Journal and USA Today and contributes to Money magazine. He brings a city-room style to the game; I guess he doesn't actually chomp on a cigar, but that's the effect. The whole concept here is that he's just off the phone with a source, what he's got is hot. The length of these segments seems determined by Dorfman's lung capacity--he sounds as if he's delivering his message at a dead run.<p>My favorite players on CNBC strike a more contemporary note--they're among the varying cast of young guest stars on the feature called Buy, Sell or Hold, analysts and managers such as Liam Dalton, David Katz, and Jim Awad. <p>The format couldn't be simpler--sort of a televised radio talk show, with callers seeking advice on stocks, moderated by a CNBC staffer, most notably the friendly, lip-glossy Sue Herera.<p>"Let's go to Alabama next, and Craig is on the line." <p>"Sue, we really enjoy your show."<p>"Thanks for watching." <p>And then the caller turns to the guest advisor for his opinion on one stock or another: Buy, sell, or hold? And invariably the fellow with the baby face and the good suit knows everything about the stock!<p> <a name="NYSE:MLT"></a><b> Mitel</b>, <a name="NASD:AMGN"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12623"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Amgen</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:HUM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10756"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Humana</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:WH"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11634"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Whitman</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:CCI"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10345"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Citicorp.</b></a> Buy, sell, or hold?<p>"Middle of an up move tax-loss bounce candidate was at eight and an eighth 18 months ago... could go to 45, showing some topping action can only give it a hold." <p>These guys are amazing. In their brains, up there in that spot behind the forehead where most of us have a screen saver, or maybe a half-remembered smile, they have nonstop stock tickers. <p>For their part, the callers are impressive too, rather moving if you take them as a cross-section of investors, their voices stretching from the redwood forest to the New York island. Boy, sell, or hoild? Bah, seal, or hol'? Bissell O'Hole? Bassail Oho? Sometimes I think the callers are just playing stump the expert. But if so, good luck.<p>"<a name="NASD:QCOM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11436"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Qualcomm</b></a> about 23 today already had a serious correction--from 33 it went down to a low of about 20 a high-multiple stock I'd rather avoid initiating a buy." <p>They sound like idiot savants, the sort of people who just happen to remember that April 21, 1758, was a Friday, but I don't know: Maybe they're just savants. Listening to Liam Dalton one day, I had the feeling that if I called in to ask his view of Keats, buy, sell, or hold, he'd quote a few lines from "Ode on a Grecian Urn," point out that the Romantics were due for a cyclical recovery, and suggest I buy. <p>Anyway: Smart guys. They're smart. It's not clear that I am any smarter having listened to them. <p>This is, after all, a very odd way to get investment advice: rapid-fire from someone you don't know, who's giving the same wisdom to hundreds of thousands of other people who are sitting at home diddling with their portfolios.<p>But I may miss the point. <p>CNBC provides a more electric, up-to-the-minute sense of belonging, of playing the great game, than you can ever get by luxuriating around Louis Rukeyser's conference table. It's the sense that everything is possible, the rush of the market coming right into your living room. This is the sheer joy of information for information's sake. <p>Knowledge is power, or so say the powerful. But information--information is something else again. I am beginning to think it is more like a drug--the opiate of the moneyed masses, the curse of the investing class. I seriously doubt that Warren Buffett receives--or wants to--as much sheer information as is available daily to the viewer surfing from CNN to PBS to CNBC to--the state of the art in raw information delivery--Bloomberg TV.<p>I'm sure it will get better than this--soon they will be able to hook up Quotron electrodes into your skull as you sleep, or Chicago commodities prices will be broadcast into your bathroom mirror, or your car won't start if London gold falls below $369. (Don't leave home until you sell those mining stocks.) But for the moment, what we have is Bloomberg, and it's pretty good. <p>The Bloomberg channel is the latest venture of Michael Bloomberg, the former Salomon Brothers trader whose second fortune rests on the financial data terminals he invented, called "Bloombergs." He's into self-eponymizing. There is also Bloomberg, "a magazine for Bloomberg users," and Bloomberg radio. <p>Bloomberg television features a distinctive format that doesn't depend on any technical breakthrough, just a kind of courage. It pushes split-screen technology to the edge. At any moment you are apt to be watching five or six different panels. Up in the upper right-hand corner sits a hapless, often rather disheveled announcer who seems to be trying to shout above the silent roar of information on the screen.<p>This is all stuff that's doubtless good to know. Within any couple of moments, you might learn the price of light, sweet crude in New York; the America's Cup trial standings; the most active stocks on the Toronto Stock Exchange and the closing Straits Times index in Singapore; the prices of May bellies and December beans; the ten most popular names (in America) for boys; the ten most popular names for girls; how many points Shaq is averaging per game; the Paris CAC index; and the good news that it's 13 minutes till the Idaho ski report appears. <p>The Bloomberg screen has what at first seems a liability, until you realize that this is the heart of its genius: It is physically impossible for the brain to register all the information that appears at any one time. For a certain kind of viewer, for the information junkie, this is pure heaven.<p>It can be disconcerting at first. The way the human mind used to work--I truly think this era may be passing--we would, when confronted with a variety of information, try to make sense of it. Make a list, prioritize, organize into a narrative. Try to answer the basic question: Why are they telling me this stuff, anyway?
But the question has no answer. Forget it. They're telling you because they know. They're telling because if they didn't the screen would be empty.<p>Let it happen to you. I occasionally turn to Bloomberg just for the pleasure of it. I let the information wash over me, picking up a fragment here and there, perhaps, despite myself, trying to puzzle it out. Maybe jodhpur sales are up in Japan, French girls are being named Marie again, cellular phone stocks were off in Sydney yesterday (or was it tomorrow?)--isn't there a play here somewhere? But no, mostly I just enjoy the rush of information past my skin. You might as well try to make sense of the surf itself. <p>------------------------------------<p>DISCLAIMING STOCK ADVICE<p>By Jonathan Butler<p>The remote control has become a new investment tool: At just about any hour of the day, TV viewers can now tune in to a diverse menu of financial advice. The question is, is any of it good?<p>While most financial programs are eager to dispense endless stock tips, they are equally anxious to avoid any association with the actual recommendations. This applies to shows on CNBC, CNN, and PBS. A spokesperson for PBS's Adam Smith says, "We're not in the business of selling stocks. If any guest offers advice, it's his opinion." Says Louis Rukeyser: "I have never recommended or disrecommended any security, and I have always been at pains to remind our viewers that nothing is endorsed by the management, meaning me." The bottom line? Guests pick stocks. Hosts don't.<p>The guests are usually recognizable specialists from the securities industry. Yet even so, they're not always right. As Dan Dorfman recently said on CNBC, "The pros I quote are not infallible." <p>Some programs issue disclaimers that pop up on the screen at show's end. On CNBC's Buy, Sell or Hold, it's this: "The investment and stock advice given in this segment is from our guest and not from CNBC." Other programs don't bother. "Since CNN does not make recommendations, CNN does not feel it is necessary to issue a disclaimer,'' says spokeswoman Karen Kemp.<p>Disclaimers may suggest good intent by management, but they wouldn't necessarily hold up in a court of law. "If somebody sits there talking falsities for five minutes and then there's a disclaimer, that doesn't wipe--both the guests and show can be sued,'' says Alexander Greenfeld, a Washington, D.C., lawyer specializing in libel. The First Amendment covers the right of someone to state an opinion, including whether a stock will go up or down, and securities law gives people the right to issue information. Trouble begins if a guest knowingly gives false advice, has an undisclosed financial stake in the recommendation, or acts "with reckless disregard for the truth," says Greenfeld. (According to the shows and to lawyers questioned, no financial talk show has been sued to date. Factual errors are often corrected on air.)<p>Most shows say they don't track the performance of their guests' recommendations. Bloomberg examined the stock picks Dan Dorfman made during a single month (March 1992) and found that they returned an average of 21.4 percent over the next 12 months, more than double the Standard & Poor's 500's return of 9.5 percent during that period. Norman Fosback, publisher of the Fort Lauderdale based Mutual Fund Weekly, surveyed nearly 2,000 stocks recommended on Wall Street Week between 1980 and 1992 and concluded that they barely underperformed the Dow if sold 12 months after their mention.<p>Rukeyser dismisses Fosback's survey as phony and accuses the newsletter writer, whom he won't refer to by name, of "smearing his betters." Rukeyser's own survey--on the securities picked by his 23 new year's panelists from 1989 to 1993 and "sold'' 12 months later? Considerably rosier, beating the Dow by three percentage points.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Stock Investing Strategies

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
