	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/05-When P/E Doesn't Mean Gym Class</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/05-When P/E Doesn't Mean Gym Class</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						By Elizabeth Macdonald<p>
If asked to select just one tool for evaluating a stock, most securities analysts undoubtedly would choose the price-to-earnings ratio--the number you get by dividing a company's share price by its profit or net income per share.<p>
The p/e, also known as the multiple, gives investors a single number that allows them to compare the values of stock prices. The higher a stock's p/e, the more investors are paying to share in that company's profits.<p>
Price-to-earnings ratios are driven, to a large degree, by earnings expectations. If investors are highly confident a company will improve its profitability or remain profitable, they are usually willing to pay more for its shares, raising the p/e. If profits are threatened or weak, the p/e will probably drop as investors demand compensation for the risk of disappointing returns. <p>
Price-to-earnings ratios also depend on how stocks compare with other investment opportunities. For instance, p/e's generally fall when interest rates rise, because bonds, CDs, and other fixed-income investments yield more and so become more attractive.<p>
Analysts use different p/e ratios to gauge a company's prospects. There's trailing p/e, which is the stock's current price divided by the company's reported earnings per share for the most recent four quarters. This is the most widely quoted figure in newspaper stock listings. It reflects actual results, as opposed to estimated, or forward, p/e, which is arrived at by dividing a stock's current price by analysts' forecasts of earnings per share for the next four quarters. <p>
These two numbers may vary widely. Consider the current share price of Oxford Health Plans, a managed-care company in Darien, Connecticut. Based on trailing earnings for the year ending 1994, this company has a p/e of 54, compared with 17 for the average stock in the Standard & Poor's 500 index. The stock's forward p/e, however, is 35. Is the stock way overpriced, slightly ahead of itself, or accurately priced? Often, the answer depends largely on the attitude of the analyst or investor toward Oxford's prospects. The forward p/e is often used by brokers pushing a particular stock.<p>
The price-to-earnings ratio also allows an investor to analyze a stock's valuation on a historical basis. Divide the stock's p/e by the p/e of the overall market; that's the relative p/e. Compare this with the stock's relative p/e over the past five to ten years. When a stock is trading below its historical relative p/e, that's often a sign that it's a cheap buy.<p>
Rick Pucci, director of research for IBES, a stock-research firm in New York City, says, "Investors can get a more accurate gauge of how expensive a particular stock is by comparing its p/e with that of other similar companies in the same industry." Also, Pucci notes, "for cyclical companies, there's the opposite effect." Such firms--producers of machine tools, cars, and steel--generally reach their highest p/e's when earnings have struck bottom and investors believe the business cycle is about to turn around, raising profits. <p>
KEYWORDS: Stock Investing Strategies

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
