	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/03-Beyond Brokers' Picks</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/03-Beyond Brokers' Picks</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Your broker may not show you the best buys in small-cap stocks. Here's how to find them yourself.  <p> By Gretchen Morgenson  <p> There is a very good chance that the stocks of smaller companies will be profitable for investors in 1995. Large-capitalization stocks were investors' choice last year, when they showed big earnings growth. Because small caps--those with market capitalizations of $100 million or less--tend to lag big caps, this could be their year.   <p> But will your broker, the person you rely on for many of your stock market ideas, tell you about the best bargains in small caps? Perhaps not.  <p> Not that there's some conspiracy at work. It's just that the high-paid research drones of Wall Street tend to shun fine companies. The reasons for this mostly have to do with--surprise--money.  <p> Start with corporate-finance work. Brokerage firms are attracted to companies that need to raise cash, because the firms get paid to help such outfits float additional equity or issue new debt. A positive research report on a potential customer can make the difference between winning and losing this business. It's not exactly quid pro quo--it's just how things work.  <p> Another huge source of profits for Wall Street is over-the-counter trading operations. It is here that firms make markets in Nasdaq stocks. Most Nasdaq stocks carry higher spreads than those shares listed on the New York or the American stock exchanges; those hefty spreads--the difference between what investors get when they sell shares and what they pay to buy--go directly into the brokerage's pocket. This is why Wall Street firms are much more willing to tout the OTC stocks they make markets in than recommend listed shares of small, obscure companies.   <p> Then there are the fees a firm can make providing so-called executive services to corporate chiefs. These include selling insiders' shares on the open market or allowing insiders to borrow against restricted stock held in their name at the brokerage. All profitable reasons to keep relations with the company smooth. Upbeat research reports help.  <p> Recent shrinkage in Wall Street firms has also reduced the numbers of analysts; those that remain feel compelled to cover mainstream companies. And, oddly enough, research analysts at some firms never taste their own cooking. They choose not to invest their money in stocks they recommend or in equities of any kind. A broker at a major firm who handles many analysts' accounts says, "I think it's outrageous they don't put their money where their mouths are."  <p> What's this all add up to? Individual investors are likely to hear only about stocks that Wall Street must recommend--the big household names, for example--or that a firm feels chummy with. That leaves a lot of respectable stocks out in the cold.  <p> Investors have to track them down alone. The few research boutiques that specialize in digging up Wall Street's buried treasures usually report their findings to institutional investors, such as money managers or fund chiefs. They get paid for their work by executing these institutions' trades.  <p> Michael Reisert, president of J.M.R. Inc. in Fort Lauderdale, Florida, specializes in uncovering unknown companies. "I always look for something that's misunderstood by Wall Street, a hook," he says. "Something that will happen in the future that will make a company's earnings come on."  <p> Investors who want to go solo in small-cap stocks should begin by identifying trends with staying power. Then, figure out the best ways to play those trends.   <p> For instance, radio is in a renaissance; talk radio is the rage and industry ad revenues are rising. Since most radio stocks trade at 12 times cash flow, the trick is to spot a company that's cheaper than the rest (and doesn't deserve to be). Another example: Surging truck sales are creating a bull market for suppliers to the big diesel makers. Instead of buying Consolidated Freightways, look for a lesser-known company that will benefit from truckmakers' growing needs.   <p> Once you've identified an appealing industry, narrow the field. There are several characteristics Reisert and others like him look for before they feel comfortable investing in a company. These include:  <p> Large ownership by management. Top management should own at least one quarter of the company themselves. That way, their motivations are the same as yours. Check the proxy statement. <p> Little or no debt and little need for fresh capital. Debt-to-equity ratios shouldn't exceed 15 percent, or else the company's growth could be sidetracked by the need to service borrowings. Raising new capital dilutes the holdings of existing investors. Calculate debt-to-equity by dividing the company's total liabilities by its shareholder equity.  <p> A management that can verbalize its plan for the future. The company must be able to articulate a credible business plan for at least the next two years. Small-company managements are usually more available to discuss plans with investors; if they're unwilling, look elsewhere.  <p> A product or system that's difficult to replicate or as close to being unique as possible. You don't want to invest in a me-too company; you want a specialist.  <p> Little or no institutional ownership. Your goal: To own a stock before institutions spot it. Therefore, less than 10 percent of a stock should be held by institutions now. (A company spokesman can tell you this figure.) As the company increases its market value into the mid-cap range--to $100 million or more--it will begin to hit institutions' radars. When the bigs start buying, think about selling.  <p> Some companies that meet these criteria, according to small-cap specialists:   <p> <a name="ASE:GNK"></a><b>Globalink</b> (ASE: GNK, $15) produces language-translation software for use on personal computers; translations are 90 percent grammatically correct. Competitors produce gear only for mainframes. Sales rose 90 percent in the first three quarters of 1994.   <p> <a name="ASE:NTN"></a><b>NTN Communications</b> (ASE: NTN, $6.50) is an interactive TV network producing sports-related and trivia game shows. Balance sheet is virtually debt free; revenues rose 52 percent in first nine months of '94.   <p> <a name="ASE:PLX"></a><b>Plains Resources</b> (ASE: PLX, $5.75), an oil-exploration concern with a book value around $10 a share, has one of the few oil-storage facilities up to environmental code in Cushing, Oklahoma, through which all Gulf of Mexico oil must pass. Debt is a bit higher than the other stocks here, but operating management has nearly its entire net worth invested in the company.   <p> <a name="OTC:PRNI"></a><b>Premiere Radio Networks</b> (OTC: PRNI, $7), the fourth-largest U.S. syndicator of radio programming, has low debt and trades at eight times cash flow. Management owns two thirds of the company; institutions own under 8 percent. The cheapest play on radio.  <p> <a name="OTC:WMCO"></a><b>Williams Controls'</b> (OTC: WMCO, $3.50) earnings are growing 50 percent a year; the stock trades at 12 times earnings. The company makes digital throttles that diesels need to meet Clean Air Act standards.   <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Stock Investing Strategies

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
