	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/03-The Oracle of the Bond Market</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>

				<img src="">	
				<p>
				<font size=5><b>The Oracle of the Bond Market</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/03-The Oracle of the Bond Market</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						March 1995 
<p>
Worth magazine/Advisor  
<p>
 THE ORACLE OF THE BOND MARKET 
<p>
Learning how to read the all-important yield curve  
<p>
 By Manjeet Kripalani  
<p>
 What's the best move for an investor who wants to buy a bond?
Is it better to snap up bonds that offer higher yields but mature
over longer horizons? Or would it be smarter to settle for a
lower rate on one that pays you back faster?  
<p>
 You could ask your broker or money manager for help in answering
this question. Or you could do as the pros do and divine where
to stash your cash yourself with the help of the yield curve.
Understanding this tool and how it works can help you make the
best choice in buying bonds 긆ne that provides the optimum combination
of yield and maturity.  
<p>
 Those who know how to look at the curve and read its meaning
also can glean information important to all investors. For the
yield curve is the bond market's oracle: It tells how the bond
market views the future at any given moment.  
<p>
 The yield curve is actually the name for a simple line on a
graph that plots the interest rate paid by bonds of similar types
but different maturities. There are many yield curves, but the
most widely followed is the one for Treasury debt, which lists
three-month bills to 30-year bonds. The horizontal axis of the
graph measures the length of time until each bond matures. The
vertical axis, meanwhile, measures the yield of each bond. The
higher the points on the line, the greater the interest paid
by the bond.  
<p>
 Normally, the line slopes upward. That's because longer-term
investments (the ones plotted on the right side of the graph)
carry more risk and thus must pay higher rates of interest as
compensation. In the case of Treasurys, which are guaranteed
by the U.S. government, the primary risk is inflation, which
reduces the worth of a bond's coupon payments as well as its
eventual redemption value.  
<p>
 Occasionally, the curve slopes downward and is said to be inverted.
Such an event took place in 1981, when short-term yields approached
20 percent but 30-year bonds yielded only 14 percent. This inversion
occurred primarily because the market believed the long-term
risk of inflation was much less than the short-term threat. The
last time this happened was 1989.  
<p>
 When both short- and long-term interest rates are roughly the
same, the curve is said to be flat. That is how most of the line
looked when we began the new year (see below). Two-year Treasurys
yielded 7.63 percent, 30-year bonds 7.86 percent. That's a tiny
spread, and it means that the market currently sees little difference
between the short- and the long-term risks of inflation. So investors
who buy longer-term bonds currently receive only a slight premium.<p>
<p>
 A year ago, the spread between the 2-year note and the 30-year
bond was over two full percentage points, or 200 basis points.
The spread between the 3-month bill and the 30-year bond exceeded
300 basis points. Thus, the yield curve looked much different:
sloping more steeply.   
<p>
 But then an overheated economy and inflation fears caused Federal
Reserve chairman Alan Greenspan to become alarmed. To cool things
down, the Fed moved to increase short-term interest rates, making
borrowing more expensive for consumers and businesses. The Fed
hiked rates six times in 1994, starting in February. Yields on
the 3-month Treasury bill jumped to 6 percent from 3.03 percent,
and the long bond went from 6.23 percent to around 7.86 percent
in a year. This is what gave us the predominantly flat curve
we had in January.  
<p>
 Notice, however, that the January yield curve has a bend between
the two- and three-year maturity mark. This is called a shoulder,
the place where the curve turns from steep to flat. Typically,
the shoulder is where investors can find the ideal combination
of the highest yield with the least maturity. "The curve is cheap
just now for short maturities," said Rich Suttmeier, yield strategist
at Smith Barney, earlier this year. Two-year and three-year notes
were thus smart buys.  
<p>
 The curve changes daily, of course, as investors trade billions
of dollars worth of Treasurys. What will the curve resemble in
the coming months? That depends largely on the prospects for
inflation.  
<p>
 When the curve is mostly flat, as it is now, another effective
strategy is to buy at both ends of the line. "It's the barbell
effect귿eavy on two ends," says Ashok Varikooty, Treasury strategist
at First Boston. The effect allows for what essentially is a
hedging tactic. By buying both of the ends, short and long, investors
can ensure that their total bond holdings will remain balanced
whatever happens with interest rates in the future.  
<p>
 The yield curve can be especially valuable for longer-term investors.
Those with shorter time horizons should place more emphasis on
their own needs. For instance, someone who plans to cash in a
bond in three years for a down payment on a home should buy one
with an equivalent maturity. That way, the home buyer will know
exactly what to expect upon redemption of the bond.   
<p>
 The other option, buying a bond with the intention of selling
it on the open market prior to redemption, carries an additional
level of risk긊he threat that interest rates will rise and undercut
the underlying value of the bond. Of course, rates could drop
and produce a nifty profit. But such speculation is chancy. The
bond markets are probably the most efficient in the world긄eaning
that at any given moment the probability that rates will rise
or fall are equal.  
<p>
 The yield curve is published every day in Investor's Business
Daily and The Wall Street Journal. Buy Treasurys through a mutual
fund, a broker, a bank, or a commission-free government program
called Treasury Direct. For information, call (202) 874-4000,
or write Department of the Treasury, Bureau of the Public Debt,
Washington, D.C. 20239. An account will be opened in your name,
and you'll be given an auction schedule.   
<p>
  <hr>  
<p>
