<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/11-The Great Bond Caper</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>The Great Bond Caper</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/11-The Great Bond Caper</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						November 1994
Worth magazine/Feature<p>THE GREAT BOND CAPER
How did the biggest-ever bank heist become linked with a bunch of small-timers in a seedy New York neighborhood? Well, it all started when Anthony Lama  tried to get two bookies off his back ...<p>By Christopher Byron<p>At the Seaview Diner in South Brooklyn, the ambience has more flavor than the food. Neither could be called four-star -- but in hard-bitten Canarsie, New York, charm is a relative thing.<p>Just steps from the windswept marshes of Jamaica Bay, the Seaview is a leatherette haven from the dank projects and embattled row houses outside. There's calamari and fried peppers, and Mr. Sinatra will fly you to the moon for a couple of quarters in the jukebox -- a nice distraction from the corner boys who hassle old women in the neighborhood.<p>Canarsie is graffiti and intimidation, discount shoes and chop shops. There's no such thing as easy money in this neighborhood; Wall Street's canyons aren't visible from here, and they might as well be a million miles away. Canarsie's major contact with international commerce comes in the scream of transatlantic jets making their final approach to the runways of John F. Kennedy Airport.<p>Yet it was here in Canarsie that the seeds were sown for what might be called the great bond caper. Linking huge robberies in Wall Street and the City of London, it became a wild ride through the world of high finance that would eventually involve a bloody murder, a hoard of famous paintings, international terrorists, and several hundred pieces of paper each worth more than $1.5 million.<p>Five years later a criminal probe into the caper has stalled, and mystery still shrouds the most spectacular element: the largest unsolved robbery in history, a half-billion-dollar heist of notes issued by the Bank of England.<p>On a late winter's day in Canarsie in 1989, however, all of that still lay in the future. This yarn, much of which has never been told before, started more modestly here in the Seaview, as two local bookies convened in a well-worn booth to put some pressure on a man who owed them a gambling debt.<p><p>The heavies were straight from central casting. One was named Robert Rosenfeld, at 230 pounds a hulking meat slab of a man. His partner was Ted Ballison, a Brooklyn gym teacher who flashed around town in a Jaguar equipped with a cellular phone. The man sitting opposite them was Anthony Lama, a back-office clerk who was having trouble making his vigorish -- the interest on his gambling debt, which now ran to $350 a week.<p>Lama was a likable but not terribly bright young fellow. After graduating in 1972 from Xavierian High School in Brooklyn with a mediocre record, he had dropped out of community college. He managed a local Baskin Robbins ice cream shop before starting as a bank clerk for $7,500 a year. Then a friend offered to get Lama a Wall Street job -- working at Salomon Brothers for $12,000 a year.<p>Dazzled by the salary and prestige, Lama leaped at the chance. And according to his personnel file, Salomon's new hire turned out to be conscientious and hardworking. His job was to help log all the bonds that Salomon traders bought and sold for clients each day. Trading in such securities is done on computers, of course. But when a transaction is completed, an actual piece of paper usually changes hands. That's what Lama did for Solly: He kept the paper moving.<p>In the 1980s, few firms on Wall Street were more important in the bond market than Salomon; its expertise helped fuel that decade's debt explosion. And like the rest of America, those in Salomon's back office weren't immune from this cult of leverage. Though Lama's salary rose steadily to reach $20,300 plus bonus in 1985, his debts rose even faster. According to an investigator's report prepared for Salomon, Lama owed more than $10,000 on his Citicorp credit cards and another $1,000 to <a name="NYSE:AXP"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10085"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>American Express</b></a>. He also owed $6,000 on an auto loan and had unpaid bills at stores including Macy's and Sterns.<p>To climb out of his hole, Lama turned to gambling. A friend introduced him to Rosenfeld and Ballison around this time, and Lama started betting with the bookies. He didn't do well. In fact, by Thanksgiving of 1987 Lama had declared bankruptcy. And though he neglected to list it on his Chapter Seven decree, his most crushing burden was to Rosenfeld and Ballison. According to FBI records, Lama owed the sharks $20,000 -- nearly a full year's salary.<p>Depositions, affidavits, and pleas in a subsequent criminal investigation detail what followed. The bookies offered Lama a deal: He could pay off his debt by borrowing the $20,000 from them at 3 percent a week. Cornered, his credit destroyed, Lama felt that he had little choice. And for a while, he was actually able to make his interest payments.<p>But Lama had become addicted to gambling, and, incredibly, he kept on betting with his new bankers. As a result, despite scraping up $17,000 for Rosenfeld and Ballison from friends and family, Lama soon owed the bookies $15,000 all over again. By year's end 1988, the clerk was ducking phone calls from his creditors on a regular basis.<p>Finally, in February of 1989, the bookies caught up with him. In a sit-down at one of the Seaview's formica tables, Lama agreed to resume paying vigorish at a reduced $200 a week. But he stopped again almost immediately. And so, when the three men sat down again at the Seaview a few weeks later, there was no deal on the menu. According to Lama's statements to the FBI, Rosenfeld and Ballison began threatening to harm his family. It was time to make good on his debt, they said. To drive the point home, Lama told the feds, Rosenfeld pulled back his suit jacket to reveal a holstered revolver. The bookies deny that any threats were made.<p>In any case, what happened next would change the lives of many people, from a high-living Houston businessman to an undercover agent to a motley crew of figures from England's underworld. None of these dubious characters ever met Tony Lama, but all would be affected by the clerk's hasty solution to his gambling problem -- stealing from his employer to pay off the bookies.<p><p>Lama worked at Salomon's offices at 55 Water Street, in the heart of New York's financial district. His area was known as the cage -- a space stacked with bonds and certificates, constantly monitored by video cameras. Lama had toiled in the cage for years, and he knew what the cameras could see. Just as important, he knew exactly what they couldn't see.<p>Lama's actions are detailed in a federal indictment, the FBI case file, and two internal reports prepared for Salomon Brothers. At quitting time on St. Patrick's Day in 1989, shortly after meeting with Rosenfeld and Ballison in the Seaview, the former model employee carefully choreographed his moves and walked out the door of the cage with $700,000 in corporate bonds.<p>It was as simple as that. And when the bonds were discovered missing a few days later, nothing much happened. The theft had occurred on a "settlement day," when huge volumes of paper get shuffled at houses such as Salomon. The general assumption was that the bonds had been misplaced, so company officials did little except note the disappearance, search the area, and go about their business. The bonds were expected to show up eventually.<p>By contrast, Lama's willingness to steal wasn't lost on Rosenfeld and Ballison, who took the notes from Lama and told him of a millionaire buddy in Texas who would hold them as collateral against Lama's debts. In the meantime, Ballison says in court records, the bookies urged Lama to deliver as many bonds to them as he could. Several weeks later, on April 28, Lama obliged with another theft.<p>This time the clerk walked out with $135,000 worth of New York State Job Development Authority bonds. Just days later, Lama stole another $150,000 in bonds -- stowing them at his home on New York's Staten Island, he claimed, so he could bribe Rosenfeld and Ballison if they came to threaten his life or his family.<p>By now, close to $1 million worth of securities was missing from Salomon's vault, and Lama's biggest haul was still to come. The grab occurred on August 29, when Lama turned up for work and walked out the door with a stunning $6 million in commercial paper from <a name="NYSE:GM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10640"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>General Motors</b></a> Acceptance Corp.<p>Unfortunately for Lama, Salomon officials were watching. Having at last realized that bonds were disappearing from the cage, the firm's security personnel had secretly augmented the area's camera system. Lama was caught on videotape stealing the GMAC bonds.<p>Faced with the prospect of a Salomon-administered polygraph test, the clerk confessed his crime and was handed over to the FBI. From there the feds had an easy ride to Rosenfeld and Ballison, apparently leaving just one more man to bring in -- Mark Osborne, the Texan who was holding the stolen bonds for Lama's bookies.<p>But real life seldom follows a script. And as the FBI probed deeper into this seemingly minor case, it began to take on international dimensions.<p><p>Like Tony Lama, John Mark Lee Osborne was a compulsive gambler who lived beyond his means. Unlike Lama, however, Osborne carried it all off in grand style. The subject of repeated investigations and sanctions by the Securities and Exchange Commission, Osborne wound up barred from the securities industry. But he still lived in the swanky Hunter's Creek Village section of Houston and managed to maintain a seemingly respectable family life with his wife, Virginia, and their college-age son. As a gambling client of Rosenfeld's, this crooked financier was a natural destination for Lama's stolen bonds.<p>Some bonds are almost like money: They're not imprinted with the owner's name, so they're essentially the property of whoever holds them. Fencing such "bearer" bonds is a delicate matter, however. Face values are large enough that the serial numbers of stolen notes are easily circulated; reputable dealers will check to see if a bond is hot.<p>Still, if the instruments are passed through enough uninformed hands before they're identified as stolen, the issuer generally has little choice but to honor them. The ideal buyer of a hot bond, therefore, is overseas: In theory, the bonds won't be tagged as stolen until they arrive back in their home country -- by which time they'll have been laundered clean.<p>Rosenfeld and Ballison had sent many of Lama's bonds to Osborne, but Osborne had no intention of holding them. Faced with money problems, he decided to see if he could sell the notes in Europe. Through a friend he hooked up with an English con man named Keith Cheeseman. It was a partnership that would turn out badly for both of them.<p>Cheeseman himself was a piece of work. To borrow a line from Tom Jones, it was the universal opinion that he was born to be hanged. With his laughing eyes and round, full face, Cheeseman had charmed the knickers off half the women in London's East End. But even more than a ladies' man, Cheeseman was a brazen and lifelong fraudster, with a string of arrests and convictions that stretched back to the early 1970s.<p>To please his wife, Kerry -- herself the former owner of a Mayfair escort agency -- Cheeseman had tried to go straight for a while in the 1980s. But the effort hadn't worked. Now here was a Texan who wanted to fly to London to talk to him about a deal involving some bonds. "So I said fine," recalls Cheeseman.<p>Not long afterward, Osborne turned up as promised. "He arrived with this Zsa Zsa Gabor lookalike bird," says Cheeseman, describing Osborne's mistress, Alice Walker. "They checked into a suite at the Savoy Hotel and started this glorified drink-up that went on for days."<p>Osborne had arrived with a briefcase of the GMAC bonds, claiming to have plenty more back in Houston. Intrigued, Cheeseman agreed to come to Texas to see for himself. In January of 1990 he did so, followed by Kerry. The two visited with Osborne for ten weeks.<p>"He had this multimillionaire lifestyle," says Kerry Cheeseman between mouthfuls of cold poached lobster and souffle at London's Carlton Towers Hotel. "Every car he had was black or gold. He took us everywhere -- the Houston Racquet Club, all the most exclusive places. He was known everywhere. But he had no manners. I mean, he would throw peanut shells on the floor and pay the waiters $50 to pick them up."<p>The quartet -- Osborne, Walker, and the Cheesemans -- cut a tacky swath across Houston, as Osborne spent lavishly and behaved like a boor. Kerry Cheeseman says she was especially mortified by Walker's appetite for garish display. "She used to shop two or three times a week on Mark's charge card at Neiman Marcus," she recalls. "But the woman had no taste. I mean, one time she bought this atrocious pair of fur boots for the rodeo."<p>Both Cheesemans recall Osborne's obsession with gambling and cite it as a reason they felt he couldn't be trusted. "He said he had these colossal debts," says Kerry. "Seven digits at least. But he was always working some wild angle. I remember he actually talked about having his wife bumped off and collecting the insurance."<p>By the time the Cheesemans returned to England in March of 1990, Osborne was frantic to place some of the Salomon bonds somewhere. The Texan soon appeared in London once more, apparently in hopes of fencing one of the notes. The man he wound up talking to was a shady English character named Ray Ketteridge. Cheeseman tells of attending a meeting between Osborne and Ketteridge at the home of a local lawyer.<p>As Osborne tried to unload the certificate, says Cheeseman, he boasted wildly to Ketteridge about his banking connections back in the U.S. -- and the braggadocio seems to have impressed Ketteridge. Nothing much got done at the meeting, but federal officials charge it wasn't long before Ketteridge acted on his new friendship, irrevocably linking Lama's thefts to a far more sensational crime.<p>That crime happened just days later: On May 2, a courier was robbed at knifepoint on a street in the City of London, England's equivalent of Wall Street. In broad daylight, the thief got away with 301 bearer bonds, almost all of them issued by the Bank of England and worth 1 million pounds each. It was the biggest armed robbery in history, dwarfing famous jobs of an earlier era such as the Great Train Robbery. In U.S. currency, the haul amounted to about $500 million.<p>Ketteridge seems to have had no part in the actual robbery. Yet only a day or two after the mugging, Cheeseman says, Ketteridge called him and asked for Osborne's phone number in Houston. "He led me to believe he had some of the Bank of England bonds," says Cheeseman, "and that he wanted to unload them with Mark."<p>Ketteridge couldn't be reached for his side of the story. But in a surreptitiously taped interview for a British documentary called The Biggest Robbery in the World, the Englishman says his alleged role in the affair is a case of mistaken identity.<p>In any event, Cheeseman says he indeed hooked Ketteridge up with Osborne. By doing so, he closed the loop between the two bond robberies. Unknown to the con artist, however, the FBI had already cracked open the Salomon case and was tracking Osborne's moves. With Cheeseman and Ketteridge involved, the feds apparently believed they had stumbled upon a massive conspiracy -- a transatlantic ring of bond robbers who had looted Salomon and were now emptying out the Bank of England.<p><p>To tackle the thieves, the FBI set up a sting. By July 31, 1990, Mark Osborne had arrived in New York City for what he thought was a date with the Mafia. In his briefcase he had ten stolen Bank of England bearer bonds, each worth 1 million pounds. From his room at the Grand Hyatt, he headed around the corner to Ryan McFadden's Bar & Restaurant. His contact's name was Tony, supposedly a member of a New York organized-crime family.<p>As Osborne understood it, Tony had agreed to buy all ten bonds, which a federal indictment says were in turn supplied by Ketteridge. For the first certificate, the mob would pay $204,000. For the rest they would work out a deal later, if the initial deal went okay.<p>The meeting went off exactly as scripted. The Texan produced one of the bonds from his briefcase. Tony took it, then suggested that the two step outside so Osborne could get paid. But once the two had left the restaurant, FBI agents swooped down upon them, handcuffing the stunned Osborne and taking him into custody.<p>"Tony," it turned out, was really an FBI agent named David Maniquis. The entire scenario was designed to snag Osborne, already in trouble for fencing the Salomon bonds, for the Bank of England job, too. After the arrest, Osborne was advised of his rights and agreed to become a cooperating informant. His mission: To lure Ray Ketteridge to the U.S. so the feds could bag him too.<p>In reality, of course, the two bond robberies were linked mostly by happenstance -- and furthermore, Ketteridge hadn't played a key role in either one. Nonetheless, Osborne was soon making nervous phone calls to London, saying that Tony the mobster wanted to deal with Ketteridge personally.<p>Instead of rising to the bait, the cagey Ketteridge dispatched a bag man to New York: Jeffrey Kerschel, also known as Jeffrey Kershaw, a lawyer he thought he could trust. Too bad for all concerned -- for, amazingly enough, Kerschel was working as an undercover informant for London's Scotland Yard.<p>To complicate matters still further, Kerschel says Ketteridge's order to fly to New York was so last-minute that the solicitor couldn't properly inform his controller at Scotland Yard before hopping on a plane. As a result, confusion reigned when Kerschel met with Tony -- each unaware of the other's undercover status -- for a replay of the sting that had snagged Osborne.<p>That night, Scotland Yard learned that its man had been arrested by the FBI in New York while trying to collect money from an undercover agent masquerading as a Mafia crime figure. The British cops quickly concluded that their agent had been out to double-cross them and refused to speak up for Kerschel when the FBI asked for verification of his claim to be a British agent.<p>Thereafter, Kerschel's life careened from one nightmare to the next. Forced by the FBI to become a secret informant, he was compelled to make more than a month's worth of FBI-monitored telephone calls to Ketteridge and others back in London, in the hope it might still be possible to lure Ketteridge himself to New York. <p>Nothing worked, so the FBI soon gave up the effort and left the British authorities to pursue Ketteridge. Meanwhile, as U.S. prosecutors in the case saw it, at least they still had Kerschel. In September 1990, says the solicitor, he was told that the U.S. government would press charges against him. Free on a recognizance bond, Kerschel promptly fled the country. One obvious reason was his fear of what might happen if he hung around much longer -- for in a startling and macabre development only days earlier, Mark Osborne's body had been found wedged in the back seat of a car parked in a shopping mall in Houston.<p>The Texan had been killed "gangland style," as FBI files put it -- two bullets to the back of his head. To this day, his murder remains unsolved. But to those involved in the bond robberies and their aftermath, the rubout seemed to send a clear message: Don't cooperate with the cops. By such a standard, Kerschel was now doubly exposed. He had cooperated with the police in England and in the U.S.<p>On the run, the solicitor couldn't claim protection from either set of lawmen he had helped. The FBI wanted to convict him, while Scotland Yard pretended not to know him. For Kerschel, the bond caper had become a terrifying trap.<p><p>Recently arrived in London from Cyprus, where he beat off an attempt to return him to the U.S., Jeffrey Kerschel sits with his back to the wall of a restaurant, sweating profusely and behaving like a hunted man. He says he's been expelled from his men's club and denied a license to practice law. He spent 14 months under virtual house arrest for extradition hearings in Cyprus. Exposed in headlines as a snitch, he's certain that sooner or later there will be an attempt on his life.<p>"This whole thing has been an absolute nightmare for me," he says. "And all I was doing was trying to help my government."<p>How did he get into this mess in the first place? As Kerschel tells it -- self-servingly, to be sure -- he had been an upstanding London solicitor in early 1990 when a client from Athens approached him for help negotiating the underground sale of a hoard of paintings: the famous Beit collection, stolen in 1985 from a manse in Ireland by a gang with links to Irish terrorists.<p>Excited by the situation, not to mention the prospect of a reward, Kerschel felt it was his duty to notify Scotland Yard. He agreed to become an undercover informant, and his secret snitching led to the recovery of a $10 million work by Breugel. Meanwhile, his cover remained intact.<p>Almost immediately thereafter came the Bank of England bond robbery. According to Kerschel, within days his Greek chum showed up once again -- this time with a photocopy of one of the stolen Bank of England bonds. He claimed he had access to plenty more like it. Agog, the solicitor told Scotland Yard about the turn of events and was designated an informer in this case, too. Soon, he says, he was dealing with who else but ... Ray Ketteridge.<p>But despite his eagerness to help, Kerschel could play only a minor role in solving the Bank of England case. The reason is simple: Ketteridge wasn't among the clique that plotted the crime, says Tom Dickenson, the detective who headed the City of London's push to recover the stolen bonds. Rather, he was just one of many routes used to unload the paper when the crooks' original plan fell apart.<p>"The villains were faxing copies of the bonds all over the world," says Dickenson. "Frankly, they just weren't very clever." Perhaps, but they've still eluded capture so far. Virtually all 301 bonds have now been recovered, in locations from Miami to Singapore, and Dickenson insists that London police know who the culprits are. Much of the evidence points toward involvement by Irish terrorists.<p>But curiously, the English courts have never convicted anyone in the world's biggest robbery -- not even Ketteridge, who was arrested when police found nine stolen bonds in his car. When Ketteridge was brought to trial in 1992 in London, the prosecutor for the Crown stunned the courtroom by announcing that the government had decided not to proceed, vaguely citing "the interests of the state."<p>Dickenson is evasive on this subject. But apparently the British have a well-placed mole, perhaps in the IRA, whom they didn't want to expose in court. "We had an informant" is how one English official puts it. "Someone on the inside. We knew that we couldn't get convictions without revealing his identity, so we made a calculated decision not to go forward. We basically had no choice."<p>It also remains a puzzle why Kerschel was cut loose by Scotland Yard and left to fend for himself from the FBI sting onward. But it's clear the former snitch has reason to fear for his life: Mark Osborne wasn't the only person in the great bond caper to meet a grisly death. In a British echo of that killing, a career criminal believed to have been the stickup man in the Bank of England robbery was found murdered in his East End flat in December of 1991. Police believe he was killed for fear he had turned informer.<p><p>Back in the U.S., federal prosecutors had problems too. While the original indictment listed 12 people as codefendants in the case, only one received a lengthy sentence: Keith Cheeseman, the crooked charmer -- who, ironically enough, had played no role in the Salomon or Bank of England bond robberies.<p>Cheeseman was seized in the Canary Islands in January of 1992 and pleaded guilty to conspiracy and transporting stolen goods. He was sentenced to six years in prison; at press time he was due to be released early, and sat in a New York holding cell awaiting deportation to England.<p>Meanwhile, our opening trio from the Seaview Diner -- Lama, Rosenfeld, and Ballison -- all got relatively mild treatment. Lama, the actual thief, became an informant for the FBI and was rewarded with five years probation and no jail time at all. He still lives on Staten Island; through his lawyer, he declined to comment for this story.<p>What of bookies Rosenfeld and Ballison? They plea-bargained and wound up receiving three and a half years and one year in prison, respectively. Both men have yet to serve out their sentences in the Salomon case -- Ballison's stretch began in July, while Rosenfeld is still appealing his punishment.<p>Neither bookie would comment for this story, but they have both been back in the news since they triggered this whole chain of events. Even as they negotiated their deals in the Salomon case, prosecutors have charged, Rosenfeld and Ballison continued to run a bookmaking operation from an apartment building in Queens, New York, not far from Canarsie. They were busted last winter. Ballison pleaded guilty again and was scolded with a painless sentence -- a $5,000 fine and no jail time. Rosenfeld pleaded not guilty; his case is still pending.<p>After almost five years, the great bond caper had come full circle, ending as it started with a small-time gambling hustle born in a neighborhood far removed from the canyons of Wall Street. <p>Christopher Byron is a contributing editor of Worth<p>

