		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/08-Rights Offerings: Should You Buy In?</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
They're no free lunch, but ignore them at your peril.<p>By Jonathan Burton<p>It sounds like an offer you can't refuse: The closed-end investment company whose shares you own offers you rights to buy one additional share for each four you own -- and at a price 20 percent below market value. Has the fabled free lunch finally appeared on your table?<p>No; it's just Wall Street raising money again. Rights offerings are by no means gifts; they cost you whether you buy into them or not. <p>If you don't subscribe to the rights offering, the value of your existing shares get diluted by those issued to honor the exercise of the rights. And if you do, further dilution can occur if some of the fresh cash you pony up feeds the brokerage industry's fee mill. The best course to take if you want to remain a shareholder and minimize potential for loss is to sell the amount of shares you hold the rights to and then exercise those rights. That way you will come close to breaking even. The worst option is to do nothing. <p>The markets have been awash in rights offerings by closed-end funds, whose shares are traded in securities markets rather than sold and redeemed by mutual fund organizations. From January 1992 through April this year, 59 closed-end funds raised $3.3 billion through rights offerings, according to Chicago-based fund watcher Morningstar. Many closed-end funds have enlisted brokerage firms to promote their offerings, normally paying them between 3 percent and 3.75 percent of the proceeds. <p>Closed-end fund managers like such deals because, unlike managers of open-ended funds, they see none of the cash that changes hands when investors buy and sell shares every day. To raise fresh cash for investment, closed-end funds sell new shares. Distributing rights to existing shareholders is the best way to make sure an offering succeeds. <p>Fund managers may argue that the more money there is under management, the better off shareholders are. Neither portfolio theory nor investment experience validates this view. It is, however, undeniably true that the more money that management manages, the better off management is. <p>Why do shareholders barely break even, if that, in a rights offering? Let's say you own 100 shares of a closed-end fund with a market value of $10 a share. You and other shareholders exercise your rights to increase your holdings by 25 percent, one new share for each four shares held, at a price of only $8 a share.<p>You started with 100 shares worth $1,000 and you've just paid $200 for 25 new shares. If all that new cash goes to the company, your 125 shares should now be worth $1,200, or $9.60 a share; you have just about broken even. If you'd done nothing and let the rights expire, your 100 shares would be worth only $960, a 4 percent decline.<p>Never again wonder why the market value of closed-end fund shares shrinks after a rights offering is announced. If you plan to exercise your rights, wait until the latter part of the subscription period, when any uncertainties about the offering would have surfaced. Shareholders who don't want new shares can offset or minimize dilution of their existing shares several ways, depending on the deal's terms. Rights have an intrinsic value: the difference between the cost of exercising them and the value of the shares acquired. So you may be able to sell your rights when they start trading.<p>Non-transferable rights -- those you can't sell -- are a bit different. These, too, have value. If you don't want to add money but want to preserve your holdings, sell as many shares as you hold rights to, then exercise them.<p>You'll have to time this carefully. Typically, it takes two to three weeks from the time the offering is announced until the day the rights become shares, called the record date. However, you cannot sell your original shares until the ex-rights date, four trading days prior to the record date, if you want to receive your rights.<p>Suppose you own 300 shares of a closed-end fund with non-transferable rights to buy 100 additional shares at 80 percent of their $10 market price. On the ex-rights date, the shares will trade down to $9.50 each; your 300 shares are worth $2,850. Sell 100 of them for $950 using the proceeds to exercise your right to buy 100 new shares at $8 each, or a total of $800.<p>You keep the $150 in cash, minus transaction fees, plus 300 shares that, after dilution, are worth $2,850. Total:$3,000, just what you started with. Had you done nothing, you would have lost the $150, less transaction costs. <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Mutual Funds Investing, Market Trends

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
