				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/06-Know a Bear When You See One</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
Like bull markets, bears follow predictable patterns.<p>By Jim Jubak<p>What to call this market? A true bear - one of those periodic bloodlettings that cost investors 25 percent or more - or merely a correction that has almost run its course? <p>Trouble is, bear markets look exactly like corrections early on, says James Stack, editor of the InvesTech Market Analyst newsletter. Stack voted with the bears last January, advising readers to raise cash levels in portfolios to 60 percent. Now he's estimating that the bear will last until early fall. <p>That's short-lived compared to most major bear markets since 1937 but more drawn out than the 1987 and 1990 declines. Those were atypical, Stack says, lasting two and three months respectively - far short of the 16.5-month average. <p>Bear markets typically unfold in steps. They might begin with a 7 to 10 percent drop - so swift that no one can get out - like the one that began in late March 1994. Then prices stabilize or rally slightly as investors decide to buy on the drop. Another fall is followed by another small rally - known as a bear trap - that's "just enough to get investors to put a little money back in," Stack says. And tech stocks often get clobbered first and hardest in a bear - check out <a name="NASD:INTC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13787"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Intel</b></a> and <a name="NYSE:MOT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11023"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Motorola</b></a> in mid-April.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Stock Market Trends

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
