<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/03-Part 2, The Commuter</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/03-Part 2, The Commuter</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Nicholas Wren knew his daring stock play would be the gamble of his life. But he didn뇺 know how much he had on the line. <p>By Colin Harrison.<p>Can a man find salvation in the stock market? Nicholas Wren is betting he can. At the end of Part 1 of 늆he Commuter, Wren had just confronted the man sleeping with his wife and was faxing an order to his broker: Short RemoteCount뇹 stock for all the money he could put his hands on, nearly $300,000. It뇹 a huge gamble. But Wren knows something about the company that the analysts don뇺: Problems with electromagnetic radiation at Remote-Count뇹 headquarters will force the company to virtually shut down operations. Wren plans to clear up to $250,000 on the bet듨oney that will allow him to move his family away from New York and back to his wife뇹 hometown in Ohio. Money that he hopes will save his failing marriage.<p><p>Nicholas Wren was sitting in the backseat of a late-model <a name="NYSE:C"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10334"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Chrysler</b></a> Fifth Avenue, speeding north through a gray winter morning on I-270, a spotless ten-lane artery spoking out from Washington, D.C., and again he was agonizing over the price of RemoteCount stock. Again!등hen he should be worrying about this morning뇹 presentation, which, potentially, promised a huge contract, a bigger annual bonus, possible promotion. All he could think about was RemoteCount. His every dollar was riding on the bet that the stock would fall. He뇫 shorted 5,700 shares at $47듮he price couldn뇺 stay there for long. He was sure of it. Hadn뇺 his analysis been correct? Hadn뇺 he weighed all the factors? Oh, but if he뇫 known how nerve-racking this business was going to be, well, then he뇫 never have듍o! That was not the way to be thinking. He had to have faith! Faith! Without it he뇫 be lost. It had been three trading days since Jane Chung, his broker, had executed the order, and since then nothing! Well, yesterday the stock had crept up, just half a point, just enough to terrorize him, and before getting the 5:14 home, he뇫 needed to stop off at a bar outside New York뇹 Grand Central and knock back a couple just to relax.<p>And now the market had been open for nearly an hour, and he didn뇺 know what was happening! 뉷on뇺 turn into a quote junkie on me, Nicholas, Jane had warned. 뉼f there뇹 anything important, I뇳l let you know. In other words, don뇺 bug me. Jane was right; he needed to maintain his composure. He looked out the window hoping for distraction. The highway flowed through the newest paradigm of American civilization듢leaming exurban office parks, townhouses rolling over what used to be cornfields, the landscape tidy as a microchip. He hated it. What he wanted was an Ohio farmhouse tucked away on a bumpy lane, a couple of old maples in front, a few acres out back. That was the plan, to make a bundle on RemoteCount and move Lisa and the kids to<p>Now wasn뇺 the time to be thinking of this. In a few minutes the car would pull into the parking lot of Girardi Corp. Nicholas뇹 task was to hustle the services of his employer, Belton Associates, an engineering consulting firm. According to the research prepared by Nicholas뇹 office, Girardi had grown from an $18 million house contractor to a $277 million office-complex developer. The Washington metropolitan area had kept growing through the Bush recession. Why? Its traditional suburbs, like Chevy Chase, were insanely expensive; the federal government뇹 payroll kept growing; D.C. itself was more or less segregated; and the city was staggeringly violent, even by New York standards. And the newer suburbs were far enough north that one could actually commute to Baltimore듡or a developer, what could be better? Too bad Girardi was privately held.<p>The company had seven projects in the pipeline, each worth more than $40 million, and some of its younger executives had begun to worry about electromagnetic-field radiation등hich is where Belton came in. The office buildings Girardi had under construction required powerful electrical systems for their tenants, who often had as many computers as people. No one had absolutely proved that high EMF levels caused cancer, but the research, nationally and internationally, suggested a correlation, and there was a whole school of lawyers who had made a specialty of EMF liability cases.<p>Nicholas was here to propose to Girardi Sr. a consulting arrangement드 three-year training and project-oversight deal. Belton Associates would train Girardi engineers and architects to avoid high-level EMFs in their new buildings, thereby lessening the threat of expensive lawsuits. It could mean a lot of money for the firm. Just yesterday, Bart Belton himself had come by Nicholas뇹 office to ramble on about how the deal might help them get more business in the Washington market, develop a relationship with a deep-pockets company, even create the possibility for joint <p>But the RemoteCount stock! What was it doing? He leaned toward the driver. 뉻ow long before we get there?<p>늉e got about nine, ten minutes.<p>Time enough to call Jane. He hoped that RemoteCount had already started to drift downward. He picked up the car뇹 cellular phone. Jane was there on the first ring.<p>뉽ane, hi, I뇴 in D.C. this morning.<p>뉼뇴 surprised you didn뇺 call me from the shuttle.<p>늉e were landing. The phones didn뇺 work. How뇹 it look?<p>늉ell, the market뇹 started to rise on the lower oil prices ... wait a sec.... He could hear her tap her keys. 뉴ll right, here등ell, no, RemoteCount뇹 up a quarter point.<p>늂n top of yesterday뇹 half point.<p>늉ell, the Labor Department released some numbers saying more people have jobs. That means more insurance claims for RemoteCount to process. Good for the stock.<p>He straightened his tie. 늁ot good for me, Jane.<p>뉼뇫 say not.<p>Up three quarters of a point, multiplied by the 5,700 shares; he was down about $4,300. He wasn뇺 about to panic, right? Scared money always loses. Some investment guru had said that. To contemplate panic is to panic. Sounded like a Chinese philosopher. 뉽ane, you mind if I give you a call at the end of the day?<p>늁icholas, if there뇹 any kind of significant action, I뇳l call.<p>늋ou can leave it on my voice mail in New York.<p>Next he phoned Lisa at the small law office where she worked part time in their suburb outside New York City. It was a general-purpose law firm, but Lisa had developed an odd specialty든xamining the medical depositions of people who had been in car accidents.<p>뉻i, he said. 늋ou just get in?<p>뉹ew minutes ago, she answered.<p>뉻ow뇫 you sleep?<p>늉ell enough. Her every word a bomb thrown in his direction.<p>늉hat do you have going today? More human misery?<p>늋es, Nicholas, more misery.<p>Fake charm was only going to get him trouble. 뉼 think I can make it home just after dinner. I뇳l try to make the 4 p.m. shuttle.<p>늂kay.<p>늂kay? he pressed.<p>늋eah, okay.<p>뉼s that an 넲kay, that뇹 great, it뇳l be nice to see you? Or 넲kay, try to choose a plane that has no working engines?눖<p>늁icholas, we뇼e both got long days ahead of us.<p>늂h, come on. I got my sad ass up at five o뇪lock this morning in the cold, and I뇴 just looking for a little cheap affection from my wife.<p>He heard her sigh, followed by a long pause as she considered what level of conflict she wished to pursue. <p>뉼뇼e got to get off, she said. 뉼뇴 expecting a call from London.<p>뉾ids fine?<p>늆heyre fine. Tommy said he had a nightmare.<p>늉hat did he딊<p>뉼뇼e got to get off here, Nicholas. I뇼e got to get off.<p>늂kay. We should see a movie sometime.<p>늋eah, we should. Bye.<p>He hung up. Things would get better with Lisa after the RemoteCount deal. That was one of his operating principles. If the deal worked, then he might appear to her as more than the irritating man who got off the train each night and ate dinner in her dining room. To contemplate panic is to panic. Perhaps that applied to a marriage, too. <p>
The car rolled into the girardi corp. office cluster, and a minute later he was gulping coffee in a huge conference room, wondering again if RemoteCount had started to fall, and then all the Girardi executives came in and he forced himself to concentrate on the business at hand등hich he did, performing quite a nice sell job on old Girardi Sr., a big-bellied man with hands that had once grasped hammers and power saws. Girardi Sr. seemed skeptical of anything he could not touch himself, but he had clearly seen the worry in the faces of his young vice-presidents who were helping him make so much money. <p>So Girardi Sr. was receptive, and Nicholas듮hinking ahead to the home he뇫 soon be buying in Ohio든ven slipped in a question about what kind of seed Girardi Corp. used in the lawns around its office parks. Girardi brightened. 뉾entucky bluegrass, he boomed. 늅tick it in on any kinda soil.  <p>With the obvious success of the meeting, Nicholas was hoping he could shrug off RemoteCount뇹 three-quarters-of-a-point rise. Worry and youre lost; believe and you뇼e won, he뇫 heard a failed television star profess on a late-night infomercial, and so, no, he was not going to worry. He believed in his heart that once RemoteCount뇹 EMF troubles became more widely known, the stock would drop. Jane had said that most of the RemoteCount stock was held by the pension funds and they뇫 probably dump it all at once, causing the stock to nosedive. So he뇫 sit tight. RemoteCount would drift along at 47, okay, maybe 48, and suddenly drop. Maybe he뇫 graph the stock뇹 falling price on his Mac using the Microsoft Excel 4.0 that he뇫 bootlegged from the office. No problem. He wouldn뇺 even bother Jane at the end of the day.<p>
He called her from the shuttle at 4 p.m.<p>뉹orty-eight and an eighth, she said.<p>늉hat? Why?<p>늆he broad market is really up today. People are buying everything. The Dow was up 53 points after lunch and settled back up 39.<p>뉵ut why RemoteCount? <a name="NYSE:WMT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11600"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Wal-Mart</b></a> or <a name="NYSE:MCD"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10974"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>McDonald뇹</b></a> or something I could understand, but딊<p>뉻ey, Nicholas, I just trade them, right? Jane said irritably. 뉵ut you know, one of the pension funds could have taken a profit somewhere in a big position in another stock and decided to pick up some interesting smaller stocks, and they just bought a rising RemoteCount price until they filled their position. That could be it.<p>He hung up and did the math; he was down $6,400. His stop order was at 50, and suddenly that seemed rather close. <p>
He tramped inside the front door just after 7 p.m., as the kids were getting in the bath, and hollered upstairs to say he was home, then tossed his briefcase on the floor and floated into the living room. In the kitchen he ate the rest of the kids vegetables and rice out of the pot and idly pressed the play button of the phone machine to see who might have called: nothing. You never knew what could turn up듮his was how he뇫 learned about Lisa뇹 recent (and presumably terminated) affair with Richard Chambers. Ever since Nicholas뇹 brutal little lunch with Chambers a week ago, he could only assume that Chambers had immediately cut short the relationship. And as much as he wanted to confront Lisa about the whole thing, perhaps it was better to wait until they moved. New York would seem like a million miles away. Maybe he뇫 stoically never even bring it up. Or maybe he liked keeping the secret들t let him stay angry at his wife. <p>Upstairs, he stuck his head into the bathroom, and there they were, Lisa bent over the tub reading a book, Sally and Tommy in the warm suds, their little chests and shoulders above the bubbles.<p>뉻i, he said. 뉻ow뇹 my kids?<p>늉ere almost ready here, Lisa said, flipping the page.<p>늂kay. <p>She pushed her dark hair out of her face and looked at him, waiting. Even in her exhaustion, she was still lovely, still someone he admired and wanted to please. But a marriage, he now understood, was not just a static condition; it was a series of marriages between the same two people, and these days theirs was weakened by his inattention to her, burdened by children and work, and poisoned by her affair. They needed a new start, they needed hope, they needed RemoteCount to drop by 20 points. But maybe he could say something pleasant, signal his willingness not to fight. 늆here뇹 a lot of building going on outside Washington.<p>She nodded, faking interest in this comment. 뉼뇴 glad youre back. <p>Did he believe her? He wasn뇺 sure. <p>늀e, too, he mumbled.<p>In the bedroom, he flipped through the mail. The usual bills, the usual junk mail듭olicitations for investment newsletters and credit cards, catalogs for women뇹 dresses and Japanese power tools. Then Tommy, his five-year-old, ran into the bedroom, hair wet, trailing his towel. <p>뉷ad, do dead people all die lying down? he asked.<p>뉼 don뇺 know, Tommy. That뇹 kind of a strange question.<p>뉵illy Meyer says all dead people when they die, they have their tongues sticking out.<p>뉼 don뇺 think so. He toweled off his boy뇹 back. 뉿et뇹 get your pajamas.<p>뉵illy Meyer told me in school.<p>뉻as Billy Meyer seen a lot of dead people?<p>뉻e was with his mom, and they saw a dead man lying on the sidewalk.<p>뉻e saw that? Nicholas said, aghast.<p>뉵illy says they all die with their eyes shut and if드nd if they forget to shut them, then the bugs eat the eyeballs.<p>He looked at his boy and at the smoothness of his cheeks and the odd wet cowlick and his bright eyes and breathless patter.<p>뉷on뇺 worry about it, pal, okay?<p>From the bathroom came the happy sounds of Sally and Lisa finishing up. He and Lisa had made various parenting mistakes듮oo long in the crib for Tommy, too early with the play group with Sally득ut they뇫 gotten bedtime down, never varying the ritual. The kids actually seemed to like going to sleep. Lisa came into the bedroom, followed by Sally, who marched around the room in chubby excitement, her skin pink and warm. His wife flipped a diaper on the bed, and he swooped Sally up, held her gently on her back, dabbed a pinch of Balmex on her rear and put on the diaper. He뇫 once calculated that they뇫 spent nearly $5,000 on Pampers듢ood reason to buy Proctor and Gamble; he뇫 ask Jane about the stock. Now the kids ran around in their pajamas for a few minutes, and then Nicholas got down on his hands and knees like he always did and Tommy flew onto his back for an 는xecutive ride, which meant that Tommy rode on Nicholas over to the bed, where he leapt dramatically into the covers. <p>Sally was in her little bed, and then Lisa turned the light out, and Sally, like she always did, asked, 늁ight-light? And Nicholas answered, 늋es, sweetie, it뇹 on, let뇹 go to sleep, and the kids settled down while he sang 늆ake Me Out to the Ball Game, one of the few songs he knew by heart. While he warbled, 뉵uy me some peanuts and Crackerjack, I don뇺 care if we ever go back... he wondered what he would do if RemoteCount went any higher. A few punk 25-year-old fund managers who knew more about Air Jordans than they did stocks could have a look at RemoteCount tomorrow and start buying for the hell of it; Jane뇹 stop-loss order would kick in at $50 a share and he뇫 be finished듪ut of the game with a $17,000 loss, his foolishness confirmed.<p>
Later, he found lisa in bed reading. <p>늉ell? he said. 뉻ow about a romantic interlude?<p>뉶an I finish my chapter?<p>늅ure.<p>He took off his clothes and got into bed naked, laying his hands on his stomach. He뇫 lose weight once they moved to Ohio. Start running again, biking at least. Then he felt the weight of his wife as she got beneath the covers, and they lay quietly there for a few minutes as they both made the long transit from their respective thoughts toward each other. When he finally rolled toward her, he hoped that she wouldn뇺 be thinking of Richard Chambers, his beguiling smile, his toned buttocks, and so on.<p>Twenty minutes later, after Lisa had returned from the bathroom and he뇫 pulled on a T-shirt and underwear, he drifted in a fugue state, a half dream, in which he saw a new car skidding sideways across a wet road in slow motion. The wet skin of the car, the brilliant spray, the poetry of advertising. The dark figure behind the windshield was him. He liked the Ford Taurus. He was driving and turned off up a long driveway that led to a classic white farmhouse. The buffalo grass made a thick green carpet around the house. The stuff didn뇺 need much water. He뇫 plant a nice row of flowering trees듑argent crab apples, perhaps, or flowering white dogwoods (cornus florida). Or the rare magnolia hybrid Pink Goblet, a vigorous grower, according to the catalog, plantable in USDA zones 6-9. Pruning them was something of an art<p>늁icholas, came Lisa뇹 voice in the dark, 뉼 was trying to buy Tommy some shoes today and they wouldn뇺 take the Visa.<p>늋ou usually use the MasterCard, he said sleepily, tasting his pillow.<p>늋es, that뇹 true, but not because there isn뇺 one dime of credit on the Visa. I haven뇺 been using it, so that means you딊<p>늆here뇹 a $5,000 cash advance on the Visa.<p>늉hy, may I ask?<p>Yes, why? he wondered. 뉼 borrowed it to make an investment.<p>늉hat kind of investment?<p>He sighed. Tasted his own breath, already sour.<p>뉼뇼e put together a들t뇹 an idea to m