늋ou think딊<p>뉷on뇺 worry, he said. 뉼뇼e spent a long time putting this thing together. Youre just going to have to trust me.<p>늆rust you? she screamed.<p>늋es. He leaned close to her face in a way that was not affectionate, and she drew back. With one hand he reached up to the light above the bed and switched it on; both of them winced in the sudden brightness. 늋es, Lisa, he said slowly. 늆he same way that I뇼e trusted you.<p>
For three more days, nothing happened. RemoteCount flicked up and down, feigning a run-up here, dropping three eighths there. He began to hate the stock as if it were a human being who was being purposefully cruel. Meanwhile, despite the argument over RemoteCount, Lisa was warmer toward him, and they had even hired a sitter one night and slipped out to see The Piano, which had a couple of hot scenes between Holly Hunter and Harvey Keitel드 couple of hot adulterous scenes, Nicholas noted. In the darkness of the movie theater he slipped a glance at Lisa. Her face was a mask of rapture as the two naked bodies embraced on the huge screen. He looked away. <p>But when they got home, she said she wanted to apologize for her outburst a few nights back. 늋ou should have discussed the idea with me, but I guess I could have reacted better, she said, getting him a beer from the refrigerator. 뉼 mean, I didn뇺 catch all the details, but it sounds like a pretty smart deal.<p>What accounted for Lisa뇹 sudden pleasantness? Having just seen that movie, he thought bitterly, she believed in true love tonight. Then again, he had been something of a jerk not to tell her of the RemoteCount play. He뇫 try to be agreeable. 뉼뇴 just waiting for it to drop, he said.<p>늉ill you explain the whole thing to me again? I got so worked up the other night that I was hardly listening.<p>She listened intently as he laid out the whole play. She was a good listener and quickly  caught on.<p>뉻ow much do you think we could make? Lisa asked. 늀aybe twenty or thirty thousand?<p>뉻ard to say. It would be better not to get her hopes up too high. 뉼f it went well, really well, and the stock dropped to $30 a share, say, that would be about $97,000.<p>His wife stared at him. Really?<p>Really.<p>
The next afternoon, he got an urgent call from Jane.<p>늁icholas, it뇹 at 493/4, and my guess is that it뇳l hit 50 any time.<p>늉hat뇹 going on? Why didn뇺 you call me when it hit 49?<p>뉵ecause it happened fast. One of the technology analysts gave it a buy this morning.<p>뉻e뇹 an asshole. Now, look, you should have called me immediately<p>늁icholas, you have a stop order at 50. I don뇺 have to call you듳ou have already decided what youre doing. I called as a matter of courtesy딊<p>뉶ancel the stop-loss, he ordered suddenly.<p>늉hat?<p>뉶ancel it, he insisted. 뉷on뇺 sell at 50.<p>늉ait a minute, you worked out how much you were willing to lose.<p>뉼뇴 changing my mind.<p>늆his is not the way to make decisions. Youre not a professional trader.<p>뉶ancel the stop-loss. Please do it now.<p>뉴nd what, said Jane, exasperated, 늡hould I replace it with?<p>Yes, of course, she had to put in some kind of stop-loss order. <p>늉hat뇹 my margin here? I had some kind of 10 percent overage in my account, right?<p>뉼t was 10 percent of 47, which is 4.7, which, rounded down, is four and five eighths. If you add that to 47딊<p>늃ut in the stop loss at 511/2.<p>늆hat leaves you exactly one eighth of a point. We can뇺 do this again.<p>늋es.<p>늋ou don뇺 have any more money, Nicholas. If it hits 511/2, I뇴 not going to listen to any noise about sticking more money into your account.<p>He heard the anger in her voice. 늋es, Jane.<p>늁ow you better fax me instructions to cancel the stop-loss at 50 and to put in a new one at 511/2.<p>Which he did. At the end of the day he called Jane to get the quote. Sure, he was being an asshole, but it was his money on the line; he뇫 bought the right to be an asshole. But there was no answer. Jane was gone for the day.<p>
That night he forced himself not to call the brokerage for the price and instead watched the CNN business report, and of course, there was no mention of why RemoteCount had gone up and how far. Who cared? Nobody. It was a nothing stock. Perhaps ten people in America really cared듢ot sweaty balls듮hinking about RemoteCount, and six of them were probably RemoteCount executives. They knew the stock was going to tank. He뇫 seen this pattern. It had to happen. The company made all of its money with 1,400 people sitting in front of screens in one large facility in Seattle that had EMF readings above 3,000 mG. RemoteCount would be forced to shut down and tear the hell out of the building in order to correct the problem. The RemoteCount executives were all cheats and liars afraid to tell their stockholders what was happening to the company. They were sitting at home and telling their wives they뇫 better not buy the Lexus right now. They couldn뇺 sell their own RemoteCount holdings, of course, because that might be insider trading and also could trigger the landslide. Nicholas hated them. They were killing him.<p>
The next morning he walked outside in the cold in his bathrobe, ripped the Times out of its plastic bag, snatched the business section, folded the rest of the paper under his arm, and flipped to the stock tables. RemoteCount had closed at 511/4. Death! Somebody was buying the stock! Today the price would probably vibrate up to 511/2, and there would be nothing he could do about it! Jane뇹 computers would sell his position, and the effect of the whole insane fantasy would have been that he had given away $18,000등hat was that? A Ford Taurus? No. The Taurus ran higher. But certainly a Ford Aerostar minivan. Driver뇹-side airbag, antilock braking system. I뇳l take it in Cayman green with mocha interior trim.<p>When he got to the office, Hal Gruber, his immediate boss, came in. 뉺irardi called Belton last night.<p>Nicholas looked up. He뇫 forgotten about Girardi Corp.<p>늉hat뇫 he say?<p>늉hat did he say? Gruber exclaimed. 뉻e said he wanted to do a three-year deal, and he asked if we were thinking of expanding in Washington, D.C., and needed investors!<p>Really?<p>Gruber slapped him on the shoulder and shook his hand. 뉼 don뇺 know what you said to him down there but jeez, Nicholas, great job. Really great job. Jeez, I mean, Belton was really pleased.<p>Nicholas arranged his features into something resembling a hearty grin. What did it mean, really? Two bosses pleased, a few more pieces of candy in the Christmas bonus. He was still inconsolable. After Gruber left, he pushed the paper around on his desk absentmindedly. He had no interest in calling Jane. Why hasten the bad news? How would he face Lisa? She뇫 been so excited, so happy, when he뇫 told her the workings of the RemoteCount play. She뇫 talked about Ohio, how nice it would be to live near her mother again. Take care of her. And the kids would love being in the country. He뇫 let all of them down.<p>So, right before lunch, when he received the phone message that Jane had just called, he wondered how he would ever get Lisa and the kids out of the city. He couldn뇺 work for Belton Associates the rest of his life. He wanted out, he wanted grass. There had been another incident in their neighborhood recently, a hit-and-run with some Bronx kids whacked out on drugs. A four-year-old was on a respirator, severe brain swelling. When the cops arrived, it got even worse. The kids in the car inexplicably started shooting at them, and the police had been forced to shoot two of the kids. And Billy Meyer had seen a dead man on the sidewalk. And that lunatic had killed a bunch of people on the Long Island Railroad a few months back. This was 1994. What would it be like in 1999? Perhaps he was never going to get his kids and wife out of the sinkhole of New York City. His loss on RemoteCount made the goal even moreremote. Ha, no pun intended! Hell, he thought, get it over with. Life is a series of bets, and sometimes you lose! Yes! He knew that all along! Ha! He shut his office door and punched Jane뇹 speed-dial button on his console. <p>뉽ane?<p>늁icholas, finally! RemoteCount is down to around 38!<p>늉hat?<p>뉼 tried you when it hit 46, she said in excitement. 늆heyre dumping on the West Coast. Calpers sold its entire position.<p>뉴nybody else selling yet?<p>뉼 can뇺 find out. I got a couple of calls in.... Wait, here it is듮he volume is huge, it뇹 at 363/4. The Seattle paper has a long story on closing the facility this morning, Jane said excitedly. 늆hat뇹 what kicked it off. Let me read you the article; I had the whole thing faxed to me. It just came out. Here, it뇹 their business writer. 넨mployees leaving the building yesterday afternoon, some carrying personal items, expressed complete shock at the announcement and worried about making a living in the coming months. 늆hey said they don뇺 know when theyre going to let us in again, said Shanelle Johnson, a data entry clerk.눖<p>뉷oes it say anything about the stock? Nicholas asked.<p>뉼t quotes a local analyst who says that he expects that the company will lose market share.<p>늋eah, I guess so. They뇳l have no market for at least six months.<p>늉ait, also, he says that he expects the company뇹 debt will be downgraded.<p>뉶all me when you get another price, okay?<p>He almost called Lisa; no, he thought, better to wait until the deal is finished; he뇫 go home that evening and give her the exact figure, down to the penny. Instead he went out and treated himself to a big lunch at the Oyster Bar, and then felt too happy to go back to the office. So he wandered into a hardware store two avenues to the east and charged up a new shovel, rake, trowel, and leather work gloves. Sure, it was silly! But wasn뇺 life!<p>And just as he returned at 3 p.m., Jane called again.<p>늆he stock뇹 at 13. Someone bought 3,000 shares at 13.<p>늆hirteen? It seemed impossible.<p>늋oure making serious money here, Nicholas. All the pensions are dumping. Theyre being quite ruthless, positioning themselves for a bounce.<p>늉e have to sell on an uptick, right?<p>늋es.<p>늅hould I sell now?<p>A pause.<p>늁o, she said. 늂ur guy who specializes in technology stocks says he thinks the 3,000 shares is someone trying to stabilize the stock, somebody who owns a lot more still. See, it뇹 only been bought a couple of times on the way down. You got something like a million shares in sell orders, and he says that only about 80,000 have been bought.<p>뉼 don뇺 get it딊<p>늆here are no buy orders. Our own guy is calling some of his clients who might want to make a play on the stock on the way up.<p>늆rying to hit the bottom, knowing that when the company pulls itself back together the stock could do well?<p>늆hat뇹 the idea, she said. 늁ow, for you듈 want instructions to buy on an uptick at anything less than 10.<p>뉵ut it뇹 at 13.<p>늂h, I think it could go lower.<p>뉵ut딊 He stopped himself from asking why she thought that. Jane might have guessed at the rough price that the other broker at her firm would suggest to his own trading clients. They뇫 know the fundamentals of the company and decide to buy at a certain price, which would make a market for the stock again. The sudden buying volume might attract more buying. But now he was scared and wanted to get out. 뉻ow about 111/2?<p>늂kay, Jane said. 뉼뇳l call when I뇼e got the uptick. Under 11 is going to be no problem is my guess.<p>
Her guess was good. she called 40 minutes later.<p>늋oure famous around here.<p>뉽ane?<p>늁ine and an eighth.<p>뉽esus.<p>뉼t뇹 one of the best shorts I뇼e ever seen, she told him. 뉴nd one of the most obscure, too.<p>He wasn뇺 interested in her praise, just his money. 늋ou bought at 91/8?<p>뉹ive thousand at 9 and the rest at 91/8. It was heading back up pretty fast.<p>늉hen will my account be settled?<p>늆hree days.<p>늆his happened? I뇴 done, I don뇺 have to worry anymore?<p>뉺o out and buy a bottle of champagne.<p>Well, yes. They뇫 soon be buying all kinds of things! But first he뇫 call Lisa! Get a sitter, babe, were going out for dinner. Better yet, come into the city and we뇳l see a show, maybe Angels in America, which from its title sounded optimistic, good fun. But there was no answer. Tommy was old enough to pick up the phone. Strange. He left a message saying he뇫 be home soon with big news. Maybe they went out, but Lisa usually ran her errands after picking the kids up from school. He always called at the end of the day. He felt both irritated and fearful. Perhaps someone had broken into the house, perhaps듣e pushed back the possibilities. He glanced at his watch; 4:56 p.m. If the kids had been picked up at the end of their day, at 2:50 p.m., then that meant that all was normal up to that point. Then again, if they hadn뇺 been picked up, the school would have called him, since his office number was on the emergency form. He got the number of the school, dialed it, and reached the lower-school principal뇹 office.<p>He quickly explained to the principal, Mrs. Kroeber, that he was checking to see that his wife had picked up their kids. Was there any way she could check?<p>뉼f your children were still here, I would know about it, she said firmly. <p>Right. Of course.<p>뉴re you worried about them?<p>늉ell, no, I have no reason.... I called home, and there뇹 no answer.<p>Mrs. Kroeber didn뇺 respond. There was an appraising silence on the other end of the line. He knew she saw all kinds of