<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/03-Fear of Money</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/03-Fear of Money</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						<p>Is money a threat? Can it provide peace of mind? Or freedom? Grappling with these issues can be a lifelong battle.<p>By Robert Kotlowitz<p>There are people in this world who are afraid of money. I know, because I have battled this issue myself a lot. Psychiatrists have told me my fear of money is a cover-up, that I'm really afraid of something else, that I'm confused. Maybe so, but I doubt it. I think it is real and always has been, ever since my childhood during the Depression, when money was not an especially friendly object or even a very common one. Back in those days, you really had to seek it out and tease it into existence, holding onto it as though it were life itself. Of course, that is the nature of all depressions.<p>The Depression was not called the Depression for nothing. More than the economy was depressed. We all were, children and adults alike. My psyche seems to have suffered more or less permanent damage. The effects linger to this day. For instance, I hate debt. I loathe it so much that I have refused to take out a mortgage--two houses so far, both bought in full with a single cash payment. I haven't bought a car, or anything else, on time. Debt unnerves me. I view it as something that corrodes the spirit. And it is far too real. It's an inescapable presence in our lives, built to last.<p>I also don't like hearing about the stock market. When it comes to reading the morning paper, I'd almost rather peruse the obituaries than the financial pages. To me, the news is just as awful: market drops, lowered bond rates, corporate failures, mass layoffs. When I see those headlines, my courage sometimes fails me. I block. My day's mood--the way I will see and respond to the world--can be set over breakfast by bad news about money. Even my fantasies are at stake.<p>I happen to know the exact moment that I was first gripped by the fear of money--the sense that there never would be enough, no matter how much I would make one day; the shyness in its presence; the assurance that while the world might be my oyster, money was for other people.<p>I was seven when one of my pals, who was probably too smart for his own good and certainly for mine, began to quiz me. We were at recess. We were both wearing scruffy Depression clothes, full of holes that we tried to hide from each other. My pal asked me this: "Does your old man make 40 bucks a week?"<p>That stopped me cold. I had never thought of the matter before. Yet the question felt very close to the bone, maybe too close. I had no answer, and that was unnerving, too. I felt helpless. And the question threw my own father's probity into doubt. Even though I was only seven, I certainly knew it was an important issue. The Depression was a time when earning money was the central issue in every American household.<p>Did my old man make 40 bucks a week?<p>It is important at this point to understand that I grew up as the son of a clergyman. Now clergymen are often wonderful people-- staunch, faithful, exhortative, and other positive things--but rich they cannot be. Possibly as a result, money is often denigrated in the clergyman's home. It is positioned among the lesser values, something to turn one's back on. It is even claimed to be the root of all evil, a notion that has its charms when there is little money around.<p>But my grade-school chum's question still hung over me like an accusation, one I could not easily escape. Did my old man make 40 bucks a week? When I got up the nerve to ask, my father was not able to relieve my anxiety. In fact, he laughed in my face, not joyously, as I remember it. He also looked slightly crazed, then withdrew. Such was his anxiety about money. I never got a straight answer, then or later. (Over time, I learned that he always avoided the subject, always looked slightly crazed when it came up.) So money became something I was going to have to figure out for myself. I had to figure out what it meant, why there was so little of it. And I had to do this while fear settled inside me, the acrid fear of childhood.<p>For a while, then, $40 a week, almost $2,100 a year, became a standard for me. As far as I knew, that's what you had to have to amount to anything. Or even to be safe. And what could $40 a week add up to? At the time, I calculated that it would pay the rent on our row house; assure us of heat in the winter; provide telephone service (limited), gas, and electricity; clothe us (basically); feed us; and enable us to read the newspaper every day--delivered by hand to our front porch--and take in a weekly movie (15 cents for me). I also had a piano lesson every Sunday for 50 cents. Providing all that, which seems a lot when I catalog it this way, was what was called, then, "making a living," a concept that has now disappeared from the lexicon of the American dream, like so many other primitive notions.<p>Slowly, I grew more sophisticated. I read about the salaries of movie stars. I began to understand the extent of certain great family fortunes: Rockefeller, Vanderbilt, Astor, and many others. My vistas broadened. By the time I was ten years old, 40 bucks a week, as a standard, was out. It was superseded during a walk I took with my grandfather down New York's Park Avenue. This gentleman, who was something of a dandy even in the worst of times, was also a freelance custom tailor (another man of the cloth) who had occasional access to great homes and rich patrons, with whom he plied his trade on a rather perfunctory basis.<p>My grandfather's attitude toward money was basic, if not crude: "I want it when I need it" just about sums it up. In other words, a child's view, like mine. In any case, as we wandered down Park Avenue, where my grandfather had several customers, he eyed the handsome buildings that lined the street and suddenly said: "You have to make $10,000 a year to be able to live in one of those apartments."<p>Ten thousand dollars a year! As though I had asked. The figure rattled around inside my head, like fruit in a one-armed bandit. What did $10,000 a year mean? It was incalculable, infinite, totally abstract, like the national debt today. It was also intimidating, scary, and surely unattainable by the likes of me, to say nothing of my old man. Ten thousand dollars a year was for other people, those who were not afraid of money, who seemed at one with it, at their ease; those, in short, who had it coming to them. Those who had chosen to live on Park Avenue and did.<p>I would say that that moment changed my life. The grit of ambition settled into my bones at my grandfather's airy words, edging fear out for the first time. They were a challenge. They gave me a dim sense that perhaps I might be one of those who had it coming to them, if I chose to be. In short, that it was in my power to control money, not vice versa. I would go for it.<p>I got it, too, but not in any dramatic sense. The only problem was that the target kept shifting. Ten thousand dollars a year was soon made obsolete by $30,000, and $30,000, of course, by...well, you name it. But my confidence grew; that was the point, although it had to be constantly nurtured, like a candle threatening to go out in the prevailing winds. And of course there are always plenty of blustery threats out there to nourish the fear of money, the ongoing anxiety about the sweet crinkly green that feeds the body and lifts the spirit. And what if the whole delicate balance of international finance crashes again, like the house of cards it sometimes seems to be?<p>As I suggested earlier, fear breeds fantasy, and I have become a great dreamer about money over the years, especially when shaving in the morning. Huge abstractions wash over my mind as I wield the razor in front of the mirror. Sometimes I stumble onto $8 million in my morning dreams (inherited, lottery-won, unexpected royalties--every man has his own list). How to divvy it up among my family, how to make my wife, my children, and myself both safe and happy? How to invest, how to save, how to spend? Who gets what?<p>One morning not long ago, the $8 million, which has a nice, even ring to it, took a natural turn and swelled to $80 million, which rings even more nicely, then $800 million, and finally--jackpot!--$1 billion. With $1 billion in hand, I entered the land of Oz. Everything was suddenly in color, I walked on bricks made of gold, the world worked as I dreamed as a child it would. And my natural generosity was liberated. First, I would give $500 million to medical research, right off the bat. Then $250 million to literacy, education, and minority opportunities. Another $200 million to selected institutions whose survival and growth I deem essential to the commonweal. The rest--a mere $50 million--to me and my family and perhaps a few friends (they know who they are), all of us strong, purposeful, valiant, and unafraid. Especially me.<p>One thing I've learned: The fear of money is very close to the fear of being lost, of being set adrift without power or autonomy. I think that both my father and my grandfather shared this sense of helplessness (who didn't then?) and that each, in his own way, helped to pass it on to me. They had no choice. How vulnerable they must have felt about money, like most of their contemporaries. I like to think it's behind me now. I like to think I've thrown it off, that I'm no longer under constraint. But the fact is I'm still always looking over my shoulder to make sure I'm ahead of the game, still wary, still nervous. Maybe that's not so bad, after all. Maybe it's a positive thing. It certainly makes sure that I pay close attention to the subject, that I actually think about money rationally. And I am still free to pursue wealth, to take a dare and choose courage. Some day, even a billion dollars won't seem like so much.<p>Robert Kotlowitz's most recent novel is His Master's Voice (Knopf, 1992).<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Family Finance
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

