<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/03-Discount vs. Deep Discount</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/03-Discount vs. Deep Discount</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
Does your relationship need a major adjustment?<p>By Jill Andresky Fraser<p>For all the attention paid to hiring one, little if any information is available about when--and how--to fire a financial advisor. Yet avoiding or delaying a decision to cut the cord can be quite costly. <p>All too often clients are intimidated or confused about their rights and expectations in their relationships with financial planners, brokers, and accountants. Many people have a sense something's wrong but resist taking action because they don't know who else to go to or whether it's even worth the effort. And there's that guilt factor about firing someone you like personally. "I see these kinds of delays very often," says David Shellenberger, a Boston-based attorney who specializes in investor claims against financial advisors. "It's psychologically very difficult for people to understand that their trust has been breached. So they delay, often for years." <p>Of course there's nothing to be gained by waiting to fire an incompetent or unethical advisor. To make the decision, it's often helpful to have objective guidelines that indicate when it's time to call it quits. Although every situation is different, there are three clear warning signs that an advisory relationship isn't working:<p>--Poor results. Does your financial planner or stockbroker seem to consistently recommend strategies that don't work out as planned? Are you getting audited or penalized by the IRS regularly over tax plays your accountant recommended? When you evaluate your family's financial results, do you suspect you would have been better off investing on your own? To establish an objective basis on which to evaluate performance, clearly set out in writing the goals your advisor is expected to help you achieve and the results you expect to move your portfolio toward that end. Use specific numbers and deadlines whenever possible--for example, beat the market index, earn a 7 percent after-tax annual return, increase life-insurance coverage to $500,000 by the end of the first quarter, etc. Your expectations should be clear, reasonable, agreed to by both parties, and most important, measurable. Then set a time to meet and review the results. And while nobody's perfect, don't be too quick to overlook an advisor's shortcomings. "You've got to aggressively question your advisor about what went wrong in the past and how things will be different in the future. If you're not satisfied with the answers or explanations, move on," advises John Perkins, the securities commissioner of Missouri. <p>--Communication problems. These can run the gamut, warns Christine Bruenn, supervisor of enforcement for the Securities Administration of Maine, from advisors who don't return telephone calls promptly to those who "don't listen to your priorities about risks and returns." If, for whatever reason, you feel you just can't get through to your advisor, complain once or twice--then take your family's business elsewhere.<p>Don't dismiss intangible concerns, such as a feeling that you're just not comfortable with your advisor. They can reflect a sensitivity to high-pressure tactics or high-risk recommendations that are inappropriate for you. If you don't feel comfortable, there's probably a reason.<p>One caveat: Sometimes clients themselves are the problem, as when, in Perkins's words, "they tell their advisors that they don't want to be involved in risky investments but they want to earn large returns." In such cases, it's up to advisors to communicate the trade-offs between those two goals and to help clients set more realistic expectations. But the client also has to help.<p>--Churning and burning. Here's where advisors may cross the fuzzy boundary between incompetent and unethical activities--and in egregious cases, clients might even want to think about suing, as well as firing, an advisor. <p>One obvious no-no: Transactions (purchasing stocks, transferring funds between accounts, paying fees) that take place without approval or authorization from the client. Often the only way to identify that this has happened is by analyzing bank, brokerage, and other regular financial statements. That's a good reason not to rely on an advisor to read and file these for you.<p>Another all-too-common warning sign is account churning. "Watch out for advisors that keep pushing you to carry out an excessively high volume of transactions," warns Stephen Diamond, Maine's securities administrator. Remember that you pay, and your broker earns, a commission every time you buy and every time you sell a stock. Make sure each transaction that a broker suggests makes investment sense to you.<p>Here's the bottom line: You, not your financial advisor, are your family's last line of defense in the investment arena. It's up to you to supervise your advisor's performance and, when you're not satisfied, move on.<p>Fortunately, the act of firing a financial advisor is nowhere near as difficult as deciding whether or not to fire him or her. The key point: Do it by mail (return receipt requested) rather than by telephone. It's not as personal, but a letter preserves a record of your complete instructions, including the date the relationship was terminated. <p>If you suspect you might have some grounds for a legal complaint against your advisor, "hire a lawyer to prepare your termination letter," advises Shellenberger. "The letter should be very straightforward, directing the advisor to terminate the account, effective immediately, and to transfer promptly all financial records, securities, and other documents to an authorized location." <p>Above all, avoid recriminations or complaints. Shellenberger warns, "If you make any statements in your letter about why you're ending the relationship, you might end up limiting your rights and ability to sue later on because you failed to disclose other problems. It's better to end the relationship first, then decide upon other actions if appropriate." <p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

