<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/02-What Goes Up...</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/02-What Goes Up...</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						A faddish investment technique called momentum investing has propelled stock prices into the heavens. What happens when the fad fades?<p>By Gretchen Morgenson<p>Folks who had the good fortune to be in the stock market last year enjoyed one delightful ride. In spite of some dizzying dives in individual stocks or the occasional industry group, 1993 was stellar for equities. <p>The biggest winners were shareholders in the small-capitalization companies, as the averages show. Hands-down winner was the Russell 2000, an index of small-cap stocks, which had increased some 15 percent by mid-December. <p>An only slightly lesser performer was the Dow Jones Industrial Average, up 13 percent. In third place was the Nasdaq composite, an index of 4,400 companies that was up 12.5 percent last year; trailing was the larger-capitalization S&P 500 index, up only 6.5 percent on the year.<p>Hoping for more of the same, investors are piling into the stocks and mutual funds that won 1993's capital-gains race. Will they be handsomely rewarded once again? Maybe so, but markets rarely stay the same long enough to reward investors assiduously chasing last year's trend. <p>Particularly worrisome is the recent nature of that trend. As more money floods into the stock market, increasing numbers of fund and money managers are taking up a method of investing that has all the earmarks of the latest stock market fad. It's called momentum investing.<p>Unlike past investment fashions, the fad of the moment hasn't affixed itself to a particular group of stocks; neither does it revolve around an industry. What the investment trendies are up to today is a method of stock picking that relies little on how a company is doing--the so-called fundamental analysis of an operation's net worth, business prospects, or balance sheets. Instead, it focuses on how the company's stock is doing. <p>Like all Wall Street fads, momentum investing is beautiful in its simplicity. If a stock's price is going up, it's a buy. When it stops going up, it's a sell. In the world of physics, momentum is motion conjoined with force. In the world of investing, momentum is the motion of a stock conjoined with the force of the herd. <p>Steven Vannelli is a money manager at KJMM Investment Management in San Francisco who has been watching the momentum game play out for some months now. Investors should be concerned about how the game will end, says Vannelli. "The danger with momentum investing is it's great in an up market, hell in a down market," he says. <p>The fuel that has been driving stocks skyward is indeed a volatile mix: low inflation, low interest rates, and increased levels of corporate efficiency, which translate to higher margins and earnings among issuers. Last, but by no means least, is investors' apparently insatiable appetite for investments that will return something greater than the 2.5 percent rate currently found in bank CDs. It is this craving that explains the $411 billion investors poured into stock mutual funds in the last half of 1993, a figure that was up 39 percent from the year before.<p>All in all, it's the perfect environment for creating the newest high-octane investment fad. All rising markets have them. In the bull market of the 1960s, the no-brainer investment strategy revolved around the Nifty Fifty--a group of stocks, including Avon, National Student Marketing, and <a name="NYSE:EK"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10500"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Kodak</b></a>, that could do no wrong for investors. The bear market of 1974 brought that little fantasy to an end. Then, in the early 1980s, anything to do with high technology became a stock market darling. Until the summer of 1983, that is, when tech stocks crashed to earth. Alas, all good investment fads must come to an end.<p>Momentum investing--investors looking for price action in a stock, bond, or commodity and hopping on for the ride--is nothing new. In the 1970s, it was more popular in the commodities pits than it was on stock exchange floors. It was known then as "trend following," and crafty traders made money with it for several years until the commodities became virtually trendless. Then the followers had nothing to follow. In the 1980s, adherents to what we now call the momentum school were more often known as "relative strength" players, because they looked for strength in stock prices.<p>Today, however, the use of actual earnings growth among momentum players has been superseded by investors who buy stocks largely on recent price behavior. As one money manager explained it, these investors seem to believe that buying on price jumps is a shortcut to the same end. Why waste time slogging through financial statements looking for earnings growth? If a stock's price is rising, it's probably because somebody else who has done the analysis likes it and is buying.<p>When momentum investors buy a stock, their thinking goes something like this: You like it, I like it, maybe we can find a third person who'll like it too. As long as buyers continue to snap up the stock, all is well; like a rocket leaving the launching pad, momentum looks unstoppable, initially. Trouble comes when investors have pushed the stock as high as it will go and a few start to bail. Then, momentum slows, and suddenly, the very reason everyone bought the stock in the first place has disappeared. Everybody heads for the exits at once. When the only reason to buy a stock is based on its rising price, there's little reason to hold when it begins its descent. <p>This explains the violent and seemingly inexplicable downdrafts that are often seen in stocks today. Shares in Household International, for example, dropped almost 8 percent in one day's trading in early December when the financial-services company said its 1994 earnings would likely be at the lower end of analysts' projections. The momentum crowd is also the force behind the troubling volatility evidenced in certain industry groups (see "Swings in the Sectors").<p>Just how popular is momentum investing? Exact numbers of money managers playing the game are hard to come by--they're certainly not listed as such in fund directories. Equally difficult to pin down are numbers of assets currently controlled by momentum players. Part of the problem, according to some fund types, is that few folks want to admit to being proponents. <p>Arthur Nicholas, for example, head of the hugely successful Nicholas-Applegate money-management group ($12 billion under management), hates being described as a momentum player. This in spite of the fact that his portfolio managers count heavily on price and earnings momentum when picking stocks for institutional clients and mutual fund portfolios. The momentum label trivializes his investment style, says Nicholas. Buying stocks based on price moves just doesn't have the gravitas that investors demand of their money managers. <p>Still, the strategy is becoming more mainstream every day. Money manager Vannelli believes momentum investors are an enormous force in today's market. "There's so much money being run by people who don't even read annual reports today," he says. "Huge numbers of investors--insurance companies, mutual fund managers--just buy the momentum." <p>Amy Arnott, an analyst at Morningstar, a mutual fund-analysis firm in Chicago, agrees that momentum investing is on the rise in the fund business. "I've noticed more portfolio managers talking about it," she says. "Plus, when you see a lot of people piling into the same stocks, that's probably the reason." <p>Momentum investing was also behind a big December pitch made to investors and prospects by Carlton Lutts, editor of the Cabot Market Letter, an investment newsletter. Calling his investment strategy the Momentum System 1000, Lutts says it is the secret to "turning $5,000 into $225,000 with just one stock." Lutts writes, "I have discovered what I call the single most important tool for picking winning stocks: Momentum Analysis." When an investing strategy is sold through the mails, you know it's mainstream.<p>Here's some evidence that points to an increase in momentum players among mutual fund managers today: The average turnover ratio of aggressive-growth stock funds, as measured by Morningstar, is up significantly from premomentum levels of a decade ago. <p>How many times a fund manager turns over his portfolio in one year--a 100 percent ratio means a manager has bought and sold the equivalent of his entire portfolio during the year--can be revealing of the fund manager's style. Momentum players, by their very nature, have higher turnover ratios than value investors do; this is because price players move in and out of stocks more quickly--they're happy to abandon a stock simply because it is no longer rising fast enough. Other types of investors are more patient and turn over their portfolios less frequently. <p>It's not surprising, then, that over the past ten years, the average annual turnover rate among aggressive-growth funds--where most momentum players can be found--has increased by 67 percent. Compare this to the averages among other equity-fund categories: Turnover among small-cap-fund managers, for example, grew just 12 percent over the decade, while the average growth and income fund turned over its portfolio just 16 percent more than it used to. And turnover rates among foreign-stock-fund managers actually declined 16 percent during the decade.<p>Another measure of momentum's new acceptance among investors? The cover of the November issue of Institutional Investor, a publication read by professional money managers, celebrates Richard Driehaus, a Chicago-based money manager and big momentum player. And, Wall Street sources say, momentum investing has even trickled down to the ranks of retail brokers, who are pitching their clients on the merits of investing with the herd.<p>People in the fund-management business observe that even former value investors are jumping on the momentum trend. This worries market observers who note that when investors change their strategies midstream, it often signals the beginning of the end of a strong market. Michael Long, principal of Rockbridge Partners, an investment firm in Charlotte, North Carolina, says: "More value types have capitulated to momentum theory. The only way for managers to get money from investors is to be in stocks that have done well." In other words, the biggest movers.<p>Long's point is key to understanding why momentum investing is surging in popularity today. Each new billion that cascades into stock mutual fund coffers puts money managers into this ever more tremendous bind: "How on earth should I invest this money intelligently?" It's a nice problem to have--too much money--but it is a problem nonetheless. The apparent solution, to more and more managers: Invest with the crowd.<p>Veterans of the momentum approach to investing stress that it can only work properly if combined with diligent fundamental analysis. Columbine Capital, a money-management firm in Colorado Springs, has supplied a price-momentum investment model to institutional clients since the late 1970s. The firm studies 12 months of a stock's price moves, corrects the data for excess volatility, and ranks the stock for "relative momentum." John Brush, president of Columbine says, "This gives considerable predictive power, relative to all other stocks. It's a helpful addition to the valuation of stocks. But nobody in their right mind invests on price momentum alone." <p>No? Some of the biggest names in momentum investing today (see "Momentum Mutual Funds") seem to be straying well beyond the boundaries that disciplined adherents, like Brush, stick to. For example, Columbine excludes all new issues from its model --a stock must have at least a year's worth of trading behind it before it has any predictive capabilities. Yet Dreihaus, the momentum trader profiled in Institutional Investor, bets early and often in the new-issue market. So does Catherine Avery, a portfolio manager at Nicholas-Applegate, who runs a $2.3 billion (assets) emerging-growth portfolio. <p>Initial public offerings that skyrocket in price right out of the gate--Snapple Beverage, Boston Chicken, and Callaway Golf are three examples--become immediate favorites of momentum investors if only because their stocks suddenly jump. <p>How does a momentum player make investment decisions? Most fund managers don't like to reveal their secrets, but the process seems to go something like this. Because the fund manager trades constantly through many different brokerage firms, he or she is likely to get the first call from a broker offering shares in a hot IPO. The manager buys all he can, knowing it is likely to rise substantially because there are not enough shares to satisfy investor demand. He also agrees to buy more shares in the open market after they begin trading. As other investors, shut out of the initial offering, snap up the stock, its price typically continues to rise. This action confirms to the momentum investor that he should stay in the stock.<p>Selling time comes when something about the stock's prospects--sales, earnings, or even its price--starts to crest. Maybe there's a sense on Wall Street that the industry the company's in is going to slow its growth. Or the money manager may simply feel there are faster-moving stocks elsewhere that are better buys. Before you can say, "Fire!" everybody's crowding the door.<p>As practiced today, momentum investing can pretty much be summed up this way: aggressive money chasing yesterday's highfliers. Says fund manager Long, "People can't find any other reason to justify paying these prices for stocks, so they call it momentum." Although the practice is not totally responsible for sky-high stock valuations today--both price-to-earnings ratios and book values on the major equity indexes are at all-time highs --it has certainly contributed to rich stock prices. And it has made some sectors of the market much more volatile than before. <p>The trouble is, those rocketing returns of yesterday are what every mutual fund, brokerage firm, and managed-account investor is looking to his fund managers to beat tomorrow. As Tom Wolfe would say, tout le monde has become a momentum investor.<p>And why not, while the market's rising? Momentum makes for fun and gains on the way up. And there's that famous Wall Street maxim "Don't fight the tape." Still, investors have a right to wonder now: What effect will the increasing numbers of momentum investors have in the unwanted but inevitable down market? What happens when stock prices go into a cyclical decline, creating a massive sell signal to all momentum players? <p>The simple answer is that what we all witnessed on the upside will be mirrored in a decline. But as anyone who has lived through a blistering bear market will tell you, gravity has a way of dragging stocks down further than is truly justified. And because certain stocks have been driven to unsustainable heights by the current euphoria of the investing crowd, when their prices fall, the decline will be all the more precipitous.<p>To get a glimpse of what such a descent might look like, check out the action in some of the sectors and stocks that the momentum players have recently abandoned. Consider, for instance, the volatility that characterized just three weeks of trading in the electronics, insurance, and heavy-duty transportation industries during November (see "Swings in the Sectors"). In just three weeks of trading, ending November 12, the electronics component of the S&P 500 went from being the number 11-ranked performer out of 108 industry groups to the 84th, then back again to number 1. The insurance group began the period ranked number 87, then moved down to near the bottom at 101, only to zoom to number 6 by week three. Moves like these, jarring to buy-and-hold investors, have much to do with fast-money momentum players. <p>The effects are even worse in individual stocks. Newbridge Networks, for example, a favorite of the hot-money crowd, lost almost 10 points in the week of trading ended November 19. That's a staggering $392 million of market capitalization, gone in a flash. And why did the computer-networking stock take such a hit? The company's crime was that its second-quarter results as reported--earnings and margins were both up sharply--only just met analysts' expectations. What Newbridge should have done, had it wanted to keep its stock high, was exceed those expectations. <p>Similarly perverse reactions befell other momentum stocks during the same week Newbridge stumbled (see "Swings in the Stocks"). L.M. Ericsson Telephone's American depositary receipts fell almost 10 points on the week, losing $2 billion in market value for the Swedish telecommunications giant. And Qualcomm, a maker of digital wireless-communications gear, plunged almost 20 points on the week, costing it $466 million in market value. Both stocks were victims of unrealistic expectations held by investors who, as is always the case with the momentum game, sold at the first whiff of disappointment. Or, as in these three cases, well before the first whiff of disappointment was evidenced. <p>"I'll sell if the reason for my purchase of a stock is no longer valid," says Nicholas-Applegate's Avery. "If sales are going to be flat or fundamental leadership of the stock has changed and its price has turned down." <p>Not that the company's no longer a winner, mind you. As Avery points out, "It does us no good to be in a company that's good but that nobody cares about." No longer is an investment made because of the company; it's now made because of the stock. And because others like the stock.<p>There are a variety of reasons why investors should be worried about what will happen to stock prices in general when the rocket that is momentum investing begins to reverse. How do we know it will? Because all investment fads do, especially those that require everlasting increases in earnings or stock prices. Even the most benighted investor knows that nothing grows to the sky. Not even <a name="NYSE:IBM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10796"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>IBM</b></a>. Not even <a name="NYSE:WMT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11600"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Wal-Mart</b></a>.<p>As money man Vannelli puts it, "Companies have cycles. They can't keep going ad infinitum at a constant level of change." So investors seeking that unattainable constant pile in and out of companies and industries ever more rapidly, roiling the markets and whipsawing investment bystanders.<p>The very nature of momentum investing determines that the decline, when it comes, will be plenty ugly. Why? Because many of these investors care little about fundamental methods of valuing companies and their shares, so they are largely uninformed of what a company's fair value might be. When an investor has no concept of valuation, he has no concept of value. The result: Declines in stocks that are excessive. <p>Say, for example, that by looking at a company's history and making calculated guesses about its immediate earnings potential, you determine its fundamental value to be around 12 times earnings. But, in their euphoria, momentum investors have bid the stock up to 18 times earnings. When these fickle folk bail out, you may well see the stock drop to 8 times earnings--well below its fundamental value--before it finds its true level again. This is because fewer and fewer investors understand what a company's fundamental value is. <p>Wall Street analysts contribute to this lack of understanding by regularly predicting outlandish earnings for companies in the far-off future. Broderbund Software, a highflying PC software maker trading at around 32 times trailing earnings, is a hit among momentum players. That's because analysts estimate Broderbund's earnings will be $1.64 a share in 1994 and will continue growing at more than 25 percent annually until 1998. Investors, therefore, can rationalize paying 32 times past earnings for Broderbund because they're really only paying 26 times '94 estimates for the stock. Fine, until Broderbund fails to meet analysts' expectations.<p>Veterans of the investing scene say that many analysts' projections today are so hopelessly pie-in-the-sky as to be worthless. Why is this? In the past, analysts would typically shave 15 percent off their cash flow projections to account for uncertainties such as potentially rising inflation or interest rates. Now, analysts only discount their estimates by roughly 3 percent, a much smaller margin for error. <p>Another reason why stocks may fall precipitously when the momentum game finally loses steam? There are fewer short sellers around to buy shares as they're dropping. These investors have been driven out of many stocks by their explosive moves up. <p>Short sellers sell shares they don't own, in the belief that a stock is overvalued, and hope to close out their positions profitably by buying the shares back at a lower price. This buying force provides something of a floor in a falling stock and can actually mitigate a broad decline. But short sellers have been so brutalized by highflying stock prices that many have thrown in the towel and become buyers instead. Since 1991, money under management among the shorts has gone from an estimated $4 billion to $2 billion today.<p>Although down markets are no fun for anyone, they are particularly hard on momentum players. Mark Hulbert, editor of the Hulbert Financial Digest, has studied investment-newsletter writers' performance in up and down markets. He has concluded that these types of investors perform especially badly at the beginning of a downturn because they continue to favor stocks that were top price performers but no longer are. Neither are momentum types winners at the beginning of a bull move. Why? Stocks that have the most relative price strength are stodgy numbers like utilities, which won't participate much in a rally. "Relative strength works best," says Hulbert, "in the final stages of a bull market."<p>The long-term performance of Columbine Capital's earnings-momentum model confirms this thesis. Stocks that ranked highest in the firm's model outperformed the market by almost 2 percent a month during bull phases like 1973 and 1982. But in tougher markets, like those of the mid-'70s and 1983, the model either underperformed the market or eked out only minuscule gains. These returns do not take into account transaction costs. <p>Also troubling is the fact that many fund managers who are big in momentum today have not lived through a long-lasting bear market. Arthur Nicholas, for example, opened up his shop in 1984; portfolio strategist Avery started managing money shortly thereafter. Investors can take little comfort knowing that these managers have not yet survived the crucible of a down market. <p>The folks at Nicholas-Applegate are confident that their system will not fail them, regardless of how the market behaves. Ashley Rabun, president of the mutual fund branch, explains that they weigh their investment criteria differently, depending on overall market conditions. She says, "We're very disciplined. Our weightings change to reflect whatever is getting the highest premium in the market at the time." Meaning, if big price moves in stocks are being rewarded by other investors more than big earnings moves, they'll go with the price flow. But if that suddenly changes, Nicholas-Applegate managers will take the new tack.<p>Newcomers to momentum investing may not know what to do when the herd moves to the next market fad. This worries Robert Moyer, vice president of Driehaus Capital Management, the firm profiled in Institutional Investor. "We're watching the tape moment by moment. We've got a bunch of people standing by ready to move. When [the market] breaks, it will break faster. People are more likely to get hurt because they can't react as quickly."<p>Of course, nobody wants to think bear-market thoughts--particularly when the momentum game is so much fun. And when anybody does mutter darkly about what might happen in a market downdraft, bullish investors happily point to the towering piles of cash currently sitting undeployed in stock-fund portfolios as evidence that the Big Mo will roll on (see "Cash on Hand"). Indeed, the Investment Company Institute reports that stock-fund managers are holding some $58 billion in cash in their portfolios. If the market began to drift lower, the thinking goes, this cash would flood into stocks, providing something of a floor to the fall. Fifty-eight billion dollars is surely enough to stop a downdraft in its tracks.<p>Maybe so. It's certainly a sizable hoard. But when you place it against the market capitalization of all three U.S. stock markets--the New York Stock Exchange, the American, and Nasdaq--the hoard shrinks considerably. That total market value currently stands at an astonishing $5.3 trillion. <p>What does this mean? Even if all the $58 billion in cash now sitting in stock funds went into equities, it would help not one iota in stopping a market decline. In fact, all that money would be absorbed by just about a 1 percent drop in the averages. In a $5.3 trillion stock market, $58 billion is a drop in the bucket. <p>Even the much larger amounts of investor cash sitting in money market funds would be of little help in a falling market. According to the Investment Company Institute, investors currently hold some $564 billion in taxable and tax-free money funds. Every nickel of it would be absorbed by an 11 percent downward move in equities, which is roughly the loss in market capitalization experienced in 1990. So much for the consolation that cash on the sidelines is protection against a big bear move in equities. <p>The fact is, there is never much in the way of protection for investors when stocks start to slide. Add to this the ill effects that are likely when the trendy momentum game reverses itself, and you've got more than a little reason for caution. As Steven Vannelli says: "The storm isn't here yet, but the yellow flags are certainly up."<p>Forewarned is forearmed.<p>Gretchen Morgenson is the executive editor of Worth.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Stock Market Trends, Stock Investing Strategies
A faddish investment technique called momentum investing has propelled stock prices into the heavens. What happens when the fad fades?<p>By Gretchen Morgenson<p>Folks who had the good fortune to be in the stock market last year enjoyed one delightful ride. In spite of some dizzying dives in individual stocks or the occasional industry group, 1993 was stellar for equities. <p>The biggest winners were shareholders in the small-capitalization companies, as the averages show. Hands-down winner was the Russell 2000, an index of small-cap stocks, which had increased some 15 percent by mid-December. <p>An only slightly lesser performer was the Dow Jones Industrial Average, up 13 percent. In third place was the Nasdaq composite, an index of 4,400 companies that was up 12.5 percent last year; trailing was the larger-capitalization S&P 500 index, up only 6.5 percent on the year.<p>Hoping for more of the same, investors are piling into the stocks and mutual funds that won 1993's capital-gains race. Will they be handsomely rewarded once again? Maybe so, but markets rarely stay the same long enough to reward investors assiduously chasing last year's trend. <p>Particularly worrisome is the recent nature of that trend. As more money floods into the stock market, increasing numbers of fund and money managers are taking up a method of investing that has all the earmarks of the latest stock market fad. It's called momentum investing.<p>Unlike past investment fashions, the fad of the moment hasn't affixed itself to a particular group of stocks; neither does it revolve around an industry. What the investment trendies are up to today is a method of stock picking that relies little on how a company is doing--the so-called fundamental analysis of an operation's net worth, business prospects, or balance sheets. Instead, it focuses on how the company's stock is doing. <p>Like all Wall Street fads, momentum investing is beautiful in its simplicity. If a stock's price is going up, it's a buy. When it stops going up, it's a sell. In the world of physics, momentum is motion conjoined with force. In the world of investing, momentum is the motion of a stock conjoined with the force of the herd. <p>Steven Vannelli is a money manager at KJMM Investment Management in San Francisco who has been watching the momentum game play out for some months now. Investors should be concerned about how the game will end, says Vannelli. "The danger with momentum investing is it's great in an up market, hell in a down market," he says. <p>The fuel that has been driving stocks skyward is indeed a volatile mix: low inflation, low interest rates, and increased levels of corporate efficiency, which translate to higher margins and earnings among issuers. Last, but by no means least, is investors' apparently insatiable appetite for investments that will return something greater than the 2.5 percent rate currently found in bank CDs. It is this craving that explains the $411 billion investors poured into stock mutual funds in the last half of 1993, a figure that was up 39 percent from the year before.<p>All in all, it's the perfect environment for creating the newest high-octane investment fad. All rising markets have them. In the bull market of the 1960s, the no-brainer investment strategy revolved around the Nifty Fifty--a group of stocks, including Avon, National Student Marketing, and <a name="NYSE:EK"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10500"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Kodak</b></a>, that could do no wrong for investors. The bear market of 1974 brought that little fantasy to an end. Then, in the early 1980s, anything to do with high technology became a stock market darling. Until the summer of 1983, that is, when tech stocks crashed to earth. Alas, all good investment fads must come to an end.<p>Momentum investing--investors looking for price action in a stock, bond, or commodity and hopping on for the ride--is nothing new. In the 1970s, it was more popular in the commodities pits than it was on stock exchange floors. It was known then as "trend following," and crafty traders made money with it for several years until the commodities became virtually trendless. Then the followers had nothing to follow. In the 1980s, adherents to what we now call the momentum school were more often known as "relative strength" players, because they looked for strength in stock prices.<p>Today, however, the use of actual earnings growth among momentum players has been superseded by investors who buy stocks largely on recent price behavior. As one money manager explained it, these investors seem to believe that buying on price jumps is a shortcut to the same end. Why waste time slogging through financial statements looking for earnings growth? If a stock's price is rising, it's probably because somebody else who has done the analysis likes it and is buying.<p>When momentum investors buy a stock, their thinking goes something like this: You like it, I like it, maybe we can find a third person who'll like it too. As long as buyers continue to snap up the stock, all is well; like a rocket leaving the launching pad, momentum looks unstoppable, initially. Trouble comes when investors have pushed the stock as high as it will go and a few start to bail. Then, momentum slows, and suddenly, the very reason everyone bought the stock in the first place has disappeared. Everybody heads for the exits at once. When the only reason to buy a stock is based on its rising price, there's little reason to hold when it begins its descent. <p>This explains the violent and seemingly inexplicable downdrafts that are often seen in stocks today. Shares in Household International, for example, dropped almost 8 percent in one day's trading in early December when the financial-services company said its 1994 earnings would likely be at the lower end of analysts' projections. The momentum crowd is also the force behind the troubling volatility evidenced in certain industry groups (see "Swings in the Sectors").<p>Just how popular is momentum investing? Exact numbers of money managers playing the game are hard to come by--they're certainly not listed as such in fund directories. Equally difficult to pin down are numbers of assets currently controlled by momentum players. Part of the problem, according to some fund types, is that few folks want to admit to being proponents. <p>Arthur Nicholas, for example, head of the hugely successful Nicholas-Applegate money-management group ($12 billion under management), hates being described as a momentum player. This in spite of the fact that his portfolio managers count heavily on price and earnings momentum when picking stocks for institutional clients and mutual fund portfolios. The momentum label trivializes his investment style, says Nicholas. Buying stocks based on price moves just doesn't have the gravitas that investors demand of their money managers. <p>Still, the strategy is becoming more mainstream every day. Money manager Vannelli believes momentum investors are an enormous force in today's market. "There's so much money being run by people who don't even read annual reports today," he says. "Huge numbers of investors--insurance companies, mutual fund managers--just buy the momentum." <p>Amy Arnott, an analyst at Morningstar, a mutual fund-analysis firm in Chicago, agrees that momentum investing is on the rise in the fund business. "I've noticed more portfolio managers talking about it," she says. "Plus, when you see a lot of people piling into the same stocks, that's probably the reason." <p>Momentum investing was also behind a big December pitch made to investors and prospects by Carlton Lutts, editor of the Cabot Market Letter, an investment newsletter. Calling his investment strategy the Momentum System 1000, Lutts says it is the secret to "turning $5,000 into $225,000 with just one stock." Lutts writes, "I have discovered what I call the single most important tool for picking winning stocks: Momentum Analysis." When an investing strategy is sold through the mails, you know it's mainstream.<p>Here's some evidence that points to an increase in momentum players among mutual fund managers today: The average turnover ratio of aggressive-growth stock funds, as measured by Morningstar, is up significantly from premomentum levels of a decade ago. <p>How many times a fund manager turns over his portfolio in one year--a 100 percent ratio means a manager has bought and sold the equivalent of his entire portfolio during the year--can be revealing of the fund manager's style. Momentum players, by their very nature, have higher turnover ratios than value investors do; this is because price players move in and out of stocks more quickly--they're happy to abandon a stock simply because it is no longer rising fast enough. Other types of investors are more patient and turn over their portfolios less frequently. <p>It's not surprising, then, that over the past ten years, the average annual turnover rate among aggressive-growth funds--where most momentum players can be found--has increased by 67 percent. Compare this to the averages among other equity-fund categories: Turnover among small-cap-fund managers, for example, grew just 12 percent over the decade, while the average growth and income fund turned over its portfolio just 16 percent more than it used to. And turnover rates among foreign-stock-fund managers actually declined 16 percent during the decade.<p>Another measure of momentum's new acceptance among investors? The cover of the November issue of Institutional Investor, a publication read by professional money managers, celebrates Richard Driehaus, a Chicago-based money manager and big momentum player. And, Wall Street sources say, momentum investing has even trickled down to the ranks of retail brokers, who are pitching their clients on the merits of investing with the herd.<p>People in the fund-management business observe that even former value investors are jumping on the momentum trend. This worries market observers who note that when investors change their strategies midstream, it often signals the beginning of the end of a strong market. Michael Long, principal of Rockbridge Partners, an investment firm in Charlotte, North Carolina, says: "More value types have capitulated to momentum theory. The only way for managers to get money from investors is to be in stocks that have done well." In other words, the biggest movers.<p>Long's point is key to understanding why momentum investing is surging in popularity today. Each new billion that cascades into stock mutual fund coffers puts money managers into this ever more tremendous bind: "How on earth should I invest this money intelligently?" It's a nice problem to have--too much money--but it is a problem nonetheless. The apparent solution, to more and more managers: Invest with the crowd.<p>Veterans of the momentum approach to investing stress that it can only work properly if combined with diligent fundamental analysis. Columbine Capital, a money-management firm in Colorado Springs, has supplied a price-momentum investment model to institutional clients since the late 1970s. The firm studies 12 months of a stock's price moves, corrects the data for excess volatility, and ranks the stock for "relative momentum." John Brush, president of Columbine says, "This gives considerable predictive power, relative to all other stocks. It's a helpful addition to the valuation of stocks. But nobody in their right mind invests on price momentum alone." <p>No? Some of the biggest names in momentum investing today (see "Momentum Mutual Funds") seem to be straying well beyond the boundaries that disciplined adherents, like Brush, stick to. For example, Columbine excludes all new issues from its model --a stock must have at least a year's worth of trading behind it before it has any predictive capabilities. Yet Dreihaus, the momentum trader profiled in Institutional Investor, bets early and often in the new-issue market. So does Catherine Avery, a portfolio manager at Nicholas-Applegate, who runs a $2.3 billion (assets) emerging-growth portfolio. <p>Initial public offerings that skyrocket in price right out of the gate--Snapple Beverage, Boston Chicken, and Callaway Golf are three examples--become immediate favorites of momentum investors if only because their stocks suddenly jump. <p>How does a momentum player make investment decisions? Most fund managers don't like to reveal their secrets, but the process seems to go something like this. Because the fund manager trades constantly through many different brokerage firms, he or she is likely to get the first call from a broker offering shares in a hot IPO. The manager buys all he can, knowing it is likely to rise substantially because there are not enough shares to satisfy investor demand. He also agrees to buy more shares in the open market after they begin trading. As other investors, shut out of the initial offering, snap up the stock, its price typically continues to rise. This action confirms to the momentum investor that he should stay in the stock.<p>Selling time comes when something about the stock's prospects--sales, earnings, or even its price--starts to crest. Maybe there's a sense on Wall Street that the industry the company's in is going to slow its growth. Or the money manager may simply feel there are faster-moving stocks elsewhere that are better buys. Before you can say, "Fire!" everybody's crowding the door.<p>As practiced today, momentum investing can pretty much be summed up this way: aggressive money chasing yesterday's highfliers. Says fund manager Long, "People can't find any other reason to justify paying these prices for stocks, so they call it momentum." Although the practice is not totally responsible for sky-high stock valuations today--both price-to-earnings ratios and book values on the major equity indexes are at all-time highs --it has certainly contributed to rich stock prices. And it has made some sectors of the market much more volatile than before. <p>The trouble is, those rocketing returns of yesterday are what every mutual fund, brokerage firm, and managed-account investor is looking to his fund managers to beat tomorrow. As Tom Wolfe would say, tout le monde has become a momentum investor.<p>And why not, while the market's rising? Momentum makes for fun and gains on the way up. And there's that famous Wall Street maxim "Don't fight the tape." Still, investors have a right to wonder now: What effect will the increasing numbers of momentum investors have in the unwanted but inevitable down market? What happens when stock prices go into a cyclical decline, creating a massive sell signal to all momentum players? <p>The simple answer is that what we all witnessed on the upside will be mirrored in a decline. But as anyone who has lived through a blistering bear market will tell you, gravity has a way of dragging stocks down further than is truly justified. And because certain stocks have been driven to unsustainable heights by the current euphoria of the investing crowd, when their prices fall, the decline will be all the more precipitous.<p>To get a glimpse of what such a descent might look like, check out the action in some of the sectors and stocks that the momentum players have recently abandoned. Consider, for instance, the volatility that characterized just three weeks of trading in the electronics, insurance, and heavy-duty transportation industries during November (see "Swings in the Sectors"). In just three weeks of trading, ending November 12, the electronics component of the S&P 500 went from being the number 11-ranked performer out of 108 industry groups to the 84th, then back again to number 1. The insurance group began the period ranked number 87, then moved down to near the bottom at 101, only to zoom to number 6 by week three. Moves like these, jarring to buy-and-hold investors, have much to do with fast-money momentum players. <p>The effects are even worse in individual stocks. Newbridge Networks, for example, a favorite of the hot-money crowd, lost almost 10 points in the week of trading ended November 19. That's a staggering $392 million of market capitalization, gone in a flash. And why did the computer-networking stock take such a hit? The company's crime was that its second-quarter results as reported--earnings and margins were both up sharply--only just met analysts' expectations. What Newbridge should have done, had it wanted to keep its stock high, was exceed those expectations. <p>Similarly perverse reactions befell other momentum stocks during the same week Newbridge stumbled (see "Swings in the Stocks"). L.M. Ericsson Telephone's American depositary receipts fell almost 10 points on the week, losing $2 billion in market value for the Swedish telecommunications giant. And Qualcomm, a maker of digital wireless-communications gear, plunged almost 20 points on the week, costing it $466 million in market value. Both stocks were victims of unrealistic expectations held by investors who, as is always the case with the momentum game, sold at the first whiff of disappointment. Or, as in these three cases, well before the first whiff of disappointment was evidenced. <p>"I'll sell if the reason for my purchase of a stock is no longer valid," says Nicholas-Applegate's Avery. "If sales are going to be flat or fundamental leadership of the stock has changed and its price has turned down." <p>Not that the company's no longer a winner, mind you. As Avery points out, "It does us no good to be in a company that's good but that nobody cares about." No longer is an investment made because of the company; it's now made because of the stock. And because others like the stock.<p>There are a variety of reasons why investors should be worried about what will happen to stock prices in general when the rocket that is momentum investing begins to reverse. How do we know it will? Because all investment fads do, especially those that require everlasting increases in earnings or stock prices. Even the most benighted investor knows that nothing grows to the sky. Not even <a name="NYSE:IBM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10796"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>IBM</b></a>. Not even <a name="NYSE:WMT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11600"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Wal-Mart</b></a>.<p>As money man Vannelli puts it, "Companies have cycles. They can't keep going ad infinitum at a constant level of change." So investors seeking that unattainable constant pile in and out of companies and industries ever more rapidly, roiling the markets and whipsawing investment bystanders.<p>The very nature of momentum investing determines that the decline, when it comes, will be plenty ugly. Why? Because many of these investors care little about fundamental methods of valuing companies and their shares, so they are largely uninformed of what a company's fair value might be. When an investor has no concept of valuation, he has no concept of value. The result: Declines in stocks that are excessive. <p>Say, for example, that by looking at a company's history and making calculated guesses about its immediate earnings potential, you determine its fundamental value to be around 12 times earnings. But, in their euphoria, momentum investors have bid the stock up to 18 times earnings. When these fickle folk bail out, you may well see the stock drop to 8 times earnings--well below its fundamental value--before it finds its true level again. This is because fewer and fewer investors understand what a company's fundamental value is. <p>Wall Street analysts contribute to this lack of understanding by regularly predicting outlandish earnings for companies in the far-off future. Broderbund Software, a highflying PC software maker trading at around 32 times trailing earnings, is a hit among momentum players. That's because analysts estimate Broderbund's earnings will be $1.64 a share in 1994 and will continue growing at more than 25 percent annually until 1998. Investors, therefore, can rationalize paying 32 times past earnings for Broderbund because they're really only paying 26 times '94 estimates for the stock. Fine, until Broderbund fails to meet analysts' expectations.<p>Veterans of the investing scene say that many analysts' projections today are so hopelessly pie-in-the-sky as to be worthless. Why is this? In the past, analysts would typically shave 15 percent off their cash flow projections to account for uncertainties such as potentially rising inflation or interest rates. Now, analysts only discount their estimates by roughly 3 percent, a much smaller margin for error. <p>Another reason why stocks may fall precipitously when the momentum game finally loses steam? There are fewer short sellers around to buy shares as they're dropping. These investors have been driven out of many stocks by their explosive moves up. <p>Short sellers sell shares they don't own, in the belief that a stock is overvalued, and hope to close out their positions profitably by buying the shares back at a lower price. This buying force provides something of a floor in a falling stock and can actually mitigate a broad decline. But short sellers have been so brutalized by highflying stock prices that many have thrown in the towel and become buyers instead. Since 1991, money under management among the shorts has gone from an estimated $4 billion to $2 billion today.<p>Although down markets are no fun for anyone, they are particularly hard on momentum players. Mark Hulbert, editor of the Hulbert Financial Digest, has studied investment-newsletter writers' performance in up and down markets. He has concluded that these types of investors perform especially badly at the beginning of a downturn because they continue to favor stocks that were top price performers but no longer are. Neither are momentum types winners at the beginning of a bull move. Why? Stocks that have the most relative price strength are stodgy numbers like utilities, which won't participate much in a rally. "Relative strength works best," says Hulbert, "in the final stages of a bull market."<p>The long-term performance of Columbine Capital's earnings-momentum model confirms this thesis. Stocks that ranked highest in the firm's model outperformed the market by almost 2 percent a month during bull phases like 1973 and 1982. But in tougher markets, like those of the mid-'70s and 1983, the model either underperformed the market or eked out only minuscule gains. These returns do not take into account transaction costs. <p>Also troubling is the fact that many fund managers who are big in momentum today have not lived through a long-lasting bear market. Arthur Nicholas, for example, opened up his shop in 1984; portfolio strategist Avery started managing money shortly thereafter. Investors can take little comfort knowing that these managers have not yet survived the crucible of a down market. <p>The folks at Nicholas-Applegate are confident that their system will not fail them, regardless of how the market behaves. Ashley Rabun, president of the mutual fund branch, explains that they weigh their investment criteria differently, depending on overall market conditions. She says, "We're very disciplined. Our weightings change to reflect whatever is getting the highest premium in the market at the time." Meaning, if big price moves in stocks are being rewarded by other investors more than big earnings moves, they'll go with the price flow. But if that suddenly changes, Nicholas-Applegate managers will take the new tack.<p>Newcomers to momentum investing may not know what to do when the herd moves to the next market fad. This worries Robert Moyer, vice president of Driehaus Capital Management, the firm profiled in Institutional Investor. "We're watching the tape moment by moment. We've got a bunch of people standing by ready to move. When [the market] breaks, it will break faster. People are more likely to get hurt because they can't react as quickly."<p>Of course, nobody wants to think bear-market thoughts--particularly when the momentum game is so much fun. And when anybody does mutter darkly about what might happen in a market downdraft, bullish investors happily point to the towering piles of cash currently sitting undeployed in stock-fund portfolios as evidence that the Big Mo will roll on (see "Cash on Hand"). Indeed, the Investment Company Institute reports that stock-fund managers are holding some $58 billion in cash in their portfolios. If the market began to drift lower, the thinking goes, this cash would flood into stocks, providing something of a floor to the fall. Fifty-eight billion dollars is surely enough to stop a downdraft in its tracks.<p>Maybe so. It's certainly a sizable hoard. But when you place it against the market capitalization of all three U.S. stock markets--the New York Stock Exchange, the American, and Nasdaq--the hoard shrinks considerably. That total market value currently stands at an astonishing $5.3 trillion. <p>What does this mean? Even if all the $58 billion in cash now sitting in stock funds went into equities, it would help not one iota in stopping a market decline. In fact, all that money would be absorbed by just about a 1 percent drop in the averages. In a $5.3 trillion stock market, $58 billion is a drop in the bucket. <p>Even the much larger amounts of investor cash sitting in money market funds would be of little help in a falling market. According to the Investment Company Institute, investors currently hold some $564 billion in taxable and tax-free money funds. Every nickel of it would be absorbed by an 11 percent downward move in equities, which is roughly the loss in market capitalization experienced in 1990. So much for the consolation that cash on the sidelines is protection against a big bear move in equities. <p>The fact is, there is never much in the way of protection for investors when stocks start to slide. Add to this the ill effects that are likely when the trendy momentum game reverses itself, and you've got more than a little reason for caution. As Steven Vannelli says: "The storm isn't here yet, but the yellow flags are certainly up."<p>Forewarned is forearmed.<p>Gretchen Morgenson is the executive editor of Worth.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Stock Market Trends, Stock Investing Strategies

