<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/02-Cold-Call Cowboys Ride On</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b> </b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/02-Cold-Call Cowboys Ride On</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 
Why investors are never safe from the broiler-room tactics of brokerage firms like Stratton Oakmont.<p>By Gretchen Morgenson<p>So what if the securities and exchange commission has filed suit against them? The boys at bucket-shop brokerage Stratton Oakmont, Inc. are busier than ever. Dialing as many as 400 investors a day with talk of fat stock market profits, one of the 200 or so Stratton brokers may be calling you next. Hang up the phone if they find you--according to the SEC, they're very good at separating investors from their money. <p>The securities-fraud trial, which targets the firm and its three top guns, Jordan Belfort, Daniel Porush, and Kenneth Greene, is scheduled to begin this month in New York City. Although Belfort and his pals have been awaiting trial since March 1992, they've certainly not been wasting time. After all, hot markets for initial public offerings--like the one we've seen recently--don't come along every day. And there's just too much money to be made on the crummy new stock issues Stratton Oakmont likes to churn out. The stock-flogging show must go on. <p>Stratton sure has chutzpah. The SEC seeks $11 million in ill-gotten gains it alleges the firm made manipulating a stock called Nova Capital. Yet even as the government pursues that action, the Long Island-based brokerage firm is expanding operations and bringing new stock issues public.<p>Last fall, the four-year-old firm threw a big bash at the University of Maryland's job fair, to try to attract recruits for a new office the company is rumored to be opening in the state. The party, with an open bar and live music, was held at a hotel near the university's College Park campus. Not surprisingly, given today's tough job market for college graduates, some 500 people came to learn more about a "career" in the brokerage business with Stratton. As one former Stratton salesman says: "I can just imagine the speech given to these kids: 'You, too, can have all this.' They might as well feed them punch, like Jim Jones did."<p>Stratton's stock-selling techniques are a thing of beauty to behold--as long as you're not one of the investors sucked in. Here's how the game works, as explained by a refugee from the firm. <p>Belfort, 31, a former meat salesman, or one of his colleagues finds a crony or an acquaintance who has a company that can be brought public. It doesn't have to be much of a company, mind you, for Belfort to turn it into one hell of a stock. <p>For instance, one of Stratton's most recent offerings was 1.7 million units--a combination of common stock and warrants--in Steve Madden, Ltd., a four-year-old shoe retailer and designer, which has lost a cumulative $75,000 on sales of $4.75 million since its birth.<p>Why, in the competitive women's shoe industry--dominated by huge, well-capitalized players like U.S. Shoe and Brown Group--would Stratton choose to launch an unknown like Steve Madden? One reason, according to former insiders: The footwear designer is a childhood friend of Daniel Porush, Stratton's president.<p>This kind of association is typical in Stratton's offerings. Consider Master Glazier's Karate International, a New Jersey operator of four karate-instruction centers, which Stratton brought public last October. Never mind that the company, incorporated last March, had losses of $63,800 on sales of $637,000 for the first half of 1993 and a negative net worth prior to the offering: Master Glazier's president was a college pal of Jordan Belfort's. The day the units came public at $4, they zoomed to $9.75. They recently traded at around $9 each.<p>Before you wish that you'd gotten in on the Master Glazier deal, consider this. According to a former salesman who observed numerous Stratton deals, very few "average" investors get the stock at or near the offering price. Those lucky spots are reserved for friends of the firm and insiders. Only after the stock has risen do outside investors get the chance to buy. And this "opportunity" is given only because the insiders want to take their profits and run.<p>Stratton IPOs are often paybacks to Stratton insiders or pals who have loaned money to the fledgling company or its executives. In the Madden deal, for example, Belfort, Porush, and Green are sole stockholders in Madden Acquisition Network Group; upon conclusion of the offering they held almost 40 percent of Steve Madden Ltd.'s common stock. <p>Another of the offerings Stratton intends to dump on the public shows how handsomely the firm likes to reward its friends. The deal is 1.5 million units of something called Arnie's Bagelicious Bagels, a three-year-old bagel manufacturer in Brooklyn that earned $325,000 in the year ending April 1993. Once again, the company is setting out to take business away from established bagel suppliers like Skulnicks, Sara Lee, and Lender's, a division of Kraft/General Foods. In this effort, it may or may not succeed.<p>But Arnie's future success or failure matters little to the investors who loaned the company money prior to the offering. They're getting theirs as soon as Stratton launches the stock. <p>One such inside investor is, you guessed it, Steve Madden, of shoe-store fame. For the $250,000 Madden loaned Arnie's Bagelicious last fall, he will receive full repayment plus 7 percent interest and 150,000 units of Arnie's stock. These units consist of common stock and three different kinds of warrants. What are friends for? <p>After an offering is placed--Arnie's, Steve Madden, it doesn't really matter--the real fun starts. Stratton cold callers, working in rooms of 100 or so, pound the phones casting for clients. If they land a big one--an investor willing to put $100,000 toward a trade--he's called a whale. All others, especially the more recalcitrant customers, are called pikers. <p>The undersea metaphor is apt: Stratton brokers are nothing less than sharks, even if they do wear business suits. At the front of each office is a blackboard where big trades get written up and celebrated. Often, if a salesman opened three accounts, he or she got a $100 bonus. The cold-call cowboys have even sent out three-month-old copies of Worth to new accounts in an attempt to legitimize their firm.<p>But there's nothing legitimate about it, according to the SEC. In its complaint, the commission describes the high-pressure, boiler-room sales practices of Stratton brokers, few of whom have any prior experience in the securities business. Belfort and pals, according to the complaint, "urged Stratton registered representatives to 'take' customers 'to the mat,' 'to rip their heads off.'" Porush and Green gave Stratton brokers a new moniker: "phone terrorists." <p>It is this phone terrorism that propels Stratton stocks into the stratosphere. Rising stocks, like Master Glazier's and Nova's, provide an excellent opportunity for anybody holding shares at a lower price to take profits. After the insiders sell, the stocks typically seem to crater, leaving the outsiders holding the bag.<p>One after another of the Stratton deals--Outtakes, Judicate, Repossession Auction-- spike up in price, only to sink to less than $1 a share. All the way down, investors are strongly discouraged from selling the Stratton stocks they've had the misfortune to buy into.<p>This is just what happened to shares of Nova Capital, the case the SEC is pursuing Belfort and gang on. The SEC claims that Stratton brokers pushed Nova's stock by making exaggerated statements about the company's prospects, then sold their own holdings at the higher prices. The stock, which traded as high as $7, crashed to around $1.50 a share.<p>But there's always another gullible investor waiting to answer the phone. So Stratton continues, unabated.<p>Will the SEC succeed in shutting down Stratton Oakmont this month? Ira Lee Sorkin, Stratton's attorney, thinks not; he is vigorously defending the case. "The SEC complaint is, for the most part, always more serious than the facts truly show," he says. "If you do any analysis of the firm's business, you'll see it has not underwritten blind pools, shell companies, or blank checks. The firm has been successful, and the firm's offerings have been successful." Perhaps. But what about the firm's customers? <p>If the commission wins its case, Jordan Belfort may have to go back to selling steaks. Only trouble is, stocks are much more lucrative. In the two years ending October 1991, Belfort made $9.4 million in salary, bonuses, commissions, and trading profits, according to the SEC. And in the years he's been perfecting his game, Belfort's become quite partial to Ferraris, Mercedes 600s, and $28,000 bottles of wine.<p>Shame to have to give all that up now.<p>Gretchen Morgenson is the executive editor of Worth.<p> <p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

