<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/02-Making Sense of Economist-Speak</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/02-Making Sense of Economist-Speak</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
Why stable growth doesn't guarantee rising stocks<p>By Jim Jubak<p>Factor out all the interesting disagreements economists have on the immediate future of the U.S. economy and you get the consensus: 1994 is going to look a lot like last year, with growth and inflation of about 2.5 percent to 3.5 percent. Keep in mind, though, that those figures are for the year as a whole. Quarter to quarter, we're in for a bumpy ride.
Richard Hoey, chief economist at the Dreyfus Corp., expects that growth will trace a U pattern in 1994. After a 4 percent first quarter, the economy will slow in the spring.
Stan Nabi, chief economist at Bessemer Trust Cos. in New York, also foresees a big pothole in the spring following a move by the Federal Reserve to raise interest rates modestly--one quarter of a percent, or 25 basis points. He expects the Fed's move to come between February and April.
Three percent growth versus 2.5 percent, so what? Well, look at the relationship between economic-growth rates and the stock market in the chart to the right. The market seems to anticipate the economy. Good years for the market, 21.44 percent in 1982, for example, often come in bad years for the economy (down 2.2 percent), because the market anticipates a coming economic upturn. In 1993 the market foresaw another year of growth in 1994. Smooth sailing of 3 percent a quarter in 1994 won't disturb those expectations. But if growth dips from 4 percent in the last quarter of 1993 and the first quarter of 1994 to just 2.5 percent in the spring--and if the Fed raises rates--the market could start anticipating a very different future. And that could give a jolt to stock prices.
 <p>
KEYWORDS: Economy

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
