<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/02-Battle of the Crystal Balls</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/02-Battle of the Crystal Balls</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 
Is the market's future full of 10 percent returns?<p>By Jim Jubak<p>Is the market going up? Yes, says the investment firm of Goldman Sachs. One of its models shows that the market is undervalued by 24 percent.<p>Are we due for a correction? Absolutely, says one prominent stock-market strategist. He calculates the market is overvalued by 25 percent. <p>Whom to believe? Both. The two models actually agree: The15 percent annual returns of the1980s are over.<p>The bearish view comes from Michael Murphy, editor of The Overpriced Stock Service. Using the operating earnings of the 30 Dow Jones Industrials stocks and the average price-to-earnings ratio at market highs, he figures the Dow is fully valued at 2970. It hit 3716 on December 15.<p>The bullish Goldman Sachs model, for its part, relies on today's low interest rates and inflation to reach its conclusion.<p>Contradictory views? Go to the end of 1994 and see what happens. No one expects interest rates or inflation to fall in 1994, so any appreciation in either model has to come from earnings growth.<p>As of mid-November 1993, the mean Wall Street estimate of 1994 earnings for the Dow stocks was $228. That's unlikely but not impossible: Earnings in1989, the best year of that decade, were $221. Still, using Murphy's formula, that's just 4104 on the Dow, a 10 percent gain for 1994.<p>After a 4.2 percent increase in 1992 and about 13 percent in '93, a 10 percent rise would bring the three-year average to 9.1 percent, close to the historic norm for equities. Not bad, as long as investors don't take on excessive risk fighting for 15 percent when the market's only giving 10.
 <p>
KEYWORDS: Stock Market Trends

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
