<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/02-Stocks That Won't Remain Cheap</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/02-Stocks That Won't Remain Cheap</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 
Three downtrodden issues worth buying<p>By Derrick Niederman<p>In a market widely viewed as overvalued, are there any "cheap" stocks left? If so, are they worth buying? One way to look for bargains is to single out issues that are priced less expensively than the S&P 500. Currently, the average price of a stock listed in this index runs about 17 times anticipated 1994 earnings. <p>Of course, such a criterion alone would yield hundreds of candidates, many of which deserve a below-average price.<p>So let's add two other things to our search. The first: Visible, predictable earnings growth. A stock with this feature offers hope that the market will one day honor the company's performance by removing whatever skepticism is reflected in the current discount valuation. This would ideally lead to a higher multiple on higher earnings. <p>The second thing we'll look for is a "wild card"__a potential development that could boost the shares of the company in question, but which investors aren't paying for in the current price of the stock. <p>Among today's assortment of cheap stocks, here are three that meet the above criteria, offering a combination of underlying stability and wild-card potential:<p><a name="NYSE:SLM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11410"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Sallie Mae</b></a>(SLM), the Student Loan Marketing Association, now trades at $44 per share, less than eight times expected 1994 earnings. Just 12 months ago, the stock traded above $75 per share. The reason for the decline was the well-publicized initiative by the Clinton administration to get involved with direct lending to students__effectively bypassing Sallie Mae. 
Despite this, note that Sallie Mae's current stock price is about the same as the liquidation value of its portfolio. The drastic valuation prevails even though the growth of the student-loan market should enable Sallie Mae to post double-digit earnings increases for several years even as the government phases in its plan. Finally, whatever the government's intent, it may have difficulty implementing a plan that would hurt Sallie Mae as much as the market suggests today. That "negative wild card" is the final piece of the buy recommendation.<p><a name="NYSE:PT"></a><b>Pet Inc.</b> (PT) is an oddly named collection of packaged-food brands: Progresso (soups) and Old El Paso (Mexican food), Van de Kamp (frozen seafood), and Underwood (canned meat). Pet stock trades at $17 per share, just 13 times expected earnings for calendar year 1994. This low valuation persists despite double-digit earnings growth in each of the last three quarters, an unusual achievement in the beleaguered packaged-food industry. (Companies that fail this test include <a name="NYSE:K"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10841"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Kellogg</b></a>, Quaker Oats, ConAgra, Borden, Heinz, and CPC International.) Progresso's market share alone has grown from 24 percent to 31 percent in a recent comparison to the previous year.<p>Wild card: The stock has been held back by investor concerns about competition in Pet's Mexican-food segment, notably from Taco Bell (<a name="NYSE:PEP"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11166"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>PepsiCo</b></a>) and Ortega (RJR Nabisco). These competitive pressures may persist for some time, but the category itself is growing strongly (6 percent a year versus 1.5 percent for the food category as a whole). Moreover, Pet has stabilized its share within this category at a healthy 23 percent. If Progresso could retain its franchise against the likes of Campbell and ConAgra, then investors may be worrying too much about competition in Mexican food. <p><a name="NYSE:BIC"></a><b>Bic</b> (BIC) is a solid consumer company with established product franchises in shavers, pens, and lighters. Bic's stock trades cheaply, at about 15 times expected earnings for 1994.<p>The mature character of Bic's product lines suggests an uninteresting investment story. But there may be a wild card where you'd least expect it: in the lighter business. Cheap competition, a backlash against smoking, and product-liability issues have hurt the lighter business__all that's already reflected in the stock. But recently, the Consumer Product Safety Commission has mandated that manufacturers of lighters make their products child-resistant by mid-1994. Bic has been a trend setter in this area, with several patents to its credit. With this head start, the company figures to gain additional market share in a business that it already dominates.<p>Separately, Bic's lighter margins have been increasing, a result of lessened expense in the product liability area, a nagging problem for Bic a few years ago.<p> <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Stock Investing Strategies

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
