<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 93/10-Fundamentally Green</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b> </b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>93/10-Fundamentally Green</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 
Now's the time to clan up with out-of favor environmental stocks<p>By Marie D'Amico<p>Environmental stocks are down in the dumps. The garbage crisis that was supposed to boost waste-company stocks never happened. Recyclers can't find enough markets for their laboriously collected paper and plastic. And the highly publicized market for pollution rights now lies comatose from lack of interest.<p>So now is the time to invest in environmental stocks. Right? <p>Well, actually, yes. And not just to save the world or to behave like a brave contrarian. Opportunities in these stocks exist because most of the damage to this sector of the market has already been done--and in many cases overdone. What's more, the long-term trends that once made these stocks look so attractive are essentially still in place. There are many companies in this industry growing at rates as high as 15 percent annually.<p>But please note that we're talking about individual stocks here. Not environmental mutual funds. The lesson of the last three years is that investors in this part of the market should avoid these funds at all costs. In fact, it's the spectacular disappointment created by these funds that has provided this buying opportunity. Investors who want to understand environmental stocks should know a little bit of the history behind that.<p>Environmental-sector funds were born because of the warm glow created by the 20th anniversary of Earth Day in 1990. And they proliferated like an algae bloom.<p>The funds sold investors a great-sounding story: The passage of the Clean Water Act, the Clean Air Act, and the Resource Conservation and Recovery Act in the late 1980s had created a new industry and an ever-expanding market for environmental products and services. Lawrence Greenberg, who at the time ran <a name="FUND:FSLEX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/FSLEX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Fidelity's Select Environmental Services Portfolio</b></a>, called environmental services "one of the growth industries of the 1990s."<p>The story these funds were selling wasn't really wrong--it was just oversold. Investors "were thinking that they were getting funds that were going to help clean up the environment," says Kurt Brouwer, a partner in Brouwer & Janachowski, a San Francisco investment-advisory firm, "whereas the mutual fund companies were looking to benefit from the fact that environmentalist was a hot buzzword." Investors were promised the moon--a clean conscience, terrific growth, and almost no downside, even in tough times. "Everybody thought you needed pollution control, environmental control, even through a recession," says Tom Desmond, environmental-sector analyst for Morningstar. <p>It was too much. This relatively small sector of the market couldn't handle the new influx of fund money. By the end of 1990, Fidelity's fund had $96.8 million, John Hancock's Freedom Environmental had $51 million, and Oppenheimer's Global Environment $53 million.<p>The result: Fund managers had to overpay for stocks. This drove up prices and expectations, which in turn led to disappointment and a sector-wide slaughter. Rian Fried, editor of Clean Yield, an investment advisory newsletter, wrote in March of 1992: "There were too few publicly held companies with too little stock to afford investment fund managers the luxury of picking and choosing suitable investment candidates.. . .  Their actions were driven by necessity--their prospectuses claimed they were organized to purchase environmental stocks, so they had to purchase environmental stocks."<p>While the average equity mutual fund rose 38.4 percent between the end of July 1990 and the end of that same month in 1993, many of the environmental funds showed declines. The Fidelity fund dropped 11.68 percent during that period. Thomas Sprague, who managed the Fidelity fund until August 5, declared while he still headed the fund: "I don't recommend my fund to people. I suppose I should, but I don't."<p>Today's argument for investing in the environmental sector is far less hyperbolic than the one the fund companies sold three years ago. There are no miracles on the horizon, and the last recession proved that these stocks suffer when the economy turns toxic.<p>Sure, the Clinton administration will give the sector a modest boost. But the emphasis there is on the word modest. If the White House does indeed tighten enforcement of existing regulations, antipollution stocks will benefit, as will the stocks of companies that operate large landfills. Clinton has also promised to encourage development of new environmental technologies like electric batteries and photovoltaic cells, which gives hope to investors on the high-tech side of the environmental sector. The best estimate is that the worldwide market for environmental products and services, now at $200 billion, will grow by 5 percent annually.<p>"Compared to the last 12 years, we have a situation where conditions are going to be better for companies involved in environmental improvement," says David Beckwith, manager of the John Hancock Freedom Environmental Fund. "It's just a question of when it's going to happen," says Rian Fried. The consensus among analysts points to a pickup in this sector late in 1994.<p>So the key to smart investing in this sector is to hunt for value. In other words: Find stocks that are cheap relative to their real growth prospects. Fried, who in addition to publishing a newsletter manages a $30 million portfolio, says his basic approach is "not to pay more than the growth rate." He adds: "We also look at book value. We like to pay between one and two times book."<p>The basic trends supporting these fundamentals look stronger today than a few years ago. Based largely on the expenditures necessary to meet the requirements of the Clean Air Act Amendments of 1990, which go into effect in November 1994, Robertson Stephens & Co., a San Francisco investment bank, is predicting 8 percent to 10 percent annual growth in air-pollution-control stocks over the next five years. That law should also help companies developing alternative fuels. The long-expected water-supply crunch is now clearly a reality, giving the business of selling clean water a growth rate approaching 10 percent. Spending on environmental cleanup and remediation (the task of repairing damaged land), perhaps the fastest growing sector, is expected to increase to $174 billion in 1995 from $56 billion in 1989.<p>Solid-waste stocks, on the other hand, still aren't very appealing. There is just too much excess capacity in the industry. Subtitle D regulations of the Resource Conservation and Recovery Act mandate better linings for landfills to keep hazardous chemicals in garbage from seeping into the groundwater. That will make the cost of owning and operating dumps higher and eventually force smaller companies out of business. But small operators have received a waiver exempting them from the rules until April 1994. Analysts expect that only about 10 percent of the current capacity will shut down in the next two years. That will mean fewer companies to compete with, but the large haulers like Browning Ferris still won't be able to raise prices by much--if at all. According to Fidelity's Sprague, solid-waste stocks as a group are selling at prices 15 to 20 times earnings but only growing at 10 percent to 15 percent a year. "I like it when the [price-to-earnings ratios] are less than growth rates, not more than growth rates," he says.<p>Fried's value/growth rules lead him to stocks such as <a name="NASD:ARCI"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=15921"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Appliance Recycling Centers</b></a> (ARCI) of Minneapolis. Appliance Recycling is "a very simple idea that makes intuitive sense," says Fried. The company collects old appliances and takes them apart to recover the chlorofluorocarbons. It gets rid of hazardous materials and then recycles the metals. The company works with large appliance makers like <a name="NYSE:WHR"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11632"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Whirlpool</b></a> and with retailers. A few months ago when it was trading at $17.50, or about 40 times earnings, Fried thought it was too expensive. "This is a company that can grow 40 percent to 50 percent a year and has because it's so small," he says. "I'd want to be looking at more like 30 to 35 times earnings, which would be more in the $15 range." The price has recently declined to that level.<p>The environmental sector seems ideally suited to this kind of investing. There is no single company that an investor must own--and therefore no need to chase any stock. The technologies are fluid, and no one can predict which companies will dominate the future. An investor has plenty of time to buy a few shares, learn more about the company, and then, perhaps, buy more when the price is right. This is one market sector where the future will wait for an investor.<p>A final lesson. In 1990 Fidelity's Lawrence Greenberg crowed to Forbes that Waste Management (now called WMXTechnologies), which at the time was at $33.50, a hefty 25 times trailing earnings, was worth every penny because the company was then compounding its earnings at 25 percent a year. "If you assume that growth keeps up for even another two years, the stock doesn't look so overpriced," Forbes concluded. But growth didn't, and today the stock is selling at $30.75, 18 times earnings. An indictment of investing in environmental stocks? No, but a clear sign that investors who overpay live to rue it.<p>
Think Globally, Pick Carefully: Five small companies where the price is right<p>In many sections of the country, supplying enough clean water to cities and industry is already difficult, and municipal officials from Santa Barbara to Phoenix to Long Island are counting on finding new sources. That will create big opportunities for companies that can clean up wastewater or turn salt water into fresh. "I continue to think clean water is going to be one of the great businesses of the '90s," says Dan Leonard, who until recently was manager of the <a name="FUND:FSEVX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/FSEVX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Invesco Environmental Fund</b></a>. One of the best companies in the business, according to analysts, is <a name="NYSE:ION"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12061"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Ionics</b></a>, Inc. (ION), which sells a proprietary system for water purification. Ionics has a lucrative long-term contract with the city of Santa Barbara to convert seawater into fresh H2O. Although the stock has been as high as $60, its current price of $39.25 makes it an attractive long-term investment again, according to Leonard. At that price, the stock is trading at 20 times the last 12 months' earnings per share. Book value of $28.50 a share limits the downside on the stock.<p><a name="NASD:WATR"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14418"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Tetra Tech, Inc. </b></a>(WATR), another water play, is a consulting company that advises clients on how best to clean up their wastewater. (Don't confuse the stock with the similarly named TETRA Technologies [TTRA], which is a waste-treatment and recycling company.) Its biggest potential client: the Department of Energy, which plans to spend $35 billion over the next five years to bring its nuclear-weapons facilities into compliance with federal environmental rules. Over the longer term, cleaning up those sites will cost $200 billion, analysts estimate. The company's technical skills are well suited to this job, according to Randy Scherago, environmental stock analyst at Robertson Stephens & Co. The company now has $450 million to $500 million in bids outstanding. At a current price of $15.75, the stock was trading at 19 times earnings. For fiscal 1993, the company is expected to show $56.1 million in revenue and earnings of 79 cents a share.<p><a name="NASD:OMEG"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=16266"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Omega Environmental Inc.</b></a> (OMEG) sells a patented pressurized system for preventing leaks in underground petroleum storage tanks, a major--and expensive--environmental problem for oil companies. Omega's edge? The company has hooked up with American International Group, the largest pollution liability-insurance underwriter in the U.S. AIG will insure at low rates companies that use Omega's system. Tank companies previously found it virtually impossible to get insurance, and when they did, the cost was outrageous. "Omega has actually changed the actuarial tables," says Mari Bari of Mabon Securities. With 2 million registered underground storage tanks, not to mention 5,000 to 7,000 new installations each year, and the possibility of expanding into aboveground tanks, the company has no shortage of growth opportunities. Bari expects revenues to grow to $225 million by the end of fiscal 1996 from $8 million in fiscal 1993. The company is currently not profitable. Recently the stock was trading at $6.<p><a name="NYSE:WLM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11618"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Wellman Inc.</b></a> (WLM), the nation's largest recycler, turns plastic and fiber wastes into polyester, nylon fibers, and plastic resins for specialty markets and the home-furnishings industry. According to Rian Fried, an investment manager and newsletter editor, although the company uses recycled materials that it buys cheaply to make its products, the company's profit margins depend on the markets for the raw materials it sells to the producers of carpets, bottles, and other products. Recently the stock was $20, or about 12 times expected calendar 1993 earnings of $1.65, a price that Fried considers a strong reason to buy.<p>As environmentalists continue to battle cutting in old-growth forests, the price of wood pulp used in papermaking is expected to rise. <a name="NYSE:MTX"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12333"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Minerals Technologies Inc.</b></a> (MTX) has developed an alternative, precipitated calcium carbonate (the major ingredient in limestone and chalk), which is much cheaper than wood pulp. In addition, the process solves another environmental problem of papermaking--it's already white, so the paper doesn't need to be bleached, a practice under fire from environmentalists. The company's proprietary product allows it to dominate its market, according to Lazard Freres analyst James Winchester. "The company has been a fantastic performer; it's very well run and not leveraged at all." At its recent price of $28, the stock was trading at nearly 23 times projected 1993 earnings per share. Earnings growth is pegged at 20 percent a year.--M.D.<p>
Marie D'Amico writes about environmental issues and personal finance.
 <p>
KEYWORDS: Mutual Funds Investing, Stock Investing Strategies

