<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 93/10-Why Buy Now?</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b> </b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>93/10-Why Buy Now?</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 
Stocks that should be in your portfolio--even if you have to buy them<p>By Derrick C. Niederman<p>Despite the myriad investment articles that are published every day, one problem that affects almost every common- stock investor on the planet has gotten virtually no attention: Many first-rate stocks go unbought indefinitely--possibly for an investor's entire lifetime--simply because there was no specific moment that seemed like the right time to buy.<p>Stock recommendations that say "buy now" are surely the most compelling. The phrase appeals to our competitive instincts-- after all, buying now may mean getting there ahead of the other guy. That's also consistent with our understanding that business conditions can change quite rapidly, as can the stock market itself.<p>In the last year or so, we have heard recommendations such as "Buy <a name="NYSE:C"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10334"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Chrysler</b></a>; the economy is recovering," or "Buy Mylan Labs; it's a Clinton stock." Or even "Buy Sallie Mae; the student-loan system may not be as ill-fated as is commonly believed." Each of these recommendations is rooted in the present. There's certainly nothing wrong with that--and there are hundreds of other ideas where these came from.<p>But even this long list has some glaring omissions. For example, would an investor who inherited a portfolio today be upset if <a name="NYSE:MCD"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10974"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>McDonald's</b></a> was in it? Of course not. But change the question just a little bit. Would the same investor go out and buy McDonald's today? Probably not--simply because there is no specific reason to buy that hasn't been around for years. And, in an ironic way, buying today is an admission that it was a mistake to not buy it before. <p>Note that in the case of McDonald's, I could have said exactly the same thing if this article had been written in 1988, because even then there was no immediately compelling reason to buy. Some analysts might argue they saw the promise of the company's burgeoning international operations, but these factors existed before 1988. At the time, McDonald's was trading at $22 per share. Today it's above $50. And the international argument still applies.<p>Where will McDonald's stock be five years from now? I can't say precisely, but it's an excellent bet that it will be higher than it is today; that's what steady earnings growth will do. Yet companies with results this consistent--and whose names are well-known --are often not the sort of companies that leap up on any given day to tell you that your portfolio can't live without them.<p>Included on this list would be companies such as <a name="NYSE:TOY"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11495"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Toys "R" Us</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:DIS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11603"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Disney</b></a>, Fannie Mae, and other industry leaders. These stocks are not underfollowed, nor are they underrecognized, but they are worth owning. I could come up with reasons why they could be considered particularly attractive now--Disney's share price has recently been depressed by continued disappointments from its Euro Disney subsidiary; Toys "R" Us now trades at a smaller than normal premium to the S&P 500, the result of a few months of only moderate same-store sales increases. But for stocks like these, investors shouldn't require reasons of this type, because they aren't as important as these companies' fundamental strengths.<p>Ironically, the proliferation of financial information in the last several years has played a role in steering supposed long-term investors away from such holdings. Part of the "problem" is that to be a long-term investor is to be responsible. No short-term thrill seeking. Yet being responsible surely means acting on the latest possible information. How can you invest on the basis of information that could be several weeks old?<p>Perhaps the extra financial information we get these days is the "too much" part of the proverbial good thing. If the whole world truly did change every two weeks, there would be no such thing as long-term investing. What the stocks above have in common, of course, is that they have been extremely successful long-term holdings, or put another way, the reasons for owning them have been true year after year, even at increasingly higher share prices. Yet by the very virtue of these long-term advantages, any demandfor the most exciting story of the moment will leave them out.<p>The paradox of the hunt for the right time to buy can be made worse by personal quirks. Many of us love bargains. We dismiss the above stocks--which don't tend to trade inexpensively--on the grounds that someday in the future, they'll run into a short-term problem, and we can buy them then, when they're a bargain.But what kind of strategy would reject a stock at $20 and then buy it at $40 because it has been at $50? And what if the short-term problem never comes? Again, the need for an immediate reason to buy can get in the way.<p>It should come as no surprise that similar difficulties arise on the sell side. If we are to sell a stock now, most investors like to know that now is the best time to sell. Sounds nice, but it's a bad start. <p>In 1990, I wrote a brief column suggesting investors sell <a name="NYSE:IBM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10796"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>IBM</b></a>, then trading for just over $100 per share. Given what's happened since, it will go down as one of the best sale recommendations I ever made, and certainly one I don't mind bragging about. But remember, IBM once traded at $175; my recommendation wasn't timely in the least.<p>Back then, it was difficult to foresee the magnitude of IBM's losses and the magnitude of the dividend cut, although both were certainly possibilities. What was more evident was that IBM had thousands of shareholders who were hoping (largely without foundation) that IBM would come back. No particular point seemed like the time to sell. From that backdrop, the most likely scenario was a multiyear southward pattern as more and more investors gave up the ship. And that's what happened. The climactic drop of the last year was stunning but, in a sense, gravy.<p>The psychology of selling a stock that has already declined parallels the buying side and is perhaps even easier to see: It's an admission that we were wrong when we didn't sell earlier. In these cases, our egos prefer that the stock return to its previous highs, enabling us to ignore the downturn altogether. But why should it? If the company's franchise has been damaged enough, the stock won't come back at all. The act of selling a past-peak stock is never psychologically rewarding, but do it anyway--there could be rewards down the road.<p>Today, that consideration applies to such companies as <a name="NASD:AAPL"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12644"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Apple Computer</b></a>, Borland International, a host of pharmaceutical companies, and even to IBM itself. A sale today guarantees doing so at the wrong time, because each of these stocks could have been sold for more had they been sold earlier. But the old rule applies: If you wouldn't buy it today, then perhaps you shouldn't hold it, either. What that really means is that a decision to do things in a nice timely way might just improve the performance of your portfolio.<p>Contributing editor Derrick C. Niederman is a mathematician turned securities analyst.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Stock Investing Strategies

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
