<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 93/10-Rx for Burned Investors</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b> </b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>93/10-Rx for Burned Investors</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 
Do-it-yourself arbitration can save investors a bundle in legal fees<p>By Katherine Vessenes<p>Linda Martin, a nuclear-medicine technologist living in Minneapolis, had mediocre success investing in Big Board stocks, so in 1985 she started buying penny stocks on margin. The first stock she bought went from $.50 to $3.75 in a few months, and she was hooked. "Although I didn't appreciate it at the time," she says, "it might as well have been roulette."<p>In 1989 Martin closed her account from a large regional brokerage house to work with stockbroker Gary Tjosvold at Schneider Securities in Phoenix, a firm dealing in many of the small-company stocks she wanted to buy.<p>One of those stocks was Westar, in which she bought a substantial holding. In October 1990 Martin wanted to increase her cash for some upcoming personal expenses and advised Tjosvold to sell some of her Westar stock and some bonds she owned. But when she got her monthly statement the day before Thanksgiving, she saw that Tjosvold had sold her bonds but had used the proceeds to purchase 52,000 more shares of Westar for her account.<p>Martin called Tjosvold for an explanation. He assured her it was a clerical error and she shouldn't worry. "Call me after the weekend," he said, "and we'll straighten everything out." She agreed to wait a few days because Schneider Securities had a history of getting her statements wrong. Although Tjosvold had always corrected the "errors" in the past, this time it seemed like more than a mistake, and she planned a major confrontation with him after the long weekend.<p>The day after Thanksgiving, Martin got a phone call from the firm, telling her that Tjosvold had died of a heart attack. She immediately contacted Tjosvold's supervisor, Dick Sheneman, who steadfastly denied that Tjosvold had made any unauthorized trades or had used her bond proceeds inappropriately. He claimed he could find no paperwork indicating she wanted to sell Westar at all.<p>Over the next month, she continued to request that Schneider rescind the trade and refund her $7,500 from the bond sale, plus cover her losses on her Westar stock that should have been sold:The company had gone bankrupt shortly after Tjosvold's death.<p>Sheneman offered Martin only $7,500. "At that point I started looking around for alternative solutions," she says. "I called the Minnesota attorney general and the National Association of Security Dealers." Based on the advice Martin got from the regulators, early in 1991 she filed a grievance with the NASD, the self-regulatory organization of brokerage firms.<p>But in September 1991, after months of investigation, the NASD found "insufficient evidence" to support any wrongdoing, offering no further explanation. Schneider Securities promptly reduced its settlement offer from $7,500 to $2,000.<p>"I was thoroughly discouraged," Martin remembers. "I called several law firms and learned they didn't take [contingency] cases for less than $100,000. With no lawyer to help me, I felt I was up a creek." Without a lawyer who would forgo a fee up-front in return for a percentage of what Martin would win (if anything), taking Schneider to court was out of the question: Even a simple securities case can run up $30,000 in pretrial fees and another $30,000 if it goes to court, way more than the $15,000 she was claiming.<p>One of the attorneys she talked to suggested arbitration, where disputes against brokers are heard in an informal setting by three arbitrators chosen locally by the NASD, but predicated on acceptance by both parties. For investors, arbitration has many advantages over a civil trial. Arbitrators aren't bound by the courtroom rules of evidence and procedure, so cases can move more quickly. What's more, brokers can't use many defenses, such as the statute of limitations or hearsay rules. And arbitration can be significantly less expensive than litigation.<p>Nevertheless, it's not unusual to spend $25,000 in legal fees to get through an arbitration hearing, and that was still not in Martin's price range. A solution was suggested by attorney Terry Fleming of Lindquist & Vennum: He would coach Martin to handle the case herself. Fleming specialized in cases involving investors and brokers and had assisted a number of clients through do-it-yourself arbitration.<p>Fleming helped in a number of ways. He told her how to organize her files to impress the arbitrators. Martin developed a loose-leaf notebook system for her exhibits her monthly account statements, trade confirmations, correspondence with Tjosvold, and a summary of gains and losses, all filed chronologically and color coded for easy reference. "Setting this up was a lot of work," Martin says, "but it really paid off."<p>Fleming also helped Martin distill her presentation into a short, simple, chronological account of what happened and a precise statement of what she wanted the panel to do to solve the problem. He even advised her on what to wear to the hearing (conservative but tasteful; it doesn't hurt to impress the panel with a touch of class) and how the panel would act; she would know everything to expect so as not to be surprised. On Fleming's advice, she filed a claim for $15,200 based on unauthorized trading, misrepresentation, and illegal use of her bond proceeds in her margin account. "Meeting with Fleming gave me increased confidence and a clearer focus," says Martin. His total bill: $400.<p>Walking into the hearing room on January 15, 1992, without a phalanx of attorneys was one of the worst moments of the entire process. At first, Martin was intimidated by the behavior of the Schneider Securities representative and the three arbitrators, all men, who chatted amiably among themselves, virtually ignoring her. She waited quietly for five minutes past the appointed time and then took charge, asking for the hearing to begin. When they readily agreed, Martin began presenting her case. Six hours later she finished.<p>The Schneider representative, in contrast, was ill-prepared and spent less than 30 minutes presenting his side, relying chiefly on the favorable decision by the NASD grievance investigators. He tried to discredit Martin by producing internal memos in which Schneider personnel had called her a "flake" and "off the wall." "They were overconfident since they had won the initial round with the NASD grievance process," Martin explains, "so Schneider didn't prepare, and it showed."<p>Justice came in the mail on April 3, 1992. The arbitrators found in Martin's favor and ordered Schneider to pay her $7,300 without explaining their decision or how they arrived at the amount. This result is close to recent NASD statistics that show clients in arbitration win 60 percent of the time and on average are awarded 61 percent of the amount they claim.<p>Even though the process was long and at times humiliating, and in the end she received only what she was originally offered, Martin is satisfied. She is still investing, but more conservatively, and she has gone back to her former broker at the established firm.<p>-----<p>IT'S CHEAPER TO SETTLE:<p>It's not unusual for trusting investors to naively follow a broker's advice without understanding the risks or sales charges. Don't despair. There are a number of effective actions that don't involve litigation: <p>Step 1: Get a strategy. Losing money by itself is not a basis for a complaint. The most common complaints used against brokers are failure to disclose risks or sales charges and recommendation of an unsuitable investment. Claims against brokerage firms almost always allege failure to supervise the firm's brokers.  <p>Step 2: Set the objective. Some clients want their investment returned; others want interest too; some just want an apology. <p>Step 3: Contact the broker. Call him and explain the problem. Then listen to what he has to say. If that isn't satisfactory, tell him clearly what would be. Then send the broker a letter summarizing the call and the desired solution, giving a deadline for a response. <p>Step 4: Contact the firm. Some firms are so concerned about their reputations that they'll go to extremes to keep a client satisfied. Most reasonable firms would rather settle with an investor than incur the costs of litigation.<p>Step 5: File a grievance. Complaints to the NASD and state departments of securities can terrify a broker since these agencies have the power to fine, suspend licenses, or even put them out of business. It's an effective and inexpensive way to get relief. <p>Step 6: Arbitrate or litigate. Litigation requires competent securities counsel, but arbitrating yourself can be a cost-effective way to reach a satisfactory settlement.<p>Katherine Vessenes is a certified financial planner and attorney with the St. Paul law firm Chandler and Mason. She speaks nationally on investor issues and ethics in financial planning.<p> <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Stock Investing Stratgeies, Ethical Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
