	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 93/09-How to Create a Bear-Proof Portfolio</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>93/09-How to Create a Bear-Proof Portfolio</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						September 1993 <p>Worth magazine/Features  <p> HOW TO CREATE A BEAR-PROOF PORTFOLIO <p>(and still make money)  <p> Anybody can outsmart a bear market: Just move into cash. Butwhat if the market goes up? Here's how to play it safe withoutlosing the upside.  <p> by Stuart Weiss  <p> Monday, October 19, 1987 was the beginning of the end of a lotof careers on Wall Street, including mine. I started the morningin a hotel room in San Francisco, preparing to visit severalBay Area companies that looked like interesting investments.As I was getting dressed, the debacle in New York was underway. <p> Surprisingly학ut, as things turned out, appropriately핪he panicin New York did not infect the companies I was going to see.No one canceled on me. The investor-relations folks were calm,brushing aside the mayhem to discuss their businesses. At Clorox,the company rep talked about cleansers and the competition, thoughhe did pause every so often to look at his Quotron machine. <p> When I got back to New York, the chaos on Wall Street had begun.Equity research analysts at my firm were fired one by one overthe next few years. (I lasted until 1989.) The crash destroyedthe Wall Street job market, killed the New York City real estatemarket, and generated gobs of introspective articles in Barron'sand the Wall Street Journal. But for investors who stayed calm,Black Monday was simply a one-day bear market. True, some stockslost half their value that day. But most came back by the endof the year. As a group, stocks were up slightly for 1987.  <p> Today a lot of people are nervous about the stock market's highvalues, rising interest rates, and the effect of higher taxeson the economy. If there were another crash하nd a crash is lesslikely now than in 1987 because of additional trading safeguardsinstalled by the exchanges핪he best advice would be: Don't panic.In fact, savvy investors would probably snap up the bargainsthe next day, just as they did in 1987.   <p> A more troubling concern is whether investors can insulate theirportfolios against a far worse calamity하 prolonged bear market,the likes of which we haven't seen in 20 years. Sure, there havebeen some bad stretches since then: the months leading up tothe Gulf War and the mini-crash of October 1989, to name two.But there hasn't been a grinding bear since 1973. In that downturnthe market lost half its value in two years, and recovery tookanother eight years.   <p> Like 1987, the years 1973 and 1974 were not good ones to beworking on Wall Street. But unlike 1987, they were disastrousfor investors. On January 11, 1973, the Dow Jones IndustrialAverage reached a new all-time high of 1052. By December 6, 1974,thanks to the first OPEC oil shock, Watergate, inflation, anda recession, it had sunk to 578.   <p> What equities got clobbered the hardest in the '70s? Growthstocks. The so-called Nifty Fifty stocks, which were bid up toinsane multiples of earnings. "You had guns and butter from Vietnam,inflation getting out of control, and a gross overvaluation ofgrowth stocks핪he reverse of today," recalls Graham Tanaka, presidentof Tanaka Capital Management in New York, who was employed atMorgan Guaranty at the time. "Morgan was a major proponent ofthe Nifty Fifty. They helped create it. You had companies sellingat three or four times the market multiple. And then the NiftyFifty unraveled."   <p> Stocks such as Polaroid, whose price-to-earnings ratio approached100 in 1972, plunged from $150 to $15. By the end of the 1970s,Polaroid managed to reach $30, a pale image of its former self.Honeywell fell from $140 to $21; by the end of 1974 the companywas selling at just four times earnings. Disney stock tradedin Fantasyland before the bear market할ts stock pushed up to$122. Two years later the stock was mired in the low $20s, andit didn't recover until 1987. General Motors, which previouslypeaked at $115, plummeted to $45하nd never really recovered.It was a time when stocks on average sold for seven times earnings,the Dow languished below 1050, and many cheap stocks got a lotcheaper.  <p> Today's economy is completely different from that of the mid-1970s.There is no oil crisis, no double-digit inflation, no Vietnam.But there is a bulging mutual fund industry full of customerswho will bolt at the first hint of trouble. There is an averageprice-to-earnings multiple that's triple what it was in 1974.There is a huge budget deficit. And there's the specter of highertaxes. "Excessively high tax increases would choke the economy,"warns Tanaka. Adds a broker who lost his shirt in 1973, "Everybodyalways thinks that this is the bull market that won't ever end,but it always does."  <p> In 1993 there's no Nifty Fifty, but the current market has plentyof excesses of its own: biotechnology stocks that sell at $50when there are no earnings하nd sometimes not even any revenues.Hot software stocks selling at 40 times earnings. Multimedia,CD-ROM, telecommunications, local-area networks, wide-area networks.Five hundred channels and nothing on.  <p> If the great bear market of 1973 taught us anything, it's thata bear market can appear with no warning. And once investorsfind themselves in one, it's tough to make adjustments. That'seven more true today because of the speed of information: It'svery hard to realize that something is happening before everyoneelse has realized it, too.   <p> All of this means that investors who believe that a bear marketis looming (and that should be just about everyone) need to takesteps now. What to do? The old bear gave us a few hints. Forone thing, lighten up on the current hot stocks, those that aretrading at tremendous premiums to the market. If the Dow JonesIndustrials are selling at 20 times earnings today, a stock at50 times earnings should raise a red flag.   <p> Instead, buy stocks that have low price-to-earnings and price-to-bookratios (available from any stock reporting service, includingStandard & Poor's and Value Line). "Almost everything I own isgoing to go down less than the market as a whole," says ScottBlack, president of Delphi Management, "because we've got stockswith low P/E's and low book values." How low is low? The market'scurrent price-to-earnings ratio is about 20 times 1993 earningsand its price-to-book ratio is about three. So look for saferstocks with price-to-earnings ratios below 15 and price undertwo times book.   <p> For many investors, this creates an opportunity to sell stocksthat have run up fast and use the money to buy stocks that haven't핦rbetter yet, to buy stocks that have already had their own littlebear market. "The first thing investors should do is take profitson stocks that have done well for them," says Steven Carvell,a professor of finance at Cornell University. Because the marketas a whole, as measured by the Dow, hasn't moved much since mid-1992,investors should look for sales among stocks that have risenmore than a third in the past year.   <p> But resist the temptation to sell the entire portfolio in afree fall하 few stocks may never come back, but most of themwill. "Investing is far less an intellectual exercise than itis an exercise in guts," says David Hunter of Hunter Associatesin Pittsburgh.  <p> That means this is no time to be buying stocks on margin (borrowingfrom a brokerage house to buy more stock, usually to a maximumof 50 percent of a portfolio's value). A lot of people were wipedout in 1974 when the stocks they bought on margin dropped invalue and the erosion in the collateral value of the stocks forcedthem to sell at the bottom of the market.   <p> Investors should also be wary about the company they keep. Stocksheld by a lot of institutions, which are notoriously quick tobail out in bad weather, can be more volatile than those heldby wealthy families or even individuals. "Often the upside gainis not worth the downside risk for money managers," says Carvell."If they make good money, they'll get a pat on the back. Butif they lose money when nobody else did, they're gone." Hereutilities offer an advantage, because of their proportionatelyhigh ownership by long-term investors. To check out other stockowners, refer to S&P's research reports or call company investor-relationspeople.  <p> The balance sheet provides additional clues about which stocksstand the best chance of surviving the next bear. Steady andconsistent earnings, revenues, and cash flow are especially important.Particularly in times of trouble, the market tends to view companieswith steady growth far more favorably than those with erratichistories, even if they've been profitable. On the other sideof the balance sheet, a lot of debt is even more troublesomein a bear market as interest rates rise and business conditionsworsen. Investors should worry about companies with a lot ofmerger-related or leftover leveraged-buyout debt, such as RJRNabisco, Safeway, and Time Warner. And stocks that get additionalprice support from high dividends score big points with a nervousmarket. Dividends above 3 percent are a nice bonus, consideringthat savings accounts and money market funds pay 2 percent. That'sanother reason to look favorably on utility stocks; they generallypay 4 to 5 percent.  <p> A company's industry or product can also make an important differencein how it is perceived on Wall Street. Is the company's stapleproduct a big-ticket item or is it a small portion of a householdbudget? Is it necessary or discretionary? A bear market usuallymeans a recession is on the way or already here, so low-pricedand necessary items are better. That's why utilities hold upso well핥o matter how bad things get, people want that A/C ona July day in New York City or Dallas. Drug companies, food companies,and discount retailers historically do well when times are tough.These days it looks like personal computers may be added to thatlist: We've become so chip-dependent that there seems to be amarket for new innovation regardless of what the economy is doing. <p> On the downside, investors will do well to cut back on holdingsin banks and brokerage houses. A bear market driven by higherinterest rates tends to hurt banks because the spread betweenthe rates they pay and what they lend shrinks. And stock brokerssuffer in a bear market as the demand dries up for lucrativenew issues of stock. Banks and brokers have ominously high earningsmultiples today; they've gone up a lot in the past year or twoas interest rates have come down and the Gulf War break in themarket recedes further into history. At the same time, inflation-hedgestocks such as gold and real estate tend to do very well in toughtimes.  <p> Finally, today's investors should lighten up on mutual fundsand boost their holdings of individual stocks. Why? Mutual fundsare bursting at the seams with novice investors who will wantto pull their money out at the first hint of trouble. (One exceptionis in the international arena, where funds offer geographicaldiversification. Plus, it's often tough to buy individual issuesin foreign countries.)  <p> Of course, it would be virtually impossible to find a stockthat fits all of these criteria. But investors still can constructa nearly bear-proof portfolio with the goal of staying investedbut losing less money in the event of a bear market. Here areten stocks, in alphabetical order, that could help accomplishthat. If there's another 1987-type correction, there'll be nowhereto hide"Everything's going to get blown apart," in the wordsof Scott Black, "especially the over-the-counter stocks." Butin a more-likely bear market these ten stocks should hold upbetter than the market as a whole. And, best of all, if there'sno downturn, investors will continue to do better in stocks thanjust about any place else.   <p>  <p>A former Wall Street analyst, Stuart Weiss has written for BusinessWeek and CFO.  <p>  <hr>  <p>Copyright 1993 Capital Publishing Limited Partnership. All rightsreserved. <p>
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
