	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 93/09-Stocks at the Crossroads</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>

				<img src="">	
				<p>
				<font size=5><b>Stocks at the Crossroads</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>93/09-Stocks at the Crossroads</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						September 1993 
<p>
Worth magazine/Advisor  
<p>
 STOCKS AT THE CROSSROADS 
<p>
With interest rates bottoming, mortgage stocks are in a period
of transition. It's time to look for opportunities.  
<p>
 By Derrick Niederman  
<p>
 One of the basic tenets of investing is that a stock should
be sold if the original reasons for owning it are no longer valid.
But what happens when new reasons to own are right around the
corner?  
<p>
 That's what's happening today for investors in mortgage banking
stocks. Some of the forces that have made these stocks such outstanding
investments over the past few years are surely receding. Yet
for those with the courage to weather the turbulence of transition,
some of these stocks have tantalizing silver linings.  
<p>
 It's no secret that long-term interest rates have been declining
for several years. Lower rates on long-term Treasuries have translated
into lower mortgage rates, prompting the largest wave of refinancings
in history and creating a bonanza for the mortgage banking industry.<p>
<p>
 Savings and loans didn't reap anywhere near the windfall that
mortgage banks did. Whereas S&Ls both originate mortgages and
hold at least some of those mortgages in their own portfolios,
a mortgage bank typically sells the mortgages it originates to
one of the government agencies Fannie Mae, Freddie Mac, Ginnie
Mae. But the mortgage bank retains servicing rights on the sold
mortgages, sending out monthly statements, collecting payments,
and the like.   
<p>
 In the 1980s, as the S&Ls foundered and the mortgage-backed
securities business of Fannie Mae, Freddie Mac, and Ginnie Mae
boomed, the mortgage bankers' share of the mortgage origination
market vaulted from 20 percent to almost 50 percent. This tremendous
growth in market share has continued as rates have gone down
in the last couple of years; competing savings and loans have
concentrated on adjustable-rate mortgages to insulate themselves
from interest-rate swings, and these have become less popular
as fixed rates have reached record lows. Today mortgage banks
account for more than 60 percent of all new loans.  
<p>
 Perhaps the greatest beneficiary of these gains has been Countrywide
Credit, the nation's largest independent mortgage banking company.
In fiscal 1991 the company originated $4.6 billion worth of mortgages.
In 1992 that figure jumped to $12.2 billion. And in fiscal year
1993 (Countrywide's fiscal year ended on February 28) it hit
$32.4 billion. During this time earnings quadrupled, and Countrywide
stock moved from $5 to its current level of about $27 per share.<p>
<p>
 Today, however, the stock market appears worried about lenders
in general and Countrywide in particular, and not without reason.
Long-term rates can't come down indefinitely. More than 85 percent
of Countrywide's earnings are derived from the writing of new
loans, and 75 percent of that comes from refinancings. These
levels look dangerous. Anyone who bought the stock because of
the refinancing boom has plenty of reason to bail out now.  
<p>
 By all accounts, many investors have done just that긊he stock
now trades at just nine times earnings, cheap by any standard.
In the words of the redoubtable Jonathan Gray, financial services
analyst at Sanford C. Bernstein, "Countrywide's stock price seems
to have inherited the S&Ls' historic role as the ballot box into
which interest-rate votes are cast."  
<p>
 Here's where the opportunity lies. Countrywide isn't nearly
as vulnerable to higher interest rates as conventional wisdom
would have it, and the same goes for competitors such as Margaretten
Financial and North American Mortgage. It may be hard to believe,
but even if interest rates flatten out or go up slightly그nd
refinancing volume therefore dries up considerably근arnings at
these mortgage banks still have the potential to go up.   
<p>
 The paradox is explained by a couple of accounting wrinkles.
The first wrinkle is the loan servicing business. Although refinancing
has been a bonanza for the origination side of the business,
it also reduces the number of old loans being serviced. (The
mortgages that are being repaid have to come from somewhere.)<p>
<p>
 This "runoff" for Countrywide in 1992 was about 30 percent of
its portfolio, well above the 10 percent figure that a normal
year might bring. Not only does that cost the company servicing
revenues, but the run-off also reduces earnings. As with most
companies, Countrywide spreads the costs of acquiring a loan
over the life of the loan; but if those loans are refinanced,
these charges are accelerated and subtracted from current earnings.
Although this risk can be partially hedged, it can produce charges
against earnings that are far bigger than the servicing earnings
themselves.  
<p>
 When refinancings are down, however, these charges are reduced,
and servicing margins then go up. Best of all, servicing all
those new loans can produce a large, reliable income stream as
long as the volume of refinancings stays low. Even if rates completely
flatten out, earnings could move from $2.28 in 1992 to more than
$3.00 in 1993, and could continue to grow at a 10 percent-plus
pace for years to come.   
<p>
 Think of it this way: When a basketball team averaging 100 points
per game loses a player averaging 30 points per game, the team
doesn't then go out and score 70 points. Sometimes other factors
can more than make up the difference그nd that is where Countrywide
stands today.  
<p>
 The other accounting wrinkle is quite different, and so are
its potential beneficiaries. To understand this one, consider
the differences between Countrywide and Margaretten Financial.<p>
<p>
 Countrywide is the industry's low-cost producer, with origination
costs running about 1.5 percent of the amount of the mortgages;
Margaretten, though not the highest-cost producer, has origination
costs almost a full percentage point higher. In a world where
margins are everything, that's a huge difference.  
<p>
 In addition, a big percentage of Margaretten's earnings (90
percent in 1992) comes from the sale of mortgage servicing rights.
Countrywide, by contrast, simply doesn't sell servicing rights.<p>
<p>
 But that doesn't make Margaretten a bad investment; there is
one difference that could work in its favor. Only 14 percent
of Countrywide's new mortgages are generated through its retail
operations (that is, writing mortgages directly to homeowners);
the rest come primarily from mortgage brokers. Margaretten, on
the other hand, produces 77 percent of its mortgage originations
through its retail operations, by far the highest such figure
for any mortgage banker.  
<p>
 This isn't an inherent advantage글n fact, it contributes to
the high cost of originations극ut it could become an advantage
if the Financial Accounting Services Board (FASB) ever decides
to level the playing field for mortgage servicing rights. Under
current regulations, the cost of originating servicing rights
is an expense that must be accounted for at the time of the transaction;
by contrast, the cost of purchased servicing rights can be spread
over a ten-year period. This dramatically understates the earnings
of Margaretten (as well as those of North American Mortgage).<p>
<p>
 If originations and purchases were accorded the same accounting
treatment, earnings at both Margaretten and North American would
more than double. Even if the FASB doesn't act, the fact remains
that actual cash earnings are being understated, which is reason
enough for these companies to buy back stock or for some outside
party to take a keen interest in them.  
<p>
 Are there risks in owning mortgage banking stocks? Of course.
One possibility is a price war on the origination side, which
could happen if vast amounts of mortgage money become available
and go chasing after a smaller pie. And the low valuations are
by themselves no consolation. If the mortgage business ever did
enter such a shakeout period, price-to-earnings ratios would
go up only because earnings had gone down. Fortunately, there
aren't any signs of such a price war starting.  
<p>
 A more realistic concern for investors is the wait for the transition
from refinancing to servicing. Servicing could become the dominant
force, but that doesn't mean the market is ready for it yet.
At this point, it appears that Wall Street is, quite reasonably,
taking a "show me" attitude toward mortgage bankers and their
ability to thrive in a flat-rate scenario. That's a standard
market response for times like these. But when rates do eventually
flatten out그nd when the earnings reports produce gains anyway긊he
stocks should move appreciably higher, rewarding those who invested
during this tricky transition period.  
<p><p>
<p>
Contributing editor Derrick Niederman is a mathematician turned
securities analyst.  
<p>
  <hr>  
