<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 93/08-When Brokers Turn Bankers</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b> </b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>93/08-When Brokers Turn Bankers</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 <p>By Andrew Feinberg<p>Pssst, want a loan that's cheap (rates as low as 4.5%), a cinch to get, and often tax-deductible? That doesn't use the house as collateral? How about a margin loan? <p>Seriously.<p>Hundreds of thousands of investors who have never considered margin loans could benefit by reexamining their prejudice against this type of financing. Margin loans can be marvelously convenient and efficient, and they're often a smart alternative__or supplement__to home-equity debt. They may be especially appealing for short-term borrowing needs, such as paying taxes or an emergency. <p>But why borrow against a securities portfolio at all? Why not simply sell assets now and restock the larder later? For at least three reasons. A sell-and-replenish strategy may subject investors to capital gains taxes (in theory, those stocks were bought low and are now selling high). It'll cost more in commissions (for another buy-and-sell ticket). And then there's the opportunity cost if the assets rise sharply after they are sold.<p>Of course, those assets might go into a cataclysmic tailspin, causing a strong desire to shoot the person__in this case, me__who ever told you about the virtues of margin indebtedness. <p>So let's pause here for some words about the mayhem margin can cause and further warn you that margin borrowing generally seems cheapest and most prudent during a bull market. <p>Margin debt can cause major, and potentially irrevocable, damage to psyche and portfolio if not used properly. Ask a market pro about margin and he'll invariably tell at least one stomach-churning tale about leverage's dark and wretched downside. Surprisingly often, the story will be about the market pro himself.<p>Or herself. "Thirty years ago I ran $500 into half a million on margin," says Muriel Siebert, president of Muriel Siebert & Co., a discount brokerage. "Soon afterwards, the half a million turned into $20,000. I said I would never let that happen to me again."<p>And she hasn't. But Siebert__as a creditor__knows firsthand how badly the Crash of '87 bloodied some of her highly margined customers. "We still have liens against people's homes because of '87," she says. <p>The best way for investors to benefit from margin borrowing is to view it as a cheap credit alternative rather than a speculative weapon.<p>Essentially, there are two ways to borrow on margin. Investors can buy on margin__putting up as little as $50 to purchase $100 worth of stock__or can borrow against the assets already in their portfolio.<p>In either case, investors can borrow up to 50% of the value of eligible stocks, mutual funds, and convertible bonds; up to 85% of the value of municipal bonds; and up to 95% of the value of Treasury securities. But the fact that they can doesn't mean they should. Margin makes the most sense when much less leverage is used; borrowing, say, 3%, 5%, 10%, or maybe 15% of the value of a balanced portfolio. (No, balanced doesn't mean owning eight biotech stocks.) Borrowing this way will prevent a margin call, even in a crash.<p>What does the privilege cost? Discount brokers offer discount loan rates__for as low as 4.5% on loans of more than $100,000 from some deep discounters. Other brokers will charge from 5.75% to 8.5%. Typically, investors can get cash instantly, and without a fee by means of a credit card, debit card, or check. (If used to buy securities, the interest on a margin loan is usually deductible against investment income. Investment deductions can be carried forward indefinitely.) <p>"I think people should certainly use margin to refinance higher-interest debt, especially credit-card debt," says Mark Griege, a partner with Robertson, Griege & Thoele, a financial advisory firm in Dallas. "The taboo against using margin__the sense that all margin is bad__is almost an old wives' tale. Margin is an important tool in our toolbox."<p>When might it make sense to reach for this particular tool? <p>* For a short-term bridge loan.<p>* To make a down payment on a home (particularly if it's an extraordinary deal).<p>* To meet an immediate one-time expense that can soon be paid off.<p>* To avoid selling a security prematurely.<p>* To defer taxes on the sale of an investment into the following year.<p>Margin borrowing has been growing as the bull market rumbles along. In February, margin debt hit $44.3 billion, finally eclipsing the previous record, which (what a surprise) was set right before the '87 Crash. Yet there are no hard numbers to prove that conservative use of margin is growing. <p>In recent years, some brokers, most notably <a name="NYSE:MER"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10990"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Merrill Lynch</b></a>, have been pushing margin debt as a credit-management tool (Merrill's margin brochure doesn't even mention the notion of increased leverage until page five.) Merrill is trying hard to rehabilitate the image of margin accounts, partly by toying with the language. Investors don't open a "margin" account at Merrill. They get an Investor CreditLine. And don't worry; no matter what calamities befall a portfolio, they can't possibly trigger a "margin" call. It's now a maintenance call instead. <p>"We're trying to tell our clients that they can do a far better job of managing credit," says Charles A. Humm, senior vice president at Merrill Lynch Credit Corp.<p>Brokers, though, are frustrated that more consumers haven't used margin loans to get rid of other debt that may be 10 or 12 percentage points more expensive. Why is this such a tough sell? Fear and lack of familiarity are two reasons, but there are others. <p>"When people think of loans, they think of banks, not brokers," says John J. DeMarco, a senior vice president at PSI, a Tampa-based financial-services research and consulting firm that regularly surveys affluent households' attitudes toward margin. "Forty percent of the most affluent households carry credit-card debt, but only 6% have margin accounts."<p>Paradoxically, consumers say that paying higher interest rates on their debts makes them feel richer rather than poorer. "Customers like to keep their borrowing separate from their investing, and they feel they're earning more if they don't have a debit balance against their investment accounts," says David Diefenbach, vice president of investor lending services at Prudential Securities. "It's a completely perceptual thing."<p>Although margin borrowing can sharply reduce annual debt-service costs, one potential pitfall of using margin is that the new debit simply accumulates, so there's a temptation never to pay it off. "Before borrowing on margin, investors should have a plan for paying off the debt," advises William G. Brennan, head of the personal financial counseling group at Ernst & Young's Washington, D.C., office.<p>Despite such appeals, margin borrowing sometimes works better in theory than in practice. So says another broker at a major wire house, a man who temporarily left the securities business after seeing the 1973-74 bear market maul his margin clients. "I'm not against using a little margin to buy a blue chip," he says, "but my experience is that people generally use margin to buy garbage. And even if they buy something good, they really start to worry if the stock drops 10%. Because if they're on 50% margin, that's really a 20% drop__and 20% is a magic number that causes some people to go crazy. Buying on margin accentuates the pressure on decision-making." <p>And that can't be a good thing from either a mental-health or an investment perspective. One way to deal with the anxiety is to use margin borrowing only as a short-term, cash-management strategy.<p>Investors, though, can start off using margin intelligently and conservatively and eventually become addicted. "I've seen people start small and then the next thing they know they're leveraged to the hilt," says Jim Rogers, a professional investor and co-host of CNBC's "Your Portfolio." "And then they're wiped out. Investors have to be very, very sure that they know what they're doing."<p>With the market near its all-time high, any investor who uses margin should be very careful. Leverage is the ultimate double-edged sword.<p>Andrew Feinberg, a contributing editor to Worth, is the author of Downsize Your Debt: How to Take Control of Your Personal Finances (Penguin).<p>-----<p>FEAR OF MARGIN CALL<p>Let's address the dread directly: What can I lose? If a Merrill Lynch client buys 100 shares of a $60 stock for $3,000 (that is, on 50% margin), he'll get a margin call if the stock falls to $4278, which represents a 29% decline. In the event of such unpleasantness, he either has to sell some of the stock or put up additional cash or securities as collateral. Use 30% margin, however, and he won't get a margin call until the stock hits $2534, having dropped 57%. Put up 90% cash and use only 10% margin, and the call won't come until the stock hits $9, after a free-fall of 85%. <p> <p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Bond Investing, Investing Strategies, Stock Investing, Stock Market Trends

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

