<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/06-Let's Fix the Flat Tax</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/06-Let's Fix the Flat Tax</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						It has problems, and the politicians have moved on. But the flat tax makes sense. Let's make it work.<p>By Elizabeth Macdonald<p>In march, while waiting to testify before Congress about tax reform, I watched as a panel of experts discussed the federal tax system's problems. Four gold-leaf eagles loomed silently over the House Ways and Means Committee hearing room. Rachel Wildavsky, senior staff editor of Reader's Digest, took the microphone to tell Chairman Bill Archer and his colleagues about a nationwide poll conducted by her magazine. I sat up to listen.<p>The poll asked 1,015 taxpayers for their opinions about the fairness of the current tax system. The most compelling finding: Americans from all income levels and nationalities resoundingly agree that the maximum tax rate for a family of four with $200,000 in income should be 25 percent. "If you asked whether the ocean was wet, you'd probably find this kind of unanimity," she told the committee.<p>Wildavsky also reported the less surprising news that most Americans believe not only that they are overtaxed but that their neighbors--both rich and poor--are overtaxed, too. She concluded that the poll found no support for the myth that many middle- and working-class Americans believe rich people are not paying their fair share. Wildavsky then sat back in her chair. There was a pause.<p>Representative Sam Gibbons blinked his swollen eyes, cleared his throat, and harrumphed, "The needs of government are greater than 25 percent of the American citizens' income." Next, Representative Charles Rangel piped up to ask Wildavsky, "What annoys taxpayers most about their taxes?"<p>"High rates," she replied.<p>"That's never going to change," declared Rangel.<p>There. They said it. It was a moment of shocking candor, breathtaking stupidity, or both. The members of the most powerful congressional committee had just revealed their true cynicism (and a reason for term limits) about the tax dollars they collect from citizens like you and me.<p>I was a little surprised at how angry I felt as I left the hearing room later that day. When I got back to my desk in Manhattan, I did more research and talked with tax experts across the country about the best ideas to fix the tax system. The outcome: Although I'm still skeptical about some of its tenets, I'm now a believer in the concept of a flat tax.<p>I'm convinced that Congress has become too adept at obscuring its every costly move in a fog of multiple tax rates and a spiraling budget deficit. The complexities of the tax system make it hard for us to know not only exactly when our taxes are going up or down--but whose fault it is. The cruelest trick of the current system is that many people end up blaming their steep tax bills on themselves. For example: "If I had just planned my finances better, I could have taken a few more deductions."<p>Along with making ample cuts in unnecessary spending, Congress should seriously consider a tax system with one flat rate--or one of several compelling new proposals (based on the principles of a flat tax) that would at least reduce rates and curtail deductions.<p>Yes, I did write last October about the problems associated with a flat tax: namely, the elimination of certain deductions and the possible loss of employer-provided health benefits. Yes, I did poke fun at the flat tax proposed by Representative Dick Armey and Senator Richard Shelby for proclaiming to kill all deductions when, in fact, it would allow a 100 percent write-off for business-entertainment costs.<p>These negatives, however, don't outweigh the positives of converting the federal income-tax system to a flat tax.<p>The current tax system is unfair and polluted with unnecessary complexity. It costs taxpayers tens of billions of dollars just to comply with its arcane rules and regulations. It costs the economy tens of billions of dollars in wasteful investments. It fosters an environment in which more than four million people don't file tax returns each year, including 26,883 federal workers (956 of whom work for the Treasury, according to the weekly Tax Notes). Thanks to artificial subsidies, it makes housing and health care more expensive than necessary.<p>This country needs a saner, simpler, cheaper, and, most of all, fairer tax system. The Kemp Commission stated the principle of fairness in this way: If a taxpayer earns ten times as much as his or her neighbor in taxable income above a personal exemption, he or she should pay ten times as much in taxes. Not 20 times as much, as he or she does (give or take the input of a good accountant)  with multiple tax rates.<p>The single greatest benefit of the flat tax would be that everyone could easily anticipate how much they'd be expected to pay each year--including years in which Congress decided to raise or lower the overall rate. Of course, this is also the biggest reason politicians and other Washington insiders dislike the idea, regardless of what else they might say in public. With a flat tax in place, Congress could no longer raise taxes without Americans' understanding exactly and immediately how it would affect their family budgets.<p>The flat tax would also strip self-serving Washington insiders of much of their power to award favors. It's no coincidence that the chairmen of the two tax-writing committees, the Senate Finance and the House Ways and Means, are routinely among the leaders in attracting campaign contributions--and that their fellow committee members typically rake in above-average contributions as well.<p>The complexities of the current tax code are also part of the reason there are more lawyers in the D.C. bar (65,000) than in the New York City bar (45,000), even though the capital's population is a third smaller than New York. The tax-preparation industry is a $35 billion business that owes its very existence to the current system.<p>Merton H. Miller, a Nobel Prize winning professor emeritus of economics at the University of Chicago, noted recently that a flat tax "may well strike politicians as nutty because they would lose their main tool for handing out hidden subsidies--deductions, credits, and exemptions for favored constituents and special interests. And, of course, armies of tax lawyers and accountants would lose their jobs and be forced to enter productive employment."<p>Then there's the Internal Revenue Service--America's museum of mass confusion. The federal income tax chews up 6,439 pages of fine print covering some 336 feet of shelf space. Each year, the IRS churns out about eight billion pages of forms and instructions to about 114 million taxpayers--a paper load for which 293,760 trees pay the ultimate sacrifice.<p>Not surprisingly, the code leaves many a taxpayer in a swivet every spring. Individuals annually spend a collective 1.7 billion hours and more than 100 billion nondeductible dollars embroiled in tax-related paperwork. (Even Albert Einstein needed help with his income taxes.) The tax man is often stumped, too. A retired IRS agent from Michigan recently told the Kemp Commission: "When people who are employed to enforce the tax laws have difficulty understanding its complicated and sometimes incomprehensible provisions, it's time for a change."<p>Furthermore, the current system is a disaster when it comes to helping people save and invest. Say a family in the 28 percent tax bracket finds a way to earn an additional $1,000. They'll pay $280 in taxes on that amount. If they invest the $720 they have left over in a company's stock, their share of any profits will be reduced by federal taxes on corporate earnings (up to 35 percent). If the stock pays a dividend, the family has to pay tax on that at the 28 percent rate. If the stock rises in price, the family will pay the 28 percent capital-gains rate upon sale. If they hold the asset long enough, the government will eventually take its bite when it collects estate taxes (up to 55 percent).<p>Dale Jorgenson, a professor of economics at Harvard University, estimates that household income and wealth in the U.S. would be $1 trillion  higher than it is today without these multiple layers of taxation. That's an increase of about 13 percent, or $6,500 a year for typical middle-income American families.<p>At the moment, the only extant flat-tax proposal is the one sponsored in the House by Armey and in the Senate by Shelby. Their flat tax mirrors a plan introduced in 1981 by Robert E. Hall and Alvin Rabushka, senior fellows at the conservative Hoover Institution. The Armey version starts with a 20 percent tax rate but drops to 17 percent in the third year. (The Treasury Department says a 20.8 percent rate would be revenue neutral.) It doesn't tax estates, gifts, capital gains, interest income, dividends, or Social Security benefits. 
It also offers hefty standard deductions. At its 17 percent rate, these deductions amount to $11,350 for singles and $22,700 for married couples, with dependents at $5,300 each. Because of these fat deductions, not only would poor people not be hurt, as many have protested, but many would not have to pay any taxes.<p>Armey says his plan is progressive, too, because its low effective rate (total tax divided by total income) rises with income. A family of four with $50,000 in income would pay an effective tax rate of 5.7 percent; one earning $100,000, nearly 11.3 percent; and one pulling in $200,000, 14.2 percent.<p>Still, the ArmeyShelby plan is encountering stiff opposition for two reasons: It wipes out the deduction for the payment of home-mortgage interest, and it would allow a rich person living off interest and dividend income to escape paying a fair share of the cost of government services.<p>Adding any deductions to a flat-tax plan causes the rate at which revenue remains constant to increase. Still, they're worth considering, since the resulting rates are generally lower than what we face now. William Gale, an economist at the liberal Brookings Institution, says adding payroll-tax deductions to the flat tax would boost the base rate to 23.5 percent. Adding a mortgage-interest write-off on top of that would raise the rate to 24.8 percent. Adding a further deduction for charitable contributions would hike it up to 25.2 percent.<p>However, J. D. Foster and Art Hall, economists at the Tax Foundation, suggest a possible solution: a flat tax that offers a choice. Taxpayers could either take the personal exemption or choose the mortgage-interest and charitable deductions. This choice would produce effective tax rates along the lines of the ArmeyShelby proposal.<p>As for the second problem, Foster and Hall offer another solution: Levy the flat-tax rate on all personal capital acquired before the enactment of the tax, but provide a $1 million exemption and give taxpayers ten years to pay up. This onetime tax on only old--as opposed to new--capital (which amounts to $11.5 trillion after the million-dollar exemption) would actually enable government to set a revenue-neutral flat-tax rate as low as 16.2 percent. Although revenue from this old-capital tax would be exhausted after ten years, Foster says it's possible a flat tax could boost economic growth enough to make up the difference.<p>This flat tax would also give the middle class a sizable tax cut--a political necessity for enacting true tax reform.<p>Any transition to a new system is bound to cause problems--a lot of problems. It will unwind and undo every weird anomaly Congress has legislated into the economy--against the better judgment of a free market. It won't favor wealthy, middle-aged home owners over young adults who are just beginning their careers and can afford only to rent. It won't provide tax advantages to couples who decide against marriage or those who decide to divorce. It won't favor cheaters over honest folks. It won't discourage investing, hard work, or pursuing the American dream.<p>It will, however, require politicians to tell us exactly how much they plan to charge us for the cost of government. It will make it cheaper and easier for us to do our taxes. And it will make it less costly for the government to collect them. <p><p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Taxation, Government Adgency, Politics, Family Finance

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

