<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/05-Giving Families the Business</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Giving Families the Business</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/05-Giving Families the Business</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						May 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Personal Adviser  <p> GIVING FAMILIES THE BUSINESS <p>The estate-tax bill comes with more strings than an orchestra <p> By Elizabeth Macdonald  <p> The estate-tax bill introduced last July by Senator Bob Dole is still kicking around in Congress -- but is it a good thing? As it stands, the proposal would gradually increase the amount excluded from estate tax from $600,000 to $750,000. It would also give some relief to family-owned businesses, exempting the first $1 million in certain holdings and 50 percent of the next $1.5 million.   <p> So far, so good. But take a deep breath. To qualify, the value of a family-owned business must represent at least half the deceased's estate. No stock or debt of the company can have been publicly traded over the previous three years. The deceased must have materially participated in the business for at least five out of eight years before death. And each heir (or a member of his or her family) must materially participate in the business for five out of eight years within ten years after the death -- or the tax break would be lost retroactively.  <p>  <p>
KEYWORDS: Family Business, Government, Taxation, Estate Planning

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

