	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/04-Putting a Face on Fear</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Putting a Face on Fear</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/04-Putting a Face on Fear</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						April 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Features  <p> PUTTING ON A FACE OF FEAR <p>Behind the terrifying, all-powerful Internal Revenue Service are real live human beings. If you can't love them, respect them. It may help you survive an audit.   <p> By Elizabeth Macdonald  <p> As a faceless bureaucracy, the Internal Revenue Service knows no peers. No agent has risen to national prominence. no commissioner has garnered much public attention. Although Americans find the agency frightening and secretive, it has yet to capture the imagination of Stephen King or Tom Clancy. Buck Henry played an agent in the movie Grumpy Old Men, but big deal: Buck Henry is hardly Arnold Schwarzenegger or Harrison Ford. Nor do agents get clever monikers. They aren't G-men or T-men or spooks or narcs. Even the IRS accountant who nailed Al Capone is a virtual unknown. What's his name? Elmer Irey. But who cares!   <p> Deep down inside, we think that no single individual put away Capone. We think he was brought down by the whole kit and caboodle-- the IRS itself, in all its glory. So successful has the IRS been at convincing us of its utter anonymity that we quake before it, like some sort of bewildered Kafka character. Without stretching our imaginations much, we become this infernal machine's pitiful victims.  <p> A pretty picture, but incomplete. Yes, the IRS is indisputably powerful, and yes, taxpayers find it hard to extricate themselves once the IRS's gears begin to turn. But the agency is made up of thousands of agents and auditors -- more than 19,000 in all. And they probably have more individual power than any other government workers, with perhaps the exception of Supreme Court justices. They are cop, prosecutor, and judge all rolled into one. They gather facts, analyze them, and mete out punishments.  <p> Agents are instructed to make audits as crisply professional-- i.e., anonymous -- as possible. But as much as an agent may hope to make the audit seem like a bunch of numbers (the taxpayer) meeting a body of law and a computer (the agent/auditor), itis really one human being sitting down with another, a bunch of biases, points of view, and backgrounds coming together over a steel desk. (Agents know what people think of them: Whenever someone asks what she does for a living, Manhattan auditor Jacqueline Wright says, "I work with lawyers." Auditor Ed Carroscio says,"I tell people I work for the Treasury Department.")  <p> Agents can make you or break you; they can be nice or they can be mean. So save yourself some money: Get to know them. You'll find they are just like the rest of us. Some just want to get through the day. Others are looking for promotions. None wants to be messed with.  <p> Meet Etta Owens. She's a wry, somewhat world-weary agent of 48 who works out of a Manhattan IRS office. She began life in Birmingham, Alabama, in a big old house with her parents and six brothers and sisters. Her father made metal pipes at the local American Cast Iron Pipe Company until the 1950s, when he was almost killed in an explosion that left a train track of stitches across his forehead. Etta's mother ran a beauty shop over the garage.  <p> Growing up black in Birmingham during the 1950s and 1960s put Owens square in the center of the civil-rights movement. She lived under Jim Crow laws and found a hero in Martin Luther King Jr. "What he was saying was true," she says. "We couldn't get jobs, we saw what our parents were going through, we were tired of being poor, of being told where to sit, where to walk, where to drink교nd I thought, Enough is enough."  <p> On the morning of May 3, 1963, King's associates turned up at the doors of A. H. Parker High School, Owens's school. With the rest of her schoolmates, she went to the rally at the 16th Street Baptist Church. Then she marched downtown. She was there when police commissioner Bull Connor jumped into a white army tank, and she watched as his men turned water cannons, police dogs, and billy clubs on the marchers.   <p> She left Birmingham in l967, because, she says, "it was time. I had become a radical in attitude; I didn't believe in saying 'Yes, ma'am, No, sir' to white people day in and day out. They didn't show my parents the same respect. Then I was a little ornery, a little headstrong." Bowing to the wishes of her mother,she enrolled in college, Hudson County Community College in New Jersey, and graduated in 1972, a part of the first huge wave of black women to go to college. Her relatives in Birmingham, she says, "are proud of me now, considering that they thought I was radical."  <p> Today, Owens is divorced and lives with her 16-year-old daughter, Azur宓, whose photograph she keeps on her desk along with a sign that reads: a closed mouth catches no flies. She sings in a church choir on weekends and meets once a month for a hand of bid whist with her buddies, half of whom have had run-ins with the IRS. She says she never talks about her job because her friends consider the agency a "nuisance." Her Birmingham days are "a lifetime away," she says. "You'll see no hint of retribution from me. You grow, you get older. I've become shrewd, astute, thick-skinned. I've learned how to deal with people."  <p> As a practical matter, Owens has had no choice. In her 25-year career, she has audited about 10,000 returns, some in the office, some in the field. She started out auditing individuals; today, she goes after bigger fish -- businesses in the underground economy. She compares outside audits to "going into an abyss" and remembers one taxpayer who had strewed anatomically correct male dolls all over his apartment. "I thought that was in really poor taste," she says. <p>It was also just another lesson in human behavior. "Being an auditor makes you street-smart," she explains. "I know now exactly when a person is B.S.'ing me. I can pick up the stench of a dishonest taxpayer."  <p> Etta Owens is one of seven New York City examiners we interviewed to find out where agents come from, what they're like, and how they spend their days. In Manhattan, many auditors and agents are female and minorities. Nationally, 35 percent of all agents are female; 20 percent are minorities.  <p> All agents are required to have a minimum of three years of college study, appropriate business experience, or a combination of both. Auditors earn from $20,617 to $40,614; revenue agents such as Etta can make up to $70,032. (A number of the agents we talked to worry about job security, mostly because of the recent discussions of the flat tax and the downscaling of the IRS's latest budget requests.) <p>Every year, agents must attend several seminars on integrity. In New York City, employees go to either a conference room at headquarters or an auditorium at New York University. There they are dutifully told not to take bribes, not to snoop into taxpayers' returns (like those of a neighbor or a former girlfriend or boyfriend), and not to use their personal lives as a yardstick when auditing taxpayers. The first two are relatively easy to avoid. The third can be more difficult.  <p> Rosalee Chin-Young, 29, is a voluble, bright woman with a powerful memory, the fifth child of a family of ten who emigrated from Jamaica to the United States at the age of 16. Her mother, Joyce, is a nurse; her father, Watson Fook Chin-Young, is a barber. Rosalee came to the IRS in October 1990 with a degree in marketing from the State University of New York at New Paltz. "I always dreamed of being a doctor or a dancer," she says wistfully. "But I always liked business." After just two years as an auditor, she has already completed 3,000 examinations.  <p> Chin-Young's day begins when she and about 20 other auditors arrive at their desks at 8:30. They work in a midtown office roughly the size of a football field, with lowish ceilings, fluorescent lights, and the omnipresent hum of paper shredders (five in all). Each morning Chin-Young pulls up her standard-issue black metal chair to her standard-issue black metal desk and plugs in tax-return information on a Gridcase 1520 portable laptop computer. Leafing through her desk drawers -- stuffed with awards and certificates the IRS hands out for reasons such as "patriotic service" --she pulls out 1 of the 12 forms she may need to complete an audit. Overhead are three shelves of income-tax regulations and the Internal Revenue code.   <p> Chin-Young is expected to close each case the day of the audit, preferably within five and a half hours. When she's free, she spends hours going through records, filling out forms, writing reports and letters, and researching IRS manuals, publications, and data on the IRS computers. She must also meticulously track each and every thing she does for an audit -- from making phone calls to assessing penalties -- by using as many as three different logbooks. At 4 p.m. she fills out her "activity record." Twice a week she completes a record of the hours spent on each audit, how much money she assessed, and how much she collected. Most days Chin-Young leaves at five sharp.  <p> She now dreams of working in the national IRS office in Washington,D.C., on a congressional task force where she can make recommendations on how the IRS can simplify its tax forms and procedures. It is a long way from Swan Lake.   <p> According to a 1993 survey of 2,000 taxpayers conducted by Roper Starch Worldwide and sponsored by Worth, 7 percent, or 140 people, had been audited by the IRS. Of those, 35 percent said they felt "just terrible" about their experiences, 40 percent said they were only a little upset, and 17 percent said it was no big deal. Is this surprising? Not really. Just the notice in the mail --the dull white efficiency of the stationery, the plain black typeface, the little plastic address window, and the return address, "Internal Revenue Service" -- can bring on heart palpitations. <p> Chin-Young keeps magazine clippings of Naomi Campbell and Cindy Crawford on her bulletin board along with a sign that reads: maturity is the ability to control anger and settle differences without violence or destruction. In her office, letters and packages are routinely scanned for mail bombs; occasionally, a taxpayer will show up with a weapon. "Usually men," she says matter-of-factly. "They come in with a knife or gun. We try to get them to reschedule without it."  <p> Numbers and law are important in an audit, but so is the relationship established between the auditor and the "client," the euphemism the IRS uses for an alleged tax cheat. IRS auditors are allowed to search computer records compiled by the post office and the Social Security Administration; by divorce, probate, and bankruptcy courts; and by banks, insurance companies, and, sometimes, credit agencies. They can summon employer personnel records, subscriber-information services, and local and state public records showing ownership of cars, boats, and airplanes. In short, they can probe into the most intimate details of a taxpayer's life.   <p> The IRS recently decided that an auditor is supposed to audit "the taxpayer, not just the tax return," according to IRS auditor training materials. At the same time, comparisons of lifestyles are not supposed to be made. The auditor is not supposed to reflect on the differences between her client and herself. Once that happens, says Etta Owens, "you're no longer a professional." <p> Yet is this always possible? Of course not. Owens recalls an incident early in her career when "a taxpayer came in with a little pushcart filled with nothing but 1099s. Her interest income was $65,000 alone. Of course, she wasn't paying any estimated tax. She owed a few thousand dollars, and she asked me, 'Where am I going to get the money to pay it?' I'm sitting there saying to myself, 'I'm making $20,000 in total wages annually and you got $65,000 in interest?' All I said was 'I don't know what to tell you.'"  <p> The IRS estimates that about one in six taxpayers does not comply with tax regulations. (Of course, even the IRS can't audit that many people, so it settles for fewer: In 1994, 1.2 million people were audited, with about 87 percent owing a total of $6.2 billion.) And our seven auditors believe that rich people are less likely to comply than poor people are. "Higher-income people definitely cheat more than lower-income people," says one auditor. Another says, "Just as most children don't lie because they have to learn how, the same goes for the majority of the higher-income people. They learn to manipulate the tax system."  <p> Chin-Young says that establishing a good relationship eases all differences. "We have reasonable allowances and a certain latitude in an audit. For example, depending on the rapport I have with the taxpayer, I'll pick out the largest three or four expenses and maybe not look at the others. Or if a taxpayer verifies 75 percent of their return, I may give them the remaining 25 percent based on their credibility. But for those who try to push me around, then it's going to be a firm by-the-book audit, and we'll go through all of the lines on the return."   <p> The message here is pretty simple. Says Owens, her eyelids resting at half-mast, "The point is not to make us feel small. That's a big mistake."  <p>  <p>STUPID TAX TRICKS  <p> It's not surprising that Ralph Kramden lapsed into his signature stammer -- "hummuna hummuna" -- when the IRS scrutinized his tax return on a Honeymooners episode. Taxpayers often give themselves away with twitches, nail biting, lowered eyes -- signs IRS training materials instruct auditors to look for.  <p> Our seven auditors, who have seen all this and more, share some of the more ridiculous stunts taxpayers use to flummox agents and reduce fines. They offer this advice:  <p> Don't delay. Rescheduling audits or getting the case moved to another IRS office is a dumb taxpayer tactic. Stalling increases interest charges, which run until the auditor closes the case. And anyway, auditors can close out an audit even without the taxpayer's cooperation.  <p> Don't look for sympathy. It doesn't work. Auditor Rosalee Chin-Young explains: "Many taxpayers use crying as a tool to eliminate their taxes. Sometimes they'll cry to intimidate you, and they'll cry loud." Auditor Etta Owens adds: "That's when you say, 'Yeah, right,' and give them a tissue to get on with it."  <p> Owens recalls another sympathy ploy that failed. In January 1995, a Chinese-restaurant owner and Atlantic City gambler came limping into Owens's office wearing a body brace outside his clothes. "I'm very sick," he moaned. Indeed, he went on to say that he had been unable to earn money as a result of a bad fall. Owens asked, "When did you fall?" He replied, "The other day." She deadpanned, "I'm auditing your 1993 return."  <p> Bronx auditor Yvonne Ramos, 38, has knocked off 18,000 audits in her 17 years. During one, she asked about $20,000 in medical expenses. The taxpayer "opened up his shirt to show me his open-heart-surgery scar as if that was proof of his deduction," she says. She did not feel sorry for him.  <p> Don't try to be friends. After auditing 10,500 taxpayers, Manhattan auditor Pamela Lewis, 34, is hip to such behavior. She says,"Some tax professionals figure they should try to get close to me or talk on a first-name basis. They'll say, 'What's your first name?' I'll say, 'It's Miss Lewis -- you don't need to know my first name.'" Some taxpayers go much further. One, who was claiming fake dependents, showed up at Owens's desk with an open shirt exposing his chest and gold chains. He asked Owens where she went socially. When she asked for proof of his dependents, "he pulled out his black book," she says, "and asked, 'Which one do you want to know about?'" implying that a harem of women and their kids would back him up. Owens said, "I have two words for you: 'Sign here.'"  <p> Don't try the paper shuffle. Taxpayers and tax pros often try to clutter up an auditor's desk with their records -- hoping to obfuscate the facts. Lewis says, "You have to say, 'Okay, let's make two piles. Whatever records I haven't seen, I'll put here, and those I have seen will go over here.'" It then becomes clear if the taxpayer is trying to use the same documentation for different write-offs. <p>Don't doctor deductions. Lewis said one taxpayer tried to dupeher by altering a check. "The amount in actuality was $75," she explains, "but he put a 'five' in front of the 'seventy-five'on the amount line and another '5' in front of the '75' in the check amount box." Surprise! The correct amount is found at the end of a string of numbers below the signature line in the bottom right-hand corner of every canceled check. (Beware: The auditors say the most popular spot for cheating is Schedule C, where taxpayers can fully deduct business-related expenses.)  <p> Don't be high and mighty. Some taxpayers and pros think arrogance can help whittle a bill down to zero. Wrong. Ed Carroscio, 37,who has audited 3,700 taxpayers in his four and a half years as an auditor, says, "When taxpayers or tax pros are arrogant, there are problems on the return." Plus, it annoys the auditor. Taxpayers should also beware of tough-talking pros -- some couldn't care less about their clients. "Some reps will say to us, 'Do what you have to do,' even if it means sending taxpayers to bankruptcy court," says Chin-Young. She advises clients to accompany their tax pro to the first session at least, though they can let their accountant answer the questions.  <p> Don't follow Frederick Daily's advice. In his guidebook Stand Up to the IRS, he suggests that "bad B.O. may work," i.e., repel the auditor so that he or she will get you out quickly. Says Chin-Young: "One guy came in smelling like ammonia. Maybe that was his way of getting me to hurry up and get off his return."Of course, she didn't. <p>The best strategy? Just answer the auditor's questions: "Yes,""No," or "I'll get back to you." That's the advice from our experts. <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Taxation, Government, Ethical Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
