				<font size=5><b>Is it April 14 Already?</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/04-Is It April 14 Already?</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						April 1996
Worth magazine/Personal Adviser<p>IS IT APRIL 14 ALREADY?
Some alternatives to the IRS hot line's endless busy signal<p>By Melissa Jeffries<p>So you need last-minute tax help, but you don't have a half hour to spend waiting for the IRS to answer its hot line. Not to worry: There are alternatives.<p>The American Association of Retired Persons offers its Tax-Aide program at 11,000 locations around the country. This free service is available to anyone over age 60. Call the AARP at 202-434-6000 or your local AARP office for the site nearest you.<p>The National Association of Enrolled Agents provides free tax advice on the Internet. Taxpayers can post questions on bulletin boards or participate in weekly live chat sessions on the NAEA's Tax Channel on  <a name="NASD:AMER"></a><b>America Online</b> (keyword: Tax Channel). The Tax Channel is also available on the World Wide Web at http://www.cais.com/naea/naeamain.html. If you need to hire a tax agent, the NAEA runs a referral hot line; call 800-424-4339.<p>And the IRS's Web site never has a busy signal. Check out http://www.irs.ustreas.gov for a full list of IRS online services. 
<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Taxation, Retirement, Technology Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
