	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/03-Software for Taxing Times</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Software for Taxing Times</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/03-Software for Taxing Times</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						March 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Review  <p> SOFTWARE FOR TAXING TIMES  <p>  <p>TURBOTAX   <p><a name="NASD:INTU"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=16001"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Intuit</b></a>?, $39.95 <p>Available in all formats  <p> KIPLINGER TAXCUT  <p>Block Financial Corporation, $39.95 <p>Unavailable for DOS  <p> PERSONAL TAX EDGE  <p>Parsons Technology, $19 <p>Available in all formats  <p> SIMPLY TAX  <p>4Home Productions, $19.95 <p>For Windows only  <p>  <p>By Andrew Gluck  <p> There's a reason turbotax is the tax-preparation software you should buy for 1996, but it's not that TurboTax makes filing much easier and faster than working by hand (all the programs do that). And it's not that TurboTax is a better program than the competition (they're all good, and more a like than different).TurboTax is the best vehicle because it's made by Intuit, the same company that makes Quicken, the mother of all personal-finance software.  <p> Someday, other tax-software companies may challenge Intuit for sheer reach, but Intuit is constructing a virtual financial supermarket now. It's already possible to buy mutual funds over the Internet through the Quicken Financial Network, and it won't be long before you and I can download all our investment transactions and bank statements directly into a tax-software package, thus leap frogging the biggest hurdle of personal-finance software: all that tedious data entry.   <p> Not that it's easy to go wrong with the other programs. TaxCut, Personal Tax Edge, and Simply Tax are all good programs, as I discovered with the help of Ira Somach, a CPA and president of ARC Personal Financial Planning in Jericho, New York. They do the math correctly, offer lots of filing tips and tax-planning advice, and allow entire returns to be recalculated with just a few key strokes. Also, because in the past few years their makers have copied the best features from one another's programs, these things are now mostly similar. All employ an interview format, for example, to probe a user's tax situation and guide him orher through filing. Their makers all have on-line or Internet sites for updates and information. They even look alike, except for Simply Tax.   <p> There are differences among the programs, of course, and SimplyTax suffers the most from comparisons. It doesn't offer much hand-holding, and its interface, nowhere near as pleasing as that of the others, does nothing to make up for this shortcoming. Worse, Simply Tax, which was written for Windows 95, has a tendency to crash in Windows 3.1.  <p> Differences of style matter, too, in software, and here they're most important in the multimedia versions of the programs (SimplyTax doesn't come in a multimedia version). TurboTax and Tax Cutin corporate a lot of video clips of tax experts and, in TurboTax, actors delivering advice. Personal Tax Edge has fewer video but more audio clips they can be turned off, thankfully which are deployed to guide users through the program itself.  <p> Other distinctions? Personal Tax Edge is strongest for those lucky enough to know their way around the tax rules and forms and for those who fill out multiple returns, because users work more closely with tax forms here than they do in the interviews of other programs. TaxCut handles some routine data entry, such as W-2 numbers, in the simplest way.  <p> But overall, TurboTax has the most going for it: a lot of state versions (45, a couple more than Personal Tax Edge and many more than the others); easy access to cyber-space; the best interaction with Quicken (naturally); and a new phone system that's ready and waiting with 451 people (up from 200 last year) answering calls to provide technical support. All systems are go: Rev up TurboTax.  <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Technology Industry, Taxation

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
