				<font size=5><b>Sometimes You Just Want to Look it Up</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/03-You Just Want to Look it Up</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						March 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Review  <p> SOMETIMES YOU JUST WANT TO LOOK IT UP  <p> By Kathleen Murray  <p> Even those doing a return by computer or paying a preparer may occasionally want to get informed the old-fashioned way. Here's the lowdown on those hefty, printed tax guides.   <p> J. K. Lasser's Your Income Tax 1996  <p>(Macmillan, $14.95). The most comprehensive. A step-by-step trip through the income-tax-preparation process with information for almost every imaginable circumstance.  <p>  <p>Consumer Reports Books Guide to Income Tax 1996  <p>(Consumer Reports, $14.99). A god send for its organizer worksheet. Forces even the most disorganized filers to get their acts together.   <p> The Ernst & Young Tax Guide 1996  <p>(John Wiley & Sons, $14.95). Thorough. A good place to turn for those who know exactly what they need to learn.  <p> H & R Block 1996 Income Tax Guide  <p>(Fireside Books/Simon & Schuster, $14). For those who don't mind wading through jargon: Sections on taxpayer rights and IRS audits, for example, sound as if written by the tax agency.  <p> Taxes for Dummies,  <p>1996 edition, by Eric Tyson and David J. Silverman (IDG Books,$14.99). The best of these books for tax novices. Substitutes simple English for tax-code complexities. Notable for its attitude (feisty but agreeable) and helpful icons. <p>   <p>The Complete Idiot's Guide to Doing Your Income Taxes 1996, <p>by Gail Perry (Macmillan/Alpha Books, $14.99). Too cutesy (chaptertitles include "What's So Gross About Income?"). Best tip isa notice to taxpayers: If you're using a Form 1040A or 1040EZ, scan but don't buy this book.<p>
KEYWORDS: Taxation<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
