	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/03-Court Musicians</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Court Musicians</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/03-Court Musicians</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						March 1996
Worth magazine/Features<p>COURT MUSICIANS
To help win their case against the IRS, violinists Richard and Fiona Simon played Bach for the tax judge.<p>By Elizabeth Macdonald<p>Richard and Fiona Simon would eventually win their case against the Internal Revenue Service and, in the process, overturn decades of tax-law precedent and create some fanfare in the nation's largest daily newspapers. But on a bitter December day in 1993, victory seemed a long way off. After three years of battling one of the nation's most powerful and intimidating bureaucracies, the Simons had finally made it into U.S. tax court in lower Manhattan, where Richard was trying to explain their side of the case to Judge David Laro. <p>As 2 of 18 first violinists with the New York Philharmonic, the Simons believed they had every right to depreciate their rare, 200-year-old violin bows as tools of their trade__which they had done on their 1989 tax return and which the IRS had disallowed in l990. The Simons contended they needed the bows to earn a living. Richard Simon, a big, eloquent 59-year-old, told the court that he and his wife were "damned" if they didn't use the bows. "The critics will damn us, the audience will damn us, and our own players will damn us." He asked permission to demonstrate various bows to show their differences in quality. IRS attorney Pamela Cohen objected. <p>But Laro overruled her and asked Simon to proceed. <p>Simon nervously picked through an assortment of bows and plucked out a $30 fiberglass one used for teaching and warming up. He squeaked out several notes. The courtroom flinched.<p>Next, Fiona lifted her 245-year-old Tassini violin to her chin and, with a $1,000 French bow, performed an excerpt from a Paganini caprice. This bow was "very clumsily made" and had a weak sound, Richard told the court. Fiona then performed excerpts from works by Mozart, Handel, and Tchaikovsky, using increasingly higher-quality bows, even one valued at about $12,000. <p>Finally, Fiona picked up one of the two bows at issue in the case__simple, dark wood "sticks" crafted by the master French bow maker Franois Tourte in the late 18th and early 19th centuries. "This bow has a beautiful, bright sound," Richard told the judge, and is "wonderful for...Bach." It cost $21,500. The other, more valuable one, he said, has a "sound suitable for any kind of music." It cost $35,000.<p>The baroque sounds of Bach soon sang out through the courtroom. The IRS attorneys were still. As for Laro, he was leaning back in his chair, his arms folded across his chest, a smile spread across his face.<p>"Can you do a little Beethoven?" he asked.<p>Richard and Fiona Simon's brilliant courtroom performances capped an artfully executed battle against the IRS to reinstate a $3,000 tax break. The IRS had killed the write-off for two reasons. First, the IRS argued, the Simons couldn't depreciate their bows as tools of their trade because they couldn't determine a period of "useful life"__how long the bows would last. Second, taxpayers couldn't take deductions on antique instruments that increased in value as collectibles__such as Stradivarius violins or, in this case, Tourte bows.<p>"This is the way we at the IRS saw it," says Richard Farber, a Department of Justice tax attorney who represented the IRS in court. "It's our job to interpret the law and enforce our interpretation in court." Richard Simon, of course, viewed it differently. "Buying instruments is the most expensive financial investment musicians can make in their careers," he says. "We felt their position was an injustice."<p>The Simons' odyssey took them from the IRS's Manhattan headquarters to U.S. tax court and finally to a federal appeals court in New York, which, in a landmark decision last October, upheld the couple's tax-court victory. But Richard L. and Fiona Simon v. the Commissioner of Internal Revenue is more than just a victory for the Simons and for the professional musicians across the country who will now be able to depreciate certain antique instruments. It also casts a spotlight on the IRS--a complex behemoth, obdurate and sometimes dense__and how its arguments can be unraveled by a taxpayer's grit, determination, eloquence, and ability to play Bach. Still, looking at the Simons' situation today, it is amazing that they continue to say the fight was worth it. <p>**DECK**
The case began, however, not with fugues and dreams of justice but on a prosaic note: the need to increase their household income. In the fall of 1985, Richard was playing under Zubin Mehta, who was then maestro of the Philharmonic. Two years earlier, Fiona, a fine-boned woman with quick, nimble hands, had failed an audition for a full-time position in the orchestra, but was asked to freelance (Fiona declined to comment on the case, deferring to her husband in this matter). A part-time schedule fit with her desire to stay at home with their young son, Michael. <p>One day, Richard recalls, he and Fiona sat down in the living room of their apartment on Manhattan's Upper West Side to talk about finances. "I was really in deep straits for money [because of a previous divorce], so I was eager for her to get a job," Simon says. He pressured Fiona again to apply for a vacated position at the Philharmonic. This time she made it and was told to be onstage at Lincoln Center that September.<p>Elated, Richard decided to buy his wife a gift__a new violin bow__and soon came across two largely unused Tourte bows. Neither Richard nor Fiona could resist the Tourte's design features__the special curve of the bow and the flexible qualities of the bow's Pernambuco wood, stripped from Brazilian trees. "It was as if you'd been driving a Volkswagen all your life, then got to drive a Maserati," Richard says. "We weren't going to let them go."<p>Richard bought Fiona the more expensive bow, and a month later bought the less expensive one for himself, financing the $56,500 bill with a loan from the Philharmonic's revolving instrument fund and a line of credit from their musicians union. In September 1985, with her superb new bow in hand, Fiona joined her husband in the first-violin section of the Philharmonic, where Richard had been playing since 1965. Fiona signed on for a $42,000 base salary. Richard's salary was $44,000, supplemented by $4,000 in teaching fees.<p>Soon after, the couple consulted their tax adviser, Milton Sherman, to see if they could take a tax break on their bows. At the time, taxpayers could fully depreciate business assets as "recovery property" under the Accelerated Cost Recovery System (ACRS) of the Economic Recovery Tax Act of 1981. To deduct depreciation for an instrument before 1981, a musician had to calculate how much the instrument would decrease in value__essentially figuring how long the instrument could be used to generate income, a term tax pros call "useful life." In 1981, Congress abolished these complex calculations and set up depreciation time periods for various types of property. <p>Under both tax regimes, however, the IRS frowned on depreciating antique instruments__mostly violins__that increase in value as collectibles. But that didn't seem to worry Sherman, a blas human tax encyclopedia. Although the bows were likely to increase in value as collectors' items, he told the Simons to depreciate them as tools of their trade over a five-year period. <p>During the next four years, the Simons could not be parted with their Tourte bows. In 1989, Mehta loaded the orchestra's repertoire with Mahler, Beethoven, and Mozart symphonies. That same year, the Simons depreciated their two bows by a total of $10,815__for a tax savings of roughly $3,000.<p>Although the Simons were no strangers to the IRS__the agency had audited their 1985 and 1986 returns for business expenses and found nothing wrong (the depreciation write-offs were not questioned)__Richard was still unprepared for the shock he received when he arrived home after rehearsal on a December day in 1990 and discovered an IRS envelope in the mailbox. He tore it open and gasped__there was a notice saying that the couple owed $39,000 on their 1989 return. The IRS had gone ahead and disallowed all their deductions, including the write-off for the bows, because the Simons had never responded to an earlier audit notice. Richard says they never received it. <p>Richard faxed the notice to Sherman's office in midtown Manhattan, and Sherman quickly arranged a meeting with the IRS.<p>One gray, dismal morning in January 1991, Simon and Sherman met with Fay Vulcan, an IRS appeals officer, in a tiny conference room at the agency's Manhattan headquarters on Church Street. (Vulcan declined to comment.) The IRS maintained a hard line at the appeals meeting. Fully exercising her authority to sanction or deny write-offs, Vulcan axed the Simons' travel deductions, reportedly remarking, "You don't need to take cabs, you can take the bus." Next she torpedoed 75 percent of the couple's business entertainment write-offs. According to Richard Simon and Sherman, she said, "People take you out and you take them out, it's a fair trade." At a second meeting in April, which lasted five hours, Vulcan handed Simon a bill for $8,000. But she said she still wasn't finished. "She was hung up on the depreciation," says Simon.<p>Vulcan sent them on their way and reportedly went to the Lincoln Center library to look up "Tourte" in Grove's Dictionary of Music and Musicians, which says that the Tourte is regarded as the Stradivarius of bows because of its "extraordinary beauty and superb playing qualities." According to the IRS, Stradivarius violins couldn't be depreciated because they increase in value as collector's items.<p>At the beginning of the Philharmonic season, on September 15, 1991, Sherman called Richard. "I have a little present for you," he said jokingly. Vulcan had refused the depreciation. The Simons owed the IRS $11,000.<p>Richard Simon wasn't having any of it. He ordered Sherman not only to get the bill down to zero but to get his refund back, which amounted to a couple thousand dollars. Sherman did get Vulcan to zap everything except the $3,000 write-off. But Simon still wouldn't back down. "I deserved the write-off, and so does every other musician," he says. The IRS refused to budge. <p>DECK**
Each year, the IRS sends out roughly 40 million notices, demanding more money or ordering taxpayers to attend an audit. Some taxpayers quietly pay up or settle at the agency's appeals division. But a few intrepid souls refuse to pay. When this happens, they can either take the matter to U.S. tax court (where penalties and interest pile up until the case is resolved), or pay the tax and file a refund suit in either U.S. claims court or U.S. district court. The Simons decided to go to tax court, where their case would join 32,491 others. "Our backs were to the wall," says Richard. First, though, he wanted to find out whether other musicians had depreciation problems with the IRS. <p>Early in 1992, Richard mailed an informal survey to roughly 1,500 string musicians in major U.S. orchestras. After looking at about 1,200 replies, Simon discovered that 25 percent of the respondents had been audited by the IRS; of those, about 40 percent had been audited on their depreciation write-offs. Tax experts say that such a large number is not unusual. "The IRS thinks the entertainment industry is a fertile audit ground," says Andrew Blackman, a New York City certified public accountant. <p>Knowing their case could benefit musicians nationwide__and needing some financial help__Richard and Fiona arranged to have about $11,000 in donations collected by Local 802 of their musicians union and the International Conference of Symphony and Opera Musicians. They hired New York tax lawyer Arthur Pelikow, who, besides having worked as an attorney for the IRS, had made a mark representing musicians in the Metropolitan Opera orchestra before the tax court. <p>In December 1993, about three and a half years after filing their disputed return, the Simons finally arrived at the hearing room in the U.S. courthouse. At roughly 10:40 a.m., Judge David Laro swept in. Although Pelikow knew little about Laro before the case, it quickly became clear to him, he says, that Laro "was very knowledgeable, very businesslike and...good. He was an activist judge who frequently directed his questions to those testifying." Pelikow stepped up to the lectern first. He argued that the Simons rightfully deducted depreciation for their Tourte bows because they needed them to keep their jobs. "The Tourte bows, which are used by Petitioners [the Simons] on an almost continuous basis, produce the superior tonal quality which meets the demand and expectation of the music director, presently Kurt Masur, and the listening audience," he told the court.<p>IRS attorney Kevin Kilduff spoke on the government's behalf. He argued that the Simons must establish a determinable useful life for the bows, despite the fact that the law had changed: "The Petitioners [the Simons] argue that the useful-life requirement was abolished by ACRS [Accelerated Cost Recovery System]. Respondent [the IRS] disagrees with this position. It is our position that a useful life must still be established by Petitioners." <p>Pelikow then introduced the Simons' case. "I wanted to put them on the stand to get the point across that these bows were working tools, not works of art," he explains. "Calling the Simons as witnesses would engender sympathy, too."
It turned out to be an excellent strategy. Fiona demonstrated the various bows, then she and Richard took the stand for their final courtroom performance. "This is an excerpt of the last movement of the Bach Double Concerto, and I'm using the earlier of the Tourte bows," Richard told the court. After the last notes of the concerto echoed through the room, the judge responded. "That was superb," he said.<p>The IRS was not about to give up, however. Attorney Pamela Cohen assailed the write-off, using two lines of attack. First, she argued that bows do not suffer wear and tear. Furthermore, because works of art, including violin bows, have indeterminable useful lives as collectibles, they cannot be depreciated. 
But violin bows do deteriorate, Simon told the court. They get knocked against music stands and become warped when clutched in sweaty hands: "The air-conditioning system of [Avery Fisher Hall] is one of the most atrocious...you could imagine," said Simon. With frequent use, Simon said, a violin bow will eventually become "played out"__that is, lose the ability to vibrate properly. He held up a page of color pictures from a book by Etienne Vatelot, who is considered by many the world's authority on bows. The pictures showed "what can happen to a bow if you abuse it and you don't take extreme precautions," Simon explained. 
Cohen then blundered. "Present day, do your Franois Tourte bows look the same as that photograph?" she asked. Richard replied, "You mean do they look absolutely identical to that? No. But they look partly like that, of course, because they suffer wear." <p>That afternoon, the government began its case, calling Wiley Grant, the IRS's fine-arts appraiser, to establish that the Simons could make a profit by selling their bows as antiques. Grant, a 21-year IRS veteran who testifies in hundreds of IRS cases each year, ticked off his qualifications__he has a degree in English literature from George Washington University and has taken some basic real-estate-appraisal courses. <p>Under Pelikow's questioning, Grant admitted that his only experience in valuing musical instruments came from evaluating charitable contributions and inherited property in estate settlements. Moreover, he said that he was only slightly familiar with the depreciation rules the Simons had used to write off their bows. Later, in response to questions from Laro, Grant also conceded that the value of the violin bows was limited to their use as tools of a musician's trade, thereby refuting the IRS's position that the bows had no determinable useful life. Says Pelikow, "After the Grant testimony, I felt that the case began to move in our favor."<p>The judge then confirmed Pelikow's optimism, concluding the hearing with a quote: "As early as 42 b.c., it was said by Publius Syrus that the bow too tensely strung is easily broken, and it's not unnatural, therefore, to find that these bows are subject to wear and tear."<p>Outside the hearing room, Pelikow and the Simons chatted with the opposition. Richard says one member turned to him and said, "I want you to know I had dinner with my mother in New Jersey last night, and she said, 'Listen, we've been subscribers to the Philharmonic for 15 years.... Go easy on him.'" Another IRS lawyer said that her father had admonished her, too, saying, "Don't you dare hurt these guys."<p>The case was sent for review to the 16 other tax-court judges, a routine procedure in U.S. tax court for decisions of major importance. 
Roughly eight months later, while the Simons were touring in England__ playing Beethoven's Leonore Overture no. 3 and Barber's Second Essay for Orchestra__10 out of the 17 tax-court judges ruled in their favor. The judges agreed that determinable useful life was not a sine qua non for depreciation. Moreover, they ruled, since Congress eliminated the determinable-useful-life requirement in 1981, it left as the sole criterion for depreciation substantial wear and tear. The court concluded that the Simons' bows were not works of art but tools of their trade subject to wear and tear.<p>Neither the case nor the IRS's interest in it stopped with that court. On December 23, 1994, the agency appealed the decision to the United States Court of Appeals for the Second Circuit in New York. IRS watchers throughout the country understood that the Simons had a major battle on their hands. "We all knew there was a decision from the top at the IRS, that the agency would not let this issue stand any longer," says tax expert (and French-horn player) Dan Braden. For the appeal, the Simons hired former U.S. district-court judge Marvin Frankel as lead attorney, with Pelikow acting as counsel.<p>In June of 1995, a panel of three appellate judges heard the case. "Our strategy was to reiterate that the tax-court decision was correct," says Frankel. "We emphasized that the question was not whether the depreciation statute as Congress rewrote it was a wise statute, but whether Simon was entitled to the deduction as the law was written." Assistant attorney general Loretta Argrett and Justice Department attorneys Gary Allen, Richard Farber, and Edward Perelmuter stuck to the tack used by the IRS in tax court. However, when the government attorneys started referring to IRS regulations that predated the changes Congress made in 1981, Frankel says, the judges threw out their arguments.<p>As the case made its way through the appeals court, Richard and Fiona continued their high-profile careers. Then, in July at Avery Fisher Hall, while playing The Gypsy Baron, a Johann Strauss operetta, Richard began hemorrhaging out of his mouth, forcing him to leave the stage. Since then, he has undergone surgery for thyroid cancer, and he has stopped playing with the Philharmonic.<p>On September 8, the Simons received good news: The federal appeals court in Philadelphia ruled in favor of Brian P. Liddle, a Philadelphia musician who had claimed a 1987 tax deduction of $3,170 for his 17th-century Ruggeri bass viol, which he had bought for $28,000 and depreciated on the grounds of wear and tear. (Interestingly, this case had nearly the same cast of characters__Grant testified as an expert witness, and Laro wrote the decision.)<p>A month later, on October 3, the appellate court rendered its judgment. The federal appeals panel agreed that the Simons were entitled to a tax deduction for depreciation of their antique violin bows, in much the same way as companies depreciate the cost of factories and equipment. <p>The government has decided not to appeal the matter to the U.S. Supreme Court, says Wilson Fadely, an IRS spokesman. But that doesn't mean the IRS can't eventually have its way. "There are various options we can consider," Fadely says, showing why the agency is a law unto itself. "We can write a revenue ruling that says we'll follow the appeals-court ruling only in the New York circuit but not in other circuits. We can continue to litigate a different but similar case in other circuits. Or we can ask Treasury for a legislative remedy, too." <p>The case rests now in the Philharmonic's archives, along with programs, scores, and recordings of the great maestros__Leonard Bernstein, Arturo Toscanini, and Bruno Walter. But as much as the Simons' case is now a footnote in musical history, it has devastated their finances. After paying $15,000 and collecting $11,000 in donations, the Simons still owe more than $42,000 in legal bills. Says Richard: "I'm now considering taking out a loan to pay off this case. Or I may have to sell our Tourte bows."<p>Additional reporting contributed by Maxwell Dale.<p>
IF YOU HANG IT ON A WALL, IT'S ART<p>Richard and Fiona Simons' appellate victory worried at least one participant: Appeals Court Judge James Oakes. In his dissent he wrote that taxpayers could start playing fast and loose with depreciation deductions. "A car buff in the trade or business of buying, collecting and selling antique automobiles, who drives his autos to auto shows, may obtain a depreciation deduction, or the law office that buys fine Sheraton or Chippendale desks or chairs for office use can take a deduction, though in each case the auto or furniture is actually appreciating in value and has no determinable useful life."<p>But the majority opinion signed by the two other judges acknowledged Oakes's problems and also dashed the hopes of some art buyers: "Paintings that hang on the wall of a law firm merely to be looked at__to please connoisseur clients or to give the appearance of dignity to combative professionals__do not generally suffer wear or tear." <p>The judges noted that some latitude in interpretation may result from the ruling but wrote that that was the price Congress was willing to pay to simplify depreciation rules. Congress did so, they said, "to stimulate investment in business property generally." That comes with a caveat, Judge Ralph Winter warned:"One should not exaggerate the extent to which our holding is a license to...depreciate valuable property that a taxpayer expects to appreciate in real economic value."<p>So what's deductible? Says Marvin Frankel, the Simons' appeals-court attorney: "Under the statute, whether you like it or not, there are two main requirements to depreciate something: First, is it used in the trade or business? And secondly, is it subject to wear and tear? The contrast is with a work of art that you could hang on the wall of your office, which in a sense is using it for a trade or business, but it's not subject to wear and tear. So if you took a Stradivarius and hung it on a wall, you couldn't depreciate it."<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Taxation, Art Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

