	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Is Your CPA a Snitch?</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/03-Is Your CPA a Snitch?</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						March 1996
Worth magazine/Advisor<p>IS YOUR CPA A SNITCH?
Tax secrets aren't always safe with an accountant.<p>By Elizabeth Macdonald<p>Nothing is more intimate than a tax return, and taxpayers trust no one with the details of their financial lives like they do their tax accountant. Right now, millions of taxpayers are confessing their every boneheaded financial move, their every fudge and cut corner, to their tax pros, expecting them to maneuver their returns through the system while keeping mum about what they know.<p>But anyone considering crossing the line from corner cutting to out-and-out criminality should think again. Unlike communications with lawyers, communications with tax accountants are not recognized as privileged under federal law. <p>Nervous now? You should be, because bestriding this situation like a green-eyeshade-wearing colossus is the Internal Revenue Service. The IRScan subpoena an accountant to turn over every receipt, every canceled check, and notes from every conversation from a client's file. "When CPAs are subpoenaed by the IRS, there are no confidences," says David Doran, associate professor of accounting at Penn State University at Erie. "They are obligated by law to testify against their clients." <p>Here's another surprise: Accountants don't necessarily know the rules. In a study Doran conducted in 1992, 18 percent of the accountants surveyed incorrectly said that information shared between a CPAand a client is privileged.<p>If all that isn't disheartening enough, consider this: According to the book Lost Rights, by James Bovard, the IRS admitted in 1989 that it was using 900 controlled informants (that is, double agents), 40 of whom were accountants. The use of double agents continues today.<p>Fortunately, there's a little good news here. CPAs boast of a proud tradition that doesn't includeturning tattletale, and they do resist the IRS when they can. "Rather than being privileged, like lawyer-client talks are privileged, CPAs' contacts with clients are confidential," says Herb Finkston, director of the professional-ethics division at the American Institute of Certified Public Accountants. "For a CPA to respond to a subpoena, it has to be validly issued and enforceable. If the CPA believes the subpoena is a fishing expedition, such as an IRS request to hand over every piece of paper the taxpayer accumulated in the past five years, the accountant can get the subpoena quashed in court." What's more, a significant minority of states recognize client-CPA conversations as privileged__which could protect those involved in local tax disputes.<p>The IRS maintains no data on how often it subpoenas accountants' files, but taxpayers need worry only if they fear their fudging has turned felonious. "This is something that usually only comes up in a criminal investigation," says Carol C. Markman, a CPAin Westbury, New York. <p>"The best thing to do is to not be dishonest from the beginning__that's the government's message," says Doran. "Because if you aren't honest, there's no safe harbor."<p>
FILER BEWARE:THE IRS'S HOT BUTTONS
Every year, the IRS supplies its agents with a list of fire-engine red audit flags tose in scrutinizing returns. Taxpayers should tread carefully in the following areas:<p>*Underreported income The IRS will check to see if there is enough income to support a taxpayer's financial lifestyle as reflected in such items as the mortgage-interest deduction.
*Suspicious gross profit marginThe IRS is particularly interested in small- business owners who report low profit margins and high expenses in excess of gross receipts.
*Inflated business write-offsTaxpayers often deduct unallowable job expenses such as questionable business meals.
*Suspicious child-care credits The IRS will nix this credit__and may impose a $50 penalty__if it sees no Social Security number reported for a nanny.
*Deductions for miscellaneous write-offs on Schedule CTaxpayers can deduct miscellaneous expenses only if they exceed 2 percent of adjusted gross income. Some taxpayers wrongly shift these deductions to Schedule C, which is strictly for business profits and losses.
*Failure to pay early-withdrawal penalties on retirement accountsTaxpayers who receive retirement money before age 5912 must turn in a completed Form 5329 along with the 10 percent excise tax.
*Missing self-employment taxTaxpayers often neglect to include this for partnership income or miscellaneous income reported on Form 1099.
*Suspected fake dependentsThe IRS will check reported income to see if the taxpayer earned enough money to support a flock of claimed dependents.
*Hobby losses deducted as business expensesIf a hobby, such as dog breeding, is to be considered a business (and thus have its expenses qualify as deductible), it must turn a profit for three out of five years. If the hobby/business involves horses, it need turn a profit only in two out of seven years.
*Erroneously deducted passive-activity lossesTaxpayers sometimes try to avoid the limitations on passive losses by not reporting whether a loss comes from a passive or active investment.
*Payroll-tax evasion Employers often report employees as independent contractors in order to avoid paying Social Security levies.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Taxation, Government Adgency

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
