<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/01S-Heads Up, Taxpayers!</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Heads Up, Taxpayers!</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/01S-Heads Up, Taxpayers!</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						January 1996--Special issue <p>Worth magazine/Features  <p> HEADS UP, TAXPAYERS! <p>It's time to stop thinking about Congress--they'll get to those cuts eventually--and start thinking about April.  <p> By Elizabeth Macdonald  <p> Don't wait. That's what the experts at Ernst & Young, Price Waterhouse, KPMG Peat Marwick, and tax publisher CCH Inc. are saying about the congressional tax breaks that are apparently eventually coming down the road. The House and Senate's seven-year omnibus budget bill includes numerous tantalizing breaks. GOP conferees recently reached a tentative agreement on a number of changes to the tax code. But President Bill Clinton, Senator Bob Dole, Speaker Newt Gingrich, and other politicians great and small aren't done slugging it out. Dole says the high-level tax harangue will last through December, which means taxpayers may have to sit tight for a while.  <p> Not that that's anything new. As a practical matter, "tax planning" is an oxymoron, given that the tax code has changed just about every year since1980. That's why, according to the best minds in the field, the smartest plan is to adopt a long-term strategy and update it as changes come down the pike from D.C. Here are the experts' best ideas all of them useful right now on how to lower income taxes.  <p> BULLETPROOF INCOME. Many mutual fund investors over pay their capital-gains tax when they sell shares. Generally, equity funds report distributions in December, and investors pay tax the next April on those distributions. The problem is that when investors sell, they often forget to increase their cost basis by the amount of the distributions. For example, suppose you put $1,000 into an equity fund in 1992, and in each of the following three years, you get a $50 distribution. When you cash out of the fund, you should report a basis of $1,150, not $1,000.   <p> Stock investors tend to make a related mistake: They fail to double-check the accuracy of their 1099s, which report dividend income, and to look for any distribution that's a partial return of capital. The distribution isn't taxable, but taxpayers must remember to adjust their records, reducing the basis, or cost, of the investment by the amount of capital distributed. (And don't forget to include the commission paid for purchasing stock when figuring a gain or loss.) Also, government sources say IRS computers in five of ten service centers are now misreading 1099s. So if you get a notice saying you misreported interest and dividends, don't assume the IRS is right.  <p> Upper-income investors should compare the yields on tax-exempt and taxable bonds to get a higher tax-free return. To figure out a comparable yield on a taxable bond, divide a municipal bond's yield by 1 minus your tax bracket, then multiply that number by 100. So an investor in the 28 percent bracket who owns a municipal bond yielding 5 percent would need an equivalent taxable yield of 6.94 percent (5 percent divided by 0.72 times100). Investors in the 39.6 percent bracket would need an 8.28 percent yield to equal the tax-free 5 percent.  <p> Parents should consider transferring assets that generate ordinary income, such as dividends and interest, to dependent children to take advantage of their lower tax bracket. Parents in the39.6 percent tax bracket who shift $10,000 in investment income to a child in the 15 percent bracket (as most children are) will save $2,460 in taxes (the parents' tax of $3,960 minus the child's tax of $1,500). Caution, though: "Children will then have control of that money, so parents can't prevent them from spending it," says Jim Shambo, a tax expert in Colorado Springs, Colorado.If the dependent child is under 14, parents can take advantage of the so-called kiddie tax, which exempts a child's first $650 of unearned income.   <p> Retirees should take note of Congress's recent rejection of a proposal that would have allowed senior citizens to earn more income without losing Social Security benefits. The law still taxes up to 85 percent of Social Security benefits received when what's called "provisional" income (tax-exempt income plus half of Social Security benefits plus adjusted gross income) surpasses $44,000 for joint filers and $34,000 for single filers (who are then taxed at their marginal tax bracket). Retirees who face this scenario should realize income carefully, says Nadine Gordon Lee, a tax expert at Ernst & Young. Senior citizens can also shift some of their investments from income-producing assets to assets that favor capital appreciation.  <p> While it may seem that the government has found a way to dun everything in sight, not all income is taxable. It's worth any taxpayer's while to review the list of nontaxable sources of income in J.K. Lasser's Your Income Tax 1996.  <p> Finally, a quick but important exception to the recommendation against trying to anticipate coming tax changes: Do plan for a capital-gains rate cut, which experts say will be effective January 1, 1996. If possible, avoid selling assets you've held for more than a year until after the first. It could save you a lot.  <p> SCROUNGE FOR DEDUCTIONS. Rare is the write-off in an increasingly stingy tax land. For example, taxpayers can deduct medical expenses only for the part that tops a stiff 7.5 percent of adjusted gross income. Miscellaneous expenses, too, get stuck under a 2 percent floor. But did you know you can get a write-off for hair-transplant operations? Strange but true. To jump that 7.5 percent hurdle, taxpayers can deduct as medical expenses the cost of removing lead-based paint from a home, contact lenses, birth control pills, teeth straightening (including clarinet lessons advised by adentist), doctor-prescribed visits to a health spa, metabolism tests, sacroiliac belts, and air conditioners necessary for relieving an allergy or difficulty in breathing. For a full list, consult the Lasser guidebook. Taxpayers should also count payments made on behalf of their children, parents, and other dependents for whom they provide more than half of the total support (more than10 percent if the parents qualify under a multiple-support agreement). Also, self-employed taxpayers can now write off 30 percent of the cost of their health-insurance premiums, up from 25 percent in 1994.  <p> Besides write-offs for things like mortgage interest, investment deductions abound, too. They include set up charges and annual custodial fees for IRA and Keogh accounts (the fees must be paid separately); safe deposit box fees, so long as the box is used for share certificates and similar items; investment books, newspapers, and magazines (including this one); fees for investment counseling; tax-planning fees; postage and telephone costs related to investing; and part of the cost of a personal computer used to manage investments. On that last one, strict rules apply the IRS will let you take this write-off only if the computer is used 50 percent or more of the time for investing.   <p> Even though a total of 38.4 million taxpayers took a record 220 million business trips during 1994, according to Official Airline Guides, the tax law restricts most business travel and entertainment write-offs. But there is still some relief available. Taxpayers who lease their cars can deduct the part of the lease payment that is for the use of the car for business or work. Normal operating costs and maintenance may also be deducted (specialrules apply, though, so check with a tax pro). Taxpayers can deduct travel expenses for attending conventions or similar meetings in connection with a trade or business, but they can't write off those costs if they went to increase their investment income. Also, beginning last October 1, the IRS increased the threshold at which receipts are required for deductions for business travel, gift, and entertainment expenses from $25 to $75.  <p> Taxpayers can reap a double tax advantage by donating appreciated property to a charity. They get a hefty deduction for the full, appreciated value of the asset, and they avoid the capital-gains tax they would have paid if they had sold the property. Say a taxpayer in the 39.6 percent bracket wants to donate a $10,000 stock, bought for $5,000, to a charity. By donating it outright rather than selling it and donating the proceeds, the taxpayer will save $3,960 in federal taxes and avoid $1,400 in capital-gains tax. Remember, the IRS says a charity must give you a receipt for any contribution over $250.  <p> If an asset tanks, taxpayers should probably sell it first, then donate the proceeds. That way, they'll generate both a charitable deduction and a deductible capital loss against any capital gains and up to $3,000 in ordinary income. This is one move taxpayers may want to make soon. Congress now wants to reinstate a rule, in effect before the 1986 tax reform act, that says an individual must have two dollars in long-term capital losses to offset one dollar of ordinary income. So taxpayers would need $6,000 in net long-term losses realized after January 1, 1996, to get the maximum $3,000 deduction against ordinary income.  <p> And finally, don't forget that interest on up to $100,000 in home-equity loans is still tax deductible. "Taxpayers should consolidate their debt with one and get a 35 to 40 percent subsidy from the government," says Nadine Gordon Lee.  <p> WATCH OUT FOR THE DREADED AMT. With any of these moves, taxpayers should avoid triggering the alternative minimum tax, a specialrate that snares taxpayers who have lots of itemized deductions and untaxed income. Basically, the AMT is there to make sure everybody pays his or her fair share. Taxpayers typically trigger the AMT if they have started up a new business or if they own large tax-sheltered investments. Those stung by the AMT will pay either the higher of their AMT, which can be as much as 28 percent, or their regular rate.  <p> SIGN UP FOR COMPANY BENEFIT PLANS NOW. Not everyone is taking advantage of flexible spending accounts, which are now available at close to 70 percent of all companies. This is just plain foolish. These plans let taxpayers set aside a percentage of their pretax money each pay period for dependent-care expenses or medical costs not covered by insurance, typically up to a maximum of $5,000 for each plan. By using pretax dollars, taxpayers effectively shave the cost of their unreimbursed expenses by 40 percent or more (they can pare down their Social Security taxes, too). In1994, however, only 20 percent of eligible employees contributed an average of $707 to a health care FSA, and just 4 percent of eligible employees contributed an average of $2,979 to a dependent-care FSA, according to Hewitt & Associates, a benefits-consulting firm in Lincolnshire, Illinois. Taxpayers can use pretax dollars to pay for insurance deductibles and co-payments, medical supplies, and even contact lenses. Child-care plans can cover the cost of after-school care and camp for children up to age 12. The beauty of these plans is that at any point in the year you can spend more than you've put into your FSA (though not more than you're scheduled to contribute by year's end). As a matter of fact, if you leave your job before your contributions catch up with your spending, the company must pick up the bill, says IRS spokeswoman Jody Patterson. Careful, though: The IRS will grab any portion left unspent in the account at year-end.  <p> If there's one thing worse than not taking advantage of FSA plans, it's not making the most of a 401(k) plan. More than 80 percent of all companies will match contributions, usually one dollar for every two dollars taxpayers set aside out of pretax earnings. Some employers allow contributions of as much as 20 percent of pretax income, to a maximum of $9,240 in 1995. Again, despite such hefty benefits, workers are putting away just 5 percent in these plans, down from 6 percent in 1994, according to a recent survey by KPMG Peat Marwick.  <p> FATTEN UP OTHER RETIREMENT PLANS. Taxpayers still seem to prefer not to know how much money they'll need in retirement. According to the Employee Benefit Research Institute, 60 percent of 1,000 workers polled recently said they put aside some of their money for retirement, but only 35 percent of those with retirement savings said they have tried to determine how much they will need to save.  <p> You have until April 15, 1996, (later if you get an extension) to get a 1995 deduction for an IRA worth as much as $2,000 (up to $2,250 for a spousal or joint IRA). The earlier the contribution, the better. For example, say two taxpayers each invest $2,000 annually in an account yielding 8 percent. The first taxpayer invests each year on January 2, while the second does so on April15 of the following year. After ten years, the first taxpayer will have $33,794 in the account, while the second will have just $30,498.   <p> Self-employed taxpayers have until the last day of the year to open a Keogh plan and until April 15 to open a simplified employee pension plan. Taxpayers can put away as much as 13.043 percent of their self-employment income into these plans, up to $19,564, even if they're already covered by a 401(k) or other employer-provided retirement plan at a separate company. Contributions are tax deductible.   <p> Depending on their income, some taxpayers can't fully fund their 401(k) plans. The law puts a $150,000 limit on the amount of compensation that can be considered when calculating contributions to qualified 401(k) and pension plans. Since maximum 401(k) plan contributions are determined by complicated formulas that balance the contributions of high-income workers at a company with those of lower-income employees, the new ceiling may also slam those earning as little as $66,000, says Howard Edelstein, a principal at the Cleveland office of the Todd Organization, a retirement consulting firm. To make up for this shortfall, companies have increasingly offered nonqualified plans (plans that don't qualify for tax-deferred status) to even midlevel executives. In a recent ruling, the IRS approved a nonqualified plan that lets employees defer part of their salary into a nonqualified plan first. After the end of the year, when the maximum amount of permitted 401(k) contributions is known, the deferral amounts and matching employer contributions (without earnings) are then transferred into the qualified 401(k) plan. <p>
KEYWORDS: Retirement, Taxation  <p> 

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
