	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/10-Tax Reform Unplugged</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Tax Reform Unplugged</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/10-Tax Reform Unplugged</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						October 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Experts  <p> TAX REFORM UNPLUGGED  <p> By Elizabeth Macdonald  <p> It's a political fact of life that partisan clamor over tax-law changes always drowns out the truth, and that's certainly true of the current tax-reform debates now gripping Washington. Congressmen Dick Armey and Richard Gephardt have each introduced plans to overhaul the income-tax system. Senators Sam Nunn and Pete Domenici share authorship of another plan, which they've given a patriotic name. And because America's general hatred of the income tax makes for good campaign fodder, Republican presidential hopefuls Richard Lugar and Arlen Specter are working up tax-reform positions. All this has pressed Bill Clinton into considering his own proposal. <p> None of this should be surprising. Would-be tax reformers rightly complain that the current income tax is riddled with $500 billion worth of loopholes that permit some millionaires to pay no income taxes whatsoever. Cheats rip off the government by roughly $127 billion each year, while honest taxpayers spend more than $100 billion a year to figure out what they owe. Ben Franklin was right when he said the two things that are certain in life are death and taxes, but another wag captured the true mess: The major difference between death and taxes is that Congress can't make death any worse than it is.   <p> Various tax-reform proposals have been floating around Washington for a number of years. The two most widely discussed proposals lately are House Republican leader Armey's flat-tax plan and Nunn and Domenici's Unlimited Savings Allowance plan, a consumption tax they'd like you to remember as the USA Tax.  <p> Most Americans don't know a lot about either of these plans  except that one of them has to be better than what we have now. But is that even true? The current debate draws more on emotion and intuition than on empirical evidence about how either proposal would actually affect taxpayers. Let's try some of the latter. It can't do much harm to inject facts into the Great Tax Reform Debate.  <p> The flat tax. Politicians of all stripes have spent time on the flat-tax wagon, from 1992 liberal presidential candidate Jerry Brown to White House chief of staff Leon Panetta to, lately, Dick Armey. Armey's flat-tax plan is based on one introduced in 1981 by Robert E. Hall and Alvin Rabushka, senior fellows at the Hoover Institute, a conservative think tank.  <p> All flat-tax champions say the same thing: that although the name suggests otherwise, a flat tax is progressive that is, its tax bite moves higher with income, because flat-tax proposals first give each taxpayer a fat personal exemption and then tax all income above that amount at the flat rate. And they do mean all income: Armey proposes to eliminate virtually all the deductions, exemptions, and credits that help make the current system so convoluted.  <p> Armey proposes a tax rate of 20 percent, dropping to 17 percent in the second year of implementation. The standard deductions, which Armey dubs "family allowances," are $13,000 for singles and $26,200 for married couples, with dependents worth $5,300 each. These deduction figures would rise with the cost of living.  <p> Armey says his plan is fair because its effective rates move higher with income. A family of four with a wage income of $50,000 would pay an effective tax of 5.7 percent; one earning $100,000, nearly 11.3 percent; and one pulling in $200,000, 14.2 percent.  <p> And yet the tax bite rises for taxpayers at middle and lower income levels, largely because of the lost deductions, exemptions, and credits and the taxation of fringe benefits (more on that below). Roughly $843 billion in deductions would vanish under Armey's plan, including $51 billion in mortgage-interest deductions. A recent Treasury Department study concluded that under the flat tax, families with incomes under $200,000 would see their after-tax incomes drop by 3 percent or more. Families with incomes of $200,000 or more would see their after-tax incomes rise 8 percent.  <p> There's more good news for the well-off. Under Armey's plan, investment income would not be taxed. If you made your money at a job, you'd pay 17 percent on it. If you lived off investment income or inheritances, you wouldn't owe a cent. "It is an obvious mathematical law that lower taxes on the successful will have to be made up by higher taxes on average people," Hall and Rabushka state in a report for the journal Tax Notes. "Tax reform will be a tremendous boon to the economic elite from the start." <p> One thing you have to appreciate about the various tax-reform plans is that they're going to get people thinking about the social agendas tax policies promote and the way tax policies are priced into economic transactions. The mortgage-interest deduction, introduced with the first income tax in 1913, was designed to open up home ownership to more people. By this point, flat-taxers argue, it's merely propping up prices. Take away the prop, they say, and prices will be reestablished at truer levels after a period of adjustment.  <p> There would be winners and losers, though, during the adjustment. A flat tax would be good news for first-time buyers, who typically finance three quarters or more of the price of a house. That's because the flat tax wouldn't touch a lender's interest income from loans, so mortgage rates could be expected to fall by a point or two. And homes would be about 15 percent cheaper, according to a recent study by DRI/McGraw Hill. Of course, this is going to distress the people who bought homes under the old rules. <p> Employees who enjoy hefty company-provided fringe benefits, from medical coverage to fitness counseling, would lose big under Armey's proposal, because businesses would no longer be able to deduct benefits and could be counted on to be stingier about offering them. Worse, employees would pay the flat tax on the value of the benefits, which in 1993 equaled 18 percent of total compensation. Again, Hall and Rabushka see things sorting themselves out after a bit, with employers offering workers "higher pay in exchange for lower fringes." You might find it difficult to support that kind of optimism in today's business environment.  <p> More losers: Divorced spouses would not be allowed to deduct alimony payments under a flat tax, which could affect some people's ability and willingness to live by the terms of their divorce decrees. And no longer would the blind and the elderly get extra exemptions of $950, because, Hall and Rabushka say, "Many of the elderly and a few of the blind are well-off." Armey's plan also axes the child-care credit, though Rabushka and Hall happily predict that "more people will join the labor force or work longer hours, especially two-earner households." (Ponder that in terms of family values.) Strangely, the only write-off to survive under Armey's flat-tax plan would be a 100 percent deduction for business meals.  <p> Labor-intensive companies in the service sector would be flattened by Armey's tax, since it wipes out the deduction of half the Social Security tax. This would clobber the self-employed, who pay all their Social Security taxes themselves. The manufacturing industry would win big, thanks to extensive write-offs of capital equipment.  <p> Is this, in sum, a plan that's likely to go down easily with taxpayers? Perhaps not. Armey and Senator Richard Shelby of Alabama couldn't have been overwhelmed by the results of their own recent poll of 800 homeowners: Just 38 percent said they supported the flat tax.  <p> The USA tax. How do you like the sound of "Schedule S"? If Sam Nunn and Pete Domenici's consumption-tax plan goes through, Schedule S will be a big part of every taxpayer's life. The goal of Nunn and Domenici's USA plan is to encourage savings. Anything you save or otherwise invest, you defer taxes on. Anything you spend  including your own savings you are considered to have consumed, and you pay now. Schedule S is for tracking it all.  <p> Here's a basic example: Joe Smith earns $100,000 in 1998. He puts $20,000 into the stock market. So his taxable income is $80,000. The next year, Joe Smith earns $100,000, but he doesn't invest a thing. In fact, he takes $10,000 out of the stock market. His taxable income is $110,000.  <p> The USA plan employs a progressive tax-rate scale. Married couples filing jointly would pay 19 percent on amounts up to $5,399,27 percent up to $23,999, and 40 percent on up. Nunn and Domenici expect to be able to lower rates a few years down the road. <p> This plan would shake things up less dramatically than the flat tax would. Nunn and Domenici continue to extend favorable treatment to IRAs, pensions, owner-occupied housing (the mortgage-interest deduction wouldn't be touched), and tax-exempt debt such as municipal bonds.   <p> Baby boomers, though, would find things changed in important ways. Boomers are getting the lion's share of the blame for the worrying decline in the national savings rate, from 7.1 percent of gross domestic product in the 1970s to 3.8 percent today. They're thought to be selfishly spending all the money they should be investing and thereby making available to the capital markets. <p> There's a problem with this. Studies show that senior citizens are actually doing the spending. Seniors typically spend a truckload of money, much of it from Social Security and Medicare, on housing costs, leisure activities, and medical expenses. In fact, the Congressional Budget Office says the decline in the savings rate is attributable directly to the elderly who rely on entitlements. Economist Laurence Kotlikoff of Boston University has studied the national savings decline and concludes: "Today's 70-year-olds are consuming, on average, roughly one fifth more than 30-year-olds."  <p> Nevertheless, the idea here is to control the spending of boomers,and that means controlling their borrowing. The USA plan discourages borrowing by counting it, except for the first $35,000, against any savings credit. If, for example, in the year Joe Smith saved $20,000 he also borrowed $50,000 to buy something other than a house, his Schedule S would show a savings credit of just $5,000. <p> But Lee Sheppard, a columnist for Tax Notes, has discovered a gigantic loophole for debt-happy boomers. It still allows consumers to write off interest on $1 million in mortgage debt. The inevitable result, Sheppard believes, would be high-income earners succumbing to an urge to run out and refinance. This is something they do now: They buoy their consumption levels by refinancing their mortgages.  <p> The big winners under this plan, then, are taxpayers wealthy enough and smart enough to exploit the rules on financing savings accounts with debt. The losers are middle- to lower-income families who can't afford to set aside money.  <p> If your first impression is that Schedule S doesn't sound like the keystone to a simpler tax system, you're right. The USA Tax would be of staggering complexity. Taxpayers would have to keep a running record of any nondeductible and debt-financed savings. It's also worth asking whether it would in fact improve saving.William Gale, an economist at the Brookings Institution, a nonpartisan think tank, says his research shows the USA plan would increase the national savings rate by only 10 percent.  <p> what, then? Neither the flat tax nor the USA tax (nor any other proposal out there) would fix the real problems with the currentincome tax namely, the underground economy, the low savings rate, and the quantity of rich people who don't pay. That's one reason Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin says the Clinton administration has looked at all the reform plans and found "none of these are clearly better than where we are today." Clinton wants to simplify, not overhaul, the tax code. Plenty of people can show him good places to start.  <p> One argument alone is enough to support preservation of the current income-tax system: Experts widely agree that the transition to any new tax system would be an expensive, messy nightmare. Most of the problems with the income tax are administrative, largely because the current system has transmogrified into anenormous social experiment. Today, tax law is used to support everything from housing policy to R&D of better ketchup bottles. <p> In the end, Congress will probably streamline the current system in a way that acknowledges the goals (and influence) of the flat tax and USA proposals. Expect changes that encourage savings and investing, such as raising income levels for IRA deductibility and excluding more capital gains from taxation the longer an asset is held. These are the kinds of changes that are least likely to jolt the economy, and the taxpayers.   <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Taxation, Government, Legislation

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
