	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/10-You Can't Take it With You</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>You Can't Take it With You</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/10-You Can't Take it With You</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						October 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Advisor  <p> YOU CAN'T TAKE IT WITH YOU <p>So you're thinking about retiring to one of the seven states that don't tax income, like Florida or Nevada, where you can bask in the sun and in the knowledge that your money is safe from the state taxman. Think again.   <p> By Liz Macdonald  <p> In 1974, Howard Smith quit as a detective with the Los Angeles Police Department after 25 years and moved with his wife to the town of Friday Harbor, Washington. Four years later, he retired from the local police force, after his accountant had confirmed with a California Franchise Tax Board official that he would owe no taxes on his monthly LAPD pension.   <p> Then, in December 1988, Smith received a demand from California for 14 years' back taxes on his LAPD pension, plus a 55 percent late penalty and a 12 percent annual interest charge compounded daily. And since California, like 20 other states, used Smith's total income before deductions to calculate his taxes, he moved into a higher tax bracket.   <p> In 1992, the state began seizing $683, or 27 percent, of his $2,553 monthly pension. Smith has lost $18,188 to California and owes another $35,000. Tax officials put a lien against any property he should ever buy in Sacramento County. "They're just squeezing me to death," says Smith. "If I'd known about this, I would never have moved."  <p> Numerous retirees, whether former civil servants or from the private sector, find themselves in the same boat the same thing is happening to an estimated 100,000 retirees in Nevada. Other states, too, have grown more aggressive in pursuing retired former residents, says the Retirement Savings Network in Washington, D.C., a group of employers and organizations battling this tax. For example, former New Yorkers who take a lump sum from their retirement accounts or receive more than $20,000 annually from their plan must pay a nonresident tax (taxpayers who take the money as an annuity aren't liable). New York also claims it is owed taxes on all the earnings growth from these accounts. Thus, a person who opened an IRA while a New Yorker for one year and then lived elsewhere for 29 years would pay New York income taxes on the first year's contribution plus the compounded interest over the 29-year period.  <p> Thirteen states in all carry laws that allow them to collect source taxes on pension income from former residents, though some choose not to, says Sally Adams, a tax analyst with CCH,Inc., a tax publisher in Riverwoods, Illinois (see table). Conceivably, retirees could be taxed on retirement income by every one of these 13 states in which they ever worked. And with many states scrambling to balance their budgets, "source states that have not here to fore taxed the pension income of nonresidents might decide to go after these funds," says Adams.  <p> State officials say pensions are deferred income. "States have the right to tax benefits earned while the person lived and worked in the state," says Harley Duncan, executive director of the Federation of Tax Administrators. However, some argue that pension taxes are levies on intangibles, not wages, and are properly assessed where the money is received. Taxes "should be paid by those who get state services," says William Hoffman, president of RESIST, an anti-source-tax group in Carson City, Nevada.  <p> California actually hires collection agencies to find ex-residents, among them Ellen and Bert Wight, who in 1994 were found in Arizona and dunned $4,799 because they took $6,000 from an IRA to pay Bert's doctor bills (he later died of colon cancer). Part of the tax bill was for an earthquake tax.  <p> With its heavy debt load, California can't afford not to pursue this revenue. If it did, the state would lose more than $1 billion annually, says Gerald Goldberg, a California Franchise Tax Board official.   <p> Pension-source laws are a potential nightmare for employers,too. Some retirees must show how much of their pension is due to each state in which they worked. To do this, employers may ultimately be required to track employees' benefits over their careers. But more than 70 percent of 401(k) plans accept rollovers from other plans, according to the Profit Sharing Council of America's 1994 survey of retirement benefits. If employers are responsible for employees' retirement-account histories, they may bar rollovers.   <p> Some have suggested that states tax only those retirees who move to escape taxes. But this would be virtually impossible to prove. Representative Barbara Vucanovich of tax-free Nevada, who calls source taxes "unjust," has proposed a bill to limit the amount a retiree could shield from these levies to $25,000 a year. In 1993, however, nearly one million Americans received lump-sum retirement distributions larger than $30,000, according to the U.S. Current Population survey. Representative Owen Pickett of Virginia has proposed a bill to eliminate the source tax, but it would exclude state and federal civil servants and members of the armed forces.   <p> Any bill to curtail nonresident taxes faces stiff opposition; states that collect it compose roughly a third of the House of Representatives. And Republicans, champions of states' rights, may refuse to set states' tax policies.  <p> Before taking your pension, know the law of the state where you earned it, and file for tax credits in your present state for any payments you must make. For information, call RESIST at 702-887-1296, or your state's department of taxation. Arizona, Colorado, New Hampshire, New Mexico, Nevada, Texas, and Washington stop other states from seizing assets of newly arrived retirees, according to CCH. Also, New Jersey and Iowa have repealed their nonresident pension tax in the last decade.  <p>  <p>  <p> STATES THAT CAN  <p>TAX NONRESIDENT PENSIONS  <p>  State IMPOSE TAX?  <p>  Arizona  No <p> California  Yes* <p> Colorado  No  <p> CONNECTICUT YES**  <p> Kansas  Yes <p> Louisiana  Yes***  <p>  Massachusetts Yes**  <p> Minnesota  Yes**    <p> New York  Yes***  <p> NORTH DAKOTA NO   <p> Oregon  Yes* <p> Vermont  Yes**  <p> Wisconsin  Yes**   <p>  * Withholds an income tax on nonresident payouts.  <p> ** Taxes only nonqualified plans.   <p> *** Exempts government plans.  <p> Source: CCH.   <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Taxation, Retirement

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

