<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/10-Tax Break Worth Dwelling On</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>A Tax Break Worth Dwelling On</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/10-Tax Break Worth Dwelling On</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						October 1995   <p>Worth  magazine/Advisor  <p> A TAX BREAK WORTH DWELLING ON  <p> By Kenneth R. Harney  <p> Money-wise homeowners are generally well versed in the basic tax write-offs available to them. These include mortgage-interest deductions, local property-tax write-offs, capital-gains treatment of resale profits, and, for those 55 or older, the one-time $125,000 exclusion on gains.  <p> But even the most astute homeowners are often unaware of what could be the biggest tax break of all: the qualified personal residence trust. In 1992, the Internal Revenue Service issued regulations establishing these trusts, which are expected to mushroom as aging baby boomers begin serious estate planning.Those with total estates above the $600,000 federal estate-tax credit threshold particularly families with second homes are good candidates for qualified residence trusts, say tax professionals. <p> "Given the sheer numbers of people who qualify," says David Gerson, tax partner with the accounting firm of Ernst and Young, "I expect [residence trusts] to really take off in popularity. After all, if you can save taxes on your largest asset, why wouldn't you?"  <p> Residence trusts allow you to move your primary or second home or both out of your estate, transferring the current value to designated family members at some predetermined future date, free of gift or estate taxes. That date can be 10 years down the road, 15 years later, or whenever you choose. Once the property is in the trust, its value is frozen for tax purposes, allowing your children to take over the real estate tax free, despite years of appreciation.  <p> Until the transfer date, you continue to live in the property, rent free. You still control it, and you're responsible for it. When the designated date arrives assuming you're still alive ownership shifts to your designees. You can then either move or continue to live in the house indefinitely for a fair-market rent. Alternatively, you can repurchase the property just before the transfer date. The price will be the same as the property valuation when you created the trust, even if the house has since doubled in value. <p> The key to the concept is that you are making a gift but retaining a quantifiable interest in that gift before turning it over.What's left in the property after your term of use what the IRS calls the "remainder interest" will be a fraction of the house's market value and the only part of the gift subject to taxation. All appreciation from the date of the trust escapes gift and estate taxation, provided you don't die before the transfer date specified in the trust.  <p> Consider this example provided by Ameek Ashok Ponda, a tax attorney with the Boston law firm of Sullivan and Worcester. You're 60 years old and own a debt-free $400,000 home. You want to minimize estate taxes, so you put the house into a qualified residence trust with a term of ten years. According to IRS annuity interest and mortality tables, the remainder interest after ten years will be just $172,076. That amount eventually gets charged against your $600,000 estate-tax credit limit but is $227,924 less ($400,000 minus $172,076) than it would have been without the trust.  <p> Your children, meanwhile, stand to take over a piece of real estate that could be worth $500,000 or more after a decade. If they retain it, there is no tax; if they sell, they are liable only for capital-gains taxes on profits in excess of the tax basis in the property at the time it was placed in trust. That's not so bad, considering that the maximum capital-gains rate is currently 28 percent, compared with the much higher rates (upto 55 percent) on estate taxes.  <p> There is no cap on the value of the house that can be contributed to a trust. In fact, because of the generous IRS discount computation rules, the more costly the home and the larger percentage of the estate it represents, the bigger the tax savings.  <p> Only personal residential realty qualifies. If you own an expensive vacation home that you rent out, you must make personal use of it for at least 14 days a year or 10 percent of the total rental days. <p>Most residential trusts specify that the property will revert to the donor's estate if he or she dies before the transfer date. That could expose the property to full estate-tax treatment. So choose a term you feel confident about (Ponda calculates that the ideal term for a 60-year-old male in good health is about14 years).  <p> If, while living in a house after gifting it to the trust, you make capital improvements a new bathroom, say you are adding value to your gift and may face gift-tax liability. So, too, with principal payments on a mortgage. Ponda advises clients to pay off the debt on a home if possible before putting it into a trust to simplify the deal. As with all estate-planning issues, consult your tax advisor before moving ahead.  <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Taxation, Real Estate, Homeowners, Estate Planning, Government

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
