	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/09-Exorcising the Demon Audit</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Exorcising the Demon Audit</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/09-Exorcising the Demon Audit</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						September 1995
Worth Magazine/Advisor<p>EXORCISING THE DEMON AUDIT<p>By Elizabeth Macdonald<p>Thirty years ago, the internal Revenue Service audited more than 5 percent of taxpayers. That number has fallen steadily, until today the IRS audit rate is 0.7 percent. As a result, many taxpayers have concluded that they can safely underpay their taxes. The annual revenue lost because of this cheating has risen to $127 billion (including $33 billion owed by corporations) from $60.1 billion in 1981.<p>This October, Big Brother strikes back. For the first time since 1988, the IRS will drag taxpayers--153,000 of them--through its Taxpayer Compliance Measurement Program, a super audit in which every line of a return must be documented. <p>The IRS won't just audit returns; it will also introduce its computer-aided examination of taxpayers' personal lives--so-called economic reality and market segment audits--to uncover discrepancies between their returns and "economic lifestyles," as estimated by their "market segment" (an industry, profession, or tax issue--there are about 80 in all). The IRS is particularly curious about the self-employed, who it says evade $35 billion in taxes each year.<p>The agency expects this technique will yield an additional $7 billion or so each year, though House Republicans and tax pros have criticized it as costly and invasive. "The new program could triple the costs of hiring a tax pro for audit preparations," says Claudia Hill, a tax expert at Tax Mam in Cupertino, California. Hill also says her colleagues oppose these audits because regular individuals are being dragged through fraud probes.<p>The super audit will target 33,000 filers of forms 1040A and 1040, 59,000 small businesses, and 61,000 partnerships and corporations. As in other TCMP audits, once selected, taxpayers must answer up to 367 questions and prove every item reported, even the existence of spouses or children. However, this time the IRS will assiduously hunt for economic-reality clues before the audit by tapping the records of the Social Security Administration; banks; divorce, probate, and bankruptcy courts; and insurance agencies. It will also examine employer personnel records, subscriber-information services, and newspaper articles and will interview landlords, employees, employers, ex-spouses, and neighbors.<p>Here's how taxpayers who receive audit notices can prepare:<p>DON'T SHOW. Ignore IRS notices that say "You will be present at the initiation of the audit." Such demands are in violation of the Taxpayer Bill of Rights. As with other audits, "it is not mandatory for the taxpayer to be present at a TCMP examination," says IRS spokesman Don Roberts. Instead, hire a tax pro with extensive audit experience to represent you and assemble your documentation. Enrolled agents charge $100 to $200 per hour for an audit. For referrals, call the National Association of Enrolled Agents at 800-424-4339. If you're self-employed, have your pro persuade the agent that a home audit would be too disruptive. <p>DON'T BE INTIMIDATED. The IRS is telling taxpayers to bring a completed Form 4822, "Reconstruction of Expenses," to the audit. Tax experts say you don't have to fill it out. The form, which asks taxpayers to explain how they paid for personal expenses during the year in question, "is an old internal worksheet the IRS uses to lay the groundwork for criminal-fraud inquiries," says Hill. When she recently refused to complete 4822 for a client, arguing it was an invasion of privacy, the IRS withdrew the demand.<p>Similarly, don't answer questions such as "What cash did you have on hand in 1993 usually, personally or for business, not in a bank, in a safe deposit box, or hidden somewhere?" Says Michael Knight, a CPA in New Canaan, Connecticut: "By law both the CPA and the IRS must shut down the audit when these questions are asked because they can lead to civil or criminal fraud inquiries." Raymond J. Smith, an official with the IRS Office of Compliance Specialization, recently told a group of CPAs that taxpayers needn't answer questions about their education or health: "We're not going to subpoena the taxpayer for that information." <p>BE HONEST. "IRS examiners are trained to ask for information they already have in order to test credibility," says Hill. One training manual for examiners cites the case of a taxpayer who admitted to three bank accounts, when the auditor already had divorce-court records listing 62.<p>DON'T BE A JERK. Read "Your Rights as a Taxpayer," included with audit notices. But keep in mind that your auditor, probably burdened with 35 other returns, may make life easier if you are cooperative. You can request a delay at any time in order to seek help. <p>IF YOU LOSE, APPEAL. Auditors use cost-of-living data from the Bureau of Labor Statistics to see if reported income matches residential profiles. However, critics, including Federal Reserve chairman Alan Greenspan, say these statistics are inflated. If you disagree with the final bill, appeal. If you don't sign the audit-adjustment agreement, your case will automatically go to an IRS appeals officer. The average appeal results in a 40 percent decrease in taxes, penalties, and interest. In fact, you may owe nothing; IRS statistics show that about one in five audited returns had nothing wrong with them. <p>THE IRS'S REALITY CHECK
The Internal Revenue Service uses these criteria--part of its definition of "economic reality"--to see if your lifestyle matches your income<p>* Address
* Neighborhood
* Number and age of dependents
* Education, tuition 
* Work experience
* Average income for profession
* Total assets (including home)
* Licenses (professional, personal)
* Location and type of business
* Profit margins
* Number of employees
* Stocks and bonds
* Investment income
* Interest expense
* Bank accounts 
* Trusts
* Personal living expenses
* Gambling winnings or losses
* Mortgage interest
* Automobiles, boats
* Trips
* Club memberships
* Hobbies
* Legal actions
* Weddings 
* Use of credit
* Insurance coverage 
* Cultural background
* Rental property
* Property sales
* Alimony paid or received
* Tax delinquencies<p>Source: Tax Savings Report <p>
KEYWORDS: Taxation

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
