<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/08-Tax Break?  Work for It</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Tax Break?  You1ll Have to Work for It</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/08-Tax Break?  Work for It</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						July/August 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Features  <p> TAX BREAK?  YOU'LL HAVE TO WORK FOR IT <p>It's getting harder to please the IRS on home-office deductions <p> By Carol Marie Cooper  <p> Dallas accountant James Hopson tells of the local housepainter who always counted on a hefty tax deduction for the office space he had set aside in his home. After all, the painter arranged jobs and billed clients there and stored paint and ladders elsewhere on his property. That was before 1994, when the IRS audited him, ordered him to pay back taxes, and went so far as to contact his clients during the dispute.  <p> Like a lot of other Americans, the painter will resist taking that juicy write-off again. While increasing numbers of Americans are working in their homes, the IRS has gotten downright stingy in granting the deduction.  <p> A 1993 U.S. Supreme Court decision, Commissioner of Internal Revenue v. Soliman, made the business of writing off home-office expenses even trickier. In that case, an an esthesiologist had to cough up back taxes and interest after the court decided his home office, his only office, was not his principal place of business because his patients were all in hospitals.  <p> Some accountants advise clients to forgo the deduction, even if it's deserved. It just isn't worth the risk of an audit, says Hopson.  <p> Home-office deductions once ranked in the IRS's top ten most frequent audit issues, says IRS spokesman Don Roberts. But that was before the 1991 tax year, for which the IRS introduced Form 8829, which allowed the agency to see how self-employed filers calculated the write-off.   <p> Until then, "there was no clear way to delineate the expenses," Roberts says. "The only way we could question whether or not a taxpayer had correctly completed the deductions was to conduct an examination [IRS-speak for audit]." Now, Roberts says, home-office audits rank 34th.   <p> The IRS has long insisted that home-office space be used exclusively for business and that the office meet one of three criteria: that the taxpayer sees clients there, that the office is in a separate building, or that it is where the principal work effort takes place. The Soliman decision narrowed the definition of principal work effort so that a traveling salesman or plumber, say, would be hard put to write off a home base under this rule. <p> If you have a home office, you are allowed to deduct a percentage of household expenses equal to the fraction of space the office occupies. In a 2,000-square-foot home, a 300-square-foot office would allow deductions of 15 percent. That 15 percent is applied to mortgage interest, property taxes, or rent. But remember, mortgage interest and property taxes are already deductible for people who itemize. Only a renter gets an unadulterated gain. <p> The office deduction does count toward otherwise nondeductible items like utilities, homeowners' insurance, security systems, and maintenance. If you're paying $3,000 a year for home insurance, the 15 percent can be written off. The same is true for utilities, although the IRS says that since you won't be showering in your office, you should reduce the water deduction accordingly. And you'd have one phone line anyway, so only additional lines count. <p> You can also depreciate 15 percent of the value of your home and home improvements over 39 years. But this write-off gets complicated. You can't depreciate the ground below. A $300,000 house sitting on a $100,000 lot is worth only $200,000. Depreciating15 percent, or $30,000, gives a deduction of about $770 a year. <p> Be careful, though. If you depreciate part of your house as a business expense, you lower the amount you have invested in it, increasing the chance of capital gains later. Worse, the business portion of your home won't fall under the usual rules that allow you to defer or avoid capital-gains taxes.  <p> If you sell at a loss, the rules could work in your favor. Suddenly, part of your loss from home ownership becomes a business deduction. <p> Whether it makes sense to risk the hassles depends on your situation. Richard Joyner, a CPA in Price Waterhouse's Dallas office, says clients with large homes and big mortgages and utility bills more often take the deduction. The self-employed have more to gain than the guy whose boss insists he telecommute, because an employee can deduct only expenses left after subtracting 2 percent of his or her adjusted gross income. But if you're self-employed, the deduction doesn't just pare income on which you would pay15 to 39.6 percent in federal income taxes; it also reduces the amount subject to 15.3 percent in Social Security and Medicare taxes for the self-employed.  <p> Hopson says his typical home-office client saves about $1,300 if he or she doesn't get audited and wind up paying Hopson to represent him, as the painter did.  <p> Even without claiming a home office, you can deduct or depreciate computers and other office equipment from self-employment income. If you're an employee and need the equipment for your job, you can write it off on Schedule A, subject to the 2 percent income rule. Here again, the amount to be deducted is based on the percentage of its use for business. Only $17,500 can be deducted in a single year. And some items like computers and printers, must be depreciated over several years unless they're used more than 50 percent of the time for business.  <p> Hopson knows first hand the perils of home-office deductions. He worked from home while starting his practice. The first two years, fearing IRS scrutiny, he didn't claim the deduction. Then, for 1988, he did. "Guess what happened? I got audited."  <p> Hopson was able to convince the IRS he was entitled to the deduction. But the $700 or so he saved in taxes cost about $1,500 in billable time.   <p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Homeowners, Small Business Ownership, Taxation

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/4pages.gif"><br>About 4 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
</td>
	</tr>
