<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/08-The New Corner Office</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>The New Corner Office</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/08-The New Corner Office</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						July/August 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Features  <p> THE NEW CORNER OFFICE <p>The heart of the home office that works is five essential tools: a multiline phone, a fax modem, an answering machine, a PC with a CD-ROM drive, and a printer-copier-fax.  Start-up cost:  About $3,500.  Here are our choices for the basics--and we've added some extras.   <p> Herman Miller's TD furniture collection is proportioned so that everything is within arm's reach (available at Crate & Barrel; pieces from $9 to $1,999). The Compaq Presario 900 Series PC has a space-saving minitower design and is bundled with <a name="NASD:MSFT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14120"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Microsoft</b></a> Works (from about $1,800). The BitSurfr digital modem (about$400) from <a name="NYSE:MOT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11023"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Motorola</b></a> connects to an ISDN line and lets users talk on the phone or send and receive faxes while data is being sentor received by computer. <a name="NYSE:HWP"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10723"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Hewlett-Packard's</b></a> HP OfficeJet (about $700) prints, copies, and faxes. The Bogen Friday two-line digital answering machine (about $300) has eight mail boxes and call forwarding. <a name="NYSE:T"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10103"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>AT&T</b></a> makes a number of multiline phones (from about $70). The extras: Mouse pad by Knoll ($55), Suna lamp ($465), SX tape dispenser($25), all from the Museum of Modern Art Design Store, New York; stainless steel tumbler ($25) by Thermos Nissan; Roladisc Wood (stores 100 CDs, $35) by Roundhouse Products; Elsa Peretti leather box ($215) from Tiffany & Co.; Jean Pierre pen ($155), leather book ($99), Bigso round box ($9), and rubber band ball ($5.50),all from Kate's Paperie, New York City; Coach leather organizer ($188); Krups Compac Therm Deluxe coffee maker ($150).  <p> Look for halogen lighting, which is whiter and brighter than traditional lighting. The Lillyna desk lamp ($125) is a scaled-down version of the famous 1937 original, updated with a halogen bulb, from the Museum of Modern Art Design Store, New York.  <p> Stainless steel Folle stapler ($60), Italicus scissors ($34), and letter opener ($25), all from the Museum of Modern Art Design Store, New York. Sterling silver notepad ($115) and pencil sharpener ($80) from Tiffany & Co. Desk Watch ($95; 800-442-2706) by Swiss Army Brands. Harman Kardon Festival 500 bookshelf entertainment system ($1,199;800-422-8027) and JBL Sat 2 speakers ($399).  <p> The Iomega Zip drive ($199; 800-697-8833) provides hard-drive backup and unlimited storage on 100-megabyte discs for about $250 less than its competitors; the Brother PT-25 electronic labeling system (about $139) creates laminated adhesive-backed labels; Texas Instruments' PS-6800 personal organizer (about $99; 800-842-2737) has 128k of memory and an optional PC docking station (about $50) that makes downloading files a snap; roam up to 50 feet with the HelloSet Cordless headset from Hello Direct ($349; 800-444-3556). A tilt mechanism helps Herman Miller's Aeron chair ($750$1,150; 800-851-1196) adjust to the body's full range of motion.  <p> <p><p>
