	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/08-Ensure That Your Capital Gains</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Ensure That Your Capital Gains</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/08-Ensure That Your Capital Gains</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						July/August 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Advisor  <p> ENSURE THAT YOUR CAPITAL GAINS  <p> By Elizabeth Macdonald  <p> Few tax rules change as often as those on capital gains, the difference between an asset's purchase and selling price. The House's recently passed tax bill reduces the long-term capital-gains rate to a maximum effective rate of 19.8 percent on assets sold after December 31, 1994. For assets purchased since then, the government would tax only profits realized in excess of inflation. The tax cut would amount to $31.9 billion over the next five years and $119 billion over the coming decade, according to the Joint Committee on Taxation. This is a huge change from the current law, under which investors who sell or exchange assets held for over a year face a maximum 28 percent federal tax on long-term net capital gains (the gain minus long-term and net short-term capital losses).  <p> The prospects for the House bill are unclear, but investors should be aware that one thing that isn't likely to happen is a reduction in the rate for short-term capital gains. The penalty associated with this high rate can be severe. Currently, gains on assets held one year or less are taxed as if they were ordinary income, which can mean a rate of 39.6 percent or higher.  <p> Another thing that is not likely to change is the complexity of figuring out capital gains in certain situations. Here are some tips on keeping your tax tab as low as possible:  <p> Property received from an estate. The fair market value of inherited property is automatically adjusted to its worth at the time of the benefactor's death. Some people forget this when calculating capital gains, says Janice Johnson, tax director of Coopers & Lybrand in New York. Suppose an individual inherits $10,000 worth of stock that was purchased for $1,000 in the 1950s. Then suppose that taxpayer sells it 13 months after inheriting it for $12,000. The important thing to remember is that long-term capital gains are due on just the $2,000, not the entire $12,000.   <p> Gifts. If a taxpayer receives property as a gift and sells it for a gain, he or she can include in the holding period the length of time the donor held the gift. "So even if the gift was given to you last week, if the donor had held the property for more than one year, you get long-term capital-gains treatment if you sell it now," says Johnson.  <p> Mutual fund distributions. How long you own the fund isn't what's important. Capital-gains distributions are taxed at long- and short-term rates depending upon the time frame for the fund's investments.  <p> Futures contracts. Today, 60 percent of capital gains from certain futures contracts, such as nonequity options and foreign currencies, are taxed at the long-term rate, no matter how long a taxpayer held the investment. "If you buy a broad-based stock index such as the S & P 500 today at $1,000," says Johnson, "and you sell that index next week for $1,500, 60 percent of your $500 gainis treated as long-term capital gain."  <p> Convertible bonds and preferred stock. If a taxpayer converts a corporate bond into common stock of the same corporation, the bond-holding period carries over to the stock. However, if a taxpayer converts a bond into stock but needs to pay additional cash for that stock, says Johnson, "the holding period for the portion of the stock acquired with cash begins the day after the cash purchase is complete."  <p> Property received in a tax-free exchange. The holding period of property given up in certain tax-free exchanges can be added to the holding period of the new property. "If a taxpayer swaps a vacation house in the Poconos for one in Aspen," says Johnson, "no gain is realized for tax purposes, and he or she gets to tack on the holding period for the Poconos property to the one in Aspen."  <p> Personal residences. Taxpayers can roll over all of their gain into a new residence, so long as the new one costs more than the old one. "They can also tack on the holding period of their old residence to the new one," says James Hegel, a tax expert in McLean, Virginia.   .0<p> Property distributed by a partnership. The length of time a partnership holds property distributed to a partner, such as stock or real estate, is added to the taxpayer's holding period. "However, taxpayers who sell inventory within five years of receiving it from that partnership cannot include the partnership's holding period to get long-term capital-gains treatment," says Hegel. <p> Real estate sales involving indebtedness. Suppose a taxpayer buys a piece of land and sells it to an investor, who purchases it with a mortgage. Then the buyer defaults and the land is repossessed. If the original seller repurchases the property, he or she can add the prior holding period to the holding period starting with the date of reacquisition (but not the time when the mortgage holder held title). "It's as if the property was never sold, ignoring the time it was in the hands of the buyer," says Hegel. <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Government, Taxation, Bond Investing, Legislation, Real Estate, Homeowner

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

