	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/05-A Small Victory Over Taxes</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>A Small Victory Over Taxes</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/05-A Small Victory Over Taxes</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						May 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Advisor  <p> A SMALL VICTORY OVER TAXES  <p> By Elizabeth Macdonald  <p> With the trauma of tax time still fresh in both memory and wallet, we offer this strictly legal list of tax breaks to stick on your refrigerator door. We hope it will help make next April a little less painful.   <p> The exemptions and deductions below come from the Office of Management and Budget in Washington, D.C., which annually delivers a list of tax expenditures tax breaks that cost the government billions to congressional tax-policy analysts. We also consulted Commerce Clearing House, a tax publishing firm in Chicago, andcertified public accountants Janice Johnson of Coopers & Lybrand and Sidney Kess, both of New York City.   <p> "By paying attention to these breaks," says Johnson, "an individual who earns $100,000 annually in adjusted gross income could save an extra $3,000 a year." Other incidental breaks exist in thelaw핝or a more complete list, consult your tax pro.  <p> Non taxable distributions.  <p>If you receive a dividend that includes a return of your capital,typically the case with utility shares, you may owe no tax onthat amount. Ask the company you invested in to separate the taxable and nontaxable dividends. Also tax free: Dividends paid as stock, stock rights (which let shareholders buy newly issued stock at a discount), stock received in a split, mutual fund dividends that represent tax-exempt interest, and dividends on insurance policies (so long as they don't exceed your net premiums).  <p> Retirement plans.  <p>This year, the retirement-plan exemption will cost the government $66.22 billion, and experts say the deficit will eventually force Congress to tax these benefits. So max out while you can on 401(k)contributions, individual retirement accounts, Keoghs, and simplified employee-pension (SEP) plans, and consider after-tax contributions.These retirement plans are not all equally suitable for every taxpayer. Lump-sum distributions from Keoghs qualify for five-year averaging, which may result in lower taxes, and SEPs do not. But, Kess says, "the IRS requires no annual reporting and plan documentation for SEPs, plus they can be opened any time before taxes are filed, unlike Keoghs."   <p> Life insurance.  <p>Money received by the beneficiary of a life insurance policy is not taxed. However that rule applies to the principal amount only not interest. Also, up to $5,000 in death benefits from company-provided life insurance is tax-exempt (the same rule applies to the estate of the deceased employee). That amount must be prorated if there are multiple beneficiaries.   <p> Legal settlements.  <p>This is a complex, evolving area, but in general, you don't have to pay taxes on awards from lawsuits filed for personal injury, sickness, libel, damages, or race, sex, or age discrimination.  <p> Employer-provided benefits.  <p>The IRS will forgo an estimated $60.7 billion this year by not taxing these. However, "if you get better health benefits because you're a top executive, but other employees have to self-insure or get less coverage, you'll have to pay tax on the difference between the annual benefit payments," says Kess.   <p> Dependent care.  <p>A growing number of companies are offering on-site child care. Such benefits are tax-exempt up to $5,000 in value. Ask your employee-benefits department for a year-end statement of the value of the services you used. Also, taxpayers who furnish more than half the total support for a parent, child, in-law, or other household member who earns less than $2,500 annually may claim a $2,500 exemption for 1995. That applies even if your parent resides in a nursing home, so long as you are head of your household and provide over half of the support, including nursing-homefees.  <p> Gifts and inheritances.  <p>No income tax is owed on property received from a gift or inheritance.  <p> Real estate.  <p>Two breaks stand out: If you are age 55 or over and have lived in your principal residence three out of the last five years,you are eligible for a one time exclusion of up to $125,000 inprofits from selling your home. The OMB says this rule will save taxpayers $4.7 billion this year. Also, income from renting a residence for less than 15 days each year is tax free.   <p> Scholarship and fellowship grants.  <p>You owe no tax on scholarship and fellowship grants awarded bya nationally accredited educational institution for tuition and course-related fees, books, supplies, and equipment.  <p>- - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - -- - - - - - - - <p>A field Guide to Lower Taxes  <p> Start documenting these write-offs:  <p>  Capital losses  <p>  Medical expenses (including cost of travel to medical care, telephone calls made to out-of-town physicians, contact lenses, and even birth-control pills)  <p>  Mortgage interest   <p>  Charitable donations   <p>  Home-office deductions   <p>  Furniture used in home office   <p>  Business equipment  <p>  Depreciation of home computer required by a job  <p>  Dividend reinvestment plan fees  <p>  Investment management and advice fees   <p>  Investment publications, books, and newsletters   <p>  Appraisal fees to figure out a casualty loss  <p>  Fees to administer collectibles acquired with intent to make a  profit   <p>  Passport fees for business trips  <p>  Certain attorneys' and accountants' fees  <p>  Certain employee education expenses  <p>  Job-search fees    <p>  Professional club dues, publications   <p>  Union expenses  <p>  Safe-deposit-box rentals  <p>  Medical exams required by a job  <p>  Cost of uniforms and cleaning expenses  <p>  Work supplies and tools  <p>  Work-related convention and seminar fees  <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Insurance Industry, Retirement, Taxation, Government, Homeowner<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/4pages.gif"><br>About 4 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
