	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/03-Breakdown at the IRS</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/03-Breakdown at the IRS</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						The nation's tax collector can't keep up with Congress. Its slow-moving bureaucracy continues to hurt innocent taxpayers and botch federal deficit-cutting plans. Current social and economic trends are now threatening to push the agency over the edge.<p>By Elizabeth MacDonald<p>"Taxes are what we pay for civilized society," Oliver Wendell Holmes wrote in a 1904 legal opinion. He was right. Taxes built it, after all--the whole impossibly complex grid of modern life. Holmes felt so strongly about this that he even spoke of the pleasure he took in writing out his tax checks each year.<p>How times have changed.<p>Today, the cultural consensus supporting the system is teetering. Taxes don't seem to buy personal safety, much less civility, and the national infrastructure raised by generations of accreting revenue--airports, bridges, dams, roads--is crumbling.<p>The purest expression of that breakdown is the Internal Revenue Service, to whom Holmes would have tithed a small percent of his income in the days when it was called the Bureau of Internal Revenue. Back then, only the well-heeled paid federal income taxes and the maximum rate was 10 percent.<p>The IRS was as big as big government ever got, a faceless bureaucracy that knew everything about us and operated according to its own laws. When Richard Nixon, seeking to escape the Watergate noose, threatened to use the service to punish his political "enemies,'' the country wasn't just shocked, it was frightened.<p>Today, however, the institution is seen less as awesome than awful. It can't keep up with the demands of politicians, who change tax laws with alarming regularity. The latest bunch of would-be reformers--House Speaker Newt Gingrich and his Republican colleagues--plan nothing less than a complete overhaul of the income-tax system, at a time when the IRS has trouble handling its most basic function: collecting taxes. It can't spot the $127 billion in taxes evaders annually hide from it or nab the 10 million individuals who don't file each year. And when returns flood in each spring, IRS employees err on one of every ten they enter into the agency's computers, contributing to the monumental disarray of its records. According to the General Accounting Office, the IRS now has more than $200 billion in misstated taxpayer payments and refunds on its books.<p>What's more, the IRS mainframe computers, some more than three decades old, are obsolete and in some cases literally crumbling. A huge effort to upgrade the system is failing, according to both the GAO and the National Research Council, a branch of the National Academy of Sciences in Washington, D.C. Last April at a Cato Institute debate in Washington, Shirley Peterson, IRS commissioner under President Bush, called the current income-tax system "an unwieldy, inefficient, ungodly mess" that cannot be fixed by "tinkering." <p>Government officials say the IRS's problems now jeopardize the funding of the government. The IRS's difficulties are so severe that the GAO had to warn Congress, the Joint Committee on Taxation, the Department of the Treasury, and the Office of Management and Budget that they all harbor "an exaggerated idea" of IRS's ability to help the government slash its $3.6 trillion deficit through improved tax collection. According to a 1992 NRC report to Congress, "a major breakdown of the nation's tax system'' could occur before the year 2000.<p>The accelerating transformation of the U.S. economy, which grows daily more decentralized and international, is moving the IRS closer to that reckoning. Moreover, the developing cashless economy of the Internet and the declining proportion of people employed by large corporations will make the job of collecting taxes far more difficult in the near future.<p>The IRS, with 110,656 people--a full-time workforce greater in size than <a name="NASD:MCIC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13996"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>MCI</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:MER"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10990"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Merrill Lynch</b></a>, and <a name="NASD:AAPL"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12644"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Apple Computer</b></a> combined--is like Gulliver pinned down by the Lilliputians, caught in the massive shift of technological power from the public to the private sector.<p>The cold war, the space race it engendered, and the cost of computation power once kept government at the leading edge of technological progress. But the development of the personal computer in the late 1970s began to push the pendulum in the other direction. Access to data and the power to manipulate it became virtually universal, a commodity, and the private sector proved far more clever and nimble in its application than government. George Orwell's dystopian vision of state control receded.<p>That still leaves the problem of how to administer society, which begins with funding government--$1.2 trillion annually--and includes providing the financial data required to assess the impact of its tax policies. An incompetent IRS diminishes the ability of lawmakers to govern and punishes taxpayers, upon whose uncoerced consent the tax collector ultimately depends.<p>Yet incompetence is rife in the IRS--a conclusion supported by interviews with IRS officials, members of Congress, and former IRS commissioners, as well as an examination of 55 confidential IRS studies, GAO reports, and reviews conducted by the NRC.<p>Some of the IRS's difficulties have been well publicized, such as its plummeting audit rate, down to 0.7 percent from a high of 5 percent in the mid-1960s, and the 1992 scandal in which the IRS caught 368 of its employees snooping through taxpayer returns. Some 132 of them were disciplined, with varying degrees of severity, but just six were fired.<p>The full extent of the IRS's troubles, however, are still emerging--partly as the result of the first-ever audits of the tax agency, conducted by the GAO in 1992 and 1993. These audits paint a picture of a very leaky ship. Among other things, the GAO concluded the IRS can't even document how it spends its own $7.2 billion budget, nor does it have accurate records for nearly $800 million in assets, such as cars and homes, seized from taxpayers.<p>Findings like these and others shed new light on the emerging debate over the merits of the present income-tax system. Although current arguments for abolishing the income tax are generally ideological, the sorry state of the IRS raises more practical considerations. Foremost among them: Is it even feasible to continue collecting an income tax?<p>One cause of the problems at the IRS has been inconsistent leadership. Over the last 42 years, the average tenure of the IRS commissioner has been one and a half years. The pattern continued over the last six years, as four different people have held the job. This turnover in the top post allowed the IRS bureaucracy to mushroom, while making it impossible to pursue long-range planning.<p>The current commissioner is Margaret Richardson, a native of Waco, Texas, and friend of First Lady Hillary Clinton. Richardson snared the appointment after taking a leave of absence from her position as a partner in the Washington, D.C., law firm of Sutherland, Asbill & Brennan to campaign for Bill Clinton in 1992. Between 1969 and 1977, Richardson worked in the chief counsel's office at the IRS in D.C., first as an attorney, then as an administrator. <p>Several months after her confirmation, Richardson told a congressional subcommittee: "Prior to l989, there was no comprehensive effort devoted to improving financial management at the IRS. At that time, we were operating with outdated accounting systems that did not allow us to adequately account for the operations of our organization. We knew there were problems but did not know to what extent.... The audit of our financial statements by the GAO was a watershed for the IRS.''<p>Richardson responded to these problems by abolishing seven assistant-commissioner positions and taking an energetic, hands-on approach to the job. She regularly bursts into subordinates' offices demanding updates on IRS problems. While away on vacation, she called audit manager Eva Williams and discussed the IRS's problems for three hours. <p>This approach, however, has served to mostly alienate IRS bureaucrats throughout the ranks. Her habit of publicly dressing down people is so feared that employees often avoid going to staff meetings with her. <p>Management style, though, probably isn't the real problem. It's unclear whether anyone could halt the agency's decline. For instance, Richardson is now presiding over a much-ballyhooed replacement of the IRS's computer hardware. The new technology, including networked workstations, is expected to reduce paperwork through electronic filing and optical scanning of all tax returns. Richardson told Congress in the fall of 1993 that the modernization program will save taxpayers billions in lower tax-preparer fees and a billion hours spent in contact with IRS. <p>The computer upgrade, begun in 1986, is one of the most expensive civilian computer projects ever. It is projected to cost $23.3 billion through 2008. Of this amount, $7.8 billion is for new computers. The remaining $15.5 billion will go toward keeping the IRS's current computers running. <p>Already, however, the program is well behind schedule. Partly because of the red tape of the government procurement process and partly because of technical snafus with some of the first new computer systems it received, the IRS has to date spent just 17 percent of the money earmarked for the hardware upgrade.<p>Problems with new equipment last year contributed to an alarming number of refund scams that slipped through undetected--particularly those associated with electronic filing. When Congress learned that the IRS had paid out as much as $5 billion in bogus refunds for 1993 tax returns, it slashed the agency's computer budget for 1995 to $650 million from $989 million in the fall of 1994.<p>Last November, the NRC said it "continues to have very serious concerns about the IRS's ability to successfully complete the upgrade on time and within budget." The NRC's skepticism is well-founded. Twice before, in 196878 and in 198286, the IRS started to overhaul its computer system, but then abandoned each attempt. Eight years into the current upgrade, with no end in sight, Robert Clagett, a professor of business at the University of Rhode Island who chairs the NRC committee that reviewed the IRS, says, "I don't think any of us who work in the computer industry would have organized a computer upgrade like the IRS."<p>Still, the system must somehow be fixed. Otherwise, there will only be more incidents such as the one in the Philadelphia service center in 1985: After a computer crash, officials found employees stuffing tax returns into the ceiling and in drawers in an effort to keep up with their work quotas.<p>At the IRS, a computer crash is not always a metaphor. Former commissioner Peterson recalls the time a service-center system went down in 1992: "When we sent a technician out to fix the computer, the broken part was so old and rusted it crumbled in his hand."<p>
The IRS's problems in processing tax returns begin at its ten service centers, where thousands of IRS employees toil in chaotic, football-field둅ize offices, seeking to deal with an ever-rising mountain of work.<p>This year, more than 200 million businesses and individuals will post their returns to one of these centers, roughly triple the number filed in the 1950s. If the IRS taped together all the pieces of paper it receives annually, the trail would wrap around the earth roughly 36 times. "Both the IRS and taxpayers are drowning in a sea of paper," IRS commissioner Richardson told Congress in 1993.<p>Each filing season, thousands of IRS employees sit hunched over gun-metal gray, government-issue desks in offices that look like something out of an anxiety dream. Before them are stacked wooden cubbyholes, called Tingle tables after Jim Tingle, an IRS man who invented them in the 1960s. These employees shove different schedules and tax forms by hand into different Tingle slots. The contents of these boxes then go to part-time IRS keypunchers, paid roughly $18,000 a year, who enter 40 percent of the information on each return--feeding the data into old Unisys and Sperry computers. Each of these workers is expected to plow through 29 to 35 returns per hour.<p>(Some service centers use even more antiquated technology. The IRS center in Austin, Texas, for example, has Gould and Perkin Elmer mainframe computers that were built in the late 1950s and early 1960s. According to Clagett, old returns processed by the Austin center are crammed into the top floors of empty military airplane hangars 190 miles away in Fort Worth.)<p>Clerks at the various centers dispatch the keypunched data to the main IRS data-processing facility in Martinsburg, West Virginia, where computer operators merge the information into the agency's master file. This gigantic repository houses the nation's tax-return data.<p>Martinsburg then matches income-reporting documents from financial institutions with this tax-return data. If these computers discover a mismatch between these documents and income and deductions reported on a tax return, it notifies the service center. The service center then issues notices of underreported income to taxpayers.<p>The IRS says 21 percent of the 1040 returns entered by its clerks contain some sort of error. "About half of the mistakes are IRS, half are taxpayers," says Lawrence Westfall, the IRS official in charge of the agency's computer-modernization program.<p>That means the IRS processes about one in five returns erroneously. The IRS contends it fixes a large percentage of the mistakes before the data ever leave the service center, but the GAO asserts that many types of errors slip through. For example, it says IRS workers incorrectly typed 450,000 addresses into the agency's computers for 1988 tax returns, the latest year for which these data are available. Because of these mistakes, the IRS that year sent approximately 300,000 notices demanding $49 million in additional taxes to wrong addresses.<p>
What happens when the IRS drops the ball on a return? In 1990, Michael Peak, 59, an executive vice president of Sukut Construction in Santa Ana, California, found out.<p>Peak at the time was legal guardian for his 17-year-old niece Yulena, who earned a few thousand dollars working in a senior citizens' residence. In 1990, Peak filed Yulena's 1989 income-tax return, enclosing a $14 check dated April 14 for taxes owed. Peak dutifully wrote Yulena's name and Social Security number on the check, which the IRS cashed on April 24, 1990.<p>That fall, the IRS service center in Fresno spit out a notice saying that Yulena hadn't paid her taxes. In reply, Peak sent the IRS copies of the canceled check, front and back, with a letter explaining Yulena's situation. Two months later, the IRS service center in Fresno sent a second notice demanding payment, this time $16.<p>Peak again sent the Fresno service center copies of the relevant documents and an explanatory letter, but in August 1991, a third notice arrived from the IRS district office in Laguna Niguel, California. Peak placed a telephone call to Laguna Niguel to argue his case, but the agent who fielded the call told him to pay his bill--now $18--or she would garnish Yulena's wages and slap a lien on her property. He duly sent off a new check to the IRS.<p>Ultimately, Yulena didn't lose any of her salary, and the IRS sent Peak a $20 check. Soon after, an IRS ombudsman from Laguna Niguel called and apologized. Nonetheless, it took a year and wasted who knows how many IRS man-hours to resolve a petty goof made worse by the agency's thuggish behavior.<p>
Experts on the IRS point out that one of its problems is its inability to deal with the mobility of Americans--not exactly a recent sociological development. The seven regional offices, 63 district offices, and ten service centers rarely communicate with each other, and their computers aren't networked. As a result, taxpayers who move routinely run afoul of different IRS offices across the country.<p>Frank and Ann Cook were two such people, harassed for ten years by the IRS, largely because it didn't register the Cooks' move from the West to the East Coast. In autumn of 1983, the Cooks, living in Seattle, paid a modest amount in back taxes after an IRS audit of their 1981 return. Two years later, they moved to Hartford, notifying the IRS in writing of the change of address.<p>That year, the IRS audited the couple's 1982, 1983, and 1984 returns and eventually sent to the old Seattle address a bill for $6,300, which the Cooks never received and hence never responded to. The IRS interpreted their silence as tax delinquency and ultimately attached the bulk of Ann's wages as a hospital technician from 1987 to 1989. Not until 1989, despite repeated phone calls and letters to the Hartford office, did the couple receive written notice of the audits the IRS conducted. Ironically, Frank Cook claims he had complete receipts for the deductions the agency disallowed back in 1985.<p>Ultimately, the IRS seized $35,000 in salary and savings. The Cook family, including three children, was reduced to living for an entire year on $150 per week. "You'd think in the United States a simple taxpayer would be able to ask the IRS, 넹hy are you doing this? We didn't owe all of this money,'" Ann Cook says today. Had an agent checked the Cooks' file or wondered why they hadn't responded to the audit notices or the liens, the agonizing process that left a family impoverished and embittered would have been unnecessary. Why didn't this happen? The probable answer is sheer bureaucratic rigidity.<p>
This same quality shows up in the way the IRS responds to women, who pose a particular challenge at an agency that has yet to acknowledge women's liberation or the demographic changes it created.<p>The distaff problem is a sizable one. Every year at least 3 million women change their last names because of marriage or divorce. According to the GAO, these women are all at risk of receiving wrongful penalty notices stating that they did not file their returns. This occurs because the IRS's computer system is the same "as it was in 1962," according to a confidential IRS report, and cannot immediately fix a mismatch between its records and the taxpayer's new last name.<p>The IRS stores joint returns under the name of the first spouse listed, usually the husband. If the wife gets divorced or remarries, the IRS often assumes she is not filing tax returns because it can't match her new name to the one on file. Instead, it sends out a failure-to-file notice, often a lien on her property.<p>Worse, the GAO says these notices are sent to the last known address of the spouse of record on the old joint return, meaning the husband. According to the confidential report, IRS computer programs make a number of comically outdated assumptions about women and our society. They assume "women would report their income on joint returns, husbands would prepare joint returns, and husbands would be the primary taxpayers." They also expect women to report name changes to the Social Security Administration themselves and, in any case, that they will only marry once and will not revert to their maiden names if divorced. IRS inspectors concluded that the agency has yet to acknowledge that "over the last 31 years, women accounted for 60 percent of all new workers entering the workforce, the number of divorced women quadrupled, and remarriages increased 60 percent."<p>Even when wrong, the IRS can be a bad enemy, according to a Pittsburgh woman who asked to remain anonymous. She and her husband filed jointly in New York City for many years before moving to Pittsburgh in 1991. That year, she received a notice from the IRS service center in Holtsville, New York, stating she never filed her 1984 income taxes and demanding $7,598.12 in ten days, under threat of losing her house, car, and wages.<p>The IRS relented only after she provided a copy of the disputed return. One year later, the Philadelphia service center dunned the couple for taxes on the same "missing'' return. Though the couple eventually fixed their problem, "every time I get a letter that says Internal Revenue Service on it, I cringe," says the woman.<p>Six years ago, IRS inspectors suggested that simply by including a line on returns for maiden names, or keeping a separate file under the second taxpayer's surname and Social Security number, everyone could stay matched to their tax records. Officials in the returns-processing division rejected the recommendations as too expensive. <p>
Today, the halls of Congress resound with brave GOP talk about tax cuts and government waste. If a new tax law is enacted this year, it will mark the 32nd time elected officials have changed the tax code in 41 years, according to the Tax Foundation, a public-policy research group in D.C.<p>"On more than one occasion Congress made a tax change, but before the IRS had finished reprogramming its computers, it changed the law again," says former commissioner Peterson. This endless revision makes administering the tax code still more difficult. Each year the IRS must revamp its computer programs for 80 percent of its 400 forms. The antique IRS hardware must be programmed using "assembler'' language, in which each letter of every word and each digit is separately written. Thousands of IRS workers must spend hundreds of hours learning new laws, codes, revisions. The 1986 Tax Reform Act hardly accomplished its mission of simplifying the law. And now the Republican Congress is talking about upending the law once again.<p>The IRS's problems often come back to haunt Congress. Lawmakers, in deciding how much income to tax, rely chiefly on estimates from the Joint Committee on Taxation and the Congressional Budget Office. When Congress publicizes how much money it will raise from certain tax-law changes, it bases that information on IRS sample studies of 194,000 tax returns.<p>That sample, the GAO says, is too limited and often flawed. IRS computers can only indicate how much in gross taxes people pay in various income brackets. They don't show how much revenue is raised by different components of the income tax. Plus, the information is often two years old. The IRS operates "with no forethought to setting up records that would let Congress compare its budget numbers to actual, real-time numbers," says Gregory Holloway, director of civil audits at the GAO and the person who headed up its IRS audit. "Because IRS's records are so poorly set up, nobody can accurately tell what the impact of new federal tax policies will be."<p>In 1989, the Office of Treasury Analysis, which also relies on IRS data for budget estimates, included this disclaimer in briefing materials sent to congressional staffers: "More often than not the effect of tax law changes cannot be adequately quantified by the use of tax return data. Estimates frequently involve novel ideas where there is little or no data, no previous experience to draw upon, no studies to refer to, indeed, nothing available but the estimator's past experience."<p>Then too, the IRS has on occasion ignored its own inadequate data to make exaggerated claims about future revenues in response to congressional pressure to bring in more money. In 1991, for instance, the IRS told Congress it could collect as much as $105 billion in outstanding taxpayer fines. Yet when the GAO later examined the IRS's own records, it found piles of duplicate entries and incorrect bills. Eventually, the IRS concluded that only $28 billion in fines could be collected--either because taxpayers didn't actually owe what the IRS thought, couldn't afford to pay, or couldn't be located.<p>Again in 1989, the IRS promised to raise $666 million between 1990 and 1991 by auditing 12,000 small-business pension plans--retirement plans at small law firms, auto body shops, hair salons, and the like. Based on the IRS's assertions, Richard Darman, then director of the Office of Management and Budget, logged an additional $666 million into President Bush's proposed budget for fiscal year 1990, which Treasury sources say Congress promptly began to spend. <p>In reality, however, OMB says the IRS probably won't collect more than $80 million from those funds. In 1990, when the American Society of Pension Actuaries challenged the IRS's calculations, it discovered that the IRS intended to penalize pension plans that calculated benefits based on interest rates of less than 8 percent or a retirement age of less than 65. The IRS apparently had decided that these estimates were too low, even though the IRS's own retirement plan carried a 7 percent rate and a retirement age of 55 at the time.<p>Pension administrators challenged the IRS in court and won six straight cases. The IRS "did not do their homework and they lost resoundingly," says John Woyke, a principal at Towers Perrin, a benefits consulting firm based in Valhalla, New York.<p>
For an agency that demands numerical exactness from the taxpayer, the IRS puts little faith in its own numbers. The GAO says it is an unspoken IRS policy to amend the cash records it gives to Congress representing taxpayer payments or refunds so they jibe with the Treasury Department's fiscal year-end financial statements. Despite the fact that the Treasury's books documenting the government's revenues have never been audited, the IRS routinely uses Treasury's numbers to resolve cash differences between these records instead of figuring out whose numbers are correct. This procedure violates IRS and Treasury regulations.<p>In September 1993, the GAO reports, IRS officials in the chief financial officer division in Washington, D.C., which is in charge of the IRS's bookkeeping, recorded a phantom $79 million in revenue on its books in order to square its accounts with Treasury's. In 1992, the GAO says, IRS officials in the agency's National Revenue Accounting Unit in D.C. ordered IRS accountants at the Brookhaven, New York, IRS service center to type in their records that they received $55 million from taxpayers in January, even though they really got that amount in March, again to match Treasury's cash records.<p>Of course, if taxpayers amended their returns to coincide with, say, erroneous bank records, the IRS would be quick to penalize them. <p>
The fiddling extends to all levels of the bureaucracy. According to a January 12, 1993, confidential report by Donald Kirkendall, then Treasury Department inspector general, 24 employees in Buffalo filed 65 complaints with his office, charging that IRS managers there "manipulated" audit statistics to "receive merit pay awards," especially in tax audits that target small-business excise payments for gasoline and tobacco taxes. IRS managers, according to Kirkendall, were "gaming the numbers." <p>Kirkendall concluded that statistics compiled by the Buffalo office "are routinely inflated by all levels of management." He also warned that this practice has "service-wide implications," especially for the veracity of the IRS's numbers. With bracing candor, Kirkendall concluded, "We are building a house of cards."<p>
The IRS, still behind the curve of decades-old demographic trends, certainly isn't ready for new changes on the horizon, such as the advent of electronic money. Already, an estimated 30 million people and 20,000 companies around the world log on to the Internet computer network. Users in the first wave of online shopping can buy books and clothes, paying for them electronically via credit cards with the help of companies such as First Virtual Holdings in Cheyenne, Wyoming, the first entirely electronic bank. The number of Internet users is expected to reach 200 million by the turn of the century. By then, experts say, Net surfers will be able to conduct virtually any kind of commercial transaction through cyberspace.<p>Digital cash that requires no credit card is also coming, and soon. "Already, there's an estimated $100 to $200 million sold annually on the Net, and this figure is expected to balloon to anywhere from $2 billion to $600 billion by the year 2000," says Richard K. Crone, a senior manager at KPMG Peat Marwick's Center for Electronic Banking in Los Angeles.<p>Furthermore, anyone with a computer and a telephone line can become a small business (the number of small businesses rose from 15 million in 1984 to 21 million in 1992). As more taxpayers conduct business and get paid via the Internet, experts say the day will soon come when electronic income and assets online can easily be hidden from the IRS.<p>Crone says the IRS could track electronic transactions and that tax payments could be automatically sent to the IRS via computer, but the IRS will have to count on what merchants report and the sophistication of its auditors and computer systems. Crone is pessimistic. "The IRS is still behind the Berlin Wall in terms of computing power,'' he says.<p>Lee Stein, president of First Virtual Holdings, agrees. The electronic transactions will be "as untraceable as any merchant wants them to be," he says. "A person can rent space on a local computer system in a U.S. domain such as the island of Tonga, which has liberal tax laws, and conduct all financial business through it.'' You can live in Maine and run your Tongan business online, with no one the wiser. Beyond that, says Crone, "the Net will make it easier for a merchant to evade taxes, say, by setting himself up with a foreign E-mail address. There's no border control on the Net, and it is averse to any government intervention, which will also make it harder for the IRS to impose rules." <p>As the IRS nurses its computer systems into the next millennium, no one knows whether the agency's manifold problems can be fixed, or patched, in time to prevent an agency meltdown. Congressional apathy only adds to the problem. When Senator John Glenn conducted a hearing on the GAO's audits last July, 10 of the 14 congressmen on the committee didn't show up. The four who did stayed for ten minutes, then left.<p>Glenn, who orbited the earth alone in a space capsule, is still flying solo. At some IRS hearings, he says, "I sit up there taking testimony all by myself." <p>Additional reporting by Kathleen Murray and Bruce Upbin<p>
YOUR SOCIAL SECURITY BENEFITS COULD GET TRAPPED<p>By Elizabeth MacDonald<p>Like it or not, the government's problems are your problems, and they affect more than your taxes. The GAO says at least 10 million workers could miss out on thousands of dollars in annual Social Security benefits because the IRS and the Social Security Administration aren't cooperating in crediting roughly $25 billion in contributions owed to workers.<p>The affected workers' last names or Social Security numbers were incorrectly entered on their W-2 earnings statements, so the SSA cannot match their Social Security contributions to their accounts. Also, the GAO says thousands of defunct businesses failed to send in W-2s for their former employees.<p>The GAO says the IRS, because its records are constantly updated, could help resolve this problem. The agency tries to keep its records current by holding onto refund checks until taxpayers whose records are faulty provide correct information. The IRS also penalizes businesses if they don't provide accurate tax records on their workers. <p>The IRS, however, "does not give the Social Security Administration its updated taxpayer name and Social Security information so we can correct our benefits records for individuals," says Paul Russin, the SSA's IRS liaison. It is hard to understand why the IRS doesn't cooperate with the SSA, particularly as it willingly shares its taxpayer information with more than 200 state and local taxing authorities across the country. To catch criminals, certain state agencies, such as the Oregon Public Utility Commissioner and the Washington Department of Fisheries, also get IRS tax-return information on request. In its defense, the IRS says it tells taxpayers to correct their name and Social Security numbers with the SSA when the IRS notifies them about a mismatch in its records.<p>Another problem arises when companies go bankrupt and don't provide the IRS or SSA with current and correct information. In 1992, the IRS drew up proposed regulations that would force shaky businesses to report employees' earnings to SSA quarterly instead of annually and to send a W-2 form to SSA within 30 days of shutting down. But the IRS only followed through on the first of the two ideas, and did so just this past December.<p>Until these problems get resolved, you must do your own Social Security benefits checkup. The SSA keeps a lifetime record of employee contributions going back to 1937, and to 1951 for the self-employed. To get your Social Security benefits statement, call Social Security at 800-772-1213 and ask for Form SSA-7004, "Request for Earnings and Benefit Estimate Statement." After you send back the form, in about a month and a half you'll get a statement of the contributions, or earnings, Social Security has recorded under your name. The statement will also show your estimated monthly benefits if you retire at age 62, 65, or 70. <p>To check Social Security's math, gather your old W-2 forms, tax returns, and pay stubs. If your current employer reported the wrong wage amount to Social Security, contact your payroll office and ask them to alter the figure to match your W-2. If you don't have your tax return, get a certified copy from your IRS service center by sending in a form 4506 and a $14 check. The IRS should take about a month to send you one. Next, report the mistake to Social Security by sending copies of your correct earnings, W-2s, pay stubs, and tax returns. From February to October of this year, Social Security will also mail its benefits estimate to those taxpayers age 60 or older who are not yet receiving Social Security checks. Younger taxpayers will receive a free benefits statement when they turn 60, and by the year 2000, Social Security plans to send this statement to everyone age 25 or older.<p>
OR MAYBE MOONSHINERS HAD THE RIGHT IDEA<p>By Joel Slemrod<p>Fueled by a widespread belief that the current income-tax system is too complex and curbs incentives to work, save, and invest, Capitol Hill is abuzz with talk of abolishing the income tax. But what are the alternatives, and how do they stack up against the current system? Here are four:<p>THE VALUE-ADDED TAX<p>A staple of most European countries' revenue systems since the 1960s, a VAT doesn't require individuals to file tax returns. April 15 would thus be a day like any other day. Businesses would remit a flat percentage of gross sales receipts minus most material and supply costs other than labor. The effects of a VAT are much like a sales tax, raising the prices of everything we purchase by the rate of the tax--probably about 25 percent if it replaced the income tax entirely. A VAT would eliminate taxation on savings and investment, but it would also raise taxes paid by low-income households. Congress could try to reduce the impact on the poor by levying lower VAT rates for goods such as food, shelter, and medical services, but such measures wouldn't make up the difference and would also make administration of the tax far more complex. Conservatives have long been wary of the VAT, fearing it would become a "money machine" providing painless revenue for a ballooning government.<p>CONSUMPTION TAXES<p>People would still have to report their income on tax returns but would be allowed to deduct all net new savings, such as money placed in a savings account or new investments in stocks, bonds, or mutual funds. A graduated rate structure would help maintain the current distribution of the tax burden by income group.<p>Senators Sam Nunn of Georgia and Pete Domenici of New Mexico plan to introduce a personal consumption둆ax bill (at press time, their target date was mid-February). A preliminary version retains home-mortgage deductions and the earned-income credit, allows credits for charitable giving, and permits limited deductions for education. This option offers neither simplification nor lower rates. Because no country operates a personal consumption tax, there could be unforeseeable glitches in its administration. The switch to such a system might also require taxpayers to report their total financial assets--a potential paperwork nightmare.<p>THE FLAT TAX<p>Flattens the income tax in two distinct ways: by applying a single, uniform rate to taxable income and by eliminating most, if not all adjustments, deductions, and exemptions.<p>House Republican Majority Leader Dick Armey of Texas has been pushing a 17 percent flat tax that eliminates deductions for mortgage-interest payments, charitable contributions, and state and local tax payments. It features a standard deduction of $26,200 for joint filers but excludes interest, dividends, and capital gains from the tax base. A flat tax could simplify the tax code enormously, while lightening the tax load on households earning more than $200,000 a year. It would increase the tax burden on middle- and lower-income households. The exclusion from tax of all capital income undoubtedly would strike many as inequitable. The person paying a flat 17 percent tax on his or her $50,000 salary won't be pleased that next door, a taxpayer who receives $50,000 in interest and dividends doesn't have to pay a dime.<p>SUPPLEMENT THE INCOME TAX<p>Replacing the income-tax system with any of these three proposals would make the Tax Reform Act of 1986 look like fine-tuning in comparison. Instead of replacing the income tax, Congress could add, say, a VAT to its arsenal of federal taxes and use the revenue to cut income-tax rates or increase the standard deduction. In the current tax-cutting environment, however, neither party is likely to embrace this approach. <p>
BEST DEFENSE: HOW TO USE THE IRS'S OWN WEAPONS AGAINST IT<p>By Elizabeth MacDonald<p>If you're like most taxpayers, you probably can't wait to loll on a faraway island once you get your refund check. But don't pack your steamer just yet: The IRS may not be done with you. Last year the agency demanded over $1 billion in extra payments from taxpayers, mailing intimidating notices to millions of filers who--the IRS says--calculated their returns wrong.<p>What taxpayers should know is that such notices often result from sloppy bookkeeping. Yet the IRS does little to vet its work. According to a confidential agency report, only demands for $25,000 or more are checked by humans for mistakes. IRS computers spit out bills charging lesser amounts with reckless abandon--and taxpayers often pay up without a peep. That's too bad, because with a little effort you can challenge such an assessment, or even the result of an audit. Says New York City accountant Nancy Gallagher: "Many don't realize that taxpayers can beat the IRS at its own game."<p>Unfortunately, the IRS's main game is record keeping, not writing, and its notices and records might as well be written in Sanskrit. Still, don't panic. If you receive what you believe is a bogus bill from the IRS, there's a sensible procedure to follow. First, call the telephone number on your notice and get the IRS's taxpayer service division on the line. Ask for a printout of the past two years' worth of your records from the IRS master file. This is the governmental equivalent of your TRW credit report and will serve as a Rosetta stone in your campaign for justice. Of course it's written so only a computer could understand it, so be sure to ask for a glossary of IRS codes, too.<p>Your transcript will take about three weeks to arrive. When it comes, you'll see that it shows your name, the dates you filed your returns, any money you paid or still owe, and any bills the IRS sent you. There will also be a bunch of weird alphanumeric sequences: Remember, you're dealing with mainframe computers. Each time the IRS pokes into your tax account, it enters a "transaction code" in your file. On your printout you'll see this activity identified by the letters TC, followed by a three-digit number. There'll be a brief explanation to the right of every entry. This is where to look for information on what the taxman is doing to you--and for ammunition to fight it.<p>For example, if the IRS says you owe more taxes, you should be on the lookout for liens (TC 582) that the agency may have filed against your bank account without telling you. That's important, since the IRS has confiscatory powers. If you've been asked to say interest (TC 190 or 196), you can use your transcript to argue for an abatement. Compare the printout to your own records and note every error or delay in recording payments. This will serve as powerful evidence that the IRS itself contributed to your problem.<p>If you find mistakes in your transcript, write to the tax examiner listed on your original delinquency notice. These workers can correct IRS errors and will decide whether your fines should be abated. Remember, be polite. Many IRS workers are underpaid and overwhelmed. Tell them the year of the tax you're disputing, describe the mistake clearly, and explain what you think the IRS should do. Include copies of any documents that support your case. Supply your Social Security number and the 14-digit locator number found in the upper right-hand corner of your notice. Also include your daytime phone number. And remember: Keep your printout, records, and all IRS correspondence in a safe place. Fight paperwork with paperwork.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Government Adgency, Taxation, Retirement

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
