	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Tax Savings for Big Paychecks</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/03-Tax Savings for Big Paychecks</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						March 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Advisor  <p> TAX SAVINGS FOR BIG PAYCHECKS <p>Why firms are offering nonqualified retirement plans   <p> By Rebecca Lewin  <p> Top wage earners have begun finding new ways to supplement their retirement savings--tax free. Current tax-law limits set the salary cap for contributions to so-called qualified retirement plans--such as 401(k)s--at $150,000. (The pre-Clinton limit was $236,000.)  <p> But new types of nonqualified plans let participants set aside more income, tax-deferred, than the qualified-plan limits allow. Some of the new arrangements, however, are tricky. All also come with one major drawback: They don't provide outright controlor ownership the way typical 401(k)s do. If they did, the assets in them would be taxable--and deductible to employers--now. "A lot of people don't know that," says Robert Scharff, principal of the Todd Organization Inc., a consulting firm in St. Louis. The trick is to make sure that control does change hands after retirement. The new nonqualified plans include:  <p> Deferred-compensation plans. These relatively straight forward setups let participants contribute, tax-deferred, as much of their salary and bonus as they wish. The company then invests funds to meet the minimum returns promised to the employee. Avariation on this is the so-called mirror 401(k), a nonqualified plan that invests in the same mutual funds or other vehicles as the company's qualified 401(k).   <p> Supplemental executive-retirement plans. Suppose a company's qualified pension plan pays lower-level workers 50 percent of their salaries on their retirement. Those with heftier incomes, however, may be limited to receiving, say, 20 percent because of the tax laws. In such cases, management can create and contribute to a nonqualified "excess" or "restoration" plan. These plans ensure that the higher 50 percent figure comes to executives at retirement.  <p> Target supplemental executive-retirement plans. These vehicles set a target percentage of an employee's final compensation--say, 60 percent. The plan takes into account what the employee will receive in qualified pension and Social Security payments and antes up to meet the target.  <p> These plans are unsecured and thus vulnerable to three major dangers. First is change of control, in which a new management takes over and stops the nonqualified-plan payments. Then, there's change of management heart. This is what happens when the company's chiefs decide to stop funding executives' futures because the company needs the money for something else. Finally, there's bankruptcy, in which creditors may snatch up retirees' savings. <p> There is some protection from the first two threats, called the Rabbi Trust. Originally created to safeguard a rabbi's retirement funds, this trust becomes irrevocable and a trustee becomes responsible for paying the benefits if a change of control or management commitment to the plans takes place. Rabbi Trusts, however, do not provide protection from creditors' claims in bankruptcy. <p> <p>
KEYWORDS: Retirement, Taxation, Family Finance, Government

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
