	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/03-Picking the Best Tax Software</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Picking the Best Tax Software</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/03-Picking the Best Tax Software</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						March 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Advisor  <p> PICKING THE BEST TAX SOFTWARE <p>We liked all four products, but our favorite was...  <p> By Andrew Gluck  <p> Our pick for the best tax-preparation software this year: Turbo Taxby <a name="NASD:INTU"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=16001"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Intuit</b></a>. After examining and testing four of the top tax programs on the market, we chose Turbo Tax because we liked the simple--even friendly--way it takes users through the other wise pencil-chewing process of completing a tax return.  <p> Actually, we thought all four of the programs we tried were pretty good. The other three: Tax Cut by Block Financial Software(our top choice last year), Personal Tax Edge by Parsons Technology, and Simply Tax by 4Home Productions.  <p> Each of these products can help save time in completing a 1994 federal tax return. They also eliminate errors in arithmetic (Pentium chips notwithstanding). According to the Internal Revenue Service, math mistakes are the most common problem on taxpayer returns.   <p> The software programs also make it possible for users to change a single entry on a return--for example, to boost a charitable donation--and then recalculate the entire return with a single keystroke.  <p> Advantages like these have helped make tax-preparation software immensely popular. During the last tax season, software companies sold a total of 3.4 million tax preparation packages--a 50 percent jump over the previous year, according to the Software Publishers Association in Washington, D.C. Federal tax programs sell in the discounted range of $20 to $35; state versions go for $20 to $25.   <p> We examined the Windows versions of the four top sellers and also looked at CD-ROMs for Turbo Tax, Tax Cut, and Personal Tax Edge. The latter were identical to the Windows products except for some additional audio and video features that we sometimes found silly, such as when the computer merely voiced the samething that appeared on the screen.  <p> Each of the programs works essentially the same way: They are set up as personal interviews, asking the user questions. Depending on the answer, the programs then ask follow-ups. The process goes on like this until the return is complete.   <p> In our tests, we prepared a number of sample tax returns using the programs and invited each company to give us a tour of its product to ensure we'd see the best features. We also enlisted the help of tax expert Robert Lipsky, a certified public accountant in Jericho, New York. We ran the programs on a computer with a 386 processor running at 33 MHz and another with a 486 processor running at 66MHz.   <p> One of the things we liked about Turbo Tax was the way its interview format helped keep work to a minimum. Lipsky found that Turbo Tax was the only program savvy enough to automatically transfer data from a Schedule C to a Schedule A. When Lipsky allocated 20 percent of the mortgage interest and property taxes he paid in 1994 to his home office on Schedule C, Turbo Tax automatically put the other 80 percent of his mortgage interest and property taxes onto a Schedule A.   <p> Turbo Tax also handled other common tax scenarios better. For instance, during the demos, we asked each company to show us how someone with a small business could depreciate a computer. Turbo Tax's interview was the only one that immediately selected the right depreciation method--using a first-year expensing as allowed under Section 179 of the IRS Code.  <p> Our second favorite program for preparing a1994 return is Tax Cut. It received our No. 1 pick last year mostly on the strength of its easy-to-read help screens. But this year Tax Cut's help screens blasted us with so many instructions that we found them confusing. There was simply too much to read. In contrast, Turbo Tax improved its tax advice by translating tax-speak into plain English. Users get help screens only when they instruct Turbo Tax to provide one. Tax Cut also has abandoned the cartoon like icons we liked so much last year.   <p> Simply Tax gave us the most problems. It ran so slowly on our386-33 MHz machine that we lost patience in the middle of the company's demonstration. An official said the program was built to run on machines people are buying today, which use 486 and Pentium microprocessors. But data from SPA indicates that no more than 23 percent of the households that own computers in the U.S. have machines with 486's or Pentiums.    <p> Personal Tax Edge is a fine product for accountants and other professional preparers because its interview prompts users to enter data directly onto IRS forms. Its format, however, isn't nearly as pleasant as Turbo Tax and doesn't provide enough hand-holding to guide a tax know-nothing through a return.  <p> Computer and software companies make a lot of promises about the advantages and utility of their products. Some day, they may even live up to some of their more outlandish claims. At the moment, however, tax-preparation software is one of the few categories that really does help to make life a little simpler. Only those with the most complicated returns need fear a dissatisfying outcome--at least with the software, that is. 
 <p>
KEYWORDS: Taxation, Technology Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/3pages.gif"><br>About 3 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

<font size=+1><b>Company Index</b><br>
</font>						<a href="#NASD:INTU">Intuit Inc.</a><br>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
</td>
	</tr>
	<tr><td width=390>
	
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  
		<a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  
		<a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  
		<a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b><p>
		<font size=-1><i>&copy; 1996 Capital Publishing Limited
		Partnership</i></font>
		

		</center>
	
	</td>
