	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/03-Advisor Briefs</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Advisor Briefs</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/03-Advisor Briefs</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						March 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Advisor  <p> ADVISOR BRIEFS  <p> By Peter G. Miller and Deborah Pont  <p> DEEP DISCOUNTERS GO DEEPER  <p> Brokerage commissions have been rising at both full-service and discount brokerages but falling at the so-called deep-discount firms, according to Mercer Inc., a New York셕ased research firm that keeps an eye on discount brokers. A Mercer survey of 90 brokerage outlets found that full-service firms charged customers an average commission per trade of $246 in September 1994, up3 percent from $239 in February 1993. The three largest discount firms--<a name="NYSE:SCH"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10320"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Charles Schwab</b></a>, Fidelity Investments, and Quick & Reilly--charged an average of $102, up from $101 in 1993.  <p> But deep discounters charged an average commission of $50 last year. Mercer says that represented a drop of 6 percent from the average $53 a trade assessed by the deep discounters in 1993. <p>  <p>THE RADON PANIC   <p> Rising concern about radon--a harmful, invisible, and odorless gas produced by radioactive decay--has led to an increase in in-home testing nationwide. The U.S. Environmental Protection Agency, estimating that 1 in15 homes has elevated radon levels, already has trained more than 3,000 radon testers. But thousands more testers are active because most states don't require a license to do such work.  <p> The problem: Many of the inspectors are using unreliable short-term tests--ones that attempt to measure radon levels in a home in just a few days. The EPA found that positive readings for radon on two common short-term tests were false 49.9 percent of the time.  <p> "You can't be sure what the atmospheric pressure will do during any given week, and so the results are not reliable," says Thomas P. Sheahen, president of Western Technology in Derwood, Maryland. Sheahen was certified as an EPA radon inspector but says he left the business because staying would have meant "becoming a crook." <p> Tests that measure for radon over at least a 90-day period are much more accurate but are often viewed as impractical in real-estate transactions. The solution: When buying a home, require the sellers to create an escrow fund for radon repairs. Then do a long-term test. If it shows a harmful level of radon, the fund can be used to pay for repairs. The cost for repairs generally runs from $500 to $2,500 per home, according to the EPA.  <p>  <p>WATCH THOSE FUND FEES  <p> Beware of hidden mutual fund fee increases--or so we've read in a number of recent press accounts. But are fees really rising? Not according to data collected by Lipper Analytical Services. Lipper says the average fees on general equity funds rose a scant 0.8 percent last year. On the other hand, given the sort of year most funds had in 1994, even that seems like a hefty increase to us.  <p>  <p>THE LOVE TRUST  <p> What's the most widely used form of trust fund? Possibly the credit-shelter trust, which helps married couples take advantage of the credit that allows $600,000 in every estate to pass from one spouse to the other free of federal estate taxes.   <p> Say a couple has $1.2 million and has not established a credit-shelter trust. Each spouse can will everything to the other without triggering estate taxes. But if the value of the estate is still $1.2 million when the survivor dies, the tax collector gets $235,000--the estate tax on the amount in excess of $600,000. When each spouse puts $600,000 into a credit-shelter trust, however, the survivor can use the money and eventually pass it on to the children tax-free. Another advantage: Investments in a credit-shelter trust can continue to appreciate free of taxes.  <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Investment Strategies, Homeowners, Taxation, Estate Planning

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
