	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/02-Lenders Eat Crow on Escrow</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Lenders Eat Crow on Escrow</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/02-Lenders Eat Crow on Escrow</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						February 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Advisor  <p> LENDERS EAT CROW ON ESCROW <p>But new federal rules may not go far enough  <p> By Elizabeth Macdonald  <p> Paul and Nancy Griffin of Pocatello, Idaho, are livid. They figured their mortgagor, First Security Bank of Idaho, should know full well that property-tax payments are remitted when due, not when past due. They thought wrong.    <p> Each month Paul, 58, and Nancy, 55, dutifully send their bank a prorated $110.56 escrow payment equal to one twelfth of their annual property tax bill for their $59,000 fixed-rate mortgage. The bank then pays the couple's full $1,326.72 annual property-tax payment each year by December 20. Mortgage lenders typically collect escrow money along with mortgage payments to pay property taxes and homeowner's insurance.   <p> But instead of mailing the Griffins' annual property-tax payment by the December 20, 1992, deadline, First Security mailed their property taxes two months later, in February 1993. When the couple sat down that April to deduct this payment on their 1992 tax return, their anticipated $500 refund check turned into a $464 federal and state tax bill.  <p> As the Griffins' tale shows, this little account can cause enormous headaches. Besides bigger tax bills, borrowers have been slapped with liens, credit-report blemishes, and even foreclosure proceedings because of lender tardiness, according to the Consumer Federation of America.   <p> First Security said the glitch happened because a supervisor at its escrow servicer, Transamerica Tax Service, was out sick. In addition to the Griffins, another 107 borrowers may have been stuck with tax bills totaling $50,000 because of late property-tax payments. Although the bank offered to pay these borrowers interest for any delinquent amounts, it also told them it was not liable for any "inconvenience" it caused. Says Paul Griffin: "It would have been slightly more than an inconvenience if we had falsely deducted these taxes--we would have violated the law." First Security, though, did not break any federal laws because there are no federal laws to break. Experts say state laws governing escrow accounts are lax, too.  <p> Homeowners are also getting stung by lenders who ask for a bigger escrow cushion in these accounts than necessary, which is then used interest-free by lenders. In 1975, Congress tried to fix this problem when it amended the Real Estate Settlement Procedures Act to prohibit lenders from holding on to more than two months' worth of escrow funds. Since then, lenders have largely ignored this ceiling. The amounts involved could be steep--according to the Mortgage Bankers Association, an estimated 36 million mortgages have escrow accounts. The New York Consumer Fraud Bureau, which has extensively investigated escrow problems, reports that some $30 billion is now sitting in these accounts.   <p> New regulations from the Department of Housing and Urban Development taking effect April 24 will require lenders to make timely escrow payments. The rules also will restrict lenders to two months' worth of escrow payments on loans originated after that date (the rules are not generally retroactive). Plus, lenders must now conduct an annual analysis of every escrow account and reimburse homeowners within 30 days for any surpluses in excess of $50. HUD says at least $1.5 billion will be returned to borrowers who were overescrowed, beginning this April. Says Sarah Rosen, a special assistant in HUD's housing division, "They're very strong and dramatic changes."  <p> Yet these rules are often in reality a slap on a lender's wrist. For one, the HUD regulations governing escrow accounts are enforced by civil penalties, not by more powerful court injunctions. Furthermore, just one HUD penalty is in force against lenders--a $100 civil penalty for intentionally failing to send a borrower a copy of his or her annual escrow analysis ($50 per borrower for unintentional violations). Lenders get off lightly for other major infractions, such as the more expensive overescrowing. "If the lender keeps too much escrow money, we don't have the ability to penalize them," says Rosen. And banks still don't have to pay interest to borrowers on these accounts. Today, only state-chartered savings banks and savings and loans in 14 states require such interest. "We would have liked to see [HUD] go further," says Mel Goldberg, spokesman for the New York Consumer Fraud Bureau.  <p> Additionally, HUD's six investigators are sorely underequipped to handle the nation's 36 million mortgage-escrow accounts. To fix the problems not addressed by the HUD regulations, Congress will consider tougher escrow-account measures in a bill, H.R.27, this year. Among the provisions is a requirement that lenders pay borrowers interest on escrow accounts. However, the mortgage industry is threatening to hike interest rates and fees paid by borrowers at the time a loan is originated if mortgage lenders have to pay borrowers such interest. Says Stephen B. Ashley, spokesman for the Mortgage Bankers Association: "The bottom line for borrowers is that H.R. 27 would add an average of at least one-quarter discount point [on a $100,000 loan] to the up-front cost of getting a mortgage." As borrowers continue to get stung while mortgage lenders get tough on these seemingly benign accounts, homeowners may want to consider investigating exactly what is happening to their escrow accounts. Otherwise, this little account could cost you.  <p> SOME HELPFUL HINTS  <p> In light of lender threats and inadequate regulations, what can borrowers do?  <p> * Many homeowners believe that escrow money belongs to the lender. Not true. The bank's requirement of an escrow account is bank policy, not law. Homeowners can opt out of a lender-based escrow account, because they are a negotiable part of a mortgage contract in every state. Before signing on the dotted line, homeowners who want to set up an escrow account in their name should make sure their mortgage contract allows it. Borrowers now stuck with lenders who make tardy payments should take a cue from Paul Griffin:"We would never have had this problem if we had taken care of this payment ourselves."  <p> * Since the new rule requiring lenders to give borrowers an annual audit statement of their escrow accounts is not retroactive, and given the weak enforcement of the rules, borrowers who are told by lenders that they have not been overcharged may want to consider getting an escrow checkup. For a fee ranging from $99 to $269, Mortgage Monitor in Stamford, Connecticut (800-283-4887), will audit an escrow account. In over 70 percent of the cases analyzed so far, the borrower was due a refund, ranging from $400 to more than $2,000.  <p> * When negotiating a mortgage contract, borrowers should ask their lenders to pay a standard savings rate on escrow accounts. Although such payments are not required of most lenders, it doesn't hurt to try.  <p> * Homeowners who refinance their loans must bug their lender to transfer old escrow accounts to their new loans. Otherwise, they may end up paying money into two escrow accounts for the same loan. Eventually, borrowers can get reimbursed, but they could be out several thousand dollars while the problem gets fixed.  <p> <p>
KEYWORDS: Banking Industry, Taxation
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
